Good. Those answers lock in a lot. Let me crystallize the key design decisions before I write, so we're building on the same foundation:
Aethel is canonical, it's in Rosland, and it's a living city — not a ruin. That's a powerful choice because it means Rosland's democratic traditions have a physical monument to point at, which makes House Ironside's power grab feel like desecration rather than just politics.
Xaria as a provincial outpost of a larger overseas empire is a massive detail that changes everything about how the peninsula functions. It means Xaria isn't isolated jungle primitives — it's the frontier edge of something potentially as large or larger than the Nionic Empire ever was. That empire beyond the map is a source of dread, mystery, and leverage. The temple-cities aren't just local religion; they're colonial infrastructure. That's going to ripple through everything.
The language situation — a shared tongue with regional dialects and a "neutral register" for cross-regional communication — is very realistic and very Chilean, frankly. It's how Spanish works across Latin America. That grounds the world immediately.
Gunpowder-era lost tech — cannons, Da Vinci-style war machines — means the deep past was in some ways more technologically advanced than the present. That's a beautiful irony: civilization went backwards. The Age of Fire didn't just impose order, it destroyed knowledge in the process of conquering. The empire burned libraries to build roads.
Now here's the Age of History, written as the first section of Book I of the lore bible.

BOOK I — COSMOLOGY & DEEP HISTORY
THE AGE OF HISTORY (c. 50,000 BE – 1,211 BE)
Preamble: On the Poverty of the Record
What follows is reconstructed from fragments. The Age of History spans roughly forty-nine thousand years — a period so vast that the entire Age of Fire, with its nine centuries of imperial glory, could fit inside it fifty times over and still leave room for civilizations to rise and fall unnamed. The Magos of the Isle of Knowledge have spent centuries attempting to assemble a coherent chronicle from the scraps that survive: clay tablets in languages no one reads, stone foundations buried beneath later construction, tool-marks on quarry walls that imply machines no living smith can explain, and the oral traditions of remote peoples who remember things in song that they cannot remember in fact.
The difficulty is not merely the distance of time. It is that the Age of Fire, for all its accomplishments, was catastrophically destructive to what came before. The Nionic emperors did not conquer a blank continent. They conquered a continent full of history, and then they burned it. Libraries were torched to deny rebels knowledge. Temple archives were seized and rewritten to serve imperial theology. Local scripts were suppressed in favor of Munnish. Construction crews demolished ancient structures for building material — the great imperial roads are paved, in many stretches, with the crushed tablets of civilizations whose names are now unknown. What the emperors did not destroy, time and neglect finished. By the present day, Year 1308 of the Age of Faith, the deep past is less a history and more a wound: a place where knowledge used to be, visible only by the scar it left.
The Magos divide the Age of History into three broad periods, though they acknowledge these divisions are imposed rather than intrinsic. The boundaries are soft, the dates approximate, and the confidence of any claim diminishes the further back one reaches.

I. The First Peoples (c. 50,000 – 30,000 BE)
The Indigenous Presence
The continent of Mundus was not empty when the great migrations began. In at least four regions — Xaria, the Red Coast, the Frozen South, and western Rosland — archaeological evidence and persistent oral tradition point to human populations that predate the migrations by an unknown but considerable span. Who these people were, where they originated, and how they arrived on the continent are questions that have no satisfying answers.
In the Frozen South, the clans preserve fire-songs — sung genealogies passed mouth to mouth across generations — that claim descent from people who "were born from the mountain's breath," a poetic way of saying they have always been there, as native to the land as the volcanic stone itself. The oldest fire-songs make no reference to arrival, to crossing water, or to any homeland beyond the fjords. To the southern clans, the question of origin is nonsensical. They are the land's children. The land made them. That is enough.
On the Red Coast, the evidence is physical. In the deep canyons of the Montañas de Cobre Rojo, Magos expeditions have documented cave paintings executed in mineral pigments whose chemical composition does not match any known artistic tradition from the later city-state period. The paintings depict human figures alongside animals that are either fantastically imagined or faithfully rendered from species that no longer exist — broad-skulled quadrupeds with copper-colored hides, long-necked wading birds the height of a man. The pigments have been dated, through the layering of calcium deposits, to periods that precede the earliest migration estimates by millennia. Someone was there. Someone was painting. Their descendants mixed with later arrivals so thoroughly that the seam is invisible, but the paintings remain, silent and unexplained, deep in canyons where the sun reaches the floor for only twenty minutes a day.
In Rosland, the western fjord communities maintain traditions distinct from the inland population — different boat-building techniques, different funerary practices, a strain of folk medicine that shares no ingredients with the Heartlands pharmacopoeia. Linguistic scholars on the Isle of Knowledge have identified a substrate layer in western Roslandic dialect: roughly two hundred words with no cognates in Munnish or any other regional variant, words for specific coastal weather patterns, tidal movements, and shellfish species that appear to belong to an older, unrelated language. These words survive as fossils in the living tongue, the bones of a language whose flesh has long since rotted away.
Xaria presents the most complex case. The peninsula is not an isolated landmass but the western edge of a much larger island empire — the Ix'Atani Dominion — whose full territorial extent stretches beyond the eastern horizon, across waters that Mundane sailors have never successfully navigated. The Xarian population is therefore not indigenous to the continent in the same sense as the southern clans or the Red Coast cave painters. They are, rather, the westernmost settlement of an external civilization, a colonial frontier that predates the Nionic Empire by tens of thousands of years. How long the Ix'Atani have maintained their presence on the peninsula is unclear even to their own chroniclers. Their temple records, carved into basalt step-pyramids, reference a "First Planting" — the establishment of the original temple-cities — but the date is expressed in a calendrical system that Magos scholars have been unable to reconcile with continental chronology. The Xarians themselves consider the question irrelevant. The gods placed them where they are. The jungle grew around them. They have been feeding K'tharr since before the sun learned to set. That is their history, and it requires no further explanation.
The Great Migration
At some point — the Magos place it tentatively around 40,000 to 30,000 BE, though this range is little better than a guess — humans arrived on the continent of Mundus in successive waves from an unknown landmass or landmasses. The migration was not a single event. It was a process stretched across centuries, possibly millennia, with different groups arriving at different points along the continental coastline and penetrating inland along river systems.
Where they came from is the great unanswered question of Mundane history.
The most popular scholarly theory among the Magos is the Single Origin Hypothesis: that all migrant populations departed from the same continent, but from different coastal regions of it, arriving at Mundus from multiple directions across open ocean. This would explain both the broad physiological similarity of the continent's peoples and their initial cultural diversity — they shared a deep ancestry but had diverged before departure. The theory is elegant. It is also unprovable, since no Mundane ship has ever successfully crossed the deep ocean and returned with reliable charts of what lies beyond.
A minority of Magos scholars advocate the Multiple Origin Hypothesis — that the migrants came from two or more separate landmasses entirely. They point to the significant cultural and physiological differences between, say, the tall, pale-complexioned populations that settled the northern Heartlands and the shorter, darker peoples who arrived along the southern and eastern coasts. But physiological variation can be explained by adaptation to different climates over the vast timescales involved, and cultural divergence is an inevitable product of geographic separation. The debate continues in the Scriptorium's upper reading rooms, where it generates more heat than light and has produced no fewer than seventeen competing monographs in the current century alone, none of them conclusive.
What is known — or at least broadly agreed upon — is this: the migrants arrived in groups of varying size and landed at points distributed around the continental periphery. They came by sea, which implies a maritime technology sufficient for open-ocean crossings, a capability that was subsequently lost and not recovered until the Age of Republics. They brought with them domesticated grain species, basic metallurgy, and a common linguistic root from which all modern Mundane dialects descend.
They did not arrive as a unified people. They had no shared political structure, no common religion beyond fragmented animistic practices, and no awareness that other migrant groups existed. The continent was vast — roughly three thousand miles from the northern tip of the Horns to the southern coast of the Frozen South — and the migrants dispersed into it like water poured onto sand. Groups that landed on the western coast had no contact with groups that settled the eastern river deltas. The Heartlands were reached last, as migrants pushed inland from all directions, their paths converging over generations in the fertile central plains without any awareness that they were part of the same species-wide movement.
Where the migrants encountered indigenous populations — in Rosland, the Red Coast, the Frozen South, and along the Xarian frontier — the results varied. In most cases, the process was gradual enough to leave no record of conflict. The populations mixed over centuries, intermarrying and blending traditions until the distinction between "original" and "arrived" became meaningless. In the Frozen South, the fire-songs record no foreign arrival at all, which either means the mixing was so ancient and so complete that the memory of separateness was lost, or means the southern clans genuinely predate the migrations and simply absorbed the newcomers into their existing social structures. In Xaria, the dynamic was reversed: the established Ix'Atani civilization was sophisticated enough to absorb or repel migrants on its own terms, incorporating new labor into its temple-economy without disruption to its existing hierarchies.
The result, after millennia of settlement and mixing, was a continent populated by a single species that spoke variations of the same root language but had developed, through geographic isolation and environmental pressure, into a patchwork of cultures as distinct from one another as the climates they inhabited. The people of the Horns, shaped by maritime survival on storm-lashed peninsulas, had almost nothing in common culturally with the river-valley farmers of the Heartlands, despite sharing an ancestor who might have sat in the same boat ten thousand years earlier. The thread of commonality was there — a shared grammar buried beneath layers of local innovation, a handful of cognate words for water, mother, fire, death — but it was so thin that it would take an empire to make it visible.

II. The Age of City-States (c. 30,000 – 5,000 BE)
The River Revolution
Civilization, as the Magos define it — settled agriculture, permanent architecture, written records, social stratification — emerged independently in multiple locations across the continent, driven in each case by the same basic pressure: river systems. Where water was reliable, people stopped moving. Where people stopped moving, they began to build.
The earliest known urban settlements cluster along three great river systems: the central Heartlands rivers (which would later become the backbone of the imperial road network), the Sangrea river valleys descending from the Sierras de Sangre, and the Xarian delta system (though the Ix'Atani temple-cities may predate these, their chronology remains unresolved). In each case, the pattern was similar. Agricultural surplus allowed population concentration. Population concentration demanded administration. Administration demanded record-keeping. Record-keeping produced writing.
The first scripts were not literature. They were ledgers. Grain counts pressed into wet clay with sharpened reeds. Tax assessments scratched onto bone. Inventories of livestock marked with notches on sticks that were later formalized into symbolic systems. The oldest confirmed writing on the continent — a set of clay tablets recovered from a collapsed granary foundation near the modern city of Aethel in Rosland — records nothing more poetic than the following: forty-three measures of emmer wheat received from the village of [untranslatable], twelve goats assessed as tribute, one goat dead on arrival, deducted. The first sentence in Mundane history is an accounting dispute.
From these crude beginnings, the city-states grew. They grew unevenly, in fits and starts, with long periods of stagnation punctuated by bursts of innovation or catastrophe. They grew in isolation from one another for the most part, separated by distances that, without roads or organized trade networks, might as well have been oceans. A city-state in the northern Heartlands could flourish and collapse without anyone in Sangrea ever learning it had existed.
The Patchwork of Power
By roughly 10,000 BE — and here the dates become less speculative, anchored by cross-referenced astronomical observations carved into stone monuments — the continent hosted hundreds of independent city-states in varying stages of development. They defied easy categorization. The Magos have identified at least nine distinct forms of governance operating simultaneously across the continent during this period:
Theocratic city-states dominated by priest-kings who claimed to mediate between the human and divine — common in the Heartlands, where the ziggurats and stone circles whose ruins still break the skyline were constructed as astronomical observatories and sacrificial platforms both. The priest-kings interpreted the stars, declared the planting seasons, and demanded tribute in grain and labor for construction projects whose purpose was as much theological as practical: build high enough and you can touch whatever put the stars there.
Merchant oligarchies controlled the coastal settlements of what would become the Horns and Nionia — pragmatic, transactional societies where authority belonged to whoever controlled the most trade goods. The earliest Nionian settlements were fishing villages whose headmen accumulated power by monopolizing salt production, an essential commodity in a world without refrigeration. From salt monopolies grew fleet ownership, from fleets grew the capacity to project force, and from force grew the first island polities.
Warrior aristocracies ruled in Rosland and the northern reaches, where the constant pressure of raids — from whom is unclear; possibly from other human groups, possibly from the large predatory fauna that was still abundant — produced societies where military capability was the primary qualification for leadership. The first "First Citizens" of Rosland were simply the best fighters in their communities, chosen by acclamation after battle.
Matrilineal clan structures persisted in the Frozen South, where the harsh environment enforced cooperation and punished hierarchy. Leadership was situational — the best hunter led the hunt, the best navigator led the migration, the eldest woman settled disputes — and no individual held permanent authority. This system proved so durable that it survives in modified form to the present day.
In Xaria, the temple bureaucracy of the Ix'Atani operated on principles entirely alien to the rest of the continent: a theocratic command economy in which every resource, every labor hour, and every human life was understood as currency in the Great Exchange with the gods. The Xarian city-states were not independent polities in the Mundane sense. They were administrative nodes in a religious network whose center lay across the eastern ocean, receiving directives from a priesthood that answered to authorities the continent would never see.
And then there were the stranger experiments — the ones that didn't last, that exist only in fragments: a city-state near the modern Teeth that appears to have been governed by designated eunuchs, its rationale lost; a settlement in the Red Coast whose ruins suggest governance by lottery, with leaders chosen at random from the adult population for fixed terms; a Heartlands community that seems to have been run by a council of the eldest members, period, regardless of any other qualification, a gerontocracy so absolute that all records were kept in the memories of the old rather than committed to clay, and which therefore vanished without trace when a plague carried off everyone over forty.
This was the world's great experiment in human organization, conducted simultaneously across a continental laboratory with no communication between the test sites. Every conceivable answer to the question "who should be in charge?" was tried somewhere, and most of them failed within a few generations, leaving behind only foundations and puzzles for later scholars to misinterpret.
The Lost Arts
It is during this long middle period of the Age of History — roughly 15,000 to 5,000 BE — that the most troubling archaeological evidence emerges. Troubling because it implies capabilities that the present world cannot replicate and cannot explain.
In the deep Heartlands, buried beneath the foundations of structures built during the Age of Fire, Magos excavation teams have uncovered metal cylinders of a type that no modern smith can identify. The metal is not iron, not bronze, not copper, not any alloy in current use. It resists corrosion absolutely. It is harder than tempered steel. And the cylinders — roughly two feet in length, hollow, open at one end and sealed at the other — show scorch marks on their interiors consistent with intense, directed heat. When a Magos artificer filled a recovered cylinder with black powder (a substance known to alchemists but considered too unstable and too expensive for practical use), sealed the open end with a stone ball, and ignited the charge, the ball was propelled with enough force to punch through a wooden wall at fifty paces. The Magos suppressed the report. The experiment was not repeated. The cylinder was locked in a vault on the Isle of Knowledge, where it remains.
These are not isolated finds. In the northern Heartlands, a collapsed underground chamber yielded a set of interlocking metal gears — dozens of them, machined to tolerances that modern clockmakers envy — that appear to be the remnants of a mechanical device of unknown purpose. In the Sierras de Sangre, a road-building crew unearthed a vehicle chassis: a reinforced wooden frame mounted on iron-rimmed wheels, with attachment points for what appear to have been armor plates and some kind of forward-facing projection mechanism. The chassis was too deteriorated to reconstruct, but the engineering drawings found nearby — scratched onto sheets of hammered copper that survived where parchment would have rotted — showed a war machine of startling sophistication: an armored, wheeled vehicle designed to be propelled by... something. The propulsion mechanism was on a separate sheet. That sheet was never found.
What these artifacts represent is a matter of ferocious debate among the Magos. The maximalist interpretation is that at least one city-state during the middle Age of History achieved a level of technological development comparable to or exceeding the imperial period, including functional gunpowder weapons and mechanical engineering. The minimalist interpretation is that these are isolated experiments by individual geniuses — the Da Vincis of their age — that were never scaled, never replicated, and died with their creators.
The truth, in the Magos' considered opinion, is probably worse than either interpretation. The artifacts are too widely distributed, found across too many sites and too many regions, to be the work of lone inventors. They suggest a period of genuine technological advancement — possibly spanning centuries — that was subsequently lost. Not gradually forgotten, but actively destroyed. The sites where these artifacts are found share a common feature: evidence of catastrophic fire. Libraries burned. Workshops collapsed and buried. Repositories sealed and abandoned. Something happened — a war, a religious purge, a deliberate suppression of knowledge — that erased an entire technological tradition from the historical record so thoroughly that the people who came after didn't even know it had existed.
The Age of Fire completed what that earlier catastrophe began. The Nionic emperors, building their roads and garrisons across the continent, demolished ancient sites for raw material without any understanding of what they were destroying. Tablets were crushed for gravel. Metal artifacts were melted for nails. And the oral traditions that might have preserved some memory of what had been lost were suppressed along with local languages, replaced by imperial Munnish and the official history of the Nionian Creed, which held that civilization began with Nion the Conqueror and everything before him was barbarism.
By the present day, the lost arts survive only as rumors and locked vaults. A peasant plowing a field in the Heartlands occasionally turns up a gear or a fragment of unfamiliar metal and brings it to the local lord, who either ignores it or, if he's ambitious, sends it to the Isle of Knowledge, where it joins a growing collection of things nobody can explain. The Magos catalogue these finds meticulously. They do not share their conclusions. The implications are too unsettling: that the world has been smarter than this before, and forgot.

III. The Twilight of the Old World (c. 5,000 – 1,211 BE)
The Slow Consolidation
As the millennia ground on, the hundreds of isolated city-states began, slowly and unevenly, to become aware of one another. Trade was the mechanism. A coastal settlement in the Horns that produced surplus salt discovered that an inland settlement in the Heartlands fringe would trade grain for it. A Red Coast community with access to copper ore found buyers in Sangrea who had none. These exchanges were initially local — a day's walk, a river crossing — but over centuries they extended, link by link, into networks that spanned regions.
Trade demanded communication. Communication demanded a degree of linguistic standardization. The common root language that all Mundane populations shared — buried beneath millennia of regional divergence — began, in the mercantile context, to resurface. Traders developed pidgins: simplified, shared vocabularies stripped of local idiom, designed for transactional clarity. Buy. Sell. Price. Weight. Good. Bad. These pidgins, over generations, stabilized into a common trading tongue that would eventually become the ancestor of Munnish — though at this stage it had no name, no written form, and no pretensions to being anyone's primary language. People spoke their local dialect at home and switched to the trade-tongue at the market. The habit of code-switching — speaking one way among your own people and another way among outsiders — became so deeply embedded that it persists to the present day, thirteen hundred years after the empire that formalized the common tongue has turned to dust.
With trade came conflict. With conflict came alliance. With alliance came the first multi-city polities: leagues, confederations, and petty kingdoms that controlled river systems or coastal stretches and could project force beyond their own walls. The priest-kings of the Heartlands ziggurats, whose authority had been local and absolute, found themselves competing with neighbors who worshipped different gods and possessed different armies. The merchant oligarchs of the proto-Nionian coast discovered that trade disputes could be resolved more efficiently with warships than with negotiation. The warrior aristocrats of Rosland, who had fought among themselves for generations, began to organize into larger coalitions capable of mounting campaigns against external threats.
This was not progress in any neat, linear sense. Polities formed and collapsed constantly. A successful confederation might dominate a river valley for three generations and then shatter when its founding dynasty produced an incompetent heir. A trading league might control a coastline for a century and then dissolve when a new overland route made its ports irrelevant. The political map of Mundus during this period was a kaleidoscope, its patterns shifting with every generation, leaving behind layers of ruins, abandoned fortifications, and confused genealogies that would puzzle scholars for the next forty thousand years.
The Great Beasts and the Thinning World
It was during this late Age of History that the world, by all accounts, was still thick with the monstrous and the uncanny.
The oral traditions of every region on the continent — traditions that agree on almost nothing else — converge on one point: the old world was not like the present one. It was wilder. Larger. More dangerous. And more alive with things that no longer exist.
The fire-songs of the Frozen South describe creatures called Ice-Striders — four-legged beasts taller than a longhouse, with tusks of blue ice that never melted. The Red Coast canyon paintings depict broad-skulled animals that match no living species. Sangrean harvest ballads reference "the great cats of the mountain, whose roar shook fruit from the trees," animals far larger than any modern predator. In the Heartlands, foundation stones of the oldest ziggurats bear carvings of winged serpents with bodies thicker than a man's torso. In the Horns, the tidal caves contain bone deposits from marine creatures of staggering size — jawbones six feet across, vertebrae the diameter of mill wheels.
Whether these were natural animals adapted to a younger, richer ecosystem or something more — creatures imbued with whatever metaphysical force the theologians call "echoes" — is a question that generates more theology than zoology. The Ashanite clergy maintain that all life carries a divine spark and that the great beasts were simply creatures whose sparks burned brighter, living relics of a world closer to the moment of creation. The Ayanite scholars counter that the beasts were natural animals, impressive but explicable, and that attributing divinity to them is superstition. The Alonite orders, characteristically, don't care what they were. They care that they killed people, and they killed them back.
What is less debatable is that the great beasts declined. The decline was not sudden. It was a slow bleeding, stretched across thousands of years, driven by the same forces that drove human civilization forward: habitat destruction, hunting, competition for resources, and the steady expansion of agricultural land into wilderness. Every field cleared for grain was a field where nothing wild could live. Every city wall built was a boundary drawn against the natural world. Every road cut through a forest was a wound that healed as farmland, not as forest.
By the time the first republics emerged, around 1,200 BE, the great beasts were already rare. By the time the Nionic Empire consolidated its hold, they were legends. By the present day, they are myths — stories told to children, carved into old stones, dismissed by educated men as the exaggerations of primitive ancestors who mistook large animals for monsters.
But the bones are real. The Magos have measured them. And in the deepest wilderness — the interior of the Bosque Muerto Austral, the unmapped canyons of the Red Coast, the abyssal waters off the Frozen South — there are still, occasionally, reports. Tracks too large to be any known animal. Shadows in the water that surface and submerge without explanation. Sounds in the night that no one wants to investigate.
The world thinned. But perhaps it has not finished thinning yet.

IV. The Birth of the Republic (c. 1,211 BE)
Aethel and the Philosophical Revolution
The transition from the Age of History to the Age of Republics is dated, by convention, to a single event: the overthrow of the priest-king of the city of Aethel, in what is now western Rosland.
Aethel was not the largest city on the continent. It was not the wealthiest. It was not the most militarily powerful. What it was, by the twelfth century before the Age of Fire, was exhausted. Its priest-kings had ruled for generations through a combination of astronomical expertise, ritual authority, and the threat of divine displeasure. They told the people when to plant. They told them when to harvest. They told them which gods to appease and how much grain to sacrifice. And for a long time, this arrangement worked, because the priest-kings' astronomical calculations were genuinely good and the harvests genuinely came.
But the last of Aethel's priest-kings — his name is recorded variously as Yrrol, Irrol, or Erral, depending on which fragment one trusts — was not a competent astronomer. He was an inheritor, a man who had received power without the knowledge that justified it. His planting predictions were wrong. His harvest calculations were disastrous. The granaries emptied. The people starved. And when they asked the priest-king why the gods were angry, he did what incompetent rulers always do: he demanded more sacrifice, more tribute, more submission, insisting that the problem was insufficient faith rather than insufficient competence.
The people of Aethel responded with what the Magos, in their dry way, call "the Philosophical Revolution." It was not, in truth, especially philosophical. It was a riot. A hungry mob stormed the ziggurat, dragged the priest-king from his observatory, and threw him into the river. He drowned. The mob, suddenly leaderless and uncertain what to do next, did something unprecedented: they talked about it. In the plaza where the ziggurat's shadow fell, the surviving elders, merchants, and soldiers of Aethel debated — for three days, according to the most reliable account — what should come next.
The conclusion they reached was radical in its simplicity: no more priest-kings. No more hereditary authority. No more claiming that the gods had chosen you to rule. Instead, leaders would be selected by the community based on demonstrated capability. The best farmer would advise on agriculture. The best soldier would lead in war. The best speaker would arbitrate disputes. And all of them would serve at the pleasure of the citizens, who could remove them if they failed.
This was the first republic. It was messy, contentious, frequently dysfunctional, and completely unprecedented. It was also, within a generation, visibly superior to every alternative in the region. Aethel's agricultural output stabilized under competent management. Its trade expanded as merchants, freed from arbitrary priestly taxes, invested in new routes. Its military improved as command positions went to capable officers rather than well-born incompetents. Neighboring city-states noticed. Some emulated. Some resisted. Some tried to conquer Aethel and discovered that a city whose citizens fight because they chose their own leaders fights harder than a city whose citizens fight because a priest told them to.
The republican model spread — not as a uniform system, but as a principle that each city adapted to its own circumstances and traditions. What emerged over the following centuries was the patchwork of rival republics described at the opening of the next age: the Aethelian democracy in Rosland, the Nionian oligarchy on the Isle of Kings, the Roslandic stratocracy, and dozens of smaller experiments that didn't survive long enough to earn names in the historical record.
Aethel itself endured. It endures still, in 1308 of the Age of Faith — battered by the Nionic conquest, occupied for nine centuries, liberated by the empire's collapse, and now the symbolic heart of the Roslandic democratic tradition. Its old plaza, where the priest-king drowned and the first republic was argued into existence, is paved with the same stones. Roslandic citizens swear oaths there. House Ironside's reformers avoid it. The stones remember what was decided on them, and so do the people who walk them.

That's the Age of History complete — from first peoples to the birth of the republics. It establishes the deep past as mysterious but grounded, accounts for the indigenous populations and the Great Migration, plants the lost technology as a Chekhov's gun for later use, handles the mythical beasts as an ecological tragedy rather than a simple magical decline, and lands on Aethel as a living monument that gives the present-day political conflicts emotional weight.
Good — that locks in several important things. The deep history is the Magos' secret knowledge, which makes the Isle of Knowledge not just a library but potentially the most dangerous place on the continent. Anyone who controls what the Magos know controls the future. And the lost tech being split between the Isle and a secret vault in the Teeth means there are at least two points of vulnerability — two locks that could be picked.
The Xaria picture is clear now: it's a colonial frontier run by a minor royal who's comfortable as long as tribute flows, with a capital that faces outward toward the Dominion rather than inward toward Mundus. Kaeo living there under patronage makes him a man between worlds — a mainlander who's been inside the machine of a foreign empire, which means he understands power structures that nobody back home has ever seen. That's going to make him both valuable and suspect. We'll get to that.
Now — the Age of Republics. This is the era that sets up everything the Nionic Empire later destroys, and everything the present-day factions are unconsciously trying to rebuild. It needs to feel like a golden age that rotted from within.

THE AGE OF REPUBLICS (c. 1,211 BE – 0 AF)
Preamble: The Shape of the Record
The Age of Republics is the best-documented period of pre-imperial history, and still poorly documented. The republican city-states, unlike their theocratic predecessors, valued record-keeping as a civic function rather than a priestly monopoly. They produced administrative archives, legal codes, diplomatic correspondence, and — for the first time — works of speculative thought: philosophical treatises, natural observations, and political theory written not to appease gods but to understand the world as it was.
Much of this was destroyed during the Nionic conquest. The emperor's armies burned selectively — targeting the archives of cities that resisted, preserving those that surrendered quickly enough to be useful. The result is a historical record riddled with gaps whose shape tells its own story: we know the most about cities that capitulated and the least about cities that fought hardest, which means the record is systematically biased toward compliance. The Magos are aware of this problem. They compensate where they can, cross-referencing surviving fragments from destroyed cities with diplomatic records from cities that preserved their archives. But the honest assessment, stated plainly in the Magos' own internal catalogues, is this: for every document that survives from the Age of Republics, approximately forty were lost. We are reading the chapter headings of a library that burned.
What follows is the best reconstruction available, assembled from fragments, inferences, and the physical evidence of ruins that still stand.

I. The Republican Flowering (c. 1,211 – 600 BE)
The Spread of the Idea
The overthrow of Aethel's priest-king did not immediately transform the continent. Ideas, in a world without printing presses or reliable postal services, traveled at the speed of trade caravans and gossip. It took generations for the Aethelian experiment to become visible enough to inspire emulation, and longer still for other cities to adapt its principles to their own circumstances.
The first century after Aethel's revolution was, for most of the continent, indistinguishable from the era that preceded it. Priest-kings still ruled in the Heartlands. The Nionian salt merchants still ran their island as a commercial fiefdom. The Roslandic warrior clans still chose their chiefs by who could hold a shield-wall longest. Xaria continued its sacrificial economy without interruption or interest in what the western barbarians were doing with their governance. The Frozen South didn't know Aethel existed and wouldn't have cared if it did.
What changed first was trade. Aethel's republican government, by distributing decision-making authority among capable citizens rather than concentrating it in a single priestly lineage, proved more responsive to economic opportunity. Tariffs were adjusted based on market conditions rather than theological whim. Trade agreements were negotiated by merchants who understood commerce rather than priests who understood ritual. Disputes were arbitrated by elected judges whose rulings could be appealed rather than by divine decree, which could not. The practical result was that Aethel became easier to do business with than its neighbors, and business flowed toward it like water toward a low point.
Traders who visited Aethel brought back more than goods. They brought back the unsettling observation that a city without a king was functioning better than their city with one. This information spread unevenly and was received unevenly — with fascination in some quarters, with horror in others, and with a calculating pragmatism in places like Nionia, where the merchant families immediately recognized that the republican model could be adapted to formalize what they were already doing: running things based on who had the most money.
Over the following centuries, the republican principle — that leaders should earn their authority rather than inherit it — germinated across the continent. But like any seed planted in different soils, it grew into different shapes.
The Republican Models
By roughly 800 BE, at least five major republican experiments were operating simultaneously, each reflecting the culture and pressures of its region. They shared a vocabulary — "citizen," "vote," "assembly," "term" — but the meanings attached to those words varied so dramatically that a citizen of Aethel and a citizen of Nionia would have struggled to recognize each other's system as related.
The Aethelian Democracy (Rosland)
Aethel's system remained the closest to the original revolutionary impulse. All land-owning male citizens had a vote in the city assembly. Leaders were elected for fixed terms and could be recalled by popular vote. Military command rotated among experienced officers selected by the assembly. Legal disputes were adjudicated by panels of citizen-judges chosen by lot.
The system's strength was its responsiveness: bad leaders were removed quickly, policy reflected the genuine interests of the citizen body, and the assembly served as a pressure valve for social tensions that in other cities would have erupted as coups or riots. Its weakness was its narrowness. "Citizen" in Aethel meant land-owning men. Women, laborers, foreigners, and the landless — who collectively outnumbered citizens by roughly four to one — had no political voice. The democracy was real, but it was a democracy of the privileged, and its participants saw no contradiction in this. The right to govern was earned through property, which was earned through labor, which was earned through virtue. If you were landless, you were, by definition, insufficient. The logic was circular, but it held.
Aethel's influence radiated outward through Rosland as other western cities adopted variations of its model. The Roslandic variant, however, evolved a distinctive character shaped by the region's military culture. The constant threat of raids from northern tribal groups — and, more distantly, the pressure of Heartlands expansion — meant that military service was not optional but existential. Over time, this produced the Roslandic Stratocracy: a republican system in which voting rights were tied not to property but to military service. Only veterans could hold office. Only those who had served at least two campaign seasons could vote for the "First Citizen," the elected commander who led the city's forces and administered its laws.
The stratocracy was effective militarily — Roslandic armies were disciplined, experienced, and motivated by a genuine stake in the system they defended. It was also brutally exclusionary. Anyone who could not serve — the disabled, the elderly who had never fought, women, and foreigners — was a non-person politically. The system produced soldiers of extraordinary quality and a civilian population of extraordinary resentment, a tension that would simmer for centuries without resolution.
The Nionian Oligarchy (Isle of Kings)
On the Isle of Kings, the republican principle arrived not as an idealistic revolution but as a pragmatic restructuring. The Nionian merchant families had been running the island as an informal cartel for generations. The "republic" they established was, in essence, the cartel made official: a Senate in which seats were apportioned by wealth, with the richest families holding the most votes.
This was not a cynical corruption of the republican ideal. The Nionians genuinely believed that wealth was the most reliable indicator of competence. A man who could build a trading empire, manage a fleet, and turn a profit across multiple markets had demonstrated the kind of judgment and discipline that governance required. A poor man had demonstrated the opposite. The logic was, again, circular — wealth bought the education and connections that produced more wealth — but the Nionians were comfortable with circularity. They were merchants. Profit justified itself.
The Senate met in a grand chamber on the island's central plateau, a building of white marble that would become infamous four centuries later when Nion the Conqueror locked its doors and burned it. For its first centuries, however, the Senate functioned with a rough efficiency. Tariffs were set by men who understood trade. Naval policy was directed by men who owned ships. Diplomatic relations were managed by men who had personally negotiated with foreign powers. The results — a powerful navy, a prosperous island, a dominant position in maritime commerce — seemed to validate the system.
The rot was structural, but it took time to become visible. The problem was simple: wealth concentrated. The founding generation of the Senate included roughly thirty families of broadly comparable means. Within two centuries, consolidation through marriage, inheritance, and market dominance had reduced effective control to fewer than a dozen. Within four centuries, three families controlled more than half the Senate's votes. The remaining seats were held by minor families who functioned as clients, selling their votes to whichever patron offered the best terms. Legislation was no longer a product of deliberation but of auction: laws went to the highest bidder.
The common people of Nionia — the fishermen, miners, quarry workers, and sailors who constituted the island's actual labor force — had never had political rights under the oligarchic system. For generations, they tolerated this because the system delivered prosperity: the fleets brought wealth, the wealth funded construction, construction provided employment, and employment provided food. But as the Senate calcified into a vehicle for dynastic enrichment rather than public administration, the bargain eroded. Taxes rose. Public works stalled. The navy, once the pride of the island, was neglected in favor of private merchant fleets that served the great families' commercial interests rather than the island's security. The common people grew hungry, and hungry people develop opinions about governance that comfortable people find inconvenient.
By the final century of the Age of Republics, the Nionian Senate was an institution preserved by inertia rather than legitimacy. The great families hated each other but feared the alternative more. The common people despised the Senate but lacked the organization to challenge it. The island was a powder magazine, and everyone on it could smell the fuse.
Into this situation walked a young naval officer of minor patrician birth, a man of extraordinary charisma and absolutely no patience for consensus. His name was Nion. He would not tolerate the Senate for long.
The Heartlands Confederation
The Heartlands never achieved a single republican model. The region was too large, too geographically varied, and too politically fragmented to produce a unified system. What emerged instead was a loose confederation of city-states connected by trade agreements, mutual defense pacts, and a shared cultural identity rooted in the river systems that connected them.
The major Heartlands cities — Aethel's eastern cousins, though they would have bristled at the comparison — developed their own governance structures independently. Some adopted assemblies modeled on the Aethelian pattern. Others retained hereditary leadership but constrained it with councils of merchants or landowners. A few experimented with systems that anticipated the later Argenlord model: elected figureheads whose authority was largely ceremonial except in crisis, when they could compel resources and manpower from otherwise autonomous communities.
The Heartlands' great advantage was its agricultural wealth. The central plains produced grain surpluses that made the region the breadbasket of the continent, and grain gave the Heartlands leverage that no military force could match. An army marches on its stomach, and the Heartlands controlled the stomachs. This economic centrality allowed the Heartlands cities to remain relatively stable even as the republics elsewhere began to decay, but it also bred a complacency that would prove fatal. The Heartlands assumed their wealth made them indispensable. They were correct. But indispensable is not the same as unconquerable, and when Nion's legions arrived, the granaries burned as easily as the senates.
Sangrea: The Dynastic Republics
Sangrea never truly embraced republicanism. What it embraced was the aesthetics of republicanism — the language of citizen virtue, the architecture of public assembly, the legal frameworks of civic participation — layered over a social reality that remained fundamentally aristocratic. The great Sangrean families, who controlled the fertile river valleys and the coastal trade, adopted republican titles and held elections that they invariably won, creating what modern Magos scholars call "dynastic republics": systems that looked democratic on parchment and functioned as hereditary oligarchies in practice.
The two poles of Sangrean power — the houses that would eventually become Solé and Terrarossa, though they went by different names in the republican period — competed through a cycle of economic rivalry, proxy warfare, and theatrical public politics that the Sangrean people watched with the avidity of spectators at a bullfight. The elections were real, in the sense that votes were cast and counted. They were also predetermined, in the sense that the candidates were always drawn from the same handful of families and the outcome was always decided by who had spent the most on bribes, festivals, and public works in the preceding season.
This system produced a culture of extraordinary flamboyance and equally extraordinary inequality. The great families lived in palaces of breathtaking opulence, hosted festivals that lasted for weeks, and competed with each other in displays of generosity that were, in reality, displays of dominance. The common people received the festivals' scraps and the families' contempt, and they were expected to be grateful for both. The Sunstone Wars — a recurring cycle of armed conflicts between the two great dynastic poles, fought over mining rights, trade routes, and raw prestige — provided periodic employment for the peasantry as soldiers and periodic devastation for the peasantry as civilians, a rhythm of exploitation so reliable it became a cultural institution.
Xaria: The Exception
Xaria did not participate in the republican movement. The peninsula's temple-cities continued to operate under the theocratic command economy of the Ix'Atani Dominion, answering to religious authorities whose seat of power lay across the eastern ocean. Republican ideas, when they arrived via mainland traders, were received with the polite incomprehension that a priest reserves for a heretic who hasn't realized he's damned.
The Great Exchange did not accommodate the concept of citizen choice. Life was an economy of sacrifice. The gods demanded their due. A human being who presumed to choose his own leader was a human being who presumed to choose his own god, which was not a political act but a cosmic one — a disruption of the sacrificial balance that could, if unchecked, cause the sun to falter. The Xarian priests did not argue against republicanism. They simply could not process it as a meaningful category. It was like arguing against weather.
This theological immunity to political reform gave Xaria a stability that the mainland republics envied and resented. While the Aethelian assembly debated and the Nionian Senate corroded, the temple-cities of Xaria hummed along with the reliable efficiency of a machine that runs on blood. The quotas were met. The tribute flowed eastward. The ruler — currently a member of a minor royal house of the Dominion who had been given the frontier posting as a reward for loyal service and was content to govern with a light hand as long as the numbers added up — administered his domain from a capital perched on the continent's eastern edge, where the view from his palace looked not inward toward the chaotic mainland but outward across the water toward the islands that led home.
The Xarian capital was, by all accounts, magnificent. Built on a promontory above the sea, it combined the Ix'Atani architectural tradition — massive stone platforms, step-pyramids faced with jade and obsidian, plazas designed to hold thousands for ritual observance — with a colonial pragmatism that the heartland empire would have found vulgar. The harbor was functional rather than ceremonial. The warehouses were larger than the temples. The governor's palace, while impressive, was oriented toward the docks rather than the sky, a building designed for a man who watched his shipping rather than his stars. Cacao, timber, jade, exotic pelts, medicinal plants, and a steady stream of enslaved laborers moved through the harbor toward the Dominion. In return came finished goods, religious directives, and the occasional inspector who confirmed that the quotas were met, nodded approvingly, and sailed home.
The mainland peoples viewed Xaria with a mixture of fear and fascination. The jungle was impenetrable. The religion was barbaric. The sacrifices were an abomination. And the wealth was staggering. Traders who dealt with Xarian merchants returned with goods of a quality and variety that no mainland workshop could match — dyes that didn't fade, medicines that actually worked, fabrics softer than anything produced by Heartlands looms. The Xarian frontier was a window onto a civilization that the mainland could not see, could not reach, and could not stop thinking about.

II. The Golden Centuries (c. 600 – 200 BE)
The Peak of Republican Achievement
For roughly four centuries — a span as long as the entire current Age of Faith — the republican model delivered results that, in hindsight, look like the high-water mark of pre-imperial civilization.
Trade networks matured into genuine economic systems. The Inner Sea Necklace — the maritime loop connecting Nionia, the Horns, and the Teeth — became the continent's commercial backbone, moving goods at a volume and speed that overland caravans could not match. The Great Grainway, an overland route connecting the Heartlands' agricultural surplus to the western cities, fed populations that had outgrown their local food production. The Copper Road linked the Red Coast's mineral wealth to the Heartlands' manufacturing centers. These were not planned systems. They were emergent — the product of thousands of individual decisions by traders, shippers, and merchants who were following profit, not policy. But they functioned with a reliability that later imperial planners would struggle to replicate.
Philosophy flourished. The Aethelian schools — informal gatherings of thinkers who debated in public plazas, teaching anyone who would listen — produced the first systematic investigations of natural phenomena, ethical theory, and political science on the continent. Their work survives only in fragments, mostly quoted in later Magos compilations, but the fragments are extraordinary: a treatise on the movement of celestial bodies that correctly identified the planet's orbital period; an ethical framework arguing that justice is not a divine mandate but a social contract requiring constant renegotiation; a political analysis of tyranny that reads, twelve centuries later, as a precise diagnosis of the disease that would kill the republics themselves.
Construction reached a sophistication that the Age of Fire would equal but never surpass. The Heartlands built levee systems that tamed their rivers for irrigation and transport. Rosland fortified its mountain passes with engineering that would later form the template for imperial military architecture. The Horns developed harbor construction techniques — breakwaters, dredged channels, tidal locks — that modern port cities still use, often without knowing who invented them. Even the Red Coast, isolated by its harsh geography, produced the qanat system: underground aqueducts that carried water from mountain snowmelt to desert settlements, an engineering achievement that no one else on the continent had attempted and that remains, to this day, the only reason human habitation is possible in the deep desert.
This was the period that later generations would romanticize as the golden age. The Roslandic democrats invoke it when they argue for the guild vote. The Heartlands Argenlord system is a conscious echo of the confederal model. Even the Nionian God-King, Jous Lorethian, frames his authority in opposition to it — defining his divine rule as the necessary corrective to the republics' failure. The Age of Republics is not dead history. It is living argument. Every political faction on the continent claims to have learned its lesson and draws opposite conclusions.

III. The Decay (c. 200 – 0 BE)
The Rot Within
The republics did not fall to an external enemy. They fell to themselves.
The mechanisms of decay were different in each city, but the underlying disease was universal: the systems that had been designed to distribute power were captured by the people they were designed to constrain. In every republic, over time, the gap between the theory of civic participation and the reality of entrenched privilege widened until the theory became a performance and the reality became unbearable.
In Nionia, the Senate's corruption became so absolute that legislation was openly bought and sold in the marble corridors. The three dominant families — whose names are lost, their records deliberately destroyed by Nion's regime — treated the island's treasury as a personal account and the island's navy as a private fleet. Public infrastructure crumbled. The quarries went undermaintained. The fishing fleet aged without replacement. A series of bad harvests, which a functional government would have managed through stored reserves and import agreements, instead produced famines that killed thousands while the senatorial families continued to feast.
In Aethel, the rot took a different form: populist demagoguery. The assembly, designed as a forum for reasoned deliberation, became a theater for charismatic speakers who promised the impossible and blamed the foreigner for every failure. Land reform — the redistribution of property that would have expanded the citizen body and renewed the system's legitimacy — was proposed repeatedly and defeated every time by the propertied interests who controlled the assembly's agenda. The landless grew more desperate. The demagogues grew more extreme. The assembly's debates, which had once produced policy, now produced only noise.
In Rosland, the stratocracy calcified into a military aristocracy indistinguishable from the hereditary systems it had replaced. The veteran families who held voting rights passed them to their children, who passed them to theirs, creating a caste of permanent citizens whose military service was increasingly nominal — a formality rather than a genuine obligation. The actual fighting was done by conscripts drawn from the non-citizen population, men who risked their lives for a system that denied them a voice. The First Citizens, once elected by genuine soldiers who had bled together, were now chosen by a comfortable officer class that hadn't seen combat in generations.
In Sangrea, nothing changed, because nothing had ever been real. The dynastic republics continued their theatrical elections, their lavish festivals, and their periodic Sunstone Wars with the reliability of a seasonal weather pattern. The common people continued to suffer. The great families continued to prosper. The only difference was that the pretense of civic virtue, which had once been maintained with some conviction, was now so transparent that even the families themselves had stopped believing it. They went through the motions because the motions were tradition, and tradition was preferable to the effort of inventing something new.
The Continent at the Brink
By the final decades of the Age of Republics — roughly the last fifty years before 0 AF — the continent was locked in a state of endemic dysfunction. The trade networks still functioned, but they were increasingly disrupted by piracy, tariff wars, and the breakdown of the diplomatic agreements that had kept the sea lanes open. The philosophical schools still operated, but their debates had turned inward, producing increasingly abstract and irrelevant work that had no audience outside their own walls. The military establishments still existed, but they were designed to fight each other rather than to meet a unified external threat — which was precisely the vulnerability that a unifier would exploit.
The common people of every republic shared a single, corrosive intuition: the system no longer worked for them. It worked for the families who ran it, for the merchants who profited from it, for the soldiers who enforced it. But for the farmer, the fisherman, the miner, the artisan — the people who actually grew the grain and caught the fish and dug the ore — the republic had become just another word for "the people who take your surplus and give you nothing back." The specific flavor of exploitation varied by region — theological in the Heartlands, commercial in Nionia, military in Rosland, theatrical in Sangrea — but the taste was the same everywhere: the bitterness of being governed by people who had forgotten what governing was for.
Into this exhausted, cynical, fractured world came a man who offered the simplest possible answer to the most complicated question. The question was: who should rule? His answer was: I should. And because the existing answers had all failed, and because he had a navy, and because he was willing to burn anyone who disagreed, his answer carried.
The Great Pyre was not the beginning of something new. It was the cremation of something that had already died. The republics were corpses by the time Nion set them on fire. He merely made the death visible.





