THE AGE OF FIRE (1 AF – 903 AF) — COMPLETE IMPERIAL CHRONICLE
Total Duration: 903 years Dynasty: The Nionic Dynasty (all rulers claim descent or adoption from Nion I) Regnal Name "Nion": Reserved for direct-line heirs or claimants asserting supreme legitimacy. Thirteen total. Other Regnal Names: Taken by nephews, adopted heirs, generals who married into the line, or usurpers who legitimized through the dynasty without claiming the sacred name.

PHASE I: THE CONQUEST (0 – 150 AF)
1. Nion I "the Conqueror" (0 – 55 AF)
Born a quarry laborer's son on Nionia's southern coast. Joined navy at 14. Rose through ranks on merit and ruthlessness.
The Great Pyre (0 AF): Locked the Nionian Senate in their marble chamber and burned it. ~200 senators killed. Handful escaped, including a member of Domus Marcellus.
Edicts of Iron: Abolished private fleets, centralized coinage, nationalized the quarries and mines.
Left his brother Marshal Aelor as Steward of Nionia while he campaigned on the mainland.
The Horns Campaign (2–12 AF): House Garrun of Westhorn surrendered peacefully, became imperial governors. Brinehold bought off. Nightspike besieged and starved for 8 months — its own citizens murdered House Kest and delivered their heads to Nion. Kest extinguished.
Sangrea Campaign (12–30 AF): Allied with House Solé against House Terrarossa. Siege of Altavista lasted 10 years. During tunneling, engineers unearthed remains of a Sun-Basilisk — Nion claimed to have killed it personally (it was already dead). House Ormell annihilated — estates burned, orchards salted, name struck from records. Terrarossa broken but allowed to survive in diminished form. House Solé elevated to imperial governors.
Rosland Campaign (25–40 AF): First major imperial defeat at the Battle of the Western Pass (~28 AF). Roslandic commander Aethric Daurn captured Nion's lieutenant Tertius, served him a feast, then presented him a cup made from a previous invader's skull. Nion didn't try the passes again for 7 years. Instead surrounded Rosland by conquering the Heartlands first. Pact of Iron (35 AF): Rosland entered as protectorate retaining internal governance, military traditions, and institutions. Best terms any territory received. House Daurn elevated to military aristocracy.
Heartlands Campaign (35–55 AF): Longest campaign. No single capital to take. Guerrilla resistance constant. Betrayal of House Marvoss: Marvoss patriarch Aldric offered intelligence and supplies in exchange for protection. Nion used him, then turned on him. Accused of harboring heretics. Aldric forced to watch his three sons thrown from Stonebridge with stones tied to their feet, eldest to youngest. Then beheaded, head mounted on the bridge's central pillar. Marvoss extinguished. Stonebridge — the name stuck despite official renaming.
Death (55 AF): Died in campaign near modern Vornhold. Imperial chronicles claim heroic battlefield death. Magos believe infected wound from mundane accident. Body returned to Nionia, tomb sealed with molten lead.
Family: Wife Isara (died in childbirth, 22 AF). One son, Nion (died age 7, fever). One daughter, Livia, married to General Hadros. Brother Marshal Aelor survived him and took the throne.
Legacy: Unified currency (the Iron Mark). Began the road system. Established the noble house structure. Created the Imperium Guard as personal bodyguard. Tomb location on Nionia is still known — never opened.
2. Aelor I "the Builder" (55 – 85 AF) (nephew, not a Nion)
Nion I's nephew and Steward of Nionia during the conquest. Competent administrator, no charisma.
Completed Vallan and Teeth campaigns. Vallan submitted with minimal resistance — cantons were too small and isolated to fight. House Highwell elevated as governors.
Bridge-Throat Massacre (62 AF): 500 Teeth defenders accepted surrender terms, were marched onto the Great Bridge, disarmed, and thrown into the sea in groups of ten. House Fenn extinguished. The bridge-building technique fenn-joint is named for them — nobody has replicated it since.
Began systematic construction of the imperial road network. Established the road-warden corps. Built the first standardized garrisons — rectangular stone forts at two-day intervals along major routes.
Family: Married twice. First wife died young (no children). Second wife Sera of House Garrun (political marriage binding Horns to dynasty). Three sons: Cassian (heir), Aelor (died in naval accident, age 19), Marius (governor of the Teeth).
Died of a stroke at 67. Unremarkable death for a man whose life was engineering.
3. Cassian I "the Stern" (85 – 125 AF) (not a Nion)
Aelor's eldest son. Political officer, gifted administrator, capacity for systematic cruelty.
Red Coast Campaigns (85–105 AF): Desert warfare. Conquered oasis by oasis, exploiting water scarcity — cut a settlement's qanat and it surrenders or dies. Elevated House Zaran as provincial lords.
Salt Crucifixions (~95 AF): 1,000 captured Red Coast defenders nailed to wooden frames on evaporating salt flats. Bodies mummified in mineral air. Visible for decades — standing rows of preserved corpses in the white waste.
Xarian Campaign (100–110 AF): Raided coastal temple-city of Ix'Pal. House T'shaal (coastal merchants who opposed the temples) destroyed in the chaos — burned by the temple authorities, not by the imperials. Cassian negotiated tribute arrangement with the Ix'Atani governor. Xaria became tributary, not conquered. Imperial flag flew over the governor's palace as decoration. Everyone understood the arrangement.
Created the imperial postal system. Standardized weights and measures. Centralized tax collection.
Family: Wife Valeria of House Marcellus (binding old Nionian patriciate to dynasty). Two sons: Nion (heir, took the regnal name), Lucius (military governor of Sangrea, killed in a Sunstone bandit ambush, 118 AF). One daughter: Cassiana, married into House Solé.
Died in bed, age 72. Last words reportedly a complaint about tax receipts from the Horns being late.
4. Nion II "the Watcher" (125 – 158 AF)
Cassian's eldest son. Paranoid, insomniac, effective.
Inherited a continent formally conquered but barely pacified. Rebellions simmering everywhere.
Built watchtowers on every hilltop in the Heartlands. Fortified every crossroad. Established the Vigils — an intelligence network of informers planted in every provincial administration, every guild, every military unit.
His court magician, known only as "the Ash-Speaker", claimed the emperor communed nightly with spirits of extinct volcanoes. Whether genuine mysticism, stimulant addiction euphemized as religion, or deliberate theater is unclear. The intelligence it produced was real — several rebellions crushed before they organized.
The Raven Conspiracy (139 AF): A cabal of Heartlands prefects plotting to declare independence. The Vigils identified all twelve conspirators. Nion II had them arrested simultaneously across four provinces on the same night. Executed by drowning in the rivers they'd planned to use as their new borders.
Expanded fortress networks. Built the first Watchtower at the Horns forest-gate — the seed of what would become the forest city.
Family: Wife Oriana (a Roslandic noblewoman, political marriage — she reportedly despised him). Four sons: Aurelius (heir), Cassian (died in infancy), Hadros (military career, died at 45 in skirmish), Septimus (became a scholar, never held power). Two daughters: married into Houses Garrun and Zaran.
Died at 61. Allegedly hadn't slept in years. Cause of death listed as "exhaustion" — possibly an honest assessment.
5. Aurelius I "the Sailor" (158 – 190 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion II's eldest son. Obsessed with naval exploration. Competent but distracted ruler.
Expanded the imperial navy beyond military function into exploration. Launched three major expeditions to the Frozen South. First two returned with fragmentary reports of ice-choked fjords, gold-bearing mountains, and hostile clans. Third expedition lost entirely — 12 ships, ~1,400 men, never returned. Crews from earlier expeditions reported "leviathans of the ice" — massive marine creatures in the southern waters.
Founded House Torr — granted the admiralty title and a permanent naval estate on Nionia to his most capable fleet commander, a man named Torr who had captained all three southern expeditions and survived two of them.
Domestically, a hands-off ruler. Let the provincial governors self-manage. This worked because the system was still functional, but established a precedent of imperial disengagement that later emperors would exploit into neglect.
Family: Wife Elara of House Torr (married after founding the house — binding the new naval aristocracy to the dynasty). Two sons: Nion (heir), Valens (military career). One daughter: Isara, married into House Belorn of the Heartlands.
Died at sea during a private voyage along the Horns coast. Ship capsized in a storm. Body recovered. Ironic death for a man who had survived the southern ice.
6. Nion III "the Hammer" (190 – 218 AF)
Aurelius's eldest son. Brutal warlord. Possibly the most violent emperor after Nion V.
The Iron Forest Massacre (~200 AF): Sangrea. A rebel wood — a forest that harbored anti-imperial guerrillas for decades — was clear-cut entirely. Every tree felled. Then 20,000 peasants from surrounding villages (accused of supporting rebels) impaled on the stumps. The "forest" of stakes was visible for miles. Took weeks to die. The area is still called the Campo de Estacas in Sangrean dialect.
Claimed his black war-elephants were bred from the last Stoneback Beasts — massive armored quadrupeds thought extinct. Whether genuine surviving megafauna or simply large elephants decorated with bone armor is debated.
Expanded the gladiatorial system from entertainment to population control — captured rebels, criminals, and excess slaves funneled into arenas in every major city.
Family: Three wives (first two died — one in childbirth, one "accidentally" during a hunt). Third wife Seraphina of House Solé. Six children total across three marriages. Heir: Nion (took the name). Other notable child: daughter Livia, who became a powerful political operator and outlived three emperors.
Died at 56 during a banquet. Suspected poisoning by his third wife's family, never proven.
7. Nion IV "the Pious" (218 – 251 AF)
Nion III's eldest surviving son. Religious fanatic devoted to the Old Way.
Rebuilt and expanded every major temple of the Nionian Pantheon. Commissioned massive new temple complexes in every provincial capital. Demanded mass sacrifices — animals primarily, but prisoners during high festivals.
The Festival of Ashes (~235 AF): Annual ceremony institutionalized under his reign. Prisoners burned alive in the capital plaza as offerings to the Ashen Phoenix, a mythical bird said to appear once every age. Largest single Festival: 3,000 burned. Witnesses reported a firebird shape in the smoke above the pyres — either genuine phenomenon, collective hallucination, or a trained raptor daubed in phosphorescent oil. The theological establishment declared it real. The Magos remain silent.
His religious zeal alienated the provinces, who saw the sacrifices as Nionian cultural imperialism — none of the provincial cultures worshipped the Old Way with this intensity.
Family: Wife Helena (a cousin — dynasty was starting to intermarry). Two sons: Hadros (heir, took a different regnal name), one younger son who joined the priesthood of Nionus Axke. One daughter, unmarried, devoted herself to the cult of Fortia.
Died at 64. Natural causes. His cult of personality collapsed almost immediately after his death — his specific brand of zealotry required his personal energy to sustain.
8. Hadros I "the Architect" (251 – 287 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion IV's eldest son. Reaction against his father's fanaticism — purely secular ruler focused on construction.
Greatest builder since Aelor I. Expanded the Great Bridge of the Teeth. Built monumental palace complexes in the Heartlands. Constructed the first stone aqueducts in Sangrea.
Used enslaved labor from the Teeth — including creatures the chronicles describe as "half-crab, half-men," probably a coastal species of large crustacean-like animals now extinct. Worked until they died. Nobody knows what they actually were.
Elevated House Belorn in the Heartlands from minor landholders to prefects — rewarded for logistical support during construction campaigns.
Family: Wife Antonia of House Daurn (binding Roslandic military aristocracy tighter to dynasty). Three sons: Nion (heir), Cassian (governor of the Horns, competent), Hadros II (died in construction accident at 22 — crushed by a falling column, which the court found deeply ironic given his father's profession). Two daughters.
Died at 68. In bed, surrounded by architectural plans. The Magos note that his cities still stand, but their basements — where the enslaved laborers were housed — are said to be haunted.
9. Nion V "the Bloody" (287 – 308 AF)
Hadros I's eldest son. Psychotic. Most hated emperor in the dynasty's history.
The Roslandic Blood-Pits (~295 AF): Mass execution of Roslandic nobility in quarries outside Aethel. Nobles forced to fight each other with blunted weapons while the emperor watched. Last man standing: blinded, tongue cut, sent home. House Hyren — one of the oldest veteran families — extinguished entirely. Their ruins in the western mountains became a pilgrimage site for Roslandic democrats.
Hosted gladiatorial games featuring captured Bone-Tusks — giant boars with ivory ridges, hunted from the Heartlands forests specifically for the arena. Species went extinct during his reign.
Purged the Vigils intelligence network and replaced it with personal enforcers called the Crimson Watch — less effective but more loyal to him specifically.
Family: Four wives (two divorced, one died "of sadness," one survived him). Numerous children, most disowned. Heir: his nephew Valens, who was raised by the military rather than the court.
Assassinated at 45 by a kitchen servant who put glass shards in his wine. The servant — a Roslandic woman whose family had died in the blood-pits — was executed by flaying. Her name is not recorded in imperial sources. In Roslandic fire-songs, she is called Maren of the Broken Cup.
10. Valens I "the Ironhand" (308 – 341 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion V's nephew, raised in military camps. Professional soldier. Austere, disciplined, humorless.
Restored order after Nion V's chaotic reign. Professionalized the legions — standardized training, equipment, rotation schedules. Reduced reliance on house levies in favor of a standing imperial army.
The Torvac Rebellion (310–318 AF): The empire's most dangerous slave revolt. Torvac, born on the Isle of Emberstone (the Teeth), son of quarry slaves. Sold to gladiatorial school at 12. Survived the arena 6 years. At ~22, killed his handlers, freed 70 gladiators, escaped into the Heartlands. Within a year: 6,000 followers. Within two years: 30,000. Organized rebel army into cohorts modeled on imperial legions. Burned granaries, blocked roads, poisoned wells. Defeated two legions in detail. Valens personally commanded the third. Used informers and offered freedom to turncoats. Torvac betrayed by three lieutenants, drugged, bound, delivered. Execution: Flayed alive over a week. Skin salted and stretched on a frame above the gladiatorial school where he was trained. Frame remained for a generation. In the Teeth quarries, slaves carved his likeness into mine walls — some carvings still visible.
His generals carried a gauntlet said to be forged from wyrm-scale. It supposedly shrieked at night. Probably just poorly tempered metal that contracted in the cold, but the legend persisted.
Family: Wife Lucia of House Belorn. One son: Nion (heir). Two daughters: married into Houses Silverblood (founding the Heartlands alliance) and Garrun.
Died at 65. Natural causes. One of the few emperors to die in bed at an advanced age, which says something about his competence.
11. Nion VI "the Drunkard" (341 – 352 AF)
Valens's only son. Exact opposite of his father. Decadent, alcoholic, disengaged.
Imported the last known Glass-Serpents — translucent, venomous snakes from the Xarian jungle fringe — as exotic pets for his court orgies. Poisoned them all in a drunken rage. Species extinct.
Imperial administration functioned on autopilot during his reign — the systems Valens had built were robust enough to survive 11 years of neglect. Barely.
Family: Multiple mistresses, no official wife. Three acknowledged bastards, none considered suitable heirs. Succession crisis after his death.
Died at 38. Choked on his own vomit. The imperial chroniclers described it as "a sudden illness." Nobody was fooled.
12. Nion VII "the Quiet" (352 – 383 AF)
Distant cousin elevated during the succession crisis after Nion VI's death. A compromise candidate nobody expected to last.
Reclusive, obsessed with alchemy. Spent most of his reign in private laboratories.
Paradoxically effective ruler — lowered taxes, stopped the wars, let the provinces self-govern under light oversight. The empire experienced a genuine period of peace.
The Homunculus Court: His strangest legacy. Chronicles claim he created artificial servants — pale, waxy humanoid figures that attended his private chambers. Whether genuine alchemical achievement, elaborate puppetry, or court gossip inflated into legend is unknown. Whatever they were, they "rotted" after his death, and the laboratory wing was sealed.
Family: Wife Seraphina of House Solé (political match, reportedly they barely spoke). One son: adopted — Septimus, a promising young scholar from the Isle of Knowledge. No biological children recorded.
Died at 62. Natural causes. Found in his laboratory. The room was reportedly filled with glass apparatus, chemical residue, and the remains of something "waxy and human-shaped" that decomposed before investigators could examine it.
13. Septimus I "the Chronicler" (383 – 412 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion VII's adopted son. Scholar from the Isle of Knowledge. First emperor with genuine intellectual inclinations rather than mere patronage of learning.
Sponsored the first comprehensive imperial histories — propaganda, but well-written propaganda. Commissioned glorifying accounts of every previous emperor, establishing the "official narrative" that the Magos have spent centuries trying to correct.
Ordered the extinction of Marrow-Bats — massive carrion bats that infested the imperial archives. Said to "drink words from books" — their guano was acidic and dissolved ink. Hunted to extinction across the Heartlands within a decade.
Expanded the Isle of Knowledge's role in imperial administration — Magos scholars assigned to every provincial capital as record-keepers and advisors.
Family: Wife Daria of House Argenhold (Heartlands river nobility). Two sons: Nion (heir), Aurelian (governor of Rosland). Three daughters.
Died at 67. Natural causes. Left behind the most complete set of administrative records in imperial history, which is why the Magos know more about this period than any other.
14. Nion VIII "the Harsh" (412 – 440 AF)
Septimus's eldest son. Absolute disciplinarian. Believed the empire had gone soft under his father and grandfather.
The Vallan Drownings (~420 AF): Crushed a Vallan tax revolt by diverting mountain rivers, flooding three inhabited valleys. Estimated 12,000 civilian deaths. Called "the stone floods" because the water carried so much debris it buried villages in wet rock.
The Woman of the Western Fires — Caelia of Rosland (425–433 AF): Daughter of a veteran family whose husband and sons were conscripted and killed in foreign wars. Led an 8-year guerrilla campaign in the western mountains. Never fielded an army — instead burned tax houses, granary records, census documents, destroying the paperwork that made imperial administration function. Entire civilian population of western Rosland conspired to hide her. Nion VIII responded with collective punishment — the stone floods targeted her support base. Caelia was never captured. Imperial chronicles claim she died in the floods. Roslandic fire-songs say she walked into the mountains and is still there. The Magos note both claims and decline to choose.
Allegedly rode into one battle on a War-Manticore — a massive beast with a poisoned tail. The creature died when its handlers mutinied and cut its throat during a camp dispute over rations. Whether the beast was genuine or an armored composite of existing animals is debated.
Family: Wife Corvina of House Daurn (Roslandic — ironic, given how much Roslandic blood he shed). Two sons: Varran (heir, took a different name as deliberate rejection of his father's legacy), Cassius (military, died in the Vallan campaign). One daughter.
Died at 58. Rumored poisoning — his own wife was suspected, given that he had destroyed half her homeland. Never proven.
15. Varran I "the Just" (440 – 478 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion VIII's eldest son. Took a non-Nion regnal name specifically to distance himself from his father's cruelty.
Codified imperial law — produced the Book of Chains, a comprehensive legal code standardizing criminal penalties, property rights, provincial obligations, tax procedures, and military conduct across the entire continent. The empire's greatest administrative achievement. Still referenced by legal scholars on the Isle of Knowledge.
Commissioned a parallel document: a bestiary that catalogued and legally classified every known mythical and dangerous creature on the continent, establishing regulations for hunting, capture, and extermination. Supposedly cursed himself — "no emperor after ruled without nightmares." Whether genuine supernatural consequence or the psychological weight of cataloguing every horror on the continent is left to interpretation.
Family: Wife Aurelia of House Silverring (first major alliance between the dynasty and the Heartlands mining families). Three sons: Nion (heir), Lucan (governor of Sangrea), Tiberius (entered the Magos order — unusual for imperial family). Two daughters.
Died at 70. Natural causes. The longest-serving non-Nion emperor. Left behind an empire that, on paper, was perfectly organized. The reality, as always, was messier.
16. Nion IX "the Restorer" (478 – 510 AF)
Varran's eldest son. Rebuilder after generations of internal conflict.
Massive provincial reconstruction program — rebuilt war-damaged cities, repaired roads, reorganized Heartlands prefecture system.
The Corpse March (~490 AF): During a rebellion in the Heartlands, Nion IX exhumed the preserved body of Nion I from his lead-sealed tomb on Nionia and carried it across the continent at the head of his army, claiming the Conqueror's spirit led the legions. Whether this was genuine religious conviction, propaganda theater, or the early stages of a mental breakdown is debated. The rebellion collapsed — the sight of the mummified founder apparently terrified the rebel forces more than the army behind it.
Claims his victory near Aethel against Roslandic-supported rebels was aided by the last Storm-Roc — a massive sky-beast reportedly harnessed by court mages. If true, it was the last recorded use of a mythical creature in warfare.
Family: Wife Isara of House Garrun (Horns). Four sons: Cassian (heir), Nion (died age 14 in a riding accident), Aurelius (military career), Hadros (entered priesthood of the Old Way). One daughter.
Died at 63. The lead-sealed tomb was resealed after his death. Whether Nion I's body was returned to it or kept elsewhere is unknown.
17. Cassian II "the Dreamer" (510 – 541 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion IX's eldest son. Pacifist, mystic, possibly narcoleptic.
Peaceful reign — no major wars, no major atrocities. The empire coasted on the momentum of Varran's legal reforms and Nion IX's rebuilding.
Said to "wander the empire in dreams," leaving his body inert on a throne of black salt while his mind traveled. Whether genuine mystical practice, a medical condition, or an elaborate excuse for avoiding governance is unclear. Provincial governors loved him because he never interfered.
Patronized artists and musicians. The first imperial court to include non-martial entertainment as a regular feature. Poetry, painting, and philosophical debate became fashionable among the Nionian elite for the first time.
Family: Wife Lydia of House Beaumont (Heartlands forest nobility). Two sons: Nion (heir), Septimus (scholar). Three daughters, all married into provincial houses across the continent.
Died at 59 in his throne of black salt. Reportedly no one noticed for three days, as his courtiers assumed he was dreaming.
18. Nion X "the Stern" (541 – 568 AF)
Cassian II's eldest son. Reaction against his father's passivity. Harsh disciplinarian.
The Roslandic Mutiny (~550 AF): Roslandic legions — imperial units recruited from the province — refused orders to deploy against a Sangrean uprising, arguing they owed no duty to fight other provinces' wars. Nion X responded with decimation: one in ten Roslandic soldiers executed by their own comrades. The practice had been in the Book of Chains but never enforced. Its use here permanently damaged Roslandic loyalty to the empire.
Forced prisoners from a Heartlands rebellion to march into the Desierto de Ceniza — the Ash Desert on the southeastern border — to "feed the fire spirits." None returned. Whether they died of exposure or were absorbed by desert tribes is unknown.
Family: Wife Cora of House Zaran (Red Coast). Three sons: Aurelian (heir), Nion (governor of the Teeth, competent), Marcus (died in the Roslandic mutiny — killed by the very soldiers being decimated, which added a personal dimension to Nion X's cruelty). Two daughters.
Died at 60. Heart failure. The Magos note his personal physician was Roslandic.
19. Aurelian II "the Scholar" (568 – 600 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion X's eldest son. Intellectual, bookish, genuinely curious.
Elevated the Isle of Knowledge to near-autonomous status — granted the Magos order formal independence from provincial jurisdiction, making the Isle a neutral territory under direct imperial protection. This decision would prove crucial to the preservation of knowledge after the empire fell.
Claimed to have found a living Glass Whale — a massive translucent marine creature — during a naval expedition. Had it captured, transported to a port facility, and dissected over six months by Magos scholars. The dissection notes survive in the Isle's archives. The creature's skeleton was displayed in the imperial capital. Whether it was a genuine unknown species or a creative taxidermist's hoax is the subject of an ongoing Magos debate that has lasted four centuries.
Family: Wife Paulina of House Silverblood (deepening Heartlands-dynasty ties). Two sons: Nion (heir), Lucius (entered the Magos order). One daughter, married into House Solé.
Died at 64. Natural causes. Remembered fondly by the Magos, which biases the historical record in his favor.
20. Nion XI "the Builder" (600 – 635 AF)
Aurelian II's eldest son. Great constructor — second only to Hadros I in ambition.
Built basilicas, aqueducts, administrative complexes, and granaries across the continent. Many of these structures still function in 1308 AF — the engineering was that good.
The Foundation Burials: His darkest legacy. Entire work crews — slaves and conscripted laborers — were buried alive in the foundations of major buildings, supposedly to "bind their souls into the stone" and ensure structural integrity. Whether genuine occult practice, psychological intimidation of the labor force, or a cost-saving measure disguised as ritual is unclear. The structures are said to whisper. The Magos attribute this to wind passing through imperfect mortar joints.
Family: Wife Sera of House Lockmere (western Heartlands mountain family — first major alliance between dynasty and the pass-keepers). Three sons: Lycian (heir), Aurelian (military), Cassian (died in construction accident — another ironic death given the family trade). Two daughters.
Died at 66. Natural causes. Left behind infrastructure that would outlast his dynasty by centuries.
21. Lycian I "the Decadent" (635 – 662 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion XI's eldest son. Lavish, hedonistic, culturally productive.
Hosted elaborate court festivals that bankrupted two provincial treasuries. Imported exotic animals from Xaria and the Frozen South for private menageries. Hosted feasts featuring roasted Ash-Hounds — fire-breathing canines from the volcanic regions, hunted to extinction during his reign for entertainment.
Despite (or because of) his decadence, the empire was culturally vibrant during his reign. Architecture, music, painting, and literary production reached a peak that would not be equaled until the Age of Faith.
First emperor to receive formal Lovist missionaries at court. Did not convert — found the faith "interesting but austere" — but allowed its preachers to operate freely in the capital, a tolerance that his successors would regret.
Family: Multiple official consorts (the term "wife" became complicated under Lycian). At least eight acknowledged children. Heir: Nion (his eldest son by his first consort). Several bastards placed in provincial positions.
Died at 55. Gout, liver failure, and general physical collapse from decades of excess. His court physician's case notes, preserved in the Magos archives, are essentially a medical textbook on the consequences of sustained debauchery.
22. Nion XII "the Last Pagan" (662 – 698 AF)
Lycian's eldest son. Devout follower of the Old Way at a time when the Old Way was visibly dying.
The Last Persecution: Ordered the burning of Lovist heretics across the empire. Produced martyrs rather than deterrence — Lovist preachers walked into the fires with composure that shook the soldiers. Witnesses converted on the spot. Ashes collected by the faithful and scattered on the roads. New congregations appeared wherever the ashes fell. Nion XII had tried to burn a faith and fertilized it.
Paradox: his persecution accelerated Loveism's spread by giving it martyrs, organization (underground networks formed to protect preachers), and moral authority (the faith that the empire feared must contain dangerous truth).
Claimed the old gods sent him dreams of the Bone Leviathan — a massive ocean creature said to one day devour empires. Whether genuine vision, political metaphor, or fever dream is debated. Later Lovist theologians interpreted it as Vena warning the emperor through his own dead gods.
Family: Wife Anthea of House Terrarossa (Sangrea). Two sons: Hadros (heir), Septimus (entered the Old Way priesthood — one of its last senior initiates). Three daughters, two of whom secretly converted to Loveism during their father's own reign.
Died at 64. Natural causes. The Old Way temples he rebuilt were mostly empty by the time of his death. The priests still performed the rituals, but the congregations had dwindled to elderly loyalists and political obligates. The faith that had sustained the empire for seven centuries was dying with its last true believer on the throne.
23. Hadros II "the Weary" (698 – 734 AF) (not a Nion)
Nion XII's eldest son. First emperor to be privately sympathetic to Loveism while officially maintaining the Old Way. A compromiser.
Ended the persecution of Lovists. Did not convert — maintained the Old Way as state religion — but issued the Edict of Tolerance (700 AF), granting Lovists legal right to worship, own property, and operate hospitals and schools. The edict was pragmatic: the Lovists were providing social services that the empire had stopped funding, and banning them meant banning the only functional healthcare system most provinces had.
The old temples continued to empty. The new Lovist meeting houses continued to fill. Hadros watched it happen and did nothing, because there was nothing to do.
Family: Wife Sera of House Silverring. Two sons: Varian (heir), Nion (military governor of the Horns — died of plague at 38). One daughter, married to a Lovist merchant family — the first open intermarriage between the dynasty and the new faith's adherents.
Died at 68. The Magos describe his reign as "the empire holding its breath."
24. Varian I "the Twilight Lord" (734 – 771 AF) (not a Nion)
Hadros II's eldest surviving son. Melancholic, philosophical, increasingly irrelevant.
Imperial authority was now largely ceremonial outside Nionia and the immediate Heartlands. Provincial governors ruled as independent lords in all but name. Tribute payments were irregular. Road maintenance had become a local responsibility, and most locals neglected it.
The First Provincial Wars (~750 AF): Open conflict between House Silverblood and House Silverring in the Heartlands — not a rebellion against the empire, but a territorial dispute between two imperial houses that the emperor was powerless to mediate. Varian sent envoys demanding peace. Both houses ignored him. This was the moment when the fiction of imperial unity became publicly, undeniably fiction.
Varian responded by retreating into philosophy. He corresponded extensively with the Magos, writing long letters about the nature of decline and the cyclicality of history. These letters survive and are considered surprisingly insightful — the man understood what was happening to his empire even though he couldn't stop it.
Family: Wife Lydia of House Argenhold. One son: Cassian (heir, but weak). Two daughters.
Died at 66. Reportedly said, near the end: "The roads are breaking. When the roads break, everything breaks." The Magos consider this the most accurate assessment of imperial decline produced by any emperor.
25. Cassian III "the Shadow" (771 – 803 AF) (not a Nion)
Varian's only son. Weak, sickly, controlled by court factions.
Imperial authority now confined to Nionia, Faithir (which the empire still technically owned), and the road garrisons that still functioned. Everything else was independent in practice.
The Rise of the Council of Three: Lovist religious orders, now operating openly across the entire continent, began to formalize their institutional structure. The three major orders — Ayanite, Ashanite, Alonite — established the Council of Three as a governing body for the faith. The Council's authority was spiritual, but spiritual authority was the only kind that still functioned across provincial borders. The Lovist network of hospitals, schools, and relief stations was the only continental-scale infrastructure still operating. The Council began to fill the administrative vacuum the empire had left.
Family: Wife unclear — records are fragmentary from this period. One son: Nion (heir, took the regnal name in an attempt to reassert dynastic legitimacy). Two daughters, fates unknown.
Died at 51. Tuberculosis. The imperial chronicles from this period are threadbare — the chronicler corps had been defunded, and record-keeping had been outsourced to the Magos.
26. Nion XIII "the Holy" (803 – 856 AF)
Cassian III's only son. The last emperor. The man who chose to end it.
Inherited an empire that was already dead but hadn't stopped moving yet. The treasury was depleted. The legions were provincial militias in all but name. The roads were crumbling. The Old Way temples were empty. The only functioning continental institution was the Lovist Church.
The Conversion (~810 AF): Nion XIII experienced what the chronicles describe as a divine vision — Vena herself appearing in his bedchamber, weeping tears of light, telling him the empire was built on the wrong foundation. Whether genuine mystical experience, psychotic break, or manipulation by his Lovist confessor is unknown and ultimately irrelevant — the result was the same. He converted publicly, outlawed the Old Way, declared Loveism the state religion, and began the systematic transfer of whatever remained of imperial wealth to the Church.
The Great Endowment (810–850 AF): Over four decades, Nion XIII emptied the imperial treasury. Built hundreds of cathedrals. Endowed monasteries, hospitals, and schools. Made massive donations to all three Lovist orders. The centerpiece: the transformation of the village of Ionir in the Heartlands (near the Horns border) into the city of Faithir. The Great Cathedral of Nion the Holy constructed over the grove where the three prophets lived and died. Construction employed three generations of stonemasons.
Freed imperial slaves (the decree was largely ignored in the provinces but symbolically important). Banned gladiatorial games. Disbanded the remnants of the Crimson Watch intelligence service.
The Collapse: Legions went unpaid. Roads went unmaintained. Provincial governors stopped answering imperial edicts. The noble houses discovered they were already independent and simply stopped pretending otherwise. The Imperium Guard — the emperor's personal bodyguard — was the last military unit still receiving pay, and when the treasury emptied, their loyalty was purchased by a cabal of merchant lords and disgruntled generals.
The Assassination (856 AF): Nion XIII killed in his private chapel on Nionia by the Imperium Guard. He was praying. The single surviving eyewitness — a servant hiding behind a column — reported that the emperor looked up at his killers and smiled. The Lovist Church later claimed his last word was "Finally."
Posthumous titles: "The Holy" (from the Church). "The Empty-Handed" (from Nionian historians).
Family: Wife Cassiana of House Marcellus (the same family that survived the Great Pyre — the circle closes). Two daughters, both entered Lovist orders. One son, died in infancy. No male heir. The Nionic dynasty ended with him.
27–30. The Interregnum Emperors (856 – 903 AF)
The 47 years between Nion XIII's assassination and the formal end of the Age of Fire saw a rapid succession of non-dynastic claimants — generals, merchant lords, and provincial governors who seized the title "Emperor" without the blood or legitimacy to sustain it. None lasted.
27. General Corvinus "the Usurper" (856 – 863 AF)
Leader of the Imperium Guard cabal that assassinated Nion XIII. Declared himself Emperor. Controlled Nionia and nothing else. Attempted to recall provincial legions — none answered. Murdered by his own officers when he couldn't pay them.
28. Merchant-Lord Aurius "the Coin-Emperor" (863 – 871 AF)
Nionian merchant prince who purchased the loyalty of Corvinus's surviving guard. Tried to rule the empire as a commercial enterprise. Issued bonds backed by marble quarry revenues. When the bond market collapsed, so did his authority. Fled Nionia by ship. Reportedly lived out his years as a merchant in the Horns under a false name.
29. Admiral Torr "the Last Admiral" (871 – 889 AF)
Head of House Torr, the naval aristocracy founded by Aurelius I. Attempted to hold the empire together through naval power alone — controlling the sea lanes and using blockades to force tribute from coastal provinces. Effective for 18 years, but could not project power inland. The Heartlands, Rosland, and the Frozen South simply ignored him. Died at sea during a storm, possibly murdered by his own crew.
30. Regency Council (889 – 903 AF)
A committee of Nionian notables — merchants, minor nobles, Lovist clergy — who administered the island in the absence of any viable claimant. Formally dissolved the empire in 903 AF, declaring the Age of Fire ended and the Age of Faith begun. The declaration was a formality — the empire had been dead for decades. The Council's act was not a political decision but a bureaucratic one: someone had to update the calendar.

IMPERIAL INSTITUTIONS SUMMARY (for reference)
The Imperial Roads: Continental highway network. Foundations 3 feet deep, drainage systems, standardized width. Maintained by road-warden corps with authority superseding provincial jurisdiction. Fell into disrepair after 856 AF. Many sections still usable in 1308 AF but degraded.
Munnish: Common language imposed across the continent. Derived from Nionian dialect. Regional dialects persisted underneath. People code-switched: Munnish in public, local variant in private. Survived the empire — still the continent's lingua franca.
The Old Way / Nionian Pantheon: State religion. Nionus Axke (deified Nion I, supreme god of law), Fortia (war), Copia (wealth), Viam (roads). Transactional — worship ensured state success, not personal salvation. Collapsed when the state collapsed. Formally outlawed by Nion XIII (~810 AF). Temples still standing across the continent, mostly repurposed or ruined.
The Noble Houses: Provincial governance delegated to families elevated by imperial favor. System of hostage heirs, rotating governorships, and deliberate insecurity to prevent houses from becoming too powerful. After the collapse, houses became independent rulers.
The Imperium Guard: Emperor's personal bodyguard. Originally Nion I's most loyal marines. Became an institution. Ultimately assassinated Nion XIII when their pay stopped.
The Vigils: Intelligence network established by Nion II. Informers in every province. Purged by Nion V, replaced with Crimson Watch. Disbanded by Nion XIII.
The Iron Mark: Imperial currency. Standardized coinage. Collapsed with the empire. Regional currencies emerged during the Age of Faith.
The Gladiatorial System: Entertainment and population control. Enslaved fighters, criminals, rebels. Expanded under Nion III, peaked under Nion V, abolished by Nion XIII.

KEY REBELLIONS & LEGENDARY FIGURES
Aethric Daurn — Roslandic First Citizen who defeated Nion I at the Western Pass. Skull-cup feast. Founded House Daurn.
Torvac of the Teeth (~310–318 AF) — Slave-gladiator who led the empire's largest servile revolt. 30,000 followers. Defeated two legions. Betrayed, flayed alive. Carvings in Teeth quarry walls.
Maren of the Broken Cup (~308 AF) — Roslandic kitchen servant who assassinated Nion V with glass in his wine. Flayed. Name survives only in fire-songs.
Caelia of Rosland (~425–433 AF) — Guerrilla leader who burned imperial records for 8 years. Never captured. Western Rosland conspired to hide her. Nion VIII responded with the stone floods. Fate unknown.

HOUSES ELEVATED DURING THE AGE OF FIRE
House Garrun (Horns) — port governance
House Solé (Sangrea) — client rulers
House Terrarossa (Sangrea) — broken then vassalized
House Daurn (Rosland) — military aristocracy
House Belorn (Heartlands) — prefects
House Highwell (Vallan) — canton overseers
House Zaran (Red Coast) — provincial lords
House Torr (Nionia) — naval aristocracy
House Silverblood (Heartlands) — agricultural dynasty, rose through imperial marriage
House Silverring (Heartlands) — mining dynasty, rose through imperial marriage
HOUSES EXTINGUISHED DURING THE AGE OF FIRE
House Kest (Horns) — citizens delivered their heads to Nion I
House Ormell (Sangrea) — burned, salted, name struck from records
House Marvoss (Heartlands) — betrayed at Stonebridge
House Fenn (Teeth) — Bridge-Throat Massacre
House T'shaal (Xaria) — destroyed by temple authorities during imperial raid
House Hyren (Rosland) — blood-pits under Nion V
House Velmar (Nionia) — purged early in conquest for suspected Lovist sympathies
EXTINCT CREATURES (confirmed killed during the Age of Fire)
Sun-Basilisk (found dead at Altavista, ~20 AF)
Stoneback Beasts (Nion III's war-elephants, ~200 AF)
Bone-Tusks (arena animals under Nion V, ~300 AF)
Glass-Serpents (Nion VI's pets, ~345 AF)
Marrow-Bats (Septimus I's archive purge, ~400 AF)
War-Manticore (died under Nion VIII, ~420 AF)
