That's the full Age of Fire as a factual reference — every emperor accounted for, timeline stretched to fill 903 years properly, four interregnum claimants to cover the gap between the assassination and the formal end. Dense facts, no storytelling. Ready for the Age of Faith whenever you are.


Alright. Here's the full Age of Faith — dense, factual, packed with names, events, houses, legendary figures, and the proliferation of Lovist orders. Every region accounted for in every period. Let me go.

THE AGE OF FAITH (903 AF – 1308 AF) — COMPLETE CHRONICLE
Total Duration: 405 years Defining Feature: Fragmentation of imperial unity into regional polities, rapid expansion of Loveism from a spiritual movement into a continental institutional power, gradual stabilization of trade and road culture, and the emergence of the current political order.

PERIOD I: THE SHATTERING (903 – 950 AF)
The formal dissolution of the empire by the Regency Council on Nionia (903 AF) was a bureaucratic formality — the provinces had been governing themselves for decades. But the removal of even the fiction of central authority triggered a scramble for legitimacy, resources, and borders that lasted roughly two generations.
Nionia (903–950):
The Regency Council dissolved the imperial title but retained the Nionian Senate as the island's governing body. Renamed itself the Democratic Regency of Nionia. The Senate building — rebuilt after Nion I's Great Pyre — became the seat of a republic in everything but ambition. Nionia no longer claimed the continent, only the island.
The surviving patrician houses — Marcellus, Torr, Cassian, Navarrus — divided the Senate seats among themselves. Domus Marcellus, the oldest surviving family (descendants of the senator who escaped the Great Pyre), claimed moral authority as the "custodians of republican memory." Domus Torr retained the navy. Domus Navarrus held Port Severan and the northern shipyards. Domus Cassian kept the quarries.
The Marble Compact (907 AF): The four major houses signed a power-sharing agreement dividing the island into spheres of influence. Each house governed its traditional territory and contributed representatives to the Senate proportionally. The Compact held, with modifications, for nearly 400 years.
The imperial religion (the Old Way) was formally abandoned. Temples of Nionus Axke were either demolished for building material, converted to Lovist churches, or left to rot. The Temple of Fortia in the capital was converted into the Hall of the Scales, a Lovist courthouse. The cult of Viam (god of roads) lingered longest — road-wardens continued making small offerings at mile-markers for another century before the habit faded.
Population: depleted. The civil strife of the interregnum (856–903) had killed roughly 15% of the island's population. Recovery took three generations.
The Heartlands (903–950):
The most chaotic region. No single house had enough power to dominate the plains, and several claimed the right to fill the imperial vacuum.
The Grain Riots (904–908 AF): With imperial grain distribution collapsed, three consecutive bad harvests caused famine across the central plains. House Silverblood — already the largest landowner — hoarded grain in their Vornhold silos and sold at extortionate prices. Starvation-driven riots in at least six cities. House Silverring, based in the mountains and less affected by the crop failures, sent grain caravans south to buy loyalty from the starving plains towns. This was the origin of the rivalry.
The War of Five Dukes (912–919 AF): Five Heartlands houses — Silverblood, Silverring, Beaumont, Belorn, and Argenhold — each declared themselves sovereign rulers of their territories, each claiming a variation of the old imperial title. The war was inconclusive. No house could conquer the others, but the fighting destroyed bridges, burned granaries, and killed an estimated 40,000 people.
Daven Argenhold "the Peacemaker" (919 AF): The patriarch of House Argenhold, a river lord whose territories sat at the junction between all warring parties, brokered the Treaty of Five Bridges (919 AF) — named for the five destroyed bridges he personally funded the rebuilding of as a gesture of good faith. The treaty established the Argenlord system: a ceremonial leader elected every three years by the heads of the major houses, with emergency powers in war and famine but no permanent authority. Daven Argenhold was elected the first Argenlord by unanimous vote, serving until his death in 931 AF. His diplomatic legacy became House Argenhold's defining identity — every subsequent Argenhold patriarch was raised in the tradition of mediation, neutrality, and bridge-building (literal and political). The city of Argenhold, built at the river junction, became the continent's premier trading port.
The ducal titles were adopted during this period. The houses wanted something grander than "lord" but distinct from "king" — "duke" carried echoes of imperial nobility without the pretension of a crown. The Argenlord title, with its silver prefix, reflected the region's obsession with the metal that financed everything.
House Seeder elevated during this period — Old Man Hemlock's crop rotation innovation during the famines earned his family lands and a minor title. Within two generations, they controlled the largest granary network in the plains.
Sangrea (903–950):
The Sunstone Wars, which had been suppressed (but never eliminated) during imperial rule, immediately resumed. House Solé and House Terrarossa, both freed from imperial oversight, began fighting over the sunstone deposits, river crossings, and coastal ports that defined Sangrean wealth.
The First Post-Imperial Sunstone War (906–914 AF): House Solé, controlling the coastal wealth and port access, attempted to blockade Terrarossa's inland estates. Terrarossa responded with cavalry raids on Solé caravans. Eight years of intermittent fighting with no clear victor.
The Sangrean houses adopted the viceroy model — each major house ruling its territory as an independent lord with absolute authority, styling themselves "Lord-Patron" rather than duke or king. The title carried deliberate echoes of a merchant patron rather than a feudal ruler — wealth, not blood, was the basis of authority. Minor houses (Botano, Carvallo, Fuente) aligned as vassals to one pole or the other.
The Festival of the Red Grape (c. 920 AF): House Solé instituted this annual festival in Castesol — ostensibly a harvest celebration, functionally a display of wealth and power designed to attract vassal loyalty. Musicians, acrobats, bullfights, and a public feast lasting seven days. The festival survives to 1308 AF and has become Sangrea's most famous cultural event.
Rosland (903–950):
The democratic tradition, which had survived underground during 900 years of imperial occupation — preserved in the cohort system, in fire-songs, in quiet oaths sworn on the old stones of Aethel's plaza — re-emerged rapidly.
The Restoration Assembly (905 AF): Veterans, guild masters, and surviving minor nobles met in Aethel's plaza and formally declared the restoration of the republic. The Iron Codex — a written constitution modeled on the old stratocratic principles but expanded to include guild representation — was drafted over six months of heated debate. Key provisions: the High Baron (renamed from "First Citizen" to reflect the feudal reality) would be elected for 10-year terms; noble families and guilds of wealth and renown would each cast votes; the High Baron could be recalled by a two-thirds supermajority.
First High Baron: Aethric Daurn IV (905–915 AF) — descendant of the original Aethric Daurn who negotiated the Pact of Iron with Nion I. His election was largely symbolic — binding the new republic to its pre-imperial roots. He spent his decade rebuilding the western mountain passes and establishing the Frostguard patrol in the Daudrwood.
House Greenhand did not yet exist as a major dynasty. The family that would become the Greenhands were yeoman farmers in the central valleys — the "Greens" — who earned their reputation over the following centuries through agricultural innovation and civic reform.
The Horns (903–950):
Reverted to port-city competition almost immediately. The four power centers — three port cities (Westhorn, Brinehold, Nightspike) and the forest gate city (Skogrim) — each fell under the control of different factions.
House Garrun retained Westhorn, having been the imperial governors and having the deepest roots. They transitioned smoothly from imperial servants to independent port lords.
Brinehold: Fell to the Merchant-Captains' Council, a collective of trading families who governed by commercial consensus. No single house dominated. The strongest family was House Dalgaard, salt merchants who had operated since before the empire.
Nightspike: After the Kest extermination during the conquest, the city had been governed by imperial appointees. With the empire gone, a shipwright family named House Veldren seized control — descended from the laborers Nion I had reassigned to his naval yards, they had accumulated enough skill and wealth to claim the city their ancestors had been enslaved to build.
Skogrim (the forest city): Controlled by a Lovist order called the Lampkeepers — originally lighthouse wardens who expanded inland, maintaining way-stations and signal fires through the dense forest connecting the Horns to the mainland. The Lampkeepers were technically a religious order, but in practice they were a merchant-military guild that charged tolls for safe passage through the forest. Brother Erland, the first Lampkeeper Prior, established Skogrim's neutrality as a toll city — no house could claim it, but all houses needed it. The arrangement held.
The Pilot Wars (920–935 AF): Westhorn and Brinehold fought over control of the shallow coastal straits that connected the Horns to the open sea. Whoever controlled the pilots — the specialist sailors who guided ships through the treacherous channels — controlled maritime commerce. Fifteen years of raids, blockades, and assassinations. Ended with the Pilots' Charter (935 AF) — an independent Pilots' Guild operating from a neutral island between the two ports, answerable to neither but serving both for standardized fees.
Vallan (903–950):
Smallest region, least affected by the collapse. The valley cantons had always been semi-autonomous under the empire, and the removal of imperial authority changed almost nothing about daily life.
House Valenne — a family that claimed descent from the pre-imperial valley wardens — was elected Valley-King by the canton elders in 908 AF. The title was deliberately humble ("Valley-King" rather than "King") and the power was deliberately limited: the Valley-King arbitrated disputes, maintained the roads, and represented Vallan to outsiders. Internal governance remained with the individual cantons.
The Waystone Renewal (910–930 AF): House Valenne's first major act — rebuilding and standardizing the waystone markers and road-inns that served travelers passing through Vallan's mountain passes. Every inn was required to offer food, shelter, and medical aid to any traveler regardless of origin, funded by a small road-tax. This policy made Vallan the safest travel corridor on the continent within a generation, and the road-tax revenue became the Valley-King's primary income.
The Red Coast (903–950):
The most violent transition. Without imperial garrisons to maintain order, the oasis cities immediately turned on each other in a series of water wars.
The Qanat Wars (905–925 AF): Twenty years of intermittent conflict over the underground aqueduct systems that were the only source of water in the deep desert. Houses sabotaged each other's qanats, diverting water, poisoning wells, collapsing tunnels. Thousands died of thirst rather than combat.
The Red Crown: Established in approximately 930 AF when House Cenizar — a coastal family that controlled the largest natural harbor and the most reliable freshwater spring on the coast — brokered a water-sharing agreement among the surviving oasis houses. The agreement gave Cenizar arbitration authority over water disputes, and the copper crown they wore at the signing ceremony became the symbol of that authority. The Red Crown was never a true monarchy — it was a water-court, a judicial role that expanded over centuries into broader governance. But it was always, at its root, about who controlled the water.
House Alsiroth — lords of the inland gate-city Alsiroth's Gate — resisted the Red Crown from the beginning. Their city sat at the junction of the major caravan routes and had its own deep wells, making them less dependent on the qanat system. The rivalry between Cenizar (coast) and Alsiroth (interior) became the Red Coast's defining political tension.
The Teeth (903–950):
The four islands — Northwind, Emberstone, Verwhisper, Shadowtide — had always been distinct cultures united only by the Great Bridge. With imperial authority gone, each island reverted to independent governance.
Northwind: Fell under the control of fishing and maritime families. House Stormglass — a clan of navigators who had served as imperial naval scouts — claimed the island and governed from the clifftop fortress of Galehold.
Emberstone: The volcanic island's quarry-slave population, freed by Nion XIII's edict (and actually freed, unlike most provinces, because the island's small size made enforcement possible), reorganized under a workers' council. Within two generations, the council had been captured by a family of former overseers — House Pyrmont — who ran the volcanic stone quarries with only marginally better conditions than the imperial slavers.
Verwhisper: The forested island, rich in timber and fertile soil, became a haven for Lovist monasteries. House Verdane — a family of timber merchants — governed in partnership with the Order of the Green Thorn, an Ashanite sub-order dedicated to forest conservation. The island became the most religiously devout of the four.
Shadowtide: The jungle island remained ungovernable. Dense tropical forest, hostile wildlife, and a population of fishermen and foragers who refused to submit to any centralized authority. Various families claimed lordship; none could enforce it. By 1308 AF, Shadowtide is still functionally anarchic.
The Bridge Keepers: After House Fenn's extermination in the Bridge-Throat Massacre, maintenance of the Great Bridge had fallen to imperial engineers. With the empire gone, a consortium of island families — one representative from each island — formed the Bridge Council to maintain and toll the span. This arrangement lasted until Morvayn's coup in 1298 AF.
The Frozen South (903–950):
Barely noticed the empire's fall. The southern clans had been nominally tributary but practically independent throughout imperial history. The removal of the imperial flag changed nothing about daily life in the fjords.
Clan Aurax was already the dominant force — controlling the richest gold deposits in the Kjölfoss Mountains and the largest fleet of longships. The Winter-Moot system (annual gathering of clan chiefs to settle disputes and coordinate defense) continued uninterrupted.
Clan Daudrguard held the deep forests of the interior. Clan Raudbjorn controlled the coastal settlements and the fishing grounds. Clan Eldblod occupied the geothermally heated valleys of the Heitdalr. Smaller clans — at least a dozen — occupied the spaces between, paying deference to whichever major clan controlled their water or pasture.
Clan Hroth — a mountain clan that had feuded with Clan Aurax for generations — was destroyed during a winter famine circa 940 AF. Aurax refused to share grain stores. Hroth starved. The survivors were absorbed into Aurax, and the Hroth name was erased from the fire-songs — the southern equivalent of damnatio memoriae.
Xaria (903–950):
Nothing changed. The Ix'Atani Dominion's colonial administration had never been meaningfully disrupted by the empire, and its removal was irrelevant. The Xarian governor continued to administer the peninsula from the capital on the eastern coast, paying tribute to the Dominion across the sea and ignoring mainland politics entirely.
House Ix'za — the River Kings — continued to control the delta trade and the floating capital of the peninsula's interior. The temple-cities continued the Great Exchange. The jungle continued to be impenetrable.
The Church (903–950):
The Council of Three — now the only continental institution with cross-regional legitimacy — moved rapidly to fill the imperial vacuum.
The Great Dispersal (903–930 AF): Using the enormous endowment from Nion XIII, the three major orders funded the creation of dozens of new sub-orders across the continent. Each order was given a specific mandate — healing, education, road maintenance, criminal justice, agricultural improvement, funeral rites — and a territorial assignment. The money flowed outward from Faithir like blood from a heart, and everywhere it reached, Lovist institutions appeared: hospitals, schools, courts, hostels, granaries.
First named sub-orders founded during the Dispersal:
Brothers of the Open Road (Alonite): Road maintenance and pilgrim escort. Mandate: keep the imperial roads functional. Funded by donations and road-tolls. Members took vows of service and poverty. Recognizable by their grey cloaks and iron walking staffs. Within 50 years, the Brothers maintained more road-miles than the empire had at its peak.
Sisters of the Veil (Ashanite): Cloistered women devoted to contemplation, prophecy, and the care of orphans. Founded in a convent on Nionia — the same convent where, four centuries later, Jous Lorethian would be born. Members took vows of silence and seclusion, never interacting with men. They were said to "see the thread of a soul" — whether this was genuine mystical ability, trained psychological intuition, or simply the reputation that accrued to women who spent decades in meditative silence is debated. The order was small, secretive, and deeply respected.
Order of Alon's Silence / The Wandering Mutes (Alonite): Itinerant healers and laborers who took a vow of silence in emulation of the mute prophet Alon. They traveled from village to village, fixing roofs, treating wounds, digging wells, and moving on without speaking a word. Paid nothing, asked nothing, refused nothing. Possibly the most beloved order among the common people across every region. By 1308 AF, roughly 200 active members continent-wide.
The Blind Daughters of Aya (Ayanite): Women who blinded themselves voluntarily as a devotional act, believing that physical sight obscured spiritual truth. They served as oracles, counselors, and arbiters of disputes in communities that lacked formal courts. Controversial — the self-blinding was condemned by some Ayanite theologians as self-harm, defended by others as the ultimate act of faith. The order was small and concentrated primarily in the Heartlands and Sangrea.
Order of the Harvest Bell (Ashanite): Agricultural order focused on crop improvement, seed banking, and famine relief. Operated granary-monasteries across the Heartlands and Sangrea. Their bell — rung at dawn and dusk — became a standard feature of rural life. Close relationship with House Seeder.
The Bonekeepers (Ashanite): Specialists in funeral rites, grief counseling, and the maintenance of ossuaries. In a world where plague and famine killed regularly, the Bonekeepers provided the essential service of dignified death. They maintained charnel houses, recorded the names of the dead, and performed the Rite of Rejoining — the Lovist funeral ceremony.
The Lampkeepers (Alonite): Originally lighthouse wardens in the Horns, expanded into a broader road-safety order maintaining signal fires, way-stations, and navigation aids along dangerous routes. Became the de facto rulers of Skogrim in the Horns.
Isle of Knowledge (903–950):
The Magos order, granted autonomy by Aurelian II, was the only imperial institution to survive the collapse fully intact. The Isle's neutrality — guaranteed by the fact that everyone needed the Magos' archival and arbitration services — held.
Elder Magos Kael (served c. 890–932 AF): Oversaw the transition from imperial administration to independent operation. Issued the Charter of the Pale Reed — the Isle's founding document as a sovereign micro-polity, guaranteeing neutrality, open access to all scholars regardless of origin, and the right of sanctuary.
The Magos began the Great Catalogue — a systematic inventory of all surviving imperial documents, provincial records, and oral traditions. The project would take two centuries and produce the most comprehensive historical archive on the continent.
Secret vaults of lost technology from the Age of History were consolidated — some on the Isle itself, some in a hidden vault on one of the Teeth islands (Emberstone, beneath the volcanic stone quarries). Only the Elder Magos and a small circle of senior archivists knew the vaults existed.

PERIOD II: THE AGE OF ORDERS (950 – 1050 AF)
The second century of the Age of Faith was defined by the explosive proliferation of Lovist religious orders and the gradual stabilization of regional governments.
The Church (950–1050):
Nion XIII's endowment was so vast that it took over a century to fully distribute. By 1050 AF, the number of distinct Lovist orders operating across the continent exceeded three hundred. Some were large (the Brothers of the Open Road had thousands of members), others were tiny (the Blind Daughters of Aya never exceeded fifty). Some were devoted to charitable service, others to scholarship, others to military protection, and a growing number to increasingly esoteric interpretations of the faith.


Major new orders founded during this period:


Sons of Loreth (Alonite/martial): A knightly order devoted to the defense of the faith and the protection of pilgrims. Founded circa 970 AF by a Heartlands knight named Ser Brannoc of Vornhold who organized a company of veterans to escort a pilgrim caravan to Faithir through bandit-infested roads. The mission's success inspired formal organization. By 1308 AF, the Sons of Loreth are the most powerful martial order on the continent — landed, wealthy, and politically influential. Braven Lorethson, one of the story's protagonists, is a member.
Order of the Copper Bowl (Ashanite): Alchemical healers operating primarily on the Red Coast. Specialized in mineral-based medicines derived from the region's copper deposits. Their signature: a small copper bowl used to mix tinctures, carried on a chain around the neck. Controversial for their willingness to use substances that bordered on intoxicants — Frostpetal derivatives, Dreambud infusions — as pain management.
The Chain-Breakers (Alonite): Anti-slavery order operating on the Xarian frontier and in coastal cities where the slave trade persisted. Small, militant, frequently in conflict with Xarian temple authorities and mainland merchants who profited from the trade. Named for their practice of literally breaking the chains of enslaved people they encountered, which made them heroes to abolitionists and criminals to slavers.
Order of the Quill (Ayanite): Education order operating schools in every major city. Taught literacy, basic arithmetic, and Lovist catechism. Their curriculum was standardized across the continent — a child taught by the Quill in Rosland could read the same texts as a child taught in Sangrea. This standardization, more than any other single factor, maintained Munnish as the continental lingua franca after the empire fell.
The Crimson Penitents (no specific order affiliation): Self-flagellating pilgrims who walked barefoot between holy sites, scourging themselves to atone for sins — their own and the world's. Tolerated but not endorsed by the Council of Three. Common in Sangrea and the Heartlands. Disturbing to watch. Effective at attracting donations from guilty nobles.
Order of the Still Water (Ashanite): Contemplative monasteries in remote locations — mountaintops, islands, deep forests. Monks devoted to silence, meditation, and the copying of manuscripts. Produced some of the finest illuminated texts on the continent. Their monastery on a small island off the Vallan coast — the Quiethouse — became a renowned retreat for scholars and exhausted rulers.
Order of St. Maren (Alonite): Named after Maren of the Broken Cup — the Roslandic servant who assassinated Nion V. A small, fierce order of women warriors based in Rosland, devoted to the protection of abused women and children. Condemned by the Council of Three as "glorifying regicide" but tolerated because their charitable work was genuinely needed. Popular in Rosland, despised in the Heartlands.
The Ember Watch (Alonite): The remnant of the beast-hunting orders. Originally formed to exterminate dangerous mythical creatures that threatened settlements. By 1050 AF, most of the great beasts were gone, and the Ember Watch had shrunk from a major military order to a few hundred eccentric specialists who tracked rumored creatures, investigated livestock kills, and were hired by nervous villagers to check dark caves and abandoned ruins. By 1308 AF, they are a shadow — maybe forty active members, seen as oddities or curiosities.
The Venic Path (heretical/mystical): Not an order but a movement — mystics who believed that divine truth could be accessed through altered consciousness (meditation, fasting, plant intoxicants, sensory deprivation). Named after Brother Venic, a Sangrean monk who claimed to have achieved direct communion with Loreth through a seven-day fast in a sealed cave. The Council of Three declared the Venic Path heretical in 1023 AF, but the movement persisted underground, particularly among artists, poets, and the rural poor who couldn't afford formal religious participation.
The Schism of the Lesser Life (c. 980–1010 AF): The great doctrinal crisis. Debate: do non-human creatures bear divine echoes? If animals carry sparks of divinity, then hunting them is a form of murder. If they don't, then the entire Alonite beast-hunting enterprise is justified, and the Ashanite reverence for all life is sentimental overreach.


The Conclave of Castesol (998 AF): Called after a flock of direwolves devastated Sangrean vineyards and the local Ashanite prior refused to sanction a hunt, insisting the wolves be "shepherded" to less populated territory. The wolves killed twelve villagers while the Ashanites tried to relocate them.
The Beast-Pardoners: A fringe Ashanite faction that refused any killing of any creature. Declared schismatic after a harpy flock they attempted to "protect" slaughtered an entire fishing village on the Horns coast. Their leader, Sister Galena, was excommunicated and died in exile on the Venic Path.
Resolution: The Doctrine of Measured Culling (1010 AF): Compromise. Non-human life bears lesser echoes — worthy of respect but not equal to human life. Sanctioned hunts for public safety permitted with proof of threat. Unsanctioned "trophy" kills forbidden. Alonite beast-hunters required to perform a Rite of Acknowledgment before each kill. The compromise satisfied no one fully but held.
The Logosian Crisis (c. 1020–1040 AF): An intellectual heresy emerging from within the Ayanite order. The Logosians — named for their insistence that logos (reason) was the only valid path to truth — argued that the gods were dead, that the "echoes" were psychological phenomena rather than divine residue, and that Loveism's value was purely ethical, not metaphysical. In short: keep the morality, discard the theology.


Father Thesan of Silvermont — the movement's founder, an Ayanite scholar who published The Cogitant Letters, a series of arguments dismantling traditional Lovist theology using Lovist ethical reasoning. The work was brilliant, devastating, and immediately banned.
The Council of Three's response (1035 AF): Formal condemnation. Father Thesan excommunicated. His followers — several hundred scholars and students across the Heartlands — expelled from Ayanite institutions. Many fled to the Isle of Knowledge, where the Magos offered sanctuary under the Charter of the Pale Reed (which guaranteed neutrality regardless of theological status). The Logosian tradition survived in the Magos archives, where it influenced secular scholarship for centuries.
The Purge of the Concordant (1038 AF): The Ayanite order conducted an internal purge — removing any scholar suspected of Logosian sympathies from teaching positions. Approximately 200 scholars dismissed. Some joined the Magos. Some recanted. A handful were imprisoned. The Purge created a lasting rift between the Ayanite order and the Isle of Knowledge, which the Ayanites accused of harboring heretics.
The Heartlands (950–1050):
The Argenlord system stabilized. House Argenhold's diplomatic tradition, established by Daven the Peacemaker, became the baseline — the Argenlord was expected to be a mediator, not a ruler. The title alternated between Silverblood and Silverring candidates, with occasional compromise elections of candidates from minor houses (Beaumont, Belorn) when the two silver dynasties deadlocked.
The Silver Covenant (c. 960 AF): A formal partnership between House Silverblood and House Silverring — dividing the Heartlands into spheres of influence (plains and agriculture for Silverblood, mountains and mining for Silverring) and agreeing to alternate the Argenlord title between them. The Covenant held for roughly 200 years and was the foundation of Heartlands stability. Its collapse would become the Argent Schism.
House Lockmere consolidated control of the western passes — their family had been pass-keepers since the imperial era, and the removal of imperial authority simply formalized what was already true.
Stonebridge — the site of the Marvoss betrayal during the conquest — became a market town and pilgrimage site. The bridge itself, still bearing the name of the extinguished house, was maintained by the Brothers of the Open Road. Travelers crossing it often left small offerings — a habit rooted in guilt rather than piety.
Rosland (950–1050):
The republic stabilized under a succession of competent High Barons drawn from the veteran families — Daurn, Riverblade, and a rising house called Greenhand (originally yeoman farmers from the central valleys who earned their reputation through agricultural reform and civic engagement).
High Baron Tomas Greenhand (c. 990–1000 AF): First Greenhand to hold the office. A farmer's son who rose through guild politics and was elected on a platform of land reform and expanded voting rights. His decade in office established the guild vote — giving formal political representation to artisan and trade guilds for the first time. The innovation was controversial (nobles argued it diluted their authority) but popular (the guilds represented the majority of the productive population). The guild vote survived and became a defining feature of Roslandic democracy.
House Ironside did not yet exist as a major power. The family that would become the Ironsides were mining foremen in the Fyrhold mountains — hard, disciplined men who ran their mines like military operations. Their rise would come later.
Sangrea (950–1050):
The Sunstone Wars continued their cyclical pattern — roughly one major conflict per generation, with skirmishes and proxy fights in between. Historians (and the Magos) counted at least four distinct Sunstone Wars during this century, though the boundaries between wars, truces, and armed standoffs were blurry.
The Second Post-Imperial Sunstone War (c. 965–972 AF): Triggered by the discovery of a new sunstone deposit in the disputed borderlands between Solé and Terrarossa territories. Seven years of fighting. Ended with The Feast of Mirrors (972 AF) — a peace banquet hosted by House Solé in Castesol at which both houses agreed to joint exploitation of the deposit. The feast got its name from the reflective sunstone panels that lined the banquet hall. Three years later, Terrarossa accused Solé of underreporting yields. The joint exploitation collapsed. The deposit was fought over for another century.
House Botano consolidated control of the Selvaverde jungle province during this period — the matriarchal dynasty that governed through botanical knowledge and control of the jungle's medicinal resources. Their vassal house, Carvallo, established the messenger-parrot network that gave Botano a communications advantage no other Sangrean house could match.
The Red Coast (950–1050):
The Red Crown system, under House Cenizar, gradually expanded from water arbitration to broader governance. Cenizar established the Copper Courts — traveling judges who circulated between oasis cities, settling disputes and enforcing the water-sharing agreements. The judges wore copper circlets and carried copper rods of office. Their authority was respected because everyone understood that without the water agreements, the desert would kill them all.
House Khorim — lords of the volcanic Qasr Ash'khor — rose to prominence during this period. Their territory included failing obsidian mines that still produced enough volcanic glass for a lucrative weapons trade. Khorim obsidian blades were prized across the continent — sharper than steel, though more brittle.
House Rukh and House Ramad — two houses on the volcanic peninsula — fought a bitter feud over geothermal resources (hot springs used for bathing, healing, and mineral extraction). The feud lasted four generations and was settled only when both houses nearly bankrupted themselves. The Truce of Ash (c. 1020 AF) divided the peninsula's resources and established shared access to the largest hot springs.
The Teeth (950–1050):
The four-island system stabilized. The Bridge Council managed the Great Bridge, collecting tolls and funding maintenance. Each island developed its own economy and culture.
Emberstone's Secret: The Magos' hidden vault of lost technology, buried in the volcanic quarries beneath the island, remained unknown to the island's rulers. A single Magos agent — disguised as a quarry inspector — maintained the vault. The position was hereditary within a small circle of Magos families, passed from father to son or mother to daughter without the Elder Magos' direct involvement (a dangerous independence that would later become a vulnerability).
The Frozen South (950–1050):
Clan Aurax continued to dominate through gold wealth. The Winter-Moot system functioned as the region's only cross-clan institution.
The Ice-Road Wars (c. 980–990 AF): Clan Raudbjorn attempted to establish a winter trade route across the frozen interior, bypassing Aurax-controlled mountain passes. Aurax responded by raiding the caravans. Ten years of seasonal skirmishing — fighting in winter on frozen rivers, retreating in summer when the ice melted. Ended inconclusively. The ice roads were abandoned as impractical.
No contact with the mainland beyond occasional fishing encounters with Roslandic coastal villages.

PERIOD III: THE CENTURY OF BLOOD AND CONSOLIDATION (1050 – 1150 AF)
Every region had its defining conflict during this century. The political systems that had been improvised in the first 150 years were now tested, and the ones that survived were the ones that held at 1308 AF.
Nionia (1050–1150):
The Senate functioned. Nionia experienced a genuine golden age — maritime trade boomed, the quarries produced high-quality marble for export, and the island's merchant fleet became the largest on the continent.
The Trade War of the Inner Sea (c. 1070–1085 AF): Nionia vs. the Horns over control of the sea lanes. Not a shooting war but an economic one — blockades, tariff manipulation, piracy, and espionage. Ended with the Accord of Three Tides (1085 AF), which established free navigation for all parties but gave Nionia preferential docking rights in Horns ports. The Horns resented the arrangement. It held because Nionia's navy was bigger.
Domus Navarrus emerged as the island's dominant naval house during this period, eclipsing Domus Torr (which had been declining since Admiral Torr's death in 889 AF). Navarrus controlled Port Severan, the empire's former naval headquarters, and maintained the largest fleet.
The Heartlands (1050–1150):
The Silver Covenant held. The Argenlord title continued to alternate between Silverblood and Silverring. The region's major crisis was economic, not military.
The Blight of 1087: A grain fungus devastated the Silver Plains for three consecutive harvests. Famine across the Heartlands. The Argenlord (a Silverblood) invoked emergency powers and commandeered grain from Silverring mountain stores. Silverring complied but resented it — the incident planted the seed of suspicion that the Argenlord's emergency powers could be used as a weapon by whichever house held the title. First visible crack in the Covenant.
House Belorn declined during this period — poor management, a succession of incompetent heirs, and the loss of their primary trade route to House Argenhold's river network. By 1150 AF, Belorn was a minor house, its name more prestigious than its resources.
Rosland (1050–1150):
The Ironside Rebellion (c. 1090–1095 AF): The mining foremen of Fyrhold, led by a man named Kael Ironside — a former soldier turned mine owner — attempted to secede from the republic, declaring the mountain provinces an independent state. Their grievance: the republic taxed their mineral wealth to fund agricultural projects in the lowlands, but provided no roads, no schools, and no courts in the mountains. The rebellion was put down by the republic's combined militia, but the settlement gave the Fyrhold miners guild representation and established House Ironside as a recognized noble family with a seat at the election table. Kael Ironside was pardoned, granted formal lordship of Fyrhold, and spent the rest of his life building the fortress-city of Forgetown from the profits of his iron mines.
This was Rosland's "big war" — not a full civil war but a regional uprising that reshaped the political balance. From this point forward, House Ironside was a permanent faction in Roslandic politics, representing the mountain mining interests against the lowland agricultural interests championed by the Greenhands.
Sangrea (1050–1150):
The Great Sunstone War (c. 1100–1118 AF): The largest and most destructive Sunstone War. Triggered by the assassination of a Solé heir at a Terrarossa-hosted tournament — possibly a genuine accident (jousting lance through the throat), possibly arranged. Eighteen years of open warfare across the entire region. Every minor house forced to choose a side. The Campaneros (bellringers of Sangrea's villages) used their bell networks as a military alert system — the Riverbell Alarm — coordinating troop movements across distances that horseback messengers couldn't cover.
The Butcher of Fuentarossa (c. 1108 AF): A Terrarossa general named Don Alvaro Sangreverde — nicknamed "the Butcher" — sacked the town of Fuentarossa, which had declared for Solé. He hung the town's entire male population from the bridge over the Fuente River — reportedly 800 men and boys. The bridge collapsed under the weight. The town's women and children were expelled into the countryside. Fuentarossa was rebuilt a generation later, but the name Sangreverde became synonymous with atrocity in Sangrean culture.
The Peace of the Broken Chalice (1118 AF): Brokered by the Council of Three, who threatened to excommunicate both houses if they didn't stop. The peace was sealed by a ceremonial breaking of a golden chalice — each house kept one half, symbolizing their incomplete unity. The peace held. Barely.
The Horns (1050–1150):
The Nightspike Fire (c. 1075 AF): Nightspike's dockyards burned — either an accident (tar-vat ignition) or arson by Brinehold agents. The fire destroyed 40% of the city's shipbuilding capacity and killed roughly 2,000 people. House Veldren accused Brinehold. Brinehold denied involvement. A brief naval skirmish in the straits ended in stalemate. The fire was never conclusively attributed, but it permanently weakened Nightspike's position relative to the other port cities.
House Garrun of Westhorn used the opportunity to position itself as the Horns' premier port — offering shelter and contracts to displaced Nightspike shipwrights. By 1150 AF, Westhorn was the largest and wealthiest of the three ports.
The Red Coast (1050–1150):
The Madness of King Alsiroth (c. 1080–1110 AF): The lord of Alsiroth's Gate — Lord Yusef Alsiroth III — descended into genuine madness over a 30-year reign. He ordered the construction of increasingly bizarre monuments: a tower of copper mirrors designed to "blind the sun," a canal project intended to bring seawater to the desert interior (which would have salted every farm in its path), and a palace extension built entirely of human bone (sourced from ossuaries, not fresh kills — though the Bonekeepers were furious). His court magician, a self-styled alchemist named Qadir the Dry, encouraged the king's delusions and used the distraction to embezzle enormous sums.
House Sadiq — the merchant dynasty controlling the Grand Souk — used this period to quietly acquire commercial control of the city. Merchant-Prince Rashid Sadiq (grandfather of the current Omar Sadiq) purchased land, warehouses, and trade contracts from the bankrupt Alsiroth treasury, gradually becoming the city's true economic power. The strategy continues to 1308 AF: the Sadiqs fund the mad king's projects (his descendants inherited the tendency toward eccentricity if not outright madness), knowing each project brings the Alsiroth house closer to bankruptcy and the Sadiq family closer to power.
Vallan (1050–1150):
The Annexation Crisis (c. 1120 AF): The Heartlands Argenlord — a Silverblood — proposed that Vallan be incorporated into the Heartlands as a vassal duchy, arguing that the tiny region couldn't sustain itself independently and that its road network was essential to continental trade. Valley-King Aldric Valenne II rejected the proposal, closed the mountain passes, and threatened to destroy the roads rather than surrender sovereignty. The Heartlands backed down — the cost of losing the Vallan road network exceeded the value of annexation. Vallan remained independent. The incident cemented Vallan's fierce independence as a national identity.
The Teeth (1050–1150):
The Bridge Tax Riots (c. 1100 AF): The Bridge Council tripled tolls to fund earthquake damage repairs to the central span. Merchants from all four islands rioted. House Pyrmont of Emberstone attempted to seize the bridge's northern approach, claiming "custodial authority." The other three islands formed a temporary alliance to block the grab. The crisis was resolved by the Magos, who mediated a new toll structure and quietly ensured the Emberstone vault remained undiscovered during the chaos.
The Frozen South (1050–1150):
The First Gold War (c. 1070–1080 AF): Clan Raudbjorn attempted to seize Aurax's primary gold mine — the Kjölfoss Deeps. Ten years of raiding and counter-raiding in the mountains. Aurax won through attrition and harsh weather. Raudbjorn was forced to pay tribute in whale-oil and seal-fur for a generation. The defeat created a permanent grudge.
The Church (1050–1150):
The Council of Three reached peak institutional authority during this century. The Peace of the Broken Chalice in Sangrea demonstrated that the Council could force secular rulers to the table. The Council began deploying Arbiters — senior clergy empowered to mediate disputes between houses, with the implied threat of excommunication for non-compliance.
The Crusade of the Skogrim Corridor (c. 1060–1075 AF): The first and only "Crusade of Relief." The forest road through Skogrim (the Horns gate city) had become impassable due to a combination of Grave-Stag herds (massive, aggressive cervids with bone-plated skulls) and harpy rookeries nesting in the canopy. Trade between the Horns and the mainland was strangled. The Alonite order organized a combined military-charitable expedition: Ember Watch beast-hunters to clear the fauna, Brothers of the Open Road to rebuild the path, Ashanite healers to treat the wounded. The Lampkeepers of Skogrim provided guides and tolled the cleared route. The campaign took 15 years but succeeded — the corridor was reopened, and the Horns' economic connection to the mainland was restored. It was the Ember Watch's finest hour and effectively their last major operation.

PERIOD IV: THE GOLDEN CENTURY (1150 – 1250 AF)
A century of relative peace, cultural flourishing, and the beginning of the Church's overreach.
Continental trends:
Trade flowed freely. The roads — maintained by the Brothers of the Open Road, funded by regional tolls and Lovist tithes — were safer than they had been since the imperial peak. A merchant could travel from Vornhold to Fairhaven in two weeks with reasonable expectation of arriving alive and unrobbed.
Regional identities crystallized. Each region developed distinct architectural styles, culinary traditions, musical forms, and fashion. The Heartlands became known for silver-threaded formal wear. Sangrea for bright colors and elaborate embroidery. Rosland for practical wool and leather. The Horns for oiled canvas and sailor's knots worn as jewelry. The Red Coast for copper ornament on everything.
Literacy expanded dramatically thanks to the Order of the Quill. By 1250 AF, approximately 30% of the urban population could read (compared to perhaps 5% at the empire's fall). Rural literacy remained low (~5%) but the Quill schools were slowly expanding.
The Road Culture matured. Inns, way-stations, pilgrim hostels, and market towns along major routes developed a shared culture of hospitality and mutual aid. Attacking a caravan or robbing a traveler was not just criminal but sacrilegious — a violation of the Lovist principle that roads were sacred arteries of the community. Regional governments took road safety as a point of pride. A duchy with dangerous roads was a duchy with a failing lord.
Population growth. The continent's population, which had declined sharply during the Shattering and the Century of Blood, recovered and then exceeded its imperial peak. New towns were founded. Forests were cleared for farmland. The wild places shrank.
The Church's Turn:
With the great beasts mostly gone, the roads safe, and the hospitals funded, the Church's original charitable mandate was largely accomplished. Success created a problem: what does a massive, wealthy, continent-spanning institution do when the crisis that justified its existence is over?
The answer was institutional expansion — the Council of Three began asserting authority over areas previously left to secular rulers: marriage law, inheritance disputes, commercial regulations, education standards. The justification was always theological ("all human activity is within the scope of divine concern"), but the effect was political: the Church was becoming a government.
The Indulgence Trade (c. 1180 AF onward): The Council authorized the sale of spiritual indulgences — payments that reduced the theological burden of sin. Originally intended as donations to fund construction of new cathedrals, the indulgence system quickly became a revenue machine. Wealthy nobles purchased elaborate indulgences for themselves, their families, and even their deceased ancestors. The poor, who couldn't afford indulgences, were told their poverty was itself a form of spiritual penance. The theological gymnastics required to justify this were considerable.
The Relic Markets: Bones, clothing, and personal effects attributed to saints became enormously valuable commodities. Every cathedral wanted relics; demand exceeded supply; forgery became an industry. The Magos documented at least seventeen separate "authentic" finger-bones of the prophet Alon in circulation simultaneously. The Council of Three established a certification process, which created a bureaucracy, which created opportunities for bribery, which created a certification market that was almost as corrupt as the relic market it was meant to regulate.
The Centralization Push (c. 1200–1250 AF): The Council of Three — alarmed by the hundreds of independent orders operating with minimal oversight — began attempts to consolidate authority. Orders were required to submit annual reports, accept Council-appointed auditors, and seek approval for new foundations. Many orders complied. Many resisted. The tension between the Council's desire for control and the orders' traditions of independence became the Church's defining internal conflict.
Nionia (1150–1250):
Golden age continued. The Senate functioned, trade flowed, culture flourished. Nionian marble, Nionian wine, and Nionian silk were luxury goods across the continent. The island's population peaked.
The seeds of the future crisis: wealth concentrated in fewer hands. Domus Ferronus did not yet exist — the family that would become the Ferronus were common miners in the Marchia Ferrus mountains. But the mines were being expanded, and the labor conditions were brutal.
The Heartlands (1150–1250):
Peak of the Silver Covenant. Silverblood and Silverring cooperated, alternated the Argenlord title, and the region prospered. The ducal courts became centers of art, music, and scholarship. The Vaultkeepers of Silvermont established the continent's first formal banking system — deposit accounts, letters of credit, and commercial loans.
House Argenhold continued its diplomatic tradition. The city of Argenhold became the continent's premier river port, handling goods from every region. The Bargemen's Guild became a powerful economic force.
Rosland (1150–1250):
The Greenhand Era: House Greenhand held the High Barony for three consecutive terms (~1160–1190 AF) under High Baron Aldric Greenhand "the Reformer." His administration expanded the guild vote, established public granaries, and funded the first public schools in rural areas. He was beloved by the commons and resented by the nobility. His death in office (natural causes, aged 71) triggered a contested election that House Ironside won — the first Ironside to hold the High Barony. The Ironside–Greenhand rivalry, which would define Roslandic politics for the next century, began here.

PERIOD V: THE LONG PEACE & ITS CRACKS (1250 – 1308 AF)
The last century before the story. The continent enjoyed unprecedented stability. Trade flowed. Roads were safe. Each region was proud of its identity and its institutions. But beneath the surface, tensions accumulated.
Key Events (chronological):
c. 1258 AF — The Raven's Fall (Heartlands):
House Griffinwing of Corvallis — an ancient dynasty tracing pre-imperial roots — had grown stagnant. Resources depleted. No male heir. The current head, Lord Caelan Griffinwing, was rumored to prefer men, which in the Heartlands' conservative political culture made him vulnerable to accusations of failing his dynastic duty.
House Corbeau — a merchant family from the Heartlands lowlands, funded by House Silverring — launched a swift military takeover. The assault on Griffinkeep lasted three days. Lord Caelan was captured and exiled (his current whereabouts unknown). Most of the Griffinwing household was killed or scattered.
House Corbeau installed itself as the new rulers of Corvallis. Within a decade, they improved roads, expanded trade, and invested in infrastructure — winning grudging acceptance from the common people even as the old nobility viewed them as usurpers.
The surviving Griffinwing heirs — led by Arion Griffinwing (nephew of Lord Caelan, now around 25) — waged an insurgency from the eastern hills. The insurgency was still active at 1308 AF.
The Raven's Fall was the first open act of aggression in the Argent Schism — Silverring using a puppet house to seize territory from a Silverblood-aligned province. Silverblood protested diplomatically but did not intervene militarily. The precedent was set: the cold war could turn hot.
c. 1270 AF — The Wildwoman's Bargain (Frozen South / Heartlands):
Ser Edric Corbeau — uncle of Baron Corbeau, a knight patrolling the roads through the Deadwood Valley that separated the Heartlands from the Frozen South — encountered a clanwoman of the Frozen South during a scouting mission. Her name is recorded in Corbeau family legend as Sinna (probably not her real name — southern clan names are secret). They fell in love.
Sinna returned to Clan Aurax and convinced the clan elders that trade with the mainland was advantageous. She presented the steel weapons Edric had given her as proof of what the clans could obtain. The elders agreed.
First gold-for-goods trade (c. 1272 AF): Clan Aurax began sending small gold shipments through the Deadwood Valley to House Corbeau's trading posts. In exchange: steel weapons, grain, textiles, medicines. The trade was sanctioned by Clan Aurax but secret from the other clans.
The trade enriched both parties. Corbeau's wealth increased dramatically — funding the infrastructure improvements that won them legitimacy in Corvallis. Aurax gained military advantages that made them even more dominant among the southern clans.
The Aurax Gold War (c. 1285–1290 AF): When the trade was discovered by other clans, Clan Raudbjorn and Clan Daudrguard declared war on Aurax, accusing them of betraying southern independence by dealing with mainlanders. Five years of vicious winter warfare. Aurax won — their steel weapons gave them a decisive edge over Raudbjorn's bone-and-obsidian armaments. The defeat left Raudbjorn humiliated and Daudrguard isolated. The Winter-Moot of 1291 AF confirmed Aurax's dominance but the resentment was permanent.
Roslandic scouts — sent by House Ironside to investigate the rumors of southern gold — began appearing in the Deadwood Valley around 1295 AF. House Gorban, the border wardens, reported increased activity. Nobody in the Roslandic capital cared enough to investigate. They would later regret this.
c. 1284 AF — Birth of Jous Lorethian (Nionia):
Born inside the convent of the Sisters of the Veil on Nionia — a cloistered Ashanite sub-order whose members never left and never interacted with men. His mother was a young sister named Sera (surname unknown — the order stripped family names upon entry). The circumstances of the pregnancy were never explained. The order declared it a miracle — a virgin birth, the child of Loreth himself made flesh.
The baby was raised within the convent walls for the first years of his life, treated as sacred. The Sisters' prophetic reputation — they were said to see the destiny of souls — was staked on his divinity. From infancy, Jous was told he was the son of god. He never had a reason to doubt it.
Whether Sera was genuinely a virgin or had been assaulted by an intruder, a fellow sister, or a visiting benefactor is unknown. The order's seclusion made investigation impossible. The truth died with Sera, who died in childbirth.
c. 1290 AF — The Argenhold Exile (Heartlands / Xaria):
Kaeo Argenhold, eldest son of Duke Harros Argenhold, departed Argenia under circumstances that remain unclear. He was approximately 17. The official story: he was sent to study abroad. The rumored story: a falling-out with his stepmother, Lady Marthys (née Hurth), who wanted her own son Darric to inherit. The real story: probably a combination of family politics and Kaeo's own restlessness.
Kaeo traveled south through Vallan, then east to the Teeth, then by sea to the Xarian coast. He arrived at the Ix'Atani capital and somehow obtained the patronage of the Xarian governor — a member of the Ix'Atani royal house whose relaxed style of colonial administration made him open to entertaining foreign guests, especially well-born ones with useful mainland connections.
Kaeo spent 11 years in Xaria. What he did there, who he became, what he learned — these are mysteries to everyone on the mainland. He returned only when his entire family was murdered.
c. 1298 AF — The Bridge Coup (The Teeth):
Lord Morvayn — a minor noble of Emberstone with military ambitions — assassinated Lord Borakin, the chairman of the Bridge Council, during a diplomatic dinner on the central span of the Great Bridge. The method was poison — slow-acting, mixed into wine. Borakin died over the course of the evening, his collapse initially mistaken for drunkenness. By the time anyone realized what had happened, Morvayn's men had seized the bridge's toll-gates and the two towers flanking the central span.
Morvayn declared himself Lord-Warden of the Bridge — a title he invented — and imposed new tolls that effectively gave him a stranglehold on all land trade between the northern and southern halves of the continent.
The other island lords were furious but divided. House Stormglass of Northwind wanted to retake the bridge by force. House Verdane of Verwhisper preferred negotiation. House Pyrmont of Emberstone — Morvayn's home island — was split between factions that supported and opposed him. The result was the Whispering War — a cold conflict of espionage, embargo, and assassination that was still ongoing at 1308 AF.
Critical detail: Morvayn's island, Emberstone, contained the Magos' secret vault of lost technology. Morvayn did not know about the vault. But his seizure of the bridge disrupted the Magos agent's ability to access and maintain it. The Elder Magos, for the first time in centuries, was genuinely worried.
c. 1301 AF — Vlado Ironside elected High Baron (Rosland):
Vlado Ironside — head of House Ironside, lord of Fyrhold, master of the mines — won the election for High Baron through a combination of legitimate support from the military-conservative faction and backroom deals with smaller noble houses. His platform: security, order, and the "Long Vigil" — a declared state of emergency citing unspecified external threats that justified expanded executive powers.
Within two years, Vlado had suspended several provisions of the Iron Codex, packed the judiciary with allies, and begun the process of stripping the guild vote of real power. His reforms were technically legal — each one individually justified by precedent or emergency — but their cumulative effect was the slow strangulation of Roslandic democracy.
He adopted Valo — a young man of unclear parentage, possibly the orphan son of a minor noble house destroyed in a mining accident — as his heir. Vlado was believed to be infertile. Valo was groomed as his successor: educated, trained, presented to the public as the next generation of Ironside rule. The adoption was widely seen as Vlado's attempt to found a dynasty — to turn the elected High Barony into a hereditary position by ensuring his chosen successor won the next election.
His current term ended in 1311 AF. Three years away at the story's start.
c. 1304–1306 AF — The Nionian Civil War:
The Democratic Regency of Nionia had functioned for 400 years, but by the 1300s, the Senate was as corrupt as the one Nion I had burned. Domus Marcellus and Domus Navarrus controlled the majority of seats. Legislation served patrician interests. The common people — miners, quarry workers, sailors — were taxed heavily and represented not at all.
Ferron "the Upstart" (c. 1300 AF): A common miner in the Marchia Ferrus who discovered the richest iron vein on the island. The discovery made him fabulously wealthy overnight. He used the wealth to hire mercenaries, buy influence, and — critically — fund a young man who claimed to be the son of God.
Jous Lorethian's emergence (c. 1302 AF): Jous left the Sisters of the Veil convent at approximately 18 years old. He was strikingly charismatic, articulate, and possessed of an absolute conviction in his own divinity that was either inspiring or terrifying depending on your perspective. He was also plagued by sleep paralysis and lucid dreams that he interpreted as divine communication — visions of a purified Nionia, a world scrubbed clean of corruption and sin.
Ferron recognized Jous as a weapon — a charismatic figurehead who could unite the common people against the Senate. Whether Ferron believed in Jous's divinity is irrelevant; he believed in Jous's usefulness. He funded Jous's movement, armed his followers, and provided the military muscle.
Domus Lux — originally a minor religious militia, a local chapter of the Sons of Loreth that had gone rogue — attached themselves to Jous as his personal enforcers. Their leader, a zealot of unknown origin, declared Jous the prophesied "Vessel of Loreth" and placed his order at Jous's disposal.
The Civil War (1304–1306 AF): Two years of street fighting, naval skirmishes, and political assassination. The Senate's forces — primarily Domus Marcellus's household guards and Domus Navarrus's navy — were better equipped but less motivated. Jous's followers fought with the fervor of true believers. Key events:
The Burning of the Scriptorium (1304 AF): Jous's followers torched the Nionian branch of the Order of the Quill — the island's largest school and library — accusing the scholars of heresy. The Quill's records of Nionian republican history were destroyed. This act severed the island's connection to its own democratic past.
The Battle of Port Severan (1305 AF): Domus Navarrus's fleet attempted to blockade the capital. Ferron's mercenaries, using fire-ships funded by Ferronus iron money, broke the blockade and burned six of Navarrus's warships. Navarrus capitulated and offered its surviving fleet to Jous in exchange for survival. Jous accepted.
The White Night (1306 AF): The war's end. Domus Marcellus, the last holdout, surrendered after their patriarch was assassinated by a Domus Lux infiltrator. Jous entered the Senate chamber — the same chamber rebuilt after Nion I's Great Pyre — and declared the Republic dissolved and the Senate replaced by divine rule. He did not burn the building. He converted it into a cathedral.
The Triumvirate: Three elected magistrates who had served as the Senate's executive officers were retained by Jous — not out of respect for the institution but because they had been the ones to formally place the crown on his head, ending the bloodshed. They survived as a vestigial check on his power, a procedural echo of the republic that Jous tolerated because abolishing them entirely would have required acknowledging that the republic had ever been legitimate.
Jous renamed the capital: The ancient city, which had gone by several names over the centuries, was officially rechristened Vellium — after the marble (vellum-white) that defined its architecture. The name also carried a deliberate echo of "veil" — the Sisters of the Veil who had raised him.
The Pure Way: Jous's heretical theology. Not a new religion but a radical reinterpretation of Loveism. Key differences from orthodox Loveism:
Jous claimed to be the physical incarnation of Loreth — not metaphorically (all people carry divine echoes) but literally (he was Loreth made flesh, born of a virgin through divine will).
The Pure Way emphasized purity, order, and obedience over the orthodox Lovist values of compassion, service, and intellectual inquiry. Sin was not a failure of love but a failure of discipline. Redemption came not through acts of charity but through submission to divine authority — which meant submission to Jous.
The Council of Three was declared corrupt and illegitimate. The Pure Way recognized no clerical authority above Jous himself. The three orders (Ayanite, Ashanite, Alonite) were collapsed into a single hierarchy under Jous's personal priests.
The Inquisitors of the Pure Way — white-cloaked enforcers drawn from Domus Lux — replaced the traditional Lovist clergy on Nionia. They enforced doctrinal compliance through surveillance, denunciation, and public punishment.
By 1308 AF: Jous had consolidated control of Nionia. He was 24 years old, ruler of the island, and planning the conquest of the mainland. The continent had not yet realized how dangerous he was.
c. 1307 AF — The Feast of Poison (Heartlands):
Duke Harros Argenhold — aging, weakened by drink — hosted the coronation feast for his son Darric at the castle of Argenhold. Every major figure in Argenian politics attended. By midnight, every guest was dead.
Victims: Darric Argenhold (the heir), Lady Marthys Argenhold (Kaeo's stepmother), Duke Harros himself, Lord Rynald Hurth, Ser Tovan Valenti, Lady Aevra Bargemont, Lord Pelrin Redmarsh, Father Jorn of the Ayanite Concord, plus dozens of lesser nobles and servants.
The poisoner: Unknown. Suspects include House Silverblood (seizing the opportunity to install a regency), Jous Lorethian's agents (destabilizing the Heartlands ahead of invasion), Lady Marthys's own enemies (she had many), and House Valenti (whose leader Damon was conspicuously absent from the feast).
House Silverblood moved immediately — Lord Athelric Silverblood declared a regency over Argenia "until a proper heir can be installed." A bird was sent to Kaeo in Xaria.
Kaeo's return: Kaeo departed Xaria with gifts from the governor, a household of Xarian-trained servants, and the reputation of a man who had spent 11 years inside a foreign empire's colonial apparatus. He traveled by land caravan through the jungle, north through Vallan, and into the Heartlands. He arrived in Argenia in 1308 AF — the year the story begins.
1308 AF — The Giants Arrive:
Three ships. That's all that survived the crossing from the volcanic subcontinent deep to the south of Mundus, past the most dangerous seas on the planet. A fleet of (unknown number — possibly dozens) had departed. Only three made landfall.
Ship One: Landed on the coast of the Frozen South. First contact with Clan Raudbjorn territory.
Ship Two: Landed on the Red Coast. First contact with the copper settlements.
Ship Three: Landed behind the Silver Mountains in the southern Heartlands, where the mountains meet the sea. First human to spot them: Venania Sarko, a hunter's daughter from the Sandsword holding near Ashgate.
Each ship carried a different tribal faction:
The Druids (Wisemen): Masters of druidic magic — the old magic that had faded on the continent but remained potent on the volcanic subcontinent. They understood ecology, weather, animal husbandry, and the manipulation of natural forces in ways that no mainland practitioner could replicate. Their leader was the eldest druid of each ship.
The Warriors: Giant soldiers equipped with weapons and armor scaled to their enormous size. Disciplined, hierarchical, loyal to their tribal structure.
The Builders (Engineers): Specialists in construction, metalwork, and the practical sciences. They had built the ships that crossed the ocean. They could build anything.
Physical description: Giants stood roughly 12–15 feet tall. Proportioned like humans but heavier, denser — a single giant weighed as much as four large men. Skin tones varied by tribe. Life expectancy approximately 200 years. They bred slowly — a giant woman might bear two or three children in her lifetime.
Their homeland: A volcanic subcontinent called (in their language) something the mainland peoples would later approximate as Jötunheim or Eldraholm — the Fire-Home. A landmass dominated by a single massive volcano whose eruptions had been accelerating for centuries. Lava had consumed nearly a third of the island by the time the fleet departed. The giants were not invaders. They were refugees.
The magic: The volcanic subcontinent was saturated with the old magic — the same force that had once sustained the great beasts of Mundus but had faded as civilization expanded. The giants had lived with this magic for millennia and had learned to work with it. Their druids could communicate with animals, accelerate plant growth, sense weather patterns, and perform feats of natural manipulation that would be considered miraculous on the mainland.
The fauna: The giants brought their animals. White-furred mammoths with red eyes — massive beasts they farmed like cattle, used for transport, and mourned when they died. And other creatures — things from the volcanic ecology that had never existed on the continent. These creatures, infused with the subcontinent's potent magic, began appearing in Mundus as the giants settled. The world was about to get thicker again.
Giant society: Three tribes, each defined by its role. The Wisemen/Druids governed through counsel and prophecy. The Warriors defended and conquered. The Builders created and maintained. Within each tribe, all necessary social functions existed — farmers, healers, artisans, teachers. The three tribes were not competitors but complementary parts of a single civilization. Their religion was animistic — they worshipped the volcano that was killing them, the ocean that had nearly drowned them, and the earth that they hoped would receive them. They did not understand Loveism and had no frame of reference for a god who had sacrificed himself to become the world. Their gods were the world. The world was trying to kill them. They loved it anyway.

KEY INSTITUTIONS AT 1308 AF (Summary Reference)
Political Systems by Region:
Nionia: God-King (Jous Lorethian). Absolute theocratic rule. Triumvirate as vestigial check.
Heartlands: Argenlord (elected every 3 years by ducal heads of house). Currently Silverblood. Emergency powers in war/famine.
Sangrea: Lord-Patrons (independent dynastic rule). Solé vs Terrarossa as poles.
Rosland: High Baron (elected every 10 years by nobles + guilds). Currently Ironside.
The Horns: Four-house balance (Garrun/Westhorn, Dalgaard/Brinehold, Veldren/Nightspike, Lampkeepers/Skogrim).
Vallan: Valley-King (House Valenne). Ceremonial authority.
Red Coast: Red Crown (House Cenizar). Water arbitration expanded to governance.
The Teeth: Four island lords + contested Bridge (Morvayn as Lord-Warden).
Frozen South: Clan system (Aurax dominant). Winter-Moot.
Xaria: Ix'Atani colonial administration. Governor appointed by the Dominion.
Isle of Knowledge: Order of Magos. Elder Magos leads. Neutral.
Faithir / Holy See: Council of the Holy Three. Spiritual authority, diminishing temporal power.
Number of Argenlords (903–1308 AF): Approximately 135 (elected every 3 years for 405 years). Most served a single term. Some served multiple. The title has been held by Silverblood (~45 times), Silverring (~40 times), Argenhold (~20 times), Beaumont (~15 times), and various minor houses (~15 times).
Number of High Barons (905–1308 AF): Approximately 40 (elected every 10 years for 403 years). Greenhand has held the office the most times (~12). Ironside has held it ~6 times. Daurn held it early. Other houses have held it intermittently.

NAMED LOVIST ORDERS (Comprehensive List at 1308 AF)
Major Orders (the Big Three):
Ayanite Order (Truth/Law) — scholars, judges, educators
Ashanite Order (Feeling/Healing) — healers, hospices, grief counselors
Alonite Order (Action/Service) — military, construction, beast-hunting
Named Sub-Orders (active at 1308 AF): 4. Sons of Loreth (Alonite/martial) — knightly order, largest martial force 5. Brothers of the Open Road (Alonite) — road maintenance, pilgrim escort 6. Sisters of the Veil (Ashanite) — cloistered seers, Nionia 7. Order of Alon's Silence / Wandering Mutes (Alonite) — itinerant mute healers 8. Blind Daughters of Aya (Ayanite) — self-blinded oracle women 9. Order of the Harvest Bell (Ashanite) — agriculture, famine relief 10. The Bonekeepers (Ashanite) — funeral rites, ossuaries 11. The Lampkeepers (Alonite) — lighthouses, signal fires, road safety (Horns) 12. Order of the Copper Bowl (Ashanite) — alchemical healers (Red Coast) 13. The Chain-Breakers (Alonite) — anti-slavery (Xarian frontier) 14. Order of the Quill (Ayanite) — education, literacy, schools 15. The Crimson Penitents (unaffiliated) — self-flagellating pilgrims 16. Order of the Still Water (Ashanite) — contemplative monasteries 17. Order of St. Maren (Alonite) — women warriors, protection of abused (Rosland) 18. The Ember Watch (Alonite) — remnant beast-hunters (~40 members) 19. Order of the Green Thorn (Ashanite) — forest conservation (Verwhisper, Teeth) 20. The Venic Path (heretical) — mystical consciousness exploration 21. The Logosians (heretical/exiled) — rationalist theology, based at Isle of Knowledge
Implied but unnamed orders: Hundreds more — monastic breweries, fishing cooperatives, bridge-maintenance guilds, animal husbandry orders, musical orders (the Faithir Choirkeepers), manuscript-copying orders, medicinal herb gardens, criminal rehabilitation houses, orphanages, leper colonies, and dozens of regional devotional groups organized around local saints and holy sites. The exact count is unknown because new orders formed spontaneously and many operated without Council of Three authorization, which was part of what the Council was trying to rein in.

