THE ECHOES — A Codex of Magic in Mundus
What the Learned Call "The Echo-Theory" and What Everyone Else Calls "The Old Feeling"

I. THE SOURCE: WHAT MAGIC IS
The theology is the physics. That's the first thing to understand.
Loreth and Vena did not create the world and then leave it, like an architect walking away from a finished building. They became the world. The Great Sacrifice was literal: their divine bodies dissolved into stone, water, air, soil, light, heat, growth, and decay. Their consciousness — fragmented beyond recognition, beyond thought, beyond anything a mortal mind could call "awareness" — saturated every particle of the material universe. This is Lovist orthodoxy, and in Mundus, it also happens to be true.
What the faithful call echoes — those metaphysical sparks that Aya's Scrolls describe as "the breath of the divine still warm in the clay" — are not metaphors. They are the residual presence of two dead gods whose bodies are the world and whose minds were shattered into everything that exists. A rock does not think. But a rock, at some molecular level that no alchemist has ever measured and no scholar has ever adequately described, remembers being part of something that thought. A river does not love. But a river carries, in the particular way it curves around stone and pools in hollows, the echo of something that once did.
This is what magic is in Mundus: the ability to sense, interact with, and channel the residual divine consciousness embedded in the natural world.
It is not a force. It is not energy. It is not a substance you can bottle, though alchemists have spent centuries trying. It is closer to a frequency — a hum beneath the audible, a warmth beneath the tangible, a presence beneath the visible. The Ashanite mystics, who understand it better than anyone on the mainland, describe it as "the vibration between heartbeats." The Ayanite scholars, who understand it worst, describe it as "theoretical."
The Xarians have a different name for it. They call it the Blood of the Exchange — the current of life-energy that their gods demand back through sacrifice. They are wrong about the theology but right about the mechanism: something flows through living things, and it can be moved.
The Giants call it Eldra — which translates roughly as "the warmth that was there before fire." They do not theorize about it. They work with it the way a farmer works with soil: practically, intimately, without needing to explain it.
Key principle: echoes are not evenly distributed. Some places, some creatures, some materials carry more residual divine consciousness than others. The variables are age, wildness, density of life, and — critically — how much the thing has been processed by human hands.

II. THE MECHANISM: HOW IT WORKS
The Echo Gradient
Imagine a spectrum. At one end: raw, untouched wilderness — old-growth forest, deep ocean, volcanic fissures where the earth's interior pushes to the surface, caves that have never seen daylight. These places are saturated with echoes. The divine consciousness in them is dense, layered, ancient. Standing in a primeval grove, a sensitive person feels it as a physical sensation: a pressure behind the eyes, a tingling in the fingertips, a sense of being watched by something that doesn't have eyes. The Ashanites call this feeling the Pulse. The Venic Path mystics call it the Opening. Ordinary people call it "the creeps" and walk faster.
At the other end: a smelted iron ingot. A quarried stone block, cut and polished and mortared into a city wall. A field that has been plowed, planted, harvested, and plowed again for two hundred years. These things have had their echoes beaten out of them. Every act of processing — cutting, refining, smelting, tilling, building — disrupts the delicate lattice of residual consciousness in the material. The iron in the mountain is echo-rich; the iron in the sword is echo-dead. The tree in the forest hums with it; the plank in the ship is silent.
This is why civilization kills magic. Not through any active hostility, not through any deliberate suppression. Simply by existing. Every road laid, every field cleared, every mine dug, every city built replaces echo-rich wilderness with echo-dead infrastructure. The more humans transform their environment, the thinner the echo-field becomes. The process is glacial — centuries, not years — but it is relentless and, under normal circumstances, irreversible.
How Sensitivity Works
Every living thing carries echoes — humans most of all, according to Lovist theology, because humanity was the "primary creation" (though the Schism of the Lesser Life disputes this). But carrying echoes is not the same as sensing them. A person can have a spark of divinity in their chest and never feel it, the same way a person can have a heart and never hear their own pulse.
Sensitivity to echoes — the ability to feel the Pulse, to interact with the echo-field, to use what the learned would reluctantly call magic — depends on three factors:
1. Proximity to echo-dense environments. You cannot tune a lute in a silent room. Echo-sensitivity requires exposure to echo-rich stimuli. People who grow up in deep wilderness, who spend years in old forests or on untamed coastlines, develop a sensitivity that city-dwellers never acquire. This is not mystical — it is developmental. The neural pathways that process echo-stimuli form in childhood and adolescence; if they are never stimulated, they atrophy. A child raised in the Daudrwood's deepest groves will feel things that a child raised in Vornhold's stone corridors never will. The reverse is not true: the city child cannot learn sensitivity as an adult, any more than a person blinded at birth can learn to see by reading about colors.
This is why the Ember Watch recruited from frontier villages. This is why the Frozen South's clansfolk have traditions of "skin-listening" and "bone-reading" that mainlanders dismiss as superstition. This is why the Giants — who lived their entire civilization embedded in the most echo-saturated landscape on the planet — are, by mainland standards, wizards.
2. Biological echo-density. Not all humans carry the same concentration of echoes. The Lovist doctrine of "louder echoes" in kings and saints was political propaganda designed to legitimize aristocratic power, but it was built on a kernel of truth: echo-density varies between individuals. Some people are born with a denser lattice of residual consciousness in their tissues. These people are not "chosen" — they are statistical outliers, the way some people are born taller or with sharper vision. In a world saturated with echoes (the Age of History, the Giants' homeland), this variation matters little; everyone has enough. In a world drained of echoes (the mainland at 1308 AF), the variation becomes decisive: the rare person born with high echo-density in a low-echo environment is the person who sees things others don't, who heals with a touch that shouldn't work, who knows a storm is coming when the sky is clear.
Jous Lorethian has extremely high biological echo-density. Whether this is because he is genuinely divine, because the Sisters of the Veil — who lived in one of Nionia's last echo-rich environments, an ancient convent grove — somehow concentrated the trait through generations of selective seclusion, or because of some other factor, is deliberately unanswerable. His sleep paralysis, his visions, his charisma that borders on the supernatural — these are real phenomena, not performances. He feels things that other people do not. He interprets them as proof of his divinity. He may be wrong about the interpretation while being correct about the experience.
3. Altered states of consciousness. The human mind, in its normal waking state, filters out echo-stimuli the way it filters out the sound of its own breathing. This is protective — a mind fully open to the echo-field would be overwhelmed, flooded with the fragmented consciousness of every stone and tree and insect in its vicinity. The Ayanite scholars, in one of their rare moments of practical insight, call this filtering mechanism the Veil of Reason. The Venic Path calls it the Cage.
Certain states lower the filter. Meditation. Fasting. Exhaustion. Extreme emotion — grief, ecstasy, terror. And, critically, certain substances: Dreambud opens the filter gently, producing the "vivid dreams" and heightened sensory awareness that poets and Venic mystics prize. Sun-Dust blows it open violently, producing the "fiery visions" and "intense clarity" that come with the risk of permanent damage. Bonewater doesn't lower the filter so much as scramble it, producing the dissociative states that Xarian shamans use for ritual communion with their gods.
The Venic Path's heresy was not theological but practical: they discovered that systematic alteration of consciousness — through fasting, meditation, and controlled use of intoxicants — could produce reliable, repeatable echo-sensitivity in people who were otherwise too city-dulled to feel it. Brother Venic's seven-day sealed-cave fast was an echo-sensitivity protocol, not a prayer. The Council of Three banned it not because it didn't work, but because it did — and because its implications (that divine communion was a technique, not a gift) were theologically catastrophic.
What "Magic" Actually Looks Like
Echo-work is not sorcery. There are no fireballs, no telekinesis, no conjured illusions, no spoken spells. The echo-field is not a power source to be tapped; it is a presence to be collaborated with. The distinction matters.
What an echo-sensitive person can do:
Communication. The most common and least dramatic form of echo-work. Animals, being entirely natural and echo-rich, are far more attuned to the echo-field than humans. A person with sufficient sensitivity can feel an animal's emotional state — fear, hunger, territorial aggression, maternal protectiveness — and, with practice, project their own emotional state back. This is not telepathy. It is closer to empathy pushed past the species barrier. A skilled practitioner can calm a panicking horse, redirect a hunting wolf, or sense the presence of a predator through the distress of nearby prey animals. The Giants' druids can do this with a fluency that looks like conversation — the mammoth stops because the druid feels tired, and the mammoth feels the druid's tiredness as its own. But neither is speaking. Both are resonating.
Growth facilitation. An echo-sensitive person touching a living plant can accelerate its natural growth processes — not by forcing energy into it, but by deepening the plant's connection to its own echo-lattice, allowing it to draw more effectively on the residual divine consciousness in the soil, water, and sunlight around it. In practice, this means a druid can coax a seed to sprout in hours rather than days, persuade a dying tree to rally, or cause a wound to close faster by pressing living herbs against it (the herbs' echoes reinforcing the body's own). This is why hedge-medicine works when the healer has "the touch" and fails when they don't — it's not the herb that heals, it's the echo-sensitive person's ability to activate the herb's latent echoes against the wound's disruption.
Weather-sensing. The atmosphere carries echoes — wind is Vena's breath made physical, according to Ashanite poetry, and for once the poetry is mechanically accurate. Large-scale weather patterns create echo-field disturbances that a sensitive person can feel hours or days before the physical signs appear. Every coastal village has a grandmother who knows when the storm is coming. She is not a wizard. She is echo-sensitive and lives close enough to the ocean's echo-rich environment to pick up the signal.
Dread-sense. Echo-saturated creatures — the great beasts, the cryptids, the things the Ember Watch hunted — project an echo-field disturbance that sensitive humans experience as wrongness. A cold in the spine. A pressure in the temples. A conviction, irrational and absolute, that something is there and it should not be. This is not the beast being malevolent — most great beasts are no more evil than a thunderstorm. It is the human nervous system reacting to an echo-density it was not built to process. The Ember Watch called this feeling the Chill. They trained themselves to use it as a tracking sense — following the Chill to its source. Most of them were slightly mad by the time they retired, because years of deliberately exposing yourself to echo-overload leaves scars.
Subtle influence on physical processes. At the highest levels of sensitivity and skill — levels that no living human on the mainland possesses at 1308 AF, but that Giant druids demonstrate routinely — an echo-worker can influence physical processes by manipulating the echo-field around them. Not violating natural law, but nudging it: making water flow slightly uphill by deepening the echo-resonance of the destination; making fire burn slightly hotter by concentrating the echoes in the fuel; making stone fracture along a specific line by sensing the echo-lattice within the rock and finding its natural breaking point. This is what Giant builders do when they work stone without tools — they feel where the rock wants to break and help it.
Costs and Limits
Echo-work is not free.
Exhaustion. Channeling echoes is physically draining — it uses the practitioner's own biological echo-density as a medium, and prolonged use depletes it temporarily. A druid who spends a day accelerating crop growth will sleep for fourteen hours afterward and wake ravenous. A healer who mends a broken bone will have a headache for a week.
Dissonance. The more echo-sensitive you become, the more the civilized world hurts. Echo-dead environments — cities, smelted-metal-heavy spaces, heavily processed landscapes — feel to a sensitive person the way a loud, discordant noise feels to someone with perfect pitch. Giant druids cannot spend more than a few days inside a human city without becoming physically ill: headaches, nausea, disorientation, and eventually a dissociative state the Giants call Eldra-hunger — the sensation of suffocating in a place with no air, except the "air" is the echo-field. This is a critical plot constraint: the Giants cannot simply move into human cities. They need wild spaces, echo-rich environments, or they sicken and die.
Overexposure. On the other end, spending too long in hyper-saturated echo environments — the volcanic subcontinent, the deepest old-growth forests, the places where great beasts nest — can overwhelm human neurology. The symptoms are well-documented in the Ember Watch's training manuals: hallucinations, paranoid ideation, a sense that the landscape is alive and watching, and in extreme cases, a permanent alteration of perception that the Watch called greensight — the inability to stop seeing the echo-field, which makes normal life impossible. The victims wander in the wilderness, talking to trees and stones, until they die of exposure or starvation. The Ashanites maintained hospices for these cases. They never found a cure.
Non-creation. Echo-work cannot create something from nothing. It can accelerate, redirect, communicate, sense, and subtly influence — but it cannot conjure. A druid cannot make water appear in a desert; they can sense water underground and coax roots toward it. A healer cannot regrow a severed limb; they can accelerate the healing of a wound that the body could have healed on its own, given time. The line between "facilitation" and "creation" is the hard limit of the system.

III. THE THINNING: WHY THE WORLD GREW QUIET
At the beginning — in the Age of History, before cities, before empires, before even the concept of "civilization" — the echo-field was dense everywhere. The entire continent hummed. Every forest was old-growth. Every river was untouched. Every mountain was unquarried. The great beasts walked the land in vast numbers: storm-rocs darkening the sky in migration, griffins nesting on cliff-faces, grave-stags turning whole forests into their territories, dragons (if they ever existed) coiling in volcanic vents like cats in sunbeams.
Humans, in this saturated environment, were naturally echo-sensitive. Not powerfully — they were not Giants, who had millennia of echo-immersion — but enough to feel the Pulse in the soil, to sense weather, to communicate crudely with animals, to know when a great beast was near. The shamans and priest-kings of the early city-states were echo-practitioners: they led their communities because they could feel things others couldn't, and they used that sensitivity to make practical decisions about planting, hunting, migration, and defense. The "unexplained technologies" of the Age of History were, in many cases, echo-assisted engineering — stone worked along its natural echo-lattice fracture lines, crops grown in echo-optimized rotations, buildings placed at echo-resonant locations.
Then civilization happened.
Not all at once. Not with any single act. But with the cumulative weight of ten thousand acts of transformation: forests cleared for fields, rivers dammed for irrigation, mountains quarried for building stone, ore smelted into metal, land plowed and replowed until its echo-lattice was pulverized into agricultural monotony. Each act individually was trivial. Each act collectively was extinction.
The process accelerated under the Nionian Empire. The imperial roads — which the Brothers of the Open Road now maintain with such pride — were the single most destructive echo-engineering project in continental history. Thousands of miles of wild land stripped, leveled, paved with processed stone, and lined with cleared buffer zones. The roads made the empire possible, but they also carved the echo-field into fragments, cutting what had been a continuous web of resonance into isolated pockets separated by dead corridors.
The great beasts died not because humans hunted them (though humans did hunt them) but because their habitats shrank. A storm-roc needs an echo-dense territory of thousands of square miles to sustain its biological processes — its enormous body burns echo-energy the way a furnace burns fuel, and without sufficient ambient echoes, it sickens and dies. As the echo-field thinned, the great beasts retreated to the remaining dense pockets: deep forests, high mountains, oceanic trenches, volcanic regions. And as those pockets shrank, the beasts starved. The Ember Watch did not exterminate the great beasts. The Ember Watch cleaned up the last, desperate survivors — creatures driven to the margins of human settlement because there was nowhere else to go, attacking livestock and people because they were starving for echoes and couldn't distinguish between an echo-dense wild deer and an echo-depleted domestic cow.
By 1308 AF, the mainland's echo-field is at its lowest point in recorded history. The dense pockets that remain are small and scattered: the deepest parts of the Daudrwood, certain caves in the Frozen South, volcanic vents on the Red Coast, the jungle interior of Xaria (where the Ix'Atani colonial presence has been too light to cause significant echo-disruption), and a handful of other isolated locations. The great beasts are functionally extinct. The Ember Watch has forty members and nothing to hunt. Village hedge-witches and "touched" healers are rare and getting rarer — each generation, fewer children grow up in environments echo-rich enough to develop sensitivity. The Venic Path's techniques for artificial sensitivity are the last desperate attempt to access something that is almost gone.
The Isle of Knowledge sits on what the Magos privately suspect is a naturally echo-dense geological formation — the island's bedrock is ancient, unquarried volcanic basalt that has never been processed. This may explain why the Magos' archives, stored in underground vaults cut into this basalt, have survived for centuries without the decay that plagues libraries on the mainland. It may also explain why certain Magos scholars, the ones who spend decades in the deep vaults, develop odd sensitivities: an ability to "feel" when a document is a forgery, an intuition about where in the archives a particular text is shelved, a habit of talking to the stones. The Elder Magos has never officially acknowledged this phenomenon. Unofficially, senior archivists are rotated out of the deep vaults every five years to prevent "vault-dreaming."
The Theological Paradox
Here is the thing the Ayanite scholars have never been able to resolve, the question that the Logosians used to crack Loveism's intellectual foundations:
If the echoes are the residual consciousness of Loreth and Vena — if magic is literally the presence of God in the world — then the thinning of the echo-field means that civilization is killing God. Not metaphorically. Not symbolically. Every road built, every field plowed, every city raised is an act of deicide by inches. The very progress that Loreth (god of order, structure, civilization) supposedly ordained is the thing that destroys his presence in the world.
The Logosians argued this proved the gods were already dead — that the "echoes" were diminishing because they were echoes, not a living presence, and echoes fade by nature. The orthodox response (formulated hastily by Ayanite scholars during the Logosian Crisis of 1020-1040 AF) was the Doctrine of the Willing Recession: Loreth and Vena intended the echoes to fade as humanity matured, like parents stepping back as a child learns to walk. The divine presence withdraws because it trusts humanity to carry forward the work of creation without supernatural assistance. This is elegant theology. It is also, as the Logosians pointed out, unfalsifiable and suspiciously convenient.
The truth — which no one on the mainland knows — is more complicated and more tragic, and the Giants' arrival will force the question into the open.

IV. THE FIVE TRADITIONS
1. The Old Way / Druidic Echo-Work (Eldra-Craft)
The original practice, now preserved only by the Giants and in fragmentary oral traditions among the Frozen South clans.
The Giants did not "develop" druidic magic. They grew up inside it the way fish grow up inside water. Their volcanic homeland — Eldraholm, the Fire-Home — was the most echo-saturated landmass on the planet: volcanic geology constantly bringing unprocessed material from deep in the earth's echo-rich interior to the surface, a climate that discouraged large-scale agriculture (you don't plow lava fields), and a population too small and too pragmatic to engage in the kind of wholesale landscape transformation that drained the mainland.
Giant druids are not priests, not scholars, not specialists. They are simply the members of their community who were born with the highest echo-density and then trained — from childhood, through decades of practice — to refine their sensitivity into practical skill. A Giant druid can:
Communicate with animals with a fluency that approaches (but never quite reaches) true conversation. The mammoth herders speak of their animals the way a shepherd speaks of sheep — with intimate, practical knowledge of individual temperaments, needs, and capabilities. But also with a depth of emotional resonance that no mainland shepherd experiences: a druid who has bonded with a mammoth over fifty years does not "own" the mammoth. They share an emotional landscape. When the mammoth dies, the druid grieves with a totality that humans reserve for the loss of a spouse.
Sense and influence weather with enough precision to plan planting, travel, and defensive preparations days in advance.
Accelerate plant growth dramatically — not to the point of instant results, but fast enough to sustain a community in environments (volcanic ash-fields, rocky coastlines) that would be barren without intervention.
Work stone, wood, and bone along their natural echo-lattice lines, producing constructions that are structurally superior to anything human engineering can achieve — not through technology but through intimacy with the material's internal structure.
Sense other echo-sensitive beings (including humans) at great distances, feel their emotional states, and — with consent — share memories and experiences through a process the Giants call Eldra-melding. This is not mind-reading. It is closer to a shared dream: both participants enter a state of mutual echo-resonance in which memories, emotions, and sensory experiences bleed across the boundary between individuals. It is intimate, exhausting, and considered by the Giants to be one of the most sacred acts in their culture. It is also how they mourn their dead: the druids meld with the dying person's echo-lattice as it dissolves, carrying the last fragments of their consciousness into themselves, where it persists as a kind of after-image — not a ghost, not a soul, but a warmth that the druid carries for the rest of their life.
2. Folk Magic / Hedge Craft
The diluted, practical remnant of what was once universal human echo-sensitivity.
Every region has its version. The Frozen South calls it skin-listening. Rosland calls it the Old Touch. Sangrea calls it saber del campo — "the field's knowing." The Heartlands doesn't call it anything because the Heartlands, being the most heavily civilized region on the continent, has almost none of it left.
Folk magic works because some humans still live close enough to echo-dense environments to develop partial sensitivity. A healer in a Roslandic mountain village, surrounded by old-growth forest and unquarried rock, may have enough echo-sensitivity to feel when a patient's body is fighting an infection — not as a diagnosis, but as a sensation, a warmth or a wrongness under the skin. She presses a poultice of Willowglass bark against the wound, and her sensitivity allows her to unconsciously deepen the herb's echo-resonance against the infection. The patient heals faster than they should. The healer doesn't know why it works. She knows what she was taught: these herbs, applied this way, with this pressure, while saying this prayer. The prayer is irrelevant. The pressure is irrelevant. The herb matters because it is echo-rich. The healer matters because she is echo-sensitive. But neither of them knows this, and if you told them, they wouldn't believe you.
Folk magic is:
Unreliable. It depends on the practitioner's echo-sensitivity, which varies wildly and is never formally measured.
Underpowered. Partial sensitivity produces partial results.
Unsystematic. Knowledge is transmitted through apprenticeship and oral tradition, with no theoretical framework to distinguish effective techniques from superstitious accretions. A village healer's toolkit includes herbs that work (because they're echo-active) alongside rituals that don't (because they're cultural habit), and she has no way to tell which is which.
Disappearing. Each generation, as the echo-field thins and more young people move to cities, fewer folk practitioners emerge. The knowledge isn't dying because no one writes it down; it's dying because the environment that makes it functional is shrinking.
3. Alchemy
The attempt to extract, concentrate, and deploy echoes through physical processing. Alchemy is what happens when a systematic mind encounters folk magic and asks: "What if we could do this on purpose?"
The alchemists of Mundus — clustered primarily in the Magos archives, the Red Coast's copper-bowl healers, and the private laboratories of wealthy nobles — have, over centuries, developed a practical if imperfect understanding of echo-chemistry. They know, though they don't use these terms, that certain natural materials are echo-dense (volcanic glass, unprocessed copper, old-growth wood, specific fungi, fresh spring water). They know that combining certain echo-dense materials in certain ways produces effects that individual materials don't: a tincture of Moonmilk fungus and Copperthorn oil, mixed in a copper bowl, has analgesic properties far exceeding what either substance produces alone. They don't know why — their theoretical framework attributes it to the interaction of "essences" or "humors" or "sympathies" — but their recipes work, and they've been refined over generations of trial and error.
The fundamental problem of alchemy is the paradox of processing: the act of extracting and refining echo-dense materials inevitably destroys some of their echo-density. Grinding a fungus into powder, distilling a resin into tincture, heating a mineral into solution — each step strips echoes from the material. The alchemist is trying to concentrate something that the process of concentration destroys. The best alchemists have learned to minimize this loss — using echo-dense tools (copper bowls, not iron; glass, not steel; wooden mortars, not stone), working in echo-rich environments (underground, in old buildings, near natural springs), and performing their work quickly to limit exposure to echo-dead air. But they can never eliminate the loss entirely, which is why alchemical products are expensive, unreliable, and produce effects far weaker than what a true echo-practitioner could achieve through direct manipulation.
The Order of the Copper Bowl has pushed closest to the line. Their practice of mixing Frostpetal derivatives and Dreambud infusions into copper tinctures is, without their knowing it, a crude form of echo-frequency manipulation: the Frostpetal (grown in the echo-dense volcanic environment of the Frozen South) provides raw echo-material, the Dreambud lowers the patient's echo-filter (the Veil of Reason), and the copper bowl acts as a resonance chamber that minimizes echo-loss during preparation. The combination produces genuine analgesic and healing effects that purely chemical explanations cannot account for. The Council of Three tolerates the Copper Bowl because the results are real. They distrust them because the mechanism is uncomfortably close to what the Venic Path was banned for.
The Magos' vaults contain artifacts from the Age of History — objects whose construction implies a level of echo-engineering far beyond anything the current alchemists can achieve. Tools that still function after thousands of years. Metals that don't corrode. Documents that don't decay. The Magos don't understand how these objects work. They know they were made during a period when the echo-field was immensely denser, and they suspect that the "lost technology" of the Age of History was not technology in the modern sense at all — it was echo-craft practiced at a scale and sophistication that the current world cannot replicate.
Vlado Ironside's search for immortality is, at its core, an alchemical project: he has read the esoteric texts in the Magos archives, he has noted the references to "undying metals" and "ever-living waters," and he has concluded that the ancients possessed a means of extending life that has been lost. He is not wrong. He is, however, attempting to reverse-engineer a technology that required an echo-field a hundred times denser than the one he lives in, using tools and methods that actively destroy the thing he needs. His search is doomed. But he doesn't know that, and the people he pays to pursue it don't know that, and the trail of experimental failures (and human subjects) his researchers leave behind is becoming a problem.
4. The Venic Path
The heresy that was right.
Brother Venic discovered, through his seven-day fast in a sealed cave, that extreme sensory deprivation combined with fasting dropped the Veil of Reason low enough to make even a city-born monk echo-sensitive. His experience in the cave — which he described as "drowning in the voice of God" — was not a mystical vision. It was the raw experience of a human nervous system suddenly flooded with echo-stimuli it had spent a lifetime filtering out. The "voice of God" was the echo-field of the cave's ancient, unquarried stone, and it was loud.
The Venic Path's subsequent development was a systematic attempt to reproduce and refine Venic's experience. Through generations of experimentation — much of it dangerous, some of it fatal — the Path's practitioners developed a toolkit of consciousness-altering techniques:
Fasting protocols that lower the Veil gradually rather than catastrophically.
Meditation techniques derived from Asha's Tomes of Vibration — the raised-dot patterns on the Tablets, it turns out, produce echo-resonance patterns when traced with the fingertips, effectively tuning the practitioner's nervous system to the echo-field. The Ashanites use the Tablets devotionally; the Venics use them therapeutically.
Controlled intoxicant use. Dreambud for gentle lowering of the Veil. Sun-Dust for violent breakthroughs (dangerous but sometimes necessary for practitioners who have spent too long in echo-dead environments and need a shock to restart their sensitivity). Bonewater for deep echo-work that approaches the Giant druids' Eldra-melding — though without training, Bonewater-induced melding is uncontrolled, overwhelming, and frequently traumatic.
Environmental protocols. Venic practitioners seek out echo-dense locations for their work: caves, old forests, volcanic vents, ancient ruins. The most advanced Venic circles maintain secret maps of echo-dense sites across the continent — a network of caves, springs, and groves that the practitioners call the Veins. The name, coincidentally, is also what the Giants call the echo-rich geological formations of their homeland.
The Council of Three banned the Venic Path in 1023 AF for reasons that were theological on the surface and political underneath. Theologically, the Path's claim that divine communion was achievable through technique rather than grace undermined the Church's role as intermediary between humanity and the divine. Politically, an echo-sensitive population would have practical abilities that the Church could not control, could not monopolize, and could not attribute to its own institutional blessing. A healer who can feel infections doesn't need an Ashanite hospice. A farmer who can sense weather doesn't need a Harvest Bell almanac. An arbiter who can feel lies doesn't need an Ayanite court. The Path was banned because it threatened to make the Church irrelevant.
The Path persists underground. Its practitioners — estimated at perhaps two or three hundred across the continent, concentrated in Sangrea (where the culture's sensuality provides cover), the Frozen South (where the clan traditions never recognized the Council's authority anyway), and the rural Heartlands (where enforcement is lax) — are the mainland's closest equivalent to echo-practitioners. They are also the people best positioned to understand what the Giants represent when they arrive.
5. The Pure Way (Jous Lorethian's "Miracles")
Jous is a genuine echo-sensitive. His biological echo-density is exceptionally high. His upbringing in the Sisters of the Veil convent — one of Nionia's few remaining echo-rich environments — gave his sensitivity room to develop. His sleep paralysis is a form of involuntary echo-perception: during the paralysis state, his Veil of Reason drops completely, flooding him with echo-stimuli that his waking mind cannot process. His "visions" are not prophetic — they are his mind's attempt to narrativize raw echo-data into something it can understand. The images he sees (a purified Nionia, a world scrubbed clean) are not messages from Loreth. They are his own psychological obsessions reflected back at him through the echo-field's distorted mirror.
The Pure Way's theology is built on Jous's genuine but misinterpreted experience. He does feel things other people don't. He does have abilities that seem miraculous to people who have never encountered echo-sensitivity. His personal magnetism — the almost physical pull that people feel in his presence — is an unconscious echo-projection: his high biological echo-density creates a localized field that other humans' echo-remnants respond to. People near Jous feel more — more certain, more fervent, more alive — because his echo-field is activating their own dormant sparks. This is not mind control. It is resonance. But the practical effect is the same: people in Jous's presence find it very difficult to doubt him, and very easy to believe.
The dangerous irony: Jous's Pure Way theology, with its emphasis on purity, order, and obedience, is antithetical to the conditions that sustain echo-sensitivity. If Jous succeeds in conquering the mainland and imposing the Pure Way's rigid, systematized civilization, he will accelerate the thinning of the echo-field — destroying the very phenomenon that makes him "divine." His conquest would be self-negating: the more he wins, the less miraculous he becomes. The more cities he builds, the quieter the echoes get. The more order he imposes, the deader the world.
He doesn't know this. No one on Nionia does.

V. THE BEASTS: NODES IN THE WEB
The great beasts of Mundus — the storm-rocs, griffins, grave-stags, basilisks, harpies, manticores, sea-wyrms, and the unverified dragons — were not merely large animals. They were echo-nodes: creatures whose biological echo-density was so high that they functioned as living reservoirs of residual divine consciousness.
A storm-roc in flight did not simply ride the wind. It was the wind, in the echo-field sense: its body served as a focal point for atmospheric echo-currents, drawing them into patterns that produced the storms that accompanied its migration. Kill the roc, and the local weather patterns shift. Kill enough rocs, and the continent's climate changes. This actually happened: the extinction of the storm-roc flocks between 400 and 800 AF correlates with a documented shift in rainfall patterns across the Heartlands, which Magos climatologists have attributed to "natural cycles" because they don't have the theoretical framework to connect it to fauna die-off.
The harpies of the Horns coast were echo-nodes for wind and sound. Their "shrieks" were not merely loud — they resonated in the echo-field, producing effects that physical acoustics cannot explain: sailors' reports of hearing their dead mothers' voices in harpy screams, of entire crews becoming disoriented and rowing in circles, of ships' compasses spinning. These effects ceased when the Crusade of the Skogrim Corridor cleared the Horns harpy rookeries in 1060-1075 AF. The Lampkeepers of Skogrim, who lived closest to the harpy colonies, were the most echo-sensitive humans in the Horns — their "uncanny navigational skills" were a direct consequence of decades of exposure to harpy echo-emissions.
The basilisks — the most feared of the beasts — were echo-nodes for stasis. Their "gaze that freezes blood" was not a magical power but an echo-field emission so dense that it overwhelmed the target's nervous system, producing a paralysis indistinguishable from death. The victim's heart continued to beat (barely), their brain continued to function (dimly), but their voluntary nervous system shut down entirely. Victims recovered if removed from the basilisk's range quickly enough. Victims who were not removed entered a state of cascading organ failure as the echo-overload disrupted their biological processes. The Ember Watch developed countermeasures: reflective surfaces (which scattered the echo-emission), wax earplugs (which blocked an acoustic component of the field that the Watch never understood), and a pre-encounter dose of Frostpetal (which, by stimulating the nervous system, raised the threshold for echo-paralysis). These countermeasures were effective enough that basilisk hunts had a survival rate of roughly 60%. By 1308 AF, no basilisk has been reliably sighted in over a century. The Ember Watch's remaining members carry their ancestors' countermeasure kits as talismans.
The narrative implication: The great beasts were not just animals. They were load-bearing elements of the world's echo-infrastructure. Each extinction didn't just remove a species — it removed a node from the network, weakening the overall field, accelerating the thinning, making the next extinction more likely. The process was a cascade: as the field thinned, the beasts that depended on it weakened; as they weakened, they became easier to kill; as they were killed, the field thinned further. The Ember Watch, in their heroic century of beast-hunting, did not save civilization from monsters. They completed civilization's conquest of the divine.

VI. THE RETURN: WHAT THE GIANTS BRING
Three ships. An unknown number departed; three arrived. And with those three ships came an echo-field density that the continent of Mundus has not experienced in centuries.
The Giants themselves are echo-dense. Their bodies, developed over millennia of immersion in Eldraholm's saturated environment, are living echo-reservoirs. A single Giant standing in a Heartlands meadow would produce measurable effects within a radius of several hundred yards: plants growing faster, animals behaving strangely, weather patterns shifting subtly, and echo-sensitive humans (if any were nearby) feeling the Pulse for the first time in their lives.
Their animals are echo-dense. The white mammoths, in particular, are the closest thing to surviving echo-nodes that the mainland has seen since the last griffin died. Each mammoth carries an echo-field comparable to a small old-growth forest. Where the mammoths graze, the land wakes up.
And the Giants brought seeds, spores, and organisms from Eldraholm — volcanic-adapted flora and fauna carrying echo-concentrations that mainland biology has never encountered. As these organisms establish themselves — in the Frozen South where Ship One landed, on the Red Coast where Ship Two made landfall, in the southern Heartlands where Venania Sarko watched Ship Three disgorge its passengers — they will begin to re-saturate the local echo-field. Not quickly. Not dramatically. But steadily, and with consequences no one can predict.
What happens when the echoes come back:
The beasts return. Not the extinct species — they are gone. But the ecological niches they occupied still exist, and as the echo-field re-saturates, new creatures will evolve to fill them. Within a generation of the Giants' settlement, the regions surrounding their enclaves will see animals behaving in ways that haven't been observed in centuries: livestock exhibiting unusual intelligence, wild predators developing pack behaviors of uncanny coordination, marine life in the Giants' coastal waters growing to sizes not seen since the Age of History. And in the deep places — the caves, the old forests, the volcanic vents — things will begin to stir that have been dormant for so long that no human remembers them.
Humans become sensitive again. Children born near Giant settlements — exposed to echo-dense environments during the critical developmental window — will develop sensitivities their parents never had. The first generation will be small: a child who always knows when it's going to rain, a girl who can calm horses with a touch, a boy who has nightmares about things he's never seen. By the second generation, if the Giants remain and the echo-field continues to strengthen, the effects will be impossible to dismiss as coincidence. The Ember Watch's forty remaining members — most of them old, all of them wondering if they wasted their lives training for something that no longer exists — will suddenly have something to hunt again. And they will not be ready.
The Church panics. If the echoes are returning — if the divine presence is strengthening after centuries of weakening — then the Doctrine of the Willing Recession collapses. The gods are not stepping back to let humanity mature. Something else is happening, something the theology has no framework for. The Ashanites will welcome it (the sacred is returning). The Alonites will fear it (the beasts are returning). The Ayanites will deny it (because admitting it would validate the Logosians, who argued that echoes were natural phenomena, not divine grace — and if the echoes can be strengthened by a boatload of refugees, then they clearly are natural phenomena).
Jous Lorethian becomes simultaneously more powerful and more threatened. More powerful because the strengthening echo-field amplifies his abilities — his charisma becomes more intense, his visions more vivid, his presence more overwhelming. More threatened because the Giants' druidic practice proves that echo-work is a skill, not a divine gift, and if anyone ever makes that connection, his claim to be the unique incarnation of Loreth collapses. He is not the son of God. He is an echo-sensitive human with a good story. The Giants are an entire civilization of people like him — and they're better at it.

VII. THE NAMING OF THINGS
What the various cultures call the echo-field and its phenomena:
Lovist orthodox: "The Echoes," "the divine sparks," "the resonance of the Great Sacrifice." Treated as theology, not physics.
Ashanite mystics: "The Pulse," "Vena's breath," "the vibration between heartbeats."
Ayanite scholars: "Theoretical residual divine emanation." They have seventeen-syllable names for things they refuse to admit exist.
Venic Path: "The Opening," "the Veins" (echo-dense locations), "the Cage" (the Veil of Reason).
Ember Watch: "The Chill" (beast-proximity warning), "greensight" (echo-overexposure syndrome), "the Thick" (echo-dense area, as in "the forest is thick tonight").
Folk practitioners: "The Old Touch," "the knowing," "the sight," "skin-listening" (Frozen South).
Giants: "Eldra" — the warmth that was there before fire. Adjective form: "Eldra-rich," "Eldra-hungry." Practice: "Eldra-craft." The melding: "Eldra-melding." The sickness from echo-deprivation: "Eldra-hunger."
Xarians: "The Blood of the Exchange." Their sacrificial theology is a misinterpretation of echo-mechanics: they believe the echo-field must be fed with life to continue, which is backwards — the echo-field sustains life, not the reverse. But their sacrificial practices, by concentrating emotional echo-output (pain, terror, ecstasy) in ritually charged locations, do produce localized echo-density spikes that their priests interpret as divine favor. They are performing accidental echo-engineering and attributing the results to gods who don't exist. It works anyway.
Logosians: "A natural phenomenon of diminishing residual energy consistent with thermodynamic principles." They are the closest to correct and the least likely to be believed.
Common people: They don't have a name for it. They just know that grandmother's poultices work better than the apothecary's, that the forest feels different at night, that certain places are sacred and certain places are cursed, and that it's bad luck to build a house where a great beast died. They know these things the way they know that bread rises and rain falls — without theory, without explanation, as facts of a world they have never needed to analyze.

ELDRAHOLM — The Fire-Home
A Culture Bible of the Giants of Mundus

I. THE ISLAND
Geography
Eldraholm sits deep in the southern ocean, past waters so violent and currents so unpredictable that no mainland vessel has ever reached it — not because it cannot be found, but because it cannot be approached. The island is roughly the size of Iceland: large enough to sustain a civilization, small enough that its inhabitants knew every ridge and valley by name.
The dominant feature is Urdrath — the Burning Father. A stratovolcano so massive that its summit is perpetually shrouded in its own weather system, Urdrath occupies the island's center like a fist pushing through a table. Its slopes are terraced with ancient lava flows, some cooled into fertile basalt shelves, others still glowing with the slow creep of fresh magma. The volcano has been active for as long as the Giants' oral history stretches — which is roughly eight thousand years, given their two-century lifespans and their prodigious memories. But "active" is a spectrum. For most of recorded history, Urdrath rumbled and fumed and occasionally belched lava down predictable channels that the Giants mapped and avoided. The eruptions were manageable. The ash was fertile. The geothermal heat kept the winters mild. Urdrath was not a threat. Urdrath was the foundation.
The island's terrain radiates outward from Urdrath in concentric ecological rings:
The Ashlands — The inner ring. Barren lava fields, sulfurous vents, rivers of superheated water. Uninhabitable except by the most extreme echo-adapted organisms. The Ashlands have been expanding for the last three centuries as Urdrath's eruptions intensify, swallowing territory that was once part of the second ring.
The Thornwood — The middle ring. Dense, ancient forest of colossal trees — some over three hundred feet tall, with trunk diameters measured in the tens of yards. These are not mainland trees. They are echo-saturated organisms that have been growing in the island's hyper-dense Eldra-field for millennia, their root systems intertwined into a single underground network that the druids call the Weft. The Thornwood's trees have names. The druids speak to them. The trees do not speak back — they are not sentient — but they respond, the way a body responds to a hand placed on its chest: with warmth, with movement, with something that is not thought but is not nothing. The Thornwood was the Giants' homeland — their settlements were built within the forest, not cleared from it. They lived in and among the trees, carving homes into living trunks, building bridges between canopy platforms, farming the forest floor's rich volcanic soil without ever felling a tree that had not already died. A Giant who cut a living Thornwood tree was not a criminal. They were incomprehensible — the act was so alien to Giant psychology that their language didn't have a word for it. The closest translation: "one who cuts their own veins."
The Shorelands — The outer ring. Rocky coastline, tidal flats, shallow coves, and the massive kelp forests that ring the island. The Shorelands were the least populated zone — the Giants are not a seafaring people by temperament. Their size made boat-building enormously difficult: a vessel that could carry even a single Giant required more timber, more pitch, more labor than a human ship ten times its crew capacity. The Giants built small fishing craft for coastal use and occasionally ventured into deeper water for whale-hunting (a seasonal ritual, not a commercial enterprise), but the open ocean was alien territory. They did not explore it. They did not wonder what was beyond it. They knew the sea was vast and hostile, and they had everything they needed on the island. Why would they leave?
The Barrier — The Eldra-Veil
The island's extreme echo-saturation produced a phenomenon that the Giants never named because they never needed to — they didn't know it existed. From the outside, the effect would have been unmistakable: a zone extending roughly fifty miles in every direction from the island's coast where the echo-field was so dense that it produced catastrophic effects on any organism not adapted to it.
For ocean-going animals, the zone was a wall of dread. Fish turned back. Whales altered migration routes to avoid it. Seabirds flew around it. The echo-density at the boundary was comparable to a basilisk's paralysis-field, but diffused across a vast area: not intense enough to kill, but powerful enough to produce an overwhelming, irrational conviction that something terrible was ahead. Any mainland sailor who somehow navigated the currents and storms of the deep southern ocean would, upon entering the zone, experience escalating panic, disorientation, auditory hallucinations, and — if they persisted — a dissociative break severe enough to make navigation impossible. They would turn back. They would not remember clearly why.
For the Giants, the barrier was invisible. Their echo-adapted neurology processed the island's saturation as normal — the way a deep-sea fish doesn't feel water pressure. They could sail to the barrier's edge, but at the boundary, the echo-field changed character: the dense, familiar warmth of the island's Eldra gave way to a wall of noise — chaotic, unstructured echo-emissions from the vast ocean floor, amplified by the barrier's edge into a cacophony that the druids described as "the screaming of drowned stone." It was physically painful. Giants who ventured into it became ill within hours. The few exploratory voyages in Giant history — there were perhaps a dozen across eight millennia — all ended the same way: the crew turned back, sick and frightened, and reported that the world ended at the water's edge. The ocean was not a road. It was a wall. The Giants accepted this the way they accepted Urdrath's eruptions: as a fact of their world, not a puzzle to be solved.
The barrier was not magical in the sense of being deliberately created. It was an emergent property of the island's echo-ecology — the sheer concentration of residual divine consciousness in and around Eldraholm produced a self-reinforcing boundary, the way a massive gravitational body curves space around it. The echo-field was so dense that it held itself together, creating a bubble of saturation surrounded by a shell of chaotic interference.
When the Giants' evacuation fleet broke through the barrier — driven by a desperation that overrode the pain, the fear, and the disorientation — they did not merely cross a boundary. They ruptured the bubble. The echo-field that had been self-contained for millennia began bleeding outward through the breach, dissipating into the vast echo-depleted ocean and, eventually, reaching the distant shores of Mundus. Simultaneously, the island's internal echo-density began dropping — slowly at first, then with accelerating speed as the breach widened and stabilized. The Eldra-Veil did not repair itself. It could not. The structural integrity of the bubble depended on total containment. A single rupture was fatal.
The Giants who remained on Eldraholm — those who did not board the ships, who stayed because they were too old, too young, too sick, or too proud — are now living in a world that is losing its Eldra. Their druids are weakening. Their Thornwood trees are growing sluggish. Their animals are becoming listless, confused, behaving in ways they never have. The geothermal warmth is unchanged — Urdrath still burns — but the other warmth, the one that made the island alive in a way that no mainland person has ever experienced, is leaking away through the wound in the sea. The volcano is killing them from the center. The breach is killing them from the edge. They are dying in a closing ring.

II. THE TRIBES
Deep History
At their peak — roughly four thousand years before the story, during a period the Giants' oral histories call the Long Warmth — Eldraholm's population reached approximately thirty-five thousand. For a species that breeds slowly (a giantess might bear two children in a lifetime of two centuries, and many bore only one or none), this represented millennia of steady, careful growth. The island could have sustained more, but the Giants never pushed for more. They were not expansionist. Their culture was shaped by the Eldra-field's influence: a deep, instinctive sense that they existed within something, not above it. Growth for its own sake felt wrong to them the way standing in a fire felt wrong — not a moral judgment, but a physical revulsion.
The tribes were not political units. They were ecological ones — communities organized around the particular landscape they inhabited, the particular way they interacted with the Eldra in their region, and the particular animals, plants, and geological features they lived alongside. A Giant's tribe was not their government. It was their biome.
Over eight thousand years of history, tribes formed, merged, split, reformed, migrated, and occasionally dissolved. At any given point, between eight and fifteen distinct tribes existed simultaneously. By the time of the evacuation, the following were the recognized tribal identities:
The Twelve Tribes of Eldraholm (at the time of the crossing)
1. The Velthari — "Those Who Listen to the Root"
The largest tribe. Forest-dwellers of the central Thornwood, concentrated in the ancient groves closest to Urdrath's base where the volcanic soil was richest and the trees oldest. The Velthari were the island's spiritual core — their druids maintained the deepest connection to the Weft (the underground root-network) and served as the primary interpreters of the Thornwood's slow, vast communications. A Velthari druid could press their palms against a Thornwood trunk and feel weather patterns two days away, sense the health of trees on the opposite side of the forest, and — in rare, sacred ceremonies — access fragmentary echo-memories embedded in wood that had been growing for thousands of years. The Velthari believed these memories were the voices of dead druids whose consciousness had been absorbed into the Weft through Eldra-melding at the moment of death. They were probably right.
Velthari giants were the tallest of the tribes (averaging 14-15 feet), with bark-brown skin and deep green eyes — pigmentation adapted to the forest's filtered light. They wore living garments: moss-woven cloaks that continued growing on their bodies, vine-braided belts, crowns of slowly unfurling fern fronds. Their settlements were vertical — platforms ascending into the canopy, connected by bridges of woven root, with the forest floor reserved for ceremony and burial.
2. The Korvaan — "The Forge-Blooded"
Ashlands-edge dwellers who lived closest to Urdrath's active zones. The Korvaan were the island's metallurgists and builders — not because they disdained the Eldra (no Giant could) but because they had learned to work with it through fire rather than through growth. Where the Velthari listened to roots, the Korvaan listened to stone. They could feel the echo-lattice in volcanic basalt and obsidian, sense the stress lines in cooling lava, and — their most remarkable skill — shape molten rock with their bare hands, using their own echo-density to influence the cooling process and produce structures of extraordinary precision and beauty. Their architecture was volcanic glass and basalt, carved and fused rather than cut and mortared. Korvaan buildings looked grown rather than built — organic curves, flowing lines, surfaces that caught light like frozen water.
Korvaan giants were shorter and broader than the Velthari (averaging 12-13 feet), with ash-grey skin that carried a faint reddish undertone, as if lit from within. Their hands were their most distinctive feature: thick-fingered, heat-scarred, with palms calloused into a texture like cooled lava. They were the tribe most comfortable in extreme heat — a Korvaan smith could handle materials that would blister a Velthari in seconds. Their garments were leather and woven mineral fiber, practical and heat-resistant, dyed with volcanic pigments in deep reds, oranges, and blacks.
As Urdrath's eruptions intensified, the Korvaan were the first tribe to suffer direct losses — their Ashlands-edge settlements were swallowed one by one. They were also the first to argue for evacuation, and the tribe that designed and built the evacuation fleet. Every ship that sailed was a Korvaan creation.
3. The Dyrholmar — "Keepers of the Tide-Dream"
Coastal giants. Fisherfolk, kelp-farmers, whale-hunters. The Dyrholmar occupied the Shorelands and maintained the island's only relationship with the ocean — a relationship characterized by respect bordering on fear. They were the tribe best adapted to water: slightly webbed fingers and toes, a subcutaneous fat layer that made them buoyant and cold-resistant, and an echo-sensitivity attuned to marine environments. A Dyrholmar diver could feel the Eldra-currents in deep water — underwater rivers of echo-density that followed the ocean floor's geology — and navigate by them in total darkness. They were the closest thing the Giants had to sailors, though their vessels were coastal craft, not ocean-going ships.
The Dyrholmar knew the barrier existed. They didn't understand what it was, but they had a name for the zone where the ocean became hostile: the Screamwater. Their fishing routes were mapped to avoid it. Their whale-hunts circled within it. Their oral traditions included cautionary tales of ancestors who sailed too far and came back "emptied" — a term they used for the dissociative state produced by barrier exposure. Emptied Dyrholmar were cared for by the community but never recovered fully. They spent their remaining years staring at the sea with an expression that other Giants described as "listening to something that wasn't there anymore."
Dyrholmar giants had blue-grey skin, pale eyes adapted to underwater light, and hair that grew in thick, salt-stiffened ropes. They averaged 13-14 feet and were the leanest of the tribes. They wore seal-hide and kelp-fiber, ornamented with whale-bone and polished shell. Their settlements clung to cliff faces and tidal caves, built to withstand the enormous waves that battered Eldraholm's coast.
4. The Eshkári — "The Smoke-Singers"
A small, nomadic tribe that lived in the transitional zone between the Thornwood and the Ashlands — the most ecologically volatile region of the island, where forest gave way to lava field in a shifting, uncertain border. The Eshkári were the island's storytellers, historians, and — for lack of a better word — artists. Their relationship with the Eldra was uniquely auditory: where the Velthari felt the Weft through touch and the Korvaan felt stone through heat, the Eshkári heard the echo-field. They perceived Eldra-fluctuations as sound — a constant, layered harmonic that they called the Hum. Their druids could distinguish individual voices within the Hum: the bass of deep stone, the tenor of running water, the soprano of wind through canopy, the percussive crackle of cooling lava.
The Eshkári translated the Hum into song. Their oral tradition — the longest continuous musical tradition on the planet — encoded ecological information, tribal history, navigational data, and spiritual teaching into complex polyphonic compositions that could last for days. A trained Eshkári singer could perform a song that simultaneously told the story of a historical event, described the route between two settlements, catalogued the plants growing along that route, and predicted the weather for the next three days. The songs were not metaphorical. They were data, compressed into a format that the Giants' long-lived, echo-sensitive minds could decompress through listening. Losing an Eshkári elder was like losing a library.
Eshkári giants were the smallest tribe physically (averaging 12 feet) and the most varied in appearance — their nomadic range exposed them to multiple ecological zones, and their intermarriage patterns were the least restricted of any tribe. Their distinguishing feature was their voices: deep, resonant, with a harmonic range that human ears could feel in their chests. They wore whatever was practical for their current location, but always carried a throatstone — a small, echo-dense pebble worn on a cord around the neck, tuned through years of contact with the wearer's echo-field to resonate at their personal frequency. An Eshkári's throatstone was the most intimate object they possessed. It was buried with them. Taking a living Eshkári's throatstone was the closest thing Giant culture had to a killing offense.
5. The Hrundvaal — "The Still Ones"
Highland giants. The Hrundvaal occupied the high ridges and plateaus above the Thornwood's canopy, in the alpine zone where the air was thin, the wind was constant, and the echo-field had a different character: clearer, sharper, less layered than the dense warmth of the forest floor. The Hrundvaal were the island's astronomers and weather-workers. Their echo-sensitivity was atmospheric — they felt the sky the way the Velthari felt roots and the Dyrholmar felt water. A Hrundvaal druid standing on a ridge could sense storm systems forming over the open ocean days before they reached the island, feel the pressure differentials that preceded earthquakes (an invaluable skill on a volcanic island), and — according to their own traditions — perceive the faint echo-emissions of the two suns and the two moons, which they mapped into a cosmological framework more sophisticated than anything on the mainland.
The Hrundvaal were contemplatives. Their culture valued silence, observation, and patience to a degree that other tribes found unnerving. A Hrundvaal greeting involved standing quietly in the other person's presence for several minutes before speaking — long enough to "hear their weather," meaning to sense the other person's echo-field and gauge their emotional state. Rushing this process was not merely rude; it was considered dangerous, like approaching a cliff edge at a run.
Hrundvaal giants were lean and long-limbed, with pale, almost white skin and silver-grey hair — pigmentation adapted to high-altitude UV exposure. They averaged 13-14 feet. Their garments were wind-resistant layers of felted mammoth wool, and they were the tribe most associated with the white mammoths, which they herded on the high plateaus. Their settlements were stone cairns and wind-shelters, deliberately minimal — the Hrundvaal believed that a home should leave no more mark on the land than a sleeping animal.
6. The Gahlmarr — "Blood of the Mountain"
Cave-dwellers. The Gahlmarr occupied the extensive cavern systems that honeycombed Urdrath's lower slopes — natural tunnels carved by ancient lava tubes, expanded over millennia by the Gahlmarr into a subterranean civilization of extraordinary complexity. Their echo-sensitivity was geological: they felt the mountain's internal structure the way a physician feels a patient's pulse. A Gahlmarr druid could detect magma movements deep within Urdrath's chamber system, predict eruption timing with remarkable accuracy, and sense the stability of tunnel walls by pressing their ear to the stone.
The Gahlmarr were the tribe most directly threatened by Urdrath's intensification. Their tunnels, which had been stable for thousands of years, began collapsing as the magma chamber expanded. The Gahlmarr lost more of their population to the volcano than any other tribe — entire family networks buried alive in tunnel collapses, scalded by unexpected magma intrusions, or asphyxiated by volcanic gas that their druids failed to sense in time because the mountain's echo-signature was changing faster than their models could track.
Gahlmarr giants were the broadest and most powerfully built (13 feet but heavily muscled, weighing as much as the taller Velthari), with coal-dark skin, luminous amber eyes adapted to underground darkness, and a distinctive bioluminescent pattern on their forearms — faint blue-green lines that glowed in total darkness, an echo-biological adaptation unique to their tribe. They wore stone-fiber and lichen-cloth, decorated with cave-crystal and phosphorescent fungal pigments.
7. The Solveig — "Walkers Between"
The healers. Not a geographically defined tribe but a kinship network distributed across all other tribes — a family line whose members were born with unusually high biological echo-density and a corresponding gift for echo-work applied to living bodies. A Solveig healer could feel disease the way a Gahlmarr felt unstable stone: as a disruption in the patient's echo-lattice, a wrongness that could be sensed through touch and, with skill, corrected. Their healing was not miraculous — they could not cure what the body could not cure itself — but they could accelerate healing dramatically, calm pain, reduce fever, and in some cases restart hearts that had stopped.
The Solveig were rare. At any given time, perhaps two hundred to three hundred existed across the entire island. They did not marry within their own line (their echo-density was so high that Solveig-Solveig pairings produced children with sensory overload disorders), instead pairing with partners from other tribes and producing offspring who might or might not inherit the gift. A Solveig child manifested between the ages of eight and twelve — usually by instinctively laying hands on a sick animal or injured sibling and producing a visible acceleration of healing. The child was then claimed by the Solveig kinship network and trained, regardless of which tribe's territory they were born in.
Solveig giants had no distinctive physical appearance beyond a tendency toward slenderness and an unusual warmth to their skin — other Giants described touching a Solveig as "putting your hand near a fire that doesn't burn." They wore whatever garments were customary in their host tribe's territory, with one universal marker: a pale blue cord woven into their hair, dyed with a phosphorescent lichen that glowed faintly in darkness. The cord marked them as healers and, in Giant tradition, guaranteed them safe passage through any tribal territory and immunity from any inter-tribal dispute. A tribe that harmed a Solveig was shunned by all other tribes until restitution was made. In eight thousand years of history, this happened exactly twice.
8. The Thundrekk — "Storm-Striders"
Warriors. The Thundrekk were not a standing army — the Giants had no such concept — but a martial tradition that existed across tribal lines, similar to the Solveig but defined by temperament rather than bloodline. Giants who were drawn to physicality, to competition, to the defense of territory and the resolution of disputes through controlled violence, gravitated toward the Thundrekk tradition. They trained together, developed combat techniques scaled to their enormous bodies, and served as the island's de facto military when threats arose — primarily from the island's predatory fauna (echo-saturated megapredators that could threaten even a Giant) and from the rare inter-tribal disputes that escalated beyond verbal resolution.
Thundrekk training was brutal by Giant standards and would be lethal by human standards. Initiates underwent a year-long series of trials: climbing Urdrath's active slopes, swimming the Screamwater's edge, wrestling the island's largest predators (a practice that, combined with Eldra-communication, produced a strange, respectful combat — the predator was not killed if it submitted, and the initiate was not rescued if they failed). A Giant who completed the trials was marked with ritual scarring — volcanic glass drawn across the chest in patterns that recorded their tribal origin, their mentor's lineage, and the trials they had completed.
Thundrekk giants had no unified appearance but tended to be the most physically imposing members of whatever tribe they came from. They wore the heaviest practical garments — mammoth-hide armor, volcanic-glass weapons (swords and axes scaled to their size that would serve as battering rams in human hands), and shields carved from single pieces of Thornwood hardwood, reinforced with Korvaan metalwork.
The Thundrekk tradition was the closest thing the Giants had to a cross-tribal institution. A Thundrekk's loyalty was to the tradition first and their birth-tribe second — a principle that kept the martial class from becoming any single tribe's weapon. In practice, this meant that inter-tribal disputes were arbitrated by Thundrekk councils where warriors from both disputing tribes sat together and judged, a system that worked precisely because the arbitrators' primary loyalty was to the code rather than to either party.
9. The Ysvari — "The Bone-Keepers"
The death-workers. A small, ancient tribe concentrated in a single, sacred location: the Bonewood, a grove of petrified Thornwood trees on the island's western coast where, for reasons no druid had ever explained, the echo-field behaved differently. In the rest of the island, a dying Giant's echo-lattice dissolved into the surrounding environment — absorbed by the Weft, by nearby trees, by the soil, by the air. In the Bonewood, it stayed. The petrified trunks held echo-imprints of every Giant who had ever died there, layered like sediment, creating a repository of fragmentary consciousness stretching back to the earliest recorded history.
The Ysvari maintained the Bonewood and served as the island's funeral priests. When a Giant died — anywhere on the island — the Ysvari were summoned to perform the Rite of Carrying: a ritual in which the Ysvari druid Eldra-melded with the dying person, absorbed the last fragments of their consciousness, and then carried those fragments (sometimes over weeks of travel) to the Bonewood, where they were released into the petrified trunks. The process was agonizing for the druid. Each Carrying left a residue — the dead person's strongest emotions, their most vivid memories, their deepest fears — that the Ysvari druid carried for the rest of their own life. Elderly Ysvari were visibly burdened: slow-moving, distant-eyed, their speech interspersed with words and phrases from the dead. They were respected absolutely and avoided instinctively. To be a Ysvari was to be necessary and lonely.
Ysvari giants were gaunt, with deep-set eyes and prematurely grey hair regardless of age. Their skin had a faintly translucent quality — other Giants said you could see "the Carried" moving beneath it, though this was probably metaphorical. They wore undyed linen and bone ornament, and they spoke rarely, conserving their energy for the Carrying.
10. The Feldrunne — "Seed-Callers"
Farmers. The Feldrunne managed the island's agriculture — which, on Eldraholm, was less agriculture and more negotiation. In an echo-saturated environment, plants were not passive. They responded to the druids' intentions, growing toward or away from echo-projected stimuli, producing more or fewer fruit depending on the emotional state of the cultivators, and — in the case of the oldest, most echo-dense crop lineages — exhibiting behaviors that blurred the line between plant and animal. The Feldrunne did not plow, plant, and harvest. They communed, encouraged, and asked.
A Feldrunne farm was not a cleared field. It was a managed section of Thornwood undergrowth where edible species were echo-encouraged to proliferate: tuber networks that expanded when a Feldrunne druid knelt and pressed their hands into the soil; fruit-bearing vines that ripened faster when sung to (a practice shared with the Eshkári); grain-analogues that grew in volcanic ash and tasted of smoke and iron. The Feldrunne's greatest achievement was the deep garden — a network of echo-linked root systems that could be "played" like an instrument, directing nutrients and water to specific plants across acres of territory. A master Feldrunne could feed a hundred Giants from a garden that, to a human observer, would look like untouched wilderness.
Feldrunne giants were earth-toned — brown skin, green-flecked brown eyes, thick fingers perpetually dirt-stained. They were medium-height (13 feet) and strongly built, with a patience that other tribes found either admirable or maddening. They wore plant-fiber garments and smelled, always, of rich soil.
11. The Brúnaveld — "The Mammoth-Kin"
The herders. While the Hrundvaal were associated with the high-plateau mammoths, the Brúnaveld were defined by them. Their entire culture — settlement patterns, migration routes, spiritual practice, social structure — revolved around the care and companionship of the white mammoths. A Brúnaveld Giant was bonded to a specific mammoth from childhood, chosen through a matching ritual in which a juvenile mammoth and a juvenile Giant were placed together in an open meadow and observed. If the mammoth approached the child voluntarily — drawn by an echo-resonance between their individual fields — the bond was declared. If not, another mammoth was tried. Some children were never matched. These unbonded Brúnaveld were not stigmatized but were considered to have different destinies; many became Solveig healers or Eshkári singers.
The bonded pair lived together for the rest of the mammoth's life (mammoths lived roughly 120 years — shorter than the Giants, meaning most Brúnaveld experienced the death of their bondmate and the shattering grief that followed). The Eldra-melding between a Brúnaveld and their mammoth was deeper and more constant than any other Giant-animal relationship: not a conversation but a co-existence, two echo-fields overlapping until the boundary between them blurred. A bonded Brúnaveld felt their mammoth's hunger, pain, and contentment as their own. The mammoth felt the Giant's emotions in return. Separation for more than a few days produced a physical ache in both parties — the Eldra-fields stretching like overstretched muscle, cramping and weakening.
Brúnaveld giants had the most varied appearance of any tribe (their gene pool mixed freely with the Hrundvaal and Feldrunne, whose territories overlapped), but were recognizable by their garments: mammoth-wool felt, always white or cream, and by the smell — a warm, animal musk that no amount of bathing could fully remove, because the Brúnaveld did not bathe to remove it. It was the smell of their bondmate. It was who they were.
12. The Aldruun — "The First-Named"
The elders. Not a tribe in the conventional sense but a designation: the Aldruun were the Giants who had lived long enough to become something more than individual people. A Giant who reached approximately 180 years of age — rare, perhaps one in twenty — underwent a gradual change that the other tribes called the Deepening. Their echo-density, already high, continued to concentrate rather than diminishing with age (as happened in most Giants past their prime). Their sensitivity expanded. Their personality softened — not into senility but into something vaster, less individual, more porous. An Aldruun elder sitting in the Thornwood felt the forest not as an environment but as an extension of themselves. An Aldruun elder touching the ground felt the magma chamber miles below the way a young Giant felt a warm stone in their hand.
The Aldruun did not govern. They did not command. They simply were, and their presence influenced the communities around them the way a large stone influences a stream — redirecting flow without effort. When disputes arose that Thundrekk arbitration couldn't resolve, the disputing parties went to the nearest Aldruun and sat with them. Often, the mere experience of being in an Aldruun's echo-field was enough to resolve the dispute: the elder's vast, calm resonance dampened the emotional turbulence of the conflict, allowing the parties to see each other clearly for the first time.
At the time of the evacuation, there were nine living Aldruun. All nine chose to stay on the island. They were too deeply embedded in Eldraholm's echo-field to survive the Screamwater crossing — their expanded sensitivity would have been destroyed by the barrier's chaotic emissions. They knew this. They chose to die with the island that had become, in a very real sense, their body.

III. THE CONSOLIDATION
How Twelve Became Three
The twelve tribes coexisted for millennia with minimal conflict. Disputes over territory, resources, or mating were resolved through Thundrekk arbitration, Eshkári mediation (the singers served as neutral historians who could recall the exact terms of every agreement in living memory), or simple Aldruun presence. Wars, in the human sense, did not occur. The population was too small, the island too interconnected, and the Eldra-field too binding — a Giant who harmed another Giant felt the victim's pain through the ambient echo-field, making sustained violence psychologically unbearable.
The consolidation was not political. It was ecological.
As Urdrath intensified — the process accelerating sharply about three hundred years before the story — the Ashlands expanded, the Thornwood retreated, and the twelve tribes were compressed into shrinking territory. The Gahlmarr lost their caverns. The Eshkári lost their transitional zone. The Feldrunne lost their deepest gardens. Tribe after tribe was displaced, forced to share territory with neighbors they had previously maintained comfortable distances from.
The consolidation happened naturally, driven by geography:
The Wisemen — A coalition of the Velthari, Eshkári, Ysvari, and Aldruun (the spiritual, cultural, and death-working traditions). They consolidated around the remaining Thornwood groves and the Bonewood, preserving the island's spiritual infrastructure. The Velthari, as the largest and most central tribe, became the coalition's dominant voice, but all four traditions were represented in council.
The Warriors — A coalition of the Thundrekk, Gahlmarr, and Dyrholmar (the martial, underground, and coastal traditions). Driven together by shared displacement — the Gahlmarr fleeing the collapsing caverns, the Dyrholmar retreating from rising sea temperatures that disrupted their coastal ecology — they organized around the Thundrekk's cross-tribal structure, creating a unified defensive and logistical network. The Warriors were the faction that first argued for evacuation and that organized the fleet's construction.
The Builders — A coalition of the Korvaan, Feldrunne, Brúnaveld, Hrundvaal, and Solveig (the crafters, farmers, herders, weather-workers, and healers). The most practically diverse coalition, united by the shared imperative of keeping the remaining population alive as territory shrank. The Korvaan, with their construction expertise, became the coalition's public face, but the Feldrunne's ability to grow food in shrinking space and the Solveig's healing were equally critical.
The three-faction system was not a government. It was a survival structure — a way of organizing the island's remaining seven to eight thousand Giants (the population had fallen from a peak of thirty-five thousand over three centuries of volcanic displacement, starvation, and despair) into functional groups that could coordinate the increasingly desperate effort to keep the species alive.

IV. THE CROSSING
The Decision
The evacuation was not unanimous. The Wisemen faction opposed it — the Velthari argued that leaving the Thornwood was spiritual suicide, and the Ysvari insisted that the Bonewood could not be abandoned without losing eight thousand years of accumulated consciousness. The Aldruun, consulted individually, agreed: departure meant the death of everything that made them Giants rather than merely large animals.
The Warriors and Builders overruled them — not through force (unthinkable) but through a ritual called the Gathering of Voices, the closest thing Giant culture had to a democratic assembly. Every Giant on the island — every single one capable of standing — gathered in a clearing at the Thornwood's edge, and each spoke or sang or stood in silence according to their position. The Gathering lasted eleven days. At its end, the decision was clear: more voices called for departure than for death.
The Aldruun accepted the result. They also announced they would not leave.
The Fleet
The Korvaan built the ships. Twelve vessels — the largest constructed objects in Giant history, each requiring the felling of Thornwood trees for the first time in the species' existence. The felling was performed as a funeral: each tree was Eldra-melded with by Velthari druids before the axe fell, its accumulated echo-consciousness carried to the Bonewood by Ysvari priests. The shipwrights wept as they worked. The trees, the druids reported, did not resist. They understood.
Each ship was designed to carry approximately five hundred Giants plus livestock, supplies, and seed-stock. The total evacuation capacity: six thousand. At the time of departure, the island's population was approximately seven thousand. One thousand would stay — the Aldruun, their closest attendants, those too frail to survive the crossing, and a small contingent of Velthari who refused to leave the Thornwood on principle.
The Brúnaveld loaded their bonded mammoths onto the ships — an engineering nightmare, as each adult mammoth weighed as much as twenty Giants. The Feldrunne carried seed-pouches and root-cuttings. The Eshkári memorized the complete song-archive of the civilization, distributing it across multiple singers on different ships so that no single loss could destroy the whole.
The Screamwater
The fleet entered the Eldra-Veil on a windless morning. The druids had prepared for weeks — meditating, building their echo-reserves, rehearsing techniques for projecting calm across the fleet's collective consciousness. It was not enough.
The Screamwater hit them like a wall of noise. Giants collapsed on deck, hands over ears, screaming. The mammoths panicked, thrashing in their holds, splintering timbers. The Dyrholmar pilots — the only Giants with any experience near the barrier — fought to maintain course, but their navigational echo-sense was overwhelmed by the chaotic emissions. Ships drifted apart in the first hour. By the end of the first day, the fleet had scattered.
The barrier zone extended roughly fifty miles. At the speed the Giants' ships could manage — slow, wallowing, never designed for open ocean — the crossing took three days. Three days of unrelenting echo-assault. Giants went mad. Giants died — not from physical injury but from echo-overload, their nervous systems shutting down under stimuli their biology was never built to process. Mammoths died. Ships foundered as crews became too incapacitated to manage sails and rudders.
When the survivors emerged from the barrier's far edge, the silence was worse than the screaming had been. The open ocean's echo-field was empty — not hostile, not painful, but absent, a void where the warmth had been. For a species that had never experienced echo-deprivation, the effect was devastating. The surviving druids called it the Great Quiet. Many Giants simply stopped functioning — sitting motionless on deck, staring at nothing, breathing but not living. The Solveig healers worked without rest, cycling between catatonic patients, trying to restart echo-fields that had been shattered by the barrier and were now starving in the void.
The Losses
Of the twelve ships that entered the Screamwater, four emerged from the barrier zone intact enough to continue sailing. Of those four, the ocean took three more over the following weeks — storms, hull failure, crew attrition. The Giants were not sailors. Their ships were built for a crossing, not a voyage. They had no charts, no knowledge of ocean currents, no concept of navigation beyond the Dyrholmar's echo-sense, which was useless in the echo-dead open water.
One ship reached the coast of Mundus mostly intact. It ran aground on a reef off the Frozen South's coast. The hull broke apart. The survivors who could swim or wade made it to shore.
The other three survivors arrived separately — individual Giants who had been washed overboard from failing ships, who clung to wreckage, who drifted for days or weeks before washing up on distant shores. They arrived alone. They arrived with nothing.
The Four Who Arrived
1. In the Frozen South — Two survivors.
Thyra of the Brúnaveld — A mammoth-herder, female, approximately 90 years old (middle-aged by Giant standards). She arrived from the ship that broke on the reef, wading ashore with the body of her bondmate mammoth dragging behind her in the surf — the mammoth had drowned in the wreck, and Thyra had tied its corpse to her body rather than let it sink. She buried the mammoth on the beach in Clan Raudbjorn territory and then sat beside the grave for three days without moving. The Raudbjorn scouts who found her thought she was dead. She was not dead. She was performing the Carrying — absorbing her bondmate's echo-remnants into herself without a Ysvari priest to help, a process that left her permanently changed. She carries the mammoth's consciousness inside her like a second heartbeat.
Thyra is not a leader. She is a herder without a herd, a bonded partner without a bond, a member of a civilization she may never see again. She is also the only surviving Giant in the Frozen South who has any living animal with her: a single juvenile mammoth, barely weaned, that survived the wreck by climbing onto floating debris. The calf has imprinted on Thyra as a surrogate mother. It is, as far as she knows, the last of its kind on this side of the ocean.
Grevaan of the Gahlmarr — A cave-dweller, male, approximately 65 (young adult). He arrived from the same wreck but washed up on a different stretch of coastline, several miles from Thyra. Grevaan is a tunnel-engineer and stone-reader whose entire life was spent underground. The open sky unnerves him. The cold doesn't bother him — the Gahlmarr were adapted to the temperature-stable environment of deep caves, and the Frozen South's chill feels familiar in a way that the open air does not — but the space does. He is perpetually looking for walls. He sleeps in crevices, in shallow caves, under overhangs. The Frozen South's fjords and cliff faces are the closest thing to home he has found.
Grevaan's echo-sensitivity is geological. He can feel the Frozen South's bedrock the way he felt Urdrath's tunnels — and what he feels alarms him. The continent's echo-field is shockingly thin. Stone that should hum is silent. Soil that should pulse is dead. He has pressed his palms against the Frozen South's granite and felt nothing, and the absence frightened him worse than the Screamwater did.
2. In the Heartlands — One survivor.
Sëdhra of the Velthari — A root-listener, female, approximately 140 (elder, but not yet Aldruun). She washed ashore alone, clinging to a section of hull timber that still carried faint echoes of the Thornwood tree it had been carved from. She spent the first days on the mainland pressing her ear to the ground, searching desperately for the Weft — the underground root-network that had been the foundation of her entire sensory world. It was not there. This continent had trees, but they were silent — their root systems unconnected, their echo-fields negligible, their trunks as mute as fence posts. For Sëdhra, it was like going deaf.
She landed in the southern Heartlands where the Silver Mountains meet the sea, near the Sandsword holding. Venania Sarko was the first human she encountered. To Sëdhra, the encounter was as shocking as it was to Venania: Sëdhra had never seen a creature that was simultaneously echo-bearing (all humans carry faint echoes) and echo-deaf (no human in the Heartlands has the sensitivity to feel anything). To her senses, humans were like candles that had been lit and immediately snuffed — the wick was there, the wax was there, but the flame was out. She found this profoundly sad.
Sëdhra is the oldest and most knowledgeable of the four survivors. She carries the deepest understanding of the Eldra, the most extensive oral history, and the greatest spiritual authority. She is also the most psychologically damaged by the crossing — her expanded Velthari sensitivity made the Screamwater crossing nearly fatal, and the Great Quiet afterward left scars in her echo-field that have not healed. She hears things that are not there — fragments of the Thornwood's Weft, echoing in her damaged perception like phantom pain in a severed limb. She is not mad. But she is haunted by a forest that exists only in her memory.
Three animals survived with Sëdhra: a pair of Ashland fire-salamanders (small, heat-adapted amphibians whose skin glows faintly with bioluminescent echo-patterns) and a juvenile Thornwood canopy-hawk (a raptor with a six-foot wingspan and feathers that shift color with the echo-field's fluctuations — currently shifting constantly, confused by the mainland's alien frequencies). These creatures are radically unlike anything in the mainland bestiary. The fire-salamanders, in particular, are echo-dense enough to produce visible effects on their environment: plants near them grow faster, insects are drawn to their warmth, and the soil they sleep on becomes richer. Two small animals. The beginning of an ecological revolution.
3. On the Red Coast — One survivor.
Drothek of the Korvaan — A forge-blood, male, approximately 50 (young). The youngest and most physically resilient of the four survivors, Drothek washed up on the Red Coast's copper-rich shoreline after spending what he estimates was two weeks adrift on open water. He survived by entering a self-induced state the Korvaan call forge-sleep — a deep metabolic slowdown that the Ashlands-edge dwellers developed to survive volcanic gas events, during which the body's systems reduce to minimum function and the echo-field contracts into a tight, protective shell around the core organs. He awoke on a beach of red sand, dehydrated to the point of organ failure, and dragged himself to a freshwater spring by following the faint echo-signature of underground water — the only Eldra he could feel in the barren coastal landscape.
Drothek is the most practically skilled of the four. He can work stone and metal with an expertise that no human smith can match, feel structural weaknesses in buildings and bridges by touching them, and sense mineral deposits underground. He is also the most psychologically intact — the Korvaan temperament is pragmatic, forward-looking, and resistant to despair. Where Sëdhra mourns the lost Thornwood and Thyra carries her dead mammoth's ghost, Drothek has already begun working. Within days of his arrival, he found a cave, shaped it into a shelter using his bare hands and the local stone's echo-lattice (thin as it was, it was enough for a Korvaan), and began gathering materials. He does not understand this world. He does not know where the others are, or if anyone else survived. But he is alive, and there is stone to shape, and a Korvaan does not sit idle while there is stone to shape.
No animals survived with Drothek. He is entirely alone.

V. THE ECHO-BLEED
What the Breach Is Doing
The rupture in the Eldra-Veil is not a hole. It is a collapse. The barrier's integrity depended on total containment — a closed system of self-reinforcing echo-density. The fleet's passage punched through that system in a line roughly three miles wide (the dispersal pattern of the twelve ships as they entered the Screamwater). Through that line, the island's concentrated Eldra is bleeding into the open ocean.
The process is slow by human timescales — noticeable only over decades — but catastrophically fast by ecological ones. The island's echo-field, which took millennia to reach its current saturation, is draining at a rate that will reduce it to mainland levels within approximately two centuries. For the Giants who remained — and for the Thornwood, the Bonewood, the mammoth herds, the entire echo-adapted biome — this is a death sentence.
On the mainland side, the effect is the opposite: a gradual, almost imperceptible increase in ambient echo-density, concentrated along the ocean currents that carry the bleed northward toward Mundus. The increase is far too slight for anyone to notice yet — it will be years, possibly decades, before the effects become measurable. But the four surviving Giants, each functioning as a localized echo-node, are producing immediate effects in their vicinity:
Around Thyra and Grevaan (Frozen South): The mammoth calf's echo-field, combined with Thyra's and Grevaan's, is producing a zone of enhanced echo-density roughly a mile in radius around their respective locations. Within this zone, the Frozen South's sparse vegetation is growing noticeably faster. Lichen colonizes bare rock in weeks rather than years. The local fauna — arctic foxes, seals, sea-birds — are behaving with unusual boldness and coordination. The Raudbjorn clanspeople who live nearest to Thyra's landing site have begun reporting strange dreams — vivid, emotionally intense, featuring landscapes they've never seen (Thornwood imagery bleeding through the ambient echo-field). They don't know what's causing it. They are unsettled.
Around Sëdhra (Heartlands): The Velthari elder's expanded echo-field, damaged as it is, is still immensely powerful by mainland standards. In the vicinity of her landing site, the Silver Mountain foothills are experiencing what a Feldrunne farmer would recognize as a localized awakening — trees leafing out weeks early, wildflowers blooming in profusion, insects appearing in unusual density. The fire-salamanders are amplifying the effect, their bioluminescent echo-patterns functioning as miniature resonance chambers that strengthen the ambient field beyond what Sëdhra alone could produce. The canopy-hawk, circling overhead, is extending the effect vertically — its echo-dense feathers scattering Eldra-stimuli into the upper atmosphere like a living broadcast antenna.
Venania Sarko, the hunter's daughter, lives at the epicenter of this effect. She doesn't understand what she's feeling. She only knows that the world has become louder since the enormous woman walked out of the sea.
Around Drothek (Red Coast): The Korvaan's contracted, forge-trained echo-field is producing subtler effects — his Eldra-projection is tight and focused rather than broad, influencing the stone and mineral environment more than the biological one. The cave he shaped has become a minor echo-node: the walls hum at a frequency that human ears can't hear but human bodies can feel. Copper ore in the surrounding rock is developing a faint luminescence — Korvaan echo-work interacting with the metal's natural resonance. If any Red Coast miner discovers this cave, they will find copper that glows, and they will not know what to make of it.

VI. GIANT RELIGION — THE LIVING WORLD
The Giants did not worship gods. They did not have gods. The concept — a conscious being above the world, separate from it, issuing commands — was incomprehensible to a species that lived inside the Eldra-field the way fish live inside water. You do not worship water. You breathe it.
What the Giants had was closer to animism, but animism is too weak a word. The mainland's animistic traditions — the Frozen South's spirit-beliefs, the Xarian river-god cults — attribute consciousness to natural features: this river has a spirit, this mountain has a will. The Giants didn't attribute consciousness to nature. They experienced it. The Thornwood was not like a conscious being. It was a conscious being — fragmented, distributed, non-verbal, operating on timescales that made Giant lives look like heartbeats, but present in a way that no amount of metaphor could capture. Urdrath was not like an angry father. Urdrath was — something. Not angry. Not fatherly. But aware, in its geological way, of the creatures living on its slopes, and indifferent to them the way an ocean is indifferent to the fish.
The Giants' spiritual practice was not prayer. It was attention. The highest spiritual act in Giant culture was to sit quietly in a place and listen — not with the ears but with the echo-field, opening your sensitivity as wide as it could go and simply receiving whatever the landscape chose to send. The Hrundvaal did this with the sky. The Dyrholmar did this with the ocean. The Velthari did this with the Weft. The Gahlmarr did this with deep stone. Each tribe had its own version, but the core practice was the same: be still, be open, be small. Let the world talk. It usually did.
The Giants' relationship to death was shaped by the Ysvari tradition: the Carrying, the Bonewood, the layered echo-consciousness of eight millennia of ancestors. They did not fear death. They feared silence — the possibility that the dead might be lost rather than Carried, that their echo-remnants might dissolve into nothing rather than joining the vast, slow consciousness of the Bonewood. The evacuation's greatest trauma was not the physical danger. It was the knowledge that the Bonewood was being left behind, that the entire ancestral memory of the species was trapped on a dying island, and that every Giant who died on the crossing would die unCarried — their consciousness scattering into the echo-void of the open ocean, lost forever.
The four survivors carry this weight. Thyra performed a makeshift Carrying for her mammoth — a bond-partner, not a Giant, but the principle was the same — and it damaged her. The other three have no Ysvari training. If one of them dies on the mainland, there is no one to Carry them. They will be the first Giants in eight thousand years to die alone.

VII. LANGUAGE
Giant speech is physically impossible for humans to replicate. Their vocal apparatus produces sounds in frequency ranges that human throats cannot reach — deep, subsonic vibrations that travel through stone and soil as much as through air. A Giant speaking at conversational volume produces a sound that nearby humans would feel in their bones and organs more than hear with their ears. The emotional content of Giant speech is transmitted partly through the echo-field: the speaker's emotional state modulates their echo-projection, adding a layer of meaning that exists below and alongside the words themselves. Two Giants speaking to each other are simultaneously talking and feeling — exchanging linguistic content and emotional resonance in a blended signal that human neurology cannot fully decode.
The Giants' name for their language is Eldrasong — a term that reflects the Eshkári influence on the broader culture. It is not literally song (most Giants are not Eshkári-trained singers), but it is closer to song than to speech: tonal, rhythmic, with meaning carried as much by pitch and tempo as by vocabulary. A single Giant word can mean different things depending on the emotional resonance the speaker projects alongside it.
A few terms that the four survivors will introduce to the mainland, filtered through human ears' imperfect reception:
Eldra — The warmth-before-fire. The echo-field. The divine residue. Untranslatable in its full meaning, but humans will approximate it.
Urdrath — The Burning Father. Will become the mainland's name for the Giants' homeland volcano.
Velthari, Korvaan, Dyrholmar, etc. — Tribal names, which will initially be heard by humans as personal names or titles.
Eldra-melding — The shared-consciousness ritual. Humans will struggle with this concept.
The Great Quiet — What followed the Screamwater. Will become the Giants' shorthand for the mainland's echo-depleted state.
Thundrekk — Will be adopted by some humans as a word meaning "warrior" or "champion," losing its original meaning of a cross-tribal martial tradition.

VIII. WHAT THEY LEFT BEHIND
On Eldraholm, the remaining population — roughly one thousand Giants — faces a double extinction. The volcano continues to expand, consuming the Thornwood from within. The Eldra-Veil breach continues to drain the echo-field, weakening every biological process that depends on it. The Thornwood trees are growing more slowly. The mammoth herds are producing fewer calves. The druids' abilities are diminishing — what once required a moment's concentration now requires an hour's effort, and some tasks that were routine a decade ago are now impossible.
The nine Aldruun feel the drain most acutely. Their expanded echo-fields, once vast enough to encompass entire groves, are contracting. They are becoming smaller, more individual, more alone — a process they experience as a slow death of the self, a shrinking of consciousness from something oceanic to something merely human-sized. One of the nine — the oldest, a Velthari elder approximately 210 years old — has already entered a state the others recognize as terminal: her echo-field has contracted to the boundary of her own skin, and she sits motionless in the Bonewood, unable to feel the ancestors she spent a century communing with, staring at petrified trunks that are now as silent to her as they would be to a human.
The Ysvari priests are performing Carryings more frequently as the weakened population sickens and dies. But the Bonewood itself is changing — the petrified trunks, deprived of their echo-field's reinforcement, are beginning to lose the imprints they've held for millennia. The oldest layers, eight thousand years deep, are fading first — the most ancient ancestors dissolving into silence. The Ysvari can feel it happening: a gradual thinning of the voices, like a choir losing its lowest notes one by one. They do not speak of it to the others. There is no comfort to offer.
The Korvaan remnant — the builders who stayed — are attempting to seal the breach. They have sailed to the Screamwater's edge and tried to use their forge-craft to rebuild the Veil's structure, projecting concentrated echo-fields into the gap the way they would fill a crack in a tunnel wall. It is not working. The Veil was an emergent phenomenon, not a constructed one — you cannot rebuild an emergent property by applying brute force. The Korvaan know this. They keep trying anyway. A Korvaan does not sit idle while there is stone to shape, even if the stone is falling.
If the four survivors on the mainland ever learn what their crossing has done to the people they left behind, the knowledge will be the heaviest thing they carry — heavier than grief, heavier than exile, heavier than the Great Quiet. They broke the world to save themselves. The world is dying because they lived.

MUNDUS AT 1308 AF — The Living Continent
A Regional Overview

THE SHAPE OF THE WORLD
Mundus is a single vast continent — the only major landmass its inhabitants have ever known (until this year). It stretches from the arid northern plateau and the island of Nionia in the northwest, down through temperate heartland and sunlit vineyard country, south through forests and ironwork valleys into the frozen fjords and wind-scoured steppe at the continent's ragged tail. The eastern coast fractures into islands — the Teeth — and the jutting peninsula of Xaria, separated from the mainland by dense jungle and a culture that might as well be another planet. The western seaboard drops in a long vertical spine, rocky and fjord-cut, from the Horns' salt-sprayed ports down to the Frozen South's ice-bitten capes.
The interior is dominated by the Heartlands' river systems — vast, fertile, and fought over for millennia. Mountain ranges divide the regions like vertebrae: the Silver Mountains separating the Heartlands from the southern coast, the Fyrhold range walling Rosland's mining country, the volcanic ridges of the Red Coast baking under permanent haze. Between these barriers, the land is green, old, and contested.
Travel time matters. A fast rider on good roads covers the distance from Vornhold (northern Heartlands) to Fairhaven (Rosland's capital) in roughly two weeks. A merchant caravan, loaded and cautious, takes a month. A pilgrim walking to Faithir from the Red Coast might spend three months on the road. The world is large enough that regional cultures developed in genuine isolation for centuries, and small enough that trade, war, and religion keep them tangled together.

NIONIA — The Marble Isle
The Feel
White. Everything is white. That is the first thing any visitor notices stepping off the boat at Vellium's harbor — the docks are white marble, the warehouses are white plaster over white stone, the street cobbles are pale granite worn smooth by centuries of foot traffic, and the light bouncing off all of it is blinding until your eyes adjust. Nionia is an island that has been quarried into beauty and quarried into submission in the same motion. The mountains of the interior — the Marchia Ferrus — are scarred with open-pit mines and marble cuts that look, from a distance, like wounds in pale flesh. The lowlands are terraced with olive groves and vineyards, but even these have a manicured, controlled quality — nature permitted to exist within boundaries that human hands have drawn.
The air smells of marble dust, salt spray, incense, and the particular acrid sweetness of Ashleaf smoke drifting from dockworkers' pipes. In the capital, you add to that the scent of rendered whale-oil (used in the street lamps that burn all night — Jous has decreed that darkness is a breeding ground for sin) and the faint, cloying tang of the cleansing incense that the Pure Way's priests burn in bronze censers on every major corner.
The People
Nionians are Mediterranean in coloring — olive-to-brown skin, dark hair, features that range from sharp-boned aristocratic to broad-faced dockworker. They dress in linen and light wool, layered in the formal toga-derivative that the patrician houses still affect (a shoulder-draped wrap called a pallion, pinned with a house brooch) or the simpler belted tunic of the working class. White is the prestige color — bleached linen, chalk-whitened leather, marble-dust-powdered hair for formal occasions. Under Jous's Pure Way, white has become mandatory for clergy and encouraged for everyone else. The streets of Vellium look like a city dressed for a funeral that never ends.
Before the civil war, Nionians were loud, argumentative, theatrical in their public life — the Senate's plaza debates were spectator sport, and the tavern culture was boisterous and profane. That energy hasn't died; it's been driven underground. The taverns still roar, but they roar more quietly, and conversations stop when a white cloak passes the door. Humor has become a weapon — Nionian jokes under the Pure Way are sharp, dark, coded, told in a dialect of irony that outsiders can't always parse. A Nionian will smile while insulting you so elegantly that you thank them for it.
Architecture
Columned, domed, and terraced. Nionian buildings are designed to impress from a distance and intimidate up close. Public structures — courts, temples, baths, markets — feature the colonnaded façade inherited from the republican era: rows of fluted marble columns supporting triangular pediments carved with historical scenes. The Great Dome of Vellium (the converted Senate chamber, now Jous's cathedral) is the largest enclosed space on the continent — a hemisphere of white marble and iron ribbing that catches the afternoon sun and glows like a second moon. Private homes are built around interior courtyards, with exterior walls that present blank, fortress-like faces to the street. The wealthy live inward; the poor live upward, in tenement blocks of four or five stories that lean over narrow alleys where the sunlight never reaches the cobblestones.
Food
Olive oil is the foundation. Everything is cooked in it, dressed with it, or preserved in it. Bread is dense, sour, and baked in communal ovens. Fish — grilled, salted, stewed, pickled — is the primary protein for everyone below the patrician class. The wealthy eat lamb, kid goat, and pork sausage spiced with imported Sangrean pepper and Red Coast cumin. Cheese is sheep's milk, crumbly and sharp. Wine is mixed with water (drinking it straight is considered barbaric — a distinction Nionians maintain with aggressive cultural pride). The signature dish of Vellium's streets is teglia — a shallow pan of layered flatbread, roasted vegetables, and crumbled cheese, baked in a public oven and eaten with the hands. Street vendors sell it in greased paper for a copper.
Music
Vocal. Nionians sing — in taverns, in the baths, in the streets, at work. The traditional form is the lamento, a solo vocal piece accompanied by a stringed instrument called a kitharon (a long-necked lute with a nasal, buzzing tone). Lamentos are formally about love or loss; informally, under the Pure Way, they have become vehicles for coded political commentary. The Pure Way has introduced its own musical form — the cantus, a choral hymn sung in unison by white-robed choirs, designed to be heard from blocks away, filling the city's acoustics with the sound of collective devotion. The contrast between the raw, individual lamento and the controlled, collective cantus is the sound of Nionia's cultural civil war.

THE HORNS — Salt, Sail, and Silver Tongue
The Feel
Wet. Gray. Beautiful in the way that a storm is beautiful — all drama and danger and the smell of brine. The Horns are a peninsula of three major port cities (Westhorn, Brinehold, Nightspike) and one forest gate city (Skogrim), connected to the mainland by a dense woodland corridor and to each other by the most treacherous coastal waters on the continent. The landscape is cliffs, coves, tidal flats, and rocky headlands battered by wind that never seems to stop. Everything is damp. Wood rots. Iron rusts. Rope frays. The Horns' architecture, cuisine, and temperament are all shaped by the fundamental reality that the sea is trying to eat them and they have to rebuild constantly.
The light is extraordinary. The sun, when it breaks through the perpetual cloud cover, hits the wet stone and the churning water and produces colors that painters from the mainland travel weeks to capture — silvers, slate blues, golds that last for twenty minutes and then vanish. Horns artists are obsessed with light because light is the thing they have least of.
The People
Horns folk are stocky, wind-burned, pragmatic, and ferociously competitive. The three port cities have been rivals for centuries, and the rivalry permeates everything — which port's beer is better, whose shipwrights are faster, whose pilots are more skilled. A Westhorn man and a Brinehold woman at the same tavern will argue about the proper way to salt cod with the intensity that Heartlanders reserve for dynastic succession. The competition is real but also performative — underneath the rivalry, Horns folk recognize each other as their kind in a way that excludes mainlanders. They call non-Horns people drylanders and consider them soft.
Skin tones range from the ruddy pinkish-brown of the northern fishing villages to the darker olive-brown of Nightspike's mixed maritime population (centuries of trade with the Red Coast and the Teeth have produced a city with the continent's most diverse gene pool). Hair is typically dark, worn short or braided tight against the wind. Clothing is practical: oiled canvas jackets, leather boots treated with whale-fat to repel water, wool sweaters knitted in patterns that identify the wearer's home port (a tradition so old that the patterns have legal standing — a Brinehold pattern worn in Westhorn is considered a minor provocation). Sailors wear knotted cord jewelry — bracelets and necklaces of complex sailor's knots that indicate rank, experience, and marital status. A master pilot's knot-chain can weigh half a pound.
Architecture
Low, heavy, and built to endure. Horns buildings are stone-and-timber, with thick walls, small windows, and steep slate roofs designed to shed the constant rain. In the port cities, the waterfront districts are forests of masts, rigging, and crane-arms, with warehouses built directly into the cliff faces — their fronts opening onto the docks, their backs carved into the rock. The most distinctive feature of Horns architecture is the lantern tower — every significant building has one, a narrow turret with a glass-and-iron lamp at the top, originally designed as navigation aids for ships approaching in fog. Over centuries, the towers became status symbols: the wealthier the house, the taller and more ornate the tower. Westhorn's harbor, seen from the sea at night, is a constellation of amber lights climbing the cliff face.
Food
Seafood, obviously. But prepared with an intensity and variety that surprises mainlanders who expect boiled fish and hard bread. Brinehold's signature is saltboil — a communal pot of seawater, root vegetables, kelp, and whatever the day's catch provided, simmered over driftwood fires on the docks and served in wooden bowls to anyone who contributed an ingredient. Westhorn's cuisine is richer, influenced by trade with the mainland: smoked eel with horseradish cream, oysters roasted in their shells with garlic butter, salt-cod cakes fried in whale oil. Nightspike, with its Red Coast and Teeth trade connections, serves the spiciest food on the peninsula: grilled fish rubbed with cumin, coriander, and dried chili, wrapped in flatbread, eaten standing up at dockside stalls. Beer is the universal drink — dark, heavy, brewed with kelp-filtered seawater that gives it a minerally bite that mainlanders either love or spit out. Wine is imported, expensive, and consumed ostentatiously by anyone trying to signal that they're too refined for beer.
Music
Horns music is built on the chanty — a call-and-response work song originally designed to coordinate labor on ship decks and in the dockyards. Chanties have evolved over centuries from functional commands into a sophisticated musical tradition: multi-part harmonies, complex rhythmic patterns, and lyrics that range from obscene humor to genuine poetry. The best chanty-singers are celebrities in the port cities, performing in taverns to standing-room crowds. Instruments: the squeeze-box (a small accordion that fits in a sailor's sea-chest), the bone-whistle (carved from whale rib, producing a piercing, mournful tone that carries over wind), and drums made from barrel-heads and ship timbers. The Horns' most famous musical event is the Storm Sing — a competitive performance held during the worst winter gales, when the ports close and the population retreats indoors. Taverns compete to host the best singers, and the bragging rights last until the next storm season.

SANGREA — Sun, Blood, and Vine
The Feel
Gold. Where Nionia is white, Sangrea is gold — the gold of afternoon sun on sandstone, of ripe grapes on the vine, of Ashleaf smoke curling through warm air, of the ornate gilding that covers every surface the wealthy can reach. Sangrea occupies the continent's sun-drenched midsection: rolling hills planted with vineyards, river valleys lush with citrus and olive, and a southern border that dissolves into the tropical jungle fringe where the continent's flora shifts from Mediterranean to something wilder, wetter, and less tamed. The air is warm ten months of the year and hot for the other two. Everything ripens early and spoils fast. The culture has the same quality — passionate, short-fused, and intolerant of boredom.
The landscape is beautiful and brutally worked. The vineyards that produce Sangrea's famous wines are maintained by peasant labor under conditions that range from paternalistic to feudal. The sunstone quarries — the source of the region's mineral wealth and its bloodiest wars — scar the hills between Solé and Terrarossa territory like open sores. The rivers, dammed and diverted for irrigation, have been fought over so many times that every bridge has a plaque commemorating some battle or betrayal. Sangrea is a land that smiles while showing its teeth.
The People
Sangreans are warm-skinned, dark-haired, and expressive to a degree that Roslandic stoics find exhausting and Heartlanders find suspicious. They talk with their hands. They sing while they work. They mourn with their entire bodies — Sangrean funerals are theatrical productions, with hired mourners, processional bands, and the deceased displayed in open caskets decorated with flowers and gilded trinkets. They celebrate the same way: the Festival of the Red Grape in Castesol is a seven-day explosion of music, food, wine, bullfighting, acrobatics, and public drunkenness that draws visitors from across the continent.
Clothing is color. The peasant class wears undyed linen and leather, but anyone with a copper to spare adds color: sashes dyed with grape-skin purple, embroidered vests in sunstone-orange and vineyard-green, silk scarves traded up from the Xarian border. The noble houses are peacocks — Lord-Patrons and their courts dress in layered brocade, slashed sleeves, gold thread, and jeweled brooches the size of fists. House Solé's signature is white-and-gold; House Terrarossa's is crimson-and-black. Wearing the wrong house's colors in the wrong town can get you stabbed.
Architecture
Sangrean architecture is courtyard-centered, arched, and obsessively decorated. The style descends from the pre-imperial city-states and has evolved over centuries into something that combines the functional (thick walls against the heat, interior gardens for shade, tiled floors that cool the feet) with the extravagant (mosaic façades, carved stone balconies, wrought-iron window grilles twisted into patterns of vines and animals). The signature element is the azulejo — glazed ceramic tiles in blue, gold, and white that cover the exterior walls of public buildings and wealthy homes. In Castesol, entire streets are lined with azulejo-covered facades that shimmer in the afternoon heat like walls of liquid gold.
Country estates — the haciendas — are fortified farms: manor houses surrounded by working vineyards, stables, granaries, and worker barracks, enclosed by walls that served defensive purposes during the Sunstone Wars and now serve mostly as symbols of the lord's territorial claim. A Sangrean hacienda's gate is always ornate, always guarded, and always open during daylight — the culture demands a show of hospitality even from houses that would happily poison the guest once inside.
Food
Sangrea eats well and brags about it. The cuisine is oil, wine, bread, and meat in combinations that range from rustic to absurdly elaborate. The peasant diet: bread rubbed with garlic and olive oil (pa amb tomàquet), bean stews thickened with pork fat, grilled sausages made from every part of the pig. The noble diet: roasted lamb stuffed with herbs and dried fruit, whole fish baked in salt crust, guinea fowl in saffron sauce, and desserts involving honey, almonds, and enough sugar to fund a minor war. Wine is not a beverage; it is an identity. Every hacienda produces its own vintage, and the quality hierarchy is discussed with the seriousness that other cultures reserve for theology. A Sangrean who cannot identify a wine's region, house, and approximate vintage by taste alone is considered uneducated regardless of their actual literacy.
The Selvaverde jungle border adds a wilder layer: tropical fruit (mango, papaya, passionfruit), cacao, chili peppers, and the smoked meats that House Botano's territory produces — venison and wild boar cured over aromatic jungle wood, pungent and addictive. Botano's messenger-parrot network runs partly on bribery: the parrots are trained to expect dried mango treats at every relay station.
Music
Sangrea's musical culture is the richest on the continent. The dominant form is the copla — a song tradition that ranges from the mournful (lost love, dead sons, ruined harvests) to the celebratory (weddings, victories, successful vintages) and is always accompanied by guitar-like instruments called vihuelas, hand-drums, and castanets made from sunstone-polished hardwood. The copla is not just music; it is the primary form of cultural transmission. History, gossip, political commentary, and love declarations are all communicated through song. A talented copla singer — a cantaor — has social status comparable to a minor noble; a great one is effectively untouchable, protected by popular adoration from the political consequences of the truths they sing.
The second major tradition is the campanero culture — the bellringers. Every Sangrean town has a bell tower, and the bells serve practical functions (time-keeping, alarm, market-opening) and cultural ones (wedding announcements, funeral tolls, harvest celebrations). The campaneros form a guild with its own hierarchy, training system, and fiercely guarded bell-language — a system of rhythmic patterns that can transmit complex messages across miles of countryside. During the Sunstone Wars, the Riverbell Alarm system coordinated troop movements across distances that horse messengers couldn't cover. The campaneros are technically neutral in the Solé-Terrarossa rivalry. In practice, every bellringer knows which house pays their guild dues.

THE HEARTLANDS — Silver, River, and Old Stone
The Feel
Expansive. That is the first word. The Heartlands are big — rolling plains of wheat and barley stretching to horizons that seem to pull away from you as you ride, interrupted by river valleys so fertile that the banks are green even in winter, and punctuated by the ancient stone cities that sit at every major confluence like fat spiders in the center of their webs. The Silver Mountains wall the southern edge, snow-capped and blue in the distance. The northern border bleeds into the scrubby, drier grassland that transitions toward the Horns corridor. The light is different here than anywhere else on the continent — wide, clear, and somehow deep, as if the sky has more layers than it does on the coast. Heartlanders talk about their sky the way Sangreans talk about their wine.
The rivers are the Heartlands' arteries: the Argen (the great central river, navigable for most of its length, the economic foundation of House Argenhold's wealth), the Vorn (northern tributary, running through Silverblood territory), the Silvrenne (mountain-fed, cold, cutting through Silverring's mining country), and dozens of smaller waterways that connect the plains towns to the river network. Everything moves by barge. The barges are flat-bottomed, shallow-drafted, poled and sail-rigged, painted in house colors and stacked with grain, ore, wool, and gossip. The Bargemen's Guild is one of the most powerful organizations in the region — they carry cargo, but they also carry information, and a bargeman who's been up and down the Argen three times in a season knows more about the duchy's politics than most of the dukes.
The environment shifts as you move: warmer and greener near the Sangrean border, where the cuisine picks up tropical influences and the accent softens; colder and starker as you head south toward the Silver Mountains, where the wind comes off the peaks with a bite that Roslandic visitors find familiar. The central plains — the Silver Flats — are treeless grassland, golden in summer, frost-white in winter, and the most fiercely contested farmland on the continent. Whoever controls the Flats feeds the Heartlands. Whoever feeds the Heartlands holds the Argenlord vote.
The People
Heartlanders are varied — the region is too large and too old for any single ethnic profile. Northern Heartlanders tend toward lighter complexions, sandy or brown hair, and the angular bone structure that suggests pre-imperial Aethelian ancestry. Southern Heartlanders are darker, stockier, and show the mixed heritage of centuries of contact with Sangrea and the mountain tribes. What unites them is temperament: Heartlanders are formal, careful, and obsessed with precedent. They speak slowly and mean every word. A Heartlander's promise is either iron or nothing — the culture has no tolerance for casual oaths.
Clothing reflects status with surgical precision. The ducal houses wear silver — not just as ornament but as structural element: silver thread woven into wool and linen, silver clasps and buttons, silver belt-buckles engraved with house sigils. The wealthier the house, the more silver you see. A Silverblood lord at court glitters like a fish; a minor house retainer might manage a single silver pin on their cloak. The working class wears undyed wool in winter and linen in summer, with leather boots and wide-brimmed hats to keep off the plains sun. The one universal garment across all classes is the surcoat — a sleeveless, open-fronted overgarment that displays the wearer's house colors or guild insignia. In the Heartlands, you are always wearing your allegiance.
Architecture
River architecture. The Heartlands' cities are built at confluences, on riverbanks, around bridges — and the buildings reflect this: stone foundations rising from the waterline, wooden upper stories cantilevered over the current, and bridges that are as much market-street as crossing-point. The signature structure is the riverhall — a long, narrow building oriented perpendicular to the river, with a dock at one end and a street entrance at the other, serving as both warehouse and meeting hall. Riverhalls are the Heartlands' civic centers: disputes are arbitrated there, elections are held there, feasts are hosted there. The Argenhold Riverhall — the ducal seat — is the largest on the continent, with a vaulted stone ceiling and a dock large enough to berth six barges abreast.
The older architecture — pre-imperial Aethelian ruins, imperial fortifications, early Age of Faith churches — is heavy, blocky, and built to last. The newer construction is lighter, more decorated, influenced by two centuries of peace and trade: arched windows, carved lintels, the occasional Sangrean-style azulejo panel imported by a lord trying to seem cosmopolitan. The contrast between old stone and new ornament gives Heartlander cities a layered quality — the bones of empire visible beneath the skin of post-imperial prosperity.
Food
The Heartlands eat their geography. The plains produce grain — wheat, barley, oats — and the bread culture is accordingly deep. Every town bakes differently: Vornhold's round, dark, sour loaves; Argenhold's flat river-cakes cooked on heated stones; Silvermont's braided white bread, sweet and rich with butter. Meat is beef and mutton from the plains herds, pork from the river-valley farms, and freshwater fish — pike, perch, and the enormous Argen catfish that river towns smoke over apple wood and trade downstream. Near the Sangrean border, the cuisine picks up heat and color: chili-rubbed beef, tomato-based stews, tropical fruit preserves. Near the Silver Mountains, it becomes sparser and heartier: root vegetables, dried sausage, hard cheese, and the fortified wine that miners drink to keep warm underground.
The Heartlands' signature culinary institution is the guild table — a communal meal hosted by the local guild chapter, open to any guild member and their family, featuring whatever the members contributed. The guild table is simultaneously a social event, a business meeting, and a political caucus. Deals are made over bread and salt. Alliances are forged over shared wine. Grudges are nursed over the quality of someone else's sausage.
Music
Formal. The Heartlands' musical culture reflects the region's obsession with order and precedent. The dominant form is the ballad — a narrative song, typically performed by a solo singer with a fiddle or a small harp, recounting historical events, dynastic achievements, or cautionary tales of betrayal and downfall. Ballads are long (some run over an hour), structured (verse-chorus-verse, with a bridge called "the turn" that introduces a moral or plot twist), and treated with the seriousness of legal documents. A ballad about a house's founding is considered a legitimate source of historical authority — courts have ruled on inheritance disputes based on which version of a ballad the local tradition preserved.
The counter-tradition is the riverman's strum — a loose, improvisational genre played on barges and in dockside taverns, featuring the bargeman's banjo (a three-stringed instrument with a deep, twangy tone) and lyrics that are considerably less respectful of aristocratic dignity than the formal ballads. Rivermen's songs are where the Heartlands' actual opinions live — the ones that don't get spoken in riverhalls or printed in the Ayanite gazette.

ROSLAND — Iron, Forest, and the Commons
The Feel
Dense. Green. Cold. Rosland is a land of forests — enormous, ancient, thick-canopied forests that start at the northern border and thicken as you go south, broken by river valleys, mining towns, and the clearings where Rosland's sturdy, practical cities sit like camps hacked out of the wilderness. The trees are conifers in the south and hardwoods in the north — oak, beech, elm — and they are big, the remnants of growth that predates the empire. The air smells of pine resin, wet earth, and woodsmoke. It is cold eight months of the year and merely cool for the other four. Rain is frequent, snow is annual, and the grey sky is so constant that Roslandic visitors to Sangrea reportedly weep at their first clear sunset.
The landscape is hilly, rocky, and mineral-rich. The Fyrhold mountains in the east are riddled with iron mines, copper deposits, and the coal seams that fuel Rosland's smithing industry. The mining towns — Forgetown, Karthold, Blackridge — are grim, functional places: pit-head machinery, slag heaps, workers' barracks, and the constant metallic tang of smelting operations. The contrast between the wild forests and the industrial mining valleys is Rosland's defining tension: beauty and utility, commons and extraction, the forest and the forge.
The People
Roslandic people are broad, pale, and built for endurance rather than speed. They have the stocky, heavy-boned physique of a population that has spent centuries doing physical labor in cold weather — mining, forestry, smithing, farming soil that fights back. Skin is fair, freckling easily in the rare sun; hair ranges from straw-blond to dark brown to the distinctive Roslandic red that crops up in certain mountain families and is considered (without evidence) a sign of stubbornness. Faces are wide, square-jawed, and difficult to read — Roslandic emotional expression is internal rather than external, and outsiders frequently mistake their reserve for hostility.
Clothing is functional, heavy, and layered. Wool is the base — thick, scratchy, undyed or dyed in dark greens, browns, and the characteristic Roslandic blue-grey that comes from woad processed with iron-rich water. Leather is everywhere: belts, boots, vests, gauntlets for smithwork and forestry. The wealthy add fur — bear, wolf, fox — and the occasional piece of Heartlands silver jewelry, worn with a self-consciousness that suggests they know it's imported and slightly resent the fact. The universal Roslandic garment is the kolpak — a heavy wool coat, knee-length, double-breasted, with a high collar and deep pockets, worn by everyone from High Barons to charcoal-burners. A good kolpak lasts a lifetime. Roslandic mothers begin knitting their children's kolpaks before the child is born.
Architecture
Timber and stone, heavy and functional. Roslandic buildings are designed to keep heat in and weather out: thick log walls chinked with moss and clay, steeply pitched roofs to shed snow, deep stone foundations to resist the freeze-thaw cycle. Windows are small (glass is expensive; oiled parchment serves for most households) and shuttered against winter storms. The public buildings — guild halls, court houses, the High Baron's seat at Fairhaven — are grander versions of the same principle: massive timber-frame structures with stone cladding, vaulted halls heated by fireplaces large enough to stand in, and the carved wooden decorative tradition that is Rosland's primary art form. Every beam, lintel, and doorframe in a respectable Roslandic building is carved with interlocking patterns of leaves, animals, and geometric knotwork — a tradition that pre-dates the empire and carries echoes of the old Aethelian republic's democratic symbols: the open hand, the balanced scale, the unbroken circle.
The most distinctive Roslandic structure is the muster-field — a large, open clearing at the edge of every significant town, with a raised stone platform at its center (the speaking stone), an ancient oak (the oath-tree), and enough flat ground to drill a militia company. The muster-field is where elections happen, where law is read, where military service is organized, and where the community gathers for festivals. It is the physical manifestation of Rosland's civic identity — public space, owned by no one, available to all.
Food
Hearty, sour, and smoked. Rosland's cuisine is shaped by long winters, limited growing seasons, and the need to preserve everything that can be preserved. Bread is dense, dark rye — the kind that stays edible for a week and can double as a weapon if thrown. Soups and stews are the foundation: cabbage soup, beet soup, mushroom soup, potato soup, and the famous Roslandic goulash — a thick, paprika-red stew of beef, root vegetables, and sour cream that is the national dish in everything but name. Smoked meats are a staple: sausages of every description (blood sausage, liver sausage, garlic sausage, the coal-black miners' rope that Fyrhold workers carry in their pockets), smoked fish from the western rivers, and dried elk from the deep forest hunting traditions.
Fermented foods are universal: sauerkraut, pickled beets, pickled cucumbers, fermented rye drink (a sour, slightly alcoholic beverage called kvas that tastes terrible and is consumed in enormous quantities). Beer is the primary alcohol — Roslandic beer is dark, malty, and significantly stronger than the Horns variety. Spirits are distilled in the mountain towns: a clear, brain-stripping grain alcohol called zhivka that miners drink before shifts and that outsiders describe as "drinkable fire."
Music
Roslandic music is choral. The tradition descends from the military singing culture of the old stratocratic republic — songs were commands, were morale, were identity. A Roslandic cohort that couldn't sing together couldn't fight together. The legacy survives in the fire-song — a multi-part choral piece performed around the communal fire, with no instrumental accompaniment, voices only. Fire-songs are the repositories of Roslandic history: the founding of the republic, the Pact of Iron with Nion I, the Ironside Rebellion, the guild reforms, the names of the dead. Every Roslandic child learns fire-songs before they learn to read. Every guild has its own fire-songs. Every family has private fire-songs that are never sung outside the household.
The counter-tradition is the forge-beat — rhythmic percussion music played on anvils, hammers, and whatever metal is to hand in the mining towns and smithies. Forge-beats started as work-coordination rhythms and evolved into a percussive art form that Roslandic workers are fiercely proud of and that outsiders find either hypnotic or unbearable. A good forge-beat session in a Karthold tavern — six smiths hammering in syncopated rhythm on a table full of tankards — is one of the most exciting musical experiences on the continent.

VALLAN — The Quiet Passage
The Feel
Small. Green. Impossibly tidy. Vallan occupies a series of fertile mountain valleys — the Hortakin — nestled between the Heartlands to the north and the Silver Mountains to the south, with the Isle of Knowledge accessible by boat from its eastern ports. It is the smallest independent polity on the continent and the one most fiercely attached to its independence. The valleys are terraced for farming — neat rows of grain, vegetable plots, fruit orchards stepping up the hillsides in patterns that have been maintained for centuries. The roads are the best in the world: stone-paved, well-drained, marked with waystones every mile, and maintained by a road-tax system that makes Vallan's mountain passes the safest and most reliable trade corridors on the continent.
Everything about Vallan is careful. The stone walls between fields are precisely laid. The bridge arches are mathematically perfect. The inn at every waystone is stocked according to regulations that specify the minimum quality of bread, beer, and bedding. The Vallanaise take visible pride in things working correctly — a crumbling wall, a muddy road, a poorly stocked inn is a source of communal shame rather than individual failure. Visitors from larger, messier regions find Vallan either charming or claustrophobic, depending on how they feel about being judged for the state of their boots.
The People
Small-statured compared to their Heartlander and Roslandic neighbors, olive-skinned, dark-haired, with the weathered complexion of people who spend their lives outdoors at altitude. They are quiet, polite, stubborn beyond all reason, and possessed of a dry humor so understated that outsiders frequently miss it entirely. A Vallanaise insult is delivered with such gentle courtesy that the target often doesn't realize they've been insulted until they're three valleys away. They speak Munnish with a lilting accent and a vocabulary laced with local terms for geographical features — they have fourteen words for different kinds of mountain pass and six for different grades of road surface.
Clothing is practical mountain-wear: leather boots, wool trousers, the ubiquitous Vallanaise strappjacke — a fitted wool jacket with leather reinforcements at the shoulders and elbows, designed for climbing, riding, and bridge-maintenance work. Colors are muted earth tones. The one splash of color is the hauskord — a braided cord in house or canton colors, worn at the waist, that identifies the wearer's valley of origin. Removing your hauskord is a declaration of exile; losing it is a minor social catastrophe.
Food
Mountain cuisine: cheese, bread, dried meat, root vegetables, and the obsessive cultivation of herbs that Vallanaise cooks use to transform simple ingredients into something unexpectedly complex. The signature dish is käsknöpfle — hand-shaped pasta dumplings smothered in melted alpine cheese, fried onions, and fresh herbs, served with a side of pickled cabbage. It is the most comforting food on the continent and the subject of inter-valley rivalries as fierce as anything in Sangrea. Every valley claims its version is the original.
Dairy is central: cow's milk cheese in dozens of varieties (hard, soft, aged, fresh, smoked, herb-rubbed), butter, cream, and the rich, thick yogurt that mountain workers eat for breakfast with honey and toasted grain. Meat is preserved: air-dried beef (bündnerfleisch), smoked sausage, cured ham hung from farmhouse rafters for months. Bread is dense, seeded, and often enriched with nuts or dried fruit. Wine is produced in small quantities in the lower valleys — light, crisp, acidic — but the primary drink is a clear, fierce apple brandy called obstler that Vallanaise farmers distill in copper pot-stills older than some countries.

THE RED COAST — Copper, Sand, and Hidden Water
The Feel
Hot. Dry. The Red Coast is the continent's arid belt — a crescent of desert, scrubland, and oasis cities curving along the southeastern coast, backed by volcanic ridges that shimmer in the heat haze and fronted by a coastline of red sandstone cliffs dropping into warm, copper-tinted water. The color red is everywhere: in the sand, in the stone, in the native copper that streaks through the rock like veins in flesh, in the henna that stains the hands and beards of the people. The light is merciless — white, flat, and blinding from mid-morning to late afternoon. Life happens at dawn, dusk, and night. The middle of the day is for sleeping, praying, or sitting in the shade of a courtyard fountain and drinking mint tea until the sun stops trying to kill you.
Water defines everything. The oasis cities exist because water exists; where the water runs out, civilization ends. The qanat systems — underground aqueducts that tap deep aquifer water and carry it to the surface through gravity-fed tunnels — are the Red Coast's most important infrastructure and the subject of its most bitter conflicts. A house that controls a qanat controls life itself. The politics of the Red Coast are, at root, the politics of thirst.
The People
Red Coast people are dark-skinned, lean, and adapted to heat in ways that northerners are not — they can work in temperatures that would fell a Roslandic smith, and they move through their cities with an economy of motion that conserves energy and minimizes sweat. Faces are angular, sharp-featured, with dark eyes that seem to absorb light rather than reflect it. Hair is black, worn long by women (often braided with copper beads and henna-dyed thread) and cropped short or shaved by men (head-wraps and turbans serve as both sun protection and status display). The men's beards are a cultural institution: groomed, oiled, often henna-dyed in shades from auburn to deep crimson, and styled in patterns that indicate tribal affiliation, profession, and marital status. A clean-shaven Red Coast man is either in mourning or in disgrace.
Clothing is loose, layered, and designed for the desert: long robes of light cotton or linen (thawb variants), head-wraps that can be pulled across the face against sandstorms, and soft leather boots or sandals. The color palette is earth tones — sand, ochre, rust, umber — with copper ornament as the universal status marker. Everyone on the Red Coast wears copper: bracelets, rings, belt-buckles, brooch-pins, earrings, nose-rings, and the distinctive copper circlets that the Copper Courts' traveling judges wear as badges of authority. The metalwork is extraordinary — Red Coast coppersmiths produce filigree so fine it looks like frozen flame, and Khorim obsidian-and-copper jewelry is traded across the continent as luxury goods.
Architecture
Built for shade, built for water, built to disappear. Red Coast architecture is interior-focused: blank, fortress-like exterior walls of mud-brick or sandstone, enclosing lush interior courtyards centered on fountains, pools, or cisterns. The wealthier the household, the more water in the courtyard — a Red Coast merchant's social standing can be measured by the sound of running water in their home. Public buildings follow the same principle at scale: the Grand Souk of Alsiroth's Gate is a labyrinth of covered streets, vaulted arcades, and interior plazas connected by narrow alleys that channel wind through the market like a cooling system. The effect is disorienting to outsiders and perfectly navigable to locals.
The most dramatic architecture is the qasr — the fortified tower-house that the oasis lords build on the highest point of their settlement. Qasrs are tall, narrow, and decorated with geometric patterns carved into the stone or painted in mineral pigments (copper green, iron red, cobalt blue). Each qasr's rooftop serves as a signal station — mirror-flashes during the day, fire-baskets at night — maintaining the communication network that connects the oasis cities across the desert.
Food
Survival cuisine elevated to art. The Red Coast's basic diet is dates, flatbread, goat cheese, and dried meat — the caravan staples that have sustained desert travelers for millennia. But the oasis cities, with their irrigated gardens and trade connections, have developed a cuisine of surprising richness: slow-cooked lamb with dried apricots and almonds, couscous mounded with roasted vegetables and dusted with cinnamon, stuffed grape leaves in copper-bright saffron sauce, and the magnificent bastilla — a layered pastry of pigeon meat, eggs, almonds, and powdered sugar wrapped in gossamer-thin dough, baked until golden, and served at celebrations as a demonstration of the host's wealth and the cook's skill. Mint tea is the social lubricant: served sweet, hot, and in small glasses, poured from a height that produces a frothy head. Refusing tea is an insult. Accepting tea obligates you to at least three glasses. The fourth glass is optional but expected.

THE FROZEN SOUTH — Gold, Ice, and Old Bone
The Feel
Brutal. Beautiful. Empty. The Frozen South is the continent's bottom edge — a ragged coastline of fjords, glaciers, and wind-stripped tundra that dissolves into the southern ocean's permanent grey. The landscape is extreme: mountains that rise from sea level to snow line in a single sheer wall, fjords so deep and narrow that sunlight reaches the water for only a few hours a day, glacial valleys where the ice has carved the bedrock into shapes that look deliberately sculpted. The colors are limited and intense — the black of volcanic rock, the white of snow, the grey of overcast sky, and the sudden, shocking gold of the ore deposits that streak through the mountains like the earth's blood.
It is cold. Not the manageable cold of Rosland's winters, which come and go — this is permanent, structural cold, the kind that shapes bodies and minds over generations. The Frozen South has never been warm. The people who live here have adapted or died.
The People
The clans of the Frozen South are physically massive — the largest humans on the continent, averaging six feet for women and six-four for men, with heavy bone structure, broad shoulders, and a layer of subcutaneous fat that makes their silhouettes barrel-shaped and their handshakes bone-crushing. Skin is pale, wind-burned to permanent pink across the cheeks and nose, with a weathered quality that makes everyone look older than they are. Hair is thick, coarse, ranging from white-blond to dark brown, worn long by both sexes and braided in styles that indicate clan, family, and status. Beards are universal among men and considered sacred — shaving is a punishment reserved for oath-breakers.
Clothing is fur, leather, and felted wool, layered for insulation: a base layer of seal-skin, a middle layer of mammoth-wool felt (traded from the highland herders or produced from the region's own small, shaggy musk-oxen), and an outer layer of bear-hide or seal-hide, oiled against wet and wind. Boots are the most important garment — Frozen South boots are masterworks of engineering, multi-layered, insulated with dried grass, soled with mammoth-leather that grips ice. A person with bad boots is a dead person. Color is scarce: the natural tones of fur and leather dominate, with the only bright accents being the clan-markers — woven bands of dyed wool in clan colors, worn at the upper arm, that serve the same identification purpose as a Heartlander's surcoat.
Architecture
Semi-subterranean. The clan-holds are built into the landscape rather than on top of it — longhouses half-buried in hillsides, their turf roofs blending into the terrain, their interiors warm from the body heat of communal living and the peat-and-dung fires that burn day and night. The great hall — every clan-hold has one — is the largest interior space, a long, low-ceilinged room centered on a fire-pit, its walls hung with furs, weapons, and the ancestral gold-work that is the clan's treasure and identity. The gold-work is extraordinary: Frozen South smiths are the continent's finest goldsmiths, producing torcs, bracelets, brooches, and ceremonial weapons of interlocking knotwork and animal motifs (wolves, bears, eagles, and the mythical aurora serpent) that make Heartlands silverwork look crude by comparison.
The Kjölfoss Deeps — Clan Aurax's primary gold mine — is the closest thing the Frozen South has to a city: a sprawling complex of mine shafts, smelting works, barracks, and the great underground hall where the Winter-Moot meets. It is warm (geothermal heat from the volcanic roots of the mountains) and perpetually lit by tallow-lamps that give the gold-veined walls a liquid, breathing quality. Visitors describe it as stepping inside a living jewel box.
Food
Meat, fish, and fat. The Frozen South's cuisine is caloric by necessity — the body burns fuel just staying warm. Seal meat, whale blubber, smoked fish, dried caribou, and the dense, crumbling blood-sausage called blóðmör are staples. Dairy comes from the shaggy musk-oxen: thick, sweet milk curdled into a yogurt-like substance called skyr that is eaten at every meal. Bread is rare — grain doesn't grow this far south — and imported from Rosland or the Heartlands at considerable expense. The substitute is a flatcake made from ground lichen and rendered fat, cooked on hot stones, that tastes like the idea of bread as remembered by someone who hasn't eaten bread in years.
The one luxury is mead — fermented honey wine, produced from the short summer's wildflower bloom and hoarded through the long winter like liquid gold. Mead is the social currency of the Frozen South: offered at moots, poured at funerals, exchanged at betrothals. The quality of a clan's mead is a direct index of their status. Clan Aurax's mead, made from mountain heather honey and aged in gold-leaf-lined barrels, is considered the finest on the continent by the handful of outsiders who have ever tasted it.

XARIA — The Green Furnace
The Feel
Overwhelming. That is the universal first reaction of any mainlander who enters Xaria: the heat, the humidity, the density of the vegetation, the volume of the insects, the colors, the smells — everything is more. Xaria occupies the continent's eastern peninsula, separated from the mainland by a belt of tropical jungle so dense that the two major land routes through it (the Jungle Road and the River Passage) are engineering achievements comparable to the Heartlands' river network. Beyond the jungle belt, the peninsula opens into a landscape of stepped pyramids, canal cities, plantation estates, and the muddy, vast river delta that is the agricultural engine of Ix'Atani civilization.
The air is thick — not just with humidity but with presence. This is the most echo-dense region on the mainland, though no one uses that term. The jungle interior has never been fully cleared; the temple-cities were built within the forest canopy rather than against it; the agricultural zones work with the floodplain rather than against it. The result is a landscape where human civilization and wild nature exist in a proximity that mainlanders find unsettling. A temple courtyard in an Ix'Atani canal-city might have a thirty-foot caiman sunning itself on the steps. No one bothers it. It belongs there.
The People
Xarians are dark-skinned — deep brown to blue-black, with the full range of tropical human variation. Body types range from the tall, lean canal-dwellers of the delta to the shorter, muscular plantation workers of the interior. Hair is black, worn in elaborate braided and wrapped styles that indicate caste, profession, and ritual status — a Xarian priest's hair arrangement might take two hours and require three assistants. Facial scarification is common among the upper castes: geometric patterns cut into the cheeks, forehead, or chin during coming-of-age rituals, then rubbed with pigment to produce raised, colored scars that serve as permanent identity markers.
Clothing is minimal (the heat makes layering impractical) and spectacular. The basic garment is a wrapped loincloth or skirt of dyed cotton, with an upper-body wrap for formal occasions. Color is everything: Xarian dyes — extracted from jungle plants, insects, and mineral pigments — produce hues of startling intensity: cochineal crimson, indigo blue, turmeric gold, jaguar-spotted patterns in black and ochre. Featherwork is the highest art: cloaks, headdresses, and ceremonial garments constructed from the plumage of tropical birds — quetzals, macaws, toucans — assembled in mosaic patterns that can take years to complete. A high priest's feathered cloak is worth more than a Heartlands duchy.
Jewelry is gold, jade, and obsidian. The contrast with the Red Coast's copper aesthetic is stark — where the Red Coast's metalwork is filigree and delicacy, Xarian goldwork is massive, heavy, and designed to dominate. Ear-spools the size of fists. Lip-plugs of polished jade. Pectoral plates of hammered gold depicting jaguars, serpents, and the sun in its various aspects. The effect is deliberately intimidating: Xarian ornament is not decoration, it is armor — spiritual armor against the gods' hunger.
Architecture
Vertical. Xarian architecture reaches for the sky the way Heartlands architecture reaches for the river. The step-pyramids — teocallis — are the defining structures: massive, truncated pyramids of dressed stone, rising in stepped tiers to flat summits where the sacrificial altars and the priests' quarters sit above the jungle canopy. The largest teocallis are over two hundred feet tall and visible for miles — landmarks in a landscape where the flat jungle canopy otherwise renders navigation impossible.
The canal-cities are the other architectural marvel. Built on artificial islands in the river delta, connected by a network of canals that serve as streets, they are the Xarian equivalent of Venice — except larger, hotter, and populated by caimans. The buildings are plastered stone, painted in bright colors (red, white, blue, yellow) and decorated with carved and painted reliefs depicting religious scenes, historical events, and the endless catalog of the gods' appetites. The markets — floating on barge-platforms in the canals — are the most vibrant commercial spaces on the continent, trading everything from cacao to slaves to quetzal feathers to poisons.
Food
Xarian cuisine is built on the trinity of maize, beans, and chili — supplemented by the staggering abundance of the tropical environment: mango, papaya, avocado, cacao, vanilla, pineapple, a dozen varieties of squash, and the protein sources of a jungle ecosystem (wild turkey, iguana, fish, insects, and the small hairless dogs that Xarians breed for food and that mainlanders find distressing). The signature preparation is the tamale — masa dough wrapped around a filling of meat, chili, and vegetables, steamed in banana leaves, and eaten by the dozen at festivals. Cacao is consumed as a bitter, spiced drink — ground cacao beans frothed with hot water, chili, and vanilla — that is simultaneously a stimulant, a currency, and a sacred substance used in religious ceremonies. The Xarian elite drink cacao from jade cups and consider anyone who adds sugar to it a barbarian.

THE TEETH — Four Islands, One Bridge, No Agreement
The Feel
The Teeth are what happens when you put four completely different cultures on four adjacent islands, connect them with a single massive bridge, and give them a thousand years to develop grudges. Each island is distinct enough to be its own country; the bridge forces them into proximity; the proximity produces friction; the friction produces the most colorful, contentious, and unpredictable political environment on the continent.
The bridge itself — the Great Bridge — is the defining feature. It spans the archipelago in a series of arched segments, connecting island to island to island, with towers at each junction and toll-gates at each terminus. At its full extent, it is the longest artificial structure on the continent. It was built during the Age of History by methods that no one can replicate (the Magos suspect echo-engineering), and it has been maintained, repaired, fought over, and nearly destroyed so many times that the current structure is more patch than original. Walking the Great Bridge is a journey of several days. The views are extraordinary. The toll fees are criminal.
Northwind — Windswept, rocky, treeless. Fishing villages and clifftop fortresses. House Stormglass rules from Galehold, a castle carved into the living rock of the island's highest cliff. The people are sea-hardened, suspicious of outsiders, and renowned for the accuracy of their weather predictions (generations of living on the most weather-exposed island in the archipelago have produced a population that reads clouds the way Heartlanders read balance sheets). Culture is spare, maritime, and proud. They make the best rope on the continent and consider this a legitimate source of national identity.
Emberstone — Volcanic, warm, industrious. The smoking peaks of the island's two active volcanoes give the landscape a permanent sulfurous haze. House Pyrmont runs the volcanic stone quarries that are the island's primary export — Emberstone basalt is the hardest building stone available, and it ships across the continent for fortifications, bridge piers, and the foundations of buildings that need to last. The culture is working-class, guild-dominated, and politically volatile — Morvayn's coup drew support from the quarry-workers who felt Pyrmont's management had enriched the house at their expense. Beneath the quarries, unknown to everyone, the Magos' secret vault sits in the volcanic rock.
Verwhisper — Forested, fertile, pious. The green island, covered in temperate hardwood forest and terraced farmland, is the Teeth's breadbasket and its spiritual center. House Verdane governs in partnership with the Order of the Green Thorn, producing a culture that is simultaneously agrarian, devout, and deeply suspicious of the other islands' secular politics. Verwhisper's towns have a half-timbered, devotional quality — churches at every crossroad, monastery gardens behind every wall, and a quiet, well-fed contentment that the other islands find smug.
Shadowtide — Jungle, ungoverned, dangerous. The fourth island is the Teeth's wild card — tropical forest, hostile wildlife, and a population of fisherfolk and foragers who have never submitted to any centralized authority. Various families have claimed lordship; none have enforced it. Shadowtide is where the Teeth's criminals flee, where its exiles land, and where things happen that the other three islands prefer not to know about. The island produces rare hardwoods, exotic spices, and rumors of creatures in the deep jungle that shouldn't exist.

THE ISLE OF KNOWLEDGE — The Memory of the World
The Feel
Quiet. Damp. The smell of old paper and older stone. The Isle of Knowledge sits off Vallan's eastern coast — a small, rocky island accessible only by boat, its single harbor sheltered by a natural breakwater of basalt pillars that look deliberately placed (they may have been, in the Age of History, by methods now lost). The island's surface is mostly covered by the Magos compound: libraries, scriptoria, dormitories, laboratories, observatories, and the deep vault complex that descends into the island's volcanic bedrock like an inverted tower.
The atmosphere is monastic but not religious — the Magos serve knowledge, not God, and the distinction matters. The libraries are open to any scholar regardless of origin or faith, and the debates in the reading rooms are spirited, irreverent, and occasionally violent (academic disputes among the Magos have been known to escalate to the point where the Elder Magos has to physically separate combatants). The island runs on a system of barter and obligation: scholars pay for access with labor (copying manuscripts, maintaining the archives, cataloguing new acquisitions) or with knowledge (original research, rare texts, information from distant regions that the Magos have not yet catalogued).

FAITHIR — The City of God
The Feel
Overwhelming in a different way than Xaria. Faithir is not vast — it was a small town that became a city by accretion, growing outward from the Sacred Grove at its center in concentric rings of construction that span four centuries. The result is architecturally incoherent and spiritually overpowering: the innermost ring is the Great Dome Cathedral, built by Nion XIII's architects over the prophets' original home and tomb; the second ring is the administrative district of the Council of Three, with the headquarters of the Ayanite, Ashanite, and Alonite orders; the third ring is the pilgrim quarter — hostels, hospitals, markets, and the endless stream of devotional shops selling relics, prayer tokens, and sacred souvenirs of varying authenticity; and the outer ring is the working city, where the people who cook, clean, build, and maintain Faithir's enormous religious infrastructure actually live.
The streets are always crowded. Pilgrims from every region on the continent — Heartlanders in silver-threaded surcoats, Roslandic veterans in kolpaks, Sangrean families in bright embroidery, Red Coast merchants in copper-studded turbans, the occasional Horns sailor looking uncomfortable on dry land — fill the pilgrim quarter year-round, peaking during the great festivals. The economy runs on devotion: candle-makers, relic-sellers, icon-painters, prayer-scribes, and the hospitality industry that feeds and houses hundreds of thousands of visitors annually. Faithir is simultaneously the most sacred and the most commercial city on the continent. The tension between those two identities is the city's permanent condition.

NIONIA — The Marble Isle (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — Under the God-King's Shadow

I. THE ISLAND AT A GLANCE
Population: ~180,000 (down from ~220,000 before the civil war) Capital: Vellium (pop. ~90,000) Other settlements: Port Severan (naval base, pop. ~25,000), Marchia Ferrus (mining district, scattered camps and towns, pop. ~30,000), rural villages and farming estates (~35,000) Government: Theocratic monarchy under Jous Lorethian. The Triumvirate survives as a vestigial advisory body. Economy: Marble quarrying, iron mining, olive oil, wine, fishing, and a declining but still significant maritime trade. Religion: The Pure Way (mandatory). Orthodox Loveism is technically illegal but practiced in secret by a significant minority.

II. VELLIUM — The White City
Districts
The Dome Quarter — The city's heart. Dominated by the Great Dome Cathedral (the converted Senate chamber), the God-King's palace (formerly the Consul's Residence, tripled in size), and the administrative buildings of the Pure Way's clerical apparatus. White marble everywhere, kept obsessively clean by teams of indentured street-scrubbers. The Inquisitors of Domus Lux maintain their headquarters here — the Pale House, a former patrician mansion whose basement has been converted into interrogation cells. The streets are wide, patrolled, and eerily quiet after dark. This is the only district where the whale-oil lamps burn all night.
The Colonnade — The old patrician quarter. Grand houses with columned facades, interior courtyards, and generations of accumulated art and wealth. The surviving patrician families — Marcellus, Navarrus, Cassian — still live here, maintaining the fiction of aristocratic dignity while navigating the reality of life under a God-King who could dispossess them with a word. The architecture is the finest on the island: mosaic floors, frescoed ceilings, marble fountains that still run with spring-fed water. The Colonnade's public face is one of serene compliance with the Pure Way. Behind the courtyard walls, old habits persist — private lamento performances, uncensored wine, and conversations that would get the speakers killed if the walls had ears. Some walls do.
The Dockyards — Port district. Sprawling, loud, and the one part of Vellium that Jous's white-cloak patrols haven't fully tamed. The docks handle the island's fishing fleet, its merchant marine, and the growing war-fleet that Jous is building for his mainland invasion. Shipwrights, riggers, chandlers, and the supply chain of naval preparation dominate the economy. The taverns are rough, the brothels are technically illegal (the Pure Way forbids commercial sex), and the Domus Lux presence is heavy but ineffective — dockworkers are too economically essential to alienate with aggressive enforcement. The Anchor & Chain is the district's most famous tavern: a three-story wreck of salt-rotted timber where the best lamento singers perform after midnight and the Inquisitors know better than to enter uninvited.
The Terraces — Working-class residential. Tenement blocks rising in tiers up the hillside behind the docks, connected by narrow staircases and alleyways where the sun reaches the ground for maybe two hours a day. Overcrowded, under-serviced, and the source of most of Jous's common-born followers — the people who believed his promise that the old patrician order would fall and something better would replace it. Some still believe. Many are beginning to wonder what "better" means when the price is a white cloak on every corner and the sound of hymns that you didn't choose to sing.
The Quarry Road — The highway connecting Vellium to the Marchia Ferrus mining district. Lined with workshops, supply depots, and the barracks of the mining crews who rotate between the quarries and the city on monthly shifts. The road itself is rutted, dusty, and perpetually crowded with ox-carts hauling marble blocks and iron ingots. It is the least beautiful part of a beautiful island, and it is where most of the wealth comes from.

III. THE MAJOR HOUSES OF NIONIA
DOMUS LORETH — The God-King's House
Founded: 1306 AF (during the civil war) Seat: The Dome Palace, Vellium Sigil: A white sun on a pale blue field Words: "I Am the Way"
Domus Loreth is less a dynasty than a cult. It has no ancestral estates, no centuries of accumulated legitimacy, no genealogy deeper than one generation. It exists because Jous Lorethian exists. Its power is his power. Its future depends entirely on whether a 24-year-old man who believes he is God can hold an island and conquer a continent.
Current Members:
Jous Lorethian, God-King of Nionia (age 24) — Born in the convent of the Sisters of the Veil, raised to believe he was the physical incarnation of Loreth. Strikingly beautiful — high cheekbones, pale grey eyes, black hair worn long and unbound in the style the Pure Way has made fashionable. His physical beauty is one of his weapons: people who meet him for the first time often describe a feeling of unreality, as if they're looking at a painting that stepped off the wall. He is charismatic to a degree that borders on the pathological — not warm, exactly, but compelling, the way a fire is compelling. His echo-density produces a localized resonance effect that makes people in his presence feel more certain, more fervent, more willing to believe. He does not know this is a mechanism. He believes it is proof of divinity. He may not be entirely wrong.
Jous sleeps badly. The sleep paralysis that has plagued him since adolescence produces visions he interprets as divine revelation — images of a purified world, a continent united under his rule, a future of absolute order. The visions are becoming more vivid and more specific as his echo-sensitivity strengthens in the wake of the Eldra-Veil breach (though he doesn't know the cause). He is beginning to see places he has never visited — mainland landscapes, rivers he can't name, faces he doesn't recognize. He does not doubt these visions. He has never doubted anything about himself. That certainty is his greatest strength and his most dangerous flaw.
He is celibate — not by doctrine but by temperament. He finds physical intimacy repulsive in a way that may reflect genuine asexuality, psychological damage from his convent upbringing, or simply the impossibility of intimacy for someone who genuinely believes they are God. The Pure Way's clergy have elevated his celibacy into doctrine: the God-King's body is sacred, inviolable, not to be polluted by mortal contact. This creates a succession problem that no one around him is willing to discuss aloud.
Eduard Lorethian (age 19) — Jous's younger half-brother. Born in the convent five years after Jous — same mother (Sister Sera is listed, but Sera died birthing Jous; Eduard's mother was another sister named Elara, who survived). Eduard is everything Jous is not: cheerful, sociable, physically clumsy, intellectually mediocre, and utterly lacking in the charisma or echo-sensitivity that makes Jous extraordinary. He adores his brother with a desperate, puppyish devotion that Jous tolerates without returning. Eduard has been given the title "Prince of the Way" and a ceremonial role in state functions — standing behind Jous, holding a white banner, looking pretty. He is aware that his value is entirely decorative. This awareness is slowly curdling into something darker.
Eduard drinks too much. He has begun having quiet conversations with people he shouldn't — minor functionaries in the Triumvirate, dockyard workers, a wine merchant named Cato who may or may not be connected to the remnants of Domus Marcellus's intelligence network. Eduard is not plotting against his brother. He is looking for someone to tell him he matters. The distinction may not hold.

DOMUS FERRONUS — The Iron Upstarts
Founded: c. 1300 AF Seat: Ferronus Hall, Marchia Ferrus (a fortress-manor built atop the iron vein that made the family's fortune) Sigil: A black pickaxe on an iron-grey field Words: "From the Deep, We Rise"
The Ferronus family did not exist as a political entity thirty years ago. Ferron — who history will call "the Upstart" — was a common miner who struck the richest iron vein on the island, leveraged the wealth into mercenary contracts, and then made the single most consequential bet in Nionian history: he backed Jous Lorethian's revolution.
Current Members:
Ferron "the Upstart" (age ~58) — Patriarch. Short, thick-bodied, with hands like shovels and a face like a cliff — cragged, scarred, and permanently dusted with the iron-red grit of the mines he still personally inspects. Ferron is not intelligent in the way that patricians understand intelligence — he cannot parse Ayanite theology, discuss philosophy, or identify a wine's vintage. He is intelligent in the way that a wolf is intelligent: he reads people, he reads situations, and he acts decisively. He funded Jous's revolution not because he believed in Jous's divinity but because he recognized an opportunity to destroy the patrician class that had exploited his miners for generations. Whether he got more than he bargained for is a question he asks himself every night.
Ferron's relationship with Jous is the most politically significant dynamic on the island. Jous needs Ferron's money and muscle. Ferron needs Jous's legitimacy and popularity. Neither trusts the other. Both know that their alliance is the only thing holding the new order together. Ferron attends Pure Way services with visible devotion and private contempt. He has been heard, in his cups, calling Jous "the boy" — never within earshot of anyone who would report it. Yet.
Orla Ferronus (age ~35) — Ferron's eldest daughter and the family's real administrator. She runs the mining operations, the mercenary payrolls, the shipping contracts, and the complex web of bribes and favors that keeps the Ferronus economic machine functioning. She is tall (unusual for a miner's family), sharp-featured, and possessed of a memory for numbers that borders on the supernatural. She does not like Jous. She does not trust Jous. She has calculated, with the precision of a woman who knows exactly how many tons of iron ore her family produces per month, the point at which Jous will become more expensive to support than to oppose. She has not reached that point. She is watching.
Matteo Ferronus (age ~28) — Ferron's youngest son. A disappointment. Matteo was supposed to be the family's courtly face — educated, polished, presentable in the halls of power. Instead, he developed a passion for natural philosophy and a corresponding disinterest in politics, money, or the family business. He spends his time in a private laboratory in the Marchia Ferrus, conducting alchemical experiments of questionable legality and corresponding with scholars on the Isle of Knowledge through intermediaries (direct communication would attract Inquisitorial attention). He has accidentally discovered that certain iron ores, when heated in the presence of specific volcanic minerals, produce a metal alloy of unusual strength and lightness. He does not understand why. He is the closest person on Nionia to stumbling onto echo-chemistry, and he has no idea what he's looking at.
Drusa Ferronus (age ~30) — Ferron's middle daughter. Married young to a minor Navarrus cousin to cement the alliance between new money and old navy. The marriage is functional but loveless. Drusa is pious — genuinely, not performatively. She believes in the Pure Way with a convert's intensity that embarrasses her father and delights Jous. She has been appointed to the Pure Way's charitable commission, overseeing food distribution in the Terraces, and she does the work with real dedication. She is the Ferronus family member most likely to be remembered kindly by history, and the one least likely to survive what's coming.

DOMUS MARCELLUS — The Old Blood
Founded: Pre-imperial (one of the original Nionian patrician families) Seat: The Marcellus Compound, the Colonnade (reduced from their pre-war holdings, which included three country estates — two confiscated by the Pure Way) Sigil: A golden column on a red field Words: "We Were First"
The oldest surviving family on Nionia. The Marcelli trace their lineage to the senator who escaped the Great Pyre — the one man who saw Nion I's purge coming and had the sense to run. That ancestor's survival instinct has been bred into every subsequent generation. The Marcelli have survived the Pyre, the Empire, the Republic's corruption, and now the Pure Way's revolution. They survive by bending. They never break. They never forget.
Current Members:
Lucretia Marcellus (age 67) — Matriarch. Head of house since her husband Gaius died of a "fever" during the civil war (poisoned, almost certainly — by whom is debated; the Ferronus, the Navarrus, and the Marcellus family's own internal rivals are all candidates). Lucretia is small, white-haired, impeccably dressed in the old republican style (she wears a pallion pinned with a golden column brooch that is worth more than most houses in the Terraces), and terrifying. She survived the civil war by recognizing Jous's victory before anyone else and personally delivering Domus Marcellus's surrender — along with the Senate's ceremonial keys, a chest of gold, and a letter of such eloquent submission that Jous reportedly read it twice and smiled. She is the only person on the island who can make the God-King smile without trying.
Lucretia's private opinion of Jous is unknown. She has never spoken a word against him. She has also never spoken a word of genuine belief in his divinity. She attends services, tithes generously, and maintains a household that is a model of Pure Way compliance. Her courtyard fountain still runs with spring water. Her lamento singers still perform, though they now sing approved hymns. Her wine cellar is still the finest on the island. She has made no move against the regime. She has also preserved, in a vault beneath her compound, the Senate's complete archive of republican constitutional law — every charter, every precedent, every recorded vote. If the Republic is ever restored, the legal framework exists. If it is not, the archive is kindling. Lucretia does not bet on outcomes. She preserves options.
Quintus Marcellus (age 41) — Lucretia's eldest son. A career diplomat who served as the Republic's ambassador to the Heartlands before the civil war. He returned to Nionia during the fighting, was captured by Domus Lux, and spent six months in the Pale House before his mother negotiated his release. The experience left him with a permanent tremor in his left hand, a stutter he didn't have before, and an absolute refusal to discuss what happened in the basement. He now serves as the family's public face — attending court functions, making the required obeisances, projecting the image of a broken man who has accepted the new order. Whether the brokenness is real or performance is the question that keeps the Inquisitors interested.
Valeria Marcellus (age 36) — Quintus's younger sister. Unmarried, which at her age in Nionian patrician culture is a statement rather than an accident. Valeria is a scholar — trained at the Order of the Quill's Nionian academy before Jous's followers burned it during the civil war. She now teaches privately, tutoring the children of families wealthy enough to afford education and discreet enough to want their children taught by someone other than a Pure Way catechist. She keeps a coded journal. The code is based on a pre-imperial Nionian cipher that the Inquisitors have not yet cracked. The journal's contents, if decoded, would provide a detailed record of life under the Pure Way — names, dates, incidents, and the slow accumulation of evidence that Valeria compiles with the methodical patience of a woman who learned her craft from archivists.
Young Gaius Marcellus (age 14) — Quintus's only son. Named for his grandfather. A boy who has never known a world without the Pure Way and who is, consequently, a genuine believer — not in Jous specifically, but in the idea of order, purity, and divine certainty that the Pure Way promises. His grandmother watches him recite the cantus with a face that reveals nothing and a heart that, if it could be read, would show something very close to grief.

DOMUS NAVARRUS — The Fleet
Founded: Imperial era (elevated by Aurelius I as naval administrators) Seat: The Navarrus Citadel, Port Severan Sigil: A black ship on a silver sea Words: "The Tide Serves Us"
The Navarrus family controlled Nionia's navy for centuries. When the civil war came, they bet on the Republic — and lost. Their fleet was broken at the Battle of Port Severan when Ferron's fire-ships destroyed six Navarrus warships. The family surrendered, offered its surviving vessels to Jous, and was permitted to live — diminished, humiliated, but alive. They now serve as Jous's naval administrators, building the invasion fleet under the supervision of Domus Lux observers who trust them about as far as a dead calm will carry a warship.
Current Members:
Admiral Varro Navarrus (age 52) — Head of house. A career sailor who commanded the fleet that tried to blockade the capital and failed. The defeat broke something in him — not his competence (he is still the best naval tactician on the island) but his certainty. He gave his life to a Republic that turned out to be not worth dying for, and now he builds warships for a God-King he despises. He drinks every night. He never drinks enough to be incompetent the next morning. This discipline is the only thing keeping him alive.
Varro's wife, Livia, drowned herself in the harbor three months after the surrender. He does not speak of her. The household staff has been instructed to remove all mirrors from the Admiral's quarters — he cannot bear to look at his own face. The reason, never stated, is that Livia's eyes were the same color as his.
Senna Navarrus (age 29) — Varro's daughter. Serves as the fleet's logistics officer — supplies, provisioning, crew rotation. She is competent, cold, and harboring a fury so controlled that it has become indistinguishable from professionalism. She despises the Ferronus family with a specificity that goes beyond politics: Ferron's mercenaries killed her younger brother during the Battle of Port Severan. She has his name tattooed on her inner wrist in old naval cipher. She is waiting. She does not know what she is waiting for. But she will recognize it when she sees it.
Corvus Navarrus (age 24) — Varro's nephew, son of his executed brother. Raised by the household after his father was hanged for "conspiracy against the Way" (he had been caught meeting with mainland contacts — whether for treasonous purposes or simple trade negotiation is disputed). Corvus is beautiful, charming, bisexual in a culture that has recently criminalized same-sex relations under the Pure Way, and reckless in the specific way of young men who have decided they are already dead. He serves as a shipwright's apprentice in the Port Severan yards, where his draftsmanship is excellent and his habit of bedding other apprentices is an open secret that the Domus Lux observer has not yet reported — either through incompetence, sympathy, or the accumulation of leverage for future use.

DOMUS TORR — The Admiralty's Ghost
Founded: Imperial era (by Aurelius I "the Sailor") Seat: Formerly the Torr Estate, northern coast; now reduced to a townhouse in Vellium Sigil: A golden anchor on a blue field Words: "Into the Deep"
Once the most powerful naval house on the island, Domus Torr has been declining since Admiral Torr's death in 889 AF — over four centuries of slow collapse. By the time of the civil war, the Torr were a name without a fleet, a sigil without an army, and a family of perhaps fifteen people living on the diminishing returns of ancestral investments. The civil war barely touched them — they had nothing worth taking.
Current Members:
Old Aemilia Torr (age 78) — The last of the mainline Torrs. A tiny, fierce woman who lives alone in the Vellium townhouse with three cats and a collection of naval charts dating back to the imperial era. She is technically the head of house, though the house consists of herself, two distant cousins who work as fishermen, and a grandnephew in the Marchia Ferrus who mines iron and has never seen the sea. Aemilia is the island's foremost amateur historian — she has spent fifty years compiling a history of the Nionian navy from Aurelius I to the present, written in a cramped, precise hand on recycled parchment, and it is the most comprehensive naval record on the island. The Magos would kill for a copy. The Inquisitors would burn it if they knew it existed, because it includes unflattering accounts of Jous's naval strategy during the civil war.
Aemilia attends Pure Way services with the dutiful boredom of someone who has outlived the capacity for shock. She sits in the back, mouth moving with the cantus, eyes watching everything. She has outlived three governments. She expects to outlive this one.

DOMUS CASSIAN — The Quarrymen
Founded: Pre-imperial (one of the original four patrician families of the Marble Compact) Seat: Cassian Holdings, eastern quarry district Sigil: A white hammer on a grey field Words: "We Shape the Stone"
The Cassians controlled Nionia's marble quarries under the Republic, supplying the building material that made the island's architecture possible. They were the least political of the four Compact families — content to dig, cut, and sell stone while the Marcelli and Navarri played at Senate politics. This apolitical stance saved them during the civil war: they surrendered immediately, continued supplying marble to whoever was in charge, and emerged from the revolution with their quarries intact and their family largely unscathed. The Cassians are the boring dynasty — no great heroes, no great villains, just competent stone merchants who have been doing the same thing for a thousand years.
Current Members:
Petronius Cassian (age 45) — Head of house. A quiet, square-built man who smells permanently of marble dust and speaks in the measured, deliberate cadences of someone who learned patience from rock. He runs the quarries efficiently, pays his workers fairly (by Nionian standards), and stays as far from politics as a man on a small island ruled by a God-King can manage. He attends court when summoned, contributes to public works when asked, and donates to the Pure Way's building programs with an enthusiasm that may be genuine (the Pure Way builds a lot of marble structures) or strategic (every new cathedral is a Cassian contract).
His secret: Petronius's quarry crews have been encountering something strange in the deep cuts — a vein of marble that is not white but faintly luminescent, with a blue-green light visible only in total darkness. The vein is deep, narrow, and unlike any mineral deposit his engineers have ever seen. He has sealed the section and told no one. He does not know what he has found. He is afraid of it.
Cassia Cassian (age 17) — Petronius's eldest daughter. Headstrong, curious, and possessed of an intense interest in geology that her father considers unwomanly and her tutors consider inappropriate. She has been sneaking into the sealed quarry section at night. She has seen the glowing stone. She has touched it. She is the first person on Nionia in three centuries to feel the Pulse — a faint warmth in her fingertips, a pressure behind her eyes, a sense of being watched by something that doesn't have eyes. She doesn't know what it means. She can't stop going back.

DOMUS LUX — The White Cloaks
Founded: c. 1303 AF (originally a rogue chapter of the Sons of Loreth) Seat: The Pale House, Dome Quarter Sigil: A white flame on a white field (the sigil is deliberately almost invisible — "purity needs no display") Words: "We See All"
Domus Lux is not a noble house in the traditional sense. It is a religious-military order — the Pure Way's enforcement arm, Jous's personal instrument of control. Its members take vows of obedience to the God-King, wear the white cloaks that have become the most feared garment on the island, and operate with an authority that supersedes civilian law. They investigate heresy, enforce doctrinal compliance, interrogate suspects, and — when necessary — execute the condemned. They are judge, jury, and executioner under the Pure Way's legal framework, answerable only to Jous.
Current Members:
Prior Thaniel (age ~40) — Leader of Domus Lux. A zealot of unknown origin — his accent suggests Heartlands birth, but no one has been able to confirm his history before he appeared in Nionia around 1302 AF, already attached to the early Pure Way movement. He is gaunt, tall, soft-spoken, and radiates the particular menace of a man who is absolutely certain that everything he does is righteous. His eyes are pale blue, almost white, and people who have been interrogated by him report that he never blinks during questioning — a detail that may be exaggeration but that has become part of his legend.
Thaniel is a true believer. This makes him more dangerous than a cynic would be — a cynic can be bribed, blackmailed, or reasoned with. Thaniel cannot. He believes Jous is Loreth incarnate with the same certainty that he believes the sun will rise. He has personally overseen the execution of over forty people for heresy, apostasy, or "corruption of the Way." He does not enjoy these executions. He considers them necessary surgery — the removal of diseased tissue to preserve the body's health. He sleeps soundly.
Brother Cael (age ~25) — Thaniel's protégé and the Domus Lux's chief investigator. Where Thaniel is rigid, Cael is adaptive — he understands that not every heretic can be found through brute-force surveillance, and he has developed a network of informants, paid observers, and leveraged civilians that functions as an intelligence service more sophisticated than anything the Republic's old secret police ever managed. Cael is handsome, approachable, and charming in a way that Thaniel is not — he is the friendly face of the Inquisition, the one who sits down next to you in a tavern and asks how you're doing with such genuine warmth that you find yourself telling him things you shouldn't. He files reports on everyone he talks to. He has a filing system that cross-references names, locations, associations, and suspicious behaviors. He is building a map of Nionian society that would make the Magos jealous.
Cael's personal belief in the Pure Way is genuine but less absolute than Thaniel's — he has doubts, carefully suppressed, about whether Jous's visions are divine or merely unusual. He compensates for these doubts by working harder, investigating more aggressively, and punishing more severely than his role requires. The psychology is familiar: he is proving his faith to himself by performing it at maximum intensity.
Sister Merel (age ~30) — Head of the Domus Lux's "Daughters of Purity" — the female branch, responsible for monitoring women's compliance with the Pure Way's increasingly restrictive gender codes (modesty standards, prohibitions on unaccompanied travel, limitations on property ownership for unmarried women). Merel is a former dockworker's daughter who found in the Pure Way a structure and purpose her previous life lacked. She is efficient, incorruptible, and quietly horrified by the direction her role is taking — the gender restrictions she enforces are becoming more extreme with each passing year, and she can see where the trajectory leads. She has not spoken her concerns. She knows what happens to people who question the Way.

THE TRIUMVIRATE — The Last Echo of the Republic
Three magistrates who formally crowned Jous during the civil war and were retained as a vestigial advisory body. They have no real power. They serve at Jous's pleasure. Their continued existence is Jous's concession to the fiction that his rule has legal continuity with the Republic.
Magistrate Lucan Praxis (age 55) — The eldest Triumvir. A career bureaucrat who served in the Senate's treasury office for twenty years before the war. He crowned Jous because the alternative was being killed. He now manages the civil administration — taxes, infrastructure, public works — with the numb competence of a man doing his job inside a nightmare. He drinks moderately, sleeps poorly, and has developed a facial tic that activates when Jous enters a room.
Magistrate Iona Kess (age 48) — The only woman in the Triumvirate. A former commercial judge who was appointed to the Senate's judicial committee. Sharp, pragmatic, and the Triumvir most skilled at navigating the gap between what Jous wants and what is actually possible. She has quietly blocked or delayed several of the Pure Way's more extreme proposals (a ban on foreign-language texts, a curfew for unmarried women, the demolition of the old Temple of Fortia) by burying them in procedural reviews that she designs to take years to complete. She is the most useful person in Jous's government and the one he least appreciates.
Magistrate Darvos Sull (age 38) — The youngest. A former naval officer who switched sides during the civil war and was rewarded with a Triumvirate seat. He is the only Triumvir who is a genuine Pure Way convert — he believes in Jous, supports the regime, and uses his position to advocate for military expansion. He is also the Triumvir most likely to be promoted into Jous's inner circle and the one Lucretia Marcellus considers most dangerous, because a true believer in a position of institutional authority can do more damage than a zealot with a sword.

IV. MINOR HOUSES AND NOTABLE FAMILIES
House Vellius — Olive oil magnates. Control the largest olive plantations on the southern coast. Wealthy, cautious, apolitical by long tradition. The current patriarch, Marius Vellius (age 60), has survived every regime change by the simple expedient of supplying everyone with olive oil regardless of who's in charge. His youngest daughter, Thessia (age 22), has joined the Daughters of Purity against her father's wishes — a genuine conversion that has opened a rift in the family.
House Varro — Fishing fleet owners. Based in the dockyard district. The family has operated the island's largest fishing cooperative for three generations. Captain Sextus Varro (age 50) runs the fleet and serves as the informal mayor of the dockyards — the person Domus Lux negotiates with when they want something done (or not done) on the waterfront. His cooperation with the regime is transactional: he keeps the docks quiet, they keep their white cloaks out of his taverns. His son, Little Sextus (age 19), is an apprentice shipwright in the naval yards who has begun attending secret lamento performances — the old songs, the uncensored ones — in a cellar off the Quarry Road.
The Cato Family — Wine merchants. Not a noble house but a commercial dynasty with more liquid wealth than some patricians. Galen Cato (age 44) runs the business — importing mainland wines and distributing Nionian vintages. He is the man Eduard Lorethian has been having quiet conversations with. Cato is not a political operative. He is a businessman who recognizes that a prince with grievances is a valuable relationship, and who is positioning himself to profit from whatever happens next. His wife, Renata (age 40), is smarter than he is and managing the family's real intelligence network — a web of tavern-keepers, ship captains, and dock-workers who pass information along with wine barrels.
The Palladian Circle — Not a family but a secret society. An underground network of former Quill scholars, displaced academics, and nostalgic republicans who meet in rotating locations to preserve pre-war scholarship, maintain the old curriculum, and quietly resist the Pure Way's intellectual stranglehold. They number perhaps thirty active members and a hundred sympathizers. They are amateurs at conspiracy and professionals at preservation. Their most precious possession: a complete copy of The Cogitant Letters by Father Thesan — the Logosian text that the Council of Three banned in 1035 AF — smuggled from the Isle of Knowledge by a Magos agent who sympathized with their cause. They do not understand the text's implications for the echo-theory. But someone eventually will.

THE HORNS — Salt, Sail, and Silver Tongue (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — Four Ports, Four Tempers

I. THE PENINSULA AT A GLANCE
Population: ~120,000 total across four cities and their hinterlands Major Cities: Westhorn (pop. ~40,000), Brinehold (pop. ~25,000), Nightspike (pop. ~20,000), Skogrim (pop. ~10,000) Rural/Fishing villages: ~25,000 Government: No unified authority. Each city governs independently — three under dynastic/council rule, one under a religious order. Economy: Maritime trade, fishing, shipbuilding, salt production, timber (Skogrim), and the pilot services that control access to the treacherous coastal straits. Religion: Orthodox Loveism, with strong Alonite influence (the Lampkeepers of Skogrim are an Alonite order).

II. WESTHORN — The First Port
The City
The largest and wealthiest of the Horns cities, Westhorn clings to a U-shaped natural harbor protected by two massive stone breakwaters — one natural, one imperial-era construction. The city rises in tiers from the harbor: the waterfront district (docks, warehouses, chandleries, taverns, the fish market), the Midtown (merchant homes, guild halls, the Garrun manor, the Ayanite courthouse), and the Clifftop (the old imperial fortress, now the Garrun seat, overlooking the harbor from the highest point). The streets are steep, cobbled, and treacherously slick in the perpetual rain. Everything is built of grey stone and dark timber, roofed in slate, and hung with the iron-and-glass lanterns that give the city its nighttime identity — a cascade of warm light falling down the cliff face to the water.
The harbor never sleeps. Westhorn handles more trade volume than any other Horns port — mainland grain, Sangrean wine, Nionian marble, Red Coast spices, Teeth volcanic stone, and the local products (salt cod, smoked fish, ship timber, rope, sailcloth) that keep the Horns' economy running. The Harbormaster's Tower — a seven-story stone column at the harbor's entrance, topped with a rotating signal lamp — is the city's most recognizable landmark and the operational hub of the port: every ship that enters or exits the harbor is logged, inspected, and taxed by the Harbormaster's staff.

III. THE MAJOR HOUSES OF THE HORNS
HOUSE GARRUN — Lords of Westhorn
Founded: Pre-imperial (originally the Horns' local chieftains; survived the conquest by bending knee to Nion I) Seat: Garrun Keep, Clifftop, Westhorn Sigil: A grey ship's wheel on a green field Words: "Steady as the Tide"
House Garrun has governed Westhorn for over a millennium — first as chieftains, then as imperial governors, then as independent lords. They are not the flashiest dynasty on the continent, but they may be the most durable. Their survival strategy across every era has been the same: be useful, be reliable, and never reach for more than you can hold. The Garruns are administrators, not conquerors. They run the port, maintain the roads, keep the peace, and take their percentage. The city prospers because the Garruns understand that their wealth depends on the city's wealth, and the city's wealth depends on trade flowing freely.
Current Members:
Lord Harlan Garrun (age 58) — Head of house. A blocky, weathered man with salt-grey hair and the permanently squinting eyes of someone who has spent a lifetime looking into wind. Harlan has been lord of Westhorn for thirty years and has governed with the unspectacular competence that the Garruns are known for: the docks are well-maintained, the tariffs are fair, the criminal element is managed rather than eradicated (a realistic approach that acknowledges the impossibility of eliminating smuggling from a port city), and the Ayanite courts function without excessive corruption. He is respected without being loved — a distinction that suits him perfectly.
Harlan's great concern is Morvayn's bridge coup. Westhorn's economy depends on mainland trade, and Morvayn's extortionate tolls are strangling it. Harlan has advocated military action to retake the bridge — a position that puts him at odds with House Verdane of Verwhisper (which prefers negotiation) and that Brinehold would support if Brinehold trusted Westhorn to share the recaptured bridge's revenues (which Brinehold does not).
His private grief: his eldest son, Eddan, was killed in a sailing accident seven years ago — a squall took his racing sloop in the straits. The body was never recovered. Harlan has not raced since. He keeps Eddan's trophies — a shelf of carved wooden cups awarded at regattas — in his study, where he can see them from his desk. He does not mention them. No one else does either.
Lady Maren Garrun (age 54) — Harlan's wife. Born a Dalgaard of Brinehold — one of the rare inter-city marriages that was supposed to cement an alliance between the two ports. It didn't work (the Garrun-Dalgaard rivalry is older than any marriage), but Maren herself has been an effective Lady of Westhorn: she runs the city's charitable institutions, manages the household's social calendar, and serves as Harlan's most trusted advisor on matters of public opinion. She has a Brinehold accent she has never lost and a Brinehold intelligence network she has never disclosed.
Taryn Garrun (age 28) — Harlan's second son, now heir since Eddan's death. A competent sailor and an adequate administrator who lives in the shadow of a dead brother he can never match. Taryn is responsible, hardworking, and chronically anxious — he sleeps badly, bites his nails to the quick, and compensates for his insecurity by over-preparing for every meeting, every decision, every social interaction. He would be a perfectly good lord of Westhorn if he could stop believing he wasn't. His wife, Brynn (age 26), is a fisherman's daughter he married for love over his father's objections. She is cheerful, profane, and completely unintimidated by the aristocracy — qualities that either endear her to the court or horrify them, depending on the day.
Dalla Garrun (age 23) — Harlan's daughter. Serves as the family's trade envoy, traveling between the Horns ports negotiating contracts and maintaining commercial relationships. She is the most politically talented Garrun of her generation — sharp, personable, and possessed of her mother's Brinehold gift for reading people. She has been conducting secret conversations with contacts on Verwhisper about a possible alliance against Morvayn — conversations her father doesn't know about, because Harlan's approach (demand military action, wait for consensus) is too slow for Dalla's taste.

THE MERCHANT-CAPTAINS' COUNCIL OF BRINEHOLD
Founded: c. 905 AF (after the empire's fall) Seat: The Salt Exchange, Brinehold Sigil: A white sail on a blue-black field (the Council's collective banner)
Brinehold is not ruled by a single house. It is governed by the Merchant-Captains' Council — a body of twelve trading family representatives who collectively set policy, adjudicate disputes, and manage the port's operations. The system is oligarchic but genuinely competitive: Council seats are allocated by commercial volume (the twelve families who ship the most cargo in a given year earn seats), ensuring that the governance reflects the port's actual economic power rather than hereditary privilege. In practice, four or five families have dominated the Council for generations, with the remaining seats rotating among smaller operations.
The Dominant Families:
House Dalgaard — Salt merchants. The oldest and wealthiest family on the Council. The Dalgaards have controlled Brinehold's salt production — the evaporation ponds, the packing houses, the distribution network — since before the empire. Salt is boring. Salt is also essential: every preserved fish, every cured meat, every pickled vegetable on the continent requires salt, and the Dalgaards supply roughly a third of the Horns' total production.
Elgar Dalgaard (age 63) — Council Chair (a rotating position, but Elgar has held it for nine consecutive years by the simple expedient of being richer than everyone else). A massive, booming man who fills a room the way a ship fills a dock — completely and with no space left for anyone else. He laughs too loudly, drinks too much, and negotiates with the subtlety of a battering ram. His results speak for themselves: Brinehold's salt revenues have tripled during his chairmanship, and the Dalgaard shipping fleet is now the second largest in the Horns (behind Westhorn's combined merchant marine).
Elgar's weakness is his family. His wife died young. He raised four children alone, badly, and the results are visible: Sigrid (age 35), the eldest, is brilliant but alcoholic — she manages the salt operations with one hand and holds a bottle with the other. Kael (age 30) is a sailor who abandoned the family business to captain his own ship, running cargoes of questionable legality between the Horns and the Teeth. Anja (age 27) married into a Nightspike shipping family and hasn't spoken to her father in three years (the reasons involve an inheritance dispute, a forge-worker she was forbidden to marry, and a slap across the face in the Salt Exchange that twelve Council members witnessed). Little Rig (age 20), the youngest — real name Rigvald — is a dock-worker by day and a bare-knuckle fighter by night, competing in the illegal fighting circuit that operates in Brinehold's warehouse district. He has broken his nose four times and his father's heart continuously.
House Strand — Shipbuilders. The Strands operate Brinehold's largest shipyard — the Keel Works — producing everything from fishing smacks to merchant galleons. They are the Council's industrial heart: without Strand ships, the other families have nothing to trade in.
Bera Strand (age 49) — Matriarch and master shipwright. One of the few women to run a major Horns commercial operation, and the only one who did it by building ships with her own hands for twenty years before inheriting the business. Bera is stocky, callus-handed, and speaks in a voice roughened by decades of inhaling sawdust and pitch fumes. She is the most technically knowledgeable member of the Council and the most politically indifferent — she cares about ship design, timber quality, and whether her keels are true, and she considers everything else a distraction. Her apprentices worship her. Her competitors fear her. Her children — Torsten (age 25) and Liv (age 21) — are both in the yards, learning the trade, and both showing signs of their mother's exacting standards.
House Kemm — Fish brokers. The Kemms don't catch fish — they buy, process, sell, and distribute it. Their packing houses along Brinehold's waterfront handle roughly half the city's catch, salting, smoking, and barreling it for export. They are middlemen, and they are very, very good at it.
Oskar Kemm (age 40) — Council member. A thin, precise man who dresses better than any fishmonger should and negotiates like a man who has memorized the price of every commodity on the continent. He is widely disliked and universally consulted — no one in Brinehold makes a deal without checking the Kemm rate first. His personal life is unusually wholesome for a Horns merchant: married to his childhood sweetheart, Helke (age 38), father of three, and a devoted member of the local Ashanite hospice's board. The contrast between his ruthless professional persona and his genuine domestic warmth confuses people who expect merchants to be consistently unpleasant.

HOUSE VELDREN — Lords of Nightspike
Founded: c. 905 AF (descendants of the laborers Nion I reassigned to his naval yards) Seat: Veldren Tower, Nightspike Sigil: A red hammer on a black field Words: "We Built This"
Nightspike's ruling family began as slaves. The original Veldrens were among the workers Nion I forced to build his naval shipyards on the island — laborers who toiled under imperial overseers for generations. When the empire fell, the workers' descendants — now skilled shipwrights with intimate knowledge of the yards they'd been enslaved to build — seized the city and claimed it as their own. The Veldren name was adopted by the family that led the seizure: a shipwright foreman whose original name was lost when the imperial records burned.
This origin story defines Nightspike's culture. The city is proudly working-class, reflexively suspicious of inherited privilege, and possessed of a chip on its collective shoulder the size of a warship. The other Horns ports look down on Nightspike (Westhorn considers it a backwater, Brinehold considers it a rival). Nightspike looks back up with a glare.
Current Members:
Lord Aran Veldren (age 47) — Head of house. A former shipwright who still has sawdust in his hair and calluses on his palms despite twenty years as a lord. Aran governs Nightspike the way his ancestors ran their work-crews: directly, loudly, and with minimal tolerance for excuses. He walks the dockyards daily, knows his workers by name, and settles disputes with a combination of rough justice and genuine empathy that has made him the most popular lord in the Horns among common folk and the most irritating among aristocrats.
Nightspike never fully recovered from the Great Fire of 1075 AF. Forty percent of the city's shipbuilding capacity was destroyed, and the population dropped by a quarter. Aran has spent his lordship rebuilding — new drydocks, new warehouses, a new breakwater — but the city remains smaller and poorer than Westhorn, and the suspicion that Brinehold agents set the fire has never been proven or forgotten.
Ymma Veldren (age 44) — Aran's wife. Born in the Red Coast — a copper merchant's daughter who came to Nightspike on a trading vessel, met Aran on the docks, and stayed. She is the only Red Coast woman in the Horns' aristocracy, and her presence has introduced elements of Red Coast culture to Nightspike: spiced food, copper jewelry, and a henna tradition that has become fashionable among the city's younger women. She is also Nightspike's most effective trade negotiator — her Red Coast connections give the city commercial access that the other ports lack.
Jorik Veldren (age 22) — Aran's son and heir. A natural sailor who has been agitating for Nightspike to stop rebuilding and start projecting: build a war fleet, challenge Westhorn's naval dominance, break Morvayn's bridge monopoly by force. His father considers him reckless. Jorik considers his father cautious to the point of cowardice. The tension between them is the city's primary political dynamic — the dockyards workers are split between the father's gradualism and the son's ambition.
Old Thessa Veldren (age 73) — Aran's mother, called "the Iron Grandmother" by the city. A former labor organizer who led the dockworkers' guild for thirty years before her son inherited the lordship. She is retired but not inactive — she holds court in a dockside tavern called The Bent Nail, where she dispenses advice, adjudicates petty disputes, and terrifies young nobles with stories of the old days when the Veldrens still had calluses. She is the moral authority of the house: when Aran is uncertain, he visits his mother. When Jorik is reckless, his grandmother calls him to The Bent Nail and reduces him to silence with a look.

THE LAMPKEEPERS OF SKOGRIM
Founded: c. 910 AF (by Brother Erland) Seat: The Lamphall, Skogrim Sigil: A golden flame on a dark green field Words: "Light the Way"
Skogrim is not like the other Horns cities. It is a forest city — built at the point where the dense woodland corridor connecting the Horns to the mainland opens into the peninsula. Where the three port cities face the sea, Skogrim faces the trees. Its economy is not maritime but terrestrial: timber, charcoal, forest products (resin, tar, pitch, medicinal herbs), and — most profitably — the toll revenue from controlling the only viable land route between the Horns and the rest of the continent.
The Lampkeepers are an Alonite religious order that functions as Skogrim's government, military, and highway patrol. They maintain the signal fires and way-stations that mark the forest road, provide armed escort for caravans (for a fee), and collect the tolls that fund the entire operation. They are technically monks. They are practically a merchant-military corporation with a prayer schedule.
Current Members:
Prior Wulfric (age 55) — Head of the Lampkeepers. A former Heartlands soldier who joined the order after losing his family to a roadside banditry incident — he arrived at a Lampkeeper way-station with a dead wife on the back of his horse and a toddler in his arms, and never left. He has been Prior for eighteen years and has turned the order from a loose collection of road-wardens into a disciplined, well-funded organization that controls the forest corridor with an efficiency that imperial road engineers would recognize and respect.
Wulfric is devout in the Alonite tradition — faith through action, not contemplation. He prays by maintaining roads. He worships by keeping travelers alive. He has killed seven bandits personally in the line of duty and considers each death a failure of the system he was supposed to maintain. He does not sleep well. He rises before dawn to walk the nearest section of road, checking waystone markers and lamp-oil levels. His toddler grew up to be Sera Wulfric (age 22), now a Lampkeeper herself, who patrols the deepest section of the forest corridor — the Thornway — where the trees grow thick enough to block the sky and the last reported Grave-Stag sighting (1287 AF) keeps the order's beast-watch protocols active.
Brother Aldis (age 35) — The order's quartermaster and de facto treasurer. A former Brinehold merchant's clerk who joined the Lampkeepers after embezzling from his employer and needing somewhere to disappear. The order took him without questions (the Alonites believe in redemption through service), and his financial skills have proven invaluable — he manages the toll revenues, the supply chain for the way-stations, and the complex accounting that keeps the Lampkeepers solvent. He is also skimming approximately 3% of the toll revenue into a personal account. He considers this a reasonable administrative fee. Brother Wulfric suspects but has not confirmed. The day he does will be dramatic.

IV. THE PILOTS' GUILD
Founded: 935 AF (by the Pilots' Charter) Seat: Pilot's Rock — a small island in the straits between Westhorn and Brinehold Sigil: A compass rose on a white field
The Pilots' Guild is the Horns' most powerful independent institution. Its members are the specialist navigators who guide ships through the treacherous coastal straits — shallow waters, shifting sandbars, tidal races, and submerged rocks that can rip the bottom out of a merchant vessel in seconds. Without a licensed pilot, no ship enters or leaves the Horns' harbors safely. The Guild charges for this service, and the fees are non-negotiable.
The Guild operates from Pilot's Rock — a windswept lump of basalt in the middle of the straits, topped with a lighthouse, a barracks, and the Guild's administrative offices. Pilots live on the Rock for six-month rotations, training, maintaining their charts, and waiting for the signal flags that summon them to incoming vessels. The Guild is fiercely neutral — it serves all ports equally, charges all ports equally, and refuses all political entanglement. A pilot who shows favoritism toward any port is expelled. A port that attempts to coerce the Guild is blockaded.
Guildmaster Revka Thorne (age 50) — Head of the Guild. A woman of mixed Horns-Red Coast ancestry (copper skin, sea-grey eyes, hair braided with bone beads), Revka rose through the Guild's ranks by being the best navigator on the straits — she can read a tidal chart the way a musician reads a score, instinctively, in real time. She has guided over a thousand vessels through the straits without losing one. Her authority within the Guild is absolute, earned through competence rather than politics. She lives on Pilot's Rock year-round, leaving the island perhaps twice a year for Council meetings in Westhorn. She considers the mainland a distraction.
Her secret: Revka has noticed something in the straits that she cannot explain. The currents have been shifting — subtly, over the past year, in patterns that don't match her thirty years of charts. The water temperature has risen by a fraction of a degree. The fish stocks have changed — species appearing that she hasn't seen since her grandmother's logs. She has mentioned this to no one. She is watching the water. The water is doing something new.

V. NOTABLE UNAFFILIATED CHARACTERS (THE HORNS)
Mag "Half-Mast" Korren — Brinehold's most notorious smuggler. Runs a crew of fifteen out of a warehouse on the Brinehold waterfront, moving untaxed goods between the Horns, the Teeth, and the Red Coast. Lost his left arm to a cargo-crane accident at age twenty; the stump earned him his nickname. He is cheerful, generous with his crew, and completely amoral about his cargo — he'll move anything for anyone if the price is right. He has been arrested four times and convicted zero times. The Dalgaard family uses his network for off-book shipments. Elgar Dalgaard would deny this under oath.
Sister Efa of the Salt Chapel — Ashanite hospitaller, runs Brinehold's only free clinic from a converted salt warehouse. She treats dockworkers, sailors, prostitutes, and anyone else the city's respectable physicians won't touch. She is sixty, arthritic, and in possession of a bedside manner that combines genuine compassion with a vocabulary that would make a longshoreman blush. She has delivered over two thousand babies. She is the most trusted person in Brinehold's working-class districts.
Tomasz "the Fin" Berget — Nightspike's premier tavern-keeper. Runs The Bent Nail (with Old Thessa Veldren's blessing), the closest thing the city has to a civic institution. The Bent Nail serves beer, fish stew, and unfiltered truth — Tomasz allows no pretension in his establishment. Nobles who enter are served the same beer in the same chipped tankards as dockworkers. The walls are covered with carved initials, old ship's pennants, and a stuffed foamcoil serpent (almost certainly fake) that Tomasz claims was caught in the harbor in 1289 AF.
Heska Vonn — Skogrim. An elderly herb-woman who lives alone in a cottage three miles off the forest road, deep enough in the Thornway that casual travelers never find her. She is the Horns' last acknowledged folk healer — a woman with "the Old Touch," whose poultices work slightly better than they should and whose diagnoses are slightly more accurate than any mundane observation could produce. She is mildly echo-sensitive, though she would describe it as "listening to what the plants want to say." The Lampkeepers tolerate her because she treats their injured patrols for free. The Ashanite clergy tolerate her because her methods align with Asha's teachings on natural healing. The local farmers rely on her because she is the only person within fifty miles who can tell them whether a sick cow will live or die — and she is always right.
She is seventy-three, lives with a one-eyed cat named Grudge, and has recently begun experiencing something she has never felt before: a faint warmth in the forest floor, a hum beneath the roots, as if the Thornway's ancient trees are waking up from a very long sleep. She does not know about the Giants. She does not know about the Eldra-Veil breach. She only knows that the forest feels different this year, and the feeling is getting stronger.


NIONIA — Cities, Landmarks, and Legends

VELLIUM — The White City
Major Landmarks
The Great Dome — The converted Senate chamber, now the cathedral of the Pure Way. The largest enclosed space on the continent: a hemisphere of white Cassian marble supported by a skeleton of iron ribs forged in the Marchia Ferrus. The interior is 200 feet across and 140 feet from floor to oculus — the open eye at the dome's apex that admits a single column of daylight that tracks across the marble floor as the Elder Sun moves. Nion I built the original Senate chamber. It burned. The Republic rebuilt it, grander. Jous converted it, whitewashing the frescoed walls (which depicted scenes from the Republic's history — debates, elections, naval victories) under a coat of lime plaster so thick that the paintings are preserved beneath it, invisible but intact. The floor is a single mosaic of white and pale blue tesserae depicting Loreth's sun radiating outward from the center — the spot where the speaker's podium once stood and where Jous now conducts the Pure Way's daily cantus. The acoustics are extraordinary: a whisper at the center can be heard clearly at the walls. Jous exploits this during sermons, beginning in a voice so soft the congregation holds its breath, then building to a resonance that fills the dome like a struck bell. The effect is deliberate and devastatingly effective.
Below the Dome, inaccessible to the public, the old Senate's archive chambers still exist — a network of vaulted rooms where the Republic's records were stored. Jous sealed them after the conquest. Lucretia Marcellus's preserved archive is a copy; the originals are down there, in the dark, under the God-King's feet.
The Pale House — Domus Lux headquarters. Formerly the Palazzo Severan, a patrician mansion built by Domus Navarrus in the Republican era as a city residence for visiting admirals. The architecture is beautiful — columned entrance, frescoed atrium, a garden courtyard with a marble fountain depicting dolphins — and the beauty makes what happens inside worse. The upper floors are administrative: offices, records, the filing system that Brother Cael maintains with such frightening precision. The ground floor is the public face: a receiving hall where citizens can report heresies, request dispensations, or petition for the release of detained relatives. The basement is the interrogation level. The cells are small, windowless, and acoustically isolated — screams do not carry to the street. The fountain in the courtyard runs constantly. Some say this is to mask the sounds from below. Others say the Pale House has always had a fountain. Both are true.
The Pallion Steps — A monumental staircase of 217 white marble steps connecting the harbor district to the Dome Quarter. Built during the Republican era as a civic processional route — newly elected consuls would climb the Steps to take their oaths at the Senate. Under the Pure Way, the Steps serve the same function with different content: Jous descends them during high holy days, white-robed and barefoot, attended by Domus Lux guards and Pure Way choirs singing the cantus. The Steps are wide enough for thirty people to walk abreast. At the midpoint, a landing opens onto a terrace with a panoramic view of the harbor. Vendors sell prayer-tokens and sanctified water at the base. Pickpockets work the crowds on festival days. The Inquisitors patrol the middle sections. The Steps are simultaneously sacred space, public thoroughfare, and commerce zone — a vertical cross-section of Nionian society.
The Anchor & Chain — The dockyards' most famous tavern. Three stories of salt-rotted timber, leaning at an angle that suggests imminent collapse and has suggested it for the last eighty years. The ground floor is the public room: long tables, cheap beer, fish stew that tastes better than it looks, and a permanent haze of Ashleaf smoke. The second floor is the performance space — a low-ceilinged room where lamento singers perform after midnight, the songs getting more honest as the hour gets later and the Inquisitors' shift changes make the streets less watched. The third floor is officially storage. Actually, it is the meeting room of the Dock Council — an informal body of dockworkers' representatives who manage labor disputes, negotiate wages, and occasionally coordinate work stoppages when the regime pushes too hard. The Council has no legal status. It has no need of legal status. It has the docks.
The tavern's name refers to an anchor and chain mounted above the door — supposedly salvaged from the wreck of the first Navarrus warship burned in the Battle of Port Severan. Whether this is true is debated. The anchor is real.
The Convent of the Veil — On the northeastern coast of the island, three miles from Vellium proper, a compound of whitewashed buildings surrounded by a grove of ancient olive trees. This is where the Sisters of the Veil lived, where Jous was born, and where his mythology begins. The convent is now a shrine — Jous declared it "the Birthplace of the Way" and opened it to pilgrims, displacing the remaining Sisters (those who hadn't fled during the civil war) to a smaller building on the grounds. The original chapel, where Sister Sera allegedly gave virgin birth, has been preserved as a devotional space: white walls, a simple altar, and a painted icon of Sera holding the infant Jous that is the Pure Way's most sacred image.
The grove around the convent is the oldest stand of trees on the island — olive trees whose trunks are gnarled into shapes that look deliberate, as if something shaped them. The trees are echo-dense. This is the environment that nurtured Jous's sensitivity — and anyone with even latent echo-perception, spending time in the grove, feels something: a warmth, a pressure, a sense of the air being thicker than it should be. Pilgrims report "spiritual experiences" in the grove — visions, emotional breakthroughs, a feeling of being watched by something benevolent. The Pure Way attributes these to divine presence. The mechanism is simpler and stranger.
The Forum of Tears — A public plaza in the Terraces where the civil war's worst atrocity occurred. During the final days of fighting, a company of Domus Marcellus household guards, retreating from a Ferronus advance, barricaded themselves in the Forum with approximately three hundred civilians as human shields. The Ferronus mercenaries attacked anyway. The guards, the mercenaries, and roughly two hundred civilians died in the fighting. The Forum was renamed afterward — it had been the Forum of Copia, dedicated to the old goddess of wealth. The new name stuck. The plaza is now a memorial: the cobblestones are stained with a dark discoloration that residents say is blood that won't wash out (it is actually iron-oxide leaching from the stone, but the legend is more powerful than the chemistry). Families of the dead leave small offerings — flowers, candles, written prayers — along the Forum's edges. The Pure Way has attempted to repurpose the space as a "Triumph of Faith" monument. The flowers keep appearing.
The Scriptorium Ruin — The burned shell of the Order of the Quill's Nionian library, in the Colonnade district. Jous's followers torched it during the civil war, destroying the island's largest collection of secular scholarship, republican histories, and pre-imperial texts. The building has not been rebuilt. It stands open to the sky, its walls blackened, its interior choked with weeds growing in the ash of ten thousand books. The Pure Way considers the ruin a symbol of the old corruption's destruction. The Palladian Circle considers it a wound. Valeria Marcellus visits it monthly, alone, and sits in the ruined reading room for an hour without speaking. She tells no one what she does there. She is memorizing the layout, wall by wall, shelf by shelf, so that if the collection is ever reconstructed, she can tell the builders where everything was.
The Whale-Oil Works — On the harbor's northern edge, a complex of rendering vats, storage tanks, and the long stone piers where the whale-ships unload their catch. Nionia's whale-oil industry provides fuel for the city's street lamps (Jous's decree that darkness breeds sin has tripled demand) and the pitch-based fire-weapons that the navy is stockpiling for the mainland invasion. The Works stink. The smell — rendered fat, salt blood, the chemical tang of processing — drifts across the harbor on certain winds and reaches the Dome Quarter, where the priests burn incense to mask it. The workers are the hardest men on the island: whale-hunters, flensers, renderers, barrel-makers. They are Jous's least enthusiastic subjects. The whales, they say, are harder to kill than gods, and they've killed plenty of whales.

PORT SEVERAN — The Navy's Fist
A military harbor twenty miles down the coast from Vellium. Originally built by Nion I as the empire's naval headquarters, Port Severan has been a base for warships for over thirteen centuries. The town exists to serve the fleet: drydocks, ropewalk, sail-lofts, armories, barracks, and the massive stone breakwater — the Emperor's Arm — that extends half a mile into the sea, creating a sheltered anchorage for the largest warships afloat.
The Navarrus Citadel — The Navarrus family seat. A fortress built into the cliff above the harbor, its seaward wall dropping a hundred feet straight into the water. The Citadel has been the Navarrus home for centuries and now serves as both family residence and naval command center. Jous's Domus Lux observers occupy the eastern tower — the Watchtower — from which they can see every ship in the harbor and every light in the Citadel's windows. Admiral Varro Navarrus lives in the western wing and keeps his shutters closed.
The Fire-Ship Yards — A new facility, built since the civil war, where the navy is developing and producing the fire-weapons that won the Battle of Port Severan. The yards are restricted: surrounded by a stone wall, guarded by Domus Lux sentries, and operated by a hand-picked crew of Ferronus-loyal workers. The weapons themselves are a closely guarded secret — clay pots filled with a mixture of whale-oil, sulfur, and pulverized volcanic glass that ignites on impact and burns on water. The mixture is called Pyre-Seed by the workers. It is unreliable (one in five pots fails to ignite), dangerous to manufacture (three workers have died in production accidents), and devastatingly effective when it works. The mainland has no equivalent.
The Graveyard of Masts — A shallow bay south of Port Severan where the wrecks of the civil war's naval battles still protrude from the water at low tide. Six Navarrus warships, two Ferronus transports, and an unknown number of smaller vessels lie in the silt, their masts jutting at angles like a drowned forest. The navy has salvaged what it could — ironwork, anchors, intact hull sections — but the deeper wrecks remain. Fishermen avoid the area. They say the currents around the wrecks are unpredictable, which is true. They also say they hear sounds from beneath the water on still nights — creaking timber, the snap of canvas, once a voice calling a name. This is probably the wind channeling through the submerged rigging. Probably.

MARCHIA FERRUS — The Iron Hills
Not a city but a district — a scatter of mining camps, smelting works, and supply depots spread across the mountainous interior of the island. The Marchia Ferrus is where Nionia's iron comes from, and increasingly where its marble comes from as well (the Cassian quarries extend into the lower hills). The landscape is scarred and industrial: open pit mines, spoil heaps, roads rutted by ore-carts, and the permanent grey haze of smelting smoke that hangs in the valleys on windless days.
Ferronus Hall — Ferron's fortress-manor, built on a ridge directly above the iron vein that made his fortune. The architecture is aggressive: thick walls of unfinished basalt, iron-barred windows, a gatehouse designed to withstand a siege. Ferron built it to be ugly. He succeeded. The interior is surprisingly comfortable — Orla's influence — with good furniture, warm fires, and a cellar stocked with mainland wines that Ferron drinks with the deliberate pleasure of a man who grew up on mine-water. The Hall's most notable feature is the Assay Room — a laboratory where Ferronus metallurgists test ore samples, develop alloys, and conduct the experiments that Matteo Ferronus has quietly redirected toward his own interests. The Room's walls are lined with shelves of mineral samples from every mine on the island, organized by a system that only Matteo understands.
The Cassian Quarries — The marble pits. Stepped cuts in the white hillsides, some over two hundred feet deep, where crews of quarrymen have been extracting building stone for over a millennium. The quarries are beautiful in an industrial way — the exposed marble faces catch the sunlight and glow, and the geometry of the cuts has an accidental elegance that architects admire. The deepest quarry — the White Throat — is the one where Petronius Cassian's crews found the luminous vein. The sealed section is marked with a simple "Unstable — No Entry" sign. Cassia Cassian ignores it.

NIONIAN LEGENDS
The Burning Senator — The most famous ghost story on the island. The legend holds that during the Great Pyre — when Nion I locked the Senate inside and burned them alive — one senator refused to die. He burned but kept walking, a figure of living flame, and staggered out through the door that Nion's soldiers had barred. He walked through the streets of the city, setting fire to nothing, speaking to no one, leaving footprints of melted stone. He walked to the harbor, stepped into the water, and sank. The footprints, the legend claims, are still visible on certain streets in the Colonnade — smooth depressions in the cobblestones that fill with rainwater and never dry. (Several streets in the Colonnade do have smooth depressions. They are almost certainly natural wear patterns. Locals disagree.)
The Seventh Bell — The old Senate chamber had six bronze bells mounted in its pediment, rung to announce sessions, votes, and emergencies. When the chamber burned, the bells melted. When the Republic rebuilt the chamber, six new bells were cast. But workers reported hearing a seventh bell — faint, high-pitched, ringing at dawn on the anniversary of the Pyre. The sound has been reported for over a thousand years. It continued after Jous converted the building into the Great Dome Cathedral. It was heard most recently three months ago. No source has ever been identified. Jous's clergy say it is "the voice of divine approval." Older residents say it is "the dead asking to be let in."
The Senator's Daughter — A folk tale. During the Republic's final decades, a senator's daughter fell in love with a dockworker. Her father forbade the match — the class difference was insurmountable. She agreed to an arranged marriage with a patrician she despised. On her wedding night, she walked to the Pallion Steps, climbed to the top, and threw herself off. Her body was never found. Since then, the legend says, a woman in a white dress is seen on the Steps during fog — standing at the terrace, looking toward the harbor. Sailors consider her an omen: seeing the woman means fair weather (she is looking for her lover's ship). Not seeing her means nothing. The legend is almost certainly fabricated — it follows a pattern common to every port city on the continent. But the image of the white woman on the white steps is powerful enough that Jous's Pure Way has been unable to suppress it, despite several attempts.
Nion's Jaw — A geological feature off the island's northern coast: a natural arch of volcanic rock, roughly fifty feet high, that frames the view of the open sea. The arch is shaped like an open mouth — two pillars of dark basalt with a curved lintel connecting them. Local legend: when Nion I sailed north to conquer the mainland, the island itself opened its mouth to let him pass, and the Jaw is what remains. Fishermen use the Jaw as a navigation marker. Children dare each other to swim through it. One child drowns approximately every decade. The parents blame the currents. The children blame "the Teeth inside" — a submerged ridge of sharp rock just beneath the waterline that the arch conceals. The metaphor is too perfect for a world-builder to ignore.
The Last Griffin of Nionia — A widespread but unverified legend. The Forum Griffin — the heraldic beast of the old Republic — was supposedly based on a real creature that nested in the Marchia Ferrus mountains during the pre-imperial era. Mosaic depictions survive in several Colonnade mansions, showing a winged, leonine creature with an eagle's head perched on the Senate's pediment. The last living Forum Griffin was allegedly killed by Nion I's soldiers during the Great Pyre — the creature attacked the troops who were barring the Senate doors, and was brought down by javelin-fire. Its skull was mounted above the Senate entrance as a trophy. The skull disappeared during the Republic's reconstruction. Some say it was destroyed. Some say it was taken by the Marcelli and hidden. Old Aemilia Torr's naval history includes a footnote: "The Griffin's skull is in the deep archive. I have seen it. It is not what you expect."

THE HORNS — Cities, Landmarks, and Legends

WESTHORN — The Lantern City
Major Landmarks
Garrun Keep — The Clifftop fortress. Built on the highest point of Westhorn's harbor cliff, the Keep has been the seat of House Garrun for over a millennium. The original structure was a pre-imperial chieftain's hill-fort — a ring of dry-stone walls around a timber hall. Over centuries, the fort became a castle: stone walls, towers, a great hall with a hammer-beam roof, and the famous Garrun Lantern — a signal tower rising from the Keep's highest point, topped with a fire-basket large enough to be visible twenty miles out to sea. The Lantern has been lit every night since the Garrun family took power. It has never been extinguished — not during storms, not during sieges, not during the Nightspike Fire when half the peninsula was illuminated by burning dockyards. The maintenance of the Lantern is the Garrun heir's ceremonial duty. Taryn Garrun climbs the tower every evening at dusk to check the fuel, trim the wick, and ensure the light burns through the night. His dead brother Eddan did it before him. The climb takes fourteen minutes. Taryn times it. He always takes exactly fourteen minutes.
The Harbormaster's Tower — Seven stories of grey stone at the harbor entrance, functioning as port authority, signal station, customs office, and the most visible symbol of Westhorn's commercial power. Every ship that enters the harbor is logged in the Tower's records — a continuous ledger that stretches back to 923 AF, the oldest commercial record on the continent. The current Harbormaster, Gorran Felk (age 61), has held the position for twenty-five years and knows the name, tonnage, captain, and usual cargo of every vessel that regularly trades in Westhorn waters. He is also hard of hearing, stubborn, and in the habit of pretending not to understand foreign accents to gain negotiating time. He is universally described as "impossible" and "irreplaceable" in the same sentence.
The Knotmaker's Street — A narrow, cobbled lane in Westhorn's Midtown, lined with the workshops of the city's knotmakers — artisans who produce the sailor's knot-jewelry that is the Horns' most distinctive cultural product. The knots are not merely decorative; each pattern carries specific meaning (rank, experience, home port, marital status, number of successful voyages), and the knotmakers who produce them are trained in a guild tradition that takes seven years to master. The finest knot-work — the Master's Chain, a single cord twisted into a continuous pattern representing an entire career — can sell for the price of a small boat. Knotmaker's Street is also, not coincidentally, the best place in Westhorn to hear gossip: the artisans work with their doors open, their clients sit and talk while waiting, and the accumulated intelligence of a thousand dockside conversations filters through the workshops like coffee through a cloth.
The Regatta Grounds — A stretch of open water outside the harbor where Westhorn hosts its annual sailing races. The Regatta is the city's defining social event: two weeks of competitive racing in classes ranging from single-handed dinghies to full-crewed cutters, accompanied by onshore festivals, tavern competitions, and the kind of inter-port trash-talk that occasionally requires magistrate intervention. The Regatta has been held every year since 971 AF. Eddan Garrun won the cutter class three years running before his death. His trophy shelf in Lord Harlan's study includes a fourth cup — posthumously awarded, carved by the Knotmakers' Guild, with the inscription "The sea keeps what it takes, and gives nothing back." Harlan has never read the inscription aloud.
The Storm Wall — Westhorn's seaward fortification: a massive stone breakwater, fifty feet high and fifteen feet thick, that shields the harbor from the open ocean's worst weather. Built in sections over five centuries, the Storm Wall is a patchwork of construction styles — imperial basalt at the base, Republican limestone in the middle, Age of Faith granite at the top — and it has been breached, repaired, and reinforced so many times that local stonemasons can read its history like a geological cross-section. The Wall's landward face is covered with carved graffiti: names, dates, ships, declarations of love, obscene commentary on rival ports. Some carvings are centuries old. The oldest readable inscription, dated approximately 950 AF, reads: "HROLF WAS HERE. BRINEHOLD EATS BARNACLES." Some traditions endure.
The Drowned Chapel — A Lovist chapel in the harbor district, built at such a low elevation that it floods during the highest tides. The chapel — dedicated to Alon, patron of service — was constructed in 1034 AF by a Lampkeeper missionary who apparently didn't understand tidal charts. Rather than relocate, the congregation adapted: services are held at low tide, the pews are mounted on stone risers, and the altar is built on a platform three feet above the floor. During flood tides, the chapel fills with seawater to knee-depth, and fish swim between the pews. The congregation considers this a feature rather than a bug — "Alon served all creatures," they say, "even the ones with fins." The chapel's resident priest, Father Erven (age 45), conducts services in hip-waders and has a theological argument prepared for anyone who suggests the chapel should be moved. He has never lost the argument.

BRINEHOLD — The Salt City
Major Landmarks
The Salt Exchange — Brinehold's seat of government and commercial center. A massive stone building on the waterfront, with a trading floor large enough to hold a thousand people and an upper gallery where the Merchant-Captains' Council holds its sessions in full public view. The Exchange was built in 967 AF and has been the heart of Brinehold's commerce ever since: every major trade deal, every shipping contract, every tariff negotiation happens on the floor or in the private rooms that line its corridors. The building smells permanently of salt — the crystalline tang that permeates everything in Brinehold, from the stone to the food to the clothes to the air itself. Newcomers find it overwhelming. Residents stop noticing after a week and then find other cities smell wrong.
The Exchange's most famous feature is the Tide Clock — a massive mechanical device mounted on the building's seaward wall, powered by the tidal flow through a channel cut in the foundation. The clock doesn't tell time; it tells the tide. Its single hand points to the current tidal state (flood, ebb, slack, high, low), and its mechanism produces a low, rhythmic clunking that Brinehold residents use as a background pulse — they can tell the state of the tide without looking at the water, just by listening to the building breathe.
The Evaporation Terraces — Brinehold's salt works. A series of shallow stone pools stepped down the cliff face south of the city, where seawater is channeled and left to evaporate in the (rare) sun, leaving behind salt crystals that are scraped, sorted, and packed in the Dalgaard warehouses. The terraces cover approximately three acres and produce, in a good year, enough salt to supply the entire Horns peninsula and export to the mainland. In a bad year (too much rain, too little sun), production falls and prices spike, producing the periodic salt crises that have been the Horns' most reliable economic disruption for four centuries. The terraces are beautiful from a distance — the pools reflect the sky in graduated shades of blue and pink as the salt concentration increases — and backbreaking up close. The salt-rakers who work the terraces are the lowest-paid laborers in Brinehold, and their skin cracks and bleeds from the constant salt exposure. Their guild, the Brotherhood of the Rake, is the most militant labor organization in the Horns.
The Barrel Vaults — Brinehold's famous underground storage complex. A network of natural sea-caves beneath the city, expanded and reinforced over centuries into a climate-controlled warehouse system where salted fish, cured meats, and other preserved goods are stored for export. The Vaults extend for roughly a mile beneath the waterfront, with multiple access points from the street level. They are cool, damp, dark, and perpetually haunted by the smell of brine and smoke. The Kemm family operates the largest section; smaller merchants rent space from the city. The Vaults are also, inevitably, the site of Brinehold's smuggling operations — the cave system has passages that open onto hidden coves outside the city walls, and goods that enter through those coves pay no tariff. The Merchant-Captains' Council is aware of this. The Council members who don't use the passages themselves periodically call for enforcement. Enforcement periodically occurs. The smuggling periodically resumes.
The Bone Pier — A long, narrow wharf on Brinehold's eastern waterfront, built of whale-bone and ship timber salvaged from wrecks. The Pier is the traditional gathering place for Brinehold's fishermen — they meet here at dawn to divide the day's fishing grounds, compare catch reports, and settle the minor territorial disputes that are the permanent background noise of any fishing community. The Pier's name is literal: whale ribs, jawbones, and vertebrae are incorporated into the structure's pilings and railings, giving it a skeletal appearance that visitors find unsettling and locals find homey. The largest bone — a whale jawbone over thirty feet long, mounted as an arch at the Pier's entrance — is called Old Gape and is Brinehold's most recognizable landmark after the Salt Exchange. Tradition: a fisherman beginning their first voyage walks through Old Gape and spits into the water. A fisherman on their last voyage walks through and doesn't.

NIGHTSPIKE — The Reborn City
Major Landmarks
Veldren Tower — The ruling family's seat. Not a castle but a tower — a single, massive column of dark basalt rising from the harbor's edge, built (according to the Veldrens) by the original freed laborers using the same techniques they'd been forced to employ building imperial warships. The Tower is deliberately stark: no ornamentation, no courtyard gardens, no comfortable receiving rooms. The interior is functional — living quarters, a council chamber, an armory, and the Veldren archive (a collection of dockyard records, labor contracts, and the handwritten account of the original seizure of the city that the family treats as a founding scripture). The Tower's rooftop platform serves as Nightspike's signal station and, on clear nights, as Old Thessa Veldren's preferred location for telling stories to her grandchildren. She says the wind carries better up there. She means the stories, not the air.
The Char — The section of Nightspike's dockyard that burned in the Great Fire of 1075 AF and was never rebuilt. The ruins have been cleared of debris but not replaced: a stretch of blackened stone foundations, empty drydock basins filled with stagnant rainwater, and the stumps of crane-posts that once served the city's largest shipbuilding facilities. The Char is Nightspike's open wound — a permanent reminder of the catastrophe that reduced the city from a serious rival to Westhorn to a recovering underdog. Lord Aran has proposed rebuilding the Char multiple times. The funds are never sufficient. His son Jorik has proposed converting it into a naval weapons-testing facility. His grandmother has proposed leaving it as it is: "Scars heal. Memory doesn't. We need the memory."
The Char is also, by default, Nightspike's public gathering space — large enough for the entire city to assemble, flat enough for market stalls, and emotionally charged enough that speeches delivered there carry an extra weight. Political rallies, labor protests, and the annual Fire Remembrance (a candlelight vigil for the 2,000 dead) all happen on the Char's scorched ground.
The Bent Nail — Old Thessa's tavern. Already described in the house profiles, but worth noting architecturally: the building is a former ship-chandlery, still cluttered with nautical hardware (coils of rope, barrel hoops, iron fittings) that serves as both decoration and, in at least one memorable bar fight, improvised weaponry. The tavern's sign is a literal bent nail — a twelve-inch iron spike, hammered crooked, mounted above the door. The story: when the Veldrens seized the city, the last imperial overseer was nailed to his office door by the dockworkers. The nail bent under the force of the blow. Someone pried it out and kept it. Whether the nail above The Bent Nail is actually the original is debated. Old Thessa says it is. No one argues with Old Thessa.
The Sheerwater Cliffs — The natural feature that defines Nightspike's geography: a vertical wall of dark basalt rising 200 feet from the waterline, against which the city is built and into which much of it is carved. The cliffs are riddled with natural caves and hand-cut chambers that serve as homes, workshops, and storage for the city's poorer residents. The highest caves — accessible only by rope-ladders and carved foot-holds — are called the Nests and are home to Nightspike's most independent-minded residents: people who value privacy more than comfort and who can climb a vertical stone face with a sack of provisions on their back. The Nests have their own informal governance, their own water-collection system (carved channels that catch rainwater and funnel it to cisterns), and their own legend: the Cliff Witch of Nightspike, a healer who supposedly lived in the highest Nest during the imperial era and who could cure any illness by touching the patient with hands that had been washed in seawater and dried in wind. No one knows her name. Her cave is identifiable by the smooth, palm-shaped depressions worn into the stone at its entrance — worn by visitors touching the rock for luck. The depressions are very old. People still touch them.

SKOGRIM — The Forest Gate
Major Landmarks
The Lamphall — Lampkeeper headquarters and Skogrim's seat of government. Built of Thornway timber — massive, dark hardwood beams, some over three feet in diameter — the Lamphall is the largest wooden building in the Horns and one of the largest on the continent. It serves as meeting hall, chapel, barracks, toll office, and the operational center for the forest road network. The interior is dominated by a single great room, 120 feet long and 40 feet wide, with a ceiling of exposed beam-work so high that the upper reaches are permanently in shadow. The room is lit by a double row of iron braziers running down its center — the "lamp-row" that gives the building its name — and by the narrow windows cut into the eastern wall, which admit the morning light in slanting columns that make the dust motes look like floating sparks.
The Lamphall's most striking feature is the Map Wall — the entire western wall, covered floor to ceiling with a painted map of the forest road network. The map is updated annually by the Lampkeepers' cartographers and shows every waystone, every way-station, every bridge, every known hazard, and the current patrol routes. It is the most accurate map of the Horns' interior in existence. It is also, incidentally, a work of art — the cartographers, working in the Lampkeeper tradition of combining function with devotion, have rendered the forest in such detail that individual tree species are distinguishable, and the terrain features are shaded with a depth that makes the wall seem like a window into the actual landscape.
The Thornway — The forest road itself. Not a single road but a corridor: a cleared path roughly thirty feet wide, cut through the ancient forest that connects the Horns peninsula to the mainland. The Thornway runs for approximately forty miles through the densest woodland on the continent — trees 150 feet tall, canopy so thick that the road is in perpetual twilight, undergrowth so dense on either side that stepping off the path means disappearing from view within ten paces. The Lampkeepers maintain the road with religious dedication: paving stones are replaced, drainage ditches are cleared, fallen trees are removed, and the signal-lamp posts — iron standards topped with covered lanterns, spaced every quarter-mile — are checked and refueled daily.
Every five miles along the Thornway, a way-station provides shelter: a stone-and-timber building with a fire-pit, a water supply, stored firewood, basic medical supplies, and a Lampkeeper guard post. The way-stations are the closest thing the Thornway has to civilization, and they have developed their own micro-culture: way-station keepers are Lampkeepers who have chosen (or been assigned) solitary postings, and they tend toward the contemplative, the eccentric, or the antisocial. Travelers who stay overnight at a way-station are guaranteed safety, food, and the company of someone who may not have spoken to another human being in a week and who therefore talks with either desperate enthusiasm or unsettling reserve.
The Green Gate — The formal entrance to the Thornway on the Horns side: a stone arch built into the forest's edge, carved with Alonite devotional inscriptions and the Lampkeeper motto ("Light the Way"). The arch is flanked by two ancient oaks — the largest in the Horns — whose branches have grown together over the road, forming a natural vault. The effect is deliberate: entering the Thornway through the Green Gate feels like entering a cathedral. The light changes. The sound changes. The air smells different — pine resin, wet earth, the musty sweetness of decomposing leaves. Travelers who have made the crossing dozens of times still report a moment of adjustment at the Gate: a breath held, a sense of threshold, a recognition that the forest is not just a place but a presence.

LEGENDS OF THE HORNS
The Pilot Who Sailed Home — The oldest legend in the Horns. A pilot of the straits, lost in fog, sailed through a channel he'd never seen before and emerged in a harbor he didn't recognize. The buildings were made of living coral. The people spoke a language like breaking waves. They fed him fish that tasted of silver and wine that tasted of nothing. He stayed for what felt like a night. When he sailed back through the channel, twenty years had passed. His wife had remarried. His children didn't know him. He returned to the channel, but it was gone. He spent the rest of his life sailing the straits, looking for it. The other pilots say his ghost still sails — a lantern light moving through the fog on nights when the currents run wrong.
The Nightspike Fire-Bride — A folk tale from Nightspike. During the Great Fire of 1075 AF, a young dockworker named Asa tried to rescue his betrothed from a burning warehouse. He entered the fire. He didn't come out. Neither did she. But workers on the opposite dock reported seeing two figures walking through the fire — hand in hand, unhurried, untouched by the flames — and stepping off the burning pier into the water. They sank together. Neither body was recovered. On the anniversary of the Fire, Nightspike's fishing families launch small wooden boats, lit with candles, into the harbor — one for Asa, one for his unnamed bride. The boats burn to the waterline and sink. The ritual has been performed every year since 1076 AF.
The Brinehold Leviathan — A sea-monster legend. Brinehold fishermen have reported, for centuries, a massive creature in the deep waters beyond the straits — something too large for a whale, too slow for a shark, producing a wake that can be seen from the cliff-tops. Descriptions vary: a serpent, a turtle the size of a ship, a shape that defies comparison. Sightings are rare (perhaps one every decade) and always at a distance. No one has ever seen the creature up close. No one has ever found a carcass. The Ember Watch investigated in 1156 AF and found nothing. The Magos logged the reports and filed them under "Unverified Megafauna (Marine)." The fishermen don't care about verification. They leave offerings at the harbor mouth — small fish, coins, cups of mead poured into the water — and they do not fish in the deep water on days when the sea is unnaturally calm. "When the Leviathan sleeps," they say, "let it sleep."
The Seventh Tree of Skogrim — A Lampkeeper legend. The Thornway passes through six named groves — stands of particularly ancient trees that the Lampkeepers use as navigational markers and which have, over centuries, acquired individual personalities in the keepers' lore. The First Tree is the great oak at the Green Gate. The Sixth Tree is a lightning-struck elm at the mainland exit. The Seventh Tree, according to legend, does not exist on any map. It appears only to Lampkeepers who are lost — truly lost, not merely disoriented — and it marks the way home. The tree is described differently by everyone who claims to have seen it: an oak with white bark, a pine that smells of honey, a willow growing from a stone. The one constant is the light: a glow from within the wood, as if the tree is burning without being consumed. Prior Wulfric does not discuss the Seventh Tree publicly. In private, to his daughter Sera, he has admitted: "I saw it once. The night your mother died on the road. It showed me where to go." He has refused to elaborate.
The Rope That Binds — A universal Horns legend about the origin of the knotwork tradition. A fisherman's wife, waiting for her husband to return from a voyage, began tying knots in a length of cord — one knot for each day he was gone. The voyage lasted a year. By the time he returned, the cord was so dense with knots that it had become a solid rope. She presented it to him at the dock. He wept. He wore it around his wrist for the rest of his life. When he died, the rope was buried with him. When the grave was opened a century later (during a church expansion), the rope was intact — the only thing that had not rotted. The knots were still tight. The lesson, Horns folk say, is that love is the only thing that does not decay. The practical lesson is that good rope-work outlasts everything, which is why you should buy your knots from a certified knotmaker and not the cheap imitations sold at the market.
The Lampkeeper's Oath — Not exactly a legend but a tradition so old it has the weight of one. Every Lampkeeper, upon taking their vows, is led alone into the Thornway at night without a lamp. They walk in total darkness for one mile. At the end of the mile, a single lantern is lit — by the Prior, waiting in the dark. The new Lampkeeper must walk toward the light. The mile is not dangerous (the road is cleared and patrolled), but the darkness is real, and the forest at night is not silent — it creaks, rustles, breathes, and occasionally produces sounds that no natural explanation comfortably covers. The point of the oath is not courage. It is trust: trust that the light will be there, that someone is waiting, that the darkness is temporary. Every Lampkeeper remembers their oath-walk. Most of them lie about how scared they were.


NIONIA & THE HORNS — Minor Settlements, Geography, and Natural Landmarks
NOTE FOR FUTURE REGIONS: The complete regional build follows a three-prompt pattern:
Houses & Characters — Major/minor families, hierarchy, current members with traits, political dynamics
Major Cities & Legends — Landmarks, monuments, districts, local myths and folk tales
Gazetteer — Minor towns, villages, rivers, natural features, religious outposts, trade stops — the connective tissue
This document is Prompt 3. Repeat this pattern for each remaining region pair.

NIONIA — The Gazetteer

Rivers & Waterways
The Albara — Nionia's only significant river. Runs from the Marchia Ferrus highlands south-southwest to the sea, emptying into a silted estuary six miles east of Vellium. Shallow, fast-moving, unnavigable for anything larger than a flat-bottomed punt. Used primarily for freshwater supply, irrigation of the southern olive groves, and washing marble dust out of the quarry workers' lungs. The Albara turns chalky white downstream of the quarries — locals call the lower stretch "the Milk." Fish can't survive in it below the third quarry outflow. Above the quarries, the Albara is clear, cold, and home to a brown trout the locals call stone-trout — bony, bland, eaten only by miners who can't afford anything better.
The Veiled Springs — A cluster of freshwater springs on the island's northeastern coast, near the Convent of the Veil. The springs emerge from a basalt cliff face into a series of natural pools before draining into the sea. The water is unusually warm (geothermal origin, though the Nionians attribute it to divine blessing) and faintly mineral-tasting. The Sisters of the Veil used the springs for bathing and ritual purification. Under the Pure Way, the springs have been declared sacred — pilgrims bathe in them for spiritual cleansing, paying a fee to the shrine custodians. The water is genuinely good for skin conditions. The echo-density of the surrounding basalt may have something to do with it.
The Quarry Channels — Not natural waterways but an engineered drainage network: stone-lined channels that carry rainwater and groundwater away from the marble quarries to prevent flooding. The channels converge into the Albara at several points, contributing the chalky runoff that gives the lower river its color. The channel-keepers — a small guild of hydraulic engineers maintained by the Cassian family — are among the most quietly essential workers on the island.

Minor Settlements — The Coast
Ostara (pop. ~2,000) — Fishing village on the southern coast, twelve miles from Vellium. Known for its octopus. Ostaran octopus, grilled over olive-wood coals with lemon and sea salt, is considered the finest preparation of the dish on the island and is served at patrician tables in Vellium at prices that would make the fishermen who catch it weep. The village is built into a rocky cove with a single stone jetty. An Ashanite hospice — the House of the Settling Wave — provides care for elderly fishermen and their widows. The hospice's resident healer, Brother Demos (age 55), is an Ashanite monk who has been quietly refusing to implement Pure Way liturgical changes for three years. No one has reported him because Ostara is too small for the Inquisitors to bother with and Brother Demos delivers their babies.
Kephira (pop. ~1,500) — Coastal town on the western shore, built around a natural harbor used primarily by the island's smaller fishing boats. Known for two things: its lighthouse (a pre-imperial stone tower maintained by a family called the Pharoi who have been lighthouse keepers for eleven generations — the current keeper, Old Tessa Pharos (age 70), can recite the name of every keeper back to the founding) and its black sand beach, which is volcanic basalt eroded to fine grit. The black sand is exported in small quantities as a scouring agent for marble polishing. Children collect colored pebbles from the beach and sell them to tourists as "god-stones."
Pallonis (pop. ~800) — A hamlet on the northeastern coast, three miles from the Convent. Exists primarily to service the pilgrim traffic to the Veil shrine: two inns, a stable, a prayer-token vendor, and a bakery that produces the small, round, white-glazed biscuits called veil-cakes that pilgrims buy as devotional souvenirs. The baker, Marta Kolos (age 40), inherited the recipe from her grandmother and guards it with lethal seriousness. Knockoff veil-cakes produced in Vellium are, she will tell anyone who listens, "an insult to the Mother's milk."
Antheon (pop. ~3,000) — The island's second port, on the northern coast. A working harbor without Vellium's grandeur — salt-stained docks, a fish market, a rope-walk, and the island's only tannery (leather-working is prohibited inside Vellium's walls due to the smell). Antheon's reputation: tough, unglamorous, and resentful of Vellium's cultural dominance. The town produces the island's best salt-cod and the island's worst wine. An Alonite chapterhouse — the Brothers of the Northern Watch — maintains a small garrison here, ostensibly to patrol for pirates, actually to keep an eye on smuggling between Antheon and the Horns. The chapterhouse's captain, Ser Ilias (age 38), is a devout Alonite who refuses to join the Pure Way and has not been forced to — his usefulness as an anti-smuggling officer has so far outweighed his doctrinal inconvenience.
Kelossa (pop. ~600) — Tiny fishing hamlet on the island's southern tip. Famous for nothing except its remoteness and its annual Squid Festival — a three-day celebration of the autumn squid run during which the entire population gets drunk on squid-ink wine (yes, it's real; no, it doesn't taste good; yes, it stains your teeth black for a week). The village's only structure of note is a crumbling Alonite waystation — a remnant of the pre-war pilgrim road network — now used as a goat shelter.

Minor Settlements — The Interior
Ferronus Camp (pop. ~5,000, fluctuating) — The largest settlement in the Marchia Ferrus. Not a town but a sprawling mining camp: barracks, tool sheds, an assay office, a company store (operated by Ferronus agents at prices the miners consider extortionate), a drinking hall, and a Bonekeepers' ossuary for the workers killed in mining accidents (~20 per year). The camp has no permanent architecture — everything is timber-and-canvas, designed to be disassembled and moved when a mine is exhausted. The camp moves roughly every fifteen years. Its current location has been occupied for eight years. The miners call it "home" without irony and decorate their barracks with carved graffiti, pinned drawings, and the small personal altars that Lovist orthodoxy encourages and the Pure Way has not yet bothered to regulate in a place this remote.
Quarrytown (pop. ~3,500) — The Cassian family's company town, adjacent to the White Throat quarry. More permanent than Ferronus Camp: stone houses (built from quarry off-cuts), a marketplace, a school run by the Order of the Quill (one of the few Quill operations still functioning on the island, tolerated because Quarrytown is too far from Vellium for the Pure Way to have established an alternative), and a Harvest Bell granary that supplies the quarry workers' food. The town's social center is the Chiseler's Rest — a tavern built entirely of marble scrap, the walls glittering with embedded crystal inclusions that catch lamplight like stars. The proprietor, Demos "Chisel" Raxa (age 50), is a retired quarryman who lost three fingers to a splitting accident and turned to tavern-keeping. He serves a homebrew called Stone Bitter that tastes of minerals and regret.
Greenholm (pop. ~1,200) — An agricultural village in the island's central valley, the most fertile land on Nionia. Olive groves and vineyards. Quiet, prosperous, boring in the way that successful farms are boring. The village's claim to distinction: it produces the olive oil used in the Great Dome's eternal lamps. This contract — held by the same family, the Dassos, for over two hundred years — is worth more than the entire village's other output combined. The current contract-holder, Yiannis Dassos (age 44), treats his olive trees with the devotion of a father for his children and tests every pressing personally, rejecting any batch that doesn't meet his standard. He has rejected oil supplied to three consecutive governments without political consequence because everyone needs lamp oil and no one wants to argue with a man who can tell the difference between last week's pressing and today's by smell alone.
Petravale (pop. ~900) — A hill village in the Marchia Ferrus foothills, too high for olives, too rocky for grain. Known for its goats (the Petravale Black, a hardy breed with a reputation for stubbornness that mirrors its owners'), its cheese (a hard, sharp variety cured in volcanic caves), and its folk tradition of stone-singing — a practice in which elderly women sit against sun-warmed boulders and hum, producing harmonics that the stone allegedly amplifies and returns. Whether this is echo-sensitivity, acoustic resonance, or the self-fulfilling expectations of a community that has been doing it for centuries is unclear. The Venic Path maintained a small circle in Petravale until the Pure Way's ban; the circle dissolved publicly but its members still sit against the stones. They just don't talk about it.
Irongate (pop. ~2,000) — A fortified waypoint on the Quarry Road, halfway between Vellium and the Marchia Ferrus. Exists to provide security, rest, and resupply for the ore caravans. The town's defining structure is its namesake: an iron portcullis spanning the road, operated by a garrison of Alonite road-wardens (a small chapter of the Brothers of the Open Road, the only mainland order with a permanent Nionian presence). The gate is closed at sunset and opened at dawn. Between those hours, the road is dark. Bandits have been a problem on the Quarry Road for as long as the road has existed — not organized gangs but desperate individuals, usually deserters from the civil war or miners who've been fired from the camps. The Brothers deal with them efficiently and without drama. Their captain, Sister Nola (age 32), is a former Sangrean mercenary who took Alonite vows after a religious experience she refuses to describe. She is the only person on the island who carries a Sangrean-forged sword and an Alonite prayer-book with equal conviction.

Natural Features
The Marchia Ferrus Range — The island's mountainous spine. Not high by continental standards (the tallest peak, Mount Pallax, reaches ~4,000 feet) but rugged, heavily mineralized, and the source of virtually all of Nionia's non-agricultural wealth. Iron, marble, basalt, and trace deposits of copper and tin. The mountains are bare above the treeline — scrubby grass, exposed rock, wind — and forested below with the drought-resistant Ferrovan Iron-Olive that clings to the quarry edges. The eastern slopes catch the morning sun and are warmer; the western slopes face the prevailing wind and are battered.
The Throat — A narrow sea passage between Nionia and the mainland, roughly seven miles wide at its narrowest point. Strong tidal currents, unpredictable winds, and a shallow bar of submerged rock make the Throat hazardous for large vessels. Smaller boats cross regularly — fishermen, messengers, smugglers. The imperial navy maintained a chain across the Throat during certain periods; the anchor-points are still visible as rusted iron bolts driven into the cliffs on both sides. The Pure Way has stationed patrol vessels at the Throat's narrowest point, theoretically to intercept smugglers, actually to control who leaves the island.
Nion's Jaw — The volcanic sea-arch on the northern coast (described in legends above).
The Ash Flats — A barren plateau in the Marchia Ferrus interior, approximately two square miles of flat volcanic rock covered in a thin layer of ash and pumice. Nothing grows. Nothing lives there except wind. The Flats are used by the Ferronus mining operations as a waste dump — slag, spoil, and the chemical residue of smelting operations are piled on the edges. At dawn, when the rising sun hits the ash and the slag heaps glow with residual heat, the Flats look like a vision of the world after everything alive has been removed. Miners avoid it. Matteo Ferronus conducts some of his experiments there because no one will bother him.
The Corsair's Teeth — A line of sharp, half-submerged rock spurs extending from the island's western cape into the open sea. Navigation hazard. Three recorded wrecks in the last century. Named for a pre-imperial pirate captain — Kassander the Lame — who allegedly used the rocks as a trap, luring merchant ships into the shallows with false signal fires. Kassander's cave — a sea-cave accessible only at low tide — is a popular dare for Antheon's teenagers.
The Sister Pools — Two circular freshwater pools in the highlands above Greenholm, fed by underground springs, connected by a narrow channel. The larger pool is warm (geothermal); the smaller is cold (spring-fed). Local tradition: couples who swim together in both pools — warm first, then cold — will stay together for life. The tradition predates Loveism, probably predates the Republic, and has survived every religious and political change by the simple mechanism of being romantic enough that no authority has bothered to ban it. An Ashanite shrine — a carved stone basin with Vena's moon-symbol — sits between the pools. Offerings of flowers and small coins accumulate in the basin. A Bonekeepers' volunteer clears them monthly.

THE HORNS — The Gazetteer

Rivers & Waterways
The Skogrun — The Horns' only significant river. Runs from the interior highlands through the Thornway forest, emerging into a broad, marshy delta near Skogrim before draining into the sea through a network of channels too shallow and tangled for navigation. The Skogrun is the Thornway's drainage system — it carries the forest's runoff and, according to Lampkeeper patrols, occasionally carries stranger things: logs that haven't rotted despite floating for miles, fish species that don't match any known freshwater catalog, and once (reported by Sera Wulfric, 1306 AF) a smell "like honey and hot iron" that persisted for an hour and then vanished. The Skogrun's upper reaches, deep in the forest, have never been fully mapped. The Lampkeepers patrol the road, not the river.
The Strait of Knives — The primary navigation channel between Westhorn and Brinehold, named for the submerged rock formations that slice through the tidal flow like blades. The Strait is navigable only with a licensed Pilots' Guild navigator — unlicensed attempts average a 30% loss rate. The tidal race through the narrowest section produces standing waves up to six feet high during spring tides, and the currents shift with a complexity that defies simple charting. The Guild's pilots learn the Strait the way musicians learn an instrument: through years of practice, constant study, and an intimate, almost physical relationship with the water.
The Bone Channel — A secondary passage between Brinehold and the open sea, running through a gap in the underwater reef that protects the harbor. Narrower and shallower than the main approach, the Bone Channel is used by smaller vessels and, not coincidentally, by smugglers who want to avoid the Harbormaster's Tower. Named for the whale bones embedded in the reef — the remains of a whale-hunting station that operated on the reef's surface during the imperial era, now submerged by centuries of tidal erosion.
The Galewater — The open stretch of ocean between Northwind (the nearest Teeth island) and the Horns peninsula. Roughly forty miles of water notorious for sudden squalls, freak waves, and currents that can push a ship miles off course in hours. Crossing the Galewater is a two-day voyage in good weather and a significant gamble in bad. Ships that make the crossing carry Pilots' Guild charts, which are updated annually and are the most valuable navigational documents in the Horns.

Minor Settlements — Westhorn's Hinterland
Saltmere (pop. ~1,200) — A village three miles inland from Westhorn, built around a freshwater mere (small lake) that supplies the city's drinking water via a gravity-fed aqueduct. The village's economy is split between water management (the aqueduct keepers are a hereditary guild, the Merefolk, who maintain the pipes, filters, and cisterns with fanatical dedication) and sheep farming. Saltmere wool — coarse, oily, water-resistant — is the raw material for the heavy knit sweaters that are the Horns' signature garment. The village pub, The Wet Ewe, serves a lamb stew that Westhorn merchants make the trek inland specifically to eat.
Craghaven (pop. ~800) — A clifftop hamlet north of Westhorn, overlooking a cove where the tide exposes a shelf of fossil-rich limestone. Known for its fossils: ammonites, trilobites, and the occasional complete fish skeleton, which the locals extract with practiced skill and sell to collectors, scholars, and the occasional Magos agent who visits every few years to purchase specimens for the Isle's natural history collection. The hamlet's most famous son: Rolfe Cragg (deceased, 1245 AF), a fisherman who discovered a fossil so large and strange that the Magos sent a team to examine it. The team's report is classified. The fossil was removed to the Isle. Rolfe was paid handsomely and drank himself to death within three years. His descendants, the Cragg family, still run the fossil-hunting business and still refuse to discuss what Rolfe found.
Windhollow (pop. ~500) — The Horns' most exposed settlement: a scatter of stone cottages on a treeless headland north of Westhorn, battered by wind 300 days a year. The inhabitants are shepherds and seabird-egg collectors — people who climb vertical cliff faces with rope and iron pegs to harvest gull and gannet eggs from nesting ledges. The eggs are a delicacy in Westhorn (richer and more pungent than chicken eggs, with a faintly marine aftertaste). Windhollow's children learn to climb before they learn to read. The village has no tavern, no inn, no chapel — services are conducted by a visiting Lampkeeper who rides out from Skogrim once a month. The wind is so constant that the village's dogs have learned to walk leaning into it.
Tarrock (pop. ~1,000) — A fishing village on Westhorn's southern coast, specializing in crab and lobster. Known for the annual Crab Feast — a two-day gluttony festival held after the autumn crab haul, during which the entire village eats crustaceans until physically unable to continue. The Feast draws visitors from Westhorn and even Brinehold (who attend despite the inter-port rivalry because the crab is genuinely exceptional). Tarrock's other distinction: it has the Horns' only oyster beds, cultivated in the sheltered cove behind the village's breakwater. The oysters are small, briny, and consumed raw with a squeeze of the sour citrus that grows in the village's single, stubborn lemon tree — a Sangrean import that somehow survives the Horns' climate through sheer obstinacy and the fact that the tree is planted against a south-facing stone wall that retains the day's heat.

Minor Settlements — Brinehold's Territory
Rakkholm (pop. ~1,500) — An island settlement on a rocky islet two miles offshore from Brinehold, connected to the mainland by a tidal causeway that is walkable only at low tide. Rakkholm is Brinehold's quarantine station: ships suspected of carrying plague, rot, or foreign pests are directed to Rakkholm's isolated dock, where their cargo and crew are inspected by Brothers of the Still Anchor — a tiny Ashanite sub-order (twelve members) dedicated to disease prevention in port cities. The Brothers maintain a hospital, a fumigation chamber, and the most comprehensive log of maritime diseases on the continent. Their prior, Brother Havald (age 60), has personally identified and quarantined three separate plague outbreaks before they reached the mainland. He is the most important person in the Horns that no one has ever heard of.
Salthearth (pop. ~600) — A hamlet south of Brinehold, built on the cliffs above the evaporation terraces. Home to the salt-rakers and their families. The hamlet has no structures of its own distinction — it is a workers' village, functional and impoverished — but it is the spiritual home of the Brotherhood of the Rake, the salt-workers' guild, which holds its meetings in a converted drying-shed and whose members can be identified by their cracked, salt-white hands and a shared vocabulary of grievance. The Brotherhood has called three work stoppages in the last decade, each one resolved by Dalgaard concessions that were immediately eroded by subsequent policy changes. A fourth stoppage is being discussed. Elgar Dalgaard is aware of this. His response: "Let them stop. The tide doesn't stop. The salt makes itself."
Cormorant Point (pop. ~300) — A tiny fishing settlement on a spit of land jutting into the strait, named for the thousands of cormorants that roost on the rocks offshore. The settlement's sole economic function: supplying fresh fish to Brinehold's market, caught in the shallow waters where the strait meets the open sea. The fishermen of Cormorant Point are the only people in the Horns who routinely encounter Pilots' Guild vessels at close range — the pilots pass the Point on every approach — and they have developed a custom of waving a specific flag pattern (green over white) when a pilot passes, which the pilot acknowledges with a horn blast. The exchange has no practical purpose. It has been happening for over a century. Neither side remembers how it started. Neither side would dream of stopping.
Dunhallow (pop. ~700) — An inland village ten miles from Brinehold, in the scrubby grassland behind the coast. Sheep country. Dunhallow's sheep are the source of the black wool that Brinehold's rope-makers twist into the heavy, tar-impregnated marine rope that is the Horns' most important export after salt and ships. The village is unremarkable except for its chapel — a small Alonite stone building with a bell tower that was, improbably, designed by a Sangrean architect who was shipwrecked on the Horns coast in 1187 AF and who, while waiting for a ship home, designed a chapel for the village that had rescued him. The result is a miniature Sangrean-style building — arched doorway, azulejo-tiled interior, a bell with a tone more musical than anything the Horns has produced before or since — sitting in the middle of a sheep pasture. The architect, one Don Ferrer of Castesol, made it home eventually. The chapel remains, maintained by the village with a pride that borders on worship. They call it the Stranger's Gift.

Minor Settlements — Nightspike's Shore
Ashwick (pop. ~400) — A settlement built on the ruins of a pre-imperial fishing village, three miles south of Nightspike. Named for the ash trees that somehow grow in the thin, salt-sprayed soil of the cliff-edge. The village's specialty: ash-smoked eel, a local delicacy produced by smoking freshwater eels (caught in the Skogrun's delta) over burning ash-wood. The flavor — sweet, woody, faintly mineral — is unique. A small Harvest Bell granary serves the village and the surrounding farmsteads, run by Sister Ingva (age 45), an Ashanite who came from the Heartlands twenty years ago and has assimilated completely into Horns culture while retaining a Heartlands accent and a Heartlands recipe for rye bread that the locals have adopted as if it were their own.
Skarrholm (pop. ~200) — The smallest named settlement in the Horns. A cluster of stone cottages on a rocky islet accessible by rowboat from Nightspike's outer harbor. Skarrholm's residents are net-menders — specialists who repair and maintain the fishing nets used by every vessel in Nightspike's fleet. The work is tedious, poorly paid, and essential. The islanders are insular, intermarried, and possessed of a dialect so thick that mainland Munnish speakers need a translator. They are also the Horns' most reliable weather predictors — generations of observing the sea from a fixed point have given them an empirical forecasting tradition that rivals the Hrundvaal giants' atmospheric sensitivity (though through entirely different mechanisms). When the Skarrholm folk bring their boats to the inner harbor, Nightspike's captains cancel their voyages.
Ironshore (pop. ~1,000) — A settlement at the base of the Sheerwater Cliffs, south of Nightspike, where a shelf of iron-rich rock extends into the sea. The settlement exists because of the rock: the iron ore, though lower-grade than Nionian iron, is accessible by surface mining and provides Nightspike's shipwrights with a local source of nails, fittings, and anchor chain. The mining is done by hand — pick and hammer — by a workforce descended from the same laborers who built Nion I's naval yards. They are aware of the irony. An Alonite forge-chapel — dedicated to Alon-as-Builder — occupies a cave in the cliff face, where a Brothers of the Open Road smith named Brother Torben (age 50) maintains a forge and produces ironwork for the Lampkeepers' road-maintenance operations. He is the best blacksmith in the Horns and the worst conversationalist — he communicates primarily through grunts and the directional pointing of hammers.

Minor Settlements — The Thornway & Skogrim
Waystation One through Six — The Lampkeeper way-stations along the Thornway, spaced at five-mile intervals. Each station has a name, a keeper, and a personality:
Greengate Station (WS1) — Adjacent to the Green Gate. The most visited station, serving as the entry-point toll office and supply depot. Keeper: Brother Amis (age 28), young, enthusiastic, and convinced that every traveler has a fascinating story. He is right about 10% of the time.
Deepshade Station (WS2) — In the densest section of the Thornway, where the canopy blocks most daylight. Keeper: Sister Brenna (age 55), a woman of terrifying competence who has killed a wolf, a boar, and (she claims) a grave-stag calf during her twenty years at the post. The grave-stag claim is unverified. Her station is the cleanest, best-stocked, and most intimidating on the road.
Splitoak Station (WS3) — Named for a massive oak that was struck by lightning and split in half, both halves still alive and growing in opposite directions. Keeper: Brother Voss (age 42), a former Heartlands soldier who took Lampkeeper vows after deserting his lord's army during a campaign he considered unjust. He is quiet, capable, and harboring a guilt that manifests as obsessive road maintenance — his section of the Thornway is the best-paved stretch on the entire route.
Coldspring Station (WS4) — Built near a natural spring that runs year-round at a temperature just above freezing. Keeper: Brother Halm (age 63), the oldest active Lampkeeper, who has served at Coldspring for thirty-one years and has refused every offer of transfer. He knows every tree within a mile of his station by sight and claims to know several by name. Whether this is Alonite devotion, folk eccentricity, or latent echo-sensitivity is an open question.
Ridgetop Station (WS5) — The highest point on the Thornway, where the road crosses a forested ridge with views of the sea on both sides of the peninsula. Keeper: Sister Marga (age 35), a former Nightspike dockworker who joined the Lampkeepers to escape a violent marriage. She patrols her section with a crossbow and a sawed-off boat-hook and has been involved in more bandit confrontations than any other keeper on the route.
Mainland Gate Station (WS6) — The exit point, where the Thornway opens onto the mainland road network. Keeper: Brother Edric (age 48), the most politically aware Lampkeeper, who monitors mainland traveler traffic and compiles informal intelligence reports for Prior Wulfric. He can tell you the current grain price in Vornhold, the latest Argenlord election gossip, and which Heartlands houses are feuding, all from conversations with passing merchants.
Mosshearth (pop. ~600) — The only civilian settlement inside the Thornway proper. A timber village in a natural clearing roughly halfway along the route, home to charcoal-burners, resin-tappers, and the woodsmen who supply Skogrim's timber trade. Mosshearth is technically under Lampkeeper jurisdiction, but in practice it governs itself — the village elder, Grandma Rys (age 74), has been settling disputes, allocating grazing rights, and cuffing misbehaving children for forty years, and the Lampkeepers have the sense to let her. The village's claim to fame: its charcoal, produced from slow-burned Thornway hardwood, is the highest-quality fuel on the peninsula. Westhorn's finest metalworkers will accept no other. Grandma Rys has leverage and knows it.
Heska's Cottage — Not a settlement but a landmark. The herb-woman Heska Vonn's home, three miles off the Thornway on a track that isn't on any map. The cottage is small, stone-built, and surrounded by a garden of medicinal herbs organized in a system that makes sense only to Heska. A carved stone at the track's entrance — unmarked, undecorated, just a standing stone — serves as the only waymarker. Locals who need Heska's services know where to find her. Everyone else walks past the stone without noticing it. This may be intentional. This may be coincidence. Heska isn't saying.

Natural Features — The Horns
The Sheerwater Cliffs — Nightspike's defining geography (described in landmarks above). Extending roughly three miles along the coast, reaching heights of 200+ feet, riddled with caves and hand-cut dwellings.
The Stacks — A line of sea-stacks (detached rock pillars) off Westhorn's northern coast. The Stacks are nesting sites for thousands of seabirds — gannets, kittiwakes, puffins, and the enormous Gale Kestrels that Horns sailors salute as storm-omens. The largest stack, Old Man, rises over a hundred feet from the water and is topped with a natural platform where (legend has it) a hermit once lived for twenty years, fed by fishermen who rowed out to the base and left provisions in a bucket hauled up by rope. The hermit's name is lost. The bucket's rope-groove is still visible in the rock.
The Fog Banks — Not a physical feature but a meteorological one. The Horns' coastal waters are subject to sudden, dense fog — banks of white mist that roll in from the open ocean without warning, reducing visibility to arm's length within minutes. The Fog Banks are the primary reason the Pilots' Guild exists: navigating the straits in fog is suicide without an experienced pilot. The Banks form where warm ocean currents meet the cold water draining from the Thornway's river system, producing a temperature differential that generates condensation. They are most common in autumn and spring. They are always unwelcome. The Horns have a saying: "The fog is the sea's tax on everything you own."
Pilot's Rock — The Pilots' Guild headquarters island (described in house profiles). Worth adding: the Rock is home to a colony of grey seals that have lived on the island's western shore for centuries and are considered unofficial mascots of the Guild. Harming a Pilot's Rock seal is punishable by Guild law (not because the seals are legally protected, but because the Guild makes its own laws on its own rock and the pilots like their seals). The seals, for their part, have learned to associate human presence with discarded fish scraps and show no fear of the pilots whatsoever.
The Thornway Canopy — The forest itself is the Horns' most significant natural feature. Ancient hardwood — oak, beech, elm, and the enormous Span-Elms (whose wood is used for ship timbers and bridge construction) — growing in a density that mainland foresters find almost impossible. The canopy is so thick that the Thornway's road exists in permanent twilight. The forest floor is a carpet of moss, fern, and decomposing leaf-matter so deep that a person stepping off the road sinks to their ankles. The smell is earthy, wet, and faintly sweet — the decomposition of centuries of organic matter producing a fertile humus that, if it were farmland, would be the most productive soil on the continent. It is not farmland. It is the Thornway, and the Lampkeepers will break the hands of anyone who brings an axe within a mile of the road.
Wrecker's Cove — A hidden cove on the Horns' eastern coast, accessible only through a narrow gap in the cliffs. The cove has been used by smugglers for centuries — its concealed entrance makes it invisible from the sea, and its deep-water approach allows even large vessels to anchor close to shore. The Merchant-Captains' Council periodically "discovers" Wrecker's Cove and "clears" it of illegal activity. The cove is operational again within six months. The most recent clearance was 1304 AF. The cove is currently being used by Mag "Half-Mast" Korren's crew to store untaxed goods moving between the Horns and the Teeth. The entrance is marked by a weathered carving on the cliff face — a crude depiction of a hand giving a gesture that, in the Horns, means "mind your own business."
The Bellows — A geological curiosity on the coast between Brinehold and Nightspike: a sea-cave whose entrance narrows to a slit through which incoming waves are forced, producing a deep, rhythmic booming sound audible for a mile inland. The Bellows fires approximately every forty seconds during high-energy wave conditions — a steady, bass-register pulse that Brinehold's eastern neighborhoods use as an ambient clock. The sound varies with wave height: gentle weather produces a soft thump; storm waves produce a concussive blast that rattles windows and sends dogs under tables. Local folklore: the Bellows is the breathing of the Brinehold Leviathan, asleep beneath the cliff. The geological explanation (wave compression in a resonance chamber) is more plausible and significantly less interesting.

SANGREA — Sun, Blood, and Vine (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — The Beautiful War

I. THE REGION AT A GLANCE
Population: ~4,200,000 Capital: Castesol (pop. ~255,000) Other Major Cities: Puerto Luciente (~140,000), Altavista (~125,000), Muroverde (~108,000), Fuenterroja (~106,000) Government: Monarchic in name (House Doravanto), oligarchic in practice. The Lord-Patron system gives each major house absolute authority over its province. The crown arbitrates. Poorly. Economy: Wine, olive oil, sunstone mining, spice trade (coastal), tobacco, tropical fruit, medicinal herbs (jungle border), livestock, and the arms trade that the Sunstone Wars have made permanently profitable Religion: Orthodox Loveism with strong Ashanite and Alonite presence. The Venic Path persists underground, particularly among artists and rural communities. The Crimson Penitents are a common sight on the roads between holy seasons. Provinces: Five recognized provinces — Altasol, Costadoro, Vallesangre, Fuentarossa, Selvaverde

II. THE PARROT NETWORK — Sangrea's Living Post
Before anything else: the parrots.
They are everywhere. That is the first thing a visitor to Sangrea notices after the heat and the color — the birds. Bright green, scarlet-chested, blue-winged, yellow-headed, raucous and profane, perched on every rooftop, every balcony railing, every market awning, every nobleman's shoulder. They scream at dawn. They chatter through midday. They go quiet at dusk and then start again at midnight if something disturbs them. The sound of Sangrea is the sound of parrots.
Most of these are wild or semi-wild — feral populations descended from the Selvaverde jungle's native species, spreading northward over centuries as the region's agriculture created an abundance of fruit and grain that turned every orchard into a parrot buffet. They are pests, companions, alarm systems, and entertainment. Every Sangrean child grows up with a parrot story. Every Sangrean tavern has a resident bird that repeats the most embarrassing things said by last night's drunks.
But the trained parrots — House Carvallo's messenger birds — are something else entirely.
The Carvallo Messenger System
House Carvallo has been breeding and training messenger parrots for roughly three hundred and fifty years. The system began as a Botano family communication tool — the jungle's density made conventional messengers (horseback, foot-runner) unreliable, and the native Selvaverde Scarlet (a large, long-lived parrot species with a vocabulary capacity of several hundred words and an uncanny ability to distinguish between individual human voices) proved trainable for message delivery.
The training takes three years per bird. Carvallo trainers — called loreros — raise chicks from hatching, imprinting them on a home-station (a specific perch, roost, and feeding point at a Carvallo relay house). The birds are trained to fly between their home-station and up to three other relay houses, covering distances of up to sixty miles per flight. They carry messages in two formats:
Vocal messages: The lorero speaks a phrase to the bird, clearly and slowly, repeating it until the bird can reproduce it accurately. The parrot then flies to the destination relay house, where a receiving lorero transcribes the bird's speech. The system is limited by the bird's vocabulary and pronunciation — complex sentences are broken into shorter segments, each carried by a different bird. A message of fifty words might require five parrots, arriving in sequence. The birds are trained to land on the receiving perch in order (first bird on the left perch, second on the middle, and so on), so the segments can be reassembled correctly. Error rate: approximately 5% per segment. For critical messages, each segment is sent twice by two different birds. The redundancy doubles the cost but reduces error to less than 1%.
Written messages: Small, tightly rolled strips of parchment in wax-sealed copper tubes, attached to the bird's leg. Faster (one bird per message), more secure (the message is encrypted in Carvallo ciphers that only Carvallo loreros can read), and used for the most sensitive communications. The copper tubes are reusable and stamped with the Carvallo serpent-and-mortar sigil. Finding a Carvallo message tube that isn't yours is a criminal offense in Sangrea — the penalty ranges from a fine (for commoners) to the loss of a finger (for nobles who should know better).
The Relay Network: Carvallo maintains approximately forty relay houses across Sangrea — at least one in every major town, two in the cities, and a chain of jungle-edge stations connecting the Selvaverde to the interior. Each relay house employs two to four loreros and maintains a flock of thirty to fifty trained birds. The total network: roughly 1,500 active messenger parrots, serviced by approximately 120 loreros. The network is the fastest communication system on the continent — a message from Castesol to Muroverde (approximately 200 miles) can be transmitted in under a day via relay, compared to three days by horseback. The Campaneros' bell network is faster for simple alarm signals but cannot transmit complex messages. The parrots can.
Who uses it: Everyone who can afford it. The service is not free — Carvallo charges per message, with rates scaled by distance, urgency, and encryption level. A simple vocal message between neighboring towns costs a few coppers. An encrypted written dispatch from Castesol to Puerto Luciente costs a silver mark. The two great houses — Solé and Terrarossa — are the network's largest customers, each maintaining permanent contracts for priority service. Carvallo's neutrality is essential to the network's function: if either great house believed Carvallo was reading or delaying their messages, the network would collapse overnight. Carvallo does read the messages. They read all of them. The intelligence this produces is the real source of House Botano's political power — the Matriarch knows everything because Carvallo's loreros know everything.
The wild parrots' role: The feral populations serve an unintentional secondary function. Because parrots repeat what they hear, the wild birds that roost near relay houses, taverns, and market squares pick up fragments of conversation and broadcast them randomly across the region. A parrot screaming "TERRAROSSA MARCHES AT DAWN" from a rooftop in Castesol is probably repeating a drunk's boast, not an intelligence report — but it might not be. The result: Sangrea's air is saturated with ambient information, most of it garbage, some of it gold. The ability to distinguish signal from noise — to hear the real message inside the parrot-chatter — is a valued skill among spymasters. The Solé intelligence service has a specialist, Dona Vela (age 45), whose sole job is monitoring wild parrot speech in Puerto Luciente for fragments of useful intelligence. She keeps a journal of every phrase she collects. Most entries are obscenities. Occasionally, one isn't.

III. THE PROVINCES AND THEIR HOUSES
ALTASOL — The Sun-Baked Plains
The central province. Rolling golden hills, baked dry eight months of the year, dotted with the haciendas and tower-estates that the nobility has been building and burning for four centuries. Castesol sits on the province's highest hill like a crown on a sunburned head. The Doravanto monarchy rules from here — technically rules all of Sangrea from here — and the province's culture is accordingly courtly, theatrical, and exhausting.
House Doravanto — The Crown
Seat: The Alcázar of Castesol (a palace-fortress on the city's summit, rebuilt six times — once after each major Sunstone War, because it keeps getting besieged) Sigil: A golden sun crowned with seven rays on sky blue Words: "We Keep the Peace"
The Doravantos are descendants of the Nionian imperial governor assigned to Sangrea during the occupation. When the empire fell, they stayed, adopted local customs, married local nobility, and gradually transformed from foreign administrators into the region's nominal monarchs. Their authority was always fragile — they held the crown because the two greater houses couldn't agree on which of them should wear it — and by 1308 AF, the fragility has become structural. The Doravanto crown is the prize in the Sunstone Wars. Everyone wants it. No one respects it.
Queen Jasmina Doravanto (age 27) — Placed on the throne as a compromise after the last bloody chapter of the Wars. Intelligent, dignified, and trapped. Her court is infested with Solé agents — the faction called the Dorado Crows — who buy influence, sponsor poets, and commission towers from Los Torrebrava that make the crown's own palace look modest. Jasmina knows she is a puppet. She also knows that the strings are the only thing keeping her alive — without Solé's "support," Terrarossa would march on Castesol within a month. She drinks Botano herbal tea for the chronic insomnia that has plagued her since her coronation. The tea helps. The parrots outside her window, repeating courtiers' whispered conversations in garbled fragments, do not.
Prince Cassian Doravanto (age 19) — Jasmina's brother. Handsome, popular, reckless. He jousts in the Solé-sponsored tournaments, attends their parties, and accepts their gifts with the cheerful obliviousness of a young man who has never been forced to think about who pays for his life. He is being groomed — though he doesn't know it — as a potential replacement for his sister. Solé prefers a grateful, malleable king to a resentful, intelligent queen.
Dowager Lady Anais Doravanto (age 65) — Jasmina's grandmother. A survivor of the last Sunstone War who saw her husband killed, her son forced into a humiliating peace, and her granddaughter crowned as a compromise she considers a slow-motion execution. Anais is confined to her chambers by the grey wheeze — a chronic lung disease that has been slowly suffocating her for a decade — but her mind is intact and her network of informants, built over forty years of courtly survival, is still active. She is Jasmina's only trusted advisor. Their conversations happen at dawn, when the palace is quiet and the parrots haven't started yet.
The Alcázar's Parrots: A flock of semi-tame Scarlets nests in the Alcázar's bell tower. They have been there for at least a century and are considered palace fixtures. They repeat fragments of overheard conversation with the accuracy and timing of comedians. During formal court sessions, the parrots occasionally interrupt proceedings with comments that are either meaningless or devastating depending on what was said in the antechambers that morning. Jasmina has considered having them removed. Anais advised against it: "They say what we can't. Let them talk."

House Solé — The Golden Tide
Seat: The Solé Palazzo, Puerto Luciente (a cliff-top merchant palace with a private harbor, a spice warehouse the size of a cathedral, and the continent's only heated seawater bathing pool) Sigil: A golden kraken seizing a silver ship on deep sea-blue Words: "The Tides Bring Us Gold"
House Solé is new money in the oldest sense — merchants who became magnates who became lords who became kingmakers, all within the span of the post-imperial era. Their wealth comes from the sea: spice imports from Xaria, trade with the Horns and Nionia, and the merchant fleet that is the largest private navy in the region. They control the Costadoro province — the golden coastline — and from Puerto Luciente they project economic power across the entire continent. They don't need the crown. They need the crown to need them.
Lord Valerius Solé (age 37) — Patriarch. Charming, cultured, amoral. Valerius can discuss Ayanite theology, Sangrean wine vintages, and the terms of your assassination with equal eloquence and equal sincerity. He is the architect of the current cold war — the strategy of slow economic strangulation designed to make Terrarossa's vassals switch sides without a single sword being drawn. It is working. He takes no pleasure in cruelty but suffers no inconvenience from it either. He is the most dangerous man in Sangrea and the most pleasant dinner companion.
Lady Lyra Solé (age 45) — Valerius's wife. Eight years his senior, a marriage of alliance that has become, unexpectedly, one of genuine partnership. Lyra runs the household's intelligence operations from her salon — an evening gathering of artists, poets, merchants, and diplomats at the Solé Palazzo that is the most coveted social invitation on the coast. To be invited is to be important. To be uninvited is to be finished. Lyra tracks alliances, feuds, debts, and affairs with a precision that makes Brother Cael of Domus Lux look like an amateur. She maintains a parrot — a blue-and-gold macaw named Fortuna — that sits on a perch beside her salon chair and has been trained to say "How delightful" and "Tell me more" at appropriate intervals. Guests find this charming. They should find it terrifying.
Gaius Solé (age 24) — Heir. Ambitious like his father, lacking his father's subtlety. Known for decadent parties, a stable of prized racehorses, and a temper that has resulted in three duels (all non-fatal, all embarrassing for the other party). He is being groomed for leadership but is not ready. He knows this. The knowledge makes him reckless.
Serena Solé (age 21) — Valerius's daughter. Beautiful, cunning, trained in the arts of social manipulation since childhood. She operates as her father's agent at the Doravanto court in Castesol — attending the queen's functions, befriending the prince, gathering intelligence, and projecting the image of Solé generosity and cultural refinement that greases the family's political machine. She is good at her job. She hates it. The performance of constant charm is exhausting, and she has begun to suspect that the person she performs as is more real than the person she is underneath.
Admiral Lucan Solé (age 42) — Valerius's brother. Commander of the house fleet. A grim, capable sailor who personally oversees the disruption of Terrarossa's trade routes — not through piracy (too crude) but through tariff manipulation, port-access restrictions, and the selective enforcement of maritime regulations that Lucan himself writes and the crown rubber-stamps. He has the sea-weathered look of a man who has spent more of his life on water than on land, and the moral flexibility of a man who has jettisoned conscience as excess cargo.

House Terrarossa — The Old Blood
Seat: Altavista, the high city (a fortress-city built on a ridge overlooking three valleys, its walls incorporating the living rock of the mountainside) Sigil: Crimson grapes on a gnarled vine, on earthen red Words: "The Old Blood Endures"
If Solé is the future, Terrarossa is the past — and they wear it like armor. House Terrarossa traces its lineage to a pre-imperial warlord who first cultivated the great vineyards of the Vallesangre, and every generation since has defined itself against whatever threatens the old order. They are land-wealthy, honor-bound, and possessed of a stubbornness that has kept them fighting the same war for four hundred years. They cannot match Solé's gold. They trade in loyalty and steel — calling in ancient oaths, maintaining the vassal relationships that Solé's money is slowly eroding.
Lord Titus Terrarossa (age 58) — Patriarch. Proud, stubborn, tied to tradition in ways that are simultaneously admirable and suicidal. He sees the current cold war as a temporary and dishonorable state — an interval between the last Sunstone War and the next. He is not wrong. He is preparing accordingly: reinforcing Altavista, drilling his household guard, and sending his son to the vassal houses to tighten bonds that Solé gold is loosening. He drinks his own wine (the Terrarossa Reserva, the finest vintage in Sangrea, which he refuses to sell to Solé buyers even when the price is extravagant) and he prays every evening at the chapel where the Broken Chalice's Terrarossa half is displayed in a glass case. He considers the half-chalice a reminder that peace is always incomplete.
Ser Roric Terrarossa (age 30) — Heir. A warrior of genuine skill and genuinely terrifying temper. Roric has won every tournament he's entered, broken three opponents' arms (two accidentally, one not), and earned a reputation as the best sword in Sangrea. He is also his father's greatest vulnerability — his temper makes him exploitable, and Solé agents have been engineering provocations designed to make Roric do something public and unforgivable. So far, his father's restraining hand has held. So far.
Elara Terrarossa (age 26) — The daughter. Pious, gentle, betrothed to the heir of House Montefior in a match designed to cement the Terrarossa-Montefior military alliance. She accepted the betrothal as a duty. She does not love Ser Hector Montefior. She loves the convent library where she spent her girlhood and the Ashanite sisters who taught her to read. She writes poetry — quiet, careful, technically excellent — that she shares with no one.
Marius Terrarossa (age 55) — Titus's brother. A brilliant strategist broken by loss. His wife and son died in the last Sunstone War — the son at the Battle of Fuente Bridge, the wife of grief three months later. Marius has been prone since then to episodes of the red grief — a Sangrean term for a depressive state so severe that the sufferer cannot move, speak, or eat, sometimes for weeks. Between episodes, he is the sharpest military mind in the region. During them, he is a ghost occupying a chair in Altavista's war room, staring at maps of campaigns he can no longer finish.

House Botano — The Jungle Matriarchs
Seat: Muroverde (the gateway city, half-stone half-jungle, where buildings are laced with vine and the streets smell of medicinal herbs and rot) Sigil: A green serpent coiled around a silver mortar and pestle, on jungle-green Words: "Every Leaf Has Its Purpose"
House Botano rules the Selvaverde — the jungle border province where Sangrea's culture dissolves into the Xarian frontier. They are matriarchal (the eldest daughter inherits, always), their power is botanical (they know every plant in the jungle — which heals, which kills, which does both), and their neutrality in the Sunstone Wars is the fulcrum on which the entire conflict balances. Both great houses need Botano's medicinal supplies. Both great houses need Carvallo's messenger network. Neither dares to alienate them.
Matriarch Elena Botano (age 65) — A wise, weary woman and one of the most gifted healers on the continent. She trained at the Ashanite hospice in Faithir before returning to Muroverde to assume the matriarchy. She is trapped in a poisoner's dilemma: the Orden de Cascabella — the poison masters' guild that operates in her city — sells their products to both great houses, and Elena is forced to treat the victims of poisons she knows were purchased in her own market square. She has considered expelling the Cascabella. She has calculated the consequences. The Cascabella would relocate to Xarian territory, beyond her influence, and continue selling. At least in Muroverde, she can monitor them.
Joric Botano (age 35) — Elena's son and heir-apparent (the matriarchy passes to the eldest daughter, but Elena's daughters died young; Joric is a compromise heir whose accession will break tradition and create a succession crisis). He is a skilled herbalist who lacks his mother's moral conviction. He has been meeting with Cascabella representatives privately. Whether he is trying to regulate them, bribe them, or join them is unclear even to Elena.
Calla Botano (age 18) — Elena's niece, daughter of her deceased younger sister. The matriarchy's true heir by tradition — Elena's sister's daughter takes precedence over Elena's son. Calla is being raised in the Muroverde convent, educated in both herbalism and Ashanite theology, and kept carefully out of Joric's sight. Elena has not announced Calla's claim. The announcement, when it comes, will split the house.

House Carvallo — The Parrot-Lords
Seat: The Carvallo Aviary, Muroverde (a compound of breeding halls, training pens, and the relay headquarters from which the entire messenger network is managed) Sigil: A scarlet parrot on a golden branch, on white Words: "The Message Finds Its Way"
Vassals of Botano but functionally independent — the Carvallos run the messenger network that every power in Sangrea depends on, and that dependency gives them leverage far beyond their nominal status.
Lord-Lorero Tomás Carvallo (age 50) — Head of house and master trainer. A thin, sun-darkened man whose fingers are permanently scarred from parrot bites and whose conversation is regularly interrupted by the birds that perch on his shoulders, head, and arms at all times. Tomás is quiet, observant, and in possession of the most comprehensive intelligence picture in Sangrea — because he reads every message that passes through his network. He shares this intelligence with Elena Botano. He shares selected portions with whoever he chooses. He denies everything.
Rosalia Carvallo (age 28) — Tomás's daughter and the network's chief cipher-master. She designed the current Carvallo encryption system — a substitution cipher that changes keys monthly, based on a botanical codebook that only Carvallo loreros possess. She is the only person in Sangrea who can read every encrypted message in the system. She is also, quietly, one of the most powerful people in the region, and she knows it. She has a parrot named Chisme (gossip) that she's trained to say "I know what you did" in three languages. She uses this at dinner parties.

House Montefior — The River Lords
Seat: Castillo del Río (a fortress commanding the main bridge over the Sangra River in Vallesangre) Sigil: A silver fish leaping from a blue river on green Words: "The River Flows to War"
Terrarossa's most powerful vassals. The Montefiors control the Sangra River — the waterway that irrigates the great vineyards — and their barge-mounted soldiers are Terrarossa's primary military asset. Loyalty: absolute. Ambition: none. The Montefiors want exactly one thing: to serve the old order and fight its enemies.
Lord Rodrigo Montefior (age 48) — A bluff, hearty soldier-lord. Childhood friend of Lord Titus. More comfortable on a horse than in a council chamber. He has six sons, all trained as knights, and he considers each one a weapon pointed at Solé. His wife, Lady Sofia (age 45) — a Terrarossa cousin — manages the household and the river-barge logistics with the efficiency of a quartermaster and the warmth of a brick.
Ser Hector Montefior (age 25) — Eldest son and heir. Betrothed to Elara Terrarossa. He is dutiful, competent, and aware that his betrothed doesn't love him. He has decided that this doesn't matter. He is wrong, but he won't know that until it does.

House Bellacorte — The Cliff Lords
Seat: Bellacorte Castle (a fortress carved into the coastal cliffs north of Puerto Luciente, accessible only by a switchback road that a dozen men could defend against an army) Sigil: A silver falcon on a red cliff, on blue Words: "We Hold the Heights"
Solé's primary military vassal. The Bellacortes are warriors in service to merchants — an arrangement they find philosophically uncomfortable and financially indispensable.
Lord Dario Bellacorte (age 55) — A proud, impoverished aristocrat whose castle is magnificent and whose treasury is empty. He serves Solé because Solé pays his bills. He despises this dependency. He compensates by maintaining the highest martial standards in the region — his household guard is smaller than Terrarossa's but better trained and better equipped (with Solé money).
Isabela Bellacorte (age 23) — Dario's daughter. Fiercer than her father, scornful of the "soft" Solé court, a skilled falconer and archer who hunts in the coastal cliffs with the intensity of someone working out a grudge against the universe. She has no interest in the marriage market. She has considerable interest in the Cascabella's poison catalogue. The combination makes people nervous.

House Cigarral — The Tobacco Lords
Seat: Fuenterroja (the oasis town in the Fuentarossa dry fields) Sigil: Two golden tobacco leaves crossed behind a red clay pipe, on tan Words: "The Best Leaf Finds the Highest Bidder"
The swing house. Cigarral controls the tobacco crop that half the continent is addicted to, and they sell to anyone who pays. Their loyalty is to profit. Their diplomacy is hospitality. Their strategy is duplicity.
Lord Malio Cigarral (age 50) — A shrewd, smiling man who hosts lavish parties for agents of both great houses simultaneously, plying them with tobacco, wine, and carefully calibrated promises. He has six children and is using each as a marriage pawn — one daughter engaged to a Molinaro heir, one son courting a Bellacorte cousin, the others positioned at various minor houses. He is building a web of alliances so complex that attacking any single strand would shake the whole structure. This is deliberate. A spider in its web is hardest to kill.

House Molinaro — The Mill-Owners
Seat: Molinoblanco (a fortified town built around a series of white-plastered water mills on the Fuente River) Sigil: A golden water wheel on brown Words: "The Wheel Turns, the Grain is Milled"
The grain processors. Every sack of flour in central Sangrea passes through a Molinaro mill. This makes them essential and invisible — the most powerful house that no one thinks about until the bread stops coming.
Lord Pio Molinaro (age 60) — A cautious, hardworking man overwhelmed by the political games being played around him. He wants to mill grain, pay his workers, and attend chapel on holy days. The Sunstone Wars keep interrupting. His eldest son is engaged to a Cigarral daughter. He considers this a commercial partnership. Cigarral considers it a leash.

Guilds and Orders
Los Torrebrava — The Tower Builders — A construction guild based in Castesol that builds the competitive towers the nobility uses as status displays. Every new tower is a commission — a Solé-funded spire here, a Terrarossa-sponsored belfry there — and the skyline of Castesol is the physical register of the cold war's balance of power. The guild is technically neutral. Its current master, Maestro Gallo (age 55), accepts commissions from both sides and maintains a secret ledger recording exactly how much each house has spent on vertical ego. The ledger, if published, would be devastating. It stays locked.
Los Navegantes — The Cartographers — Based in Puerto Luciente. Master map-makers who chart Sangrea's sea lanes, coastal geography, and — increasingly — its political landscape. Their maps are the best in the world, and Solé's exclusive access to their intelligence-grade charts gives the house a navigation advantage that translates directly into military power. The guild's master, Cartógrafo Mayor Iñigo (age 62), is an artist and a spy in equal measure. His maps are beautiful. His intelligence reports are more beautiful.
Los Campaneros — The Bell-Founders — Based in Altavista but operating across Sangrea. The bellringers serve as the region's auditory communication network — coded chime patterns that transmit messages across valleys faster than horseback messengers. The system is less versatile than the parrot network (bells can send alarms and simple coded signals, not complex messages) but faster and more reliable in bad weather. The Campaneros are Terrarossa-aligned by tradition and geography, making the bell network a de facto Terrarossa military asset. Their master-founder, Doña Campana (age 70) — real name forgotten, everyone calls her Doña Campana — has been casting bells for fifty years and can tune a bell to a specific note by ear alone. She is deaf in her left ear from the forge. She considers this a reasonable professional expense.
Orden de Cascabella — The Poison Masters — Based in Muroverde. A feared and secretive guild of poisoners whose services are available to anyone with coin. They produce, test, and sell poisons derived from the Selvaverde jungle's vast pharmacopoeia — from subtle slow-acting compounds that mimic natural illness to fast-acting toxins that kill within minutes. The Cascabella maintain a code of professional neutrality — they sell to all parties and guarantee the confidentiality of their clients. Their current master, El Silencio (age unknown, face never seen in public), communicates exclusively through intermediaries and is rumored to be three different people, or no people at all, or a woman, or a Xarian exile. The uncertainty is cultivated. Fear is the Cascabella's best marketing.

IV. CASTESOL — The Golden City
The City
Sangrea's capital sits on a high, flat-topped hill in the center of the Altasol plain — a city of golden sandstone, tiled roofs, and the competitive towers that make its skyline look like a mouth full of crooked teeth. The Alcázar (the royal palace-fortress) crowns the summit. Below it, the city descends in concentric rings: the Court Quarter (noble mansions, guild halls, the Ayanite courthouse), the Market Ring (shops, taverns, the Great Souk where everything from spices to slaves is traded), and the Worker's Hem (tenements, workshops, the slaughterhouses and tanneries that aristocratic noses prefer to keep downhill).
The Alcázar — Six times rebuilt, always grand, always slightly shabby in the way of buildings that are more symbol than structure. The current incarnation is a Moorish-influenced palace-fortress: arched courtyards, tiled fountains, geometric azulejo covering every surface, and the throne room where Jasmina holds court under a dome painted with a sun-map of Sangrea that was commissioned by a Doravanto king three centuries ago and has never been updated. The parrot flock in the bell tower adds its commentary to every state function.
The Tower Forest — Castesol's most distinctive visual feature. Over two hundred private towers, built by noble and merchant families over four centuries of competitive construction, rising from the Court Quarter like a petrified forest. Some are functional (bell towers, watchtowers, grain-drying towers). Most are vanity projects — the tallest, thinnest, most elaborately decorated towers their builders could afford, commissioned from Los Torrebrava as displays of wealth and political allegiance. The tallest tower — the Torre del Sol, commissioned by House Solé, 180 feet high, capped with a golden sunburst that catches the morning light and blinds anyone looking east — was built specifically to be twelve feet taller than the Terrarossa-sponsored Torre de la Sangre next to it. The Terrarossa tower's architect responded by adding a wrought-iron weather vane that extends the height by another six feet. The dispute continues.
The Great Souk — Castesol's market. A labyrinth of covered arcades, open plazas, and narrow alleys where every commodity in Sangrea (and much of the continent) can be purchased. The Souk is organized by trade: the Spice Alley (Solé-controlled imports), the Vine Quarter (Terrarossa wines), the Smoke Market (Cigarral tobacco), the Green Stalls (Botano herbs and medicines), and the Shadow Market — a section that technically doesn't exist, located behind the legitimate stalls, where Cascabella products, forged documents, and information are traded in whispers. The Souk's parrots are legendary: generations of birds have learned the vendors' sales pitches and repeat them at random, creating a cacophony of "FRESH PEPPERS THREE FOR A COPPER" and "FINEST TERRAROSSA RESERVA" that echoes through the arcades and drives newcomers to distraction.
The Festival Grounds — A flat expanse below the Alcázar's walls where the Festival of the Red Grape is held every autumn. The Grounds are empty most of the year — a dusty field used for livestock auctions and military drilling. During Festival, they transform into a city-within-a-city: pavilions, stages, a bullring, wine tents, food stalls, a parade route, and the enormous bonfire at the Grounds' center around which the opening-night copla competition takes place. The Festival draws 30,000 visitors over seven days. The Grounds' capacity is 15,000. The overflow camps in the fields surrounding the city, creating a temporary shantytown that has its own economy, its own disputes, and its own parrot population.
The Broken Chalice Chapel — An Ashanite chapel in the Court Quarter where the Terrarossa half of the Peace of the Broken Chalice is displayed (the Solé half is in a private shrine in Puerto Luciente). The chapel is small, plain, and the most heavily guarded building in Castesol after the Alcázar — the Chalice half is a sacred relic, and its theft or destruction would be an act of war. Pilgrims visit the chapel to pray for peace. Soldiers visit to pray for its absence.

V. PUERTO LUCIENTE — The Shining Port
Sangrea's second city and its economic engine. Built on a curving bay where the Costadoro cliffs drop to sea level, Puerto Luciente is everything Castesol pretends to be — rich, cosmopolitan, alive — without the political paralysis that makes the capital feel like a beautiful cage.
The Solé Palazzo — The family's compound. Not a single building but a complex: the main residence (a cliff-top villa with panoramic bay views), the spice warehouses (stone vaults the size of cathedrals, climate-controlled by sea-breeze ventilation), the private harbor (six deep-water berths, guarded by Bellacorte marines), and the heated seawater bathing pool that Lyra Solé uses for her salon gatherings. The pool is tiled in gold and deep blue. The parrots that roost in the surrounding palm trees have been trained by a Carvallo lorero on Lyra's payroll to greet arriving guests by name. The effect is simultaneously charming and deeply unsettling.
The Spice Docks — Puerto Luciente's commercial heart. A mile of waterfront lined with warehouses, chandleries, trading offices, and the customs house where every imported cargo is inspected, taxed, and recorded by the Navegantes guild. The air is extraordinary — a layered perfume of cinnamon, cardamom, clove, pepper, vanilla, and the salt-rot of the harbor, mixed with the coal-smoke of the smithies and the fish-stink of the market. A person standing on the Spice Docks with their eyes closed can identify where they are by smell alone. A parrot can identify it from a mile away. They circle the docks in screaming flocks, diving for spilled grain and discarded fish-heads.
Los Navegantes' Hall — The cartographers' guild headquarters. A stone building on the harbor hill, its interior walls covered with the guild's master maps — hand-painted charts of every coastline, sea lane, current, and depth-sounding from the Horns to the Teeth. The maps are works of art: color-coded, precisely scaled, annotated in the Navegantes' own shorthand. They are also state secrets. Non-guild members may view the public maps (displayed in the entrance hall). The intelligence-grade charts (in the upper floors) are accessible only to Navegantes members and their Solé patrons.

VI. ALTAVISTA — The High City
Terrarossa's fortress-capital. Built on a ridge 2,000 feet above the Vallesangre floor, Altavista commands three valleys and is visible from every vineyard in the province. The city is fortified: thick walls of red-brown sandstone, battlements, gate-towers, and a keep — the Sangre Torre — that rises from the ridge's highest point like a fist raised at the sky. The city has been besieged four times in the Sunstone Wars. It has never fallen.
The Great Cellars — Altavista's most famous feature. The city sits on top of a network of natural caves that the Terrarossa family has converted into the largest wine-aging facility in Sangrea. The cellars extend for miles beneath the city, their temperature and humidity perfectly stable year-round, producing aging conditions that cannot be replicated elsewhere. The Terrarossa Reserva — aged a minimum of fifteen years in the Great Cellars — is considered the finest wine on the continent. It is also, discreetly, a diplomatic weapon: every bottle sent as a gift carries the implicit message "we can afford to give away fifteen-year wine."
The Belltower of San Campaña — The largest bell tower in Sangrea. Twelve bells, tuned to a chromatic scale, operated by Los Campaneros. The tower can transmit messages across the Vallesangre in minutes using the Campaneros' coded chime patterns. It can also, when all twelve bells are rung simultaneously, produce a sound loud enough to be heard thirty miles away — a full-muster alarm that has been sounded three times in history, each time summoning the entire Terrarossa military apparatus to war footing within hours.

VII. MINOR SETTLEMENTS AND GAZETTEER
Viña del Puente (pop. ~2,000) — A vineyard town on the Sangra River between Altavista and Castesol. Famous for its bridge — the Puente de la Sangre — where Don Alvaro Sangreverde hung 800 men in 1108 AF. The bridge has been rebuilt. The town has not forgotten. A memorial wall on the bridge's western approach lists every name — or, where names were lost, simply "hijo del puente" (son of the bridge). A Bonekeepers' ossuary beneath the bridge holds the remains that were recovered from the river. The town produces a wine called Sangre del Puente — a deep red, almost black, that tastes of iron and grief. It is not popular outside the town. Inside, it is served at every funeral.
Bahía Dorada (pop. ~3,000) — A fishing town on the Costadoro south of Puerto Luciente. Known for its pearl divers — women who free-dive in the warm coastal waters to harvest oysters from the bay's shallow reef. The pearls are small, irregularly shaped, and tinted gold by the copper-rich water. They are less valuable than eastern pearls but distinctively Sangrean, and Solé jewelers set them in designs that command premium prices on the mainland. The head diver, Marisela "La Buza" (age 40), can hold her breath for four minutes and has been diving since age eight. She is missing three toes (shark) and one finger (moray eel) and considers both losses acceptable business expenses.
Molinoblanco (pop. ~1,500) — The Molinaro seat. A fortified mill-town on the Fuente River where the water is channeled through a series of white-plastered mills that grind grain for the entire interior. The mills run day and night during harvest season. The sound — a constant, low, rhythmic grinding — is audible for a mile. Workers sleep to it. Visitors cannot.
Ceniza (pop. ~800) — A village in the foothills of the Vallesangre's southern mountains, built on the site of a sunstone quarry that was exhausted two centuries ago. The quarry is now a lake — a flooded pit of startling turquoise (mineral deposits coloring the water) that locals swim in during summer and avoid during winter (the water temperature drops to levels that have killed three incautious swimmers). The village survives on charcoal production and the surprisingly good goat cheese made by a Harvest Bell monastery — the Brothers of the Ash — who maintain a small goat herd on the quarry's terraced slopes.
Fuenterroja (pop. ~6,000) — The Cigarral seat. An oasis town in the dry interior, built around the Red Spring — a natural artesian spring whose water is tinted red by iron-oxide deposits. The spring feeds a system of irrigation channels that support the tobacco fields, pomegranate orchards, and grain farms of the Fuentarossa province. The town's streets are unpaved red earth. The buildings are red adobe. The sunsets, filtered through the dust, are red. Everything in Fuenterroja is red. The smell: dry tobacco leaf, pomegranate blossom, and the mineral tang of iron-water. The Cigarral family's tobacco-drying barns line the town's eastern edge — long, low, ventilated structures where the harvested leaves hang in dense rows, curing in the dry heat. Workers move through the barns in the predawn hours, turning leaves, checking moisture, and feeding the parrots that roost in the rafters and have learned to mimic the quality-assessment calls ("buena hoja," "mala hoja" — good leaf, bad leaf) that the inspectors use.
La Cascada Negra (pop. ~300) — A hamlet in the Selvaverde jungle border, built where a river drops 200 feet over a basalt cliff into a black pool. The waterfall's spray creates a permanent mist that supports a micro-ecosystem of ferns, orchids, and the luminescent fungi that the Botano healers cultivate for medicinal use. The hamlet's economy: gathering jungle products for the Muroverde market. The hamlet's fame: the Black Pool itself, which is sacred in local folk tradition. Offerings are thrown in — flowers, coins, small carved animals — and the pool supposedly returns them weeks later, washed up on the downstream bank, transformed. Coins come back green with copper patina. Flowers come back as seed-pods. Carved animals come back polished smooth. The explanation is probably the pool's unusual mineral chemistry. The locals prefer the other explanation.
Torremira (pop. ~1,200) — A hilltop town halfway between Castesol and Puerto Luciente, known for its watchtower (the oldest surviving Torrebrava construction, built in 987 AF, still manned by a Doravanto-paid garrison that has nothing to watch but the road below). The town produces the best Ashleaf pipe-tobacco outside Cigarral territory — a milder, sweeter blend grown on the hilltop's windward slopes. The tavern, El Loro Borracho (The Drunk Parrot), is famous for its resident macaw, a venerable bird named Don Pedro who is estimated to be over sixty years old, speaks four languages badly, and bites anyone wearing Terrarossa crimson. No one knows why. Don Pedro isn't saying.
Valle de los Huesos (pop. ~400) — A valley in the southern mountains, remote and superstitious. Named for the fossils — enormous bones, too large for any known animal — that erode from the valley's limestone walls during the rainy season. The locals believe the bones belong to "los antiguos" — the ancient ones, giants or gods who walked the world before human memory. A Magos geological survey in 1278 AF identified the bones as belonging to an extinct species of megafauna. The survey team also noted that the valley's ambient temperature was unusually warm and that their compass readings were inconsistent. They attributed this to geothermal activity. They may have been right. They may not have been.
Puerto Sombra (pop. ~2,500) — A secondary port on the Costadoro, south of Puerto Luciente. Used primarily for the Xarian trade — ships too large or too suspect for Puerto Luciente's regulated harbor dock here instead. Puerto Sombra is the Costadoro's back door: less policed, less taxed, less respectable. The town's economy runs on things that Puerto Luciente's customs house would confiscate: Xarian cacao, unregulated spice, the occasional human cargo (slavery is illegal in Sangrea but enforcement is selective, and Puerto Sombra is where selectivity goes to die). The Alonite Chain-Breakers maintain a safehouse here — a battered stone building with a green door where escaped slaves are sheltered, fed, and transported inland. The safehouse has been raided twice by Solé port authorities. Both times, the building was empty when they arrived. The Chain-Breakers' intelligence network is better than Solé's. This enrages Admiral Lucan personally.

VIII. NATURAL FEATURES
The Sangra River — Sangrea's central waterway. Rises in the southern mountains, flows north through the Vallesangre, past Castesol's western edge, and empties into the sea through a marshy delta north of Puerto Luciente. The Sangra is navigable by barge for most of its length and serves as the region's primary transport corridor. Montefior barge-soldiers patrol the river in flat-bottomed war-barges painted in Terrarossa crimson. The river's name means "blood" — whether named for the red silt it carries during the rainy season or for the battles fought along its banks is debated.
The Fuente River — A tributary of the Sangra, running through the Fuentarossa dry fields. The Fuente's water is red-tinted by iron deposits — the same geology that produces the Red Spring of Fuenterroja. The river is shallow, seasonal (dry for three months of the year), and critical to the interior's agriculture. The bridge at Fuentarossa is the one Sangreverde destroyed. The rebuilt bridge is wider, stronger, and painted white — a deliberate contrast with the red water beneath it.
The Costadoro Cliffs — The golden coastline. Sandstone cliffs, 50-200 feet high, running for roughly eighty miles north and south of Puerto Luciente. The cliffs are riddled with sea-caves used by smugglers, pearl-divers, and the Bellacorte castle's defenders (the castle's escape route runs through a cave system that emerges at a hidden cove a mile from the main harbor). The cliff-tops are where Sangrea's coastal estates are built — the haciendas with the million-crown views.
The Selvaverde — The jungle. Dense tropical and subtropical forest covering the province's southern and eastern reaches, thickening as it approaches the Xarian border. The Selvaverde is one of the most echo-dense environments on the mainland — largely uncleared, ancient growth, home to species that have disappeared from the rest of the continent. The jungle produces medicinal plants, poisons, exotic hardwoods, cacao, vanilla, and the Selvaverde Scarlet parrot. It also produces a persistent sense of unease in anyone who enters it — the forest watches. The Botano healers, who spend their lives in the jungle, describe the sensation as "the green attention" — a feeling of being observed by something that doesn't have eyes. They consider it normal. Mainlanders do not.
The Sunstone Fields — The disputed quarries in the borderlands between Solé and Terrarossa territory. Sunstone is a translucent mineral — amber to deep orange — that transmits light in a warm glow and can be polished to a mirror finish. It is valuable as a decorative stone, as a lens material, and as a status symbol. The deposits are concentrated in a twenty-mile band of hills between the two provinces. The quarries have been fought over so many times that the landscape is scarred with trenches, fortifications, and the ruins of extraction camps that were destroyed and rebuilt with each change of control.
The Vallesangre — Terrarossa's three valleys. Steep-sided, south-facing, terraced with the vineyards that produce Sangrea's finest wines. The valleys are beautiful in the postcard sense — rows of grapevines stepping up hillsides in perfect geometry, stone farmhouses with red-tile roofs, the Sangra River winding through the valley floor — but the beauty is maintained by labor conditions that range from feudal to brutal. Vineyard workers are seasonally employed, poorly paid, and housed in barracks that the Ashanite hospice in Altavista has repeatedly condemned as inadequate. Lord Titus considers this criticism impertinent. The workers consider it accurate.

IX. LEGENDS OF SANGREA
The Butcher's Bridge — The most famous Sangrean legend because it's true. Don Alvaro Sangreverde hung 800 men and boys from the Fuentarossa bridge in 1108 AF. The bridge collapsed under the weight. The bodies fell into the Fuente River and were carried downstream. For a week, the river ran red — not with blood (the water was already red from iron deposits) but with the clothing and personal effects of the dead, tangled in the riverside vegetation for miles. The legend: on the anniversary of the hanging, the bridge creaks as if bearing weight. The water beneath it runs darker. And if you stand on the bridge at midnight and listen, you hear breathing — not one person's breathing, but hundreds, shallow and afraid, the sound of 800 people trying to breathe through nooses that are slowly tightening. The Bonekeepers who maintain the memorial ossuary confirm none of this. The locals confirm all of it.
The Parrot King — A folk tale. A Carvallo lorero, the best in the guild's history, trained a parrot so perfectly that the bird could carry a conversation — not just repeat phrases, but respond to questions, improvise answers, and argue with the person it was speaking to. The lorero sent the parrot to the Doravanto court as a gift. The king was so impressed that he appointed the parrot to his privy council. For three years, the parrot advised the king on matters of state. The kingdom prospered. Then the king's human advisors, jealous, poisoned the bird. The kingdom immediately fell into war. The lesson: parrots are better than people. This is the most popular story in Sangrea. Doravanto courtiers hate it.
The Cascabella's Price — A cautionary tale about the poison guild. A nobleman hired the Cascabella to poison his brother. The Cascabella quoted a price. The nobleman paid. His brother died. A year later, the nobleman received a visit from a Cascabella agent who informed him that his brother had also hired the Cascabella — to poison him. The agent produced a vial: the nobleman had been drinking the poison for six months, a slow-acting compound mixed into his morning wine. The antidote, the agent explained, would cost exactly as much as the original contract. The nobleman paid. He survived. He never drank wine again. The lesson: the Cascabella work for everyone, and what you buy from them, your enemy buys too. Whether this specific story is true is unknown. The Cascabella's general practice of playing both sides is confirmed by every intelligence service on the continent.
The Song That Burned Castesol — A copla legend. During the Great Sunstone War, a cantaor named Maela de la Fuente composed a copla so scathing about both great houses — naming names, detailing bribes, mocking the dead — that both Solé and Terrarossa agents were sent to silence her. She sang the copla at the Festival of the Red Grape, to an audience of 10,000, standing in the bonfire's light. The song lasted forty minutes. She named every atrocity. She named every liar. The crowd rioted. Three buildings burned. Maela escaped in the chaos and was never seen again. The copla survives — it is called "La Verdad de la Sangre" (The Truth of the Blood) — and singing it in full is technically illegal under a Doravanto decree that has never been repealed. Young cantaores sing fragments of it as an act of rebellion. The fragments get longer every generation.
The Jungle's Memory — A Selvaverde legend. The jungle remembers. Every person who enters the Selvaverde leaves an impression — a scent, a warmth, a trace — that the jungle retains. Botano healers who spend decades in the jungle can reportedly feel the traces of previous visitors: this spot was where a hunter knelt; this tree was where a child cried; this path was where soldiers marched during a war that ended before the healer was born. The impressions fade over time but never fully disappear. The deepest jungle — the parts no human has entered in centuries — still holds the traces of people who walked there before the empire existed. What they felt is still there, the healers say, thick as honey in the air, old as stone. The Ayanite scholars call this superstition. The Botano healers smile and change the subject. They are describing echo-perception. They don't know that. They don't need to.
SANGREA — Expansion Supplement
Population Correction & Broader Scope

I. CORRECTED DEMOGRAPHICS
Total Regional Population: ~4,000,000 Castesol: ~120,000 Puerto Luciente: ~85,000 Altavista: ~45,000 Muroverde: ~20,000 Fuenterroja: ~15,000 Other named towns (50+): ~600,000 combined Rural population: ~3,100,000
Sangrea is densely populated by continental standards — fertile river valleys, a long growing season, centuries of agricultural investment. Every viable water source has a village on it. Every viable hilltop has a watchtower or a hacienda. The landscape is worked — terraced, irrigated, walled, fenced, and fought over until every acre has a name and an owner.

II. EXPANDED CULTURAL LAYERS
Honra — The Currency of Reputation
Sangrea runs on honra — honor, reputation, family name, and social credit combined into a single currency governing every interaction. A person with honra borrows without collateral, marries above their station, walks into any tavern knowing they'll be served first. A person without honra is socially dead — refused service, excluded from guilds, children unmarriageable.
Enforcement is communal. In villages, the song decides — a cantaor who sings that a man cheated a neighbor has convicted him without trial. A cantaor who sings a woman's virtue has given her an asset worth gold. The copla tradition is not merely cultural — it is judicial.
The dark side: honra killings. When a family's honra is damaged, the family restores it through violence. Technically illegal. Universally practiced. The Ayanite courts process approximately forty honra-related homicides per year. The actual number is higher. Many are staged as duels or bandit attacks.
Saudaverde — The Green Longing
A word with no direct translation: the ache for something beautiful that is gone or that never was. Homesickness for a home that may not exist. Grief for a future that was promised and never delivered. Sangrea's specific melancholy — it permeates their music, poetry, wine-drinking, and wars.
Saudaverde is why the Sunstone Wars never end. Both great houses fight for a vision of Sangrea each believes the other has stolen — Terrarossa for the old order where blood and soil meant something; Solé for the mercantile future where talent and gold outweigh birth. Neither vision has ever existed. Both houses ache for it. The ache drives the war. The war deepens the ache.
The Bull Culture
The toro bravo — the Sangrean fighting bull — has been bred for aggression, beauty, and courage for a thousand years. The breeding haciendas of the Vallesangre produce bulls weighing over a ton. They are the region's most valuable livestock.
The corrida is not a sport. It is a sacrifice. The bull enters knowing nothing. The matador enters knowing everything — that the bull will die, that honra rises or falls on the quality of the kill. A clean kill earns ovation. A messy kill earns silence, which is worse than jeering. The matador who fails is punished by the absence of song. No cantaor will sing his name.
The corrida seals alliances the way signatures seal treaties. The Festival of the Red Grape's opening-night corrida — six bulls from the finest breeders — is the most prestigious event in Sangrean culture.
The Processions
Every holy day, saint's feast, and seasonal transition is marked by procesiones — hooded penitents in pointed hoods carrying torches and icons through torch-lit streets, accompanied by drums, horns, and deep Alonite chant repurposed as devotional music. The Crimson Penitents join every major procession, blood speckling the cobblestones behind the sacred floats.
The most famous: La Procesión de las Ánimas — the Procession of Souls, held on the autumn equinox night. Hooded figures in black carry a float bearing a carved skeleton dressed in a queen's robes. The skeleton is La Dama del Olvido (the Lady of Forgetting) — not death that takes life, but death that erases name, honra, memory. The procession defies her: the crowd names the dead aloud as the float passes. The dead are spoken. The dead remain.
Folk belief: if you see the Procesión from inside your house, you are safe. If you see it from the street, you are already dead, walking with the souls, and you will not return. Every Sangrean child is taught to stay inside on equinox night. Approximately once a decade, a young person dies that night. The deaths are always explicable by mundane means. The explanations are never satisfying.
The Meigas
Sangrea has witches. Called meigas — wise women who live in rural margins, practice folk medicine, predict weather, curse enemies, bless crops. Most have no more echo-sensitivity than any village healer, but they operate within a folk tradition preserving fragments of genuine echo-knowledge: which plants respond to attention, which stones hold warmth, which places feel different at night.
The Ayanite order considers them heretical. The Ashanite order considers them colleagues. Common people consider them essential. A village without a meiga is a village without medicine.
The most feared: meigas chupasangre — blood-drinkers. Women accused of draining the vitality of livestock, children, and rivals through curses. Whether any meiga has harmed anyone through supernatural means is debated. Whether communities have murdered accused women is not — it has happened repeatedly, and the Ayanite courts have been complicit in at least twelve documented cases.
Castells — The Human Towers
A tradition practiced at festivals across Sangrea: teams of men, women, and children build castells — human towers reaching heights of forty feet or more. The base (the pinya) consists of dozens of tightly-packed men locking arms. Successive tiers climb on their shoulders, each lighter than the last, until a child — the anxaneta — crowns the summit and raises a fist. The tower holds for thirty seconds, then carefully dismantles. A successful castell earns the team enormous honra. A collapse (which happens roughly once per festival season, sometimes injuring or killing participants) brings collective shame but also respect — the attempt itself has value.
The castell tradition is nominally secular but carries deep cultural weight. The metaphor is obvious: Sangrea stands only when everyone holds everyone else up. The metaphor is also obviously ironic in a region where two great houses have been trying to topple each other for four centuries. The castell teams are drawn from both factions. For the duration of the tower, they cooperate. For the duration of the tower only.

III. EXPANDED SETTLEMENTS
Altasol Province
Villarosa (pop. ~8,000) — Livestock hub. Cattle, sheep, goats, fighting bulls. Annual Feria de Ganado draws 20,000. Famous for its leather-workers' quarter — saddlers, boot-makers — exporting continent-wide.
Soltera del Campo (pop. ~3,000) — Grain town on the Sangra's western bank. Home to the province's most respected meiga, Vieja Consuelo (age 77) — women travel from Castesol to consult her on fertility and marriage. She talks to her garden plants. The plants, neighbors say, listen.
Piedranegra (pop. ~2,000) — Black-basalt fortress-town on the Altasol-Vallesangre border. Changed hands seven times during the Wars. Currently neutral Doravanto garrison. Commander Capitán Ruiz maintains peace through a weekly card game for officers from both sides.
Campomuerto (pop. ~1,200) — Named for a 1045 AF battlefield: 3,000 dead in one afternoon. Field never plowed — dead buried where they fell. Haunted by the Compañía Silenciosa (Silent Company) — ghost soldiers marching as a line of torchlight on moonless nights. The Magos sent three investigators. One returned with no data. One returned with notes written in a language he didn't speak. One didn't return.
Loma del Rey (pop. ~5,000) — Ceramic capital. The Loma tiles are Sangrea's finest azulejo — hand-painted geometric patterns adorning buildings from the Alcázar to village chapels. Tile-masters' guild Los Azulejeros requires seven-year apprenticeships.
Aguasclaras (pop. ~4,000) — River town at a limestone gorge. Known for Sangra pike (grilled whole with garlic and lemon) and one of three paper mills in Sangrea. Paper quality good enough for Magos standing orders.
Torre de Vientos (pop. ~1,800) — Hilltop town famous for its windmills — thirty stone towers grinding grain on the province's windiest ridge. The mills are painted white with blue trim and visible for miles. The miller's guild has maintained them for three centuries.
Aldea de las Sombras (pop. ~500) — A village in a narrow valley that receives direct sunlight only four hours per day. Known for its mushroom cultivation — the Shadows' cellars produce the finest setas (wild mushrooms) in Sangrea, dried and exported in linen-wrapped bundles that sell for silver in Castesol's Great Souk.
Encrucijada (pop. ~3,500) — Crossroads town where the Castesol-Fuenterroja road meets the Castesol-Altavista road. Three inns, a Crimson Penitent wayhouse, a small Ayanite court, and the continent's busiest road-shrine — a carved stone alcove where travelers leave offerings for safe passage. The Brothers of the Open Road maintain a waystation here. Their warden, Brother Felix (age 50), knows every merchant, pilgrim, and spy who passes through and keeps a mental ledger more accurate than any customs house.
Costadoro Province
Bahía de las Sirenas (pop. ~6,000) — Ship-repair port south of Puerto Luciente. Safest natural harbor on the coast. Three drydocks. The Cofradía del Ancla guild competes with Horns shipbuilders. The bay produces a harmonic moaning in certain winds — the "sirens" — caused by sea-cave acoustics but attributed to drowned women who lure ships to safety.
Roca Fortuna (pop. ~3,500) — Lighthouse town. Treacherous coast has claimed over a hundred ships. Lampkeeper outpost. Current keeper Brother Isandro (age 38) — former Solé sailor, sole survivor of a wreck on the rocks below his own lighthouse. Keeps the light burning with atoning intensity.
Caleta Oscura (pop. ~1,500) — Twilight fishing hamlet. Its perpetual-shade cove breeds pale, blind pez fantasma — a raw delicacy in Puerto Luciente. Also harvests ambergris used by Cascabella alchemists.
Peñaroja (pop. ~2,500) — Red-cliff town. Salt pans, and annual Fiesta del Mar featuring cliff-diving from 60-80 feet. Deaths rare. Injuries common. Honra gained in quantities no other activity matches.
Puerto Sombra (pop. ~4,000) — Secondary port, Costadoro's back door. Less policed, less taxed, less respectable. Where the slave trade persists despite being illegal. The Alonite Chain-Breakers maintain a safehouse (green door) for escaped slaves. Raided twice by Solé authorities. Both times, empty when they arrived.
Arrecife (pop. ~2,000) — A town built on a coral shelf exposed at low tide. The reef produces the reddish-purple dye called múrex — extracted from sea snails in a process so foul-smelling that the dye-works are legally required to operate downwind. Múrex-dyed cloth is the most expensive textile produced in Sangrea and a Solé monopoly.
Punta del Halcón (pop. ~800) — A falcon-breeding station on a clifftop. House Bellacorte maintains the finest hunting falcons in Sangrea here — peregrine and gyrfalcon crosses bred for speed and aggression. A trained Bellacorte falcon sells for as much as a warhorse. Isabela Bellacorte visits monthly.
Vallesangre Province
Bodega Real (pop. ~7,000) — Wine-processing center at the Sangra's confluence. During harvest, population doubles. Streets run purple with spilled grape juice. The town's Bonekeepers' chapel doubles as a tavern after vespers.
Sangreverde (pop. ~800) — Named for the Butcher's atrocity. Maintains el silencio — one day per year, no one speaks. Not a word. Children learn the silence before anything else.
Puente de Hierro (pop. ~4,000) — Iron-bridge town, Montefior military chokepoint. Market under the bridge sells mountain goods: cured ham, hard cheese, orujo brandy.
Ermita de la Llama (pop. ~200) — Hermitage around a perpetual natural-gas flame burning from a limestone fissure. Has burned longer than memory. Ashanite shrine. The hermits report "visions in the fire." The flame sits on a geological fault bringing unprocessed stone from deep strata — echo-dense. The visions may not be superstition.
Viña Oscura (pop. ~1,000) — A vineyard village producing Sangrea's most unusual wine: the Tinta Negra, a black wine made from a grape variety that grows only on the valley's shadowed northern slopes. The wine is opaque, tannic, and tastes of blackberry, iron, and something undefined that wine experts describe variously as "smoke," "earth," "the end of something." It is an acquired taste. Once acquired, it is never abandoned.
Los Huesos (pop. ~400) — A valley where megafauna fossils erode from limestone walls. Locals call them "los antiguos." A Magos survey in 1278 AF identified extinct species and noted unusual warmth and compass anomalies. The hamlet's children collect fossil fragments and sell them to travelers.
Campana Alta (pop. ~1,500) — A mountain village known for its bell-foundry — the Los Campaneros' primary production site. The furnaces run year-round. The sound of hammer-on-bell testing is the village's constant background music. Children born here are reportedly immune to noise.
Fuentarossa Province
Tabacalera (pop. ~5,000) — Largest tobacco-processing town. Cigarral curing barns handle half the region's output. Air thick with curing-leaf scent. Workers develop nicotine tans. Local copla style: the hoja seca (dry leaf), performed in the barns.
Ojo del Diablo (pop. ~600) — Hamlet around a 200-foot sinkhole of warm, green, sulfurous water. Local legend: the eye of a buried beast. Ember Watch investigated 1201 AF, found nothing, recommended monitoring. Monitoring never happened.
Cortijo de los Perdidos (pop. ~0) — Ghost estate. Abandoned during the Great Sunstone War, never reoccupied. Three resettlement attempts failed — settlers left within a year, citing "the feeling." Livestock refuse to enter the main house. The well contained forty bodies. Bonekeepers sealed it. The feeling persists.
Pozos Rojos (pop. ~2,000) — Iron-oxide mining town. Produces the navajas — folding knives every Sangrean man carries. The smith's guild Los Herreros del Rojo stamps each blade. Counterfeiters get their hands broken.
Fuente Seca (pop. ~1,200) — A town whose spring dried up thirty years ago. The population stays because the tobacco fields don't need the spring (they're rain-fed) and because leaving would mean abandoning the ancestral cemetery. Water is hauled by mule from Fuenterroja, six miles away. The cost is ruinous. The people pay it. The dead keep them.
Molinoblanco (pop. ~1,500) — The Molinaro seat. White-plastered mills grinding grain day and night during harvest. The sound — constant, low, rhythmic — is audible for a mile.
Selvaverde Province
Raíz Profunda (pop. ~3,000) — Staging point for jungle expeditions. The Rastreadores guide guild provides escort. Rates high. Survival record good. Stories excellent.
Pueblo Veneno (pop. ~500) — Cascabella ingredient-gatherers' village. The work is lethal. Bonekeepers' chapel performs more funerals per capita than any settlement in Sangrea. Survivors immune to a remarkable range of toxins through controlled exposure.
Sombra Verde (pop. ~1,000) — Deepest permanent settlement in the Selvaverde. Built in the canopy — tree-house platforms 80 feet up, rope-ladders pulled up at night. Home to independent Yerbateros herb-gatherers who've domesticated the mono rojo (red monkey) as a secondary messenger system rivaling Carvallo parrots in the deep interior.
La Cascada Negra (pop. ~300) — Hamlet at a 200-foot waterfall dropping into a black pool. The pool is sacred. Offerings thrown in return weeks later, transformed — coins green with patina, flowers as seed-pods, carved animals polished smooth. Probably mineral chemistry. The locals prefer the other explanation.
Cruce de Jaguares (pop. ~700) — A settlement at the junction of two jungle tracks, named for the jaguar population that makes the surrounding forest dangerous after dark. The village maintains a night-watch of torchbearers who patrol the perimeter. Jaguars avoid flame. The torchbearers are the village's most honored citizens. The current watch-captain, Doña Selva (age 45), has personally encountered over sixty jaguars and killed two that entered the village. She wears their teeth as a necklace and is the only person in the Selvaverde whom the jaguars, by local account, recognize and avoid.

IV. EXPANDED NATURAL FEATURES
The Sunstone Badlands — Entire landscape of eroded sunstone-veined formations: pillars, canyon walls glowing amber, dry riverbeds floored with gemstone gravel. No water. Extreme temperature swings. Military ruins from four centuries of fortification. Deserters from both houses live here — los quemados (the burned ones) — hard men mining secret deposits and raiding caravans.
The Garganta del Diablo — Canyon where the Sangra narrows to twenty feet and drops through rapids so violent the noise carries five miles. Unnavigable. Montefior barges portage around it. The muleteers — the Garganteños — charge extravagant fees. They've been doing so for three centuries. They're the richest commoners in the Vallesangre.
The Bosque de los Ahorcados — Cork oak forest where both sides hung captured spies during the Great War. Trees still bear rope-marks. Now a Cigarral cork reserve. Unauthorized harvesting punished by hanging. The symbolism is intentional.
The Mar de Piedra — Fifty square miles of eroded limestone formations: pillars, arches, balanced rocks resembling a frozen ocean. Uninhabited. One of the most echo-dense locations in Sangrea — ancient, unprocessed limestone retaining residual presence. Meigas avoid it. Venic Path practitioners seek it out.
The Río Sangra — Central waterway. Navigable by barge for most of its length. Montefior war-barges patrol in Terrarossa crimson. Named "blood" — either for the red silt during rainy season or the battles along its banks.
The Río Fuente — Tributary, red-tinted by iron deposits. Shallow, seasonal. The bridge at Fuentarossa is where Sangreverde hung 800 men.
The Selvaverde Canopy — The jungle. Dense tropical forest thickening toward the Xarian border. One of the most echo-dense environments on the mainland. Largely uncleared ancient growth. Produces the "green attention" — a feeling of being observed by something without eyes. Botano healers consider it normal. Mainlanders do not.
Sierra de los Toros — A mountain range in the Vallesangre's southern wall where the fighting bulls are bred. The slopes are open grassland — natural pasture that has never been cultivated — and the bulls that graze here are semi-wild, rounded up annually in a dangerous cattle-drive called the recogida that involves fifty horsemen, two weeks of mountain work, and an average of three injuries per season.
The Isla de Sal — A small island off the Costadoro coast, roughly three miles from the mainland. A salt-production station and, since 1285 AF, a penal colony — the Doravanto crown sends its most dangerous prisoners here. The island has no fresh water (supplied by barge from the mainland), no shade, and no escape route. The current population: approximately eighty prisoners and twelve guards. The conditions are deliberately horrific. The Ashanite hospice has petitioned for reform seven times. The petitions have been noted, filed, and ignored.

V. EXPANDED LEGENDS
The Comte Maldito — Count Arnal Terrarossa (c. 970 AF) made a pact with something in the Selvaverde to win a Sunstone War. He won. But every night for the rest of his life, he rode a phantom horse through the Vallesangre, burning with invisible flame, screaming for forgiveness that never came. His descendants hear hoofbeats on nights when the wind comes from the south. Terrarossa stable-boys confirm the horses panic on those nights.
La Moura Encantada — A beautiful woman appears at springs and wells, combing her hair with a golden comb, offering travelers a drink from a golden cup. If they drink, they forget everything — name, family, purpose — and wander until they die. If they refuse, the spring runs dry. A water-scarcity parable. Also possibly a folk-memory of echo-phenomena at water sources — the springs where the Moura appears are invariably the oldest, deepest, most echo-dense water sources in the region.
El Sebastián — The Hidden King. King Estevan III, killed at the Battle of Piedranegra in 1056 AF, body never recovered, is sleeping in a cave beneath the Sunstone Badlands, waiting to return and unite Sangrea. Every generation produces a pretender. The most recent (1298 AF) — a charcoal-burner from Campomuerto — attracted hundreds before being arrested. He sits in a cell beneath the Alcázar. Jasmina hasn't decided what to do with him.
La Compañía Silenciosa — Ghost soldiers marching across Campomuerto on moonless nights. Visible as torch-light moving against the wind. No sound. If you follow the torches, you join the march. You don't return. If you turn away, you carry the silence — a heaviness in the chest, a taste of ash lasting days.
The Cantaor's Curse — Every generation's greatest singer dies young. Maela de la Fuente vanished. Ruy del Camino (1189 AF) found dead in a vineyard, throat cut, guitar unstrung. Catalina Sombras (1095 AF) poisoned by one great house (which one is debated — both deny it). The pattern is consistent enough for folk tradition to declare it cosmic principle: the gods give the greatest voice to those they intend to silence.
La Bestia del Badlands — A creature reportedly seen in the Sunstone Badlands — a four-legged thing the size of a bull, plated in what witnesses describe as "living stone," with eyes that glow amber in the dark. Sightings are rare (one every decade) and never confirmed. The Ember Watch investigated in 1256 AF and found tracks — deep, four-toed impressions in sunstone gravel — but no creature. The tracks ended at a cave entrance. The Watch did not enter the cave. Their report: "Insufficient resources for subterranean pursuit. Recommend future investigation." No future investigation occurred. If the creature exists, it is the last surviving echo-node in Sangrea — a beast sustained by the Badlands' residual echo-density, too weak to leave, too stubborn to die.
El Puente de las Almas — The Bridge of Souls. Every major bridge in Sangrea has, according to folk tradition, a soul sealed inside its foundation — not a sacrificed person (the practice, if it ever existed, predates recorded history) but a volunteer who chose to die beneath the bridge so that their spirit would hold the stones together. The Bonekeepers deny this practice. The bridge-builders' guild denies it more loudly. But every Sangrean bridge-builder, before pouring the foundation, leaves a small hollow in the base-stone — "for the soul." No one puts anything in the hollow. No one fills it. Every bridge in Sangrea has a small, empty chamber at its heart. What this means is a question the builders do not ask aloud.
The Feria de los Muertos — A festival in the Selvaverde villages during the winter solstice, unrecognized by orthodox Loveism. Families build altars — ofrendas — in their homes, decorated with flowers, food, candles, and the personal possessions of deceased relatives. The dead are invited to return for one night to eat, drink, and be among the living. The altars are prepared with the deceased's favorite foods. Candles are lit at dusk. Doors are left open. No one sleeps. At dawn, the altars are dismantled and the food is eaten by the living. The Ayanite clergy condemns the festival as "necromantic superstition." The Bonekeepers quietly attend. The Ashanite hospice provides the candles.
In the deepest Selvaverde, the Yerbateros of Sombra Verde practice a variant: they build the ofrendas in the canopy and leave them overnight. By morning, the food is gone — eaten, the Yerbateros say, by the dead. More likely eaten by monkeys and jungle birds. But the flowers on the altar are always arranged differently by morning — not scattered, not disturbed, but rearranged, as if someone looked at them and decided they would be prettier in a different pattern. The Yerbateros do not explain this. They smile and change the subject. They are the most echo-sensitive human community on the mainland and they have no idea what that means.

VALLAN — The Quiet Passage (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — Valleys, Roads, and Stubborn Independence

I. THE REGION AT A GLANCE
Population: ~45,000 Capital: Brynvaal (pop. ~12,000) — the only city, built at the junction of the three major valleys where they open onto the eastern coast Government: Valley-King (House Valenne). Ceremonial authority with limited executive power; real governance rests with the canton councils Economy: Transit tolls, alpine dairy, terrace agriculture, road maintenance, bridge construction, and the port trade connecting the mainland to the Isle of Knowledge and the Teeth Religion: Orthodox Loveism, strongly Ashanite in character. The Waystone Animism folk tradition persists alongside official observance Cantons: Seven recognized cantons, each governing a valley or mountain district

II. THE LAND
Vallan is a country of vertical geography. The Hortakin Valleys — seven major valleys radiating from the central massif like the fingers of a spread hand — cut deep gorges through limestone and granite, their floors narrow and fertile, their walls rising steeply to alpine meadows, bare ridgelines, and the snowfields that feed the streams. The valleys are connected to each other only by high passes that are open eight months of the year and buried under snow for the remaining four. In winter, each valley becomes an island.
The roads are everything. Without the road network — stone-paved, waystone-marked, bridge-connected — Vallan would not be a polity. It would be seven isolated farming communities that happen to share a language. The roads make Vallan a nation. They also make it a chokepoint: the Hortakin passes are the most efficient route between the southern Heartlands and the eastern coast, and every merchant caravan heading for the Teeth or the Isle of Knowledge passes through Vallan's toll stations. The road-tax is the Valley-King's primary revenue. The roads are, accordingly, perfect.
The environment shifts dramatically with altitude. The valley floors are temperate and irrigated: terraced fields of barley, potato, quinoa, and maize stepping up the hillsides in patterns maintained for centuries, fed by snowmelt channels that the Vallanaise engineer with an obsessive precision. Above the terraces, alpine meadows — the alp — provide summer grazing for the dairy herds that are Vallan's agricultural backbone. Above the meadows, bare rock and snowfield. The air at the valley floor smells of hay, manure, and wildflowers; at the passes, it smells of nothing at all except cold.
The eastern edge of Vallan drops to the coast through a dramatic descent — the Bryn Stair, a series of switchback roads carved into a cliff face that drops 3,000 feet in six miles. At the bottom: Brynvaal, the capital, built on a narrow coastal shelf between the mountains and the sea. Brynvaal's port is the gateway to the Isle of Knowledge (visible on clear days as a dark shape on the eastern horizon, roughly fifteen miles offshore) and the northern Teeth islands.

III. THE HOUSES OF VALLAN
HOUSE VALENNE — The Valley-Kings
Founded: c. 908 AF (elected by the canton elders after the empire's fall) Seat: The Valenne Hall, Brynvaal Sigil: A golden key on a green field Words: "The Road Is Open"
House Valenne has held the Valley-Kingship for four hundred years — not through conquest or political maneuvering but through the simple, unglamorous work of maintaining the roads, arbitrating disputes between cantons, and representing Vallan to the outside world. The Valennes are administrators, not rulers. Their power is real but deliberately limited: the Valley-King arbitrates, maintains infrastructure, collects the road-tax, and speaks for Vallan in foreign affairs. Internal governance — land disputes, criminal law, inheritance, marriage — belongs to the canton councils.
Current Members:
Valley-King Aldric Valenne V (age 61) — The current monarch. A quiet, deliberate man with the leathery tan of someone who spends more time outdoors than in a throne room. Aldric's daily routine involves a morning inspection of whatever road section or bridge project is nearest to his current location — he travels the valleys constantly, spending no more than a month in Brynvaal before setting out again on circuit. He considers sitting still a form of incompetence. His court is wherever he is: a roadside inn, a canton elder's kitchen, a bridge-builder's camp. Foreign ambassadors who expect a palace audience are instead invited to walk with him along a mountain road while he checks waystone alignments. Those who keep up earn his respect. Those who can't are given a mule.
Aldric's politics are defined by two commitments: independence from the Heartlands (the Annexation Crisis of 1120 AF is Vallan's founding trauma, and every Valenne since has treated Heartlands expansion as an existential threat) and alliance with the Isle of Knowledge (the Magos are Vallan's closest institutional partner, and the port of Brynvaal exists primarily to serve the Isle's supply needs). He is aware that the Argent Schism is making the Heartlands unstable and that instability in a neighbor twenty times your size is dangerous. He has been quietly reinforcing the western passes.
Queen Marisol Valenne (age 57) — Aldric's wife. Born a Sangrean — the daughter of a minor Carvallo vassal house, she came to Vallan as a trade envoy at twenty-two and married Aldric after a courtship conducted entirely on mountain roads (he proposed at the summit of the Dawnbreak Pass; she accepted on the condition that they stop walking and eat lunch first). Marisol brought Sangrean warmth to a culture that doesn't naturally produce it — she introduced color to the Valenne household (the Hall's interior, previously monochrome stone and timber, now features Sangrean textiles, Botano-province flowers in every window, and a kitchen that produces food with actual seasoning). She is beloved by the Vallanaise in a way that their own leaders rarely are: she is exotic enough to be interesting and practical enough to be useful. She speaks four languages, manages the port's trade relationships, and has a network of Sangrean contacts that provides intelligence the Valley-King couldn't otherwise access.
Aric Valenne (age 32) — Heir. Aldric's only surviving child (two older siblings died — one to a mountain fever at age six, one to a bridge collapse at age nineteen). Aric carries the weight of being the last Valenne of his generation with a quiet intensity that manifests as perfectionism: every decision analyzed from multiple angles, every road inspection conducted twice, every diplomatic letter drafted three times. He is intelligent, responsible, and paralyzed by the fear of making a mistake that could cost the dynasty its legitimacy. His wife, Lena (age 29) — a Brynvaal port-master's daughter — is the more decisive of the pair. She has been gently steering Aric's decisions for five years. He knows this. He is grateful.
Old Esther Valenne (age 84) — Aldric's mother. The previous Valley-Queen (consort to Aldric's father, King Aldric IV). A tiny woman who walks with two canes and a contempt for weakness that has not diminished with age. She was the one who negotiated the current toll agreements with the Heartlands merchants — agreements so favorable to Vallan that Silverblood diplomats are still trying to renegotiate them forty years later. She lives in a cottage in the Brynvaal hills (she refuses the Hall, calling it "drafty and political") and receives visitors who bring her the mountain cheese and obstler she considers the only acceptable gifts. She provides advice when asked. She provides it when not asked, too.

THE CANTON HOUSES
Vallan's seven cantons are each governed by a canton elder — usually the head of the valley's most prominent family, elected by landowners for life. The cantons are:
Brynvaal Canton — The coastal canton containing the capital. Governed by the Brynner family, who run the port and the shipyard that services the Isle of Knowledge ferry route.
Elder Torben Brynner (age 55) — Port-master and canton elder. A practical man whose life revolves around tide tables, cargo manifests, and the ferry schedule to the Isle. He considers the Valley-King a necessary overhead and the Magos the region's best customer. His ambition: expand the port to handle Teeth-bound trade that currently bypasses Vallan via the longer coastal route. His obstacle: funding.
Glyncoch Canton — The western valley, bordering the Heartlands. The gateway canton — the first point of contact for any traveler entering Vallan from the west. Known for its fortified bridge — the Glyncoch Span — a single stone arch over a gorge 400 feet deep that is Vallan's most famous engineering achievement and its primary defensive position.
Elder Petra Glyncoch (age 48) — A bridge-builder by training who inherited the canton when her father died mid-span (fell from scaffolding during a repair project; the family considers this an honorable death). Petra is the best structural engineer in Vallan — she can assess a bridge's load capacity by listening to it under strain. She has reinforced the Glyncoch Span's foundations twice and considers any bridge built by non-Vallanaise engineers to be inherently suspect.
Hortakin Canton — The central valley, the largest and most fertile. The agricultural heart of Vallan: terrace farms, dairy herds, the best käsknöpfle in the region.
Elder Renzo Hortakin (age 63) — Patriarch of the canton's founding family. A cheese-maker by trade and passion. Renzo can identify any Vallanaise cheese by texture alone and has been known to reject entire dairy shipments for failing his standards. His politics: keep the roads open, keep the taxes fair, keep the Heartlanders out, and for Loreth's sake maintain the irrigation channels. His second wife, Inés (age 40) — another Sangrean import, a trend that is becoming common in Vallan's upper class — runs the canton's Harvest Bell granary and has introduced quinoa cultivation to the valley's terraces with remarkable success.
Daurvaal Canton — The southern valley, bordering Rosland. Cold, forested, and home to the region's only significant mining operations (tin and copper in the mountain's lower slopes). The Daurvaal folk are the most Roslandic of the Vallanaise — heavier, more reserved, with a taste for smoked meat and dark beer that their northern cousins find crude.
Elder Kaspar Daurvaal (age 70) — The oldest sitting canton elder. A former miner who lost his left eye to a flying rock chip at age thirty and has governed Daurvaal with depth-perception-defying competence for four decades. He is the only Vallanaise leader who openly respects the Roslandic republic, having traded with Roslandic mining guilds his entire life. His views on Heartlands feudalism: "Kings are what you get when people stop paying attention."
Sternmark Canton — The highest-altitude canton, containing the passes to both the Heartlands and the Frozen South. Sparse population, extreme weather, and the Sternmark Shepherds — alpine herders who spend six months of the year above the treeline with their flocks, moving between mountain pastures in a seasonal migration pattern unchanged for centuries. The Shepherds have their own folk traditions distinct from valley Vallanaise: llama-wool weaving (the Sternmark herds include a breed of highland camelid, the Valenne Ridge-Llama, bred for wool and pack-carrying), a fermented mare's-milk drink called kumja that tastes like sour regret, and a tradition of stone-stacking that produces the eerie cairn-fields visible on every ridgeline.
Elder Ylva Sternmark (age 52) — A shepherdess who governs her canton from wherever her flock happens to be. Meetings with Ylva involve climbing to wherever she's camped. She considers this a feature. She once made a Silverblood trade envoy climb 2,000 feet to discuss a toll agreement, then rejected his terms before he'd caught his breath. The Silverblood never returned. Ylva considers this a successful negotiation.
Sunvaal Canton — The sunniest valley, south-facing, with the warmest microclimate in Vallan. Known for its fruit orchards — apple, pear, cherry, and the small, intensely flavored golden apricot that Vallan exports to the Heartlands at prices that make Sangrean vintners jealous. Sunvaal is also the canton most influenced by Peruvian-style terrace agriculture: the hillsides are sculpted into elaborate stepped systems — andenes — that maximize sunlight exposure and water distribution with an elegance that mainland agricultural experts consider borderline miraculous.
Elder Lucio Sunvaal (age 44) — The youngest canton elder. A fruit-grower who inherited the position when his mother died last year and who is still adjusting to the role. He is good-natured, slightly overwhelmed, and married to a woman — Carmela (age 42) — who is already doing most of the governing while Lucio tends his orchards. Their partnership works. Nobody mentions that it's Carmela who answers the door when the Valley-King's messengers arrive.
Kaltbach Canton — The northernmost valley, a narrow gorge cut by the Kaltbach River — the coldest, fastest waterway in Vallan. The canton's economy is built on trout fishing, timber, and the production of a unique hard cheese aged in the limestone caves that riddle the gorge walls. Kaltbach Cave-Cheese is Vallan's most famous export product: sharp, crystalline, with a mineral edge that cheese-lovers across the continent describe as "tasting like the mountain itself." The caves maintain a constant temperature year-round, producing aging conditions that cannot be replicated elsewhere. Attempts to produce Kaltbach-style cheese in the Heartlands have universally failed. The Kaltbach folk enjoy this.
Elder Marte Kaltbach (age 58) — Cheese-cave manager and canton elder. A woman of few words whose authority derives entirely from her cheese — she controls access to the aging caves, and anyone who wants to produce Kaltbach Cave-Cheese needs her approval. This gives her a quiet veto over the canton's economy that she exercises with a restraint that makes it more powerful, not less.

IV. BRYNVAAL — The Port City
Vallan's only city sits on a narrow shelf between the Bryn Stair's final descent and the eastern sea. It is not grand — Brynvaal has the population of a Heartlands market town and the ambitions of a fishing village — but it is beautifully made. The streets are stone-paved, stepped where necessary, lined with timber-and-stone buildings whose ground floors are workshops and shops and whose upper floors are homes. The port occupies a natural cove sheltered by a curved breakwater of stacked basalt. The harbor is small — room for perhaps thirty vessels — but deep, well-maintained, and served by a fleet of ferries that make the crossing to the Isle of Knowledge twice daily (weather permitting).
The Valenne Hall — The Valley-King's seat. Not a palace but a large farmhouse: heavy timber, stone foundations, a slate roof, and a great room with a fireplace large enough to warm a hundred people. The Hall sits on a hill above the port, overlooking the harbor and, on clear days, the dark shape of the Isle on the horizon. The building has been expanded over four centuries of Valenne rule but retains the proportions and character of a farmstead — deliberate humility, reinforced by every generation. The Hall's most notable feature: the Road Map Room, a chamber whose walls are covered with painted maps of every road, bridge, and waystone in Vallan, updated annually by the royal cartographer. The maps are works of art. They are also the most accurate infrastructure survey in existence.
The Bryn Stair Terminal — Where the switchback road from the interior valleys reaches the coast. A fortified gatehouse controlling access to the city — tolls are collected here, customs inspections conducted, and Vallan's modest border security enforced. The Terminal includes a caravanserai (a covered inn-yard where pack animals and wagon trains rest after the steep descent), a Harvest Bell depot (grain stores for the coast), and a Waystone chapel where travelers give thanks for surviving the descent. The Bryn Stair is not dangerous if you follow the road. The drop on the exposed outer edge is, however, vertigo-inducing, and mules that refuse to walk the final switchbacks are a recurring logistical problem.
The Ferry Dock — The port's most important structure: a stone pier with a covered waiting hall, a signal tower for communicating with the Isle, and the berthing slips for the three ferries that maintain the crossing. The ferries are Vallanaise-built — wide-beamed, shallow-drafted, designed for stability in the coastal chop rather than speed. Each ferry is named: The Scholar, The Keeper, and The Pilgrim. The Scholar is the oldest (built 1267 AF, rebuilt twice) and is said to be lucky. The Pilgrim is the newest and is said to be cursed (it ran aground on its maiden voyage; the hull was repaired but the reputation stuck). Ferry captains are Brynner family employees. The current senior captain, Harno Brynner (age 50) — Torben's brother — has made the crossing over four thousand times and can navigate the route in fog, at night, and in his sleep (which he has allegedly done once, during a crossing so calm that the crew let him nap at the wheel).
The Stonemarket — Brynvaal's commercial center. An open-air market built on a stone platform above the harbor, where mountain products (cheese, dried meat, wool, leather, obstler, preserved fruit) are traded for coastal and imported goods (salt, fish, wine, textiles, books from the Isle, volcanic stone from the Teeth). Market day is every third day. The Stonemarket's most famous vendor: Doña Pilar (age 65), a Sangrean expatriate who runs a food stall selling empanadas — dough pockets stuffed with spiced meat, cheese, or vegetables — that she adapted from Sangrean recipes to Vallanaise palates. Her cheese empanadas, made with Kaltbach Cave-Cheese and Sternmark llama-meat, are the most popular street food in Brynvaal and a minor diplomatic scandal (the Sangrean consul considers them a cultural crime; the Vallanaise consider them a national treasure).

V. MINOR SETTLEMENTS
Glyncoch (pop. ~1,500) — The western gateway town, built at the Heartlands-side entrance to the Glyncoch Pass. Fortified: stone walls, a gatehouse, and the famous Glyncoch Span bridge. The town exists to control access and collect tolls. Known for its bridge-builders' guild — the Spanneri — whose members wear a distinctive mason's apron marked with a keystone symbol and who consider bridge-building a sacred calling. A Brothers of the Open Road chapter maintains a hostel here for westbound travelers.
Hochdorf (pop. ~800) — A high-altitude village in Sternmark Canton, 7,000 feet above sea level. Accessible only by mule-track for six months of the year. Known for its weaving: Hochdorf textiles — llama-wool blankets and ponchos dyed with alpine wildflower pigments in deep reds, oranges, and purples — are prized across the continent. The weavers are exclusively women. The tradition passes mother to daughter. Men who attempt to learn are not prohibited but are mercilessly teased until they stop.
Steinbrunn (pop. ~600) — A village built around a natural hot spring in Daurvaal Canton. The spring — the Brunn — fills a stone-lined pool maintained by an Ashanite bathing-order called the Sisters of the Warm Stone (four members, all elderly, all convinced that hot mineral water cures everything from gout to heartbreak). The village's economy is split between mining support services and a small but growing pilgrim trade — word of the Brunn's healing properties has spread, and mainlanders with joint pain and bad backs make the trek to soak. Elder Kaspar tolerates this with the expression of a man watching tourists discover his backyard.
Soltera (pop. ~400) — A sun-terrace village in Sunvaal Canton. Built into a south-facing hillside with terraced andenes stepping down to the valley floor. Known for its golden apricots, its honey (the Soltera bees feed on alpine wildflowers and produce a pale, aromatic honey with a floral intensity that Sangrean chefs use in desserts), and its annual Fiesta del Sol — a harvest celebration combining Lovist liturgy with pre-imperial sun-worship elements that the Ashanite clergy tolerates because the food is excellent and the singing is sincere.
Kaltbach Village (pop. ~700) — The settlement at the mouth of the Kaltbach Gorge. The village exists because the cheese caves exist. Everything revolves around the cheese: production, aging, grading, packing, transport. The caves themselves extend roughly half a mile into the limestone, with over two hundred individual aging chambers maintained at precise temperatures by the cave system's natural ventilation. Access is restricted — only Kaltbach-family-approved cheese-makers may enter the aging chambers. Outsiders are permitted as far as the tasting room — a chamber near the cave entrance where samples are offered to potential buyers. The tasting room is also, by long tradition, where Kaltbach Canton's disputes are settled: the elder sits behind a table, the disputants stand before her, and the conversation happens over cheese and obstler. Resolution rates are high. The cheese may have something to do with it.
Puente Alto (pop. ~300) — A tiny settlement perched on a natural rock bridge over the Kaltbach River gorge. The bridge is natural but has been improved: stone railings, carved steps, a shrine to Alon-as-Builder at the midpoint. Puente Alto exists because the bridge exists — it is the only crossing of the Kaltbach Gorge for twenty miles in either direction. The settlement consists of an inn, a toll station, a blacksmith, and a Waystone chapel. The innkeeper, Gaspar (age 55), has been operating the crossing for thirty years and has developed a system for assessing bridge safety by pressing his ear to the stone and listening for stress fractures. He has closed the bridge twice on the basis of sounds only he could hear. Both times, inspection confirmed structural issues. Gaspar attributes this to experience. He may be mildly echo-sensitive.
Nebelheim (pop. ~250) — The most remote settlement in Vallan. A village in a high, fog-locked valley in Sternmark Canton, accessible by a single mule-track that is blocked by snow for five months of the year. Nebelheim's isolation has produced a population that is deeply inbred (everyone is related to everyone else within three generations), fiercely independent (they pay their road-tax grudgingly and consider the Valley-King a distant abstraction), and possessed of folk traditions that predate Loveism and have never been fully documented. The Nebelheim folk practice Waystone Animism with an openness that would alarm an Ayanite theologian: they make offerings at the waystones (milk, bread, flowers, small carved figures), address the stones by name, and claim that the stones "speak" — not in words, but in feelings. Whether this is superstition, cultural habit, or a remnant of genuine echo-sensitivity preserved by isolation is unknown. No Magos researcher has been willing to spend a winter in Nebelheim to find out.

VI. NATURAL FEATURES
The Hortakin Massif — The central mountain complex from which the seven valleys radiate. Peak elevation: ~12,000 feet. The massif is granite and limestone, glacially carved, with permanent snowfields above 10,000 feet and alpine meadows between 7,000 and 10,000. The passes between valleys range from 6,000 to 9,000 feet — manageable in summer, lethal in winter.
The Bryn Stair — The switchback road descending from the interior to the coast. Six miles of hairpin turns carved into a cliff face. The engineering is imperial-era at the base (massive basalt blocks, military-grade construction) and Vallanaise-era above (lighter limestone, more elegant curves, better drainage). The transition is visible as a change in stone color two-thirds of the way down.
The Kaltbach River — The fastest river in Vallan. Fed by glacial melt, running through a limestone gorge so narrow that the water fills the channel wall-to-wall during spring runoff, producing a roar audible a mile away. The Kaltbach is unnavigable, unfishable during high water, and beautiful in the terrifying way that powerful things are beautiful. In late summer, when the flow drops, the gorge reveals cave openings, fossil-bearing rock layers, and (according to local legend) the entrance to a tunnel system that connects to the Isle of Knowledge's underground vaults. No one has confirmed this. The Magos decline to comment.
The Dawnbreak Pass — The highest pass in Vallan (9,200 feet), connecting the Hortakin and Sternmark valleys. Named because the sunrise, viewed from the summit, arrives visibly earlier than in the valleys below — the first rays hitting the pass while the valleys are still in shadow. Vallanaise couples traditionally climb the Dawnbreak Pass together on the anniversary of their betrothal to watch the sunrise. The tradition is so old that the path to the summit has been worn smooth by generations of feet. An Ashanite waystone shrine at the top, carved with Vena's moon-symbol and Loreth's sun-symbol side by side, marks the spot where Aldric V proposed to Marisol.
Lake Esmeralda — A glacial lake in Sunvaal Canton, fed by snowmelt, impossibly green (glacial flour suspended in the water produces the color). The lake is sacred in local folk tradition — offerings are thrown in on midsummer, and swimming in it is considered both a blessing and a dare (the water is cold enough to stop your heart if you stay in too long). The lake's shores are terraced with andenes that produce the valley's finest potatoes — a purple-skinned, yellow-fleshed variety that Vallanaise cooks roast with herbs and serve with melted Kaltbach cheese.

VII. LEGENDS OF VALLAN
The Road That Walks — The oldest Vallanaise legend. A traveler, lost in fog, followed a road that led through a valley he didn't recognize. The road was perfectly maintained — waystone markers every mile, bridges in good repair, inns at regular intervals — but the inns were empty and the waystones had no names on them. He walked for three days. On the fourth day, the fog lifted and he was standing at his own front door. He had been walking the road in a circle. The road, the legend says, was walking too — testing whether he was worthy of reaching his destination. The lesson: the road serves those who trust it. The practical lesson: don't walk in fog without a map.
The Last Bridge-Builder — A folk tale. A bridge-builder was tasked with spanning a gorge so deep that the bottom couldn't be seen. He built the span over seven years, working alone (his apprentices had all quit, claiming the gorge "breathed"). When the bridge was complete, he walked to its center and looked down. He saw his own reflection looking up. The reflection waved. He waved back. He never came home. The bridge stood for three hundred years before an earthquake took it. When the rubble was cleared, they found two skeletons at the bottom of the gorge — one on top of the other, arms crossed as if in embrace.
The Cheese That Wouldn't Age — A Kaltbach legend. A cheese-maker, dissatisfied with the normal aging process, made a wheel of cheese and left it in the deepest cave chamber — a part of the system that the Kaltbach family doesn't normally use, because "the air tastes wrong." He returned a year later. The cheese was unchanged — not aged, not molded, not decayed. Perfectly fresh. He left it another year. Same result. Ten years. Twenty. The cheese sat in the dark, untouched by time, for sixty years. When the cheese-maker died, his granddaughter went to retrieve it. The cheese was still fresh. She ate a piece. It tasted, she said, "like standing in a field that hasn't been planted yet." She sealed the chamber. The family has not opened it since.
The Stone That Sings — In Nebelheim, a particular waystone — the third stone on the northern track — is said to produce a low, humming tone on nights when both moons are full (Concordance nights). The hum is below normal hearing range — you feel it in your chest rather than hear it with your ears. The Nebelheim folk leave offerings at this stone more frequently than any other. They call it the Grandfather. Visiting Ayanite missionaries have examined the stone and declared it "a natural acoustic phenomenon, of no theological significance." The Nebelheim folk smiled politely and continued their offerings.

THE ISLE OF KNOWLEDGE (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — The Memory of the World

I. THE ISLE AT A GLANCE
Population: ~800 (Magos scholars, staff, servants, and a small permanent support community) Location: Fifteen miles off the Vallanaise coast, accessible by ferry from Brynvaal Government: The Order of Magos, led by the Grand Magos (elected for a 20-year term) Economy: Maintained by charitable donations (primarily from Vallan, the Teeth, and wealthy mainland patrons), entry fees charged to visitors, revenue from Magos consulting services, and the hidden vaults' undisclosed resources Religion: Officially neutral. The Magos acknowledge Loveism but do not practice it institutionally. All faiths are welcome on the Isle under the Charter of the Pale Reed.

II. THE ORDER OF MAGOS — Structure and Law
The Hierarchy
The Order is organized into five Circles, each representing a stage of advancement and a corresponding set of privileges and obligations:
First Circle — The Novices (Pale Reeds) — New entrants to the Order. Any person may join regardless of origin, gender, faith, or social status. Upon entry, the novice surrenders their family name (they retain a personal name but are addressed as "Reed [Name]" — e.g., Reed Boh, for the character Boh Vaakor). Novices perform menial labor: shelving, copying, cleaning, maintenance. They attend lectures but cannot access the restricted collections. Duration: minimum five years. Many wash out. The work is tedious, the conditions are austere, and the Isle's isolation drives some novices to depression or madness. Those who endure are promoted to the Second Circle.
Second Circle — The Scribes (Grey Quills) — Working scholars. Scribes are assigned to a School (see below) based on aptitude and interest. They assist senior scholars, conduct supervised research, teach incoming novices, and begin contributing original work to the archive. Scribes may access most of the library's collections but not the restricted vaults. Duration: minimum ten years. Scribes are not permitted to leave the Isle — the restriction exists to ensure that partially trained scholars do not carry incomplete knowledge into the world where it could be misapplied. The rule is absolute and enforcement is exile from the Order.
Third Circle — The Keepers (Black Stoles) — Full scholars. Keepers have completed at least fifteen years of service and have produced a masterwork — an original contribution to knowledge judged by a panel of senior Keepers as worthy of permanent addition to the archive. Keepers may access all collections except the deepest restricted vaults. They may take on personal apprentices, form consulting contracts with outside parties, and — critically — they may leave the Isle with written permission from the Grand Magos. Permission is granted sparingly. A Keeper who leaves must return within one year or be declared apostate. At any given time, perhaps twenty Keepers are off-Island on authorized missions.
Fourth Circle — The Elders (Silver Chains) — Senior scholars who have served for thirty years or more and who have produced at least three masterworks. Elders form the Order's governing council — the Conclave — which advises the Grand Magos, adjudicates internal disputes, and votes on policy. Elders may access the restricted vaults. There are currently fourteen Elders. They range in age from fifty-five to ninety-two. They agree on almost nothing, which is considered a feature rather than a bug — the Order values dissent as a check on institutional orthodoxy.
Fifth Circle — The Grand Magos (Gold Reed) — The Order's leader. Elected by the Conclave from among the Elders for a twenty-year term. The term length is deliberate: long enough to provide institutional stability, short enough to prevent personal fiefdoms. The Grand Magos has executive authority over the Isle's operations, final say in disputes that the Conclave cannot resolve, and sole access to certain vault sections whose contents are shared with no one.
The Grand Magos may serve a maximum of one term. Re-election is prohibited. The current Grand Magos is nearing the end of her term.
The Schools
The Order's scholarship is organized into seven Schools — intellectual traditions that roughly correspond to academic disciplines but that, in the Magos tradition, overlap, compete, and frequently argue:
The School of the Record — Archivists, cataloguers, copyists. The Order's backbone. Record scholars maintain the Great Catalogue, preserve deteriorating documents, and conduct the painstaking work of cross-referencing, dating, and authenticating texts. They are the least glamorous and most essential scholars on the Isle.
The School of the Natural World — Naturalists, herbalists, geographers, cartographers. They study the physical world: flora, fauna, geology, weather, and the increasingly urgent question of why certain species are disappearing and certain landscapes are changing. The Natural World school maintains the Isle's specimen collections (fossils, pressed plants, preserved animal samples) and produces the continental maps that every government relies on.
The School of the Human Record — Historians. They compile, interpret, and argue about the past. The Human Record school is the most internally contentious — historians disagree about everything, and Magos historians disagree more loudly than most, because they have access to primary sources that allow them to prove each other wrong with devastating specificity.
The School of Numbers — Mathematicians, astronomers, engineers. They study the abstract: geometry, calculation, celestial mechanics, and the practical applications thereof (bridge design, navigation, calendar correction). The Numbers school maintains the Isle's observatory — a tower on the island's highest point, equipped with the best lenses on the continent.
The School of Languages — Linguists, translators, cipher-breakers. They study the continent's languages: living (Munnish, Xarian dialects, Frozen South clan-tongues), dead (pre-imperial Aethelian, Old Nionian, the untranslated script on certain Age of History artifacts), and constructed (the cipher systems used by various governments for secret communication). The Languages school is the Order's intelligence arm — a Magos who can read every language on the continent is a Magos who can read every government's mail.
The School of Substances — Alchemists, metallurgists, pharmacologists. They study materials: what things are made of, how they interact, and what happens when you combine them. The Substances school is the most practically profitable — their knowledge of medicinal compounds, metallurgical techniques, and preservation methods is in constant demand from outside clients. They are also the school most likely to blow something up. The Isle's eastern laboratory (the Smoke Hall) has been rebuilt four times.
The School of the Unseen — The most controversial school. The Unseen scholars study phenomena that don't fit the other categories: reports of prophecy, unexplained healings, the behavioral anomalies of certain animals and plants, the properties of materials that defy conventional alchemical explanation, and — quietly, cautiously, under the protection of the Charter's neutrality clause — the Logosian philosophical tradition that was expelled from the Ayanite order in 1038 AF. The Unseen school is small (perhaps thirty scholars), intellectually rigorous (they apply the same evidentiary standards as any other school), and regarded by the rest of the Order with a mixture of respect and suspicion. The Logosian texts in their collection are the only surviving copies. Their research into "echoes" — they use the Lovist term while rejecting the Lovist theology — is the closest thing on the continent to a scientific investigation of the magic system.
Election and Governance
The Grand Magos election is the Order's most important institutional event. The process:
Nomination — Any Elder may nominate themselves or be nominated by two other Elders. Typically three to five candidates stand.
Examination — Each candidate presents their vision for the Order's next twenty years in a public lecture attended by the entire community. Questions are permitted from all Circles. The lectures last hours. The questions can be brutal.
Deliberation — The Conclave debates in closed session for as long as necessary (the longest deliberation on record: seventeen days, in 1189 AF). The debate is secret. Its contents are never disclosed.
Consensus — The Conclave votes. A two-thirds majority is required. If no candidate achieves this, the field is narrowed and the process repeats. The result is announced by the ringing of the Isle's great bell — the Pale Bell — which is heard in Brynvaal across the water.

III. THE CURRENT MAGOS — Named Characters
Grand Magos Thessaly Vane (age 72) — The current leader. In the eighteenth year of her twenty-year term. A former School of the Human Record historian specializing in the Age of History — the deep past, the era of ziggurats and stone circles and technologies no one understands. Thessaly is small, sharp-eyed, and possessed of a memory that her colleagues describe as "archival" — she can recall specific passages from texts she read forty years ago, with page numbers. She has governed the Isle with a combination of intellectual authority and administrative cunning, maintaining the Order's neutrality during the Nionian civil war (Jous's agents attempted to recruit Magos scholars for the Pure Way; Thessaly politely declined and then quietly expelled the two Scribes who had been passing information to Domus Lux).
Her private concern: the vaults. Thessaly is one of three people alive who know the full extent of what the deepest vaults contain (the other two are Elder Magos of the Unseen school and the vault-keeper). The artifacts from the Age of History — objects whose function she can describe but whose mechanism she cannot explain — are showing signs of change. Instruments that have been inert for centuries are producing faint vibrations. Materials that have been stable are shifting color. Something is different. She suspects it is connected to reports from the Natural World school of ecological anomalies on the mainland — species appearing in unexpected locations, growth patterns accelerating in certain regions. She does not have the theoretical framework to connect these observations to the Eldra-Veil breach. She is looking for one.
Elder Corvath (age 81) — School of the Unseen. The Order's most controversial scholar. Corvath has spent fifty years studying the Logosian texts, the echo-theory, and the growing body of evidence that "unexplained" phenomena are actually manifestations of a measurable natural force. He has published seven masterworks, each more provocative than the last, and his current project — a systematic survey of "sensitive" individuals across the continent (folk healers, weather-predictors, beast-trackers with uncanny accuracy) — has produced data that he believes proves the existence of an ambient energy field that varies by geography and is declining over time. He is, without knowing it, the closest person on the mainland to understanding the echo-system. His colleagues consider him either a genius or a crank. Several consider him both.
Reed Boh Vaakor (age 19) — First Circle novice. Brilliant, reclusive, socially awkward in the way of someone whose interior life is far more vivid than their exterior one. Boh arrived at the Isle three years ago from the Heartlands — his family background is obscure, possibly minor gentry, possibly a lie. He was accepted on the basis of an entrance examination that the School of Substances proctor described as "the best I've seen in thirty years." He has been assigned to the Record school (standard for novices) but spends every free hour in the Smoke Hall, conducting unauthorized experiments with materials he shouldn't have access to. His interest: the boundary between life and death — what happens to consciousness at the moment of dying, whether it can be preserved, whether it can be recalled. He has read the Logosian texts (smuggled from the restricted shelf by an Unseen school sympathizer whose identity he protects) and the Bonekeepers' funeral liturgies (available in the general collection). He is combining the two in ways that neither tradition would approve of.
Boh's vault access is zero — he is a First Circle novice with no privileges. But the deep vaults are built into the Isle's echo-dense basalt bedrock, and Boh has been sleeping in a basement storage room (unauthorized, but the dormitory warden has stopped trying to enforce curfew on him) that is close enough to the vault level that he has begun experiencing vault-dreaming: vivid, detailed dreams featuring rooms he's never entered, objects he's never seen, and a recurring image of a door made of stone that has no handle. He does not know that the dreams are echo-phenomena. He thinks they are visions. He is keeping a journal. The journal is hidden inside a hollowed-out copy of a Harvest Bell agricultural manual that no one will ever voluntarily read.
Keeper Alenn (age 45) — School of Languages. The Isle's premier cipher-breaker and the Magos agent responsible for maintaining the secret vault on Emberstone in the Teeth. Alenn has made the crossing to Emberstone seventeen times in her career, each trip disguised as a trade visit or scholarly consultation. Since Morvayn's bridge coup in 1298 AF, her access has been disrupted — the bridge tolls make legitimate travel prohibitively expensive, and Morvayn's security apparatus makes covert travel risky. She has not visited the vault in three years. Her last report indicated that the vault's contents were stable. Grand Magos Thessaly is not confident that this remains true.
Elder Pashma (age 68) — School of the Natural World. Born on the Red Coast, dark-skinned, sharp-tongued, and the Order's foremost expert on continental ecology. Pashma has spent forty years documenting species distributions, habitat changes, and the slow but measurable decline in biodiversity that she calls "the Thinning" — a term she coined independently, without knowing that the Giants use a similar concept. Her maps of species range-contraction over the past three centuries are the most compelling visual evidence that something is wrong with the natural world, and they hang in her office like accusation. She does not know why the Thinning is happening. She suspects deforestation and over-hunting. She is partially right. She is mostly wrong. The real answer would terrify her.
Keeper Odo (age 55) — The Vault-Keeper. One of three people who know the full vault contents. Odo is a School of Substances scholar who was appointed Vault-Keeper twenty years ago by the previous Grand Magos and who has spent the intervening decades alone in the underground complex, cataloguing, maintaining, and monitoring artifacts that range from the obviously impressive (a metal alloy that has not corroded in four thousand years) to the deeply unsettling (a stone tablet that is warm to the touch regardless of ambient temperature and that produces, when held for more than a minute, a sensation of being observed). Odo is meticulous, lonely, and developing what his annual medical examination describes as "minor dissociative episodes consistent with prolonged isolation." What the medical report does not say: Odo has begun hearing sounds in the vault that are not produced by any catalogued object. The sounds are irregular, faint, and musical. They started approximately six months ago. Odo has not reported them. He is not sure they are real. He is not sure they aren't.

IV. THE ISLE — Landmarks and Features
The Pale Hall — The Order's administrative center and the Isle's largest building. A long, two-story stone structure built of the local grey-green basalt, with narrow windows, a steeply pitched slate roof, and an interior dominated by the Grand Reading Room — a chamber 150 feet long, lined floor-to-ceiling with bookshelves, lit by clerestory windows that admit light without allowing direct sun to touch the pages. The smell: old paper, lamp oil, stone dust, and the particular astringent tang of the preservation solutions the Record scholars use to protect deteriorating parchment. The sound: near-silence, broken by the rustle of pages, the scratch of quills, and the occasional muttered argument between scholars who have discovered that they disagree.
The Stacks — The library's deep storage: a multi-level underground complex carved into the island's basalt bedrock, accessible through a staircase at the rear of the Grand Reading Room. The Stacks descend seven levels. Each level is progressively more restricted: Level 1 (general collection, accessible to all Circles), Level 2 (specialized collections, Scribe and above), Level 3 (rare texts, Keeper and above), and so on down to Level 7, which is the restricted vault accessible only to the Grand Magos, the Vault-Keeper, and Elder Corvath (granted access by special dispensation for his Unseen research). The Stacks are cool, dry, and lit by oil lamps mounted in iron sconces that cast a warm, even light designed to minimize page damage. The air quality is maintained by a ventilation system of carved stone channels that the Natural World scholars believe was part of the island's original construction — Age of History engineering, still functioning.
The Smoke Hall — The School of Substances' laboratory complex on the Isle's eastern shore. A stone building with reinforced walls, blast shutters on the windows, and a ventilation tower that occasionally produces plumes of colored smoke visible from Brynvaal. The Smoke Hall has been rebuilt four times (1089 AF, 1167 AF, 1234 AF, and 1302 AF — the last after a Scribe named Vellen mixed something he shouldn't have with something else he shouldn't have and produced an explosion that shattered every glass vessel in the building). The current structure is built with extra-thick walls.
The Observatory — A tower on the island's highest point (approximately 300 feet above sea level), equipped with a rotating copper dome housing the Order's best lens — a ground-glass instrument of Heartlands manufacture that allows astronomers to observe the two suns, the two moons, and the stars with a clarity unavailable elsewhere on the continent. The Observatory doubles as a signal station: a mirror-flash system communicates with Brynvaal's Ferry Dock, transmitting weather reports, ferry schedules, and emergency messages.
The Pale Bell — A great bronze bell mounted in a stone belfry beside the Pale Hall. The Bell is rung only for three occasions: the election of a new Grand Magos, the death of an Elder, and the declaration of a Charter Emergency — a crisis severe enough to invoke the Isle's neutrality protections. The Bell has been rung for Charter Emergency exactly twice in history: once during the Nionian civil war (when Jous's agents attempted to seize the Isle's Nionian history archives), and once during a Teeth pirate raid in 1178 AF. The Bell's tone is deep, clear, and carries across the water to Brynvaal. When it rings, the Vallanaise know something has happened.
The Causeway — A natural rock formation connecting the Isle to a tiny satellite islet called Scholar's Rest — a flat, grassy rock where Magos take their rare leisure time. Fishing from the causeway, swimming in the sheltered cove, and sitting on the Rest's highest point watching the mainland coast are the Isle's primary recreational activities. The causeway is submerged at high tide, requiring timing for the crossing. Two Scribes have drowned over the centuries by misjudging the tide. A brass plaque on the Pale Hall reads: "The tide keeps its own schedule. So should you."
The Hidden Harbor — On the Isle's northern coast, opposite the main dock: a small, concealed cove accessible through a gap in the cliffs. The Hidden Harbor is known only to the Grand Magos, the Vault-Keeper, and a select number of Keepers. It is the access point for the vault's external supply route — materials too sensitive or too large for the main dock are landed here and carried to the vault through a tunnel cut into the bedrock. Keeper Alenn uses the Hidden Harbor when departing for Emberstone. Its existence is not recorded in any document that a novice could access.

V. LEGENDS OF THE ISLE
The Book That Writes Itself — The most famous Isle legend. In the deepest level of the Stacks, there is said to be a book — bound in pale leather, its pages blank — that writes itself. Words appear on the pages without human intervention: sometimes poetry, sometimes mathematics, sometimes passages in languages no living scholar can read. The book is never full — pages that have been written on go blank again after a time, and new text appears. No one knows who made the book. No one knows what it writes. The Record scholars consider the legend a metaphor for the archive's inexhaustibility. Elder Corvath, who has read the Logosian texts on residual consciousness, considers it a literal possibility: a sufficiently echo-dense artifact, saturated with the accumulated intellectual output of thousands of scholars over millennia, might develop emergent properties that mimic authorship. He has petitioned the Grand Magos for vault access to investigate. The petition has been declined. Three times.
The Drowned Scholar — A cautionary tale. A Scribe, obsessed with a text he was translating, refused to stop working when the archive's flooding alarm sounded (the lowest Stacks level occasionally floods during extreme tides). He continued translating as the water rose. He finished the translation as the water reached his chest. He drowned with the completed text held above his head. When the water receded, the text was found dry, undamaged, resting on a shelf above the tideline — as if someone had placed it there. The Scribe's body was found floating between the shelves, his quill still in his hand. The text he had been translating was a Xarian agricultural manual of no particular importance. The Magos buried him with full honors and installed a better flood-warning system.
The First Grand Magos's Promise — Elder Magos Kael, who oversaw the Isle's transition from imperial administration to independence, reportedly made a promise that has been passed down through every subsequent Grand Magos: "What is hidden here will outlast the world that hid it. Guard it. Do not use it. Do not understand it. Simply guard it." Whether this refers to the vault's contents, to the archive as a whole, or to something else entirely depends on which Elder you ask. The promise is not recorded in any official document. It is transmitted orally, Grand Magos to Grand Magos, on the night of their election.
The Tide Scholar — Recent lore, not yet legend. A Natural World Scribe named Maren (still living, age 28) has been conducting a long-term study of tidal patterns around the Isle. She has documented a gradual change in the tidal rhythm over the past three years — a shift of approximately four minutes per cycle that her mathematical models cannot explain. The shift correlates, she has noted, with the faint vibrations that Vault-Keeper Odo has been declining to report. Maren does not know about the vibrations. Odo does not know about the tidal shift. Neither knows about the Eldra-Veil breach. Grand Magos Thessaly, who reads all internal reports, has noticed both anomalies and is trying to connect them without sufficient theoretical framework. She has asked Elder Corvath for a consultation. The consultation is scheduled for next month.

XARIA — The Green Furnace (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — Gold, Blood, and the Canopy's Shadow

I. THE PENINSULA AT A GLANCE
Total Population: ~3,500,000 (including ~600,000 enslaved) Capital: Ix'Zaral — The Golden Seat (pop. ~1,000,000) Other Major Cities: Zari (~160,000), Canopolis (~105,000), Ix'Pal (~40,000), Porto das Plumas (~35,000), Bahia K'tharr (~20,000) Government: The Vizier (appointed by the Ix'Atani Dominion across the sea) governs the coast and delta. The interior jungle is governed by the temple-priesthoods. The two systems overlap, compete, and pretend to cooperate. Economy: Cacao, gold, jade, exotic hardwoods, spices, featherwork, slave labor, sacrificial economy, canal agriculture, and the tribute that flows across the ocean to the Dominion Religion: The Great Exchange — polytheistic, sacrificial, animistic. Loveism is unknown and would be incomprehensible. Provinces: Three recognized zones — the Coastal Dominion (Vizier's territory), Ix'baya (the river delta), K'thulon (the deep jungle interior)

II. THE PEOPLE
The Free
Xarians are dark-skinned — deep brown to blue-black — with broad features, strong builds, and the physical confidence of a people who consider themselves the center of the world. The Ix'Atani Dominion (the overseas empire that claims Xaria as a colony) is predominantly dark-skinned, and the local aristocracy mirrors this. Beauty standards prize deep color, height, symmetry, and elaborate personal adornment. A Xarian nobleman at court is a living artwork: facial scarification in geometric patterns (cut during coming-of-age, rubbed with pigment to produce raised colored scars), hair braided in architectures that take hours to construct, gold jewelry weighing pounds, and feathered garments of such complexity that a single cloak might represent a year of artisan labor.
Clothing is minimal in coverage and maximal in display. The heat makes layering absurd. The basic garment is a wrapped skirt or loincloth of dyed cotton, supplemented by shoulder-capes, chest-wraps, and the elaborate feathered mantles that indicate rank. Color is language: priests of K'tharr wear jaguar-gold and crimson. Priestesses of Ixchela wear serpent-green and black. Warriors wear the colors of their house. Merchants wear whatever they can afford. The poorest free Xarians still wear color — a strip of dyed cloth, a bead necklace, a flower in the hair. To be colorless is to be invisible.
The Bound — The Ashborn Caste
The slave population of Xaria is not a captured foreign people. They are native — a distinct ethnic group that the Ix'Atani theological framework classifies as Ashborn: people whose ancestors were "born from the ashes of a failed creation," a lesser humanity whose purpose is to serve the true-born. The theological justification is ancient, elaborate, and self-reinforcing.
The Ashborn are physically distinct: lighter skin ranging from olive to tawny brown, eyes that run hazel, amber, and green (colors vanishingly rare among the free population), and hair that is not the tight black coil of the Xarian majority but looser, wavier, with distinctive red-brown and ginger tones that catch the jungle light like copper wire. They are beautiful by any standard, and this beauty is part of their tragedy — Ashborn household slaves are selected for appearance, and the most striking serve as personal attendants, body-servants, and decorative presences in noble courts. The aesthetic is deliberate: the contrast between the deep-dark master and the copper-bright slave is a visual statement of hierarchy that every Xarian understands without explanation.
Treatment: The Ashborn are not, as a rule, treated with deliberate cruelty. The system is more insidious than that. They are treated as valuable property — fed adequately, housed acceptably, permitted family structures (within limits), and allowed personal possessions (within limits). An Ashborn household slave in a wealthy family lives better, materially, than a free Xarian peasant in the jungle villages. The poison is in the "within limits": they cannot leave. They cannot refuse. They cannot own land, bear arms, testify in temple courts, enter a teocalli above the second tier, or look a free person in the eyes during formal address. Their children are born Ashborn. Their grandchildren will be born Ashborn. The system has no exit.
Disobedience is where the gentleness ends. An Ashborn who defies a direct order, attempts escape, or commits violence against a free person is subject to the Brand — a red-hot copper seal pressed into the forehead that marks them permanently as defiant. Branded Ashborn are transferred to the canal-labor gangs or the quarry-crews where conditions are brutal and life expectancy drops to five years. A second offense is death — sacrifice on the temple altar, their blood offered to K'tharr as "the return of failed creation to the fire."
The Alonite Chain-Breakers — the mainland Lovist order dedicated to abolition — operate covertly on Xaria's western coast, smuggling escaped Ashborn to the mainland through Sangrea's Puerto Sombra. Their success rate is low. Their courage is extraordinary. The Xarian authorities consider them criminals and foreign provocateurs.

III. THE DOMINION — The Empire Across the Sea
The Ix'Atani Dominion is vast, wealthy, and distant. It occupies a continent across the eastern ocean — a landmass that no mainland person has ever visited and that the Xarians themselves describe in terms of hyperbolic grandeur: cities of gold, libraries of jade, armies of a million, a God-Emperor whose palace has ten thousand rooms. Whether any of this is true is unknowable from the mainland. What is known: the Dominion sends a new Vizier to Xaria every twenty years, collects annual tribute (gold, jade, cacao, feathers, slaves), and otherwise leaves the peninsula to govern itself. The Dominion's navy — the only force capable of crossing the eastern ocean — visits Xaria's ports twice yearly with the tribute fleet. The fleet is enormous: fifty to a hundred ships, crewed by Dominion sailors whose language, customs, and even physical appearance differ slightly from the colonial Xarians (taller, leaner, with elaborate full-body scarification that marks them as metropolitan citizens rather than colonials).
The Dominion does not interfere in Xarian internal politics unless tribute is threatened. This policy of benign neglect has allowed the peninsula to develop its own power dynamics — the Vizier's coastal authority versus the interior temple-priesthoods — without metropolitan correction. The current Vizier is the latest in a long line of distant administrators who govern through local proxies, collect their percentage, and focus their real attention on the Dominion's own internal politics (which are, by all reports, even more complex and violent than anything on the peninsula).
The Current Vizier: Lord-Governor Ix'Amara Zol (age ~55) — A Dominion aristocrat of the highest caste, sent to Xaria as either a reward (the post is lucrative) or a punishment (the post is remote). He is urbane, intelligent, fond of debate, generous with his hospitality, and genuinely curious about the mainland civilization that the Dominion has never bothered to contact. His relationship with Kaeo Argenhold — the Heartlands exile who spent eleven years as his guest — was one of genuine intellectual partnership: they debated governance, compared legal systems, shared smoke-leaf in the evenings, and developed a mutual respect that transcended the enormous cultural gap between them. Ix'Amara gave Kaeo gifts, slaves, and an education in power that no Heartlands court could have provided. He also showed Kaeo the machinery of exploitation — the canal-gangs, the tribute barges, the temple sacrifices — without apology or embarrassment, because in the Ix'Atani worldview, the system is not cruel. It is correct. The universe runs on exchange. Everything has a price. Everything is paid.

IV. THE HOUSES AND POWERS
THE COASTAL DOMINION — The Vizier's Territory
The Vizier's Court — Ix'Zaral
Ix'Zaral (The Golden Seat) is the peninsula's capital — a coastal city of 100,000 built on a natural harbor, its architecture a fusion of Dominion imperial style (massive stone platforms, broad ceremonial avenues, gold-leafed facades) and local jungle adaptation (elevated buildings on stone piles, open-air courtyards, canopy-shade engineering). The city is golden — not metaphorically but literally. Gold leaf covers every public building's upper surfaces. The afternoon sun hits Ix'Zaral and the city blazes like a second sun, visible from miles out to sea. The effect is deliberate: the Dominion's wealth made visible, made blinding, made inescapable.
The Vizier's Palace — the Ix'Amara Compound — occupies the city's highest ground: a complex of reception halls, administrative offices, private quarters, pleasure gardens, and the Hall of Tribute where the annual collection is weighed, recorded, and stored before the fleet carries it across the ocean. The Hall is the most secure building on the peninsula — stone walls, bronze doors, a guard force of Dominion-trained soldiers who answer only to the Vizier.
The Vizier's Household:
Lady Ix'Amara Tessai (age ~40) — The Vizier's wife. A Dominion noblewoman who considers Xaria a provincial backwater and makes no effort to conceal this opinion. She maintains a separate court of Dominion-born women who reproduce metropolitan fashions, speak metropolitan dialect, and regard the local population with well-bred disdain. She is sharp, bored, and dangerous in the way that intelligent people with too much power and too little purpose are dangerous.
Ix'Amara Kozel (age ~22) — The Vizier's eldest son. Born on Xaria, raised in both cultures, more comfortable in the colony than his mother would like. He has gone native in ways that alarm the metropolitan household: he speaks the local dialect fluently, wears local-style featherwork, and has taken an Ashborn concubine — a green-eyed woman named Yara — whose presence in his chambers is tolerated because Kozel is the Vizier's heir and heirs are indulged.
Captain Ix'Amara Djen (age ~35) — The Vizier's brother, commander of the palace guard. A professional soldier with no interest in politics and considerable interest in the local fighting traditions. He trains with House Ya'ax jungle warriors when he can arrange it, considers them the finest light infantry he's ever seen, and is quietly terrified of what would happen if the interior houses ever unified against the coast.
House Ix'za — The River Kings
Seat: Zari — the floating city of stilts and bridges (pop. ~60,000) Sigil: A golden caiman crowned with jade, on river-blue Words: "The River Remembers"
The Ix'za controlled the delta for centuries — managing trade, collecting tribute, maintaining the canal systems that turn the floodplain into the peninsula's breadbasket. Their power was built on water: whoever controls the canals controls the food supply. Their navy (river barges, not ocean-going ships) was the delta's military backbone.
Then came the Red Tide — the pirate fleet that swept in from the sea three years ago. The Ix'za navy responded late, fought poorly, and was crushed. The pirates sacked the outer delta. Zari nearly burned. Salvation came from the jungle interior — House Hok'ul's warriors descending the rivers in war-canoes, annihilating the pirates in a series of ambushes called the Red Tide Defiance.
The Ix'za have not recovered. Their navy is rebuilt (with Jade Cabal money) but their legitimacy is shattered. Everyone knows who actually saved the delta. The River Kings sit on their stilts and pretend to rule.
Lord Ix'za Pakal (age 60) — The River King. Once imposing, now diminished — a large man going soft, his court still dazzling (jade, silk, gold, the finest featherwork) but his authority hollow. He drinks cacao laced with fermented honey from dawn to midnight. His decisions are made by the Jade Cabal's representatives who sit beside his throne and whisper.
Lady Ix'za Ahau (age 45) — Pakal's wife. Smarter and harder than her husband, she has been conducting secret negotiations with House Hok'ul, attempting to arrange a marriage alliance that would preserve the Ix'za name inside whatever new order emerges. She is willing to sacrifice everything except her children's survival.
Prince Ix'za Balam (age 20) — Heir. Named for the ancient jungle house in a gesture of diplomatic flattery. Young, angry, aware that his inheritance is being hollowed out from beneath him. He has been training with House Ya'ax warriors against his father's wishes, learning jungle warfare from the people who humiliated his family. His motivation: if he can't beat them, he'll become them.
The Jade Cabal
Not a house but a guild — the gem traders who control the jade supply that is Xaria's second-most-valuable export (after gold). The Cabal operates from Zari's market district, maintaining jade-cutting workshops, trading offices, and a private security force of mercenaries who guard the jade caravans. They are the delta's real economic power — they fund the Ix'za court, bankroll the navy's reconstruction, and hold debt-bonds on half the delta's landowners.
Cabal Master Ix'Kaan (age 55) — Leader. A self-made merchant who rose from a minor trading family to control the Cabal through a combination of business acumen and the strategic elimination of competitors (three rival traders died in "accidents" during his ascent; none were investigated). He is calm, patient, and utterly transactional. He has no political ideology. He has balance sheets.

IX'BAYA — The Delta Heartland
The river delta: a world of brown water, green growth, and the slow, heavy heat of a landscape that is half land and half river. The canals are the streets. Barges are the vehicles. The architecture is stilts and platforms — buildings elevated above the floodline on hardwood pilings, connected by bridges and walkways. During the wet season, the delta floods and the villages become islands. During the dry season, the mud emerges and the canals shrink to channels.
House B'alam — The Ancient Ones
Seat: B'alam House, outer delta (a fortified compound on the highest ground in the delta — a natural hill that stays dry even during the worst floods) Sigil: A black jaguar on a field of stars Words: "Before the River, We Were"
The oldest noble house on the peninsula. The B'alam claim pre-Dominion ancestry — they were here before the Ix'Atani arrived, before the Great Exchange was formalized, before the temple-cities were built. Their lineage stretches into the Age of History. They are the traditional kingmakers — their endorsement legitimizes any ruler. Without B'alam recognition, no River King is truly king.
Elder Ix'B'alam Yax (age 75) — Patriarch. Ancient, blind in one eye, still sharp. He is the most respected voice in the delta and he has said nothing publicly about the Tribute Standoff. His silence is deafening. Both sides are courting him. He is waiting to see who offers more — not money (the B'alam have land-wealth that predates gold currency) but assurance that the old order will survive. He suspects it won't. He is deciding which version of the new order he can live with.
Ix'B'alam Kan (age 30) — Grandson and heir. A warrior-scholar who studied at the Vizier's court and who has the rare distinction of being respected by both the coastal elite and the interior priesthoods. He is being positioned by his grandfather as a compromise candidate — someone who could bridge the delta and the jungle if the current crisis boils over.

K'THULON — The Deep Interior
The jungle. Dense, ancient, echo-saturated, and governed by the temple-priesthoods who have been accumulating power for centuries while the coast grew fat and careless.
House Hok'ul — The Temple Keepers
Seat: Canopolis — the treetop city (pop. ~15,000, built in the canopy 80 feet above the forest floor) Sigil: A feathered serpent coiled around a pyramid, on deep green Words: "The Gods Hunger"
The ascendant power. House Hok'ul was a religious order that became a political dynasty — the keepers of the hidden temples, the maintainers of the sacrificial calendar, the interpreters of divine will. Their leader's charisma and the Red Tide Defiance have transformed them from interior mystics into the peninsula's most powerful military force.
High Priest Ix'Hok'ul Chaak (age 50) — The most dangerous man in Xaria. Charismatic, devout, brilliant, and possessed of a certainty that mirrors Jous Lorethian's (though in a completely different theological framework). Chaak believes the Great Exchange demands more than the coast is giving — that the Ix'za's corruption has weakened the sacrificial cycle, that K'tharr is hungry, that the world is fraying because the blood-debt is unpaid. His solution: purification. Increased sacrifice. Stricter observance. And the removal of any power that stands between the gods and their due.
Chaak's echo-sensitivity is high — the jungle interior's dense echo-field has produced a population of naturally sensitive individuals, and Chaak is among the most sensitive. He interprets his perceptions as divine communication (K'tharr speaks to him in dreams, in the movement of jaguars, in the pattern of rainfall). He is not a fraud. He genuinely experiences what he claims to experience. His interpretation of the experience is culturally determined and, by mainland standards, terrifying.
War-Chief Ya'ax Bol (age 35) — Commander of Hok'ul's military arm. House Ya'ax provides the warriors; Bol leads them. He is the man who planned and executed the Red Tide Defiance — the river ambushes that destroyed the pirate fleet. He is quiet, methodical, and capable of extraordinary violence delivered with extraordinary precision. He paints his face with jaguar-spots before battle (a Ya'ax tradition) and carries a macuahuitl — a wooden sword edged with obsidian blades — that he has named Ix'Chaak (K'tharr's Tooth).
Priestess Ix'chel Naia (age 40) — Head of House Ix'chel, the medicine-gatherers. She provides Hok'ul with the botanical knowledge that is the jungle's most valuable resource — poisons for warfare, medicines for the faithful, and the hallucinogenic preparations that the priests use for ritual communion with the gods. She is the only person in the interior whose authority rivals Chaak's, because she controls the pharmacopoeia and without her compounds, the ritual cycle cannot function. She is loyal to Chaak. She is also watching him with the careful attention of a woman who knows that holy men can become monsters.

V. ADDITIONAL HOUSES AND POWERS
House K'ay — The Story-Keepers — Oral historians, loremasters, the keepers of the peninsula's memory. Not warriors, not priests — bards, essentially, whose function is to remember and to narrate. They travel between settlements singing the histories, and their accounts are considered legally binding — a K'ay storyteller's recitation of a treaty's terms is admissible in temple court. Current Speaker: K'ay Itzam (age 60), a man who has memorized over two thousand songs and who is currently composing the epic of the Red Tide Defiance, which will become the definitive account of events and will, incidentally, be extremely favorable to House Hok'ul. He knows this. He is doing it anyway, because the Hok'ul won and history belongs to winners.
House T'zolk'in — The Calendar Priests — A minor priestly house that maintains the ritual calendar — the ten-count year, the festival schedule, the sacrificial timing. Not politically powerful but institutionally essential. The calendar determines when sacrifices occur, which determines when wars can be fought, which determines everything. Current Calendar-Keeper: T'zolk'in Ahau (age 70), a meticulous old priest who has been maintaining the calendar for forty years and who considers political power a distraction from the sacred mathematics of time.
House Kuk'ul — The Feather-Workers — Artisan house controlling the featherwork trade. Their products — cloaks, headdresses, ceremonial garments constructed from quetzal, macaw, and toucan plumage — are the peninsula's most valuable luxury export. A High Priest's feathered mantle can take five years to produce and is worth more than a Heartlands duchy. Current Master: Kuk'ul Ah'kin (age 45), a perfectionist whose workshop in Ix'Zaral produces work of such quality that the Dominion's metropolitan court has placed standing orders.
The Canal Guilds — The organizations that maintain the delta's irrigation infrastructure. Technically apolitical, practically essential. The guilds employ free Xarians and Ashborn labor in roughly equal numbers (the Ashborn do the dangerous underwater work — clearing blockages, repairing submerged walls — while the free workers manage and supervise). The guilds are the delta's working class and their collective action capability is significant: a canal strike would starve the cities within weeks. Current Guild-Master: Ix'Tun Batz (age 50), a pragmatist who has kept the guilds neutral during the Tribute Standoff and who is being courted by every faction.
The Scarlet Order — A priestly military order dedicated to K'tharr, functioning as the temple-cities' permanent garrison. Not as large as the Sons of Loreth but better trained for jungle warfare. Their warriors undergo a ritual scarification process — vertical cuts from forehead to chin, filled with red pigment — that gives them a permanently bleeding appearance. They are feared. Current Commander: Ix'Scarlet Votan (age 38), a zealot who considers Chaak a prophet and who has been advocating for a full military campaign against the Ix'za coast — not a standoff but a conquest. Chaak has restrained him. So far.

VI. MAJOR CITIES
Ix'Zaral (pop. ~100,000) — The Golden Seat. Described above. The coast's center of gravity — Dominion administration, international trade, the tribute fleet's home port. Districts: the Gold Quarter (Vizier's palace, administrative complex, Dominion military garrison), the Plume Market (the continent's largest marketplace for featherwork, jade, gold, and slaves), the Canal Quarter (residential, built on stilts over the coastal wetlands), and the Ash District (the Ashborn quarter — segregated, walled, patrolled, but internally self-governing under an appointed Ashborn headman).
Zari (pop. ~60,000) — The Floating City. Built entirely on stilts and platforms in the river delta, connected by bridges and walkways. No solid ground. Everything moves: the buildings sway in high winds, the platforms rise and fall with the water level, and the entire city drifts imperceptibly downstream over decades (the pilings are replaced in rotation, effectively rebuilding the city one post at a time). Districts: the Jade Court (Ix'za palace, Jade Cabal headquarters), the Barge Ring (commercial docks surrounding the city like a floating wall), the Weaver's Maze (artisan quarter, famously easy to get lost in), and the Under-City (the space beneath the platforms, accessible only by boat, where smugglers, fugitives, and escaped Ashborn hide in the shadows between the pilings).
Ix'Pal (pop. ~40,000) — The oldest temple-city on the peninsula. Built around a massive step-pyramid — the Great Teocalli of K'tharr — that rises 250 feet above the jungle canopy and is visible for twenty miles. Ix'Pal is the religious capital: the Great Exchange's highest ceremonies are performed here, the calendar is maintained here, and the most important sacrifices (including the annual Sun-Feeding, when captured warriors are offered to K'tharr at the summer solstice) take place on the Teocalli's summit platform. The city is ancient — its foundations are Age of History construction, echo-engineered stone that has not shifted in millennia. The priests know the foundations are special. They attribute the stability to K'tharr's blessing. They are wrong about the theology and right about the engineering.
Porto das Plumas (pop. ~35,000) — The Feather Port. Xaria's western trading city, the point of contact between the peninsula and the mainland. Named for the featherwork that is its primary export. The port is where mainland traders — Sangrean merchants, Horns sailors, the occasional Heartlands factor — come to buy Xarian goods. It is also where the Chain-Breakers operate, smuggling Ashborn escapees onto westbound ships. The city's culture is the most hybridized on the peninsula: mainland Munnish is spoken alongside Xarian dialect, Lovist chapels exist alongside Great Exchange shrines, and the food is a fusion of jungle ingredients and mainland cooking techniques that produces dishes found nowhere else.
Canopolis (pop. ~15,000) — The Treetop City. House Hok'ul's seat. Built in the jungle canopy — platforms, bridges, walkways, dwellings, and temple structures all suspended 60-100 feet above the forest floor. The engineering is remarkable: the Hok'ul builders work with the trees rather than against them, integrating living trunks into the structural framework so that the city and the forest are a single organism. Canopolis has no streets. It has branches.
Bahia K'tharr (pop. ~20,000) — A coastal temple-city on the peninsula's southern shore, dedicated to K'tharr's oceanic aspect (the Sun-Jaguar who dives into the sea each night to battle the darkness). Famous for its annual Festival of the Drowning Sun — a week-long celebration during which the entire city's population wades into the ocean at sunset, holding torches above their heads, and stands in waist-deep water until the sun disappears. The visual — 20,000 torches reflected in the black water — is reportedly the most beautiful sight on the peninsula.

VII. MINOR SETTLEMENTS — Concise Gazetteer
Coastal Dominion
Porto Ouro (~15,000) — Gold-processing port. Smelting works, refineries, the stench of hot metal. Aldeia das Correntes (~12,000) — "Village of Chains." Slave market town. Ashborn are bought and sold here. Chain-Breakers have tried to shut it down twice. Both times, fire. Praia Sagrada (~1,500) — Sacred Beach. Where the Dominion's tribute fleet lands twice yearly. For two weeks, the beach becomes a city of tents, warehouses, and the controlled chaos of loading a hundred ships. Mangalar (~3,000) — Mangrove town. Built on platforms in the coastal mangroves. Fishing, crab-trapping, and the production of mangrove salt — a smoky, mineral-rich salt that Xarian cuisine depends on. Forte Ix'Amara (~800) — The Vizier's coastal fortress. Military garrison, signal tower, the peninsula's primary defensive position against seaborne threats. Built after the Red Tide. Recife dos Mortos (~400) — Reef of the Dead. A fishing hamlet on a coral reef where, according to local legend, the spirits of drowned sailors gather on moonless nights. Fishermen leave offerings of rum and tobacco on the reef's highest rock.
Ix'baya (Delta)
Ix'Canal (~8,000) — The delta's largest non-Zari settlement. Canal junction, grain processing, barge repair. Aldeia do Lodo (~1,500) — Mud Village. Built on a mud flat that floods annually. The inhabitants rebuild every year. They have been doing this for three centuries. They refuse to relocate. Ponte B'alam (~2,500) — B'alam family's secondary holding. Bridge town controlling a critical canal crossing. Arrozal (~4,000) — Rice town. The delta's primary grain-producing settlement. Three harvests per year. The rice is fertilized with bone-ash from the temple sacrifices — a practice that the Ashanite clergy on the mainland would find theologically horrifying and agriculturally effective. Ix'Mercado (~3,000) — The delta's floating market — not a town but a permanent aggregation of trade-barges anchored at a canal junction, forming a commercial district that can relocate if the water levels change. Aldeias Cinzas (~1,000) — Ash Villages. A cluster of Ashborn settlements in the delta's least desirable territory — low ground, flood-prone, mosquito-infested. The Ashborn here are "field-bound" — attached to the rice paddies and canal-maintenance crews. Their headwoman, Ashborn Maela (age 40), is the closest thing the Ashborn have to a political leader and the person the Chain-Breakers contact when organizing escapes.
K'thulon (Interior)
Templo Verde (~5,000) — Green Temple. A temple-city in the mid-jungle, halfway between Canopolis and the delta. Dedicated to Ixchela. The priestesses here maintain the peninsula's largest medicinal garden — over five hundred plant species cultivated in a cleared area surrounding the temple pyramid. Cruce del Jaguar (~2,000) — Jaguar's Crossing. Where two jungle rivers meet. Ya'ax warrior training camp. Young warriors are brought here for their initiation — a three-day solo survival exercise in the jungle with only a knife and a gourd of water. Approximately one in twenty initiates dies. The deaths are considered acceptable. Aldeia Canora (~800) — Song Village. A K'ay settlement where the storytellers train their apprentices. The village's sound — constant singing, chanting, the rhythmic clap of hands keeping time — is audible from half a mile away. Raiz Negra (~500) — Black Root. The deepest permanent human settlement in the Xarian jungle. An Ix'chel gathering station where the rarest medicinal plants are collected. Accessible only by river. The journey from Canopolis takes five days by canoe. The plants gathered here include compounds for which the Cascabella of Sangrea would pay their weight in gold. Altar do Sangue (~1,000) — Blood Altar. A sacrificial site on a hilltop cleared from the jungle, where the annual Sun-Feeding's captives are gathered before being marched to Ix'Pal. The site is permanently staffed by Scarlet Order warriors. The hilltop clearing is the only place in the interior where you can see the sky without canopy interference. The view is spectacular. The purpose is terrible. Ponte das Serpentes (~1,200) — Bridge of Serpents. Named for the anaconda population that infests the river crossing. A Ya'ax garrison town that also serves as a border checkpoint between the delta and the interior.

VIII. NATURAL FEATURES
The Rio Ix'za (Great River) — The peninsula's central waterway. Broad, slow, brown, navigable for its entire length. The delta it creates is the agricultural engine of the peninsula. Caiman-infested. The river is sacred to Ixchela — offerings are thrown in at every crossing, every departure, every return.
The Selvaverde Interior — The jungle. The most echo-dense environment on the mainland. Ancient growth, never cleared, never cultivated (the Hok'ul practice canopy agriculture rather than ground-clearing). The echo-field here is strong enough that naturally sensitive individuals experience the "green attention" — the feeling of being watched, of the forest being aware. In the deepest interior, the sensation becomes overwhelming for mainland visitors. Kaeo Argenhold, during his eleven years, reportedly spent weeks in the deep jungle at the Vizier's invitation and returned "changed" — quieter, more watchful, with a habit of pausing mid-conversation to listen to something no one else could hear.
The Coral Coast — The peninsula's eastern shore. Warm, shallow water over a coral reef system that extends for two hundred miles. The reef produces the pearl, shell, and coral that supplement the peninsula's luxury trade. The reef is also the Dominion fleet's primary navigation hazard — the tribute ships must navigate a single deep-water channel through the reef, guided by local pilots whose knowledge is hereditary and closely guarded.
The Jade Mountains — A low mountain range in the peninsula's interior, source of the jade deposits that the Jade Cabal controls. The mountains are volcanic in origin (dormant, not active) and the jade occurs in veins within the basalt — exactly the geological conditions that produce echo-dense stone. The Jade Mountains are the peninsula's most echo-rich non-jungle environment. Miners report strange effects: tools that don't rust, wounds that heal faster than expected, and a persistent humming in the deep shafts that is below hearing range but felt in the bones. The miners attribute this to the jade itself. They are not entirely wrong.
The Mangrove Labyrinth — The coastal wetland between the delta and the open sea. A maze of mangrove channels, tidal flats, and mud islands. Navigable only by locals. The Labyrinth is where the Chain-Breakers hide their escape routes — the channels are too shallow and tangled for pursuit by the Vizier's naval vessels, and the mangroves provide cover from aerial observation. It is also home to the peninsula's largest caiman population and a mosquito density that can drive a person mad within hours.

IX. CUSTOMS AND PRACTICES
The Flower Wars — Ritual combat between temple-cities, fought not for territory but for sacrificial captives. The Flower Wars are scheduled, announced, and conducted according to strict rules: both sides send equal numbers of warriors, the fighting occurs on a designated field, and the objective is to capture (not kill) opponents for later sacrifice. The captured warriors are treated with honor before their death — fed the finest food, dressed in the finest garments, and given one night with any companion they choose. Their sacrifice is considered the highest honor the Great Exchange can bestow: they feed the sun.
The Mask Festival (H'uun's Madness) — Five days of chaos. The fifth count of the Xarian calendar is dedicated to H'uun, the Monkey-Trickster, and the festival that marks it is Xaria's carnival: masks, costumes, dance, music, role-reversal (masters serve slaves for one day — the Day of Reversal — a safety valve that the system tolerates because it prevents the pressure from building to explosion), public intoxication, and the competitive mask-dances in which performers wearing elaborate animal masks dance for hours, the last dancer standing winning prestige and prizes. The costumes are extraordinary — feathered, gilded, jeweled constructions that cost a year's wages and that their wearers consider money well spent.
The Canal Races — Barge races through the delta's canal system, held during the dry season when water levels are manageable. Teams of twelve paddlers race barges decorated in house colors through a course that winds through the delta's channels. The races are simultaneously athletic competition, gambling opportunity, and political theater — a house whose barge wins gains prestige. Ashborn crews are permitted to race (a rare arena where they compete equally with free Xarians), and an Ashborn victory is celebrated with complex emotions: pride from the Ashborn community, discomfort from the masters, and the unspoken acknowledgment that a people who can beat you in a fair race might eventually wonder why they can't beat you in other arenas.
The Smoke Circle — A social institution. Xarian nobles, priests, and intellectuals gather in the evenings to smoke green leaf (a mild narcotic herb — the substance Kaeo and the Vizier shared), drink cacao, and debate philosophy, politics, theology, and gossip. The Smoke Circle is Xaria's salon, its parliament, and its confessional combined. What is said in the Smoke Circle is technically confidential. In practice, everything leaks. The institution persists because the act of leaking is itself a form of communication — you reveal what you want revealed, and the Circle is the mechanism for controlled disclosure.

X. LEGENDS AND MYTHS
The First Exchange — The creation myth. Before the world existed, there was only darkness and two gods: K'tharr (the jaguar of fire) and Ix'Tza (the serpent of water). They fought. The fighting produced sparks (stars), blood (rivers), and fragments of their bodies (mountains, forests, the earth itself). Neither won. Both were diminished. The world exists because two gods destroyed each other making it. The lesson: creation requires sacrifice. Life requires death. The Exchange is not a choice. It is the structure of reality.
The Ashborn's Origin — The theological justification for slavery. After the world was created, K'tharr attempted to make humans from sunlight and earth. The first attempt failed — the creatures were pale, soft, wrong. K'tharr burned them, but the ashes retained a spark of incomplete life. From the ashes, the Ashborn emerged — lesser beings, half-made, marked by their pale skin and strange-colored eyes. The second attempt, made with blood and volcanic stone, succeeded: the true-born, dark and strong, fully alive. The Ashborn exist to serve the true-born because they are the remnants of a failed creation — not evil, not cursed, simply incomplete. The theology is elegant, self-serving, and has survived every challenge for millennia because the people it benefits have no incentive to question it.
The Feathered Serpent — Xaria's dragon. A creature described in the oldest K'ay songs as a serpent covered in iridescent plumage, capable of flight, dwelling in the deepest jungle where the canopy touches the clouds. The Feathered Serpent is not a god — it is something older, something that predates the Great Exchange, something that the gods themselves could not consume. It sleeps. If it wakes, the Exchange ends — not because the serpent is good or evil, but because it is outside the system. It does not give and it does not take. It simply is. The Feathered Serpent is the most echo-dense creature in Xarian mythology, and unlike most mythical creatures, the K'ay songs describe it with a specificity that suggests an actual animal: "its scales were green as new leaves, its feathers were every color the sky has ever been, its eyes were gold and looked at you as if you were the dream and it was the dreamer."
The River That Flows Backward — A legend about a section of the Rio Ix'za that, during certain tidal conditions, reverses its flow — the ocean pushes upstream, and the river runs backward for several hours. This is a real tidal bore phenomenon, but the legend attached to it is richer: the backward river is Ixchela mourning her dead children (the sacrificed), and the reversal is her attempt to undo what has been done — to take back the blood, to unflow the river of sacrifice. She fails every time. The river resumes its normal course. The dead stay dead. The Exchange continues. Xarian mothers stand on the riverbank during the bore and weep. Not because they are sad. Because Ixchela requires company in her grief.
The City That Sank — An Ix'za legend. A delta city — Ix'Zanab — once rivaled Zari in size and splendor. Its lord refused to pay tribute to the Dominion. One night, the ground beneath the city liquefied and Ix'Zanab sank into the mud. The entire population — 30,000 people — disappeared. The site is known: a patch of delta where the water is always warm, where plants grow faster than anywhere else in the marsh, and where, during the dry season when the water recedes, you can see the tops of buildings just below the surface. No one has ever dived to investigate. No one will. The city is considered a warning. The warm water and the fast-growing plants are considered the city's inhabitants, transformed — still alive, still building, still refusing to pay. The echo-theory explanation: an entire city's worth of echo-dense construction material, submerged in waterlogged soil, creating a localized echo-reservoir that accelerates biological processes in its vicinity. The Xarian explanation is better.
The Night of the Jaguar — Every Xarian child is told: once in a lifetime, K'tharr walks the earth in jaguar form. He visits every home. If the family has honored the Exchange — if they have sacrificed, if they have given blood, if they have fed the sun — K'tharr passes by and the family sleeps undisturbed. If the family has been stingy — if they have withheld, if they have refused the knife — K'tharr enters the house and takes one. Not the strongest. Not the weakest. The one the family loves most. The legend is enforcement. The fear is real. Every Xarian family, even the wealthiest, even the most skeptical, makes an offering before bed: a bowl of blood (animal blood, purchased from temple butchers) placed outside the door. The bowls are empty by morning. Cats, probably. Or jaguars. Or K'tharr.
The Mask That Speaks — An H'uun legend. During the Mask Festival, a mask-maker carved a mask so perfect that it became alive. The mask spoke to its wearer, whispering secrets — where treasure was buried, who was unfaithful, what the future held. The wearer became the richest person in Xaria. But the mask would not come off. It grew into the wearer's face, replacing their features, until the wearer was the mask and the mask was the wearer. They were last seen walking into the jungle, laughing in a voice that was not their own. During H'uun's Madness, mask-makers include a deliberate flaw in every mask — a crooked line, an asymmetrical eye, a missing tooth — to prevent the mask from becoming too perfect. Too perfect, in Xaria, is too dangerous. Perfection belongs to the gods. Humans survive by being incomplete.
The Ashborn's Song — Not told by the free Xarians. Told only among the Ashborn, in whispers, in the quarters, at night. The song says: the Ashborn are not the failed creation. They are the first creation — the original humans, made before K'tharr learned to be cruel. The true-born came second, made with blood because the gods had already used up all the gentleness on the Ashborn. The pale skin is not a mark of failure. It is the color of the world before violence. The green eyes are not wrong. They see things the dark eyes cannot — they see the world as it was before the Exchange began. The song is illegal. Singing it is punished by the Brand. It is sung anyway, every night, in every Ashborn quarter on the peninsula. The masters cannot stop it. They cannot hear it. The Ashborn sing it so softly that only Ashborn ears, tuned to the frequency of survival, can pick it up. This is not metaphor. The Ashborn have developed, over generations of enforced silence, a vocal register — a sub-whisper, a vibration more felt than heard — that carries between bodies in close proximity but does not project beyond a few feet. They call it the Hush. It is the most sophisticated communication technology on the peninsula, and no one who oppresses them knows it exists.

ROSLAND — The Iron Commons (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — The Republic That Forgot Itself

I. THE REGION AT A GLANCE
Total Population: ~3,200,000 Capital: Fairhaven (pop. ~160,000) Other Major Cities: Forgetown (~80,000), Twinbridges (~45,000), Karthold (~30,000), Blackridge (~20,000) Government: Republic under the Iron Codex. High Baron elected every 10 years by noble houses and guilds. Currently Vlado Ironside (term ends 1311 AF). The Long Vigil emergency powers have suspended key provisions. Economy: Iron mining, steel, timber, coal, grain, livestock, fur, arms manufacturing, road-tolls Religion: Orthodox Loveism with strong Alonite character. Pre-Lovist Aethelian folk traditions persist throughout the countryside. Provinces: The Greens, Fyrhold, Nordmarch, The Daudrwood March, The Western Shore

II. THE HOUSES
HOUSE IRONSIDE — The Iron Fist
Seat: Forgetown, Fyrhold | Sigil: Black iron hammer on grey stone | Words: "Strength Is Order"
High Baron Vlado Ironside (age 56) — Competent authoritarian. The Long Vigil has suspended guild voting, expanded appointment powers, created the Vigil Wardens. Each measure individually justified. Collectively, a noose. Physically imposing, forge-scarred hands, speaks rarely. His adopted heir Valo (age 22) has read the Iron Codex and privately understands what it means. He has not shared this doubt.
Inner circle: Marshal Gregor Stelev (age 50) — army commander, Fyrhold loyalist, brutal when required. Lady Katva Ironside (age 48) — Vlado's sister, runs the mines, harder than her brother, considers Valo weak. Vigil-Captain Drazen Morov (age 35) — head of the Vigil Wardens, most hated man in Rosland outside Fyrhold, talent for surveillance and quiet pressure.
HOUSE GREENHAND — The People's Shield
Seat: Greenhand Hall, Fairhaven | Sigil: Green open hand on golden wheat | Words: "For the Commons, Always"
Lord Aldric Greenhand (age 62) — Leader of the Commons' Cause, fighting the Long Vigil through legal channels. The legal channels are failing. Courts packed with Ironside appointees. Guild vote diluted. Pamphlets confiscated. Has not yet considered alternatives to legal resistance. His daughter has.
Mila Greenhand (age 28) — Impatient, confrontational, meeting with disaffected officers and House Riverblade representatives. Not planning a coup. Planning a contingency. Tomek Greenhand (age 25) — Scholar, poet, fire-song composer, gentle, the family member most likely to be sacrificed by events.
HOUSE RIVERBLADE — The Northern Watch
Seat: Riverblade Keep, Twinbridges | Sigil: Silver sword crossing a blue river | Words: "The Crossing Is Ours"
Lord Davor Riverblade (age 55) — Career soldier, thirty years on the northern frontier. Leans Ironside but distrusts Vlado's ambition. Politely freezing out the Vigil Wardens. Yelena Riverblade (age 30) — River navy commander, the person Mila Greenhand is courting. Has not committed. Listening. Ser Petrov Riverblade (age 22) — Garrison commander, young, eager, exploitable temper.
HOUSE DAURN — The Old Blood
Seat: Daurnkeep, Daudrwood March | Sigil: White stag on black forest | Words: "We Remember the Oath"
Lord Harren Daurn (age 65) — The White Stag. Moral authority of Rosland. Both factions court his endorsement. Has given neither. His silence is its own statement. Verra Daurn (age 35) — Frostguard commander. Rosland's most echo-sensitive person without knowing it. Senses weather, tracks by presence, avoids ambush by feeling hostility. Considers this normal. It is not. Old Marek Daurn (age 88) — Last link to the old Daudrwood. Tells stories from a tradition older than Loveism.
HOUSE BOROS — The New Forge
Seat: Boros Works, Fairhaven | Sigil: Golden gear on copper | Words: "Build Forward"
Lord Pavel Boros (age 48) — Engineer, Greenhand's financial backer. Supports democracy because stable governance is better for business. 3,000 workers. Irina Boros (age 24) — Engineer, developing water-powered hammer systems. Brilliant, socially awkward, uninterested in politics.
HOUSE GORBAN — The Southern Gate
Seat: Gorban Hold, Daudrwood March border | Sigil: Grey wolf on white snow | Words: "We Watch the Cold"
Lord Edrik Gorban (age 45) — Sending increasingly urgent reports about southern anomalies — Heartlands gold traders, Frozen South clansmen in new places, something enormous on the coast. Fairhaven isn't listening.
MINOR HOUSES
House Colov — Mining magnates, Fyrhold. Lord Branko (age 52) never enters his own mines. Son Yuri (age 28) has, came back changed. House Stelev — Master smiths, Forgetown. Matriarch Zora (age 68), Gregor's mother, forge-master fifty years. House Bridgestone — Nordmarch engineers. House Dulagn — River fishermen, Riverblade vassals. House Varn — Grain merchants, Greenhand allies. House Zelnik — Western Shore fishing fleet. House Drenov — Daudrwood charcoal-burners, Daurn vassals. House Karev — Coal miners, Colov rivals. House Stolk — Brewers. Stolk Dark beer. Politically neutral because everyone needs beer.

III. MAJOR CITIES
Fairhaven (pop. ~160,000) — The Free City. Three-river confluence. Timber and stone, heavy and practical. The Great Muster Field with Speaking Stone and Oath-Oak. The Guildhall Quarter. The Baron's Hall — conspicuously modest, except Vlado's new wing (the Greenhands call it "the creep"). Districts: Guildhall Quarter, River Market, The Smokes (industrial), Oldtown, Southbank (working-class, Greenhand-aligned), The Frostgate (southern road).
Forgetown (pop. ~80,000) — Half underground. Hundreds of forges. Permanent smoke. The Smith's Council Hall, the Greygold Syndicate Vault, Ironside's Iron Keep carved into the mountainside.
Twinbridges (pop. ~45,000) — Two bridges spanning the border river. Fortified southern bank, trade zone on the northern. Ferrymasters' Guild, Customs House.
Karthold (pop. ~30,000) — The Coal City. Grim. Rivers run black. But the worked-out mine shafts have been converted to taverns and performance halls. Annual Hammer Festival — three days of forge-beat competition in the deep shafts.
Blackridge (pop. ~20,000) — The Charcoal Capital. Daudrwood's northern edge. Currently neutral, leaning Daurn.

IV. MINOR SETTLEMENTS
The Greens
Holmgard (~8,000) — Grain hub, House Varn granary complex, annual Harvest Court. Millhaven (~5,000) — Twelve water-powered mills. Volksted (~3,000) — Livestock fair, sausage competition (47 varieties). Zeleny Most (~2,500) — Green Bridge, Ayanite courthouse, fair-minded Magistrate Oksana. Dubrava (~1,500) — Oak-grove, annual fire-song festival. The oldest pre-imperial songs performed here only. Pashkovo (~1,200) — Flax and linen, matrilineal weavers' guild. Staraya Polyana (~800) — Ancient village, domovoi shrines in every household. Brodava (~2,000) — Ford-town on the Tikhaya. Known for reed-thatch, mosquitoes, and rusalka sightings. Korchma (~1,500) — Inn-town on the main north-south road. Seven inns. Neutral ground where Ironside and Greenhand agents drink at separate tables. Medovka (~600) — Honey village. Apiaries producing the wildflower honey used in Roslandic mead. The bee-keeper, Babushka Zoya (age 72), knows every hive by temperament. Zhitnitsa (~3,500) — Grain-Barn. The Greens' second-largest grain storage facility. Brothers of the Open Road waystation.
Fyrhold
Ugleva (~6,000) — Copper and tin mines, Bronze Guild. Ruzhny (~4,000) — Weapons town, every household a workshop. Kamengrad (~3,000) — Quarry town, grey granite. Zheleznaya (~2,000) — Iron-Water mineral springs, Sisters of the Rust Ashanite hospice. Dymselo (~1,500) — Smoke Village, charcoal kilns. Gorny Klyuch (~800) — Mountain Key pass-town, Ironside garrison. Plotilnya (~2,500) — Sawmill town. Produces the timber frames for Rosland's construction industry. Rudnik (~1,800) — Raw-ore processing settlement. The smelters here run day and night during production season. The river downstream is permanently orange. Ognevka (~700) — Fire-Village. Named for the forge-fires visible from miles away. A Stelev family workshop produces the ceremonial blades awarded to graduating military officers. Kamenny Brod (~1,000) — Stone Ford. The only reliable crossing of the Fyrhold's central river. Ironside garrison controls the crossing.
Nordmarch
Plotina (~5,000) — Dam town, Boros-engineered, water-powered mills and smithies. Beregov (~3,000) — Riverbank fishing and trading, Dulagn Fleet base, smoked pike. Lesnoye (~1,500) — Forest-Edge, last Roslandic town before the Thornway. Pogranichny (~1,000) — Border customs station, Vigil Wardens since 1303 AF. Paromsk (~2,000) — Ferry-Town. Where the northern river widens enough for ferry service. Three ferries operate. The ferrymasters are Bridgestone family. Mokraya (~800) — Wet-Village. Marshland settlement, eel-fishing, perpetually muddy. The eels here are smoked over alder-wood and exported to Fairhaven. Storozhevoy (~1,200) — Watchtower. Military outpost overlooking the northern crossing. Riverblade garrison.
The Daudrwood March
Temnograd (~4,000) — Dark-Town. March's largest settlement, timber processing, Frostguard staging point. Bonekeepers' chapel for rangers who don't return. Volchiy Log (~1,500) — Wolf's Hollow. Unusually large, coordinated wolves. Ember Watch noted "behavioral anomalies consistent with elevated echo-density." Korengrad (~1,000) — Root-Town. Buildings constructed between trunks of 500-year-old trees. Residents consider the trees neighbors. Zyabrevo (~600) — Frost-Village. Southernmost permanent settlement, Gorban garrison, fur trade with southern clans. Omutovo (~400) — Deep-Pool. Dark, warm lake of unknown depth. Does not freeze. Unknown fish species. Sacred to locals. Offerings on the shore. Residents do not swim in it. Do not explain why. Medvezhya (~300) — Bear's Den. Named accurately. The Daudrwood's bear population is concentrated in this valley. Frostguard rangers based here specialize in bear management. Sosnovka (~500) — Pine-Village. Deep forest settlement. Resin-tappers and pitch-makers. The pitch produced here waterproofs Rosland's naval vessels. Glubinka (~200) — The Deep. The most remote settlement in Rosland. A Drenov charcoal camp so far into the Daudrwood that supply runs take four days. The workers rotate on three-month shifts. Nobody stays longer voluntarily. The forest this deep is not hostile, exactly. It is attentive.
The Western Shore
Primorsk (~8,000) — Largest coastal town. Fishing port, Zelnik fleet base. Cold, wind-battered, proud. Tumangrad (~3,000) — Fog-Town. Ship repair, naval base, five patrol vessels. Skalnaya (~1,200) — Cliff-Village. Seal-hunters, waterproof leather production. Utoplennik (~500) — Drowned-Village. Named for the frequency of deaths at sea. Bukhta (~2,000) — Bay-Town. Sheltered harbor, whaling station (small-scale — one or two whales per season, processed for oil and bone). Vetrovoy (~800) — Wind-Town. Exposed headland, lighthouse, weather-prediction station. The lighthouse keeper, Old Seva (age 70), has predicted every major storm for thirty years by watching the behavior of his cats. He has eleven cats. He trusts them more than instruments. Rybachiy (~1,500) — Fisher-Town. The Shore's most productive fishing settlement. Cod, herring, and the Western Eel — a large, oily species that Roslandic cooks smoke, pickle, and stew in quantities that other cultures find excessive.

V. NATURAL FEATURES
The Daudrwood — Ancient temperate rainforest. Trees 200 feet tall. Moss, fern, permanent twilight. Never fully mapped. Produces the Groaning — a low hum on still nights, source unknown. The Ember Watch attributed it to geology. Elder Corvath underlined "geology" and wrote "Or not."
The Fyrhold Range — Eastern mountains, 200 miles north-south, peak at Mount Kovac (~9,000 feet). Mines exceeding 1,000 feet deep. Anomalies in the deepest shafts: tools don't rust, water warmer than expected, persistent sub-audible humming.
The Three Rivers — Zelena (Green, largest, navigable), Bystrina (Swift, too fast above Millhaven), Tikhaya (Quiet, slow, deep, bordered by marshlands — rusalka territory).
Lake Omut — Near Omutovo. Circular, deep, volcanic origin probable. Does not freeze. Warm water. Unknown fish. Locally considered bottomless. Magos have not investigated.
The Deadwood Valley — Southern corridor to the Frozen South. Corbeau gold trade route. Gorban scouts reporting anomalies nobody in Fairhaven is reading.
The Tikhaya Marshes — Ancient peatland, undrained, ecologically dense. One of the Greens' most echo-rich environments. Home to the rusalka legends and a mosquito population that functions as a natural defense system.
The Iron Coast — Western seaboard. Rocky, fjord-cut, storm-battered. The coastal waters contain kelp forests, seal colonies, and a whale migration route that passes close enough to shore for the Bukhta whalers to reach from rowboats.
The Cracked Tooth — A geological formation in Fyrhold: a mountain peak split in half by an ancient earthquake, the two halves separated by a gap thirty feet wide and over five hundred feet deep. The gap produces a whistling sound in high wind that miners call the Tooth's Song. A Stelev-forged steel cable spans the gap at the narrowest point — a bridge that only the bravest (or drunkest) Fyrhold workers attempt to cross. Seventeen have. Fourteen survived.

VI. LEGENDS AND FOLKLORE
The Old Spirits
The Domovoi — House-spirits. Every household maintains a hearthside shrine. Fed bread and salt. Well-fed domovoi keeps the house warm, warns of fire, makes bread rise. Neglected domovoi: milk sours, tools break, nightmares. When moving house, carry a coal from the old hearth. If it dies, the family is cursed. The Ayanite clergy calls it superstition. Roslandic grandmothers call the clergy "men who've never baked bread."
The Leshy — Lord of the Forest. A presence in the Daudrwood — described as a bark-and-moss giant, a stag with human eyes, or simply a feeling. Frostguard rangers leave offerings at crossroads: bread, salt, zhivka. Rules: don't whistle in the forest. Don't cut a living tree without asking (knock three times; if you hear a creak, the tree agrees; if silence, find another). Don't enter after dark without fire. Never answer a voice calling your name from between the trees. The Leshy can mimic any voice. The Leshy's idea of hospitality is not yours.
The Rusalki — Water-spirits of the Tikhaya marshes. Pale women with green-tinged hair and cold hands. Ghosts of the drowned, or river-spirits older than humanity, or echo-manifestations from the marsh's dense biological activity. They appear at dusk, sit on the bank, sing. Follow the singing: you drown. Resist: they weep, and the sound makes loneliness so total that water looks like comfort. One teenager per decade doesn't come back. The drownings are attributed to poor swimming. The folk explanation is more consistent.
The Vodyanoy — The river-old-man. A spirit dwelling in the deepest pools of the Zelena and Bystrina — fat, green-bearded, covered in mud and slime. He drags down those who disrespect the river: those who fish without offering the first catch, those who piss in the water, those who swim at midnight during a new moon. Millers fear the Vodyanoy most — he can break a mill-dam overnight if insulted. The mill-owners of Millhaven leave a black rooster tied to the millwheel's axle on midsummer night. By morning, the rooster is gone. The mill keeps working. Nobody asks where the rooster went.
Koschei's Needle — A sorcerer removed his death and hid it in a needle, in an egg, in a duck, in a hare, in an iron chest, beneath an oak on an island in a lake. He wanders the world undying, searching for something he forgot. Every Roslandic region claims to know the lake. Vlado Ironside's secret search for immortality maps directly onto this legend. Whether Vlado considers himself Koschei is a question whose answer is obvious to everyone except Vlado.
The Firebird — A creature of light in the deepest Daudrwood. Golden-orange, feathers that glow for three days. Not destructive — it illuminates. Following it leads you to something you need — not want. Ranger Voron (1267 AF) followed one for three days. Emerged with a fever, unidentified seeds, and a memory of a cave containing non-corroding metal objects. Died of the fever. The seeds were planted at Daurnkeep. The plant that grew glows faintly in moonlight. It's the only one of its kind on the continent. Old Marek Daurn waters it personally.
Baba Vedma — The Crone of the Crossroads. An old woman who lives in a hut deep in the Daudrwood — the hut moves, appearing at different locations, always at a crossroads. She tests travelers: three questions. Answer truly and she helps — medicine, direction, prophecy. Lie and she eats you. The eating is not metaphorical. Frostguard rangers have found human bones at crossroad clearings deep in the forest — too deep for any civilian traveler to have reached. The bones are always clean, as if boiled. The Bonekeepers collect them and do not discuss the circumstances.
Morozko — Father Frost. An old man, white-bearded, blue-eyed, walking the roads on the coldest nights. He tests: "Are you warm, child?" Answer honestly: he wraps you in his cloak, you survive. Lie: you freeze where you stand, smiling. Bodies found frozen on Rosland's winter roads have smiles on their faces. The last thing they saw was Morozko's smile.
The Crying Stones — Certain Daudrwood boulders produce moisture on dry days. The folk explanation: the stones mourn, remembering deaths that occurred nearby. The echo explanation: old granite with elevated echo-density, moisture produced by echo-field/atmosphere interaction. Both correct. Neither complete.
The Night of the Twelve Fires — Winter solstice. Every household lights twelve candles in the windows. They must burn until dawn. If all twelve survive, the year will be good. If any go out, the number indicates which months bring hardship. Pre-Lovist tradition, repurposed by the church, understood by everyone to be older than the church. On solstice night, Rosland glows — thousands of windows lit against the longest dark. The most beautiful thing the republic produces. The one thing neither faction has tried to claim.
The Banya Oath — No weapons in the bathhouse. No lies in the steam. Agreements sealed in the banya are more binding than written contracts. The Iron Codex was negotiated in a bathhouse. Vlado Ironside has not entered a public banya since taking office. The Greenhands consider this revealing.
The Buried Tsar — A Fyrhold legend. Somewhere in the deepest mine-shafts, sealed behind rock falls and abandoned tunnels, a king from the Age of History sleeps in a chamber of gold. He is not dead — he is waiting. When Rosland's need is greatest, the mountain will open and the Tsar will walk out, armed in metal that doesn't rust, carrying a hammer that splits stone with a word. The legend is older than the republic, older than the empire, older than Loveism. The miners do not believe it literally. They believe it enough to leave a lamp burning at the entrance to every sealed shaft. "So he can find his way out."
The Forge-Ghost — In Forgetown, the oldest forge — the Stelev Ancestral — is haunted by the sound of hammering that occurs when no one is working. The hammering follows a rhythm: three strikes, a pause, three strikes. The Stelevs do not consider this unusual. They consider it the forge's first master — dead four hundred years — still working. When young Stelev smiths begin their apprenticeships, they are sent alone to the Ancestral forge at midnight to listen. If they hear the hammering, they are suited to the trade. If they hear silence, they are advised to find another profession. Every Stelev smith currently working heard the hammering. Whether this says something about the forge or about the psychology of teenagers alone in a dark room at midnight is debated.
The White Wolf — A Daudrwood legend. Every few decades, a wolf is born that is entirely white — not albino (its eyes are dark, not red) but white as snow, larger than its packmates, and possessed of a stillness that other animals respond to with deference. The White Wolf does not hunt. It does not need to — the pack brings it food. It does not lead. It does not follow. It simply exists, and the forest adjusts around it. The Frostguard considers a White Wolf sighting an omen — good or bad depending on the direction the wolf is traveling (toward you: fortune; away: danger approaching). The last confirmed sighting was 1302 AF, reported by Verra Daurn herself. The wolf was heading south. Toward the Frozen South. Toward whatever landed there.

THE RED COAST — Copper, Sand, and Hidden Water (Complete Regional Bible)
1308 AF — The Thirsty Crown

I. THE REGION AT A GLANCE
Total Population: ~2,400,000 Capital: Saravenna (pop. ~200,000) — the Red Crown's seat, the largest coastal city south of Puerto Luciente Other Major Cities: Alsiroth's Gate (~150,000), Qasr Ash'khor (~40,000), Madinat al-Nahr (~30,000), Porto Rubia (~25,000) Government: The Red Crown (House Cenizar). Originally a water-arbitration court, expanded over four centuries into a constitutional monarchy whose power is real on the coast and theoretical in the interior. The Crown arbitrates, the oasis lords obey when they feel like it. Economy: Copper mining, obsidian, salt, spice trade (overland caravans from Xaria and the Teeth), dates, goat-herding, geothermal mineral extraction, and the qanat water-engineering that makes everything else possible Religion: Orthodox Loveism with heavy Ashanite influence. The Sufi-analogous mystical tradition — the Tariqat al-Nur (Path of Light) — operates alongside orthodoxy, tolerated by the Ashanite order, distrusted by the Ayanites. Desert animism persists among the deep-desert clans. Provinces: Four — The Copper Coast (Cenizar territory), The Gate Lands (Alsiroth territory), The Ashlands (volcanic interior, Khorim and allied houses), The Deep Desert (nomadic clan territory, ungoverned)

II. THE LAND
The Red Coast occupies the continent's arid southeastern crescent — a sweep of desert, volcanic ridge, and sun-battered coastline that runs from the Vallanaise border in the north to the Teeth's nearest island in the east. The color red saturates everything: the sandstone cliffs, the iron-oxide soil, the native copper that veins the rock like exposed arteries, the henna in the people's hair and beards, the sunset that paints the desert in shades of blood and amber every evening for twenty minutes of beauty before the darkness falls like a door slamming.
The geography divides into bands running roughly parallel to the coast:
The Copper Coast — A narrow strip of habitable land between the Red Sea and the desert interior. The coast is cliffs, coves, and the occasional river-mouth where freshwater springs create green oases against the red rock. Saravenna sits at the coast's widest point, where a natural harbor and the continent's most reliable coastal spring have sustained a city for over a millennium.
The Caravan Corridor — The strip of semi-arid steppe between the coast and the desert proper, threaded by the overland trade routes connecting the Red Coast to Vallan, the Heartlands, and (via the Teeth) the eastern markets. The Corridor is where the oasis cities sit — pearls strung along the caravan routes, each one a bubble of green surrounded by infinite brown.
The Ashlands — The volcanic interior. A landscape of dormant and semi-active volcanic ridges, obsidian fields, geothermal vents, and the black-glass mountains that produce the Khorim obsidian trade. The Ashlands are sparsely populated but economically critical — the obsidian, the geothermal minerals, and the volcanic glass are worth more per pound than copper.
The Deep Desert — The Desierto de Ceniza (Ash Desert). The dead heart of the region. Sand seas, salt flats, wind-sculpted rock formations, and temperatures that kill the unprepared within hours. The Deep Desert is not empty — the Saffaren clans traverse it on routes known only to them — but it is ungovernable, and every Red Crown ruler who has tried to extend authority into the deep sand has failed.
Water
Water is the Red Coast's god, currency, and weapon. The qanat systems — underground aqueducts tapping deep aquifers and delivering water to the surface through gravity-fed tunnels — are the most important infrastructure on the continent. A single qanat can be thirty miles long, requiring decades to construct and constant maintenance to keep functional. The qanat-builders' guild — the Qanat-Khanan (literally "Water-Lords") — is the most powerful professional organization in the region, more influential than any noble house, because every house depends on them. A Qanat-Khanani engineer who refuses to maintain a lord's aqueduct has effectively sentenced that lord's city to death. This has happened. Twice.
The water politics are simple: whoever controls the water controls the people. House Cenizar controls the coast's springs. House Alsiroth controls the Gate Lands' deep wells. The oasis lords each control their local qanats. The Saffaren clans control the deep-desert wells that no outsider has ever mapped. The Red Crown's authority derives from its role as water-arbiter — the institution that prevents the water-lords from destroying each other's qanats (which they did during the Qanat Wars of 905-925 AF, killing thousands through thirst).

III. THE HOUSES
HOUSE CENIZAR — The Red Crown
Seat: The Crimson Palace, Saravenna Sigil: A copper crown over flowing water, on a field of deep red Words: "The Water Remembers Who Shared It" Founded: c. 930 AF
The Cenizars brokered the original water-sharing agreements that ended the Qanat Wars, and the copper crown they wore at the signing became the symbol of arbitration that became the symbol of governance. Four centuries later, the Crown is a constitutional monarchy — powerful on the coast where Cenizar controls the springs and the harbor, weaker in the interior where distance and tradition limit its reach.
Red King Tamir Cenizar (age 52) — The current crown. A careful, intelligent man who governs through consensus because he lacks the military force to govern through command. Tamir's authority is real in Saravenna and the coastal towns; in the interior, it operates through the Copper Courts — traveling judges who carry the Crown's seal and adjudicate disputes with the implied threat of water-access restrictions for non-compliance. Tamir is aware that this system works only as long as no interior lord calls his bluff. He is also aware that Lord Alsiroth is increasingly inclined to call it.
Tamir is physically unremarkable — medium height, lean, with the dark skin and sharp features common to the coast. What distinguishes him is his voice: a deep, resonant baritone that fills a room without effort and that he deploys in council sessions with the precision of a weapon. He does not shout. He does not need to. When Tamir speaks, the room listens — not because of his title but because the voice carries an authority that the title alone cannot provide.
Queen Zahra Cenizar (age 48) — Tamir's wife, born into House Ramad (the geothermal lords). A political marriage that has become, over twenty years, a genuine partnership. Zahra manages the Crown's diplomatic relationships with the interior houses — she is the person who travels to Alsiroth's Gate, drinks tea with Omar Sadiq, and returns with intelligence that Tamir's court spies couldn't obtain. She is trusted by the interior lords in a way that Tamir is not, because she is one of them by birth and understands the desert's customs in her bones.
Prince Idris Cenizar (age 24) — Heir. A naval officer commanding the Crown's coastal patrol — six warships and a dozen fast cutters that protect the Red Coast's sea trade from Teeth pirates and enforce the harbor tariffs that fund the Crown's operations. Idris is competent, restless, and frustrated by the Crown's limited military power. He has been advocating for a larger navy, funded by increased harbor taxes. The merchants are resisting. The merchants are also the people who pay for everything.
Princess Layla Cenizar (age 20) — Tamir's daughter. Studying at the Ayanite academy in Saravenna, training as a jurist. She is the sharpest legal mind in the royal family and the person most likely to strengthen the Copper Courts' authority — if she can survive the transition from student to practitioner in a system where every powerful family has reasons to resist judicial independence.

HOUSE ALSIROTH — The Mad Kings
Seat: Alsiroth's Gate (the continent's largest inland desert city, pop. ~150,000) Sigil: A black tower on a golden desert, surmounted by a copper mirror-sun Words: "We Need No Sea" Founded: Pre-imperial
The Alsiroths are the Red Coast's great contradiction: an ancient, proud dynasty whose territory controls the continent's most important inland caravan junction, whose deep wells make them independent of the qanat system, and whose ruling family has been intermittently insane for three centuries. The madness is not universal — not every Alsiroth is afflicted — but it recurs with enough frequency that the house's vassals and rivals factor it into their political calculations the way other regions factor in weather.
The current lord is not technically mad. He is eccentric in ways that may or may not be performance.
Lord Kasim Alsiroth IV (age 45) — The Gate Lord. Grandson of the mad king Yusef III (who built the tower of mirrors and the bone palace). Kasim inherited his grandfather's tendency toward grandiose projects but has, so far, directed the tendency toward infrastructure rather than insanity: he is building a canal from Alsiroth's Gate to the coast — an engineering project of staggering ambition that the Qanat-Khanan consider feasible and that everyone else considers a money pit. The canal, if completed, would transform the Gate into a seaport without a sea — eliminating the city's dependence on overland trade and threatening Saravenna's economic dominance. Tamir Cenizar is aware of this. The canal project is the Red Coast's slow-burning political crisis.
Kasim's personality: intense, visionary, prone to sleepless weeks during which he works obsessively on the canal plans, followed by depressive episodes during which he does not leave his chambers for days. His court physician attributes this to "constitutional temperament." The Sadiq family attributes it to hereditary instability. The truth is somewhere between — Kasim is brilliant, ambitious, and insufficiently stable to be trusted with the power he holds.
Lady Nesrin Alsiroth (age 40) — Kasim's wife. Born into a minor oasis house, married to Kasim for her family's water rights. She is the practical counterweight to her husband's visions — she manages the household, the city's grain reserves, and the complex diplomacy with the Sadiq merchants who are slowly buying the city from beneath the Alsiroth throne. She knows what the Sadiqs are doing. She cannot stop it without alienating the commercial class that keeps the city fed. She is playing a game she is losing.
Young Yusef Alsiroth (age 12) — Kasim's son, named for his notorious great-grandfather. Shows no signs of the family madness. Shows signs of something else: he is quiet, watchful, and has a habit of knowing things he shouldn't — the contents of sealed letters, the outcomes of negotiations before they conclude, the location of lost objects. His nursemaid attributes this to cleverness. The boy's tutor — a Tariqat al-Nur mystic named Dervish Arman — attributes it to something else and has been quietly training the boy in the Path's contemplative techniques without the family's knowledge. Young Yusef may be mildly echo-sensitive. The Alsiroth deep wells sit on geological formations that bring unprocessed stone close to the surface — exactly the conditions that sustain elevated echo-density.

HOUSE SADIQ — The Patient Merchants
Seat: The Grand Souk, Alsiroth's Gate (a fortified market district that is a city within the city) Sigil: Golden scales perfectly balanced, on sand-yellow Words: "The Deal Is the Deal"
The Sadiqs are not lords. They are merchants. This distinction is the foundation of their strategy: they don't want the Alsiroth throne. They want to own everything the throne depends on and let the Alsiroths keep the title while the Sadiqs keep the keys.
Merchant-Prince Omar Sadiq (age 50) — Third generation of the Sadiq strategy. His grandfather Rashid began buying Alsiroth assets during Yusef III's madness. His father continued. Omar is completing the acquisition. He controls the Grand Souk (the city's commercial heart), the primary grain-import contracts, three of the five major caravanserai, and the debt-bonds on approximately forty percent of the Gate Lands' agricultural estates. He funds Kasim's canal project — not because he believes in it, but because every gold piece Kasim spends on the canal is a gold piece borrowed from Omar, and every loan tightens the noose.
Omar is patient, courteous, and possessed of a business intelligence that makes the Jade Cabal of Xaria look amateurish. He has seven sons, each managing a sector: Rashid (spice trade), Farouk (grain imports), Hasan (the caravanserai network), Khalil (the slave markets — legal on the Red Coast, unlike Sangrea), Tariq (obsidian and metalwork), Salim (property and real estate), and Little Omar (intelligence — the family's spy network, operating under commercial cover). Omar's brother, Bahram Sadiq (age 45), runs the smuggling and covert logistics that the legitimate business depends on but cannot publicly acknowledge.

HOUSE KHORIM — The Obsidian Lords
Seat: Qasr Ash'khor — the Ash Fortress (pop. ~40,000, a city carved into a volcanic ridge) Sigil: A black obsidian blade on a field of volcanic red-orange Words: "Sharper Than Steel, Older Than Memory"
The Khorims control the Ashlands — the volcanic interior — and the obsidian trade that has been the region's most distinctive export for centuries. Khorim obsidian blades are sharper than any steel, though more brittle, and they are prized across the continent as both weapons and luxury goods. The Khorim also control the volcanic glass used in alchemical instruments, mirror-making, and the construction of the signal-mirrors that form the Red Coast's communication network.
Lord Vazir Khorim (age 55) — A hard, quiet man who rules the Ashlands from a fortress carved into a volcanic ridge whose obsidian walls catch the sunlight and blaze like black fire. Vazir is the Red Coast's most independent lord — his territory is too remote and too geologically hostile for the Crown to threaten, his obsidian monopoly is too valuable to sanction, and his personal army (small but equipped entirely with Khorim glass weapons and trained for volcanic terrain) is the one force on the Red Coast that no one wants to fight on its home ground.
Vazir's secret: the deepest obsidian mines in Qasr Ash'khor have been producing something unusual for the past decade. Mixed into the volcanic glass, in veins so thin they're barely visible, is a material that Khorim's smiths cannot identify — a dark, crystalline substance that resists every cutting tool, absorbs heat without conducting it, and produces a faint vibration when held in the hand. Vazir has sealed the affected shafts and told no one. He has sent samples to the Isle of Knowledge through intermediaries. The Magos have not responded. He is considering sending a second inquiry, more forcefully worded.
Sivara Khorim (age 28) — Vazir's daughter. The family's master glass-worker. She has been experimenting with the unknown mineral — incorporating trace amounts into obsidian blade alloys — and producing weapons of extraordinary quality: blades that hold an edge longer than any natural obsidian, that ring with a clear tone when struck, and that (she has noticed but not mentioned to her father) feel warm in the hand regardless of ambient temperature. She is, without knowing it, the Red Coast's first accidental echo-smith.

HOUSE RUKH AND HOUSE RAMAD — The Hot-Springs Lords
Two houses sharing the volcanic peninsula south of Qasr Ash'khor, bound by the Truce of Ash (1020 AF) that divided geothermal resources between them after four generations of feuding.
House Rukh controls the northern springs — the larger, hotter, more mineral-rich pools used for medicinal purposes. Lord Anwar Rukh (age 60) — A former warrior gone to fat and philosophy. He spends his days soaking in his private spring, receiving petitioners while neck-deep in steaming water, and dictating a memoir that no one has asked for and everyone dreads.
House Ramad controls the southern springs — cooler, cleaner, used for bathing and the extraction of mineral salts. Lady Safiya Ramad (age 42) — Queen Zahra Cenizar's cousin, a practical woman managing her house's mineral-export business. The salts produced from Ramad springs are used across the continent in alchemical preparations, food preservation, and the Copper Bowl healers' tinctures.
The Truce of Ash holds. Barely. The shared springs at the peninsula's center — the Hammam al-Kubra (the Great Bath), a natural hot spring the size of a small lake — are jointly administered and perpetually disputed.

THE SAFFAREN — The Desert Clans
Not a house but a confederation — dozens of nomadic clans who traverse the Deep Desert on routes that predate every settled civilization on the Red Coast. The Saffaren recognize no Crown, no court, no law except their own customary code (the Sand-Law), and they interact with settled society only at the desert's edge, where they trade salt, desert herbs, and the occasional intelligence report for grain, metalwork, and things the desert doesn't produce.
Sheik Makhtar al-Saffar (age 65) — The confederation's nominal leader (elected by a council of clan elders, authority limited to inter-clan disputes and collective defense). Makhtar is the person the Crown negotiates with when it needs something from the desert — safe passage for caravans, access to the deep-desert salt deposits, or information about what's moving in the sand. Makhtar provides these things at prices that the Crown considers extortionate and that Makhtar considers fair.
The Saffaren's religious practice is not Loveism. It is desert animism — the worship of wind, sand, sun, and the deep-desert wells that they consider portals to the underworld. The Ayanite clergy has been attempting to convert the Saffaren for three centuries. The Saffaren listen politely, accept the gifts, and continue praying to the wind. Their shamans — the Sand-Seers — are the Red Coast's most naturally echo-sensitive population, their sensitivity honed by a lifetime of exposure to the desert's vast, unprocessed geology. A Sand-Seer can find water underground by feeling it. The settled population considers this superstition. The settled population also pays Sand-Seers handsomely to locate new well sites.

HOUSE SAFFARSHAMS — The Sunken Fleet
Seat: The Ship-Graveyard, Alsiroth's Gate (a district of converted ship-hulls, stranded when the river dried up) Sigil: A golden sun setting into a blue sea Words: "The Sun Also Sets"
A family destroyed by geography. The Saffarshams were sea-traders — their fleet controlled the river trade between the Gate and the coast for centuries. Then the river shifted course (approximately 200 years ago), leaving their ships stranded in mud that hardened to stone. The fleet became tenements. The dynasty became a joke.
Captain Idris Saffarshams (age 48) — A brilliant, perpetually drunk shipwright designing a "sand-ship" — a vehicle that can cross the desert like a ship crosses the sea. Everyone considers this insane. Idris has been working on it for twenty years. His latest prototype — a wooden hull on metal runners, propelled by wind-sails — actually moved during trials. Sixty feet, before it tipped over. His wife Maryam (age 44) runs a tavern to keep the family alive. His daughter Hadiya (age 19) has secretly sold herself into the service of House Sadiq to pay debts. Three sons have left the city for foreign ships.

MINOR HOUSES AND POWERS
House Narimel — Oasis lords controlling the Ain Narimel, the largest inland oasis. Pop. ~12,000. Three qanats. The oasis produces dates, figs, and the aromatic Narimel Rose — a desert flower used in perfumery and medicine. Lord Bassam Narimel (age 50) — A quiet man whose power is entirely hydrological.
House Tarazin — Caravan lords. Not an oasis house but a transport dynasty — they own the camels, the drivers, and the route-knowledge that moves goods across the desert. Caravan-Master Dima Tarazin (age 55) — A woman (rare among the Red Coast's aristocracy) who inherited from her father and has expanded the family's caravan network into the largest private transport operation in the region.
House Qadir — Descendants of the alchemist who served the mad King Yusef III. The family retained the alchemical knowledge (if not the ethics) and now operates a network of apothecaries, mineral-dealers, and the occasional poison-for-hire service. Based in Alsiroth's Gate.
The Furnace-Holders — The copper-smelters' guild, based in Saravenna. Control the processing of raw copper ore into the finished products that the Red Coast exports. The guild is technically independent; in practice, they are Cenizar-aligned because the Crown controls their fuel supply (charcoal imported from Rosland via Vallan).
The Qanat-Khanan — The water-engineers' guild. The most powerful non-noble institution in the region. Maintain, build, and repair the qanat systems that sustain every city. Their authority supersedes noble privilege in water matters — a Qanat-Khanani engineer can order a lord to cease drawing from a qanat if the engineer determines the draw-rate threatens the system's integrity. This authority has been exercised. The lords complied. They had no choice.
The Tariqat al-Nur — The Path of Light. A mystical order operating alongside (not within) orthodox Loveism. The Tariqat teaches that divine truth is accessed through contemplation, movement, breath, and the systematic calming of the mind — practices that echo (without knowing it) the Venic Path's consciousness-altering techniques. The Tariqat's adepts — called dervishes — are recognizable by their white robes and their habit of spinning in place during meditation sessions, a practice that induces a trance state the dervishes describe as "stepping sideways into the light." The Ayanite clergy considers them harmless eccentrics. The Ashanite clergy recognizes them as genuine contemplatives. The Venic Path, if they knew about the Tariqat, would recognize them as cousins. Current Sheikh: Dervish Arman (age 60) — Also young Yusef Alsiroth's secret tutor.

IV. MAJOR CITIES
Saravenna (pop. ~200,000) — The Red Crown's seat. Built where the coast's largest freshwater spring meets the sea, Saravenna is a city of contrasts: blank, fortress-like exterior walls enclosing lush interior courtyards; crushing heat on the streets and cool shade inside; the poverty of the outer districts and the water-wealth of the Crimson Palace, whose seven fountains run day and night as a statement of power. Districts: the Crown Quarter (palace, Copper Courts, administrative complex), the Harbor (the coast's largest port — thirty deep-water berths, commercial docks, the naval base), the Copper Souk (the metalworkers' market — a labyrinth of workshops producing the filigree copperwork that is the Red Coast's most famous craft), the Garden District (the wealthy quarter, where the sound of running water is the sound of status), the Dust Quarter (the poor quarter, waterless, dust-choked, and the reason the Crown exists — to ensure even the Dust Quarter's cisterns are filled).
Alsiroth's Gate (pop. ~150,000) — The Grand Junction. Built at the crossroads where every major caravan route on the eastern continent converges. The city is a commercial organism — it exists because the routes exist, and the routes exist because the city exists, a self-reinforcing loop of trade and geography. The Grand Souk — the Sadiq family's domain — is the largest covered market on the continent: miles of vaulted arcades, specialized quarters (the Spice Road, the Copper Lane, the Silk Passage, the Shadow Market where the rules are different), and the complex wind-channeling architecture that keeps the interior tolerable in temperatures that would bake bread on the street outside. The Alsiroth Palace — the lord's seat — sits on the city's highest point, dominated by the Mirror Tower built by the mad King Yusef III. The tower still stands: a column of polished copper plates that catch the sun and flash signals visible for fifty miles. Whether Yusef intended it as a signal tower or genuinely believed he could "blind the sun" is debated. The tower works. The madness was productive.
Qasr Ash'khor (pop. ~40,000) — The Ash Fortress. Khorim's seat, carved into a volcanic ridge. The city's architecture is volcanic glass and basalt — dark, angular, gleaming. The obsidian workshops occupy an entire district: grinding, polishing, blade-smithing, the production of the alchemical instruments and mirror-glass that the continent depends on. The air smells of pumice dust and the sulfurous tang of the geothermal vents that heat the city's water supply. The vents also produce the mineral deposits that the Copper Bowl healers prize — the Order maintains a permanent station here, their copper bowls and volcanic tinctures the closest thing the Red Coast has to institutional medicine.
Madinat al-Nahr (pop. ~30,000) — River City. Built where the Red Coast's only permanent river (the Wadi Ahmar, Red Wash — a seasonal river that flows year-round in its lower reaches due to spring-fed tributaries) meets the coast. The city is the region's agricultural center: irrigated fields producing dates, figs, pomegranates, grain, and the spices (cumin, coriander, saffron, sumac) that define Red Coast cuisine. The Harvest Hall — an Ashanite granary-temple — distributes surplus to the inland oasis towns during drought.
Porto Rubia (pop. ~25,000) — The Red Port. The coast's secondary harbor, south of Saravenna, specializing in the Teeth trade. The port handles volcanic stone from Emberstone, timber from Verwhisper, and the miscellaneous goods that flow through the Teeth's Bridge. Since Morvayn's toll increases, Porto Rubia has been losing traffic — merchants who can't afford the Bridge tolls route through Vallan instead, bypassing the Red Coast entirely. The port's economy is contracting. The merchants are angry. Prince Idris Cenizar has proposed a naval expedition to break Morvayn's toll monopoly. His father has not approved it.

V. MINOR SETTLEMENTS
The Copper Coast
Ain Zahra (~8,000) — Spring of the Flower. Largest oasis town on the coast outside Saravenna. Known for its rose gardens — irrigated terraces producing the Red Coast Rose, whose petals are distilled into rose-water and rose-oil for perfumery, cooking, and the preparation of medicinal tinctures. Bab al-Bahr (~5,000) — Sea Gate. Fishing port, salt production, and the coastal terminus of the overland route from Alsiroth's Gate. The caravanserai here — the Khan al-Bahari — is the largest on the coast: 200 rooms, stabling for 500 camels, and a public hammam whose waters are heated by the sun and cooled by wind-channeling architecture. Minara (~3,000) — Tower-Town. Named for its lighthouse — a copper-clad signal tower that guides ships along the treacherous southern coast. The keeper, Lightwarden Tariq (age 55), maintains the mirror-flash communication with Saravenna. Sakhrat al-Hamra (~2,000) — Red Rock. A clifftop settlement built on a copper-rich promontory. The cliff face glows copper-green with verdigris. Mining and metalwork. Duvari (~1,500) — A fishing hamlet known for its pearls — small, irregular, tinted rose-gold by the copper in the water. Porto Obscura (~4,000) — Dark Port. The coast's smuggling capital. Where goods that can't pass Saravenna's customs arrive and distribute inland.
The Gate Lands
Ain Narimel (~12,000) — The great inland oasis. Three qanats, date palms, the Narimel Rose. The oasis is the Gate Lands' breadbasket. Wahaat al-Sirr (~3,000) — Oasis of Secrets. A small, isolated oasis that has been a Tariqat al-Nur retreat for two centuries. The dervishes here maintain a library of mystical texts, including works expelled from the Ayanite archives and manuscripts that the Magos have requested access to (the Tariqat declined — politely, firmly, permanently). Qasr al-Milh (~5,000) — Salt Fortress. Controls a massive salt deposit that supplies the caravan trade. Salt from Qasr al-Milh is the Deep Desert's currency — the Saffaren will trade anything for it. Birkhat al-Qamar (~1,000) — Moon Pool. An oasis whose spring fills a perfectly circular pool that reflects the moons with unusual clarity. Sacred to the Tariqat. Dervishes meditate at the pool's edge during Concordance (dual full moon) nights and report visions of "the world as it was before thirst." Echo phenomenon from the ancient spring's geological matrix. Suq al-Turab (~6,000) — Dust Market. A caravan stop halfway between Alsiroth's Gate and Saravenna. Famous for its annual camel fair — the largest livestock market on the Red Coast — and for the quality of its dried-meat vendors.
The Ashlands
Hammam al-Kubra (~2,000) — The Great Bath. The shared hot-spring complex at the center of the Rukh-Ramad disputed territory. Not a town so much as a permanent bathhouse with a village attached — lodging, restaurants, healers, and the Copper Bowl station that draws patients from across the region. Obsidian Gate (~3,000) — The Ashlands' primary commercial settlement, where obsidian is graded, packed, and loaded onto caravans for export. Vent-Town (~800) — A settlement built around a cluster of geothermal vents, producing the mineral-rich steam that the locals channel through stone pipes for heating, cooking, and the extraction of sulfur and other chemical compounds. The smell is horrific. The residents have lost their sense of smell. They consider this an advantage. Qasr al-Nar (~1,500) — Fire Fortress. A Khorim outpost on the Ashlands' southern edge, overlooking the Deep Desert. Signal tower. Garrison. The last settled point before the sand.
The Deep Desert
No permanent settlements. The Saffaren clans move between seasonal wells on routes that shift annually based on rainfall, wind patterns, and the Sand-Seers' echo-guided water-finding. The only fixed points are the wells themselves — some natural, some hand-dug, all jealously guarded. The largest: Bir al-Jinn (Well of the Spirits), a deep natural well in the desert's center that the Saffaren consider the most sacred site in the region. The water is warm, mineral-rich, and tastes of iron. The well shaft descends over 200 feet. The Saffaren say the shaft is bottomless. They say that if you drop a stone and listen, you never hear it hit. They say things live down there. They do not specify what things.

VI. NATURAL FEATURES
The Wadi Ahmar (Red Wash) — The coast's only permanent river. Seasonal in its upper reaches (a dry streambed for six months), year-round in the lower section where spring-fed tributaries sustain the flow. The water is red-tinted by iron oxide. The river's delta, where it meets the sea near Madinat al-Nahr, is the coast's most fertile zone.
The Desierto de Ceniza (Ash Desert) — The deep desert. Sand seas, salt flats, wind-sculpted rock. Temperatures: 120°F in summer, freezing at night. The salt flats — called the Mirror by the Saffaren — are so flat and reflective that on still days the sky is indistinguishable from the ground, producing a disorientation that the Saffaren call the Blur and that has killed more caravan travelers than thirst.
The Montañas de Cobre Rojo (Red Copper Mountains) — The volcanic range. Dormant peaks, obsidian fields, geothermal valleys. The mountains glow red at sunset — the copper in the rock catching the light. The deepest mines penetrate volcanic formations that have been sealed since the Age of History, and the miners' reports of anomalies (warmth, vibration, the unknown crystalline material in Khorim's shafts) all originate from these deep formations.
The Teeth Strait — The water between the Red Coast and the nearest Teeth island (Emberstone). Roughly thirty miles of open water, navigable but hazardous — strong currents, intermittent fog, and the submerged volcanic reef called the Grinder that has torn the bottoms from ships for centuries.
The Copper Veins — Not a single feature but a geological phenomenon: copper deposits that run through the Red Coast's bedrock in branching patterns that, seen from the cliffs above, look like a circulatory system — veins of green-patinated copper against red sandstone. The largest vein system — visible on the cliff face below Saravenna — is called the Arteries and is considered sacred by the Tariqat, who believe it represents Loreth's blood still flowing through the world's body.

VII. LEGENDS AND MYTHS
The Copper Djinn — The oldest Red Coast legend. When the world was young and the copper was still liquid fire beneath the earth, a spirit — a djinn — lived in the molten metal. The djinn was beautiful, terrible, and lonely. It loved the sun but could not reach it. It loved the water but could not touch it without dying. So it shaped itself a body from cooled copper — a figure that walked the desert at night, glowing with internal heat, leaving footprints of fused sand. The djinn is still walking. On nights when the desert is silent and the wind drops to nothing, the Saffaren say you can see a light moving on the horizon — not a campfire, not a star, but a figure of copper fire, walking toward the sunrise that it will never reach.
The Forty Wells — A Saffaren legend. The Deep Desert once had forty wells — enough to sustain a civilization. One by one, the wells dried up. Not from overuse — from grief. Each well had a spirit, and each spirit died when the last person who remembered its name forgot it. The wells dried because the names were forgotten. The Saffaren maintain a ritual called the Naming — a ceremony in which the clan elder recites the names of every known well, living and dead, to ensure that none are forgotten and none dry up. The ceremony takes three hours. The Sand-Seers say that when they find a new well, they can sometimes hear — in the water's echo-resonance — the faintest trace of an old name, spoken by a voice that has been silent for a very long time.
The Mirror King — A legend about the mad King Yusef III's Mirror Tower. Yusef built the tower to "blind the sun" — to force K'tharr (who the Xarians worship and the Red Coast traders have encountered through cultural contact) to look away. But the mirrors, when aligned correctly, do something else: they focus the sunlight into a point so intense that the air itself shimmers and bends, and for a moment — a fraction of a second — you can see through the shimmer to something on the other side. What is on the other side varies by account: another desert, a city of glass, a face looking back at you. The tower's mirrors have not been aligned since Yusef's death. Lord Kasim has considered re-aligning them. His wife has hidden the alignment instructions.
The Water Bride — A qanat legend. When a new qanat is dug, the tunnelers sometimes hear singing from ahead — a woman's voice, clear and sweet, coming from the darkness. If the tunnelers follow the singing, they find water. If they don't, the tunnel collapses. The singing is the qanat's bride — the spirit of the water source itself, calling the tunnel toward it. The Qanat-Khanan do not officially acknowledge this legend. Unofficially, every master tunneler leaves a small copper ring at the point where the tunnel first reaches water — a wedding gift for the bride. The rings accumulate. Some qanat junctions contain dozens of copper rings, green with age, piled in the dark. Nobody removes them.
Simurgh — The Red Coast's greatest mythical creature. A bird of immense size — larger than a storm-roc, older than the desert — whose plumage contains every color that exists and several that don't. The Simurgh lives on the highest peak of the Copper Mountains (a peak that no one has climbed because it is perpetually shrouded in volcanic haze). It is not a god. It is something that was here before the gods. The K'ay storytellers of Xaria have a Feathered Serpent; the Red Coast has the Simurgh. Both describe an echo-node so vast and so old that it predates human mythology — a creature that is not sustained by the echo-field but that is part of it, the way a river is part of the ocean. The Simurgh has been "sighted" approximately once per century, always at great distance, always in conditions that make confirmation impossible. The Ember Watch's records contain a single entry: "1089 AF. Ash'khor ridge. Multiple witnesses. Wingspan estimated 200+ feet. No approach attempted. Recommend awe."
The Thirst Oath — The most binding oath on the Red Coast. Two parties face each other across a bowl of water. Each places a hand in the bowl. The oath is spoken. The water is poured onto the sand. If either party breaks the oath, the legend says, they will never find water again — every well will dry as they approach, every spring will retreat, every qanat will collapse. The mechanism is pure superstition. The enforcement is social: a person known to have broken a Thirst Oath is considered dead by the desert's customary law. No one will sell them water. No one will share a fire. No one will say their name. In a desert, this is not a metaphorical death.
The City Beneath the Sand — The Saffaren's oldest legend. Somewhere in the Deep Desert, buried under centuries of sand, there is a city built in the Age of History — before the desert was a desert, when the Red Coast was green and rivers ran where now only dust moves. The city was abandoned when the water fled (or when the water was taken — accounts differ). Its buildings are intact beneath the sand, preserved by the dry conditions. Its treasures — copper, gold, jade, and objects made of materials that no living smith can identify — wait in sealed chambers for someone to dig them out. Sand-Seers report that when they walk certain areas of the Deep Desert, they feel foundations beneath their feet — stone structures under the sand, aligned in patterns that suggest streets, plazas, buildings. The feelings are strongest at dawn and dusk. The Saffaren do not dig. The Sand-Law forbids disturbing what the desert has chosen to bury. But the feelings persist. And every generation, a Sand-Seer draws a map of what they felt, adding it to the accumulated archive of subterranean impressions that the Saffaren have been compiling for centuries. The maps, laid over each other, show the outline of a city roughly the size of Saravenna.
The Night Market — In Alsiroth's Gate, there is a market that operates only between midnight and dawn, in a section of the Grand Souk that is empty during daylight. The Night Market sells things that the day-market doesn't: prophecies, curses, memories (sold by the elderly to buyers who want to experience someone else's youth), and a substance called Tears of the Copper Djinn — a liquid that, when dropped into the eyes, allows the user to see in total darkness for twelve hours but permanently changes the iris color from dark to copper-gold. The Night Market is technically illegal. The city guard patrols past its entrance every hour, on schedule, giving the vendors sixty minutes of operating time between passes. The schedule has not changed in forty years. Lord Kasim is aware of the Night Market. He has attended it, twice, in disguise. He purchased a prophecy. Its contents are unknown. He has not attended since.

THE FROZEN SOUTH — Complete Regional Chronicle
Gold, Ice, and Old Bone
Total Documented History: Approximately 50,000 years of continuous habitation (the longest unbroken human presence on the continent). The fire-songs claim longer. Nobody argues.
Defining Feature: The only region of Mundus where the land was never conquered — not by the republics, not by the empire, not by the Church. The Frozen South has been nominally tributary, theoretically subject, and practically untouchable for the entirety of recorded history. Geography is the reason. The Deadwood and the Kjölfoss Mountains form a double wall of petrified forest and vertical stone that has broken every army foolish enough to march through it. The cold finishes whatever the terrain doesn't. The south has never needed diplomacy because it has never needed to negotiate from weakness. This is about to change.

I. THE LAND
Geography
The Frozen South is a peninsula — a ragged, mountainous wedge of land that juts southward from the continental mass into the permanent grey of the southern ocean. It is roughly six hundred miles from the northern tree-line of the Deadwood to the southernmost cape, and perhaps three hundred miles across at its widest point. The total area is deceptive: measured flat, it would be a modest territory, smaller than the Heartlands, comparable to Sangrea. But the land is not flat. It is folded, buckled, shattered by tectonic violence into a landscape of such vertical extremity that a journey of twenty miles on the map might require four days of climbing, rappelling, and praying.
The spine of the peninsula is the Kjölfoss Range — a chain of young, sharp-peaked mountains that runs north-south like a broken blade, their summits lost in permanent cloud, their flanks streaked with the gold-bearing quartz veins that are the region's wealth and curse. The Kjölfoss are volcanic in origin — the same tectonic scar that produced the Heitdalr's active vents and Eldraholm's Urdrath far to the south. The mountains are still growing. Earthquakes are common, avalanches routine, and the hot springs that bubble up through fractured granite in a hundred hidden valleys are evidence of a planet that has not finished shaping this particular corner of itself.
West of the Kjölfoss, the land drops in terraces of glaciated rock toward the coastal fjords — deep, narrow inlets where the sea has invaded the land along ancient fault lines. The fjords are the highways of the Frozen South: too steep-sided for roads, too ice-choked for large ships, but navigable by the flat-bottomed longships that the coastal clans build from driftwood, seal-skin, and a carpenter's understanding of how ice behaves when you push against it. The western coast is a labyrinth of stone and water and fog, and men have drowned within sight of their own hearth-fires because the mist swallowed the distance between ship and shore.
East of the Kjölfoss, the land is harsher still. The eastern slope catches the full force of the polar wind that screams off the southern ocean, and the vegetation — sparse everywhere — gives up entirely above the tree-line, leaving a moonscape of scoured rock, ice-fields, and the occasional glacier-carved valley where a handful of musk-oxen graze on lichen in the brief, pale summers. The eastern coast is cliff, mostly — sheer drops into water so cold that a man who falls in has approximately four minutes before his muscles stop responding and approximately six before his heart does. The Raudbjorn clan calls the eastern sea the Beinsjór — the Bone-Sea. The name is not poetic. It is descriptive. The currents deposit the bones of whales, seals, and drowned men on the rocky beaches in quantities that make the shoreline look like a battlefield that never stops fighting.
The northern boundary is the Daudr-vidr — the Deadwood. A vast forest of petrified trees, some standing, some toppled into chaotic tangles of stone-wood, their mineral-white trunks and branches creating a landscape that looks like winter even in the brief southern summer. The Deadwood stretches roughly a hundred miles from north to south and runs the full width of the peninsula, forming a natural wall between the Frozen South and the rest of the continent. The petrification process is not fully understood — the Magos have theories involving mineral-rich groundwater and volcanic gases, but the Treetalkers say the forest simply grew tired of being alive and decided to become something harder. Both explanations are equally useful to someone trying to navigate the place.
South of everything — past the last fjord, past the last clan-hold, past the rocks where the southernmost seal-hunters beach their boats — there is only the southern ocean, thousands of miles of grey water stretching toward the volcanic hell of Eldraholm, from which the Giants have just arrived.
Climate
The Frozen South exists in a state of permanent negotiation with cold. The region experiences two seasons: winter and the memory of summer. True summer — meaning a period where snow does not fall, where the fjords are navigable without icebreakers, where a person can work outdoors without risking frostbite — lasts approximately eight weeks in the coastal lowlands and approximately four in the mountains. The rest is winter: long, dark, and defined by temperatures that can kill an unprotected human in under an hour.
The darkness is the part that breaks outsiders. At midwinter, the sun does not rise for roughly six weeks in the deep south. The sky transitions from black to a bruised grey twilight at midday and then returns to black. Life continues — the clans are adapted, their routines structured around tallow-light and fire-pit warmth — but the psychological weight of six weeks without dawn is not something that can be explained to someone who has never experienced it. It must be endured. Mainlanders who visit the south in winter describe a feeling of being swallowed — not by danger but by absence. The light is absent. The color is absent. The warmth is absent. What remains is the sound of wind and the smell of smoke and the company of people whose idea of comfort is a room where your breath doesn't freeze before it leaves your mouth.
The Heitdalr is the exception. The volcanic province's geothermal heat creates microclimates where the air is warm, the soil thawed, and greenhouses — crude but functional, their walls made of scraped seal-gut stretched over bone frames — produce root vegetables and herbs year-round. Hotstone, the Heitdalr's only city, sits in a valley where steam rises from the ground like the breath of something sleeping underground, and the temperature rarely drops below freezing even at midwinter. To the rest of the Frozen South, Hotstone is a miracle and an anomaly — proof that warmth exists, somewhere, for someone.

II. THE PEOPLE
Physical Description
The clans of the Frozen South are the largest humans on the continent. Men average six feet four inches; women six feet even. Bone structure is heavy — broad shoulders, thick wrists, dense skulls. A layer of subcutaneous fat that never fully disappears even in the lean months gives their bodies a barrel-shaped solidity that mainlanders find intimidating and that the clans consider normal. They are not fat. They are insulated. The difference is the difference between a walrus and a pig, and suggesting the latter comparison to a southern clansman is a reliable way to lose teeth.
Skin is pale, weather-damaged to a permanent wind-burned pink across the cheeks, nose, and knuckles. Hair is coarse and thick, ranging from white-blond to dark brown, worn long by both sexes and braided in elaborate styles that communicate clan, family, marital status, and personal achievement. A woman with three kill-braids in her hair has taken three lives in combat and is not to be trifled with. A man with his beard in a single braid has sworn an oath that remains unfulfilled. An unbraided beard on an adult male means he is either an outcast, an oath-breaker, or so dangerous that no one has dared to question his grooming.
Beards are sacred. Shaving a man's beard is the gravest insult short of killing him — reserved for oath-breakers, cowards, and men who have betrayed their clan. A shaved man is a man without identity, without history, without the right to speak at moot. The punishment is worse than exile because the exile at least keeps his face. The shaved man keeps his life but loses everything that makes it worth living.
Clothing
Functionality dictates fashion and fashion dictates status, but in the Frozen South these are the same conversation. Clothing is layered: a base of seal-skin worn fur-inward against the body, a middle layer of felted musk-ox wool, and an outer shell of bear-hide or heavy seal-leather oiled against wet and wind. Stitching is sinew. Dyes are mineral — iron-red, copper-green, charcoal-black — applied sparingly. Color is scarce and therefore meaningful.
The clan-marker is the single most important piece of clothing. A woven band of dyed wool in clan colors, worn at the upper arm, it serves the same identification function as a Heartlander's surcoat or a Sangrean house emblem. Removing your clan-marker in public is a declaration that you have left your clan — voluntarily or otherwise. Finding a clan-marker on the ground means someone is dead, exiled, or wishes to be considered both.
Boots are the masterwork of southern craftsmanship. Multi-layered, insulated with dried grass and caribou down, soled with mammoth-leather that grips ice, lined with rabbit fur. A person's boots are their most valuable possession. Good boots are inherited. Great boots are buried with their owner. A man with bad boots is a dead man who hasn't stopped walking yet.
Architecture
Semi-subterranean. The clan-holds are built into the landscape — longhouses half-buried in hillsides, their turf roofs blending into the terrain until a traveler might walk over a settlement without realizing it was there. The interiors are warm from communal body heat and peat-and-dung fires that burn day and night, filling the low-ceilinged rooms with a thick, sweet-acrid smoke that stains everything and everyone a faint amber. Windows do not exist in the conventional sense. Light enters through smoke-holes in the roof and through seal-gut panels set into the turf walls, which admit a pale, diffuse glow.
The great hall is the center of every clan-hold — a long, low-ceilinged room built around a central fire-pit, its walls hung with furs, weapons, and the ancestral gold-work that is the clan's treasure and identity. The gold-work is extraordinary. Frozen South smiths are the continent's finest goldsmiths, producing torcs, bracelets, brooches, and ceremonial weapons of interlocking knotwork and animal motifs — wolves, bears, eagles, the mythical aurora serpent — that make Heartlands silverwork look crude by comparison. The gold-work is never sold. It is gifted, inherited, raided, or buried with the dead. Selling gold-work to an outsider is treason. The gold itself is commodity. The work is sacred.
The Kjölfoss Deeps — Clan Aurax's primary gold mine — is the closest thing the Frozen South has to a city. A sprawling complex of mine shafts, smelting works, barracks, and the great underground hall where the Winter-Moot meets. Geothermal heat from the volcanic roots of the mountains keeps the deeps warm, and the walls are perpetually lit by tallow-lamps that give the gold-veined rock a liquid, breathing quality. Visitors describe it as stepping inside a living jewel box. The Deeps can house roughly three thousand people during the Winter-Moot — the largest permanent gathering in the region's history.
Food
Meat, fish, and fat. The Frozen South's cuisine is caloric by absolute necessity — the body burns fuel just staying warm. Seal meat is the staple: tough, oily, iron-rich, eaten raw when fresh (the blood provides vitamins that cooked meat loses), smoked when preserved. Whale blubber is rendered into oil for lamps and cooking, eaten in strips, or mixed with berries and dried fish into a dense traveling food called reistmatur that tastes approximately like what it sounds like and keeps a hunter alive for a week on a fistful. Smoked fish — trout from the mountain streams, cod from the coastal waters — is the closest thing to a universal food. Dried caribou from the interior herds. And blóðmör — blood sausage, made from sheep's blood, oat-substitute (ground lichen), and suet, packed into a stomach lining, boiled, and sliced. It is dense, crumbling, faintly sweet, and the single food item most likely to make a mainland visitor excuse themselves from the table.
Dairy comes from the shaggy musk-oxen: thick, sweet milk curdled into skyr — a yogurt-like substance eaten at every meal, mixed with honey when available, with seal-oil when not. Bread is rare. Grain doesn't grow this far south. The substitute is a flatcake made from ground lichen and rendered fat, cooked on hot stones. It tastes like the idea of bread as remembered by someone who hasn't eaten bread in years.
Mead is the luxury and the social currency. Fermented from the short summer's wildflower honey, hoarded through the winter like liquid gold. Mead is offered at moots, poured at funerals, exchanged at betrothals. The quality of a clan's mead is a direct index of their status. Clan Aurax's mead — made from mountain heather honey and aged in gold-leaf-lined barrels — is considered the finest on the continent by the handful of outsiders who have ever tasted it.
Music & Oral Tradition
The fire-song. The Frozen South's entire musical tradition, its history, its law, and its identity are encoded in fire-songs — multi-part choral pieces performed around the communal fire, voice only, no instruments. Fire-songs are the repositories of everything: genealogy, territorial claims, battle records, love stories, funeral rites, seasonal knowledge, navigational information, and the names of the dead. They are sung in the old southern dialect — a cousin of Munnish that has diverged so far from the mainland language that a Heartlander hearing a fire-song would recognize perhaps one word in ten.
Every clan has its own fire-songs. Every family has private fire-songs that are never sung outside the household. Children learn the fire-songs before they learn to walk, their mothers singing the clan's history into them at the breast. A clan without fire-songs is a clan without memory, without legitimacy, without existence. The destruction of Clan Hroth — whose fire-songs were ritually silenced after their absorption into Aurax in 940 AF — was not accomplished by the slaughter of their warriors or the seizure of their holds. It was accomplished by the prohibition of their songs. A dead clan can be remembered. A silenced clan cannot.
The fire-songs are not written down. They exist only in the throats of the people who sing them. This is deliberate. The clans believe that writing kills a song the way pinning kills a butterfly — the form is preserved but the life is gone. A fire-song must be sung to exist. It must be heard to matter. It must be remembered to survive. This makes the fire-singers — the men and women whose memories hold the complete songlines of their clan — the most important people in the Frozen South after the chiefs themselves. A fire-singer's murder is a crime worse than regicide. You can replace a chief. You cannot replace a memory.
Beyond fire-songs, the south has a percussion tradition — rhythmic stamping, bone-rattle, and the drumskin (a seal-hide stretched over a whale-rib frame, played with the flat of the hand). Drums accompany work, war-dances, and the whale-hunt. The rhythm is fast, syncopated, and physically demanding to play. A good drummer's hands are calloused to leather.
Religion & Spiritual Practice
The Frozen South is the only region of Mundus that Loveism has never penetrated. Not for lack of trying — the Brothers of the Open Road sent a mission in approximately 1020 AF that reached the edge of the Deadwood, discovered that the forest was impassable, and turned back. A second mission in 1085 AF actually made it through the Deadwood using Roslandic border-guides, reached the first Daudrguard outpost, and was killed to the last man. Their bones were woven into the walls of Grimbone as a warning. A third mission was never attempted.
The clans practice an animistic spirituality that predates the migrations — possibly the oldest continuous religious tradition on the continent. The core belief is simple: the world is alive. Not metaphorically. The mountains breathe. The glaciers think. The sea remembers. The gold in the earth is the earth's blood, and mining it is a wound that must be healed through ritual and offering. The fire in the hearth is a living guest that must be fed and spoken to. The wind is a messenger. The aurora — the shimmering lights that illuminate the winter sky — is the visible breath of the world-spirit, and reading its colors and patterns is the highest form of divination.
There is no priestly caste in the mainland sense — no hierarchy, no scripture, no orthodoxy. Instead, each province has developed its own shamanic tradition, each shaped by the landscape it serves:
The Auren Priests of the Aurheim are the closest thing to an organized clergy. They interpret the will of the mountain — its earthquakes, its eruptions, its moods — and their counsel determines when mines are opened, when shafts are abandoned, and when the mountain demands an offering of gold returned to the earth. They are advisors to the Aurax warlords, and their word carries enormous political weight. A chief who ignores the Auren Priests is a chief who ignores the mountain, and the mountain has a long memory.
The Whaletooth Priests of Is-rim are whale-shamans whose authority derives from the hunt. They bless the longships before they sail, read the whale's death-throes for omens, and perform the Rite of the First Cut — the ceremonial opening of the whale's belly that determines how the meat will be distributed among the clan. A hunt without a Whaletooth Priest's blessing is a blasphemy. A whale killed without the Rite is poisoned meat that will bring sickness to whoever eats it. This is not superstition — or rather, it is superstition that functions as food-safety regulation, because the Rite of the First Cut includes an inspection of the whale's organs for disease that has saved more lives than the priests' theology ever has.
The Treetalkers of the Deadwood commune with the petrified forest — pressing their palms against the stone trunks, listening to vibrations that they interpret as the voices of trees that have been dead for millennia but whose spirits remain imprisoned in the mineral that replaced their wood. The Treetalkers are isolationist, xenophobic, and deeply hostile to any presence they deem "spirit-blind" — which includes all mainlanders and most members of clans other than the Daudrguard. Their prophecies are cryptic, their rituals are disturbing (they swallow chips of petrified wood and claim to dream the forest's memories), and their political influence is absolute within the Deadwood and negligible outside it.
The Burned Priests of the Heitdalr are fire-shamans who practice ritual scarification — burning sacred symbols into their own skin using heated obsidian blades. The scars are a living text, a body-scripture that records the volcano's teachings. Each pattern corresponds to a specific prophecy, warning, or geological truth (the Burned Priests can predict eruptions with startling accuracy, which suggests their mysticism rests on a foundation of practical vulcanology). They are the sole interpreters of the volcano's will, and their word determines whether the Heitdalr's geothermal resources are shared, hoarded, or offered to visitors.
The Whaletooth Compact
The Frozen South's only pan-regional institution. Established in oral tradition long before the empire existed — the fire-songs place its origin "in the time before the ice remembered its own name," which is poetic and unhelpful.
The Compact is the agreement by which the clans coexist. Its terms are simple:
The Winter-Moot gathers once a year, at midwinter, in the Kjölfoss Deeps. Every clan sends its chief and its fire-singer. Attendance is mandatory. Absence is war.
The Pack Leader is named at the Moot to guide the clans for the coming year. The Pack Leader arbitrates disputes, coordinates hunts, allocates shared resources (particularly the Heitdalr's food production), and speaks for the south in any dealings with outsiders. The position is theoretically temporary and theoretically elective. In practice, Clan Aurax has held it for most of recorded memory, because gold buys loyalty and loyalty buys votes.
Disputes between clans are settled at the Moot by one of three methods: negotiation (talking), compensation (paying), or the Holmgang — a ritual single combat between champions of the disputing clans, fought on a marked circle of hide laid on the floor of the great hall. The Holmgang is fought to first blood, not to death (though deaths occur with regularity, because "first blood" from a gold-edged war-axe tends to be followed immediately by "all remaining blood"). The Holmgang's verdict is final. No appeal. No revenge. A clan that refuses to honor a Holmgang result is outcast — stricken from the fire-songs.
The Gold-Right. The Compact acknowledges Clan Aurax's control of the Kjölfoss gold deposits but requires that a portion of the annual yield — the Moot-share — be distributed to all clans in proportion to their size. This provision was the glue that held the system together for centuries. The Aurax paid, and the other clans tolerated Aurax dominance because the alternative — war for the gold — was worse than tribute. The system worked as long as gold remained the only currency that mattered. The arrival of mainland steel has broken that equation.
Fauna
The Frozen South's animal life is sparse, specialized, and dangerous.
Domesticated: The Auric-Horn Yak — a massive, shaggy bovine with horns that develop a golden patina from mineral deposits in the mountain graze, used for milk, meat, hide, and transport. Ice-Treader Reindeer — lighter, faster, used for sledge teams in the interior; their harnesses are hung with bead-bells that ward spirits and, more practically, alert other travelers to an approaching team on blind trails. Sealbulls — semi-domesticated pinnipeds kept in corralled coastal pools for blubber harvests and feast-slaughter.
Wild and predatory: The Glacier Bear — a white-furred giant that stands eight feet at the shoulder, whose claws can shear through ice like glass and through a man's ribcage like wet cloth. Solitary, territorial, and responsible for more deaths per year than all inter-clan violence combined. The Frost Vulpine — a ghost-white fox of unsettling intelligence that folklore says steals the breath of sleeping infants. In reality, it steals food caches and has been observed using coordinated tactics to distract guard dogs while pack-mates raid storage pits.
Messenger animals: The Ivorybeak Goose of Sorn — a fjord-courier trained to carry knotted strap-messages between coastal settlements; reliable in summer, useless in winter storms. The Snow-Kite — a high-pass raptor bred by the Beinsverd mountain clan, trained to fly whistle-code messages and, during the brief winter twilight, to carry small lanterns on their leg-straps to signal across distances that ground-messengers cannot cover in the dark. The Snow-Kites are one of the south's most closely guarded assets. Their breeding pairs are never sold and their training methods are clan secrets.
Cryptid and legendary: The Aurora Serpent — a sky-creature allegedly seen swimming through the northern lights during deep winter, its body a ribbon of luminescence that ripples and coils through the aurora's curtains. No physical evidence exists. Every clan has stories. The fire-songs treat it as real. The Gold Griffin — once supposedly native to the Kjölfoss peaks, its feathers and bones were ground into smithing compounds that gave Aurax goldwork its legendary warmth and luster. No living specimen has been seen in recorded history. Whether the Gold Griffin was a real creature, a misidentified raptor, or a retrospective myth invented to explain why Aurax gold is better than everyone else's is a question that only the Auren Priests claim to be able to answer, and they're not talking.

III. THE FOUR PROVINCES
AURHEIM — The Gold-Rich Mountain Province
Ruling Dynasty: Clan Aurax — Gold mining warlords Vassal/Rival Clan: Clan Beinsverd — Ice-touched mountain warriors Spiritual Authority: The Auren Priests — Shamans and wisemen of the clans Major Settlement: Auren — The golden tribal fortress, built into the Kjölfoss Deeps Population (estimated, 1308 AF): 8,000–10,000
The Aurheim is the roof of the south and the seat of its power. Everything about it is vertical — the mountains, the mine shafts, the social hierarchy. The Kjölfoss peaks are among the youngest mountains on the continent, sharp and jagged where older ranges are worn to rounded hills, their granite flanks shot through with quartz veins that carry gold in concentrations found nowhere else on Mundus. The gold is not hidden. It is visible — veins of yellow-white running through exposed cliff faces, glittering in stream-beds where erosion has washed nuggets downslope, catching the low winter sun and throwing it back as if the mountains themselves were showing off.
Clan Aurax controls the gold and has for as long as anyone can remember. The fire-songs trace the Aurax bloodline back to a figure called Aur-kyn — literally "gold-kin" — who the songs say was born inside the mountain, delivered from a crack in the rock during an earthquake, caked in gold dust, screaming. Whether this is myth, metaphor, or embellished memory of a mine-collapse survivor is immaterial. The Aurax believe it. Their right to rule derives from it. The mountain chose them. The gold is their birthright.
The current Aurax chief — Warlord Thane Eirikr Aurax — is approximately fifty years old, which in the Frozen South means he is entering the period of maximum authority. He has held the Pack Leader title for seven consecutive Moots. He is massive even by southern standards — six foot seven, two hundred and eighty pounds of muscle, scar tissue, and political calculation — and he is the first Aurax chief in generations who is genuinely trying to transform the Pack Leader position from a temporary appointment into a permanent throne.
Eirikr's strategy is simple: use the gold. He has expanded the Moot-share distributions, funding new longhouses for minor clans, commissioning gold-work for chiefs who show loyalty, and hosting feasts of unprecedented lavishness in the Kjölfoss Deeps. He has also begun secret trade with the mainland through House Corbeau, exchanging raw gold for steel weapons, grain, and mainland medicines. The steel has given Aurax warriors a decisive military advantage — their blades hold an edge in the extreme cold where obsidian shatters and bone-weapons chip. But the trade has also made Aurax dependent on a supply chain that runs through the Deadwood, which Clan Daudrguard controls, which means the trade that was supposed to cement Aurax independence has actually created a new vulnerability.
Clan Beinsverd are the Aurheim's other power — ice-touched mountain warriors who guard the high passes connecting the Aurheim to the rest of the peninsula. The Beinsverd are smaller than the Aurax, leaner, adapted to the thinner air of the extreme altitudes where they maintain their holds. They are called "ice-touched" because of a peculiar physiological trait: Beinsverd warriors can tolerate cold that would kill other clansmen. Their exposed skin turns a faint blue-white in extreme temperatures, a circulation adaptation that prevents frostbite at the cost of making them look, to outsiders, like walking corpses. Whether this is genetic adaptation, a result of the mineral-rich hot springs they bathe in from infancy, or — as the Beinsverd themselves claim — a gift from the mountain's spirit, is debated.
The Beinsverd chief — Thane Skaði Beinsverd — is a woman of forty-five, hard as the granite she was raised on, and she despises Eirikr Aurax with a cold, patient hatred that she has cultivated for twenty years. Her grievance is specific: in 1288 AF, during the Aurax Gold War, Eirikr promised the Beinsverd a greater share of the gold yield in exchange for military support. The Beinsverd fought. The Beinsverd bled. The promised gold never came. Skaði has never forgotten. She has also never said a word about it publicly, because the Beinsverd are outnumbered and outweighed and premature confrontation would be suicide. She is waiting. She is watching the Aurax chief build his throne out of foreign steel and mainland promises, and she is counting the cracks.
The Auren Priests are the wildcard. Their traditional role is advisory — they interpret the mountain's will and the clans obey. But the priesthood is splitting. The elder priests, led by the ancient Galdrekr the Stoneblind — a seer who blinded himself forty years ago in imitation of the mountain's darkness (or in imitation of the Ayanite Blind Daughters, though he would burn alive before admitting any mainland influence) — oppose the mainland trade as a spiritual contamination. Foreign metal in southern earth. Foreign grain in southern bellies. Foreign ideas in southern minds. Galdrekr has prophesied that the mountain will "cough gold and swallow blood" if the trade continues, and his prophecies have been accurate often enough that ignoring them is politically dangerous.
The younger priests, led by a sharp-minded opportunist named Kolgrimr, see the trade as the south's salvation. More gold means more offerings. More offerings means the mountain is pleased. Steel weapons mean fewer Aurax warriors die in the mines when tunnels collapse and fewer die in border skirmishes with Raudbjorn raiders. Kolgrimr has positioned himself as Eirikr's spiritual advisor and is whispering that the Pack Leader title should be made permanent — that the mountain itself demands a king.
The Auren Priests have never been this divided. The schism mirrors the larger fracture running through the entire Frozen South: tradition against adaptation, isolation against engagement, the old ways against a future that is arriving whether anyone invited it or not.

IS-RIM — The Frozen Coastal Lowlands
Ruling Dynasty: House Raudbjorn — Fierce coastal raiders Subjugated Rival: House Bearclaw — Ice fishers and seal hunters Spiritual Authority: Whaletooth Priests — Whale-hunting shamans Major Settlement: Iceharbor — The frozen port Population (estimated, 1308 AF): 46,000–60,000
Is-rim is the Frozen South's window to the sea and, increasingly, its doorway to the world. The province occupies the peninsula's western coast — a brutal landscape of deep fjords, grinding glaciers, and the frigid open ocean that stretches westward toward nothing anyone has ever returned from mapping. The air is thick with salt spray, rendered whale-oil smoke, and the iron scent of blood on ice that is the constant perfume of a whaling culture.
The coast is where the south's most ruthless people live, because the coast is where the south's most ruthless environment is. The fjord settlements cling to narrow ledges of habitable land between the water and the cliff, their longhouses built so close to the high-tide line that storm surges regularly flood the lower rooms. The response to flooding is not to move uphill — there is no uphill — but to build the sleeping platforms higher and to teach children to swim before they can walk. Is-rim children are in the water from infancy, their skin oiled against the cold, their lungs trained to hold breath for the long dives that are necessary for kelp-harvesting and under-ice fishing. By adulthood, a coastal clansman can swim in water that would kill a mainlander in minutes, and they consider this a basic life skill rather than an achievement worth mentioning.
House Raudbjorn — the "Red Bears" — have ruled Iceharbor since before the fire-songs can remember. They are raiders, whalers, and opportunists, and they have never pretended to be anything else. Where the Aurax buy loyalty with gold, the Raudbjorns take it with violence. Their longships — fast, shallow-drafted, crewed by warriors who row into battle singing the killing-songs that coordinate their stroke — have raided every settlement on the peninsula at least once and most of them repeatedly. The Raudbjorns do not apologize for this. Raiding is how a coast-clan survives when the fishing is bad and the seal herds have moved. It is economic policy conducted with axes.
The current Raudbjorn chief — Warlord Hreiðar Raudbjorn — is forty-two years old and the most dangerous man in the Frozen South, though few outside Is-rim realize it yet. Hreiðar is not the biggest Raudbjorn (his brother Tormund is larger) or the best fighter (his cousin Sigga has more Holmgang victories) or the most charismatic (his dead wife Yrsa was the one people followed). What Hreiðar is, uniquely and lethally, is patient. He can wait. He can plan. He can smile at a man he intends to kill and make the smile look genuine for years before the blade comes out.
Hreiðar's masterstroke was the Salt-Thaw Bargain — the event that has remade the Frozen South. In approximately 1300 AF, a Roslandic trading vessel, blown off course by a winter storm, washed up in the shallows of Iceharbor with a cargo of steel tools, grain, salted pork, and woolen cloth. The crew was terrified. The Raudbjorns were fascinated. Hreiðar — already chief, already thinking — did not slaughter the sailors. He fed them. He housed them. He learned enough of their language over four months of forced hospitality to understand what they carried and what they wanted. What they wanted was safe harbor, repairs, and to leave. What they carried was steel.
Hreiðar let them leave. He also made them a deal: come back with more steel, more grain, more mainland goods. In exchange, he would provide gold (taken from Aurax tribute), seal-fur, whale-oil, and safe harbor for Roslandic ships. The Roslandic captain — a man named Harken Goss, a minor agent of House Gorban, the Roslandic border wardens — agreed because he recognized the profit potential and because Hreiðar had made it clear, with tremendous politeness, that the alternative to agreement was a shallow grave in the permafrost.
The Salt-Thaw Bargain transformed Iceharbor. Within five years, Raudbjorn warriors were armed with mainland steel — swords, axes, spearheads, mail-shirts that turned the bone-tipped arrows of rival clans into irritants rather than killing blows. The effect was immediate and devastating. Hreiðar launched the Steel Tithe — a campaign of systematic conquest along the coast, demanding tribute from every lesser clan and subjugating those who refused. House Bearclaw — the patient, skilled ice-fishers and seal-hunters who had balanced Raudbjorn power for generations — were the first to fall. Their chief, an old man named Bjálki Bearclaw, surrendered after a single battle in which his bone-armed warriors were slaughtered by steel-clad Raudbjorn berserkers. Bjálki was allowed to live — shaved, humiliated, stripped of his clan-marker — as an object lesson. His people were absorbed into the Raudbjorn labor force, their fire-songs permitted only as addenda to Raudbjorn songs, their identity erased in everything but the memory of those old enough to remember what it meant.
The Whaletooth Priests are in chaos. Their authority has always derived from the whale-hunt — the ability to bless the ships, read the omens, and ensure that the hunt was conducted according to the ancient rituals. But Hreiðar's new power comes from steel, not whales. Some priests have aligned with the Raudbjorns, declaring their military success a divine sign — proof that the sea-gods favor the strong and the cunning. Others have fled to the minor clans, preaching that the Raudbjorns have sold the south's soul for foreign iron and that the whale-spirits will exact payment in blood. The schism in the priesthood mirrors the schism in the clans, and it is producing a theological crisis: if the gods favor strength, then do the gods favor the outsiders who forged the steel? If the sea blesses the hunt, does it also bless the trade that has made the hunt unnecessary?
Hreiðar's next move is the Winter-Moot. He is coming to Auren not to vote, not to negotiate, and not to bend the knee. He is coming to challenge Eirikr Aurax for the title of Pack Leader — and he is bringing an army clad in mainland steel to make the challenge meaningful. The Raudbjorns have never held the Pack Leader title. They have never wanted it. What Hreiðar wants is not the title but the precedent: proof that gold is no longer the only currency that matters. Proof that the Compact can be rewritten. Proof that the future belongs to whoever is willing to reach outside the south and grab it.
Iceharbor is no longer just a port. It is the beachhead of a revolution, and the wave it has unleashed is about to crash against the ancient mountains of the Aurheim.

DAUDR-VIDR (THE DEADWOOD) — The Petrified Forest Region
Ruling Dynasty: Clan Daudrguard — Wardens of the north Vassal Clans: Clan Vidrskjold — Wood harvesters and forest keepers; Clan Hvitfot — Rangers and scouts Spiritual Authority: The Treetalkers — Wood shamans Major Settlement: Grimbone — The fortress of ice and stone Population (estimated, 1308 AF): 24,000–35,000
The Deadwood is the Frozen South's shield, and Clan Daudrguard is its blade.
The Daudr-vidr is not a forest in any living sense. It is a cemetery of trees — hundreds of square miles of petrified trunks and branches, their wood replaced over millennia by silica and iron minerals until every trunk is stone, every branch is stone, every fallen needle is a tiny crystal spike that crunches underfoot like broken glass. The trees stand where they died, bone-white and rigid, their stone branches reaching toward a sky they will never feel again. In winter, when the ice accumulates on the petrified limbs and the wind moans through gaps that were once knotholes, the Deadwood sounds like an organ played by something that doesn't understand music.
The petrification process rendered the forest indestructible by fire, impenetrable by axe, and navigable only by people who have spent their lives learning its paths. The Deadwood has no roads. It has game-trails that shift when ice-storms topple petrified trunks, seasonal waterways that freeze into traversable corridors in winter and become impassable cataracts in the brief thaw, and the secret paths that the Hvitfot rangers maintain — routes marked by subtle signs (a chip in a trunk, a bone wedged in a fork, a pattern of lichen that is not natural lichen but cultivated marker-moss) that are invisible to anyone who doesn't know the code. An army entering the Deadwood without Daudrguard guides will get lost within a mile and die within a week.
Clan Daudrguard has been the Deadwood's Warden-clan since before the fire-songs differentiated between history and myth. Their legitimacy does not come from gold, from conquest, or from divine appointment. It comes from a single, unarguable fact: they have kept the south safe. Every invasion from the mainland — every imperial probing expedition, every Roslandic scouting party, every Church mission, every ambitious merchant — has died in the Deadwood, killed by the forest, the cold, or the Daudrguard warriors who know both intimately enough to weaponize them.
The current Warden-Chief — Thane Vigrún Daudrguard — is a woman of fifty-three who has personally killed more mainland intruders than any Warden in five generations. She is lean where most southerners are broad, wiry where they are thick, with the coiled, ready stillness of a woman who has spent her life ambushing people in terrain that the gods designed specifically for ambushes. Her face is scarred — a Roslandic scout's steel blade opened her left cheek from ear to jaw in 1297 AF, a wound she treats as a trophy rather than a disfigurement. The scar pulled her mouth into a permanent half-smile that makes her look amused even when she is furious, which is most of the time.
Vigrún's politics are simple: the south is for the south. Outsiders are contamination. The Aurax trade with House Corbeau is treason. The Raudbjorn trade with Roslandic merchants is treason. Any clan that brings foreign steel, foreign grain, or foreign ideas through the Deadwood is an enemy of every fire-song ever sung. She has enforced this position with lethal finality.
The Spear-Winter (1296–present) is Vigrún's ongoing campaign against mainland incursion. Roslandic scouts — sent by House Ironside to investigate rumors of southern gold — have been entering the Deadwood with increasing frequency since 1295 AF. Vigrún's response has been systematic and terrifying: every patrol that enters the forest vanishes. No survivors. No bodies. No messages sent back. The only sign that anything happened is the occasional steel spearhead left embedded in a petrified trunk at the forest's northern edge, point facing north — a message that requires no translation.
The disappearances have not gone unnoticed in Rosland. House Gorban, the border wardens, has filed reports. House Ironside, consumed with domestic politics, has filed them away. When they eventually read those reports, they will find that the Deadwood has swallowed approximately forty men in three years and that the forest is sending back their weapons as postcards.
Clan Vidrskjold — the wood-harvesters — are the Deadwood's artisans. They have developed techniques for working petrified wood that no other clan possesses: carving, grinding, and polishing the stone-timber into weapons, tools, building materials, and the hauntingly beautiful household objects (bowls, cups, figurines) that are the Deadwood's only export. Vidrskjold petrified-wood weapons are the Deadwood's answer to mainland steel — in extreme cold, the crystalline structure of the stone-wood becomes harder than iron, and a Vidrskjold war-club can shatter a steel blade if the temperature drops below a certain threshold. This is not reliable enough to be a true military advantage (the temperature has to be genuinely Arctic), but it is reliable enough to be terrifying.
Clan Hvitfot — the "White-Foot" rangers — are scouts, trackers, and the Deadwood's intelligence network. They move through the forest in near-silence, their feet wrapped in white seal-skin that blends with the ice and stone, their movements coordinated by a system of whistle-calls that mimic the wind sounds of the petrified branches. A Hvitfot scout can follow a target through the Deadwood for days without being detected, and their kill reports to Vigrún are delivered with a dispassionate precision that would impress a Magos archivist.
The Treetalkers are the Deadwood's spiritual authority and its most unsettling inhabitants. They believe the petrified trees are not dead but sleeping — that the minerals that replaced the wood also preserved the spirits of the trees, trapping them in stone prisons where they have dreamed for millennia. The Treetalkers claim to hear these dreams. They press their palms and ears against the petrified trunks, entering trance states that last hours or days, and emerge with pronouncements that the clan treats as prophecy. Their current prophecy is grim: the trees are dreaming of fire. Not the fire of the volcano — the fire of the forge. Foreign fire. Fire that reshapes the natural into the useful, that turns ore into blade, tree into plank, freedom into servitude.
Vigrún is marching to the Winter-Moot. She is not going to vote. She is not going to negotiate. She is going to deliver an ultimatum: expel every outsider from the Frozen South, destroy every piece of foreign steel, sever every trade connection with the mainland — or the Deadwood will close. Permanently. No gold will leave the south. No goods will enter. The Daudrguard will seal the border with blood and stone-wood, and the mountain clans can eat their gold while the coast clans can drink their seawater, and the Heitdalr can choose whose side it prefers to burn on.
It is not an empty threat. The Daudrguard control the only land route out of the peninsula. If they close the Deadwood, the south is cut off from the continent entirely.

HEITDALR — The Volcanic Coastal Region
Ruling Dynasty: Clan Eldblod — Lords of fire Allied Clan: Clan Svartselr — Masters of the volcanic coastal waters Spiritual Authority: The Burned Priests — Fire shamans Major Settlement: Hotstone — The warm city in the ice Population (estimated, 1308 AF): 13,000–24,000
The Heitdalr is a land that shouldn't exist — a volcanic province where rivers of molten rock flow into seas of ice and the air smells simultaneously of sulfur and snow. The landscape is a battlefield between geological forces: steam vents hissing through glacial moraine, hot springs bubbling in meadows ringed by permafrost, black basalt cliffs still warm from eruptions that happened centuries ago standing beside blue-white glaciers that have been grinding forward since before humans arrived. The Heitdalr is beautiful in the way that a knife is beautiful — the beauty is in the precision of its contradictions.
Hotstone sits in a geothermally heated valley where the ground temperature stays above freezing year-round. The city — if a settlement of three thousand souls can be called a city — is built around a network of hot springs that the Eldblod have channeled into a heating system of startling sophistication: stone-lined channels carry hot water beneath the floors of every building, warming them from below. The result is a settlement where breath doesn't fog indoors, where vegetables grow in greenhouses fed by volcanic steam, and where the daily bath — in a communal hot-spring pool that serves simultaneously as bathhouse, meeting hall, and social club — is the single most important ritual in Heitdalr life. Deals are struck in the pools. Feuds are settled in the pools. Children are named in the pools. A person who refuses to bathe communally is a person with something to hide, and the Heitdalr does not tolerate hidden things.
Clan Eldblod rules the Heitdalr not through military force — they are the smallest major clan — but through knowledge. They are the keepers of the warmth. They know which valleys are safe to build in, which volcanic vents are predictable and which are lethal, where to dig for obsidian without triggering a collapse, and how to read the mountain's moods in the color of its steam and the temperature of its springs. This knowledge is survival itself. A settlement built in the wrong valley will be buried in lava within a generation. A mine dug in the wrong direction will hit a gas pocket that kills everyone inside. The Eldblod have been getting these decisions right for centuries, and their record is their claim to power.
The current Eldblod chief — Thane Hrafnkel Eldblod — is sixty years old, gentle-voiced, and possibly the most politically intelligent person in the Frozen South. Where Eirikr Aurax thinks in terms of dominance and Hreiðar Raudbjorn thinks in terms of force, Hrafnkel thinks in terms of necessity. Every clan needs the Heitdalr's food. Every clan needs the Heitdalr's obsidian. Every clan needs the Heitdalr's warmth, even if that warmth is only the knowledge that warmth exists somewhere and that refuge is possible if winter turns truly murderous. This makes the Heitdalr the fulcrum on which the entire southern balance rests, and Hrafnkel has spent his life keeping that fulcrum level.
Neutrality has been the Heitdalr's policy since before Hrafnkel was born, and he has maintained it with a diplomat's skill and a survivor's ruthlessness. When the Aurax Gold War erupted in 1285, Hrafnkel supplied food to all sides — at a markup. When the Raudbjorn began their Steel Tithe, Hrafnkel offered shelter to refugees from the conquered Bearclaw clan — and charged them for it in labor. When the Daudrguard sealed the northern border, Hrafnkel sent a gift of obsidian blades to Vigrún with a note expressing admiration for her resolve — and simultaneously sent a gift of volcanic glass to Eirikr Aurax with a note expressing concern about Daudrguard aggression. He plays every side because he can afford to. Everyone needs what the Heitdalr has.
But the neutrality is fracturing. The three-way crisis — Aurax ambition, Raudbjorn militarism, Daudrguard isolationism — has created pressures that balance cannot withstand. The Aurax want Heitdalr food to feed their growing garrison of mainland mercenaries. The Raudbjorns want Heitdalr obsidian to arm the warriors who haven't yet received steel. The Daudrguard want a commitment: choose the south or be treated as a traitor. Hrafnkel cannot give all three what they want. He cannot give any of them what they want without antagonizing the other two. The careful neutrality that has protected the Heitdalr for generations has become a trap, and the walls are closing in.
Clan Svartselr — the "Black-Seal" sailors — are the Heitdalr's naval arm. They have mastered the volcanic coast's treacherous waters, where underwater vents create sudden temperature differentials that can crack a ship's hull, where sulfurous fog reduces visibility to nothing, and where the currents shift unpredictably as the seabed vents open and close. Svartselr sailors navigate by smell (the sulfur content of the air indicates proximity to active vents), by water temperature (hands trailed over the gunwale, feeling for the warm currents that mark safe channels), and by a kind of intuitive seamanship that cannot be taught and can only be developed through years of experience and the deaths of everyone who developed it wrong.
The Burned Priests are issuing warnings. The volcano — the Heitdalr's patron, protector, and potential destroyer — is "growing angry." The priests interpret this anger through the increasing frequency of minor tremors, the rising temperature of the deep springs, and the changing color of the summit steam from white to yellow. Whether this represents genuine volcanic activity or the priests' attempt to leverage geological anxiety into political influence is impossible to determine from the outside. From the inside, it doesn't matter. The Heitdalr believes its priests, because the last time the volcano was angry — approximately three hundred years ago — it buried an entire valley in ash and killed four hundred people.
Hrafnkel is going to the Winter-Moot as a man walking a razor's edge. He carries no army, no ultimatum, no challenge. He carries the one thing that every other chief in the south needs and none of them can produce: food that grows when everything else is frozen. His vote — for Aurax or Raudbjorn or Daudrguard or none of them — will likely determine the outcome of the Moot. And every faction knows it. And every faction is making offers. And every offer comes with a threat attached to its underside like a tick on a dog.

IV. COMPLETE HISTORY
The Deep Past (Before 903 AF)
The Frozen South's human history predates reliable chronology. The fire-songs — the oldest continuous oral tradition on the continent — claim an origin so ancient that the concept of "arrival" is absent from the lexicon. The songs say the southern people "were born from the mountain's breath," and the oldest genealogies do not begin with a migration or a landing but with a name: a person who was simply there, as if humanity in the south had always existed and merely needed to be noticed.
The Magos take this seriously. Archaeological evidence — stone tools found in glacial deposits that predate known migration patterns by millennia, cave paintings in the Kjölfoss that depict animals no living person has ever seen — suggests that the Frozen South's population may be indigenous in the fullest sense: people who were there before anyone else arrived, who absorbed later migrants so completely that the distinction between "original" and "arrived" dissolved into the gene pool and the fire-songs without a trace.
During the Age of Republics (roughly 3,000–500 BE), the Frozen South had no contact with mainland political developments. The Deadwood was impassable, the sea route around the peninsula was suicidal in the prevailing currents, and neither the republican city-states nor their successors had any reason to attempt the journey.
During the Age of Fire (the Nionic Empire), contact was marginally more substantial. Imperial scouts reached the Deadwood's northern edge during Nion IV's expansionist campaigns (approximately 400 AF) and reported "a forest of stone trees beyond which nothing lives." A single successful imperial expedition — during the reign of Nion IX (approximately 600 AF) — penetrated the Deadwood using a coastal route and reached Raudbjorn territory. The expedition's commander left a fragmentary account describing "men of great size who fish from boats made of skin and who wear gold ornaments of such artistry that our own jewelers could not replicate them." The expedition withdrew after the Raudbjorns made clear that visitors were welcome to leave or welcome to die.
The empire classified the Frozen South as "tributary in name, independent in fact" and collected no taxes, posted no garrisons, and exercised no authority.
The Age of Faith — Period by Period
The Shattering (903–950 AF):
The empire's dissolution was a non-event in the south. The only significant event was the Destruction of Clan Hroth (c. 940 AF). Clan Hroth — a mountain clan feuding with Aurax for generations over secondary gold deposits — was destroyed through deliberate starvation. Warlord Bjarn Aurax refused to share grain stores during a killing winter. Hroth starved. The survivors were absorbed into Aurax and their fire-songs ritually silenced — every Hroth name, deed, and memory erased from the oral record. The destruction of Hroth set the precedent that the Whaletooth Compact's protections were contingent on power, not principle.
The Age of Orders (950–1050 AF):
The Ice-Road Wars (c. 980–990 AF): Clan Raudbjorn attempted to establish winter trade routes across the frozen interior, bypassing Aurax-controlled mountain passes. Aurax raided the caravans, destroyed way-caches, and collapsed bridge-points. Ten years of seasonal skirmishing — brutal in winter when the ice-roads were usable, suspended in summer when the ice melted. Ended inconclusively. The ice-roads were abandoned. But the wars established the Raudbjorn-Aurax rivalry as the defining tension of southern politics.
The Lovist Church sent its first mission to the Deadwood in approximately 1020 AF. The Brothers of the Open Road reached the forest edge, discovered it was impassable, and turned back. A second mission in 1085 AF made it through with Roslandic guides, reached a Daudrguard outpost, and was killed to the last man. Their bones were woven into the walls of Grimbone.
The Century of Blood (1050–1150 AF):
The First Gold War (c. 1070–1080 AF): Clan Raudbjorn, under Chief Hreiðar the Elder (ancestor of the current Hreiðar), attempted to seize the Kjölfoss Deeps. The assault was bold, well-planned, and doomed. Coastal raiders operating in mountain terrain they did not understand were funneled into mine-shaft approaches where Aurax miners fought with hammers and picks in close quarters. Ten years of fighting in conditions that would make a Roslandic veteran weep — winter battles on ice-covered slopes, night ambushes in blizzard whiteouts, clashes in mine tunnels too low to stand in. Aurax won through attrition and terrain advantage. Raudbjorn was forced to pay tribute in whale-oil and seal-fur for a full generation. The defeat created a permanent grudge.
The Golden Century (1150–1250 AF):
Relative peace. Aurax dominance unchallenged. The Winter-Moot functioned. Cultural traditions crystallized. Goldsmithing reached its peak — the Aurax smiths of this century produced pieces no subsequent generation has equaled. The fire-song tradition was formalized.
The Beinsverd Oath (c. 1200 AF): Clan Beinsverd negotiated a formal compact with Aurax — military service for autonomy and a dedicated gold share. The arrangement worked for a century. It stopped working when Eirikr Aurax broke its terms.
The Long Peace and Its Cracks (1250–1308 AF):
The Wildwoman's Bargain (c. 1270 AF): Ser Edric Corbeau — a Heartlander knight patrolling the Deadwood borderlands — encountered Sinna, an Aurax clanwoman, in the northern Deadwood. They fell in love across the language barrier, meeting at a specific clearing, exchanging gifts (his steel knife, her gold torc), building shared vocabulary from gesture and repetition. Sinna returned to Clan Aurax and argued for trade with the mainland, presenting the steel knife as proof. Warlord Gunnar Aurax authorized a trial. The first gold-for-goods trade began c. 1272 AF — raw gold through the Deadwood to House Corbeau's trading posts, steel and grain flowing back. The trade was secret from other clans. It enriched both parties and gave Aurax a decisive military advantage.
The Aurax Gold War (c. 1285–1290 AF): The secret trade was discovered. Raudbjorn and Daudrguard declared war on Aurax. Five years of vicious winter warfare. Aurax won — steel weapons gave them a decisive edge. The turning point: the Battle of Frost-Hollow (1289 AF), where the young Eirikr Aurax led a steel-armed strike force through a blizzard to catch a Raudbjorn war-camp unprepared. The Raudbjorn chief — Hreiðar the Elder — was captured, shaved, and sent home on foot. He died within three months. The Winter-Moot of 1291 confirmed Aurax dominance.
The Spear-Winter (1296–present): Vigrún Daudrguard's campaign against Roslandic scouts entering the Deadwood. Approximately forty men killed in three years. Their weapons left as warnings.
The Salt-Thaw Bargain (c. 1300 AF): A Roslandic trading vessel washed up in Iceharbor. Hreiðar Raudbjorn recognized the opportunity, learned the crew's language, and struck a trade deal with Captain Harken Goss. Steel weapons flooded the coast.
The Steel Tithe (c. 1302–1307 AF): Hreiðar's conquest of the coastal clans using mainland steel. House Bearclaw subjugated. Chief Bjálki shaved and broken.
The Giants Arrive (1308 AF): Two Giants — Thyra of the Brúnaveld and Grevaan of the Gahlmarr — survived a shipwreck off the Frozen South's coast. One juvenile mammoth survived with them. They are in Raudbjorn territory. Hreiðar is keeping them secret.

V. CURRENT STATE OF AFFAIRS — 1308 AF
The Convergence
Everything is converging on the Winter-Moot.
Four chiefs are traveling to the Kjölfoss Deeps. Each brings a different weapon. Each intends a different outcome. None of them fully understands what the others are bringing.
Eirikr Aurax arrives as Pack Leader, expecting to be confirmed for life. His weapon is gold and the inertia of tradition. He believes the Moot is a coronation.
Hreiðar Raudbjorn arrives as a challenger, armed with mainland steel and the fury of a clan that has spent a generation nursing a blood-grudge. He intends to challenge Eirikr for the Pack Leader title through Holmgang — steel against gold-plated bone-weapons. Not a contest. An execution.
Vigrún Daudrguard arrives with her war-leaders and her ultimatum. Her weapon is geography — the Deadwood's impassability, the border she can seal with a word. She wants the south purged of foreign contamination. If the Moot refuses, she will close the Deadwood permanently.
Hrafnkel Eldblod arrives carrying no army, no challenge, and no ultimatum. His weapon is food — the Heitdalr's year-round agriculture. Whoever he supports will eat through the winter. Whoever he opposes will not. His vote is the deciding vote, and he has not yet decided how to cast it.
And somewhere on the coast, in a Raudbjorn camp that no one else knows about, two Giants are waiting. One of them is listening to the ground. The other is watching a mammoth calf eat snow. Neither of them knows what the Winter-Moot is. Neither of them knows that their presence — if revealed — would change everything.
The Frozen South has survived for millennia by being too cold, too remote, and too difficult to conquer. That era is ending. The mainland is coming — in the form of steel weapons, trade goods, scouting parties, and the insatiable hunger for gold that drives empires to the ends of the earth. The clans can adapt, resist, or destroy each other fighting about which option to choose.
The fire-songs will remember whatever happens next. That is the one certainty left.

