IX. THEMATIC TENSIONS (For Narrative Use)
Tradition vs. Adaptation. Can a culture survive contact with the outside world without losing the things that made it worth preserving? The Aurax say yes. The Daudrguard say no. The Raudbjorns say the question is irrelevant — power is what matters. The Heitdalr says all three are right and all three are wrong, and tries to keep everyone alive long enough to figure out which.
Gold vs. Steel. The old currency against the new. Gold is beautiful, portable, and spiritually significant — the earth's blood, the mountain's gift. Steel is ugly, functional, and overwhelmingly superior as a killing tool. The transition from a gold-based to a steel-based power structure is the Frozen South's version of the moment when everything changes and nothing can change back.
Memory vs. Power. The fire-songs are the south's memory, law, and identity. But fire-songs can be silenced. Clan Hroth proved that. If the Raudbjorns conquer the Aurheim, whose fire-songs will survive? Memory is a weapon, and the people who control the singing control the past, and the people who control the past control the legitimacy of whatever comes next.
Isolation vs. Empire. The mainland is coming. It is coming as traders, scouts, diplomats, armies. The question is not whether the south will be drawn into the continent's conflicts but how: as a partner, a vassal, a conquest, or a force that reshapes the continent on its own terms.
The Giants. Two survivors from a dying civilization, carrying the last mammoth on the continent, hidden in a coastal camp, unknown to anyone except the most dangerous man in the south. They are refugees. They are miracles. They are weapons waiting to be deployed. And their presence — when it is finally revealed — will shatter every calculation that every chief has made, because nobody in the Frozen South has ever seen anything like them, and nobody has a fire-song that tells them what to do when the impossible washes up on the beach.



THE TEETH — Four Islands, One Bridge, No Agreement
Complete Regional Bible — 1308 AF

I. THE ARCHIPELAGO AT A GLANCE
Total Population: ~950,000 Islands: Northwind (~180,000), Emberstone (~250,000), Verwhisper (~350,000), Shadowtide (~60,000, estimate — no census has ever succeeded) Government: None unified. Each island governs independently. The Bridge Council that once provided loose coordination was destroyed by Morvayn's coup in 1298 AF. The current state is the Whispering War — a cold conflict of espionage, economic strangulation, and carefully deniable assassination. Economy: Volcanic stone (Emberstone), timber and grain (Verwhisper), fishing and maritime services (Northwind), rare hardwoods and exotic goods (Shadowtide), and the bridge tolls that were once shared and are now Morvayn's personal revenue stream Religion: Orthodox Loveism on Verwhisper (deeply), nominal on Northwind and Emberstone, and something else entirely on Shadowtide

II. THE GREAT BRIDGE — The Spine of the World
Before the islands. Before the houses. Before any of it. The Bridge.
It connects the four islands in a chain — Northwind to Emberstone, Emberstone to Verwhisper, Verwhisper to Shadowtide — with branches linking to the mainland at the Red Coast's eastern shore. Its total span, including the branch connections and the junction towers, exceeds forty miles. It is the longest artificial structure on the continent. It is also the oldest. And no one knows who built it.
The Magos' best estimate places the Bridge's construction in the deep Age of History — thousands of years before the empire, before the republics, before written language. The engineering is impossible by current standards: arched spans of fitted stone, each block weighing tons, joined without mortar by a precision so exact that a knife blade cannot be inserted between the seams. The stone is not local — geological analysis identifies it as a basalt variant found nowhere in the archipelago and nowhere on the mainland. It was quarried somewhere else and transported here by methods that no living engineer can explain.
The Bridge does not decay. The stone does not weather. Seawater, salt spray, storm wind, centuries of foot traffic — the surface shows wear, but the structure beneath is unchanged. The repair work that every generation adds (mortar patches, iron reinforcements, replacement cobblestones) deteriorates normally around the original fabric, creating a visual record: crumbling human additions bolted to inhuman permanence. The contrast is unsettling. Maintenance crews report that the original stone is slightly warm to the touch, regardless of air temperature or time of day. The warmth is consistent across the entire span. No one has ever explained it. The Magos suspect echo-engineering — the stone was worked during the Age of History when the echo-field was dense enough to produce materials with properties that current science cannot replicate. If they are correct, the Great Bridge is the largest surviving echo-artifact on the continent.
The Towers
At each island junction, a tower rises from the Bridge — not an addition but an integral part of the original construction, grown from the same seamless basalt. The towers are eight-sided, roughly 120 feet tall, with internal staircases spiraling to observation platforms at their summits. There are five towers total: Northgate, Cinderpost, Thornwatch, Tideveil, and the central tower — the Keystone — which stands at the Bridge's midpoint, equidistant from all four islands, surrounded by open water on every side.
The Keystone is where Lord Borakin was murdered. It is where Morvayn now keeps his seat.
The Current Situation
Morvayn controls the Keystone and the two towers flanking it (Cinderpost and Thornwatch). His soldiers man the toll-gates. His tariffs are set at levels designed to maximize revenue while keeping trade just barely viable — the economic equivalent of bleeding a patient: enough to weaken, not enough to kill. The other two towers (Northgate and Tideveil) are held by the island lords — Stormglass at Northgate, an uneasy Verdane-aligned garrison at Tideveil. The Bridge itself is technically open. In practice, every crossing is an intelligence operation: Morvayn's tollmen record every traveler, every cargo, every conversation overheard at the gates. The Whispering War's primary battlefield is the Bridge itself — the forty miles of stone where everyone is visible and nothing is private.

III. NORTHWIND — The Storm's Anvil
The Island
The northernmost island. Rocky, treeless, wind-scoured, and possessed of a beauty that you have to earn through discomfort. Northwind is what happens when the sea decides to carve an island out of pure stubbornness — cliffs like the edges of broken plates, coves where the water churns white year-round, and a wind that blows constantly, shifting direction without warning, strong enough to knock a grown man sideways on an exposed ridge. The island has no trees because the wind kills them. The grass grows at an angle. The sheep grow their wool so thick they look like boulders.
The sky is the island's masterpiece. Nowhere else in the archipelago — nowhere else on the continent — does the sky perform like it does over Northwind. The lack of canopy, the absence of haze, the constant wind clearing the atmosphere — the result is a dome of color that stretches from horizon to horizon: silver, slate, pearl, and the sudden, heart-stopping blue that breaks through on the rare clear day and lasts just long enough to make you ache for it when it's gone. Northwind sunsets are the most photographed natural phenomenon on the continent (if photography existed). They are also the most lied about — every Northwinder claims theirs was the best, and no one can prove them wrong.
The City
Galehold (pop. ~70,000) — The Windhome. Built into the island's eastern cliff face — the leeward side, sheltered from the worst of the prevailing westerlies. Galehold is not built on the cliff. It is built in the cliff — a city of cave-homes, carved terraces, and protected courtyards that step down the rock face from the Stormglass fortress at the summit to the harbor at the base. The architecture is horizontal rather than vertical (tall buildings catch the wind and die), with thick stone walls, narrow windows, and the distinctive windcatchers — curved stone funnels mounted on rooftops that channel the constant wind through buildings for ventilation while blocking the worst of its force. The sound of Galehold is the sound of wind moving through stone — a permanent, low, musical hum that residents stop hearing after a month and visitors never forget.
The harbor is protected by a natural breakwater — a reef of volcanic rock extending from the cliff base — supplemented by a massive stone seawall that took three generations to build and that is Northwind's proudest engineering achievement. The harbor holds the island's fishing fleet (roughly 200 vessels), the merchant marine (40 trading ships), and the Stormglass war-fleet (12 warships — small by continental standards, but crewed by the finest sailors in the archipelago).
Districts:
The Perch — The Stormglass fortress and the noble quarter. Carved into the cliff's highest point, accessible by a single switchback road. The fortress's walls are original Bridge-stone — blocks salvaged (or stolen, depending on who you ask) from a collapsed Bridge section during the imperial era. The stone is warm to the touch. The fortress has never fallen.
The Warrens — Residential district. Hundreds of cave-homes carved into the middle cliff face, connected by tunnels, stairways, and the rope-and-pulley lifts that residents use to transport goods between levels. A newcomer can get lost in the Warrens for hours. A resident can cross the district in minutes through shortcuts that don't appear on any map.
The Keel — The harbor district. Docks, chandleries, rope-walks, fish-processing sheds, and the taverns where Northwind's maritime culture lives its loudest life. The Gale's Tooth — the island's most famous tavern — serves a black beer brewed with kelp-filtered seawater and a fish pie that visiting Horns sailors grudgingly admit rivals their own.
The Roost — The guildhall of the Windreaders — Northwind's weather-prediction specialists. Not a formal guild but a knowledge tradition passed through families: the ability to read wind, cloud, pressure, and the behavior of seabirds to predict weather with accuracy that mainlanders consider supernatural. It is not supernatural. It is the product of generations of observation refined into an intuitive science. The Windreaders sell their forecasts to every ship in the harbor. A Windreader who gets a forecast wrong loses their reputation. A Windreader who gets three wrong loses their seat in the Roost. The current Chief Windreader, Thyra Halcyon (age 55), has not been wrong in eleven years. She attributes this to experience. Her apprentices suspect something more — Thyra spends hours on the cliff-top in conditions that would hospitalize a lesser woman, and she describes what she feels in terms that sound less like meteorology and more like the echo-system's weather-sensing capacity.

House Stormglass — The Wind-Lords
Seat: The Perch, Galehold Sigil: A silver lightning bolt striking a black sea Words: "We Read the Storm"
Navigators, sailors, and the Teeth's oldest surviving dynasty. The Stormglass family served as imperial naval scouts — the specialists who charted the archipelago's treacherous waters and guided the empire's war-fleets through channels that would destroy anyone sailing blind. When the empire fell, the Stormglass kept the charts and the expertise. They have governed Northwind for four centuries with the pragmatic competence of people who understand that the sea doesn't care about your politics.
Lord Aedan Stormglass (age 48) — Head of house. A sailor before he was a lord — he captained merchant vessels for fifteen years before his father's death called him home. He resents the desk. He compensates by sailing personally on the quarterly patrol of the island's waters, a tradition that his court considers reckless and his sailors consider the only reason they respect him. Aedan is lean, salt-scarred, and possessed of a calm that comes from years of navigating storms that could kill him — the calm of a man who has accepted the worst and found it manageable.
Aedan wants Morvayn dead. Not removed, not negotiated with — dead. The Bridge coup killed Lord Borakin, who was Aedan's friend, and the toll increases are strangling Northwind's fishing trade. Aedan has proposed military action to the other island lords. Verdane demurred. Pyrmont is split. Shadowtide, as always, didn't respond. Aedan is now considering unilateral action — a naval assault on the Keystone tower. His admirals tell him it's feasible but costly. His wife tells him it's suicide.
Lady Maren Stormglass (age 45) — Aedan's wife. Born a Horns Dalgaard (salt merchant's daughter), she came to Northwind as a trade envoy and stayed because the island's wind reminded her of home and because Aedan reminded her of no one she'd ever met. She is the household's strategist — not military (she defers to Aedan's admirals) but political. She maintains back-channel communications with Verwhisper through Lampkeeper intermediaries, she manages the island's rationed trade through Porto Rubia on the Red Coast (bypassing Morvayn's tolls via sea route), and she has been quietly stockpiling grain in the Perch's deep cellars against the possibility of a full blockade.
Kael Stormglass (age 22) — Heir. A navigator prodigy — he passed the Stormglass certification at sixteen, the youngest in the family's history. He can read currents by watching wave patterns and predict tidal changes by the behavior of seabirds. He is also impulsive, hot-tempered, and has been running unauthorized intelligence operations against Morvayn's toll-stations — sending agents disguised as merchants to map guard rotations and identify weaknesses. His father doesn't know. His mother suspects. Kael is the most likely Stormglass to start the shooting war that everyone is trying to avoid.
Old Edda Stormglass (age 80) — Aedan's mother. The island's living memory. She remembers the Bridge Council before Morvayn, remembers Lord Borakin alive, remembers a time when crossing from island to island was an afternoon walk rather than an intelligence operation. She sits in the Perch's highest window — a chair positioned to face the Bridge's Northgate tower — and watches. She counts the soldiers on the ramparts. She notes shift changes. She has been compiling a log for ten years. The log is the most detailed surveillance record of Morvayn's military operations in existence. She has shared it with no one. She is waiting to be asked.

Minor Houses and Powers — Northwind
House Halcyon — The Windreaders' founding family. Not technically noble but functionally essential. Chief Windreader Thyra Halcyon's forecasts are more valuable than any lordship.
House Tern — Fishing fleet operators. Control roughly half the island's commercial fishing. Captain Bram Tern (age 50) — the fleet's commodore — is Aedan's most reliable naval asset in the event of war.
House Corwyn — Rope-makers. Their product is the best in the archipelago. A Corwyn rope holds when everything else fails. The family's matriarch, Old Britta Corwyn (age 72), has been making rope for sixty years and considers the entire political situation a distraction from her real work.
The Seal-Callers — Not a house but a tradition. A small number of Northwind fishermen (~30) who can apparently communicate with the grey seals that breed on the island's western shores. They use the seals as fish-finders — the seals dive, the fishermen follow, and the catch rates are consistently higher than those of conventional fishing crews. The Seal-Callers attribute this to "knowing the seal-speech." The mechanism is almost certainly echo-communication — the fishermen, raised in proximity to echo-rich marine mammals, have developed a rudimentary sensitivity that allows them to feel the seals' behavior-patterns. They do not know this. They know it works.

Settlements — Northwind
Cliffmere (~5,000) — Fishing town on the western coast. Exposed to the full force of the prevailing wind. Every building is roped to iron stakes driven into the bedrock — during the worst storms, the ropes are all that keeps the roofs on. Known for its storm-smoked fish — caught, gutted, and hung in the wind to cure without fire, producing a texture and flavor unique to the island.
Selkham (~3,000) — The Seal-Callers' home village. A cove settlement where the grey seal colony breeds. The village has an understanding with the seals that outsiders find eerie: the seals haul out on the village's beach, sleep among the boats, and allow themselves to be touched by the fishermen. They bite anyone else. The village pub is called The Barking Dog — a joke about the seals. The seals don't get it.
Windhollow (~1,500) — A hamlet in the island's interior valley — the only place on Northwind sheltered enough from wind to grow vegetables. The valley is Northwind's breadbasket: root crops, hardy greens, and the Northwind Turnip — a vegetable so tough and flavorless that it has become a symbol of the island's character. "Hard as a Northwind turnip" is a compliment.
Ravenscar (~800) — An abandoned fortress on the island's northern tip, now home to a colony of ravens so large and so old that the birds have become semi-domesticated — they accept food from the few families that shelter in the fortress's lee. The ravens are used by Stormglass scouts as message-carriers (slower than the Carvallo parrots but capable of flying in weather that would kill any tropical bird). Raven-Master Osric (age 60) maintains the flock and speaks to the birds in a low, clicking language he claims they understand. They seem to.
The Nail (~200) — A lighthouse station on a sea-stack off the island's western coast, accessible only by rope-bridge during low tide. The lighthouse keeper — Keeper Solvei (age 35) — lives alone with a cat, a library of navigational charts, and the conviction that the sea-stack is moving. She has been measuring. It is moving. Half an inch per year, toward the open ocean. She has reported this. Nobody cares. She keeps measuring.

IV. EMBERSTONE — The Forge Beneath
The Island
Volcanic. Two active cones — Mount Sova (the larger, southern peak, perpetually smoking) and Mount Vrek (the smaller, northern cone, more active but less consistent) — dominate an island of black basalt, red scoria, and the grey-green lichen that is the only thing hardy enough to colonize fresh lava flows. The air tastes of sulfur. The ground vibrates — a low, constant tremor that newcomers find alarming and residents describe as "the island breathing." Geothermal vents provide heating, mineral extraction, and the hot springs that Emberstone's culture revolves around. The quarries produce the volcanic basalt that is the continent's hardest building stone. And somewhere beneath the quarries, in a vault carved from the volcanic bedrock, the Magos' most dangerous secret waits in the dark.
The City
Ashenport (pop. ~80,000) — The island's capital and primary port, built on Emberstone's eastern coast where the lava flows have created a series of natural harbors protected by basalt headlands. The city is warm — geothermally heated streets, steam venting from grates, and the permanent sulfurous haze that gives the air a tang the residents call "the island's perfume." The architecture is volcanic stone — dark, heavy, built to withstand earthquakes — with the distinctive Emberstone feature: steam-channels carved into the walls of public buildings, carrying geothermal heat through the structure like stone veins. In the morning, when the air is cool, the buildings exhale visible steam from their facades. The effect is beautiful and slightly infernal.
Districts:
The Crownsmoke — The Pyrmont estate and the quarry-workers' guildhall quarter. Named for the permanent smoke plume from Mount Sova visible above the rooftops.
The Baths — Emberstone's social center. A district of public and private hot-spring bathhouses — the hammam tradition here predates Loveism and has outlasted every political change. The baths are where business is conducted, alliances formed, intelligence exchanged, and Morvayn's agents eavesdrop on everyone. The grandest bath — the Obsidian Pool — is a natural hot spring lined with polished volcanic glass that reflects the bathers' bodies in dark, distorted shapes. It is simultaneously the most luxurious and the most unsettling bathing experience in the archipelago.
The Quarry Steps — Working-class district. The quarry-workers' housing, terraced into the hillside above the quarry pits. Hard, functional, and the political base that Morvayn cultivated before his coup — the workers who felt Pyrmont had enriched itself at their expense and who supported Morvayn's promise of "fair shares."
The Steamworks — Industrial district. Forges, smelters, and the geothermal-powered workshops that produce Emberstone's metalwork and glass. The heat in the Steamworks is intense enough that workers rotate on four-hour shifts. Longer exposure risks heat-madness — a disorientation produced by sustained high temperatures that Ashenport's physicians treat with cold-water immersion and that Ashenport's tavern-keepers treat with chilled beer.

House Pyrmont — The Quarry-Kings
Seat: Pyrmont House, Ashenport (a fortress built from a single massive block of volcanic basalt, carved rather than constructed) Sigil: A red flame beneath a black mountain Words: "We Work the Fire"
The Pyrmonts were overseers. That's the truth they've spent four centuries trying to bury. When the empire fell and Nion XIII's edict freed the quarry slaves, the Pyrmont family — the head overseers who had administered the quarries for the empire — simply continued administering them, transitioning from enslaving the workers to employing them at wages that the workers' grandchildren are still trying to renegotiate.
Lord Hakon Pyrmont (age 55) — The current lord. Caught between Morvayn's ambition and his own island's fracture. Hakon opposed the Bridge coup — Lord Borakin was his ally, and Morvayn was a minor noble from his own island whose ambition Hakon had been too complacent to restrain. Now Morvayn controls the Bridge, half of Emberstone's quarry-workers support him, and Hakon is a lord whose authority extends as far as his fortress walls and not much further.
Hakon is not a weak man — he is a steady man in an unsteady situation. He maintains the quarry operations (the economy must function or everyone starves), he negotiates with Morvayn's agents (refusing entirely would trigger a blockade), and he quietly supports the intelligence network that Dalla Garrun of Westhorn has been building to undermine Morvayn's position. He sleeps badly. The island's tremors, which he never noticed before, now keep him awake.
Sera Pyrmont (age 28) — Hakon's daughter. The family's firebrand. She has been organizing the quarry-workers who oppose Morvayn — the ones who realized that "fair shares" meant "Morvayn's share" — into a resistance network operating in the quarry tunnels where Morvayn's agents can't follow. The network is small (~200 workers), poorly armed, and sustained by Sera's personal charisma and the workers' memory of broken promises. Sera does not know about the Magos vault beneath the quarries. She has, however, noticed that certain deep tunnels are warmer than they should be, that the stone in those tunnels has a different texture, and that sounds carry strangely — echoes that arrive before the sound that produced them.

Lord Morvayn — The Usurper
Seat: The Keystone Tower, Great Bridge (and a commandeered estate in Ashenport's Crownsmoke district) No formal sigil — Morvayn uses a plain black banner. The absence of heraldry is deliberate: he presents himself as a man of the people, not a dynast. No formal words — his followers use: "The Bridge Provides"
Lord-Warden Edvard Morvayn (age 42) — A minor Emberstone noble who became the most disruptive political force in the archipelago through a single act of perfectly calculated treachery. Morvayn is not a monster. He is something harder to fight: a man with a plausible grievance and the intelligence to exploit it. His argument — that the Bridge Council was a cartel of island lords enriching themselves through toll-revenue while the common people saw nothing — was not wrong. His solution — murder the Council chairman and seize the Bridge — was not justified. But the workers who support him don't care about justification. They care about the gold that Morvayn's tolls generate and that Morvayn distributes (selectively, strategically) into the quarry towns, the fishing villages, and the pockets of the people whose loyalty he needs.
Morvayn is tall, dark-haired, handsome in a sharp-edged way that reads as either distinguished or predatory depending on your politics. He speaks well — the measured, reasonable tone of a man explaining something obvious to people who should have understood it already. His personal courage is real — he killed Lord Borakin himself (the poison was a backup; Morvayn had a blade under the table if the wine didn't work). His administrative competence is genuine — the Bridge tolls are collected efficiently, the infrastructure is maintained, and the travelers who pay the extortionate fees are treated with professional courtesy.
His weakness: paranoia. Morvayn trusts no one completely. His inner circle rotates — advisors who get too close are reassigned to distant postings before they can accumulate enough knowledge to threaten him. He sleeps in a different room of the Keystone each night, selected at random. He employs three food-tasters. He has not left the Bridge in two years — the Keystone is his seat, his fortress, and his prison. He controls the most important structure on the continent. He cannot walk away from it.
Morvayn's People:
Captain Gheral (age 35) — Commander of the Keystone garrison. 200 soldiers, hand-picked, well-paid. Gheral is loyal to Morvayn because Morvayn pays better than anyone else and because Gheral, a former quarry-guard, genuinely believes the old order deserved to fall.
Toll-Master Venn (age 50) — Administers the toll system. A former merchant who switched sides during the coup because Morvayn's tolls, though high, are more consistently applied than the old Council's. Venn is efficient, incorruptible by anyone except Morvayn, and in possession of the most detailed trade-flow data in the archipelago — information that Morvayn uses to calibrate his economic pressure.
The Whisper — Morvayn's spymaster. No one knows the Whisper's real name, gender, or location. Communications arrive as unsigned notes in wax-sealed copper tubes — the same format the Carvallo parrots use, deliberately echoing a system that implies organizational sophistication. The Whisper may be one person or a network. Morvayn himself may not know. The intelligence the Whisper produces is accurate, timely, and the reason Morvayn has survived ten years of assassination attempts.

The Magos Vault
Beneath the quarries of Emberstone, in chambers carved from the volcanic bedrock at a depth of approximately 300 feet, the Order of Magos maintains a secret vault of artifacts from the Age of History. The vault has been operational for over a thousand years. Its existence is known to three people: Grand Magos Thessaly Vane, Vault-Keeper Odo on the Isle of Knowledge, and Keeper Alenn — the Magos agent responsible for maintaining the Emberstone installation.
Alenn has not visited the vault in three years. Morvayn's security makes covert access to the quarries extremely difficult. The vault's automated systems (such as they are — oil-lamp timers, ventilation channels, moisture-control mechanisms) were designed for regular maintenance, not three years of neglect. Alenn does not know what state the vault is in. She fears the worst.
What's in the vault: approximately 200 artifacts, ranging from small hand-tools to large structural components, all dating to the Age of History. The artifacts include metals that don't corrode, ceramic instruments of unknown purpose, stone tablets covered in the same untranslated script found at other Age of History sites, and — the vault's most significant holding — a section of the Great Bridge's original construction material, removed during a repair operation in 1067 AF and stored for study. The Bridge-stone section is the most echo-dense object in the vault. It is warm. It hums at a frequency below hearing. When Keeper Alenn last visited, she placed her hand on it and felt — for a fraction of a second — the sensation of standing on the Bridge during a storm, with the wind and the spray and the vast indifference of the sea. The sensation was not a memory. She had never stood on the Bridge during a storm. The stone was sharing.

V. VERWHISPER — The Green Cathedral
The Island
Everything Northwind is not. Where Northwind is bare, Verwhisper is clothed — in temperate hardwood forest so lush that the island looks, from the sea, like a green dome rising from the water. Where Northwind is wind-scoured, Verwhisper is sheltered — the island's mountainous interior breaks the prevailing weather, creating a mild, humid microclimate that supports the most productive agriculture in the archipelago. Where Northwind is spare, Verwhisper is abundant — orchards, terraced farmland, managed woodland, and the monastery gardens that the Order of the Green Thorn has been cultivating for three centuries.
Verwhisper smells like earth, rain, and growing things. The light filters through the canopy in shafts of green-gold. The birdsong is constant — not the screaming of parrots (wrong climate) but the layered, melodic calls of warblers, thrushes, and the Verwhisper nightingale, whose song is so beautiful that the Order of the Green Thorn has declared it a devotional instrument — "Vena's voice in feathered form."
The island's religious character is genuine, not performative. Verwhisper is the most devout polity in the Teeth — not in the rigid, punitive mode of Jous's Pure Way, but in the gentle, nature-reverencing tradition of the Ashanite order. The Order of the Green Thorn — the Ashanite sub-order dedicated to forest conservation — is not merely present on the island; it is the island's co-government, its educational system, its healthcare provider, and its moral compass. House Verdane rules in secular matters. The Green Thorn rules in everything else. The arrangement works because both sides believe, genuinely, in the same thing: the forest is sacred, and the people who live in it are its stewards, not its owners.
The City
Thornhaven (pop. ~65,000) — The island's capital. Built in a wide valley where the forest opens onto terraced farmland, Thornhaven is the Teeth's breadbasket city — the markets overflow with grain, fruit, vegetables, cured meat, honey, and the herbal medicines that the Green Thorn monasteries produce. The architecture is half-timbered — dark oak frames filled with white plaster, steep-pitched roofs of wooden shingle, and the carved lintels depicting intertwined leaves and branches that are Verwhisper's signature decorative tradition. Every building has a garden. Every garden has a shrine — a small stone alcove containing a carved image of Asha (patron of the Ashanite order, the prophet of feeling) surrounded by fresh flowers replaced daily.
The city's most distinctive feature: the Canopy Walk — a network of elevated walkways connecting the treetops above the city center, maintained by the Green Thorn as both a devotional path (walking the Canopy is considered a form of prayer) and a practical transport system (the walks provide a second level of circulation above the crowded streets). The Walk is beautiful — dappled light, birdsong, the green-gold shimmer of sun through leaves — and it is also the best intelligence-gathering platform on the island. Morvayn's agents use the Walk to observe the city from above. The Green Thorn's monks use it to observe Morvayn's agents.
Districts:
The Greensward — The Green Thorn's headquarters. A monastery complex surrounding the island's oldest tree — the Mother Oak, an ancient hardwood whose trunk is over thirty feet in diameter and whose canopy shades an acre. The Mother Oak is Verwhisper's most sacred site. Cutting it would be an act of war. Morvayn has never threatened it. Even he understands certain lines.
The Marketvale — Commercial district. Produce markets, artisan workshops (wood-carving, weaving, herbalism), and the trading posts where island goods are packed for export.
The Pilgrim Quarter — Hostels and chapels serving the small but steady stream of Lovist pilgrims who visit Verwhisper's monasteries.
The Rootwork — The old quarter, built around the Mother Oak's root system. The oldest buildings on the island — some dating to the early Age of Faith — with foundations that incorporate the oak's surface roots, creating structures that are literally anchored to the living tree.

House Verdane — The Timber-Lords
Seat: Verdane Hall, Thornhaven (a manor house whose walls incorporate three living oak trees, their trunks passing through the structure like columns) Sigil: A green leaf on a brown field, veined with gold Words: "The Forest Provides, the Forest Remembers"
The Verdanes are timber merchants who became lords by necessity — someone had to govern the secular side of life, and the Green Thorn monks had neither the inclination nor the institutional structure for it. The Verdanes filled the gap, providing judicial services, military defense, and commercial management while the Green Thorn provided spiritual authority, healthcare, and education. The partnership has lasted three centuries with remarkably little friction, primarily because both sides understand that Verwhisper's prosperity depends on the forest, and the forest doesn't care about political ego.
Lord Aldis Verdane (age 52) — A thoughtful, cautious man who governs Verwhisper with the steady pace of someone who has internalized the forest's tempo. He opposed Morvayn's coup through diplomatic channels — letters of protest, trade restrictions, appeals to the Magos for mediation. None of it worked. He is now the reluctant host of a cold war he never wanted, maintaining Verwhisper's neutrality while Stormglass pushes for military action and Morvayn pushes for recognition. His strategy: wait. Morvayn's position is strong but brittle — sustained by force and revenue, not by legitimacy. Aldis believes that time works against the usurper. He may be right. He may also be rationalizing inaction.
Ilva Verdane (age 25) — Aldis's daughter. A Green Thorn novice who has been training in the order's herbalism tradition and who is, of all the Verdane family, the most politically active — not through conventional channels but through the monastery network. The Green Thorn has chapters on every island. Ilva has been using the order's inter-island communications (carried by the monks who maintain forest-conservation stations on Emberstone and even Shadowtide) to coordinate intelligence-sharing between the anti-Morvayn factions. Her father doesn't know the extent of her activities. The Green Thorn's Prior does.
Prior Oaken (age 65) — Head of the Order of the Green Thorn on Verwhisper. Not a Verdane but as politically significant as any lord. Oaken is the island's spiritual authority — a quiet, deliberate man who has spent forty years in the forest and who has developed, through decades of contemplative practice, a sensitivity to the island's ecological rhythms that other monks consider saintly and that the echo-system codex would describe as genuine echo-perception. Oaken can feel the forest's health in his bones — when a grove is stressed, when a spring is faltering, when the balance of the ecosystem shifts. He has felt something new in the past year: a strengthening. The forest is growing faster than it should. The birdsong is louder. The Mother Oak's canopy has expanded by a measurable amount. Oaken does not know about the Eldra-Veil breach. He knows something is different. He is listening.

VI. SHADOWTIDE — The Unlit Island
The Island
Nobody governs Shadowtide. Several have tried. None have succeeded. The island is a dense tropical jungle — the southernmost, warmest, and wettest of the four — and it has resisted every attempt at centralized authority with the passive resistance of a landscape that eats infrastructure and digests ambition.
The jungle is thick enough that ground-level visibility drops to ten feet within fifty yards of the coast. The canopy is so dense that rainfall reaches the ground as a continuous drip rather than as drops — the forest filters the sky. The fauna is aggressive, diverse, and includes species found nowhere else in the archipelago: the twilight jaguar (a melanistic big cat that hunts at dusk), the crown viper (a canopy-dwelling snake with iridescent scales and a bite that produces vivid hallucinations before killing), and the web-spinner ape (a primate that constructs elaborate structures from vines and leaves, demonstrating a level of tool-use that the Magos Natural World school considers impossible for a non-human primate and that Shadowtide's human residents consider unremarkable — "the apes build. We build. The jungle builds. Everything builds.").
Shadowtide's human population is scattered, semi-nomadic, and organized into loose family groups rather than houses or clans. They fish the coast, forage the forest, and trade with the other islands through a handful of beach-markets where goods are exchanged without formal currency (barter, weighted by the quality of relationships). They do not fight wars. They do not pay taxes. They do not attend to the political affairs of the other islands. They have been offered "civilization" by every regime that has controlled the Bridge, and they have declined every time, not through defiance but through indifference — the jungle provides everything they need, and everything the other islands offer comes with obligations they don't want.
Settlements
There is no capital. There are no cities. There are places where people tend to gather:
Driftwood (~2,000) — The closest thing Shadowtide has to a port. A scatter of huts, lean-tos, and beached boats on the island's northern coast, where traders from the other islands come to exchange metalwork, cloth, and salt for Shadowtide's exports: rare hardwoods, exotic spices, medicinal plants, and the moonpearls — iridescent freshwater pearls found in the island's interior rivers that the Teeth's jewelers prize above any marine pearl.
The Rootmarket (~variable, 500-1,500 depending on season) — An inland trading post at the junction of three game trails, where the island's scattered families meet to exchange goods, arrange marriages, and share news. The Rootmarket operates on a lunar cycle — it opens on the new moon and closes on the full. Between markets, the site is empty. Except it isn't — the web-spinner apes use the Rootmarket's clearing during the off-weeks, and the structures they build (vine-bridges, leaf-shelters, elevated platforms) are sometimes incorporated by the humans when the market reopens. The collaboration is not planned. It simply happens.
The Hermitage (~50) — A Green Thorn conservation station deep in the island's interior. Three monks maintain a botanical survey of Shadowtide's unique flora. They are the only permanent non-native residents on the island. The locals tolerate them because the monks provide medical care and ask nothing in return. The monks' reports to Prior Oaken on Verwhisper include observations that the Prior files separately from the official records: plant growth rates that defy botanical models, animal behaviors that suggest interspecies coordination, and a persistent ambient sensation that the senior monk describes as "the feeling of standing inside a conversation that I cannot hear."

The Free Families
Shadowtide has no houses. It has families — kinship networks that expand, contract, merge, and split over generations without formal structure. Some names recur:
The Duskwalkers — A family of hunters who specialize in the twilight hours when the jungle's most dangerous predators are active. They are feared and respected by the other families because they go where others won't. The current family head, Grandmother Ashani (age ~70) — no one on Shadowtide tracks exact ages — is the island's closest thing to a political leader: when disputes arise that the families can't resolve internally, they bring them to Ashani. Her judgment is not binding. It is always followed.
The Rootweavers — A family of builders who construct the vine-and-wood structures that Shadowtide's residents live in. Their technique — weaving living vines into structural frameworks that continue growing after construction, strengthening over time — produces buildings that are alive in a literal sense. A Rootweaver house doesn't decay. It grows. The older houses are partially absorbed by the jungle, their walls thick with vine, their roofs canopied by trees that sprouted from seeds dropped by birds onto the living structure. The Rootweavers consider this ideal. A house that the jungle accepts is a house that belongs.
The Tidecallers — A family of fishermen on the western coast who claim the ability to "call" tides — to predict not just the timing but the strength and character of each tide. Their predictions are accurate enough that the other families plan their fishing and beach-market schedules around Tidecaller forecasts. The mechanism is weather-reading, tidal observation, and — probably — echo-sensitivity refined over generations of coastal living. The Tidecallers don't explain their methods. They don't need to. The tides come when they say they will.

VII. NATURAL FEATURES
The Great Bridge — Described above. The archipelago's defining feature. Echo-engineered, warm to the touch, indestructible by any method the current world possesses.
Mount Sova — Emberstone's primary volcano. Permanently smoking. Last major eruption: 1189 AF (destroyed the village of Ashfall, killed ~400, redirected a lava flow that created the current harbor configuration at Ashenport). The mountain's geological activity produces the geothermal energy that heats Emberstone's cities and the volcanic deposits that the quarries exploit. Deep within Sova's root system, the Magos vault sits in basalt chambers that have been stable for millennia — but the mountain's seismic profile has been changing in the past decade, producing tremors at frequencies that Ashenport's engineers haven't recorded before.
The Singing Reef — A coral formation between Northwind and Emberstone that produces, during certain tidal conditions, a harmonic resonance audible above and below water. The sound is low, rhythmic, and has been described by sailors as "a choir of drowned voices singing a hymn in a language no one has spoken in a thousand years." The phenomenon is well-documented. The explanation is not — the reef's coral structure has acoustic properties that marine naturalists at the Isle of Knowledge have been studying for decades without conclusive results. The coral itself is unusual: denser, harder, and more structurally complex than any other reef in the archipelago. The Magos suspect it is an echo-artifact — coral that grew in the Age of History's denser echo-field and that retains properties its modern descendants cannot replicate.
The Veil — A fog bank that forms between Verwhisper and Shadowtide with unusual regularity — approximately three days out of every ten, regardless of season or weather conditions. The fog is dense enough to reduce visibility to arm's length and persists for hours. Navigation through the Veil is dangerous; ships that enter it report compass anomalies, time distortions (a crossing that should take two hours takes six, or thirty minutes), and — in a handful of documented cases — visual phenomena: shapes in the fog that look like buildings, ships, or people but that dissolve when approached. The Magos attribute the fog to the temperature differential between Verwhisper's warm, humid microclimate and Shadowtide's cooler waters. The visual phenomena are attributed to pareidolia. The time distortions are attributed to navigational error. The compass anomalies are not attributed to anything because the Magos have no explanation for them.
Shadowtide's residents do not cross the Veil by boat. They wade through the shallows at a specific point where the strait between the islands narrows to a few hundred yards, timing their crossing to a window that the Tidecallers calculate. The crossing takes twenty minutes on foot. The Veil parts around the waders, they say, "like a curtain opening for someone expected." Whether this is physical (the shallow crossing creates a microclimate gap in the fog) or something else is unknown.
The Rootsea — Shadowtide's interior mangrove system. A vast network of interconnected swamp, river, and mangrove channel that extends across most of the island's lowland interior. The waterways are navigable by canoe. The Rootsea is home to the moonpearl-producing freshwater mussels, the web-spinner apes, and — according to the Duskwalkers — something larger. Something that moves through the deep channels at night, producing a wake but no sound. Something that has been there longer than the humans. The Duskwalkers don't hunt it. They leave offerings at certain channel junctions: fish, fruit, moonpearls. The offerings are always gone by morning. The Duskwalkers do not discuss this with outsiders.

VIII. LEGENDS AND MYTHS
The Bridge-Builders — Who built the Great Bridge? No one knows. The oldest legends across all four islands agree on only one thing: the builders were not human. The Northwind version: giants from beneath the sea, who raised the stone from the ocean floor. The Emberstone version: fire-spirits from the volcano's heart, who cooled the stone from liquid flame. The Verwhisper version: the forest itself, extending its roots across the water. The Shadowtide version: the Bridge was always there. The islands grew around it. The water came after. The Bridge is the oldest thing. Even the sea is younger. None of these are correct. All of them are closer to the truth than the Magos' geological surveys.
The Fenn Ghost — House Fenn was exterminated during the Bridge-Throat Massacre — Nion I's soldiers killing every man, woman, and child of the family that had controlled the Bridge before the conquest. The massacre site — the Throat, a narrow section of the Bridge between Emberstone and Verwhisper — is the only part of the original structure that shows visible damage: a dark stain in the basalt that cleaning has never removed. On certain nights — specifically the anniversary of the massacre, which oral tradition places during the autumn equinox — travelers on the Throat report hearing footsteps behind them. They turn. No one is there. The footsteps continue. They walk faster. The footsteps match their pace. They run. The footsteps stop. And then, in the silence, a child laughs. The laugh is not malicious. It is the laugh of a child playing a game — the game of following, of being close enough to touch but never quite touching. The Fenn family had children when they died. The youngest was three. The laugh sounds like a three-year-old.
The Obsidian Oracle — An Emberstone legend. Deep in the quarries, in a chamber that the miners sealed generations ago and that no current map records, there is a wall of natural obsidian — volcanic glass, black and flawless — that functions as a mirror. But the mirror does not show the present. It shows the future. Not clearly — the images are dark, fragmented, shifting — but consistently enough that the miners who discovered it (approximately 1150 AF) were terrified into silence. The chamber was sealed. The location was lost. The legend persists. Sera Pyrmont, exploring the deep tunnels, has found sealed passages that her quarry maps don't account for. She has not opened them. She is considering it.
The Mother Oak's Dream — A Verwhisper legend. The Mother Oak — the ancient tree at Thornhaven's heart — dreams. Not metaphorically. The Green Thorn monks who meditate at its base report, consistently across centuries, the experience of entering the oak's consciousness during deep contemplation. The experience is non-verbal: a vast, slow awareness of root and soil and water and light, a sense of time measured in centuries rather than hours, and — most disturbingly — an awareness of the other trees. The Mother Oak knows every tree on the island. It knows which ones are healthy and which are sick. It knows where the water table is dropping. It knows when the seasons are shifting. And it knows — this is the part that Prior Oaken has not shared publicly — that something is coming. The Oak cannot describe what. It has no language. But the feeling the monks bring back from their meditation has changed in the past year: from the slow, steady contentment of a healthy forest to a quality that Oaken can only describe as anticipation. The forest is waiting for something. The forest knows it's coming. The forest is glad.
The Creature in the Rootsea — Shadowtide's oldest legend and its most carefully guarded secret. In the deepest channel of the Rootsea, where the mangroves are ancient and the water is black and still, something lives. The Duskwalkers have been leaving it offerings since before their genealogies can trace. It has never been seen clearly — only the wake, the ripple of something enormous moving through water that should be too shallow for it. Once a generation, the Duskwalkers' eldest member performs a ritual: they wade into the deep channel alone, at midnight, carrying a moonpearl of exceptional quality. They stand in the water. They wait. Something approaches. They feel it — the displacement of water, a pressure against their legs, a warmth that has no source. They place the moonpearl in the water. It is taken. Not pulled — taken, by something gentle and precise, the way a parent takes a gift from a child. The Duskwalker returns to shore. They do not speak of what they felt. The ritual is called the Giving. It has been performed for as long as anyone can remember. The Creature has never harmed anyone. The Creature has never appeared in daylight. The Creature is, if the echo-system theory is correct, the last living echo-node in the Teeth — a being sustained by the Rootsea's ancient, undisturbed mangrove ecosystem, the final remnant of an age when such things were common. It is the Brinehold Leviathan's cousin, the Badlands Bestia's kin, and the proof that the Thinning was not total — that in the places the world forgot to drain, the old things are still alive, still waiting, still accepting gifts from the only humans wise enough to offer them.

IX. THE WHISPERING WAR — State of Play at 1308 AF
Morvayn controls: The Keystone, Cinderpost, and Thornwatch towers. The toll system. Approximately 500 soldiers. The loyalty of ~40% of Emberstone's quarry-workers. An intelligence network (the Whisper) that has penetrated all three opposing islands. Revenue from tolls that funds everything.
Stormglass controls: Northgate tower. The Teeth's most capable navy. Northwind's fishing economy (damaged by tolls but functional). The best weather intelligence. Old Edda's surveillance log. Kael's unauthorized operations.
Verdane controls: Tideveil tower (with a garrison of mixed loyalty). Verwhisper's agricultural surplus (the archipelago's food supply, a strategic weapon Aldis has not yet deployed). The Green Thorn's inter-island monastery network (communications that Morvayn cannot intercept). Prior Oaken's moral authority. Ilva Verdane's covert coordination.
Pyrmont controls: Emberstone's quarries (the archipelago's primary non-food export). The remainder of the quarry-workers. Sera Pyrmont's resistance network. Knowledge of the deep tunnels that Morvayn's forces cannot enter.
Shadowtide controls: Nothing. Wants nothing. Is watching with the detached interest of a jungle cat observing a dogfight. Grandmother Ashani, when asked her opinion of the Whispering War, said: "The Bridge is stone. Stone endures. Men do not. We will wait for the men to finish." She did not specify which men or which finishing.
The Magos are terrified — not of Morvayn, but of what Morvayn's disruption means for the Emberstone vault. Three years without maintenance. Artifacts that were stable may no longer be. The Bridge-stone fragment that shares is sitting in a sealed chamber whose environmental controls haven't been checked since 1305 AF. Grand Magos Thessaly has authorized Keeper Alenn to attempt access by any means necessary. Alenn is planning an infiltration through the deep quarry tunnels — the same tunnels where Sera Pyrmont's resistance operates. Neither knows about the other. Their collision is inevitable.

The Bridge hums in the dark. The islands listen. The war whispers. The forest waits. And in the Rootsea's deepest channel, something ancient accepts its offering and returns to the silence from which it came, carrying a moonpearl that glows faintly in the black water, the only light in a darkness that has lasted longer than human memory and that is, for the first time in centuries, beginning to change.


THE HEARTLANDS — Complete Regional Chronicle
Silver, River, and Old Stone
Total Documented History: Approximately 3,000 years of continuous political civilization, stretching from the pre-imperial Aethelian republics through the Nionic conquest and into the current Age of Faith. The ruins are older. The grudges are older still.
Defining Feature: The Heartlands are the continent's political, agricultural, and economic core — the grain-basket that feeds half of Mundus and the web of river trade that moves the other half's goods. They are also the continent's oldest argument. No region has produced more wars, more treaties, more betrayals, more constitutions, or more sophisticated mechanisms for committing violence while maintaining the appearance of civility. The Heartlands invented the ducal system, the Argenlord title, the elective monarchy, the guild table, and the art of poisoning an entire coronation feast without leaving a single witness alive to identify the cup that carried the dose.
Political System: The Argenlord — elected every three years by the heads of the major houses, each casting one vote. Theoretically a ceremonial figurehead with emergency powers in war or famine. In practice, the emergency powers have been invoked so often that the office has accumulated genuine authority. The title has been dominated by House Silverblood (~45 terms) and House Silverring (~40 terms), with House Argenhold (~20), House Beaumont (~15), and various minor houses splitting the remainder across 405 years. Currently held by Argenlord Theron Silverblood.

I. THE LAND
Geography
The Heartlands are big. Rolling plains of wheat and barley stretching to horizons that pull away from a rider as they gallop, interrupted by river valleys so fertile that the banks stay green even in winter, punctuated by ancient stone cities that sit at every major confluence like fat spiders in the centers of their webs. The Silver Mountains wall the southern edge, snow-capped and blue in the distance. The northern border bleeds into scrubby, drier grassland that transitions toward the Horns corridor and the ancient forests of Beaumont. The light is different here than anywhere else on the continent — wide, clear, and somehow deep, as if the sky has more layers than it does on the coast. Heartlanders talk about their sky the way Sangreans talk about their wine.
The rivers are the Heartlands' arteries. The Argen — the great central waterway, navigable for most of its length, the economic foundation of House Argenhold's wealth — cuts the region roughly in half. The Vorn — northern tributary, running through Silverblood territory, its banks lined with the granaries and mill-towns that turn plains wheat into the flour that feeds the continent. The Silvrenne — mountain-fed, cold, cutting through Silverring's mining country, its current strong enough to power the forge-bellows and stamp-mills that process the mountain's ore. Dozens of smaller waterways connect the plains towns to the river network in a capillary system so dense that no settlement of any size is more than a day's walk from navigable water.
Everything moves by barge. The barges are flat-bottomed, shallow-drafted, poled and sail-rigged, painted in house colors and stacked with grain, ore, wool, and gossip. The Bargemen's Guild is one of the most powerful organizations in the region — they carry cargo, but they also carry information, and a bargeman who has been up and down the Argen three times in a season knows more about the duchy's politics than most of the dukes.
The central plains — the Silver Flats — are treeless grassland, golden in summer, frost-white in winter, and the most fiercely contested farmland on the continent. Whoever controls the Flats feeds the Heartlands. Whoever feeds the Heartlands holds the Argenlord vote. This is not a metaphor. It is the foundational equation of Heartlander politics, and every house in the region has built its strategy around either controlling that grain or ensuring that nobody else does.
The southeastern frontier — Argen's End — dissolves into desert where the Heartlands meet the Red Coast's wasteland. It is a land of dust, rock, and hard men, where the edicts of the Argenlord mean little and the only authority is the sword. The eastern hills of Corvallis crumple into rocky crags that guard the passes to Rosland and the Frozen South — ambush country, rebellion country, the place where the continent's center bleeds into its wild edges. The western passes climb steeply into alpine territory, where the fortress-city of Grintall guards the only reliable route to the sea beyond.
Climate
Temperate, variable, and politically significant. The central plains experience hot, dry summers and cold, wet winters — a Mediterranean rhythm pushed slightly colder by the Silver Mountains' influence. The growing season is long enough for two harvests in good years, which makes the Heartlands the continent's breadbasket and makes bad harvest years political crises of the first order.
Near the Sangrean border, the climate warms into something subtropical — warm ten months of the year, humid, the kind of air that makes Heartlander wool-wearers strip to their linen and curse their tailor's ambition. Near the Silver Mountains, winter arrives early and stays late, with mountain passes closing under snow from late autumn through early spring. The western passes are worse — House Lockmere's territory is effectively inaccessible for four months of the year, which is partly why the Lockmeres have maintained their independence for so long. You cannot conquer a fortress you cannot reach.

II. THE PEOPLE
Physical Description
Heartlanders are varied — the region is too large and too old for any single ethnic profile. Northern Heartlanders tend toward lighter complexions, sandy or brown hair, and the angular bone structure that suggests pre-imperial Aethelian ancestry. Southern Heartlanders are darker, stockier, and show the mixed heritage of centuries of contact with Sangrea and the mountain peoples. What unites them is temperament: Heartlanders are formal, careful, and obsessed with precedent. They speak slowly and mean every word. A Heartlander's promise is either iron or nothing — the culture has no tolerance for casual oaths.
The eastern hill-folk of Corvallis are leaner, harder, with the weathered look of people who live on land that fights back. The mountain people of Silvermont and the western passes are pale, compact, built for altitude — broad chests, short legs, the kind of lung capacity that makes them formidable at high elevation and slightly ridiculous when they try to sprint on flat ground.
Clothing & Status
Clothing reflects status with surgical precision. The ducal houses wear silver — not just as ornament but as structural element: silver thread woven into wool and linen, silver clasps and buttons, silver belt-buckles engraved with house sigils. The wealthier the house, the more silver you see. A Silverblood lord at court glitters like a fish; a minor house retainer might manage a single silver pin on their cloak. The working class wears undyed wool in winter and linen in summer, with leather boots and wide-brimmed hats to keep off the plains sun.
The one universal garment across all classes is the surcoat — a sleeveless, open-fronted overgarment that displays the wearer's house colors or guild insignia. In the Heartlands, you are always wearing your allegiance. Removing your surcoat in public is either a deeply private act (you are off-duty, you are in mourning, you are between masters) or a deeply political one (you are changing sides). A man walking through Vornhold without a surcoat draws more attention than a man walking through Vornhold naked.
Architecture
River architecture. The Heartlands' cities are built at confluences, on riverbanks, around bridges — and the buildings reflect this: stone foundations rising from the waterline, wooden upper stories cantilevered over the current, and bridges that are as much market-street as crossing-point. The signature structure is the riverhall — a long, narrow building oriented perpendicular to the river, with a dock at one end and a street entrance at the other, serving as both warehouse and meeting hall. Riverhalls are the Heartlands' civic centers: disputes are arbitrated there, elections held there, feasts hosted there. The Argenhold Riverhall — the ducal seat — is the largest on the continent, with a vaulted stone ceiling and a dock large enough to berth six barges abreast.
The older architecture — pre-imperial Aethelian ruins, imperial fortifications, early Age of Faith churches — is heavy, blocky, and built to last. The newer construction is lighter, more decorated, influenced by two centuries of peace and trade: arched windows, carved lintels, the occasional Sangrean-style azulejo panel imported by a lord trying to seem cosmopolitan. The contrast between old stone and new ornament gives Heartlander cities a layered quality — the bones of empire visible beneath the skin of post-imperial prosperity.
The ancient standing stones that line every major road are the Heartlands' most distinctive landscape feature — grey, weathered, carved with markers that predate the empire and whose original meaning has been forgotten. They serve as mile-markers, property boundaries, and the occasional gallows. The Brothers of the Open Road maintain them. Travelers touch them for luck. Children dare each other to sleep beside them at night.
Food
The Heartlands eat their geography. The plains produce grain — wheat, barley, oats — and the bread culture is accordingly deep. Every town bakes differently: Vornhold's round, dark, sour loaves; Argenhold's flat river-cakes cooked on heated stones; Silvermont's braided white bread, sweet and rich with butter. Meat is beef and mutton from the plains herds, pork from the river-valley farms, and freshwater fish — pike, perch, and the enormous Argen catfish that river towns smoke over apple wood and trade downstream. Near the Sangrean border, the cuisine picks up heat and color: chili-rubbed beef, tomato-based stews, tropical fruit preserves. Near the Silver Mountains, it becomes sparser and heartier: root vegetables, dried sausage, hard cheese, and the fortified wine that miners drink to keep warm underground.
The Heartlands' signature culinary institution is the guild table — a communal meal hosted by the local guild chapter, open to any guild member and their family, featuring whatever the members contributed. The guild table is simultaneously a social event, a business meeting, and a political caucus. Deals are made over bread and salt. Alliances are forged over shared wine. Grudges are nursed over the quality of someone else's sausage. The saying goes: "You can learn more at a guild table than at a ducal court, and the food is better."
Music
Formal. The dominant form is the ballad — a narrative song performed by a solo singer with a fiddle or small harp, recounting historical events, dynastic achievements, or cautionary tales of betrayal and downfall. Ballads are long (some run over an hour), structured (verse-chorus-verse, with a bridge called "the turn" that introduces a moral or twist), and treated with the seriousness of legal documents. A ballad about a house's founding is considered a legitimate source of historical authority — courts have ruled on inheritance disputes based on which version of a ballad the local tradition preserved.
The counter-tradition is the river-song — informal, bawdy, sung by bargemen on the water and by drinkers in the riverside taverns. River-songs are topical (new verses are added constantly to comment on current events), irreverent (no duke, no bishop, no guild-master is safe from mockery), and enormously popular with the common people, who use them as a safe channel for political commentary that would get them hanged if spoken in prose. The Bargemen's Guild maintains an unofficial archive of river-songs that is, by some estimates, the most comprehensive record of popular opinion in the Heartlands.
Religion
The Heartlands are the most devoutly Lovist region on the continent after the Holy See itself. The great cathedrals of Vornhold, Argenhold, and Silvermont are among the finest architectural achievements of the Age of Faith, their stone vaulting paid for by ducal donations and their altars served by priests from all three major orders. The Ayanite presence is strongest — the Heartlands' formal, precedent-obsessed culture aligns naturally with the order of Truth and Law, and Ayanite scholars staff the region's courts, schools, and scribal offices.
The Holy See — the seat of the Council of the Holy Three, the supreme authority of the Lovist faith — is located within the Heartlands, in the cathedral-city of Faithir. This gives the region an outsized influence on continental religious politics and makes the Council of Three an unavoidable player in Heartlander power struggles. Both Silverblood and Silverring court the Council's endorsement, sending lavish donations and competing to appear as the faith's truest defender. The Council has so far refused to take sides, but the religious orders are not unanimous — some favor the traditionalist piety of Silverblood, others the "enlightened" patronage of Silverring. Should the Council be forced to choose, their declaration could turn the dynastic struggle into a holy war.

III. THE POLITICAL SYSTEM
The Argenlord
The Argenlord is the Heartlands' answer to the question: how do you unite a region too large for any single house to dominate, too proud for any house to submit, and too rich for anyone to leave alone?
The answer, devised by Daven Argenhold "the Peacemaker" in 919 AF after the devastating War of Five Dukes, is elegant and deliberately fragile. The Argenlord is elected every three years by the heads of the major houses — each house of renown gets one vote, cast by the head of the house. The Argenlord serves as a ceremonial leader with specific emergency powers: in times of war or famine, the Argenlord can bypass individual duchies' authority, requisition troops, commandeer grain stores, and issue binding decrees. In peacetime, the Argenlord arbitrates disputes, hosts the triennial moot, maintains the Argen road network, and represents the Heartlands to the other regions.
The system was designed to prevent tyranny. It has instead produced a different pathology: a permanent cold war between the houses that can afford to buy the title and a permanent resentment from the houses that cannot. The election itself has become the continent's most elaborate exercise in political theater — months of negotiation, bribery, threat, and counter-threat, conducted through intermediaries, sealed with oaths that everyone knows will be broken as soon as the political winds shift, and resolved in a single day of voting that has been predetermined by the preceding months of backroom deals.
The Silver Covenant and Its Collapse
For roughly 200 years (c. 960–1250 AF), the Heartlands operated under the Silver Covenant — a formal partnership between House Silverblood and House Silverring that divided the region into spheres of influence. Silverblood controlled the plains and agriculture. Silverring controlled the mountains and mining. They alternated the Argenlord title between them by agreement, with occasional compromise elections of candidates from neutral houses (Beaumont, Belorn) when direct alternation was politically inconvenient.
The Covenant was the foundation of Heartlands stability, and its collapse — the Argent Schism — is the defining political crisis of the present day.
The Schism did not begin with a single event. It accumulated, like silt in a river, until the channel was choked and the water found new paths. Silverblood expanded its agricultural holdings into territory that Silverring considered part of its sphere. Silverring's Vaultkeepers began extending loans to Silverblood-aligned houses at rates that amounted to economic warfare. Trade disputes over river tariffs became shouting matches at moot. The compromise elections stopped — each house demanded the title for itself, every time, and the minor houses were forced to choose sides rather than mediate.
By 1250 AF, the Covenant was dead in everything but name. By 1258 AF, the Raven's Fall — Silverring's puppet house, the Corbeaus, seizing Corvallis from the Silverblood-aligned Griffinwings — turned the cold war hot. By 1307 AF, the Feast of Poison obliterated the leadership of the neutral house that had held the region together for four centuries. And by 1308 AF, when the story begins, the Heartlands are a powder keg soaked in river-water and silver, waiting for a spark.
Who Gets a Vote
The Argenlord election is open to every "house of renown" — a deliberately vague category that has been argued about for 400 years. The original signatories of the Treaty of Five Bridges (Silverblood, Silverring, Beaumont, Belorn, Argenhold) each hold a vote by right. Houses elevated since then — Seeder, Lockmere, Corbeau, Sandsword, and others — hold votes granted by precedent, by purchase, or by the simple fact that they showed up at moot with enough armed men that denying them a seat was more trouble than it was worth.
At 1308 AF, approximately twelve houses hold recognized votes, though the exact number is disputed (House Belorn's vote is contested — the house still exists but has been so diminished that Silverblood argues it no longer qualifies as a "house of renown"). The voting houses, in approximate order of power:
House Silverblood — holds the title
House Silverring — the primary challenger
House Argenhold — the traditional neutral (currently vacant/contested)
House Beaumont — the forest princes, officially neutral
House Corbeau — Silverring's puppet in Corvallis
House Lockmere — the pass-keepers, fiercely independent
House Seeder — Silverblood's agricultural vassals
House Sandsword — the desert frontier wardens
House Valenti — river merchants, rising fast, Silverring-aligned
House Riverborne — river fleet, secretly Silverblood-aligned
House Belorn — diminished, vote contested
Various minor houses whose votes shift with the political winds

IV. THE PROVINCES
THE SILVER PLAINS — The Vast Central Grain Plains
Ruling Dynasty: House Silverblood — Claims ancient pre-imperial bloodline Key Vassal: House Seeder — Harvest masters and granary lords Major City: Vornhold — The continental trade hub Key Guild: The Marketborn Council — Merchant princes Population (estimated): 400,000–500,000
The Silver Plains are the vast, beating heart of the continent, a seemingly endless expanse of grain that ripples like a golden sea under a wide, open sky. The roads are ancient, marked by grey standing stones that have witnessed millennia of caravans and marching armies. The air is thick with the sweet, dusty scent of cut wheat and the rich smell of rain on fertile soil.
House Silverblood controls the plains and, through the grain, controls the Heartlands. Their claim to power is double-rooted: an ancient lineage that traces (they say) to pre-imperial Aethelian chieftains, and the brutal practical reality that their Vornhold silos contain enough grain to feed or starve half the continent. The family's founding legend says that Argen the Pale, a pre-imperial chieftain, made a pact with the land itself, shedding his own silver-touched blood into the soil to guarantee eternal fertility. More cynical histories claim he simply slaughtered his rivals and buried their bodies in his fields to serve as fertilizer. Both versions are probably partially true.
The current head is Argenlord Theron Silverblood (age 59), a man consumed by the power he seized. He is a master of political theater, projecting an image of pious authority while privately indulging in paranoia and excess. He suffers from a wasting sickness that leaves him perpetually weak and irritable, and he is obsessed with his legacy, terrified that the Schism he helped create will be his only epitaph. His eldest son Ser Kaelen Silverblood (34) is a cruel, arrogant warrior whose solution to any problem is a public execution. His daughter Lyra Silverblood (29) was married off to the head of House Seeder but is far more intelligent and ruthless than her brother — she manipulates her husband and uses Seeder resources to build her own power base. His acknowledged bastard Aric Silverblood (22) serves as captain of the household guard, fiercely loyal but tormented by his low birth. And his younger brother Maester Orin (65), who renounced his name to join the Magos, serves as the family's advisor — a broken man, haunted by ghosts and dependent on wine.
House Seeder is the Silverblood's essential ally — the family that actually runs the agricultural machinery. Founded by Old Man Hemlock, a common farmer whose crop rotation innovations saved the Silver Plains during the post-imperial famines, the Seeders now control the largest granary network on the continent. The current lord, Borin Seeder (32), is simple, brutish, and utterly besotted with his wife Lyra Silverblood — which is precisely the arrangement Lyra engineered.
Vornhold itself is the continent's largest inland city — a trade hub where goods from every region converge, governed by the powerful Marketborn Council, a consortium of merchant princes who value Silverblood stability above all else and fund the Argenlord's administration in exchange for favorable tariffs.
The plains are outwardly peaceful. The harvests have been good. But the taxes are high, and the Silverblood Argenlord's decrees carry the sharp edge of a tyrant, not a first among equals. Every farmer sharpening a scythe for the harvest is also whetting a blade for what comes next.

SILVERMONT — The Silver Mountain Borderlands
Ruling Dynasty: House Silverring — Mining dynasty of the southern mountains Key Vassals: House Argensword (silver refiners), House Greyrock (gem cutters) Major City: Silvermont — The shining mountain city Key Guild: The Vaultkeepers of Silvermont — Banking guild Population (estimated): 250,000–300,000
A stark contrast to the plains. Silvermont is a jagged frontier of snow-capped peaks and deep, shadow-filled valleys. The air is thin and crisp, smelling of pine and cold stone. The constant sound is the ring of hammers on steel from the mines and forges that cling to the mountainsides. The shining city of Silvermont is a testament to the wealth torn from these mountains — its towers plated in polished silver that reflects the harsh mountain sun.
House Silverring is the Heartlands' second power and its first grievance. Once sworn partners of House Silverblood in the Silver Covenant, they are now their most bitter rivals. The Argent Schism shattered their alliance, and Silverring views the current Argenlord as a usurper. Their immense wealth — managed by the Vaultkeepers of Silvermont, the continent's first formal banking guild (deposit accounts, letters of credit, commercial loans) — allows them to fund a vast network of alliances. Silverring's strategy is economic strangulation: they are forging what is known as the Iron Pact with disaffected houses, using their treasury to offer loans and support to any who would defy the Silverblood Argenlord. While the Plains control the food, Silvermont controls the money.
The current Silverring leadership includes Duchess Anya Silverring, a woman of formidable intelligence who communicates directly with her puppet lords and proxy agents across the Heartlands. The Vaultkeepers answer to her.
House Argensword — the silver refiners — and House Greyrock — the gem cutters — transform the raw mountain bounty into the treasures that buy loyalty and fund wars.

ARGENIA — The River Valley Between the Plains and the Mountains
Ruling Dynasty: House Argenhold — Founders of the river port Rival Dynasty: House Valenti — River merchant upstarts Loyal Vassals: House Hurth — Administrators and cupbearers Major City: Argenhold — The great river port Key Guild: The Bargemen — River transport guild Population (estimated): 300,000–350,000
Argenia is the great river valley, the fertile land that serves as the main artery of trade between the plains and the mountains. The slow, wide river dominates the landscape, its banks lined with bustling ports, prosperous towns, and the villas of wealthy merchants. The great river port of Argenhold is the nexus — a chaotic, vibrant city where fortunes are made and lost on the tides.
House Argenhold is the Heartlands' traditional neutral power — the dynasty founded by Daven the Peacemaker, whose entire identity has been built on mediation, bridge-building, and the refusal to take sides. For 400 years, the Argenholds held the region together by holding themselves apart from the Silverblood-Silverring rivalry. Their wealth came from trade, not land or mines, which made them dependent on both sides and beholden to neither.
That tradition died at the Feast of Poison (1307 AF). Duke Harros Argenhold — aging, weakened by drink — hosted the coronation feast for his son Darric at the castle of Argenhold. Every major figure in Argenian politics attended. By midnight, every guest was dead.
The victims: Darric Argenhold (the heir), Lady Marthys Argenhold (née Hurth, Kaeo's stepmother), Duke Harros himself, Lord Rynald Hurth, Ser Tovan Valenti, Lady Aevra Bargemont (patroness of the Bargemen's Guild), Lord Pelrin Redmarsh, Father Jorn of the Ayanite Concord, plus dozens of lesser nobles and servants. The massacre wiped out nearly every power-broker who might have balanced Kaeo's return.
The poisoner is unknown. Suspects: House Silverblood (seizing the opportunity to install a regency), Jous Lorethian's agents (destabilizing the Heartlands ahead of invasion), Lady Marthys's own enemies (she had many), and House Valenti (whose leader Damon was conspicuously absent from the feast).
House Silverblood moved immediately. Lord Athelric Silverblood declared a regency over Argenia "until a proper heir can be installed." A bird was sent to Kaeo in Xaria.
Duke Kaeo Argenhold (28) — the last surviving Argenhold — has returned after eleven years of exile in Xaria. He left at seventeen under murky circumstances (a falling-out with his stepmother, restlessness, political exile — probably all three). He spent a decade inside the Ix'Atani colonial apparatus and has returned with Xarian-trained servants, gifts from the Vizier, and the reputation of a man nobody truly knows. He arrives in 1308 AF to find Silverbloods sitting in his hall, the Bargemen's Guild fractured, the Valentis circling, the Church suspicious, and every faction in Argenia with a plan, a test, or a knife.
House Valenti is the threat from within. Lord Damon Valenti (40) — a charismatic, utterly ruthless merchant prince descended from a common bargeman who smuggled and pirated his way to a fortune — has been systematically eroding Argenhold authority for years, peeling away allies with bribery and blackmail. His wife Oliva (38), a former courtesan, runs the family's spy network. His son Ser Lucan (22) is a skilled swordsman and cruel bully. His daughter Lelia (19) is being groomed for marriage into the Silverring family. The Valentis are secretly funded by Silverring and represent the merchant-class ambition that the old nobility fears most: the possibility that money can simply buy the aristocracy out from under itself.
House Hurth — the Argenhold family's hereditary stewards and cupbearers — is represented by the aging Lord Gregor Hurth (70), a man of unshakeable integrity who has served three generations of Argenhold dukes and is deeply worried by his house's decline. His son Ser Jon Hurth (40) is more pragmatic and less loyal — he believes House Argenhold is doomed and is secretly preparing to offer his family's services to whoever wins the coming conflict.
The Bargemen's Guild — fractured since Lady Aevra Bargemont's death at the Feast — is split between her nephew Rhodin Bargemont (pro-Silverblood, wants stability) and Cella Bargemont (anti-Silverblood, open to Kaeo). Whoever wins the Bargemen controls the river, and whoever controls the river controls the Heartlands' jugular.

BEAUMONT — The Ancient Northwestern Forests
Ruling Dynasty: House Beaumont — Forest princes with ties to Sangrea and the Horns Key Vassals: House Redheart (border wardens toward Sangrea), House Hornborne (forest wardens toward the Horns) Major City: Beaumont — The forest capital Key Guild: The Crossroad Brotherhood — Carpenters, guides, and road-experts Population (estimated): 150,000–200,000
The ancient forests of Beaumont are a world apart — a sprawling, dappled realm of towering trees and quiet, moss-covered paths. The capital is less a city and more a collection of grand halls and timber keeps woven seamlessly into the woods. The people are woodsmen and carpenters, guides and wardens, their lives intertwined with forests that border the lands of Sangrea and the Horns.
House Beaumont is caught in the eye of the storm. Their loyalties are torn, their position perilous. As wardens of the northwestern frontier, their alliances are crucial to the security of the Heartlands. Both Silverblood and Silverring court their favor — control of Beaumont's forests means control of a vital strategic flank and a near-endless supply of timber for fleets and siege engines.
Lord Alaric Beaumont walks a razor's edge, offering platitudes to both sides while secretly trying to gauge which will prevail. His vassals are staunch traditionalists: Lord Corvin Redheart (60) — a grim, pious old warrior who has held the Sangrean border for decades and despises his liege lord's weakness — and Lord Borin Hornborne (48) — a massive, hirsute man more comfortable in the woods than in any hall, whose wife Gwen is rumored to be a witch and whose dozen wild children serve as the forest's scouts and hunters.
The Crossroad Brotherhood holds the true key to Beaumont — their knowledge of the forest's secret paths and hidden ways makes them indispensable. Whichever way the Brotherhood begins to guide supplies and messengers in greater numbers will signal where the Forest Princes have placed their bet.

CORVALLIS — The Eastern Hill Country
Ruling Dynasty (current): House Corbeau — Merchant-turned-lords, Silverring puppets Ruling Dynasty (deposed): House Griffinwing — Ancient dynasty, now rebels Major City: Griffinkeep — The garrison city guarding the passes to Rosland Key Guild: The Birdcallers — Signal masters loyal to Corbeau Population (estimated): 120,000–150,000
Corvallis is a fresh wound. A land of rolling hills and sharp, rocky crags, a buffer territory guarding the eastern passes to Rosland and the Frozen South. The wind carries the shrill calls of trained birds across the valleys — the communication network of the Birdcallers, whose loyalty House Corbeau purchased along with their services.
For centuries, this was Griffinwing territory — an ancient dynasty tracing pre-imperial roots, proud as their heraldic creature. But House Griffinwing grew stagnant. Resources depleted. No male heir. Their lord, Caelan Griffinwing, was vulnerable. In 1258 AF, House Corbeau — a merchant family funded and armed by House Silverring — launched a swift military takeover. The assault on Griffinkeep lasted three days. Lord Caelan was captured and exiled. Most of his household was killed or scattered. This was the Raven's Fall — the first open act of aggression in the Argent Schism.
The current Corbeau lord, Malakai Corbeau (42), is haunted by his father's crimes, dependent on milk-of-the-poppy to sleep, and terrified of the Griffinwing loyalists who plague his lands. His wife Lady Ava Corbeau (19) — a distant Silverring cousin married to seal the pact — is the true power behind the throne, cold and ambitious. His heir Joric (18) is sadistic. His bastard half-brother Ser Rolland Flowers (25) is the only person he trusts.
The deposed Lord Arion Griffinwing (22) — the last of his line, a charismatic and vengeful rebel leader — wages an insurgency from the eastern hills with his aunt Lady Elara Griffinwing (50), who escaped the massacre and serves as the rebellion's heart. The insurgency is active, violent, and funded by Silverblood gold. Corvallis is the Heartlands' proxy war — every raid on a Corbeau caravan is another blow in the larger struggle.
Critically, Corvallis controls the passes to both Rosland and the Deadwood Valley — the route through which southern gold has been flowing to House Corbeau's trading posts. Ser Edric Corbeau (Malakai's uncle) was the knight who met Sinna of the South and brokered the gold trade. The southern gold has enriched House Corbeau enormously, funding the infrastructure that won them grudging local acceptance even as the old nobility views them as usurpers.

THE WESTERN HEARTLANDS — The Mountain Pass Province
Nominal Ruler: House Silverblood Actual Ruler: House Lockmere — Keepers of the western passes Major City: Grintall — The fortress city in the pass Key Guild: The Alphorn Mining Clique — Mountain messengers Population (estimated): 50,000–80,000
The Western Heartlands are a formidable barrier of jagged mountains, a land of high, windswept passes and deep, shadowed valleys. The fortress city of Grintall clings to the mountainside, a grey stone sentinel guarding the only reliable passage to the west. The dominant sound is the lonely, echoing call of the alphorns used by the mountain messengers — coded calls that echo across the peaks, reporting every traveler and every approaching threat.
House Lockmere is the Heartlands' most stubbornly independent minor power. Founded by a Nionian legionary who was tasked with guarding the western pass and simply closed the gates when the empire fell, the Lockmeres have maintained their position through unyielding military discipline and the geographic reality that Grintall is essentially impregnable. Lord Torvin Lockmere (55) is as silent and unyielding as the mountains he guards — a stoic isolationist whose only law is the security of the pass.
Silverblood relies on Lockmere loyalty to protect its western flank. But the Lockmeres are fiercely independent, their loyalty sworn not to any Argenlord but to the pass itself. Silverring has been sending envoys and rich gifts, hoping to persuade the Keepers that their interests are better served by a new Argenlord. Should Lockmere bar the pass to Silverblood forces, the Argenlord's kingdom would be cut in half.

RIVERBEND — The Great River's Curve
Nominal Ruler: House Silverring Key Rivals: House Riverborne, House Waterborn, House Sturgeonhelm Major City: Hardstream Port — The crescent harbor city Population (estimated): 25,000–40,000
A province defined by the great river's sweeping curve, a fertile crescent where the water is wide, deep, and slow. Hardstream Port is the heart — a bustling hub of riverine trade. This is a land of ancient river nobility where power is measured by the size of one's fleet and the strength of one's grip on commerce.
This province is a hornet's nest. Officially ruled by House Silverring, their authority is fiercely contested by a web of ancient river houses. House Riverborne commands a formidable fleet and has deep-rooted claims. House Waterborn rules Hardstream Port itself, allied with Riverborne. House Sturgeonhelm — the fishing fleet owners — are a pragmatic bloc whose loyalty shifts to whoever can guarantee the best prices.
The wrinkle: House Riverborne is secretly funded by Silverblood to act as their agents on the river, smuggling weapons and spies while maintaining the public facade of a simple shipping magnate. Lord Arryk Riverborne (39) plays this double game with cunning and nerve. Riverbend is where the Argent Schism's cold war is fought on the water — every barge that sinks, every cargo that goes missing, every customs officer who looks the other way is a move in the larger game.

ARGEN'S END — The Southeastern Desert Frontier
Nominal Ruler: House Silverblood Actual Ruler: House Sandsword — Desert march wardens Major City: Ashgate — The last city before the desert Key Force: Hashreds Mercenary Company Population (estimated): 18,000–25,000
The harsh, sun-scorched southeastern frontier, where the fertile lands give way to an endless desert. Ashgate is the last bastion — a walled city of hardened soldiers, desperate refugees, and opportunistic mercenaries. The Silverblood Argenlord's authority is a fiction here. The true power is Lord Kaelen Sandsword (48), a grim, sun-burnt warrior who was born in the saddle and rules the frontier as his personal fiefdom. His daughter Zara (20) leads the desert patrols and is more respected by the soldiers than her cowardly brother Roric (21). His sister Asha (40), captured by desert tribes as a young woman and held for a decade before escaping, lives as a recluse in the highest tower, said to possess "sand-sight" — the ability to see visions in shifting dunes.
This is the frontier where the Giant's third ship landed. Venania Sarko, a hunter's daughter from the Sandsword holding near Ashgate, was the first human to spot the Giants — a giantess named Sëdhra of the Velthari, an elder root-listener who washed ashore alone and spent her first days pressing her ear to the ground, desperately searching for the underground root-network that had been the foundation of her entire sensory world. The Heartlands' encounter with the Giants has begun here, in the desert, witnessed by a girl whose father works for a house that answers to no one.

THE HOLY SEE — Faithir and Its Environs
Ruling Authority: The Council of the Holy Three Key Orders: Ayanite, Ashanite, Alonite — and their hundreds of sub-orders Major City: Faithir — The Great Cathedral Population (estimated): 100,000–120,000 (including religious communities)
The seat of the Lovist faith sits within the Heartlands' borders, a patchwork of territories controlled by various devout religious orders, each with its own traditions and allegiances. The Council of Three's primary goal is maintaining the unity of the faith and preventing the secular conflicts from spilling into the divine realm.
The Argent Schism has placed the Council in an impossible position. Both Silverblood and Silverring claim to be the true defenders of the faith and send lavish donations, seeking the Council's endorsement. The Council has refused to take sides, but the religious orders are fractured — some favor Silverblood's traditionalist piety, others Silverring's "enlightened" patronage. Should the Council be forced to choose, their declaration could turn the dynastic struggle into a full-blown holy war.
The murder of Father Jorn of the Ayanite Concord at the Feast of Poison has outraged the Council. They may dispatch inquisitors to investigate — and those inquisitors will inevitably encounter Kaeo's Xarian servants, his foreign manners, and the uncomfortable question of whether a man who spent eleven years inside a pagan empire can be trusted to rule a Lovist duchy.

V. COMPLETE HISTORY
Pre-Imperial Period
The Heartlands' political traditions predate the empire by centuries. The Aethelian republics — informal gatherings of thinkers who debated in public plazas — produced the first systematic investigations of natural phenomena, ethical theory, and political science on the continent. Their work survives only in fragments, but the fragments are extraordinary: a treatise on celestial mechanics, an ethical framework arguing that justice is a social contract requiring constant renegotiation, a political analysis of tyranny that reads, twelve centuries later, as a precise diagnosis of the disease that would kill the republics themselves.
The Heartlands built levee systems that tamed their rivers for irrigation and transport. They developed the guild system that still underpins the region's economy. And they produced the bread culture, the river-song tradition, and the ballad form that define Heartlander identity to this day.
The Shattering (903–950 AF)
The most chaotic transition of any region. No single house could dominate the plains after the empire's fall.
The Grain Riots (904–908 AF) established the basic power dynamics: House Silverblood hoarded grain and sold at extortionate prices. House Silverring, less affected by crop failures in the mountains, sent grain caravans south to buy loyalty from starving plains towns. This was the origin of the rivalry — charity as conquest, generosity as investment.
The War of Five Dukes (912–919 AF) — Silverblood, Silverring, Beaumont, Belorn, and Argenhold each declaring sovereignty — was inconclusive. No house could conquer the others. The fighting destroyed bridges, burned granaries, killed 40,000 people, and proved the fundamental theorem of Heartlander politics: the region is too big to unite by force and too interconnected to govern by isolation.
Daven Argenhold brokered the Treaty of Five Bridges (919 AF) and established the Argenlord system. He was elected first Argenlord unanimously. The ducal titles were adopted. House Seeder was elevated.
The Age of Orders (950–1050 AF)
The Argenlord system stabilized. The Silver Covenant (c. 960 AF) divided the Heartlands between Silverblood and Silverring and established alternation of the Argenlord title. House Lockmere consolidated the western passes. Stonebridge became a market town and pilgrimage site.
The Century of Blood (1050–1150 AF)
The Blight of 1087 — grain fungus devastating the Silver Plains for three consecutive harvests — tested the Covenant. The Argenlord (Silverblood) invoked emergency powers and commandeered Silverring grain stores. Silverring complied but resented it — the first visible crack. House Belorn declined through poor management and incompetent heirs.
The Golden Century (1150–1250 AF)
Peak of the Silver Covenant. Cooperation, prosperity, the ducal courts as centers of art. The Vaultkeepers established the continent's first banking system. The city of Argenhold became the premier river port. The Bargemen's Guild became a powerhouse.
The Long Peace and Its Cracks (1250–1308 AF)
The Argent Schism. The Raven's Fall (1258 AF) — Corbeau seizing Corvallis from Griffinwing, funded by Silverring. The Wildwoman's Bargain (1270 AF) — Sinna and Ser Edric Corbeau opening the southern gold trade. The Argenhold Exile (1290 AF) — Kaeo departing for Xaria. The Feast of Poison (1307 AF) — the massacre that destroyed Argenhold's leadership. The Giants' Arrival (1308 AF) — Sëdhra washing ashore near Ashgate.

VI. CURRENT STATE OF AFFAIRS — 1308 AF
The Nest of Knives
When Kaeo Argenhold rides through the gates of the city his family built, he will find:
Silverbloods sitting in his hall. Lord Athelric Silverblood holds the castle under a regency declared the moment the feast victims' bodies cooled. His staff — Dame Rehana Silverblood (logistics), Ser Darion Krell (castle guard), Master Huld Verren (chamberlain), Sister-Justiciar Ivelle Coran (Ayanite examiner), and the physician Edrik Pall (who is quietly investigating the poison) — have turned Argenhold into a Silverblood administrative center in all but name. The regency is polite occupation. Athelric will offer Kaeo a joint-rule charter that leaves the real levers — river tariffs, road security, military levies — in Silverblood hands for three years.
Guilds and houses fractured. The Bargemen's Guild is split between Rhodin Bargemont (pro-Silverblood stability) and Cella Bargemont (anti-Silverblood, open to Kaeo). House Valenti is circling, its leader Damon conspicuously alive while everyone else at the Feast is conspicuously dead. House Hurth is divided — old Gregor is loyal but his son Jon is already hedging.
The Faith watching. Father Jorn's murder has brought the Council of Three's attention. An Ayanite inquisitor is already in the castle. Kaeo's Xarian servants, his foreign manners, his untouched slave-girl gift from the Vizier — all of it will be scrutinized for heresy, and the first accusation of impropriety will be weaponized by whichever faction finds it useful.
The Schism ready to ignite. Silverring is funding proxies. The Griffinwing insurgency bleeds Corbeau territory. House Lockmere's pass-loyalty is being bid upon. Beaumont's Brotherhood is being watched for signals. Riverbend's river-war is escalating. The desert frontier is being ignored while Giants walk its sand.
The great question: who poisoned the Feast? Every faction has a theory. Every theory implicates someone. The truth — whatever it is — will reshape the Heartlands' power structure when it emerges. And Kaeo, the man who spent eleven years learning how to survive inside an empire that practices human sacrifice, may be the only person in the room calculating clearly enough to find it.
The Argent Schism — Strategic Positions
House Silverblood's position: Controls the Argenlord title, the grain supply, the regency of Argenia, and the loyalty of House Seeder, House Sandsword (nominally), and the Marketborn Council. Weakness: the Argenlord is dying, his heir is stupid, his daughter has her own agenda, and the Schism is draining resources.
House Silverring's position: Controls the money (Vaultkeepers), the mountain passes, the puppet lordship of Corvallis, the alliance with House Valenti, and a growing network of bought loyalties (the Iron Pact). Weakness: they are perceived as the aggressor (the Raven's Fall is not forgotten), their puppet Corbeau is fragile, and the Church hasn't endorsed them.
House Argenhold's position: One man. No army. No allies he can trust. No money. A castle full of strangers wearing his enemy's silver. But: the name. The river. The tradition of four centuries of neutrality. And whatever Kaeo learned in Xaria that made the Ix'Atani governor treat him as an equal.
The Church's position: The Council of Three wants peace, stability, and continued tithing revenue. The Feast of Poison killed one of their bishops. They will investigate. Their investigation will create leverage. Their leverage will be used — the question is by whom.
The Wild Cards: The Griffinwing insurgency. House Lockmere's pass-loyalty. House Beaumont's choice of side. The Giants on the southeastern frontier. And Jous Lorethian, whose agents may have poisoned the Feast and whose invasion fleet is being assembled on Nionia — the threat that no one in the Heartlands is taking seriously enough because they're too busy fighting each other.

