PART ONE: LANGUAGE AND THE VOICE OF MUNDUS

MUNNISH — THE CONTINENTAL TONGUE
Munnish is the dead empire's longest-running ghost. Derived from Nionian court dialect, it shed its original inflection over nine centuries of conquest until what remained was a stripped-down trade language with a vocabulary wide enough to discuss grain prices, a grammar simple enough that a Frozen South clansman and a Xarian delta merchant can haggle without an interpreter, and a beauty of roughly zero. The literate class hates it. The merchant class loves it. Everyone uses it.
Three registers exist:
Velanthi — the formal register; still largely Nionian in structure; used in courts, contracts, Church services, the Ayanite judiciary; long periodic sentences; honorifics front-loaded; passive voice preferred (the passive voice assigns no agent, which is useful when no one wants to be assigned responsibility)
Mercado — the trade register; the most-spoken version; direct, noun-heavy, minimal conjugation; numbers and weights still use Nionian counting system (most merchants can count to a thousand in Old Nionian and nothing else)
Vern — street speech; wildly regional; each city's vern has its own grammar drift, loan-words, and sounds that don't exist in formal Munnish; a Westhorn dockworker's vern and a Vornhold bargeman's vern are mutually intelligible only about 70% of the time, which is enough for argument

OATHS, BLASPHEMY, AND WHAT PEOPLE ACTUALLY SAY
Nionian (Under the Pure Way)
Surviving Vethori oaths (underground, seditious to use publicly):
"Fortia's scar" — invoking courage; admiration for someone who held under pressure
"Thalvex take it" — something lost, unrecoverable, given to the hostile sea
"By Kemvar's empty cup" — a drinking toast that also implies "I know this will end badly and I'm doing it anyway"
"Meravon's door" — a death threat; also used for any situation of no return
"Pyrantha's burn" — something well-made but at cost; admiration with acknowledgment of sacrifice
Pure Way approved expressions:
"The Way holds" — approval; everything is as it should be
"Against the Way" — accusation; catch-all condemnation
"The light has not yet reached it" — diplomatic way of calling something primitive, wrong, or damned
"In the Sacrifice's name" — invocation before any serious action; the more seriously Jous's followers say it, the more hollow it sounds to everyone else
What Nionians actually say when not being observed:
"That's the old marble" — something is as it has always been; not praise, not condemnation; acceptance
"Running out of stone" — near the end of resources, patience, time
"The quarry knows" — the truth will emerge; everything surfaces eventually; also: things have been happening underground that will matter

Roslandic
The language piles consonants at the front of words and drops terminal vowels. An insult loses half its syllables. A term of endearment gains none.
Common expressions:
"Kholodnoye zhelezo" — "cold iron"; a firm refusal; something settled and done; also an absolute rejection of someone's argument
"Mertvaya kuznitsa" — "dead forge"; something irreparably broken; applied to relationships, governments, hopes
"Moot nichego ne skazal" — "the Moot said nothing"; nobody will validate your position; you are alone with your problem
"Sheveli sam" — "stoke it yourself"; you made this, deal with it; the Roslandic version of "not my problem"
"Zhivkov udar" — "Zhivka hit"; a bad decision made while drinking that seemed reasonable at the time; an unavoidable consequence of indulgence
Profanity routing through the spirit tradition:
"Leshi tebya voz'met" — "may the Leshy take you"; forest-curse; fairly mild
"Rusalka tebe ulybayetsya" — "may the Rusalka smile at you"; far worse; a drowning-curse; used only in genuine anger
"Domovoy ushyol" — "the Domovoy left"; something catastrophic is about to happen to someone's household; also used as pure insult — "your Domovoy abandoned you" means "your household is cursed and your choices drove it away"
"Koschei zdes" — "Koschei is here"; something deathless and indestructible has found you; said with dread, sometimes resignation
Guild-specific:
"Sveta ne vidit" — "sees no light"; a miner working a dead seam; extended to mean someone pursuing something with nothing in it
"Skvazhina chitayet" — "the shaft reads"; the mine is communicating something; an intuition worth following; safety language that has become general use

Sangrean
Warm, rounded, trailing downward at the end of sentences. Everything sounds like a song slowing toward its final chord. Even the insults have melody.
Common expressions:
"La corrida no para" — "the fight doesn't stop"; something inevitable; fatalism framed as beauty
"Huele el corcho" — "smells the cork"; to sense trouble before you can prove it; the wine-master's skill extended to all perception
"Sangre vieja" — "old blood"; a Terrarossa partisan; said mockingly by Solé people, proudly by Terrarossa
"Pájaro de oro" — "golden bird"; a spy or informant; the Carvallo parrot reference is deliberate; calling someone pájaro without de oro is a different and more vulgar suggestion
"Última copa" — "last cup"; a situation about to end badly; used with a kind of resigned elegance
"La vid sabe" — "the vine knows"; everything reaches the light eventually; things grow toward truth; agricultural fatalism
Profanity:
"Que te lleve el toro" — "may the bull take you"; serious curse; invoking the corrida's death in the bad way
"Manos de piedra" — "stone hands"; someone who has no delicacy, no feeling; the worst insult to a craftsperson
"Corcho seco" — "dry cork"; a dried-up person, emotionally or financially; someone who has nothing left to give
Bell-related expressions (a whole register unique to Sangrea):
"La campana no miente" — "the bell doesn't lie"; what is announced publicly is true; used to shame people who deny public knowledge
"Fuera del repique" — "outside the peal"; someone not included in the network; not receiving the messages others are; political exclusion expressed as bell-code exclusion

Heartlandic
Formal precision, latinate loan-words still in common circulation, a tendency toward sentences that establish all the qualifications before stating the point. Outsiders experience this as evasiveness. Heartlanders experience outsiders' directness as aggression.
Common expressions:
"The grain counts" — what matters is what actually produces results; productivity over pedigree; a Silverblood expression that Silverring has appropriated ironically
"Bridge-weight" — the true measure of something's worth; you know what a bridge can hold when you put real weight on it; leadership measured the same way
"Against the current" — doing something dangerous or foolish; also used admiringly (they went against the current and survived)
"Argen's blessing" — good trade luck; falling into alignment with the river's logic
"Silver-tongue" — originally admiring; now politically charged; implies Silverblood alignment; not safe to use casually
Class markers in speech:
Noble houses use full Old Nionian title sequences when addressing equals; dropping a title marker is a deliberate slight
Guild members use occupational address sequences — master/journeyman/apprentice maintained in speech patterns even outside work context
A man who earns a living by the river addresses water as she (Ixchela's grammar bleeds north through generations of canal trade with the Xarian border); a man from the mountain districts uses neutral gender for water; this marks origin instantly

Red Coast
Arabic-patterned Munnish: long vowels extended, doubled adjectives for emphasis, very formal address registers that are the minimum courtesy, tripling something makes it sacred, quadrupling it makes it dangerous.
Common expressions:
"Al-qanat yajri" — "the qanat flows"; everything is working; peace, function, normalcy
"Al-rimal tatdhakkar" — "the sands remember"; nothing is truly forgotten in the desert; a warning against assuming time erases
"Rabi' al-thani" — "the second spring"; something unexpectedly good after hardship; a survivor's idiom
"Lisan al-nahas" — "copper tongue"; a flattering liar; precise and beautiful on the surface, the wrong composition underneath
"Thirst oath" — the most serious oath possible; sworn over water; breaking a thirst oath is the one sin the desert communities believe the desert itself punishes
Regional variants:
Oasis communities say "bismillah al-qanat" ("in the name of the qanat") as a work-beginning phrase; the Lovist missionaries tried to replace this with Lovist invocations and failed; the phrase is now so embedded in canal-work practice it functions as safety protocol rather than theology
Gate Lands merchant class uses "Sadiq's measure" for anything not quite honest but not quite dishonest; the Sadiq family name has become a common noun meaning "within the letter but against the spirit"

Frozen South
Deliberate. Slow. Silence is not the absence of speech but a speech act in itself. The clans communicate in layers: surface speech for outsiders, fire-song fragments for clan members, and a third layer of significance in pauses, body positioning, and the specific words chosen from multiple valid synonyms, which the fire-song tradition trains people to hear.
Common expressions:
"Gullblind" — "gold-blind"; corrupted by wealth; a serious accusation; the Aurax are frequently called this by the other clans
"Isen hugsar" — "the ice remembers"; a grudge that won't die; something done in this generation that will be answered in the next
"Vetrsvarið" — "winter-sworn"; an absolute commitment; more binding than any written contract
"Undir beinsjó" — "below the bone-sea"; beyond the worst possible outcome; the place where bones accumulate on the eastern coast's cold floor
"Eld-blindr" — "fire-blind"; unable to see because you're sitting too close to your own fire; insularity; refusing to perceive the world outside your clan
The silence vocabulary: The fire-song tradition trains listeners to extract meaning from pauses of different lengths within a sentence. A single-breath pause after a name means the name is being honored. A two-breath pause after a name means the name is being invoked for judgment. A pause before responding to a question means the question is serious. No pause before responding means the answer required no thought, which implies it's either obvious or a lie.

Horns
Clipped, functional, maritime technical vocabulary bleeds into daily speech until the division between work and life has the same quality as the division between sea and harbor: not a wall, just a change in depth.
Common expressions:
"The knot holds" — approval; reliability confirmed; something that will bear weight
"Running out of rope" — nearing the end; resources, patience, options
"Storm-sense" — intuition; premonition; the Windreaders' specific skill extended as a general term for knowing something before the evidence arrives
"Reading the fog" — interpreting ambiguous information; making decisions when visibility is reduced
"Deader than Fenn" — utterly finished; the Fenn house exterminated in the Bridge-Throat Massacre; their name survives only as the continent's most complete example of total erasure
Inter-port vocabulary: Between cities, specific Horns words have loaded meanings:
"Westhorn" as a verb means to overcharge with politeness; the Garrun reputation for guilded extortion
"Brinehold" as an adjective means brine-preserved, i.e., old, reliable, slightly pickled, not going bad but not fresh
"Nightspike price" means the real cost underneath the quoted cost; what you'll actually pay once the salvage fees and the docking surcharges are added

THE ASHBORN HUSH — XARIA'S INVISIBLE LANGUAGE
The Hush is a sub-audible communication register developed over centuries of necessity. It is not whispering; it is a distinct system.
Physical mechanics: Tapped patterns against surfaces within reach (wall, floor, another person's arm or hand). Short-range vocalization at frequencies below the audible threshold that free Xarians cannot perceive but that Ashborn ears have been trained from childhood to detect. Specific body orientations that encode grammatical structure — facing someone directly means indicative mood; a three-quarter turn means conditional; facing away entirely means hypothetical or dangerous.
Vocabulary range: Approximately 4,000 distinct concepts; full Hush literacy requires eight to ten years of childhood immersion; partial Hush (enough for safety communication) can be learned by adults in approximately six months; the full expressive register, including metaphorical and emotional nuance, takes a lifetime
What the Hush can do that speech cannot:
Lie about the surface speech while telling truth in the Hush simultaneously; Ashborn in free Xarian company often have two conversations running at once
Express emotional register underneath diplomatic content; "yes" in Munnish while "this is dangerous and I am afraid but we have no other option" in the Hush
Reference the Hush-Truth theological tradition in ways that are theological text to Reformation members and ambient noise to everyone else
What the dominant caste knows: They know it exists. They cannot perceive it. Three generations of Dominion scholars have attempted to document and decode it. Their work is incomplete; the Hush evolves faster than the scholarship. Oya-Nua has said privately: "They think we cannot change our language. They think we have what we were given. They have not understood that necessity is a teacher who never stops."

PART TWO: DAILY LIFE ACROSS THE WORLD

NIONIA UNDER THE PURE WAY
Patrician Household (morning):
The private bath is a survival of the Old Way social bath; pure white stone basins, heated water carried by household staff before dawn; the bath is where real conversation still happens because Domus Lux enforcement focuses on public spaces
Household prayers at the family shrine — formerly Vethori icons, now Pure Way ones; the transition required whitewashing the old icons rather than removing them; several patrician households retain the original underneath
Account review with the household steward; the most important business is conducted standing at a lectern, never sitting — sitting is for leisure and leisure is now somewhat politically fraught under the Pure Way's productivity theology
The morning letter: patrician culture has elaborate letter-writing conventions; the opening line of a letter signals its urgency by the specific honorific used for the recipient; seventeen gradations from "most sovereign" (the Vizier of Xaria, technically) to "friend" (genuine intimacy) to deliberate omission of honorific (a calculated insult)
Common Nionian household (one room in the Terraces):
Four to six people per room; shift workers sleep in the same beds in rotation, which means the bed is never cold and never unoccupied
The teglia pot — a communal clay pot kept on a shared landing fire; everyone contributes scraps; what comes out is different every day and occasionally remarkable; a neighborhood is partly defined by whose teglia pot you eat from
The whale-oil lamp burns on the landing; the Pure Way's decree about darkness has paradoxically made ordinary domestic life slightly brighter, because the street lamps work; but the lamp oil costs money, and the cost has risen since the decree, and this is noted with bitter humor
The canto della scala — "staircase song" — the tradition of humming lamento melodies while climbing tenement stairs; technically legal because no words are sung; technically subversive because everyone knows the words; the Domus Lux has twice tried to ban staircase humming and given up twice because the enforcement would require a white-cloak stationed at every staircase in Vellium

ROSLAND — THE MINER'S DAY (Fyrhold)
Before the shaft:
The kolpak inspection: partners check each other's coats; a torn liner is grounds to refuse the shift; this is law since the Gordost Collapse of 1189 AF when twelve men died because two of them couldn't move freely in their damaged gear
The zhalost' — "the pity" — the small offering left at the mine-shrine figure (Saint Dretha or Alon, usually, or something older that no one has a name for); the gesture is a touching of the figure's base with the knuckle, not the palm; touching with the palm is reserved for the living
The foreman's count: names spoken aloud; every miner must respond; entering uncounted means you're not in the count when you come out
In the shaft:
The knock-code: percussive communication through rock; learned in two years of apprenticeship; carries identity, status (well/hurt/needs-help/danger/all-clear), and navigation; the full code has approximately 200 distinct sequences; most miners know 60-80; the foreman knows all of them
The pipe rest: twice per shift, ten minutes; absolute quiet; mine-gossip happens here; this is also where the partner exchange happens — small objects passed between shift partners; nothing prescribed; just the gesture of acknowledgment; a miner who stops exchanging objects with their partner is understood to be in some kind of trouble
The Rock-Marten: semi-feral small predators that live in worked-out shafts and kill the Millstone-Mice that eat stored supplies; not pets but greeted by name when visible; a dead Rock-Marten in your section is considered a sign to leave early; no miner who has worked underground for ten years ignores this
After the shaft:
The zhivka ration: not a celebration, a protocol; one measure per shift per miner, administered in the changing area; the alcohol reduces the carbon-accumulation symptoms from extended underground exposure; the physicians who wrote the dosage guidelines did not include this in the official rationale; the miners know what it's for
The guild-hall fire: every mining settlement has a central firepit that burns continuously during working seasons; it is tended by whoever is off-shift; the tending is not assigned but it is not neglected; a town whose guild-fire goes out has deeper problems than fuel
The fire-song hour: on Velisday evenings, the shift that has off-time sings; not a performance, not a celebration; a recitation; the songs that week reflect what happened that week; a collapse that killed no one gets a different song than a week of nothing significant; the songs are never dramatic in proportion to their real weight

SANGREA — VINEYARD WORKER AND LORD (Vallesangre)
The worker's day changes entirely by season:
Winter (pruning): Cold, methodical, silent work. The coplas for pruning are slow and old and everyone knows them. The evening meal is communal at the hacienda — worker's table separate from the lord's table but using the same kitchen, which is considered the key dignity in the arrangement. Once a week: the noche de los cuentos, story-night; the oldest worker present tells a story; no interrupting; thanks expressed by silence rather than applause.
Spring (training): Tactile work done by hand; the vine-trainers develop characteristic calluses in patterns that identify their trade. The tradition of speaking to the vines is observed by every experienced worker; the reasoning is practical and unexplained: the vines respond to sustained presence; workers who talk to them consistently produce measurably better yields; no one has a good theory and no one needs one.
Harvest: Everyone available; children pick; grandparents direct; the youngest and oldest work together while the middle generation carries. The first pressed grapes: poured into the soil with a specific phrase that varies by house and that most workers don't know the translation of; the phrases are in Old Sangrean that predates Munnish and in many cases predates the noble houses that now own the land. After the last cart: la noche libre — the free night; no lord present by tradition; the workers run their own table; the music is different, older, rawer.
The lord's day (minor Sangrean noble, three steps below Solé):
The morning audience: any vassal, tenant, or free citizen may request time; it is not refused without grave reason; the audience chamber smell is deliberate — fresh-cut flowers from the garden, not incense, not the smell of administration
The azulejo consultation: before any significant decision, a minor Sangrean lord of the traditional type will commission a new tile or consult an existing one; the tiles in the receiving hall encode family history in a way that only family members can read fully; bringing a matter to the tile room means invoking the family's accumulated judgment
The afternoon siesta is not optional; it is the time when the lord's household does its actual work, the correspondence and account-keeping and intelligence-gathering that cannot happen when the lord is present
The evening: the roof. The roof is everything. Who is on whose roof and when and how late is the newspaper that has no editor

HEARTLANDS — GUILD TABLE AND MARKET (Minor Noble Household)
The surcoat politics at a minor Heartlander court:
House colors on the surcoat, quality of thread signaling position within the house
A guest's surcoat is assessed the moment they enter; to receive a good seat before your surcoat is seen means the host already knows who you are
A man in traveling clothes with no surcoat visible is either a pilgrim (shown immediately to the Lovist guest-room), a Starveling Church member (shown to the door), or someone between allegiances (watched until clarified)
The guild insignia at the hem rather than the chest: the master-journeyman-apprentice distinction visible in garment position, not just quality
The Guild Table ritual:
The host places salt and bread at the center first; the first guest to pass them to someone else rather than taking first is demonstrating a specific deference (if lower-status) or a specific courtesy (if higher-status); misreading which it is can destroy a relationship before the first course
The challenge tradition: a point left unchallenged at guild table is either obviously true or the challenger is a coward; the room knows which; a man who lets too much pass unchallenged is not known for his peaceable nature but for his lack of one
Buying a round: contributing a dish; the quality is noted; a house that consistently contributes poor quality has a problem that the guild table makes public in the most socially efficient way possible

RED COAST — MERCHANT CLASS AND DESERT TRAVELER
The merchant's day (Alsiroth's Gate):
Before the heat:
The Dawn Market: every transaction requiring careful inspection of goods; done in natural light before heat distorts; contracts signed before the sun rises above the eastern ridge
The morning tea: three cups minimum with any trading partner; first bitter, second sweet, third sweetest; each cup represents a different quality of trust; refusing the third cup ends the relationship gracefully; refusing the first cup is an insult with no graceful interpretation
Letters by courier; the Carvallo parrot network's mainland reach doesn't extend to the Red Coast, so correspondence travels by human messenger; the fastest message in the Gate Lands is a Sand-Seer carrying an urgent verbal communication on camelback; they charge accordingly
Midday:
Mandatory; the city closes; anyone who breaks midday rest is either desperate or dangerous; worth knowing which
The hammam: Hammam al-Kubra's public bath; this is where alliances are actually made; the formal negotiations happen in offices, the real agreements happen in steam; a deal sealed at the hammam is more durable than a deal sealed at a desk because it was made in a context that excluded performance
Evening:
The Souk reopens; the specific merchant arcades in specific sequence; the spice quarter at sixteenth hour, the metalwork quarter at seventeenth, the carpet and textile quarter at eighteenth; the sequencing evolved from practical reasons (odor, dust, weight of foot traffic) and now encodes a commerce hierarchy that is a source of constant low-level argument
The roof culture: Red Coast wealthy households live on their roofs in the evening; a view across the rooftops of Alsiroth's Gate is a view of the city's real political map in real-time
The caravan traveler:
Route-knots: the Saffaren tradition of leaving knotted cords on specific rocks at specific angles to communicate route conditions; a two-loop knot at the eastern angle of a certain class of rock means "water in this direction, two hours"; a broken cord means danger ahead; the system has approximately 80 distinct signals and predates any current civilization by an unknown margin
The munaqqar — "the cleared rock" — a flat stone near each Saffaren well that is kept swept clean; any traveler finding the rock swept is safe to approach the well; any traveler finding it covered with sand has received a warning that the well is either depleted, contaminated, or controlled by someone unfriendly
The sand-prayer: not Lovist; not theologically organized; simply a specific posture facing the setting sun that every desert traveler learns and performs regardless of faith because it has been performed at this hour in this direction since before any current faith existed

THE FROZEN SOUTH — CLAN LIFE (Aurheim)
The communal longhouse:
The central fire is never extinguished; when a new longhouse is built, fire from the old one is carried to start it; a fire-lineage extends back to a founding fire that the fire-songs trace to a specific named moment; the oldest fire-line in the south is Clan Aurax's; it is fifteen generations old
Sleeping arrangements are functional rather than familial; you sleep nearest to who you are bonded to in work; a warrior sleeps near his partner; a druid-equivalent (Auren Priest) sleeps alone, near the walls, facing out
The morning mead-cup: small, warm, the first of the day; passed in order of age from eldest to youngest; each person holds the cup for exactly as long as they choose before passing it; the length of time signals mood in a language the entire longhouse reads fluently
The bone-carving hour: during the long winter dark when outdoor work is impossible; everyone carves; the objects made during this time are the most personal objects a southerner possesses; a bone-carved object given to someone else is more intimate than any spoken declaration
The Hunt:
The full preparation is two days; the second day is silence; the third day is the hunt itself
Kjörval — "the hunting blood-call" — a specific vocalization made immediately before separating into hunting positions; half sound, half breath; carries exactly as far as the hunting party and no further; its acoustic properties in cold air are calibrated to this function; outsiders have heard it reported as "a sound that appears behind you even when you know the source is ahead"
The Whaletooth Priest's attendance is mandatory; the first cut of the catch is the Priest's and is cast back into the sea with a formula no one outside the priesthood knows completely; the second cut is the hunt leader's and is shared with the oldest member of the party; the sequence continues hierarchically until everyone has received a portion; there is always a portion left; this portion is left on the beach

XARIA — DAILY LIFE (Temple City and Canal Delta)
The temple-city priest's day:
The sacrificial calendar governs everything. On a T'zol'kin observation day, the priest's entire day is organized around the ceremony. On a non-ceremony day:
Dawn: the ix'avar — "the first offering" — a small personal blood offering made at a household shrine; a pinprick on the left thumb; a drop on the stone; this is not the major sacrifice; this is the daily acknowledgment that the accounting exists
Morning: administrative duties in the temple bureaucracy; the temple-cities run on extraordinary administrative precision; grain inventories, tribute calculations, labor allocations
Midday: the public teaching hour; the teocalli steps serve as lecture space; anyone may attend; the K'ay storyteller tradition shares the hour with the priestly teaching
Evening: the restricted ceremonies; only initiates; the higher-register rituals whose form the public does not see
The Ashborn laborer's day (delta canal work):
Before dawn: the Hush-gathering; a brief assembly of workers at the canal section's junction point; nothing is said in audible speech; the Hush carries the day's real information — which supervisor to watch, what the quota enforcement mood is, whether anyone needs covering
The canal work itself: knee-deep in water for most of the day; the primary health risk is parasite infection from the delta water, which the temple authorities are aware of and the Canal Guild manages through rotation schedules that are not adequately enforced
The midday break: workers are technically entitled to a full meal; in practice, the meal is provided in proportion to quota performance; this is the primary enforcement mechanism
Evening: the household altar; Amara-Utu's portion left before eating; whatever was learned or witnessed today offered to the Hush-record maintained by the community's eldest member, who keeps the running oral history of the community in memory
The Hush-hour: before sleep; the community's emotional accounting; the day processed communally in the sub-audible register; what was seen, what was felt, what requires response

PART THREE: VISUAL CULTURE

NIONIAN ART UNDER TWO TRADITIONS
The Vethori Hieratic (now suppressed): Frontal-pose god-figures, strict iconographic rules (which god appears in which posture with which symbol, deviation from which is heresy), the specific purple-black of imperial sacred pigment. The mosaic tradition survives in architecture even where the theological content has been whitewashed — the floor structures in patrician homes still show the compositional mathematics of Vethori sacred geometry even with Lovist images replacing the gods. The bones of the old religion in the floors of the new.
The Pure Way Visual Language: The single isolated figure. Illuminated from no visible source. Looking toward something out of frame. Always Jous. The deliberate visual theology of radical uniqueness — every other human being appears as crowd, as "the before," as the era awaiting the figure. This is the most recognizable new visual tradition on the continent in 1308 AF and the most obviously political: you cannot look at it without understanding its argument.
The Underground Aesthetic: The lamento singer tradition has a parallel visual culture: the tavoletta — small wooden panels painted with scenes from everyday life, often containing embedded visual jokes, political commentary, and encoded Vethori references that only the initiated read. They are kept in private rooms. They are technically still legal under the Pure Way because their surface content is domestic. Their actual content is not.

SANGREAN VISUAL TRADITIONS
The Azulejo: Geometric at foundation, increasingly naturalistic through Xarian contact. The most ambitious contemporary azulejo masters incorporate simplified jungle imagery — specific Xarian birds and plants translated into tile geometry. A master tile from a major house's receiving hall: 60cm square, 4,000 individual tile pieces, laid over six months, worth more than a skilled laborer earns in a year. The best ones are not silent when you look at them. They continue.
Corrida Art: Not documentation but theology. The specific frozen moment: the final pass, the cape extended, the bull's momentum not yet redirected. Always the instant before the kill — the maximum compression of grace and danger. The theory of the suspended moment — Sangrean aesthetic philosophy argues that this specific configuration of body, cape, and animal represents the furthest extension of human physical meaning; past it, the meaning resolves and is therefore over. Before it, the meaning has not yet arrived. At this precise moment, both are present simultaneously.
Cantaor Portraiture: The only tradition of genuine individual portraiture on the continent. Lords are depicted ceremonially and impersonally. Cantaores are painted mid-performance — face fully expressive, body in the posture of a specific performance, often mid-sound. The technique: not painted from observation but from memory immediately after the performance, because the performance posture cannot be re-created and the memory is therefore the most accurate document available. The best cantaor portraits are considered to contain something the subject cannot access themselves — the external shape of an internal act.

ROSLANDIC CARVING AND THE KNOT TRADITION
The Lintel Language: Every significant Roslandic building has a carved lintel above its entrance. The carving is not decorative in the sense of being arbitrary. It encodes: family history (in knot patterns derived from fire-song mnemonic structures), the building's primary function (specific tool symbols for guildhalls, specific postures for hospices), and the date of construction in a calendar notation that uses the twelve months as symbols rather than numbers. A master carver can read a lintel history in ten minutes. An outsider sees beautiful wood.
Bone-Work: The mine-workers' intimate tradition. Animal bone, occasionally human bone (always with permission, always formalized, the bone of significant dead given to the craftsperson who will carry their presence forward). Carved objects are intimate-scale, held and handled rather than displayed. The best bone-carvers describe the process as removing what shouldn't be there — revealing the figure the bone already contained. The objects are passed between shift partners as the primary language of the partnership: a new carving given to your partner on Monday morning without explanation means more than any words you could have said.
The Grief-Post: In significant Roslandic communities, a standing carved post at the settlement's edge; added to after every significant death; the carvings for each death are specific to the individual, not generic mourning symbols; the oldest grief-posts in the deep Greens are ten feet tall and three centuries old. The fire-songs and the grief-posts together constitute the community's externalised memory — two parallel archives, one ephemeral and living, one permanent and silent.

FROZEN SOUTH GOLD-WORK
The Silence Objects: Made by Auren Priests from the Kjölfoss's deep-vein gold using techniques predating the current tradition by at least 1,000 years. Observable difference from normal goldsmithing: warm to the touch in any temperature. Echo-dense in the way the Great Bridge-stone is echo-dense. They do not leave the south. The Magos have requested access to examine one four times. Each time the request has been declined with elaborate courtesy and zero concession. The most recent response, from the current Auren Priest leadership, was: "The gold is still warm because it is still ours. You may see it when it has cooled."
The Speaking Torc: The chief's neck-torc is not a symbol of office. It is a document. The knot patterns encode the chief's genealogy, military history, significant decisions, and the fire-song fragments his rule is associated with. A torc taken from a dead chief in battle is taken to the opposing clan's fire-singer, who reads it aloud to both communities — the victor's and the defeated's. This is how the Compact's Holmgang tradition ensures the defeated clan's history is not erased: it is read by the community that beat them.

XARIAN FEATHERWORK
The Codex-Mantle: A garment-length featherwork piece incorporating hundreds of bird species in patterns that encode cosmological knowledge, genealogy, historical events, and prophetic interpretation. A master codex-reader interprets one for days. Manufacture: three to five years. Approximately forty complete codex-mantles in existence. None have ever been traded to the mainland; the few in Dominion hands were acquired through dynastic inheritance.
The Temple Reliefs: Not decoration. Not primarily history. Instructions. The specific sequences of carved imagery on teocalli surfaces describe ritual procedures, sacrificial timings, and ceremonial protocols with the precision of a technical manual. They are also, secondarily, history. But the purpose was operational first. A K'ay storyteller reads a relief the same way a Brothers of the Open Road master reads a waystone: for practical guidance first, meaning second.



