DIVINE VEINS — COSMOLOGY, CALENDAR & THEOLOGY
The Heavens · The Reckoning of Days · The Faiths of Mundus
Reference Document — 1308 AF

PART ONE: THE HEAVENS AND THE SEAS

THE TWO SUNS
The sky of Mundus holds two suns — a fact so fundamental that the oldest Heartlander word for "obvious" is velosi, meaning "clear as both suns."
Velos — the Elder Sun. A yellow-white star, the primary source of light and heat. Larger and steadier in the sky. Velos drives the seasons, marks the year, and is the cosmological anchor of all calendar systems on the continent. When people say "the sun," they mean Velos.
Keth — the Young Sun. A smaller, orange-red star in close binary orbit with Velos. From the surface of Mundus, Keth appears roughly a third the apparent size of Velos, tinted warm amber against the sky's blue. During midday the two are often perceived as a single intensified light. At dawn and dusk, when Keth's different color becomes distinct, a pair of suns is visible — one yellow, one orange — rising or setting in close formation. Artists across every culture have painted this moment. No one has ever successfully described it in words.
The binary orbit means Keth periodically passes behind Velos (a secondary eclipse: an eerie dimming of approximately twenty minutes in which the sky greys and animals grow briefly confused) or transits in front (an extremely rare event: a tiny orange disc moving across Velos's face over several hours, visible to the naked eye as a dark point). A full transit has occurred three documented times in Mundane history. Each was treated as an omen of civilizational consequence, and history has obliged each time.
The Absence — the window of approximately forty minutes that occurs, on certain days, between Keth setting and Velos rising independently. Not darkness, exactly — more like a deepening of late twilight, the color of cooling embers. The Venic Path practitioners prize the Absence for meditation. Sailors avoid beginning any voyage during it. In Nionian superstition, children born during the Absence are said to "belong to neither light."

THE TWO MOONS
Aura — the Great Moon. Silver-white, approximately the apparent size of our moon. Orbital period of twenty-nine days. Full Aura is the primary reference point for monthly calendar divisions. In clear weather, Aura at fullness is bright enough to cast distinct shadows. The Tariqat al-Nur and the Sisters of the Veil in Nionia both structure their contemplative practices around Aura's cycle. In Lovist theology, Aura is "Vena's open hand" — the hand that gives.
Teln — the Runner. Smaller, faster, with a faintly gold-warm tint to its light (warmer albedo from mineral composition, per the Magos). Orbital period of eleven days — it moves fast enough that attentive observers can watch it shift position night to night. Teln waxes and wanes nearly three times for every Aura cycle. Navigators use Teln's position for fine-grained reckoning. In Lovist theology, Teln is "Vena's closed fist" — the hand that holds back.
Concordance — when both Aura and Teln are simultaneously full. Because Aura's cycle is twenty-nine days and Teln's eleven days (both prime numbers), the full alignment repeats every 319 days — roughly once each year. Concordance is among the most important events in both the Lovist religious calendar and the regional folk traditions of every culture on the continent. The tides during Concordance are dramatically amplified.
The Tidal Consequence — two moons with different orbital periods create tidal interference of spectacular complexity. On a normal night, Mundus experiences between three and five tidal peaks, depending on the relative positions of Aura and Teln. When they oppose each other, the interference can create zones of unnaturally flat water surrounded by turbulent standing waves. When they align toward full simultaneously, tidal forces compound — during Concordance, coastal flooding is routine and expected; low-lying settlements prepare weeks in advance. This lunar chaos is the primary reason the Pilots' Guild, the Horns navigators, and the Frozen South's Dyrholmar tradition all developed sophisticated tidal prediction systems that remain closely guarded professional secrets.

WHY THE OCEANS ARE UNMASTERABLE
The seas of Mundus are not merely dangerous by weather. They are structurally, mechanically hostile to long-distance sailing, and have been since before recorded history.
The Tidal Wars — the technical term used by the Magos for the deep-ocean current systems created by competing tidal forces. Where coastal seas have predictable (if complex) tidal rhythms, the open ocean accumulates these forces across thousands of miles of water. The result: vast slow-moving zones of circular counter-current — eddies the size of island chains — that rotate through the ocean in a multi-year cycle. A ship entering a Tidal War zone is pulled in multiple directions simultaneously, driven off course, dismasted by crosswinds, and has historically broken apart. The Tidal Wars are why no fleet has ever circumnavigated the continent.
The Twin-Sun Tide — the binary star system adds a solar tidal component to the lunar one. When both Velos and Keth are roughly aligned with one or both moons (a full triple alignment), tidal forces reach catastrophic levels. These events are rare — perhaps once per generation — and cannot be predicted with current instruments. The Magos' records contain descriptions of "Valos events" (named for a harbor city destroyed by an anomalous surge circa 800 AF, no survivors) that are consistent with triple-alignment tidal amplification. The Tide Scholar Maren's recent work, unconnected to any known cause in 1308 AF, is beginning to document subtle shifts in the Tidal War pattern cycle — the first measurable change in four centuries.
The Grey Curtain — beyond approximately 200 miles from the continental shelf, permanent storm belts form. The interaction between the complex tidal forcing and the atmospheric effects of a binary star system creates storm systems in the deep ocean that do not dissipate. Sailors who have glimpsed the Grey Curtain from elevated coastal headlands describe it as a wall of cloud extending from horizon to horizon. In the Nionian Old Way, it was the domain of Thalvex, the hostile sea-god who built the storms to keep mortals from knowing what lay beyond. In Lovist theology, it is "the boundary of grief" — where the ocean of Loreth's sacrifice is too deep for living things to traverse. The Saffaren of the Red Coast, who have perhaps the most prosaic view of celestial mechanics on the continent, call it "the place where T'zal begins" — T'zal being the Xarian concept of an ocean so vast it has stopped being a place and become simply a condition.
The Eldra-Veil (now breached) — in the deep southern ocean, the echo-density of Eldraholm produced a navigational barrier of a different kind: the chaotic echo-emissions at the Veil boundary caused disorientation, panic, and dissociative breakdown in any traveler not adapted to it. This barrier is now compromised. The echo-field is bleeding northward through the breach. The tidal pattern around the southern ocean is subtly shifting as a result — one of the anomalies the Magos are beginning to notice.
The Throat, the Galewater, the Teeth Straits — even short crossings are hazardous because tidal interference is amplified by coastal geometry. The Throat (Nionia to mainland: seven miles) channels the tidal forces of both moons through a narrow passage between two different geological shelves, creating tidal surges that reverse direction unpredictably during a crossing. The Galewater (Horns to Northwind: forty miles) sits at the precise latitude where the dominant Tidal War circulation creates permanent crosswind conditions that change direction on no predictable schedule. The Teeth Straits are navigable only because local pilots have memorized the tidal windows — the two or three hours per day, per strait, when the competing currents temporarily align.

THE COSMOLOGICAL SHAPE OF THE WORLD (As Understood in 1308 AF)
The educated class accepts that the world is spherical — the Magos confirmed this through astronomical observation, the curvature of the horizon, and the behavior of lunar eclipses during Concordance. This knowledge is approximately 300 years old and has been absorbed into educated culture without significant resistance.
What lies across the oceans is genuinely unknown. The theories:
The Ix'Atani Dominion exists across the eastern ocean (Xarian colonial fact)
Eldraholm exists in the deep south (the Giants have now confirmed this)
The Frozen South clans believe the southern ocean leads to the Under-World (the realm of the honored dead)
The Red Coast's deep-desert Saffaren believe T'zal — the oceanic void — simply extends forever, that the world has no other shore
The Magos' private position, held by Grand Magos Thessaly and perhaps six senior scholars: Mundus is one of possibly several inhabited landmasses, separated by ocean that is — for current technology — impassable. The Giants' arrival confirms this. The Dominion confirms this. The question of what else exists is one that Thessaly expects will begin to answer itself within her lifetime.

PART TWO: THE VELOSI CALENDAR

THE OFFICIAL RECKONING
The Velosi Calendar — named for Velos, the Elder Sun, and codified by Nionian imperial astronomers circa 200 AF. Adopted continent-wide during the imperial consolidation and maintained into the Age of Faith by institutional inertia. Every region uses its own local names for months and festivals, but the underlying structure is universal among the literate class.
Structure:
12 months × 30 days = 360 days
5 Velindra Days (the Days Between) outside any month; added at the end of the year
Leap adjustment every 6 years: 6 Velindra Days instead of 5
The Velindra Days are legal and commercial dead time — no contracts signed, no courts open, no debt collected; in practice, the largest informal markets of the year
The year begins with Velos reaching its winter solstice low-point and beginning its return
Days of the Week (7 days, Nionian-Munnish names):
Velisday — day of the Elder Sun; rest day for clergy in orthodox Loveism
Kethisday — day of the Young Sun; travelers' day; considered auspicious for beginning journeys
Aurisday — day of Aura-moon; market day in most Heartlander towns
Telnaday — day of Teln-moon; guild meetings traditionally scheduled here
Vethday — day of the turning; the major agricultural and trade day
Morvday — day of the deep sea; sailors call it lucky; landlocked cultures think it ill-omened for beginnings
Umbraday — day of shadow; cleaning day; preparation for Velisday; the week's quiet day

THE TWELVE MONTHS
1. VELORIM — The Return Winter to early spring. 30 days. The year's first month. Named for Velos's return to strength after the solstice low-point. The Nionian New Year falls on Velorim 1 — the most important civil holiday across all former imperial regions, celebrated for three days with markets, public feasts, and the settling of the previous year's debts.
Regional names: Sorvost (Roslandic), Retorno (Sangrean), Al-Awda (Red Coast), Frostbreak (Horns)
2. KETHARA — The Twin Fire Late winter. When Keth (Young Sun) is most distinctly visible alongside Velos in the morning sky, its orange light clearly separate from Velos's yellow-white. A cold month everywhere except Xaria and the Selvaverde border. The domestic holiday of the Twin Candles falls in Kethara — families light two candles at different heights, one yellow, one orange, and eat together.
Regional names: Grenosk (Roslandic), Fuegonado (Sangrean), Nar-Thani (Red Coast)
3. AURANIS — The Gold Rising Early spring. Named for Aura-moon, which is near its closest approach and appears largest and most golden. Both moons are often visible together in the early Auranis evening sky. The Night of Offering falls in this month. Planting preparations begin.
Regional names: Thalvor (Roslandic), Doramar (Sangrean), Qamar-Kabir (Red Coast, "Great Moon")
4. SOLVANE — The Open Days Spring equinox month. Named for the equal light — Solvane is derived from the Munnish root for "balanced" and "vault" together (the sky-vault balanced). The pilgrimage season opens on Solvane 1 with the Lovist holiday Velithara. The continent's largest inland trade fair, the Stonebridge Market, runs from Solvane 15 for three weeks.
Regional names: Grebend (Roslandic), Largavida (Sangrean)
5. TELNAVAR — The Runner Mid-spring. Named for Teln-moon at perigee (closest approach), visibly faster across the sky than usual. Associated with messengers, travelers, quick decisions. The Silver Moot falls in Telnavar during election years. The Saffaren Trade Moon fair occurs on the first Telnavar full-Teln.
Regional names: Rychel (Roslandic), Correndero (Sangrean), Barq-Waqt (Red Coast, "Lightning Time")
6. MORDAEN — The Deep Early summer. The one month when the ocean is least hostile — the Tidal Wars reach a temporary equilibrium, the Grey Curtain retreats slightly. The Pilots' Guild processes the year's largest fleet movements through Mordaen. The continent-wide Water Festival of the Red Coast falls here. Mordaen markets are the largest commercial events of the year for coastal cities.
Regional names: Zlakmir (Roslandic), Profundis (Sangrean), Madd-Bahr (Red Coast, "The Flood's Rest")
7. CONCORDIS — The Meeting High summer. The month most likely to contain a Concordance night (both moons full simultaneously), though the true Concordance follows its own 319-day cycle rather than adhering to the calendar. When a Concordance falls in Concordis, it is treated as a double blessing. The three-day Concordance Festival is the Lovist church's most important observance. The Red Coast's Night Market week is traditionally held here.
Regional names: Dvusvet (Roslandic, "Double Light"), Encuentro (Sangrean), Al-Liqaa (Red Coast)
8. VETHAROS — The Turning Late summer. Harvest season begins across the continent's temperate zones. Named for the perceptible turning of light — the days grow shorter in Vetharos, and even in Sangrea's heat there is a quality to the late-afternoon sun that people describe as "Vetharos gold" — richer, more amber, faintly melancholic. The Festival of the Red Grape spans Vetharos's first two weeks in Castesol.
Regional names: Ozhav (Roslandic), Girando (Sangrean), Kharf (Red Coast)
9. AURAVAL — The Great Moon Walk Autumn. Aura reaches its apparent largest size and is visible most nights on clear skies. The harvest continues. Moonlit nights in the grain fields are an aesthetic fact of Heartlander life. The Guild Tables of the Heartlands open in Auraval's first week.
Regional names: Mechtal (Roslandic), Lunagrande (Sangrean), Badr-Kabir (Red Coast)
10. KETHMIR — The Dying Fire Autumn deepening. Keth becomes hard to distinguish from Velos in the morning sky — the days feel more monochromatic, the orange warmth fading. The Broken Chalice Day falls on Kethmir 12 in Sangrea. The approach to the Lovist fasting month creates a quiet, sobering quality to the month. Freezing nights arrive in the Frozen South.
Regional names: Gruzhen (Roslandic), Cenizante (Sangrean), Al-Khamud (Red Coast)
11. SORVAEL — The Long Coming The Lovist fasting month. Thirty days of daily observance — dawn prayers, reduced meals, almsgiving. The full fast (all day without food or water) is only obligatory for clergy; laypeople typically observe a single daylight fast per week during Sorvael plus charitable acts. The month ends with the Breaking Fast holiday Kethiran, the largest communal feast of the year.
Regional names: Dolgach (Roslandic), Nochilarga (Sangrean), Al-Sawm (Red Coast, "The Fast")
12. UMBRANIS — The Dark Deepest winter. The shortest days. The Day of Founding (Triavar) falls on Umbranis 7. The Night of the Twelve Fires is the solstice night in Rosland. The Winter-Moot of the Frozen South occurs during Umbranis. The Velindra Days follow Umbranis 30, before the year turns to Velorim again.
Regional names: Korvast (Roslandic, "Crow-Cold"), Sombranoche (Sangrean), Al-Zalam (Red Coast)

MAJOR LOVIST HOLIDAYS
(observed across all former imperial regions)
CONCORDANCE FESTIVAL — Concordis, when both moons align Three days. The Church's most significant religious event. Celebrates the moment of the Great Sacrifice — Loreth and Vena's union before becoming the world. The only major ceremony where mixed-gender participation is mandatory. Cities light double-flame lanterns (one white for Aura, one gold for Teln). The ceremony at the Great Cathedral of Faithir draws up to 80,000 pilgrims when the alignment falls in Concordis. If the true Concordance falls outside this month, the observance is still held in Concordis but called "the Memorial Concordance" — acknowledged as a commemoration rather than a true celebration.
ORANTARA — The Night of Offering (Auranis 15) Sundown to sundown — a full day's vigil. No food or drink until the second sundown, when a small communal meal is shared with strangers. The Bonekeepers process through every major city listing the names of the dead from the previous year; citizens light candles in windows for the deceased. In coastal cities, names of the drowned are written on dried kelp or salt-paper and floated to sea. The dead are said to walk close during Orantara. In practice, the holiday has developed regional carnival-adjacent traditions — Sangrea's Procesión de las Ánimas is partly this.
VELITHARA — The Long Walk Opening (Solvane 1) The official opening of the pilgrimage season. The Brothers of the Open Road plant a flowering Argen-Rush reed at every major waystone on the continent simultaneously at dawn — a logistical feat requiring months of advance coordination. Pilgrims who pass a waystone on Velithara take the reed-flower and press it into their prayer-codex; this is considered a minor blessing. In cities, a procession of the previous year's pilgrims walks the central streets to mark their return.
KETHIRAN — The Breaking Fast (last day of Sorvael) The largest communal feast of the year. Every household opens its doors; strangers are fed; debts are considered forgiven (the Church forbids debt-collection for three days around Kethiran; this is one of its few legally enforceable directives in post-imperial regions). The feast begins at sundown on Sorvael 30 and continues until the following evening. This is the most universally observed holiday on the continent — including among people who observe nothing else Lovist. In the Heartlands, the phrase "even at Kethiran" is used to mean something that happens without exception.
TRIAVAR — The Day of Founding (Umbranis 7) The anniversary of the three prophets' deaths — all three died within seven days of each other in the grove at Faithir, and Umbranis 7 is the central date around which the tradition crystallized. Each order observes it differently:
Ayanites: Public recitation of Aya's Scrolls in the central plaza of every city with an Ayanite court; the reading is open to all; any citizen may ask a question and receive a public answer
Ashanites: A healing vigil — Ashanite hospices open their doors completely, offering free treatment to anyone who arrives; donations are neither solicited nor refused
Alonites: A full day of public labor; roads repaired, streets cleaned, wells dug, water hauled for the elderly; no ceremony, only action
In former imperial cities, Triavar is the most visibly religious day of the year. Even in regions with complicated relationships with the Church (post-conquest resentment in Rosland, doctrinal disagreements in the Heartlands), the practical service of the Alonites on Triavar is broadly appreciated.

REGIONAL HOLIDAYS (Selected)
NIONIA
Vellium Founding Day (Velorim 12) — officially "the Day of Illumination"; the Pure Way's premier civil holiday; attendance at the Great Dome service is strongly implied; under Jous's regime, increasingly mandatory for public servants
The Marble Feast (Mordaen 3) — quarry workers' annual festival in the Marchia Ferrus; officially sanctioned but the Church is uncomfortable with its pagan roots (involves pouring wine on millstones and singing the Old Way quarry-songs — hymns to Pyrantha the craft-goddess that predate Loveism by centuries); the Cassian family funds it regardless
Twin Candles Night (Kethara 1) — domestic; families eat together with two candles burning at different heights; no formal religious content; persists in every class
THE HORNS
Storm-Sing (Umbranis, during the first winter storm — no fixed date) — the competitive singing festival; taverns compete for best performance; the champions hold informal cultural authority for the year; the storm that triggers it can be as early as Kethmir, as late as Velorim in mild years
The Bone Walk (Auranis 15, the Orantara tradition) — specifically the coastal version: names of the drowned written on salt-paper and floated with the outgoing tide at dawn; harbor lamps burn all night; fishing boats ring their bells on the hour
Pilot's Day (Telnavar 20) — the Pilots' Guild founding anniversary; all harbor fees waived for the day; the Guild's senior active pilot makes a ceremonial solo crossing of the main strait; enormous crowds; the day's only dangerous tradition is that young sailors traditionally attempt to follow the senior pilot's route in their own craft, with predictable results
SANGREA
Festival of the Red Grape (Vetharos 1-14) — the continent's largest annual festival; fourteen days in Castesol; corrida season; copla competitions; the House Solé opening gala; the tournament sponsored by House Terrarossa; enormous numbers of pilgrims
La Noche de los Campaneros (Mordaen 21) — midsummer bell night; every bell in Sangrea rung at midnight simultaneously for sixty seconds; the sound is reportedly audible fifty miles away when conditions are right; tradition holds that on this night you can hear bells from cities that no longer have bell towers — Fuentarossa's bell (destroyed in the Sunstone War) is said to ring from below the river
El Silencio de Sangreverde (Kethmir, anniversary of the Butcher's hanging) — one day per year in Sangreverde: no one speaks; not a Lovist observance, predating it; the one wholly secular regional tradition that even the Church declines to comment on
THE HEARTLANDS
The Silver Moot (Telnavar, election years) — three days of markets, fairs, and political theater surrounding the Argenlord election period; the busiest commercial stretch of the year; the famous saying "you can lie at the Silver Moot but the price still finds you" refers to the way false trade information during the Moot inevitably affects real contracts for the following year
Stonebridge Market (Solvane 15-Telnavar 8) — three weeks; the continent's largest inland trade fair; pilgrims, merchants, and pickpockets from every region; the Brothers of the Open Road maintain a permanent waystation here for medical emergencies; the most traded commodity is Heartlands grain futures
The Guild Tables (Auraval 1-7) — guild chapter feasts open simultaneously across every Heartlander city; foreign merchants are formally invited; the combination of alcohol, music, and favorable trade terms makes this the most efficient commercial week of the year
ROSLAND
The Night of the Twelve Fires (Umbranis solstice) — deepest winter solstice; twelve candles in every window; already established; the most beloved purely Roslandic tradition; older than Loveism, older than the empire, possibly older than the republic
Election Days (Velorim, every ten years) — the High Baron election period; muster-field gatherings at every town's Speaking Stone; fire-song vigils the night before the vote; a serious occasion that has developed its own festival character, particularly in Fairhaven where the election itself is public theater
First Salmon (Rychel/Telnavar, when the run begins) — no fixed date; when the first River-Salmon of the season are caught, the river-town that catches them flies a white banner, and the news travels by fire-song relay; the run's arrival is greeted by communal feasting; a pre-Lovist tradition the Church has never successfully claimed
RED COAST
The Water Festival (Mordaen solstice) — all qanat intake chambers opened simultaneously at dawn; the water flows higher and faster for that day; celebrations involve bathing in qanat-fed fountains and leaving copper offerings at water sources
Night Market Week (Concordis) — the one week per year when the Night Market of Alsiroth's Gate is openly acknowledged; even the city guard participates; Omar Sadiq traditionally makes it the year's most spectacular
Saffaren Trade Moon (Telnavar, full Teln night) — the Saffaren approach the desert edge for trade; no fixed location; the gathering migrates between known sites on a cycle that outsiders cannot predict; merchants who want access follow desert-guides or simply find nothing
THE FROZEN SOUTH
The Winter-Moot (Umbranis, Kjölfoss Deeps) — political, social, and religious simultaneously; the Auren Priests open and close with ceremony; already extensively documented
First Kill (Mordaen) — when the whale hunt season opens; each clan's first successful hunt; the Whaletooth Priests perform the Rite of First Cut; the entire community participates in the processing and receives a share
The Fire-Naming (Velorim, first Velisday) — children born in the previous year receive their true names sung into the fire-songs by their parents; the fire-singer witnesses; the name becomes part of the clan's living record at this moment
XARIA
Flower Wars Season (Solvane through Mordaen) — ritual combat season; governed by the T'zolk'in Calendar (see separate section); the mainland Velosi calendar is officially used for tributary purposes but internally the Xarian ten-count cycles take precedence
H'uun's Madness (five-day period in Concordis) — already established; carnival; the one time the Ashborn Day of Reversal is permitted
The Drowning Sun (Kethmir solstice) — already established; the wading-into-the-ocean festival at Bahia K'tharr
THE ISLE OF KNOWLEDGE
The Pale Bell Day (whenever a Grand Magos election is announced) — not a fixed date; when the Pale Bell rings, all work on the Isle ceases for the day; reading rooms close; the entire community gathers in the great hall; the election process begins the following morning
Charter Day (Velorim 20) — anniversary of the Charter of the Pale Reed (the Isle's founding document); a scholars' holiday with no religious content; the Deep Stacks are opened to all Circles; the Vault-Keeper is the only member of the Order excused from the general opening
PART FOUR: THE VETHORI — THE OLD NIONIAN GODS

THE PANTHEON OVERVIEW
The Vethori — "the Bright Ones" or "the Sovereign Powers" — were the gods of the Nionic Empire and, before it, the gods of the old Nionian city-states. They were not invented by the empire; the oldest Vethori hymns predate Nion I by at least six centuries. The empire formalized and codified them, deified Nion I into the pantheon (creating the awkward theology of a mortal who became divine in historical memory), and exported the religion to every conquered territory.
The Vethori were transactional gods. You did not pray to them for personal salvation; you traded with them. Sacrifice a white bull to Fortia before a battle, and Fortia's favor was yours until the next battle. Forget the offering, and you deserved what you got. This transactional theology made the Vethori popular with merchants, soldiers, and emperors — and made them incapable of competing with Loveism when Loveism promised something the Vethori never had: unconditional love.
By 1308 AF, the Old Way is formally extinct in the former imperial regions (outlawed by Nion XIII, physically destroyed by the Church). But remnants persist:
The quarry-songs of Nionia (hymns to Pyrantha that predate the empire by 300 years)
The road-offerings at mile-markers (old Viam habit that the Brothers of the Open Road haven't fully eliminated)
The harvest prayers to Copia in the Heartlander river communities
The sailor's private observances to Thalvex (hedging their bets; the Church turns a blind eye)

THE MAJOR VETHORI
NIONUS AXKE — Lord of Law, Empire, and the Sealed Road He was the chief god before he was also the deified Nion I. The original Nionus was a god of law-by-force — the law that comes not from consensus but from the power to enforce. His symbols: the iron wheel (the wheel of governance), the crossroads marker (all roads lead through him), the eagle clutching a law-scroll. His sacred color was deep imperial purple — the exact pigment that gave Nionian senatorial robes their distinctive look.
The theological awkwardness of deifying an actual historical figure into an existing deity was resolved by imperial theological decree: Nion I had not become Nionus Axke, but rather Nionus Axke had always been partially incarnate in the Nion bloodline, and the Conqueror's achievements were proof of divine will made visible. This reasoning satisfied no serious theologian and was never questioned by anyone with power, which is the characteristic quality of state religion.
His temple in Vellium — the Axkaren, the Hall of the Bound Law — was the largest building on Nionia before the Great Dome. Its ruins still exist; Jous used the foundation for the Pale House extension.
FORTIA — Goddess of War, Glory, and the Worthy Death Not a death goddess — Meravon held that position — but the goddess of war's glory specifically. Her concern was the quality of combat: courage shown, enemies met equally, the choice to stand when flight was possible. Cowardice was a theological offense to Fortia. Dying well in her service was the highest grace the Vethori offered.
Her symbols: the throwing spear (not the defensive pike — she was interested in aggression), the burning torch held downward (the torch that lights the way into battle, not home from it), the Gale-Kestrel (before the Horns sailors adopted it as a weather omen, it was Fortia's sacred animal — a bird that flies into storms).
She was painted with a scar across her left cheek in every depiction — not wound, but mark. The scar was present before any battle she appeared in. The theological interpretation: the worthy scar is one you have before you need it. Preparation over luck.
Her major festival was on Mordaen 6 — midsummer, the height of campaigning season. Gladiatorial games were officially her rites. Nion XIII abolished them.
COPIA — Goddess of Abundance, Commerce, and the Generous Sea Originally a sea deity — the benevolent ocean, the fish-bringing tide, the profitable voyage returned safely. Over centuries she expanded to encompass all abundance, and by the empire's peak she was as much a god of the marketplace as the harbor. Merchants swore by Copia when closing deals. Her temple was traditionally located at the waterfront's busiest point.
Her symbols: the cornucopia (specifically rendered in gold, not the agricultural produce inside it — Copia's gift was the vessel, not the contents, meaning the capacity to receive rather than the receiving itself), the diving pelican, the merchant's scale balanced perfectly. Unlike most of the Vethori, Copia was depicted smiling.
The phrase "Copia willing" for good commercial fortune persists in the Horns and Red Coast even in 1308 AF, where technically it should have been replaced by Lovist equivalents. The Brothers of the Open Road use it unself-consciously, which is a source of ongoing minor friction with the Ayanite order.
VIAM — God of Roads, Travelers, and the Safe Return A trickster-heretic figure by modern standards — but to the Nionian culture that produced him, he was simply the most practically useful of the gods. He protected travelers, but in a specific way: he did not protect them from danger; he made sure they knew where the danger was and had the speed to navigate around it. He was associated with cunning rather than power.
His symbols: the stone waymarker (every imperial mile-marker was technically his altar), sandals specifically (not boots, not bare feet — sandals, the traveler's footwear, the shoe that covers without enclosing), the written message. He was the god of accurate information.
The road-warden tradition — which predated the Brothers of the Open Road and gave them their institutional template — was a Viam cult in origin. The road-wardens left offerings at their mile-markers: oil, grain, a copper coin. The Brothers of the Open Road continued this practice for approximately 200 years after officially converting to Loveism, attributing it to "respect for the road's history" rather than theological persistence. By 1308 AF, only a handful of the oldest active Brothers still perform the offering, and they do it alone, before dawn.
MERAVON — God of the Honored Dead and the Dark Archive Not a frightening god — not threatening, not capricious. Meravon was the god of proper death: the death that was honored, recorded, and remembered. His concern was not dying but the treatment of the dead. A warrior killed in battle and properly buried was under Meravon's protection and care. A warrior killed and left unburied — or buried without ceremony, or denied last rites — was a theological catastrophe. Not for the dead man's soul, but for the living who had failed him.
His symbols: the black mirror (a mirror in which you can see the dead but not yourself), the sealed clay urn (properly closed, properly marked), the locked door. He was never depicted facing forward — all Meravon statues faced away, looking inward toward something visible only to him.
The Nionian funerary tradition — full record-keeping of the dead, proper ceremony, clan genealogies maintained — was a Meravon practice in origin. The Bonekeepers' tradition, which ostensibly operates within Loveism, preserves almost every element of Meravon's rites while replacing his theology with Lovist language. The Ashanite order quietly encourages this.
THALVEX — God of the Hostile Sea and the Unacceptable Horizon The dark mirror of Copia. Thalvex governed the ocean as it genuinely was — indifferent, violent, unconcerned with human survival. He was not evil; he simply did not care. The Grey Curtain was called "Thalvex's Breath" by Nionian sailors, and the description is more respectful than accusatory: this is simply what Thalvex does.
His symbols: the spiral shell (the nautilus — a form that draws inward to infinity), the anchor chain without an anchor (the chain that holds you but never reaches bottom), the drowned man (depicted not horribly but thoughtfully — a man descending through clear water, eyes open, not struggling). He was appeased rather than worshipped. Offerings before difficult crossings: wine poured off the stern, a piece of the ship's own timber burned on a small brazier and the ash scattered on the water.
Sailors who observe nothing else Lovist still pour wine off the stern. The Church has tried to rename this "an offering to Vena's deep waters" with limited success.
PYRANTHA — Goddess of Fire, Craft, and Transformation by Forge The goddess of making things. Her domain was any transformation by fire — forging, cooking, burning, illumination, purification. She was particularly associated with the moment when raw material became something else: iron becoming a blade, clay becoming a vessel, ore becoming metal. The transformation itself was sacred to her, not the finished object.
Her symbols: the double flame (two fires side by side — one to melt, one to shape), the hammer, the bellows. She was depicted with burns on her forearms — not wounds, but the casual marks of a craftsperson who works close to the fire and doesn't flinch from the occasional cost of that proximity.
The quarry-songs of Nionia are Pyrantha hymns that predate the empire by centuries. They survived the Nionic conquest, the imperial religious codification, the Age of Faith's conversion, and Jous Lorethian's Pure Way purge, because the quarry-workers simply kept singing them while officially converting to whatever religion was currently mandatory. They are work-songs. They match the rhythm of the hammer. Theology has nothing to do with it.
SELINDRA — Goddess of the Hunt, the Wild, and Aura-Moon She ran. In every depiction: running. Through forest, through night, through snow, through rain — she was always in motion and the motion was always away from cities. She was the god of the untamed, the unoccupied, the wilderness that the empire was always displacing.
Her symbols: the short recurve bow (not a war bow — a hunting bow, a single-purpose tool), the crescent shape of Aura-moon in its first quarter, the wolf. She was worshipped primarily in the frontier regions — Rosland, the mountains, the forest communities — long after the coastal cities had converted to Loveism or moved on to other things. The Frozen South has vestigial Selindra-adjacent traditions (the Frostguard's wolf-hide armor is partly a Selindra reference) though the southern clans would not recognize the name.
VELARAS — God of the Elder Sun and the Sovereign Light The male twin of Selindra in the oldest mythology, though they diverged significantly by the imperial period. Velaras was Velos's divine embodiment — the steady, organizing, warming sun-god. He was associated with clarity, with predictability, with the agricultural cycle's reliability. Not warm in the personal sense; warm in the way that sunshine is warm — impersonal, consistent, fundamentally indifferent to individual fate but structurally necessary for all life.
His symbols: the sunwheel (a circle divided into eight equal sections), the gold circlet (not a crown — a circlet, a ring of authority without a point of dominance), the rooster (because it announces Velos's arrival without fail). By the late empire, Velaras had been largely absorbed into the Nionus Axke theology — the steady administrative sun merged with the god of imperial law. The older temples to Velaras are architecturally distinct from imperial-era temples precisely because they predate the merger.
KEMVAR — God of Wine, Excess, Dream, and Creative Destruction The problematic one. The Vethori did not have an evil god, but they had a dangerous one. Kemvar was not malicious — but he was utterly uninterested in consequences. He was associated with wine, but more broadly with any altered state: intoxication, dream, artistic vision, madness, the dangerous edge of inspiration. The Venic Path mystics, who predate the ban and persist underground in 1308 AF, have deep folk-religion roots in Kemvar even though they frame their practice in Lovist language.
His symbols: the serpent eating its own tail (the Ouroboros — a symbol of recursion without progress, which was how the conservative Vethori clergy understood Kemvar's influence), the empty cup (drained, not yet refilled), the grapevine specifically in autumn (the harvest that must be crushed to become something else).
He was simultaneously the most popular god among common people and the most suppressed by the aristocracy. The Festival of Kemvar's Wake — a three-day carnival that preceded the grape harvest — was abolished by imperial decree approximately four times. It kept returning. In 1308 AF, elements of it survive in Sangrea's Festival of the Red Grape without anyone formally acknowledging the connection.
VORATH AND NETHIS — The Twin Serpents, Chaos and Order Not full deities but divine principles. Vorath and Nethis are depicted as two serpents coiled around each other — one black (Vorath, chaos, the unpredictable), one white (Nethis, order, the predictable). They are used primarily in oath-taking: to swear "by Vorath" means swearing that you will not betray (invoking chaos's witness against chaos); to swear "by Nethis" means swearing to honor an agreement (invoking order's witness for order). The paradox was intentional — Nionian oath theology held that the most trustworthy oaths invoke the principle that your violation would offend.
In the theological treatises of the later empire, Vorath and Nethis are described as the fundamental tension that preceded the creation of the gods themselves. Neither one wins; neither one can win. The world exists in the space between them.

PART FIVE: THE XARIAN FAITH

THE GREAT EXCHANGE
Everything has a price. Life is borrowed from the gods, used for its span, and returned. The return is the sacrifice. The sacrifice is not death — it is completion. K'tharr made the sun from his own blood; Ixchela made the river from her tears; the first humans were made from the blood of dead gods. To sacrifice is to participate in the mechanism that created the world. To refuse is to take without giving, which is the only true sin in the Xarian worldview.
This is not a metaphor. It is a description of how the world works.
The Ix'Atani Dominion has theologians who can argue the Great Exchange in any of seventeen intellectual frameworks. The temple-cities of Xaria have priests who can recite the Exchange's principles in seven formal registers. The Ya'ax warriors have a version that fits in three words. The Ashborn have a version they sing in the Hush that turns the theology completely inside out. All of them are, in some sense, correct.

THE IX'NAVAR — THOSE WHO WERE BEFORE THE RIVER
K'THARR — The Jaguar-Fire, Lord of the Sun's Hunger The primary god. He made the sun from his own burning body — tore himself open, placed his heart in the sky, and now the heart burns there. This is why the sun requires blood: because K'tharr is still alive in the sky, still giving, and the sacrifice is the acknowledgment that you understand this and that you reciprocate.
He is depicted as a jaguar made of fire — not metaphorically, but literally; every representation of K'tharr shows the form of a jaguar whose substance is flame. His spots are not spots but darker flames. He has no eyes in the conventional sense; where a jaguar's eyes would be, there are two points of white light.
He has two aspects: the Ascending K'tharr (rising sun, creative, generous, warmth-giving) and the Descending K'tharr (setting sun, destructive, demanding, diver-into-darkness). The transition between these aspects each day is the theological crux — the sun sets because K'tharr descends into the underworld to fight Amara-Utu's shadow-forces each night and rises again because he wins. The sacrifice fuels his strength for this battle. If the sacrifice stops, the sun does not rise one morning.
His priests wear jaguar-gold and crimson. His sacred animal is the jaguar. His sacrificial day is the summer solstice. His stone is black jade. The Scarlet Order are his warriors. His temple is the great Teocalli of Ix'Pal.
IXCHELA — The River-Mother, Lady of Healing and Transformation She did not make the river. She is the river. Ixchela wept when the world was made — at the beauty of it, at the cost of it, at all three simultaneously — and her tears became the Ix'za and the tributaries and all fresh water on the peninsula. This is why fresh water heals: because it is grief turned useful.
She is depicted as a woman with a serpent's lower body — not a monster, but an integration. The upper body is human and warm; the lower body is river-current, always moving, impossible to stop. She cannot be fully still. Even her statues are carved in motion.
She governs healing specifically in the sense of transformation: not restoration of what was but transformation into what can survive the loss. A healed wound does not look like the original skin; a grief worked through does not look like happiness; a river after a flood does not run the same channel. Ixchela is not interested in restoration. She is interested in continuation.
Her priests wear serpent-green and black. Her sacred animals are the river dolphin and the caiman. Her major observance is the River-Lotus ceremony at each new year of the T'zolk'in count. Her stone is white jade.
H'UUN — The Monkey-Trickster, Lord of the Crossroads Between H'uun made language. Before H'uun, the gods understood each other directly — thought to thought, necessity to necessity. H'uun introduced words, which meant he introduced the gap between meaning and expression, between intention and interpretation, between truth and performance. Every misunderstanding in the world traces back to H'uun's gift.
He is not apologetic about this. He finds it hilarious.
He is depicted as a spider-monkey in mid-leap — not sitting, never sitting, always in the moment between one branch and the next. His expression is always partially obscured: one hand often covers part of his face, one eye winking, or the image slightly blurred as if he moved just as it was drawn.
The five-day Madness Festival (H'uun's Madness, in Concordis) is his primary observance: masks, role-reversal, the Day of Inversion when Ashborn serve their masters and masters serve them. H'uun invented masks because he understood that the performance of a role sometimes reveals more truth than the role itself. He is the patron of performers, liars, diplomats, and anyone who navigates between two positions without fully committing to either.
No formal priesthood — those who practice trickery in sacred contexts are considered his servants by action rather than appointment. His sacred animal is the spider-monkey. His stone is obsidian that catches light unexpectedly.
AMARA-UTU — The Smoke-Between-Worlds, Lady of Memory and the Honored Dead She tends the dead between sacrifices. Not a death goddess — death is K'tharr's domain in the descent. Amara-Utu is the waiting: the space between dying and being received, between sacrifice and acknowledgment, between one incarnation and the next.
She is depicted as a vast serpent coiled around the world-tree — not threatening, not constricting, simply present. She is the permanence that the living achieve only temporarily. She remembers everything, which is her gift and her burden. She cannot forget. She holds the memory of every dead person, every dead creature, every dead moment. This is why she is also the god of grief: grief is the living's attempt to keep pace with what Amara-Utu holds always.
Her cult is the most intimate of the Xarian religions — practiced at the household level, in the domestic shrine, in the early morning before sunrise. Her offerings are not blood but food: the first portion of every meal is Amara-Utu's. She is fed before the living eat.
Her priests are always women. Her sacred animal is the anaconda. Her color is indigo — the deepest blue before black. Her stone is the dark core of bloodwood.
T'ZAL — The Deep Current, That Which Is Not Named T'zal is not worshipped. T'zal is acknowledged. The distinction is significant.
T'zal is the ocean beyond the reach of the Great Exchange — the open water where no sacrifice reaches, where K'tharr's light grows too thin to sustain the sacrificial economy, where Ixchela's tears have diluted past recognition into saltwater that cannot heal. T'zal is simply what exists beyond the gods' concern, which is not indifference on T'zal's part but a difference in kind. T'zal is not a person; T'zal is a condition.
Xarian sailors acknowledge T'zal before any deep-water voyage with a formula that translates roughly as: "We go where you are. We know it is not ours. We ask only that you notice us passing, not that you care." No offering is made; T'zal does not receive offerings. The acknowledgment is the entire ritual.
No priests, no temples, no images. Sailors know the acknowledgment formula. That is the entire religion of T'zal.
IX'CHA-KAN — The Corn-Blood, Lady of Agriculture and the Debt of Growth She is the reason food requires sacrifice. In Xarian cosmogony, the first crops grew from the blood of the dead — literally, the blood that fell from K'tharr's descent into the underworld nourished the first seeds. The soil still requires this. Every harvest has a component of return — the first fruits burned, a small blood offering at planting, the ash of sacrifice mixed into the seed-corn.
She is depicted as a woman carrying a bundle of maize that bleeds instead of being cut at the stalk. The blood feeds the earth. She is not a violent god — her expression is always one of deep calm, of someone performing a necessary task that must be done with acceptance rather than grief.
The Canal Guild's agricultural rites in the Ix'za delta are technically Ix'cha-Kan rites repurposed for hydraulic farming: the water is the blood, the qanat is the ritual vessel, the harvest acknowledges the offering.
Her priests are of all genders. Her sacred plant is maize. Her sacred animal is the heron — which stands in fields after harvest, eating what was left, completing the cycle. Her stone is blood-red obsidian.
VOROVAK — The Hunter's Debt, Lord of Necessary Violence K'tharr is war's glory; Vorovak is war's reality. He is the god of the hunt, of practical violence, of taking life in order to continue living. He is not celebrated. He is honored in the specific, serious way you honor a tool you depend on. Before every Ya'ax raiding party, before every hunt, Vorovak receives an acknowledgment: "We take what we need. We offer what we must. We do not take more." The last clause is binding. Taking more than necessary is offensive to Vorovak specifically — he is concerned with proportionality, not just acknowledgment.
He is depicted as a warrior with no face — or rather, with a different face on each image. The point: he looks like whoever is holding the weapon.
No formal temples — shrines at hunting grounds and battle preparation areas. His sacred animal is the black caiman. His stone is iron-red obsidian.
NEN-XIBAL — The Dream-Walker, Lord of the Space Between Sleeping and Waking He governs the threshold — not sleep itself (that is Ixchela's waters, where the dreaming body flows) but the specific moment of passing through, the hypnagogic threshold, the place where the waking self has not yet become the dreaming self. Nen-Xibal inhabits that gap. He communicates from it.
The Cascabella's patron deity. Their use of Dreamroot and the deeper Bonewater compounds is not recreational — it is an attempt to extend the threshold state, to widen the gap where Nen-Xibal is available. The Cascabella's intelligence operations, their poison-making, and their oracular practice are all Nen-Xibal rites in origin.
He is depicted as a figure that is partially transparent — you can see the room behind him through his chest. One eye is open; one is closed. He is always shown in profile, never fully visible.
His priests are called dream-keepers. His sacred plant is Dreamroot. His sacred animal is the owl. His stone is moonstone — specifically the milky kind that seems to glow from inside.
THE UNNAMED ONE — Supreme, Unknowable, Beyond the Exchange The Ix'Atani Dominion's highest theological concept — not worshipped, not acknowledged (that's T'zal's territory), not named (because naming is H'uun's domain and implies something knowable). The Unnamed One is the totality from which the IX'Navar emerged. The other gods exist because the Unnamed One is too large to be approached directly; the gods are, in Dominion theology, the aspects of the Unnamed One that have become small enough to negotiate with.
The Dominion's metropolitan high priests alone hold doctrines about the Unnamed One's nature, transmitted orally, never written. The Vizier of Xaria knows the first three doctrines (standard for Dominion nobility). The Xarian peninsula's temple-priests know only that the Unnamed One exists and that everything they do is in its broad awareness, which is sufficient for the practical management of the Great Exchange.
No symbols, no animal, no stone, no ritual, no prayer. Simply: it is there. The sacrifice ultimately goes to it, passing through K'tharr, Ixchela, and the others on the way.

THE T'ZOL'KIN PARALLEL CALENDAR
The Xarian peninsula operates on a parallel calendar system inherited from the Ix'Atani Dominion — the T'zol'kin, a 260-day ritual count that runs simultaneously with and independently of the 360-day Velosi year. Each day in the T'zol'kin has a specific deity association, a sacrificial requirement, and an omen quality. The two calendars converge on the same starting day once every 52 years — the Calendar Round completion, which is the most significant event in Xarian religious time.
The T'zol'kin governs:
When Flower Wars may be fought (specific T'zol'kin days only)
When major sacrificial cycles begin and end
When children are named (name-day determines which deity's qualities they carry)
When rulers may take or leave office
When specific crops may be planted
The continental Velosi calendar is used for tributary reporting to the Dominion and for communication with mainland merchants. Internally, the T'zol'kin governs everything. The disconnect between the two systems is a persistent administrative headache for the Vizier's court, which operates in both simultaneously.

