PART ONE: LANGUAGE AND REGIONAL VOICE

MUNNISH — THE CONTINENTAL TONGUE
The imperial lingua franca, derived from Nionian dialect and spread by conquest. By 1308 AF it is the only language for commerce, law, scholarship, and formal correspondence across the former empire. Every educated person speaks it. Every common person who trades speaks it. Underneath it, in every household and every village and every back-alley argument, regional languages and dialects persist — sometimes as dying tongues, sometimes as living parallel systems.
The neutral register — a simplified, accent-reduced Munnish developed by merchants for cross-regional trading — has its own character: shorter sentences, verb-initial constructions for clarity, number-focus, minimal subjunctive, no honorifics. A Heartlander grain-factor and a Red Coast copper-merchant using neutral register sound like the same flat instrument played in different tunings.

NIONIA
Speech patterns:
Formal subjunctive maintained even in casual speech: "Were it the case that you needed..." / "Should you find occasion..."
Sentence-final declarative particles: sì vedi (yes, you see) — filler that means the speaker is pausing to gauge whether the listener understands
Emotional states described through their physical effects, not named: "my chest became heavy when he said it" rather than "I was sad"
Questions phrased as observations: "One supposes the deliveries have been delayed" rather than "Have the deliveries been delayed?"
Under the Pure Way, the word puro (pure) has been politically contaminated; Nionians who want to say something is genuine now use chiaro (clear) instead; a small but legible resistance signal
Numbers in market speech rounded toward whole units: never "fourteen coppers" but "a dozen and the rest" — precision feels anxious, approximation feels confident
Past heroism referenced with present tense: "Nion walks into the Senate chamber and locks the doors" — history made immediate
Oaths and profanity:
Thal'fondo — "Thalvex's depths" — panic, deep trouble; a sailor's curse
Per Mera — "by Meravon" — a genuine oath about death and proper burial; taken seriously even by people who've converted
Kemvar te prenda — "may Kemvar take you" — someone whose loose tongue caused problems
Mani bianche — "white hands" — someone who performs Pure Way compliance for social gain; deeply contemptuous
La Luce non ti conosce — "the Light does not know you" — the Domus Lux formal execution declaration, now used sarcastically among resisters to mean someone is irrelevant
Figlio della pietra — "son of the stone" — quarry insult; means someone hard-headed and unyielding to reason (can be positive depending on tone)
Voce di Kemvar — "Kemvar's voice" — someone talking nonsense, drunk-philosophizing
Idioms and sayings:
"Il marmo ricorda" — "the marble remembers" — nothing is truly erased; used when someone thinks their actions have been forgotten
"Aspetta il secondo sole" — "wait for the second sun" — be patient; Keth rises after Velos
"Chiaro come l'Albara" — "clear as the Albara" — the river is perpetually chalky from quarry runoff; this means not clear at all; ironic
"Costruire sul vivo" — "building on the living" — doing something that will outlast you
"La pietra buona non chiede il coltello" — "good stone doesn't need the chisel" — people of quality reveal themselves without being cut open
"Canta il marmo, piange il ferro" — "marble sings, iron weeps" — Nionia and Rosland; the old rivalry expressed in material
"Pesare le parole" — "to weigh your words" — speak carefully; a warning
"Il porto non chiede il tuo nome" — "the harbor doesn't ask your name" — the docks are neutral; you can start over
What they call outsiders:
Terraschi — mainlanders (from terra, land); neutral, slightly diminishing
Asciutti — "the drys" — people who don't understand the sea
Grigi — "the greys" — Roslandic iron-workers; skin color connotation from forge-soot

THE HORNS
Speech patterns:
Sentences cut to minimum: "Wind's east. Not sailing today." Full stops are economical.
Weather used as verb: "It's weathering in" — trouble is coming; "weathered through" — survived something
Directions are cardinal/harbor-relative, never left/right: "harbor-side of the building," "wind-side door"
Insults delivered as matter-of-fact observations: not "you're an idiot" but "that's a pilot's error from a man who's never piloted" — devastating because specific
Diminutives to indicate contempt: "the little captain" said to someone who commanded a vessel badly
Long silences mid-conversation are comfortable; the Horns regard filling silence as a kind of social weakness
Information exchanged in exchange: answering a question with a question is not evasion, it's establishing whether you're owed the information
Oaths and profanity:
"Gale take it" — mild frustration
"Thalvex's fucking Galewater" — severe frustration; invokes the most hostile sea passage
"Knotless" — someone incompetent; a sailor who can't tie knots is useless
"Fog-blind" — someone who can't see what's obvious; also used as "you're fogged" for confusion
"The Reef has you" — you're in serious trouble with no good exit; from the Corsair's Teeth
"Bone Walk weather" — a day when everything goes wrong; from the storm conditions during the Bone Walk ceremony
"Three-knot work" — something done badly; a rope secured with only three knots is not secured
Idioms and sayings:
"Reads the tide or reads the ruin" — you either understand your situation or suffer for it; no middle position
"Salt earns salt" — you get what you put in; also specifically: work earns pay, don't expect charity
"The pilot doesn't ask who built the ship" — do your job; the cause of a problem is less important than solving it
"Fathoms below the charter" — far outside acceptable behavior; also used approvingly: "he drinks fathoms below the charter" — heroically
"Knotted right" — done correctly, with care; the highest compliment for practical work
"Light at Garrun Keep" — something reliable; the Garrun Lantern has never gone out
"Brinehold advice" — advice that benefits the advisor more than the advised
"The tide doesn't beg" — inevitability; also: don't waste time arguing with facts
What they call outsiders:
Drylanders — all non-Horns people; universal, slightly contemptuous
Stone-eaters — inland people who don't understand the sea (from imagining they eat rock)
Soft-knotters — specifically Heartlanders; their rope and knotwork is considered inferior

SANGREA
Speech patterns:
Present tense for past narrative: "So the man walks in, right? He says nothing. He just stands there." History told as if happening now
Precise geographic reference even in casual speech: not "somewhere in the valley" but "third terrace of the Velazco side, the one facing the sunrise"
Hombre / mujer as universal address, then immediate first-name informality; no middle register
End-of-statement uptalk that invites confirmation: "It's nothing, isn't it? Nothing at all."
Anger expressed through becoming quieter and more specific; shouting is considered common
Gossip in third person even about the speaker: "A person hears things in certain houses—"
Con sangre (with blood) = something done with genuine effort and cost: "He built that hacienda with blood"
The word peso (weight) for anything with serious consequence: "that marriage has real peso"
Oaths and profanity:
"Que te lleve el río" — "may the river take you" — serious curse; the river is Ixchela's and this invokes death by sacred water
"Sangre vieja" — "old blood" — insult; too traditional, inflexible, refusing progress
"Campanas corriendo" — "bells running" — someone talking too much and giving away information
"Cagada de loro" — "parrot shit" — something worthless or annoying; mild
"Cascabella en el vino" — "Cascabella in the wine" — something hidden and deadly in something pleasant
"Por el río rojo" — "by the red river" — a genuine oath; invoking the Fuente's color carries weight
"El toro no perdona" — "the bull doesn't forgive" — consequence is coming regardless of regret
Idioms and sayings:
"El loro repite, el maestro piensa" — "the parrot repeats, the master thinks" — about the difference between information and wisdom
"Cada campana tiene su lengua" — "every bell has its tongue" — everyone has their own way of saying things; also: you can identify the campanero by how they ring
"La vid no crece hacia el cielo" — "the vine doesn't grow toward the sky" — ambition needs to be grounded; also used to mean: what you want won't come if you only look up
"Cuentas claras, amistad larga" — "clear accounts, long friendship" — settle debts promptly; combining commerce and relationship
"El sol no pide permiso" — "the sun doesn't ask permission" — truth arrives on its own schedule
"Sangre caliente, pie frío" — "hot blood, cold feet" — someone passionate but afraid to act
"Sombra de casa ajena" — "shade from someone else's house" — living off others' work or protection; contemptuous
What they call outsiders:
Los Grises — "the Greys" — Roslandic and Heartlanders; colorless, too serious
Norteños — "northerners" — anyone north of the Silver Mountains; all the same to a Sangrean
Piedra-Fría — "cold stone" — specifically Heartlanders; reference to the Silver Mountains' color

THE HEARTLANDS
Speech patterns:
Formal register maintained in all public speech; dropping formality is a deliberate signal of intimacy or insult
"It is said" / "the record holds" for inherited knowledge vs. personal observation; the distinction matters legally
Silver metaphors saturate the language: "pure silver" = something genuine; "grey silver" = adequate; "river silver" = barely worth having
Conditional politeness in requests: "Should you find it convenient..." / "Were you inclined to consider..."
Merchant class uses trade-pidgin influence: shorter sentences, verb-initial for clarity
"The bridge holds" — this is stable, you can trust it
Class is legible in grammar: the laboring poor speak direct declarative; minor merchants speak conditional; nobility speak subjunctive and elaborate
Emotional content delivered through administrative language: "The situation has become difficult" = something is breaking my heart
Oaths and profanity:
"Stonebridge toll" — paying an unexpected, unfair cost
"Marvoss-work" — something done that will be punished; betrayal building; from the family drowned at the bridge
"By the Argen's mouth" — a genuine oath; the Argen meeting the sea is where things end
"Silver-blind" — someone who can't think past wealth and status; someone whose greed is their whole personality
"Grain-rot" — something that seemed good but is corrupting from inside
"Below the Vaultkeeper's ledger" — not worth accounting for; worthless
"Unbridge it" — fix the damage you've caused; rebuild what you destroyed
Idioms and sayings:
"Grain before silver" — practical survival before prestige; also: don't invest what you need to eat
"The barge went through before you asked" — you missed the opportunity through hesitation
"Even the Argen floods once" — even reliable things have limits; also: even patient people reach their end
"Compact hands, empty stomach" — bureaucratic competence that doesn't deliver results; the specific failure of the Argenlord system
"Count the rings before you cut" — understand what you're dealing with before you commit
"Silver thread in common cloth" — something of genuine quality in an ordinary context; a surprise worth noting
"Written in the river" — already decided, not reversible; like writing in water it will disappear but the decision is made
What they call outsiders:
Edgefolk — people from the periphery regions (Rosland, Horns, Red Coast); not contemptuous, slightly patronizing
Saltborn — coastal people; anyone whose primary orientation is the sea
Stone-blooded — mountain people (Roslandic, Vallan)

ROSLAND
Speech patterns:
States the negative: "It isn't bad" rather than "it's good"; "he doesn't lie much" rather than "he's honest"
Time is seasonal, not calendrical: "since before last harvest" / "two winters past" / "when the First Salmon ran"
Names not used in direct address among equals; you learn someone's name but don't use it to their face except in exceptional intimacy or exceptional insult
Very direct about death and illness; circumlocution about dying is considered a childish insult
"He carried his weight" — did their share; the highest compliment
Emotional declarations are private; expressing feeling in public is a kind of nakedness; content delivered through action
Sentence rhythm often ends on the verb, surviving from older grammar: "The iron, when the cold bites, harder it gets"
Collective nouns for actions: "the cohort went to work" even when talking about one person; individual accomplishment framed as group effort
Oaths and profanity:
"Daudr-vás" — "dead-wood" — something useless, petrified, no longer living; also a person who refuses to change
"Down the shaft" — into serious trouble; from mining
"Koschei's nail" — something impossibly hard to find or fix
"The wolf doesn't know your name" — you're nothing; you don't matter
"Morozko's smile" — something that looks pleasant but will kill you; frozen danger
"Zhivka's burning" — pushed past your limit; the grain-spirit burning your throat as metaphor
"Broken fire-song" — a fundamental betrayal; the worst possible insult
Idioms and sayings:
"The forge doesn't care about the ore's feelings" — the process demands what it demands
"A kolpak for every weather" — be prepared; also: practical concerns first
"The banya doesn't keep secrets" — whatever happens in the bathhouse will be known; gossip always circulates
"Iron at the core, wood at the face" — tough inside, presentable outside; how a good Roslandic person presents
"Even Fairhaven sleeps" — even busy places have quiet moments; wait for the right time
"Count your fire-songs before winter" — know your resources before you need them
"The Daudrwood doesn't negotiate" — some forces don't respond to reason; flee or fight
"He sang Maren's verse at the end" — he resisted at great cost; from the Maren of the Broken Cup legend
What they call outsiders:
Softers — anyone from a warmer climate; mild contempt; too comfortable
The Silver Folk — Heartlanders; reference to the silver rivers
Sun-Kissed — Sangrean; not always contemptuous; sometimes envious

VALLAN
Speech patterns:
Precision as cultural default: not "across the valley" but "four leagues by the eastern road past the Kaltbach junction"
Hospitality performed with specific required phrases: "The road is behind you now" on arrival; "may the pass hold" on departure; skipping these is a serious breach
Fourteen words for grades of mountain pass and road quality; casual speech references these constantly
Questions answered in full: half-answers are considered rude; if you ask a Vallanaise what time it is, they'll tell you the time, the weather affecting the journey, and whether the pass will be open
Strong silence tradition around the dead; a death is acknowledged with a hand placed briefly on the nearest person's arm; no words
The word ordnung (borrowed from Alpine-adjacent dialect) for the specific feeling of things being correctly arranged; used as both noun and adjective
Oaths and profanity:
"Kaltbach-cold" — someone who feels no warmth, no connection; the coldest thing in Vallan is the gorge water
"The pass is closed" — this conversation is over; a very final statement
"Bridge-belly" — someone who collects tolls and gives nothing back; a parasite; pointed relevance regarding Morvayn
"Llama-stubborn" — someone who absolutely will not move on a position; the Sternmark llamas are legendary for this
"Schlechtes Fundament" — "bad foundation" — something built incorrectly from the start; also a person with bad values
"By the Dawnbreak" — a genuine oath taken at altitude; the most serious Vallanaise oath
Idioms and sayings:
"The road-tax is fair; the avalanche is not" — you can work with human-made systems; you cannot negotiate with natural disaster
"A good bridge needs no sign" — quality speaks for itself
"Obstler for the summit, water for the road" — celebration is for achievement, not anticipation
"The llama knows the weather better than the shepherd" — trust those who are directly affected; listen to the one with more to lose
"Kaltbach cheese gets better with darkness" — some things require patience and isolation to become what they should be
"Vallan keeps its roads; Vallan keeps its soul" — infrastructure as cultural identity
"The mountain doesn't care if you're tired" — external demands are indifferent to your state; irrelevant to argue
What they call outsiders:
Talleute — "valley people" — lowlanders who don't understand altitude
Flachdenker — "flat-thinkers" — people without mountains in their mental landscape
Weglosige — "roadless ones" — people who don't maintain their infrastructure

THE RED COAST
Speech patterns:
Proverbs delivered as self-evident facts, not quotations: "Water finds its level" said the way mainlanders say "obviously"
Hospitality formulae are not optional: "Beitak beitak / Ma'ak ma'ak" (My house is your house / My water is your water) on entry; "Sharraftani" (You have honored me) on departure
Past tense in blessings and curses to make them accomplished: "May you have found water" = I bless your journey; "May your wells have run dry before you found me" = serious curse
The word al-maa' (the water) appears in metaphors constantly: "his word has water" = trustworthy; "dry counsel" = advice from someone who doesn't understand
Indirect approach to personal questions about finances: direct questions about wealth are rude; you learn what someone has by what they offer
Age and experience acknowledged publicly before any substantive conversation: "I speak as one who has traveled this route four times" is required framing, not boasting
Oaths and profanity:
"T'zal take you east" — deep water and no return; the worst direction
"May your well go dry" — the worst curse; can ruin a relationship permanently
"Sand in your eyes" — you're not seeing things clearly; mild dismissal
"Qanat-blind" — someone who doesn't understand the systems they depend on; used for political naïveté
"Your salt has turned" — you've become worthless or corrupted; can't be used for what you were meant for
"Khorim's edge" — sharp but brittle; brilliance that will break; not always an insult
Idioms and sayings:
"The deepest qanat is dug by the thirstiest hands" — necessity produces effort
"Copper in the eye, iron in the fist" — look beautiful, act decisively
"The desert remembers every footstep" — nothing is truly private or forgotten in a desert community
"Even the Saffaren rest at the well" — everyone has their limits
"One share of water, one share of decision" — authority should track contribution and risk equally
"A mirror-flash lasts a second; the message lasts a generation" — the medium is brief; the content matters
"Red salt, red knowledge" — the things of the desert are harsh but real
What they call outsiders:
Al-Bakhariyya — "the sea people" — anyone coastal or maritime; used for Nionians and Horns folk
Al-Farandj — "the distant ones" — a generic term for mainlanders unfamiliar with desert customs; from an old Dominion-era trade term
Ghurabaʼ — "the strangers" — travelers with no established relationship; neutral to contemptuous depending on context

THE FROZEN SOUTH
Speech patterns:
Staccato rhythm; complex emotion in few words; "The hunt was good. Twelve years since a hunt that good." is a speech about grief and joy and mortality
Animal comparisons: fox-clever, bear-stubborn, glacier-patient, seal-fat (comfortable, well-fed; not an insult)
Second person avoided: "one does" rather than "you do"; "a person might find" rather than "you'll find"
Boasting as understatement: "I've seen a few Glacier Bears" from someone with seventeen kills
Emotional declarations private; public emotional content delivered through action; if you want to say you love someone in the Frozen South, you bring them the best portion of the whale-kill for six consecutive hunts
Fire-song cadence bleeds into everyday speech: three-beat rhythm in narrative, preserved from a lifetime of singing
The word skál (used before drinking) carries enough meaning to count as an entire speech of respect and acknowledgment
Oaths and profanity:
"Broken fire-song" — borrowed into their speech; fundamental betrayal
"Ice in the marrow" — cowardice; the coldest kind
"Gold and gravel" — something that looks valuable but isn't; a fraud
"The mountain doesn't hear you" — your threats mean nothing; scale comparison
"Bjálki's beard" — humiliation; from the shaved Bearclaw chief; to be Bjálki-faced is to have lost everything
"Winter-dead" — someone who should have been cut loose but wasn't; a burden that's been kept too long
"Aurax-soft" — ironic; someone who uses gold where iron is needed; too reliant on wealth
Idioms and sayings:
"The fire-songs know what the fire-singer has forgotten" — tradition preserves things the individual loses
"A glacier moves" — even the slowest things move; patience will be rewarded
"The seal doesn't ask the bear for permission" — act; don't wait for those who would stop you to agree
"One fire-song, one grave" — each person matters; also used as a threat: I will remember what you did
"The whale knows the ocean better than the ship" — trust the creature adapted to the environment
"Gold is heavy" — wealth is a burden as well as a resource; the Aurax are heavy
"First kill, full moot" — early action establishes position; the first to strike in negotiation sets the terms
What they call outsiders:
Mainwalkers — anyone who lives on the flat land beyond the mountains
Softground — specifically Roslandic border people; contemptuous but also slightly nervous; they have iron
The Warm — Sangrean and Red Coast people; not contemptuous; the cold-tolerance is a source of subtle pride

XARIA
Speech patterns:
Multiple honorific registers carried into Munnish as a habit; formality signals simultaneous social calculation
Numbers in multiples of twenty from vigesimal heritage: "four-score and five" rather than "eighty-five"
The prefix ix' (sacred weight of) added to anything of genuine significance: ix'truth, ix'debt, ix'name
Colors as adjectives borrowed from Xarian vocabulary: jade-true = something of genuine value; blood-bright = something whose beauty masks danger
Death discussed directly; Xarians find mainland euphemisms for dying slightly amusing
Questions answered with questions first: "Why would you need to know that?" is not evasion; it's establishing what context you're owed
First person rarely used in formal speech; the self is spoken of obliquely: "One finds oneself" rather than "I find myself"
Oaths and profanity:
"K'tharr unlit" — the sun failing; the worst possible thing
"Ashborn-blind" — someone who can't see what's in front of them; also quietly used as a compliment within Ashborn communities (to be unseen is to be safe)
"The Exchange is broken" — something is fundamentally wrong; a relationship, a deal, a principle
"Hollow sacrifice" — an act performed without genuine intention; hypocrisy; the worst thing you can call someone's devotion
"H'uun's gift" — a lie told so well it became true; ambivalent; can be a compliment or a condemnation
"River-dry" — Ixchela's absence; said of someone without compassion or tears
Idioms and sayings:
"The caiman sleeps where the river fattens" — prosperity breeds complacency breeds danger
"Every sacrifice feeds something" — nothing is wasted; suffering has meaning if you're paying attention to what it feeds
"The feather falls last, the stone first" — the powerful are immediately affected; the subtle linger
"H'uun made language; the rest is H'uun's fault" — all misunderstandings trace to the same source
"A jade face and an obsidian heart" — beautiful on the outside, deadly within; highest-level insult
"The temple grows from the same earth as the grave" — sacred and dangerous are the same ground
What they call outsiders:
Ix'menos — "the uncounted" — people outside the Great Exchange; those who don't sacrifice; mainland Lovist types
Sal-boca — "salt-mouths" — people who eat preserved food rather than fresh; an old contempt for mainland diet
K'aak'al — "those without colors" — people who wear drab clothing; a genuine aesthetic judgment

PART TWO: DAILY LIFE BY CLASS AND REGION

CONTINENTAL CLASS FRAMEWORK
The Laboring Poor — farmhands, mine-workers, dockworkers, quarry-crews, river-laborers. Earn 3-6 Copper Scales per day. Own clothes, tools, perhaps bedding. Rent everything else.
The Skilled Craftsperson / Guild Member — smiths, weavers, carpenters, rope-makers, pilots, apothecaries. Earn 12-25 Scales per day. Own house, tools, small savings. Political rights in Rosland; guild voice elsewhere.
The Merchant Middle — ship captains, factors, successful traders, inn-keepers with multiple properties. Net worth 200-2000 Silver Weights. Own property; employ staff. No hereditary title; enormous practical power.
The Minor Court — lesser noble houses, estate managers (mayorazgo, capostrada), master-guild dynasties. Net worth 1000-8000 Silver Weights. Small households, local authority, marriages into and out of the lower nobility.
The Major Nobility — ducal houses, lord-patrons, great houses. Income 2000-10,000 Silver Weights annually. Dozens to hundreds in household. Armies, courts, institutional power.
Clergy — radically variable; a wandering Alonite mute owns nothing and sleeps where hospitality offers; a cathedral-chapter Ayanite lives like minor nobility; a senior Ashanite hospice administrator lives like a merchant middle.

NIONIAN DAILY LIFE
The Laboring Poor — Quarry-Worker, Dockhand, Terraces-Fisher
Before dawn: woken by the Pure Way cantus from the Great Dome, which carries across the city at dawn. This is not comfortable. Attendance at the dawn prayer is officially encouraged; practically mandatory for public employees; deliberately ignored by dock-workers who start work before the prayer ends.
Morning meal: bianco stagno — white bean stew with salt cod, eaten from an earthenware bowl with a hunk of dark bread. In the Marchia Ferrus, krovany pane (blood-and-grain cake) from the Roslandic migrant tradition has crossed over into quarry-worker diet. Water from the nearest cistern. Ashleaf pipe if you have one; the cheapest personal luxury on the island.
Work: marble quarry shifts run from dawn to two hours before sunset. Mine shifts are different — underground light is artificial, so Marchia Ferrus miners work six-hour rotations. Dock-work follows the tides. The Pure Way's new labor regulations require a mid-day prayer break of thirty minutes; this has been incorporated into shift schedules as unpaid time, which has not improved the regime's popularity.
Evening: teglia from a street vendor — 3-4 Scales for the basic; 5-6 for the version with anchovy and onion, which is the one worth eating. Eaten standing up or seated on steps. The taverns open at dusk: La Foschia and Tre Marmi in the Colonnade district for the higher-end crowd; Il Tempo Vuoto near the Pale House for people waiting for family members to be released from detention.
Leisure: Palla Rossa in alleys and squares — the street ball game; officially restricted by the Pure Way but enforcement is uneven; a game in progress in a narrow Terraces alley is one of the island's persistent small acts of resistance. Dice. The lamento singers start after midnight in certain dockyard taverns — uncensored songs, old songs, songs the Pure Way doesn't allow in daylight.
Sleeping: shared rooms of four to eight in tenement blocks. The buildings lean. The walls are thin. Everyone knows their neighbors' business.
The Merchant Middle — Factors, Ship-Agents, Minor Dealers
Home: a three-or-four-room apartment in the upper Colonnade fringe or above a warehouse. Stone floors, whitewashed walls, one good piece of furniture — usually an imported wood table or a shelf of colored glass panels from the Antheon glass-blowers, which cast warm light in the evenings and signal that you are doing well.
Social life: the tavola della piazza — a specific table at a specific café or tavern that a merchant effectively rents by showing up every day at the same time. This is where business happens. The Pure Way has complicated this because tavole della piazza became informal resistance spaces; some have been explicitly broken up; others have relocated to private homes.
Dress: white fabric where possible but not ostentatious; the line between demonstrating compliance with Pure Way aesthetic and performing it like a convert-for-status is legible to everyone on the island. A simple white-trimmed linen collar says "I'm being reasonable." An entirely white outfit says "I want something from someone in authority."
The Noble Household — Minor House, Colonnade
The courtyard: the heart of any Nionian patrician home. A marble fountain that is the household's most visible status object — the sound of running water as wealth-signal. Bougainvillea trained along walls, a lemon tree in the corner, cats that belong to everyone and no one. This is where morning correspondence is handled, where guests are received, where the family eats in good weather.
Meals: three courses at minimum; the first always involves something from the sea (anchovy paste, pickled octopus, small fish in oil); the second is the main protein (lamb, pork, or the expensive fish — sea bass, gilt-head bream); the third is sweet (honey pastry, fresh fruit, the marmara dolce that the patricians serve to show they can afford even stones made delicious). Wine mixed with water; drinking it straight is done only to demonstrate that you've reached a level of comfort where appearances no longer matter.
Under the Pure Way: the patrician household performs compliance while maintaining private non-compliance. The old portraits (realistic, republican, depicting senators who are now officially unpeople) are turned to face the wall but not burned — that would be too final a surrender. The lamento singers still perform in the inner courtyards after the Domus Lux shift changes.

SANGREAN DAILY LIFE
The Laboring Poor — Vineyard Worker, Field Hand, Canal Laborer
Rhythm: nothing important happens between noon and late afternoon. This is physiological as much as cultural — the heat in the valleys during high summer genuinely prevents sustained outdoor work. Dawn to noon: field work, harvest, irrigation. Noon to late afternoon: shelter, sleep, the children's lesson if there's an Alonite school nearby. Late afternoon until dark: more work, or market, or the plaza.
Morning: migas — fried stale breadcrumbs with garlic, olive oil, and whatever vegetable scraps are available. Served in the same iron pan it was made in. Eaten quickly. Strong, dark coffee if there's a trader nearby; otherwise the local herb infusion.
The plaza: every Sangrean village has one. The actual living room. Disputes resolved here, gossip traded here, the campanero announces the time here, children play here, old men sit and watch everything here. The social life of the village is conducted in the open because closing your door means you're hiding something.
Evening: late, by mainland standards. Dinner rarely before two hours after dark. The family meal is the event of the day — everything consumed together, talking constantly. The food is the occasion; the occasion is not the food.
Entertainment: the corrida season means nothing in the laboring class except the free day when the hacienda lord pays for the corrida seats. The copla tradition is genuine here — working songs during the harvest, courtship songs at the plaza, the political coplas circulated on folded paper that the campaneros officially don't deliver but sometimes do.
The Minor Nobility — Provincial Lord, Second-House Vassal
The hacienda: a manor surrounded by working land. The distinction between the family's living quarters and the working infrastructure is porous — you hear the wine-press from the dining room; you smell the barn in the east wing on a warm night. This is not considered unpleasant; it means the estate is functional.
The mayorazgo: the estate manager, not a noble, not a servant. Knows the land better than the lord. Manages the actual operations. The relationship between lord and mayorazgo is complex — dependency flows both ways; the mayorazgo could ruin a lord by going to a rival house, and the lord could destroy a mayorazgo's family by accusation. Most of these relationships are functional because both parties understand the mutual leverage.
Entertainment: the regional lord's court is the entertainment. Tournaments, which are partly martial practice and partly theatrical performance and partly political positioning. Card games — La Sombra Dorada, played with painted sunstone-colored tiles. Patronage of a copla singer, which is a status marker almost as significant as tower-height.

ROSLANDIC DAILY LIFE
The Laboring Poor — Miner, Charcoal-Burner, Forest-Worker
Dawn: krovny khleb — dark rye bread with rendered fat and a scraping of smoked fish. Zhivka-kasha if it's cold enough — porridge made with a small amount of grain spirit instead of water; this is genuinely warming and slightly intoxicating first thing in the morning, which the mine-owners have decided to stop caring about because the alternative is workers who can't function in subzero temperatures.
The mine shift: six-hour rotations underground; the Forge-Guard keeps shift order. Coming up from the shaft into winter air is physically brutal — the temperature difference can cause coughing fits that last minutes. Veteran miners learn to come up slowly, lingering in the shaft's warmth.
The banya: the communal bathhouse is not a luxury, it is an institution. A proper banya visit (steam room, cool plunge, repeat) happens at minimum once a week for every Roslandic person who can access one. More significant: business is conducted in the banya. The tradition that no weapons enter means the banya is neutral ground. Minor agreements are made, disputes resolved, and information exchanged in the steam.
Evening entertainment: fire-song practice. This is not formal — it's the same way other cultures might hum or sing idly; Roslandic people maintain their fire-song repertoire as casual habit, not ceremony. The communal hall at the mine-camp or village center hosts guild-meeting evenings that look like card games (Zhelezko, the iron disc game) but are also political caucuses.
The domovoi shrine: every Roslandic home, however poor, has one — a small carved wooden figure, or a stone, or simply a marked space near the hearth. The first portion of any meal set aside for the domovoi. Not religious in any Lovist sense; the Church has tried to absorb it; it remains stubbornly itself.
The Skilled Craftsperson — Master Smith, Guild Member
Guild-mark pride: every master craftsperson in Rosland stamps their work with their personal mark. The collection and identification of master-marks is a genuine art-appreciation tradition — a collector might have a shelf of small objects specifically chosen for the quality and rarity of their maker's mark. A smith whose mark is collected is a smith who has arrived.
The guild hall: stone, heavy-timbered, heated by a central forge that is also the building's functional heart. The main room is simultaneously a social club, a labor exchange, a political caucus, and an occasional court. Guild elections are held here. Work disputes are mediated here. The best and most important conversations happen here over Stolk Dark, the local beer.
Dress: functional and deliberate. The kolpak is universal — quality signals itself through the thickness of the weave, the treatment of the leather, the state of the iron clasps. A Forgetown master smith's kolpak is recognizable to another craftsperson from thirty feet by its material alone. Cheap imported imitations are contemptible.

HEARTLANDS DAILY LIFE
The Laboring Poor — Grain-Worker, River-Laborer, Mill-Tender
The harvest calendar: everything in the grain-farming community is organized around two harvests. The spring harvest (barley, early wheat) determines whether the summer will be lean or comfortable. The autumn harvest (main wheat, oats) determines whether the winter will be survivable. Between harvests: maintenance, animal care, the slow work of keeping the levees functional.
Food: bread, always. The Silver Loaf is the prestige version for noble tables. Working people eat the second-milling bread — denser, darker, slightly sour, lasts a week without going completely inedible. Argen-Pickle — river fish pickled in mineral water — served alongside. The metallic taste is an acquired one that Heartlanders defend vigorously.
The Guild Table: the communal meal hosted by the local guild chapter, open to all guild members and their families. Not charity — contribution is expected; you bring what you have. The Guild Table is the social event of the week, the political forum, and the information exchange. A Heartlander without guild membership is isolated from this structure in a way that matters enormously.
Leisure: The Argenhold Circuit — a board game modeling trade routes; children learn basic economics from it by age eight. River swimming in summer; the Argen is cold, fast, and beautiful. Ballads — the Heartlander ballad tradition is formal and long but deeply embedded; people will sit through a forty-minute ballad about a historical dispute as entertainment.
The Merchant Middle — Factor, Ship-Agent, Vaultkeeper Client
The silver table: informal private dining clubs in Vornhold and Argenhold where Vaultkeeper clients meet. Not advertised; entry by introduction only. The food is better than most restaurants; the conversation is confidential; the business conducted here moves more grain than any single ducal court.
Appearance anxiety: the merchant class wears silver but carefully — enough to signal success, not enough to invite the accusation of pretension. The precise calibration of silver ornament (how much, what quality, where worn) is a legible social code that Heartlanders read instinctively and that outsiders miss entirely.

THE HORNS DAILY LIFE
The Laboring Poor — Dockhand, Salt-Raker, Fishing-Crew
The tide structures everything: meals happen between tides, not at fixed hours. A dockhand who works the outgoing tide eats before dawn; a fishing-crew on the incoming tide eats when they return. Schedules are anchored to the Pilots' Guild signal flags, not to the sun.
Food: Storm-Stew — whatever fish was caught, whatever vegetables available, simmered in seawater with stormkelp — this is the meal. Technically different every time; emotionally constant. Blue-Herring Smoked with black bread is the lunchpail standard. The Brinehold Knotcake (a dense sweet flatcake twisted in each family's distinctive knot-pattern) is made weekly and distributed to the household.
The Knotmaster tradition: in Horns working families, one person in each generation becomes the household's knotmaster — keeps and passes down the family's distinctive knotwork patterns. The family-knot appears on the knotcake, on the knot-jewelry, on the prow of any vessel the family owns. A family without a distinctive knot is a family without history.
Leisure: Storm-Sing competition in winter. Scrimshaw — engraving bone, tooth, whale-material — during long voyages or winter evenings. Knut-Wrestle at festivals. Significant amounts of beer — the Horns brew is dark, heavy, minerally; visitors either love it or find it undrinkable; locals don't notice the taste anymore because it's what water tastes like to them.

RED COAST DAILY LIFE
The Laboring Poor — Qanat-Worker, Caravan-Hand, Oasis-Farmer
The heat calendar: nothing important happens outdoors between the late-morning and mid-afternoon hours from late spring through early autumn. This is not laziness; it is survival. The working hours are dawn-to-late-morning and late-afternoon-to-dusk, with a hot midday rest that is actually sleep.
Water ritual: every morning begins with the water-offering — a small cup poured for the household's luck, into a copper bowl placed near the threshold. The bowl is cleaned daily. The water is real (not token). A household that skips this practice is considered cursed; a household that performs it with dirty water or an uncleaned bowl is considered careless in ways that extend beyond the religious.
Food: Qasr Bread — flat, hard, keeps indefinitely in dry conditions; the caravan staple. Dates. Sharab al-Nahar — cold herb-water, served before any substantive conversation; declining it is a social error. The evening meal is the elaborate one: slow-cooked stew with spices, served communally, everyone from the bowl.
The caravanserai: the physical center of social life for any Red Coast settlement of size. Not just travelers — locals gather here, traders meet here, news arrives here. The caravanserai owner is one of the most socially significant people in any town, because they know who came through, when, and carrying what.

FROZEN SOUTH DAILY LIFE
The Laboring Poor — Seal-Hunter, Mine-Worker, Coastal Fisher
The dark months: six weeks each winter with no sunlight above the southern horizon. Life continues but the rhythm shifts completely. Sleep is longer and less structured — the fire is the only clock. Fire-song evenings that stretch for hours. The great-hall becomes the entire world; every interaction for six weeks happens with the same small group of people in the same firelit space.
Food: seal meat (raw when fresh, smoked when not). Blod-Graut — blood porridge, eaten before whale hunts; you can taste the iron. Dried caribou for the journey. Tundra-Berry — the small red berry, eaten by the handful during the brief summer, dried and hoarded through winter. The Glacier-Honey is rationed — available only at specific events (Fire-Naming, funerals, the Winter-Moot itself); eating honey outside these contexts would be considered almost obscene in its excess.
Oral culture: the fire-songs are not performed for an audience; they are performed by everyone present. A fire-song evening means everyone sings, or no one. Children learn the songs before words — the rhythm before the meaning, the melody before the text. The fire-singer (the person who holds the most complete repertoire) occupies a special social position; they are not performers, they are repositories.
Death: direct, undisguised. A dying person says what they need to say. The family gathers but does not pretend. After death, the body is prepared by the family (not specialists, unless a Ysvari-influenced priest is nearby, which in 1308 AF is unlikely outside the Heitdalr). The fire-songs for the dead are sung immediately, then periodically for a year.

XARIAN DAILY LIFE
The Free Poor — Canal-Worker, River-Fisher, Plantation Hand
The Exchange rhythm: every day begins with acknowledgment — the small offering, the brief prayer, the moment of conscious participation in the cycle. This is as automatic as breathing and as essential; Xarians who miss it feel genuinely anxious rather than guilty.
The canal-boat: many working Xarians live primarily on water — flat-bottomed boats that serve as home, transportation, and workspace simultaneously. The boat is deeply personal; its quality signals its owner's status; decorative carved-wood prow pieces are one of the few personal luxury items the laboring poor can aspire to.
Food: the tamale is the staple — masa dough wrapped around filling, steamed in banana leaves. Eaten at breakfast, at midday, carried as travel food. Cacao is drunk black and bitter — adding sugar is considered either barbaric (by the upper class) or aspirationally mainland-influenced (by those who want to seem sophisticated to traders). The communal cooking tradition: large shared pots at the canal-junction settlements, everyone contributing, everyone eating.
The Ashborn — The Bound
A separate section because their daily life is fundamentally different from that of any free person anywhere on the continent.
The Hush: the sub-audible tactile communication register that functions below any master's detection. Ashborn who live in the same household develop their Hush-fluency to the point where entire conversations pass across shared surfaces — a hand on a table, a foot touching another foot under the mat, the back of a hand against an arm while serving food. Masters who notice unusual stillness occasionally attribute it to stupidity; this is the most important misreading in Xaria.
The night room: Ashborn household slaves have a designated sleeping space that is, by law, minimally adequate. In practice, the night room is the Ashborn household's actual home — the space where the Hush-Truth is rehearsed, where the children are taught to read the pattern-language, where the small rituals of the Reformation are observed. The door faces away from the main house when this is architecturally possible. When it isn't, everyone who sleeps there keeps their back to the door.
Ix'Orath children: born approximately once per generation in any active Reformation community; fully green-eyed, not hazel, not tinted. They are hidden within days of birth — sometimes literally, in arrangements that require the master's household to believe the child died. The network that manages this is the most impressive operational security on the peninsula.

