WHAT DIFFERENT LEVELS OF WEALTH LOOK LIKE
Destitute: No stable shelter, eating by charity or theft. 0-1 Scales in possession at any time. Relies on Ashanite hospice food distribution during fasting months. The Bonekeepers will still bury you; this is important.
Working Poor: 4-6 Scales per day, most spent on food and rent. Owns their clothes, their tools if they're skilled, and their bedding. Rents their room. The domovoi shrine in Rosland, the morning water-offering in the Red Coast, the alba-stone in the Horns — these domestic rituals cost nothing and are everything.
Comfortable Laborer: 8-15 Scales per day. Owns their house (usually). Has savings: 50-200 Scales in a hiding place (not a bank — that's for merchants). Can afford the second-quality inn when traveling. Their family eats meat twice a week.
Guild Craftsperson: 15-30 Scales per day. Net worth 300-1500 Scales. Has a house, owns their tools, has a Vaultkeeper account if they're in the Heartlands. Can afford to send a child to an Order of the Quill school. Political rights in Rosland.
Successful Merchant: 50-200 Scales per day income equivalent. Net worth 2000-20,000 Scales. Has employees. Has a townhouse. Has a relationship with the Vaultkeepers. Has the kind of problem where whether to loan money to a minor lord at what interest rate is an actual personal decision they make.
Minor Lord: Net worth 20,000-100,000 Scales. Annual income 2000-8000 Silver Weights. Has a household of 15-40 people. Has an estate. Has a militia obligation. Has debt to the Vaultkeepers because maintaining the estate requires consistent capital outlays that don't always align with revenues.
Major Duke: Annual income 5000-50,000 Silver Weights. Has hundreds in household. Has armies. Has the problem of other powerful people wanting things from them. Has so much that the specific amounts stop mattering; what matters is leverage, alliance, and the ability to project force.

PART FOUR: MINOR COURT CULTURES

THE VAULTKEEPER CLASS — HEARTLANDS
The Vaultkeepers of Silvermont are officially a banking guild. Practically, they have created a class of financial administrators who are wealthier than most minor nobles and have no hereditary title and don't care.
The clavarro (literally "key-holder") is a senior Vaultkeeper agent stationed in a major city. They manage their clients' accounts, extend letters of credit, negotiate commercial loans, and — unofficially — serve as the most reliable intelligence network in the Heartlands because every significant transaction passes through their hands and they are professionally curious about patterns.
Social customs specific to the clavarro class:
The tavola d'argento ("silver table") — the regular gathering at a specific inn table, by invitation, where financial information is exchanged before markets open; attendance signals status; the conversation is never written down
Marriage strategy: clavarro daughters marry into minor noble houses; clavarro sons become Vaultkeepers; this has been happening for four generations and has blurred the distinction between old money and new capability
Dress code: silver but calibrated — a clavarro wearing more silver than the client they're meeting has made a social error; always dress one register below the most powerful person in the room
The specific posture of deference to nobility while maintaining actual power: Vaultkeepers have financed enough ruin to know exactly where the leverage is; they are exquisitely polite and never threaten
Notable specific customs:
A clavarro never quotes a price before asking three questions: what it's for, who will see it, and what happens if it doesn't work — this is functionally a risk-assessment protocol dressed as social interest
The Vaultkeeper handshake: a specific grip that encodes in its pressure and duration whether the agreement being sealed is considered sound, risky, or a favor being extended; only recognizable to other Vaultkeepers
They do not attend the Guild Tables; they send a representative who arrives, leaves early, and reports back

THE CAPOSTRADA — NIONIA
The quarry foremen class. Not nobility. Not servants. Something older.
A capostrada family has run a specific quarry face for as many as eight generations. They know which veins will produce albasto (white) grade and which will give tostana (cream), not because they've studied the geology but because their grandfather's grandfather learned it by listening to the stone. The specific sound a hammer makes in a particular seam tells them the yield before the first block is cut. The Cassian family depends on this knowledge entirely; removing a capostrada would cut marble production by a third until the replacement learned what the family knew.
Capostrada social life occupies a specific niche:
They eat with the workers, not with the family
They dress in the quarry's colors (each major quarry has developed a distinctive pigment combination for the workers' clothes — practical identification underground; also a subtle identity marker)
Their marriages are managed internally: capostrada families marry capostrada families, preserving the knowledge lineage and preventing it from diluting into the broader working class
They have their own songs — the quarry-songs, which are Pyrantha hymns adapted over centuries — that the Pure Way cannot touch because removing them would affect productivity
Under Jous's Pure Way, the capostrada class is experiencing new friction: Ferronus-appointed overseers have been inserted into the quarry hierarchy above them, and the overseers don't know the stone. Three serious accidents in the past two years are attributed to overseers overriding capostrada safety judgments. The capostrada have not publicly protested. They have begun keeping detailed written records of every instance when an overseer override preceded an adverse event. These records are being maintained with the meticulous precision of people who expect to need evidence eventually.

THE MAYORAZGO — SANGREA
The estate managers. Not noble; not servant; a profession so old it predates the title.
The word mayorazgo technically refers to a specific form of inheritance law (the estate passes intact rather than divided), but in Sangrean usage it has shifted to mean the person who runs the inheritance — the estate manager, the operational center of any functioning hacienda.
A good mayorazgo:
Knows the yield of every row of vines on the property
Knows which workers are reliable, which need watching, which have personal problems that affect output
Maintains the personal relationships with the Carvallo relay-station operators that determine whether your messages arrive before your rivals'
Manages the lord's debts without the lord knowing how close to the edge they are, because the lord's peace of mind is part of the job
Has a separate private ledger that the lord will never see, in which the actual financial position of the estate is recorded honestly
Mayorazgo social customs:
They address the lord formally and are addressed by surname only — no title, no first name
They eat alone or with the chief household staff; not with the workers, not with the family
When guests arrive, the mayorazgo appears exactly once — to confirm the arrangements are in order — and then disappears until something requires managing
The specific gesture of the mayorazgo's report: standing at the lord's left shoulder, slightly behind, voice low, face forward — delivering information without making it a conversation unless the lord turns to make it one
Some mayorazgo families have been on a specific hacienda for three generations and are, in practical terms, more central to the estate's identity than the noble family whose name the estate bears. The most powerful mayorazgo on the continent is arguably Rosalba Moreno, who runs the combined Solé-Castesol properties and has for twenty-three years. She has outlived two Lord-Patrons and is outliving the current one's attention span.

THE MASTER-SMITH DYNASTIES — ROSLAND
In Forgetown and Karthold, the distinction between "guild family" and "minor nobility" has essentially dissolved through three generations of strategic marriage and political leverage.
The Stelev family is the exemplary case. They are not noble. They own the city's most important forge-complex. The current matriarch, Zora Stelev (age 68), has been smithing for fifty years and refuses to stop doing it herself — she runs the most important commercial operation in Forgetown while personally working the forge for several hours every morning. Her son Gregor is Marshal of Rosland. The family has never applied for a noble title and never needed one.
Master-smith dynasty customs:
The forge-name: every master smith in a dynasty family takes a forge-name in addition to their birth name — a single syllable or short word that becomes their signature on their work. Zora Stelev's forge-name is Ruk (hand). Her son Gregor's is Zel (iron). The lineage of forge-names is a separate genealogy, running parallel to the family tree, documenting who made what
The proof blade: when a member of a dynasty family completes their apprenticeship, they make a single blade under their own judgment with no supervision. The blade is kept by the family, never sold, as the permanent record of the moment they became themselves
The Hammer Festival in Karthold: the annual forge-beat competition held in the worked-out mine shafts; the Stelev family has won it eleven times in thirty years; this is considered normal

THE PILOT-FAMILIES — THE HORNS
The Pilots' Guild is meritocratic in formal structure and hereditary in practice. You cannot buy your way into pilot certification; you must pass the examination. The examination is administered by pilots. The pilots were taught by their parents. The questions are not rigged; the preparation is.
There are currently seven families that have produced consecutive generations of certified pilots: Thorne (Guildmaster Revka's family), Halversen, Kolgaard, Nex, Bruvvik, Daelm, and Akervik. Between them they account for sixty percent of the Guild's active membership.
Pilot-family customs:
Tidal dreaming: many experienced pilots report dreaming in tidal patterns — their sleep follows the cycle of the moons, with deeper sleep during high tides and lighter during low. Whether this is physiological adaptation or folk belief is unclear; the correlation is real enough that pilot families track their children's sleep to assess aptitude
The crossing gift: when a pilot-family child makes their first unassisted crossing of the main strait, the family presents them with a carved bone tablet engraved with the tidal table for the day of their birth — the specific combination of Aura and Teln positions at the moment they entered the world. This is their personal tidal signature
Marriages within the pilot community are strongly preferred; the knowledge base is treated as something that should concentrate, not dilute

THE QANAT-ENGINEER CLASS — RED COAST
The Qanat-Khanan (Water-Lords) guild maintains the underground aqueduct systems that are the Red Coast's actual infrastructure. They are not nobility; they do not aspire to be; their guild authority supersedes noble privilege in all matters of water management and is legally recognized in the Red Crown's court system.
A Qanat-Khanan master-engineer is among the most practically powerful people in any Red Coast city. Their authority to close a lord's water-access is not theoretical — it has been exercised, and the lord complied.
Qanat-Khanan customs:
The underground year: most master-engineers spend at least one month per year working below ground in the qanats they manage. This is not ceremonial; the tunnel systems require regular inspection that can only be done on foot, in the dark, with the water flowing around your knees. Engineers who stop doing this lose the intuitive understanding of the system that makes their authority meaningful
The sound-map: experienced Qanat-Khanan engineers can navigate specific qanat systems by sound alone — the particular echo a tunnel produces at each junction, the distinctive drip-pattern where a known fracture is occurring. A master engineer can identify a new fracture by a change in the sound before it's large enough to see
Dress: the Qanat-Khanan wear copper-green sashes — the color of oxidized copper, which appears on every qanat pipe junction where water has been running for years. This is not ornamental; it's identification in the field

PART FIVE: SONGS, ART, AND LITERATURE

MUSIC — NAMED WORKS AND TRADITIONS
Sangrean Coplas
La Verdad de la Sangre (The Truth of the Blood) — The censored copla about the Sunstone Wars. Forty minutes, naming every atrocity, every lie, every bribe. Maela de la Fuente sang it once at the Festival of the Red Grape and vanished into the riot it caused. Illegal to sing in full in some territories. Fragments are circulated as acts of political speech.
El Matador de los Nombres (The Killer of Names) — Composed within weeks of the Feast of Poison. Circulating in Sangrean lower districts. Asks, over and over, who had the motive and the contacts to poison every important name in one room. Not a gentle song.
La Novia del Río (The River Bride) — The universal Sangrean wedding song. About Ixchela's tears becoming rivers. Five hundred years old, approximately, with new verses added in every generation. The verse added by a specific copla-master in 1284 AF (the year Jous Lorethian was born) is considered unlucky to sing at weddings in Nionia, but plays elsewhere constantly.
Siete Campanadas (Seven Bells) — A bell-ringing work song that became a love song that became an anti-war song that became a work song again. Currently it means at least three different things in three different Sangrean provinces.
Canto del Hueso Blanco (Song of the White Bone) — A funeral copla sung when someone dies far from home. About the body that won't be returned. Specific to the War of the Red Tide period but now used for any distant death. Sailors particularly favor it.
Roslandic Fire-Songs
Sorvost na Daudrvik (Winter in the Deadwood) — About the Frostguard rangers. The oldest fire-song in active circulation that anyone can reliably date; pre-imperial. Its middle section is in a dialect that no one fully understands anymore; the Frostguard sing it anyway. It sounds like warning.
Tri Mosta, Tri Reki (Three Bridges, Three Rivers) — The founding song of the republic. Sung at every High Baron election. Vaguely describes the Treaty of the Five Bridges; the specifics are wrong in every version. The emotion is correct.
Zhelezna Klyatva (The Iron Oath) — The stratocratic oath-song. Sung when soldiers graduate from their first campaign season. The modern version has different verses from the original; the original apparently included a verse about what happens to oaths sworn to kings, which was removed during the imperial period and hasn't been restored.
Pesnya Yezhy (The Hedgehog's Song) — A children's lullaby. A hedgehog knows the names of all the things in the forest and won't tell them to anyone who asks directly; you have to give the hedgehog a gift and wait. This is the Roslandic attitude toward information in song form, taught to children before they can read.
Maren's Cup (various titles) — Not a single song but a genre. Ballads about Maren of the Broken Cup. There are at least twelve distinct versions currently in circulation; the most extreme (and most suppressed under Ironside) has a final verse that is essentially a call for violence against tyrannical rulers.
Nionian Lamentos
Canzone del Marmo (Song of the Marble) — The quarry-workers' hymn to Pyrantha. Pre-Lovist. Pre-empire. The oldest continuously performed song on the continent that can be dated with reasonable confidence. The Pure Way has banned it. It is sung every morning in the Marchia Ferrus before the first shift. No one has been arrested for this yet.
La Notte Senza Luce (The Night Without Light) — A civil war resistance song. About the night the Scriptorium burned. Written by someone who was there; they remain anonymous. The Pure Way has banned it with explicit threat of execution. It is sung in the Anchor & Chain after the shift-change when no white cloaks are visible.
Voce di Thalvex (Thalvex's Voice) — A sailors' work song. Modal and unsettling. About hearing the sea say your name. It doesn't mean you're going to die; it means the sea has noticed you. Whether this is good or bad is the song's deliberate ambiguity.
Heartlander Ballads
The Three Bridges of Argenhold — About Daven the Peacemaker. Long, formal, precise about the political details of the Treaty of Five Bridges. Sung at every Argenlord election. Also sung by people who want the Argenlord system to mean what Daven intended, which is increasingly a political statement.
Marvoss's Sons — Three boys thrown from Stonebridge. Considered bad luck to sing indoors; must be sung under open sky. The last verse lists their names, their ages, and their father's crime, then asks: "Was the crime worth the weight?" The question is rhetorical in one direction.
Caelia's Fire — The Roslandic ballad about the guerrilla woman who burned imperial records. Spread into the Heartlands during the last century through trade routes. In some Silverblood territories it's banned. In Argenhold it plays at festivals and the local Ayanite court has quietly declined to prosecute.

VISUAL ART — TRADITIONS AND NAMED WORKS
Nionia
The Republic Frescoes — The Senate walls, now covered by Jous's plaster. Depicting electoral debates, naval victories, the founding of the republic. They are intact under the plaster; this is known by at least forty people on the island and spoken of by none of them. If the Pure Way falls, the plaster could be removed. If the plaster is removed first, it would be an act of war.
The Argentum Libri — Not Nionian but the Heartlands' most prestigious art form that appears most often in Nionian patrician houses as imports. Illuminated manuscripts with silver-leaf illumination, produced by the Order of the Quill's Heartlander branch. Several patrician families have complete genealogical records in this form. The Marcellus family's genealogical Argentum Liber traces their line to the senator who survived the Great Pyre. It is the most dangerous piece of paper on Nionia.
Lamp-Glass Panels — Colored glass hanging objects produced by Antheon glass-blowers. Cast colored light rather than admitting light; the effect in a stone room at night is extraordinary. Not windows — too fragile and too small. Decorative objects that signal wealth and aesthetic taste. The Deep Crimson series (using blood-copper oxide for the red) are a pre-Pure Way Nionian specialty that is now politically charged — wearing crimson or keeping crimson glass is quietly being interpreted as a republican statement.
Sangrea
Corrida Paintings — The dominant Sangrean visual art form by market volume. Specific painters specialize in capturing corrida moments: the pass, the turn, the kill. The best work is genuinely thrilling — the best painters have found a way to convey motion in static image that architectural painters in the same period haven't matched. Every tavern has one. Every noble hall has several. The best ones hang at the Alcázar in Castesol.
Las Siete Verdades (The Seven Truths) — A specific painting by an anonymous Terrarossa-court artist, approximately 1180 AF. Seven panels depicting the seven Sunstone Wars, each panel showing the same valley from the same angle with different ruins. Currently in the Altavista great hall. House Solé has offered to buy it three times. House Terrarossa has refused each time. The painting is the clearest visual argument ever made for why the war never resolves anything.
Azulejo Tradition — The Loma-tile tradition. Not just decoration: specific patterns encode specific meanings. A threshold with a sol y agua pattern (sun and water, alternating) signals a hospitable house open to travelers. A threshold with a mano roja (red hand) pattern signals a house in mourning. A threshold with a cascabela (rattle-pattern) signals — to those who know — a Cascabella distribution point.
The Heartlands
La Pace dei Cinque Ponti (The Peace of the Five Bridges) — The great tapestry in the Argenhold Riverhall. Forty feet wide, eight feet tall, depicting the Treaty signing and the five bridges being rebuilt simultaneously across the region. The borders show every major house involved, with their sigils. Three of the border sigils depict houses that no longer exist. Three depict houses currently at war with each other. The tapestry is frequently referenced in political arguments about what the Argenlord system was supposed to be.
River Maps — The Navegantes guild's master charts of the Heartlands river system. The public versions are beautiful and accurate. The intelligence-grade versions are classified. Even the public versions are art objects: color-coded by depth and current speed, annotated with every waystation, every ford, every seasonal flood pattern. The best river maps are passed down through merchant families as heirlooms.
The Silver Chronicle of House Silverblood — An Argentum Liber genealogical record begun in 951 AF and maintained continuously. Currently seventeen volumes. The most recent volume was commissioned by Argenlord Theron and stops at his ascension, which the scribes have noted with careful ambiguity is "the current generation's beginning." What happens next is unwritten and the blank pages feel political.
Rosland
The Pesnya-Reza Tradition — Woodcuts illustrating notable fire-songs. Produced as broadsheets and traded across the republic. The technique: a specific method of multiple-pass cutting that produces almost photographic depth of shadow. The most valuable pesnya-reza are those depicting banned or suppressed fire-songs — Maren's Cup in several versions, Caelia's Fire, and the fragmented verse of Zhelezna Klyatva that was removed during imperial occupation.
Guild-Mark Collecting — Every master craftsperson stamps their work with their personal mark. The practice of collecting pieces specifically for the rarity of their maker-mark is a Roslandic form of art appreciation. Zhelezka Marks (marks from Zelnik family smiths) and Stelev Marks (from the Stelev dynasty) are the most collected. A complete set of Stelev-family marks across four generations represents over sixty distinct individuals and is worth more than the objects themselves.
Cemetery Art — The quality of a Roslandic gravestone reflects the quality of a life, which has created a competitive art market around death. The best cemetery in Fairhaven (the Vechniy Sad — the Eternal Garden, established 920 AF) has gravestones that are considered the finest stone-carving on the continent. Poor families save for decades for a good stone. The best carvers are booked years in advance.
The Red Coast
The Miqyas Tradition — Precision instruments made beautiful. The Red Coast has the most sophisticated astronomical and mathematical tradition on the continent (driven by the Tariqat al-Nur and its predecessors). Astrolabes, water-clocks, qanat-flow measuring vessels — functional objects elevated to art through geometric inlay, copper filigree, and the specific visual language of Arabic-adjacent geometric beauty. The best instruments are in the Grand Souk of Alsiroth's Gate; some have been in circulation for centuries.
Al-Khattat al-Ahmar (The Red Calligrapher) — a specific manuscript illuminator active approximately 1150-1180 AF whose identity is unknown. Produced a series of Tariqat al-Nur contemplative texts in a script-illumination style that later became the standard for Red Coast formal documents. The original manuscripts are in three locations: the Saravenna royal archive, the Tariqat al-Nur retreat at Wahaat al-Sirr, and — according to a persistent rumor — the Magos vault on the Isle of Knowledge.
The Frozen South
The Kjölfoss Goldwork — Already established as the finest on the continent. The specific technique: interlocking knotwork on a base metal form, with the gold wire worked into the base in patterns that represent specific fire-song passages. A piece of Kjölfoss goldwork is simultaneously jewelry, portable property store, and a chunk of encoded oral tradition. If you know how to read the knotwork patterns, you can tell which fire-songs a goldsmith was thinking about when they made a piece.
Bone Carving — Small portable objects, seal-bone and whale-ivory. The Frozen South equivalent of pocket art. The best carvers produce objects of extraordinary delicacy and expressiveness. A specific tradition: carving the faces of the dead from memory. Not portraits — the Frozen South doesn't have portrait tradition — but spirit-impressions; the carver produces what they felt from the person rather than what the person looked like. These pieces are deeply unsettling to mainlanders.
Xaria
The Teocalli Reliefs — The sequential carved panels on the pyramid faces at Ix'Pal and Canopolis. The most elaborate stone-carving on the continent. Each panel tells a segment of the cosmological narrative; reading the complete story of K'tharr's descent and ascent requires walking around the entire base of the great Teocalli, which takes approximately an hour if you stop to read. The panels are painted (the paint is regularly renewed); the original stone beneath some panels is reportedly carved differently from the surface layer, which the K'ay storytellers say is because the deeper story is different from the public one.
Featherwork Cloaks — Already established as the highest Xarian art form. Named works exist. The K'tharr's Mantle — a cloak held in the Ix'Pal treasury, attributed to a master featherworker who lived approximately 400 years ago — depicts K'tharr's descent into the underworld in a mosaic of quetzal and macaw feathers so detailed that the jaguar spots of his fire-form are individually placed feathers. The cloak requires two people to carry it.

LITERATURE — NAMED TEXTS
The sacred texts (Aya's Scrolls, Asha's Tomes of Vibration, the Alon Codex) are already documented in the Lovist faith section.
The Cogitant Letters by Father Thesan of Silvermont — The Logosian philosophical text. Banned everywhere; present everywhere. Arguing that the divine echoes are natural phenomena rather than divine remnants, that the gods are dead in the literal sense and always were, and that Loveism's ethical framework can survive the removal of its theological foundation. This last claim is what makes it dangerous — not the atheism but the argument that the Church is unnecessary even if Loveism is true.
The Menna Papers by Corvath Menna — The Starveling Church founding text. A hundred pages of unadorned observation: what the prophets owned (nothing), what the Church owns (a partial list, with approximate values). The style is deliberately plain, almost boring. The effect is not.
The Gardens of Altavista — A Sangrean erotic novel set during a Sunstone War. Officially suppressed; widely circulated. The military setting is the frame; the actual subject is desire under conditions of mortality, which is the correct subject. The author's identity is unknown. Current consensus among people who discuss this: someone in the Terrarossa court, female, with access to both houses' intelligence services. The Solé intelligence service's theory: it was written by a man. The disagreement has become a secondary drama in Sangrean cultural circles.
Seravann's Preface — The introduction to the Alon Codex by his primary disciple. The most quoted single document in Lovist scripture. "He did not speak. He therefore could not be misunderstood. What he did remained what it was." Short, careful, devastating in its implications about language and its failures.
The Velindra Calculations — The Magos astronomical text that confirmed the world's sphericity through lunar eclipse analysis during Concordance. Three hundred years old. Required reading at the Isle; available at any Ayanite school with a decent library. The specific mathematical proof has been reproduced, checked, extended, and accepted. The theological implications (the world is a sphere; the spherical shape has no preference; the divine center the Lovist faith posits is not architecturally available in a sphere) are addressed in a lengthy appendix that manages to be simultaneously rigorous and carefully inconclusive.
On the Nature of Echoes — Elder Corvath's unpublished research notes at the Isle of Knowledge. Exists in three partial copies, none complete. The most important unacknowledged scientific text in existence. Documenting the echo-field's distribution, its historical decline, and the first theoretical framework that accounts for both the folk magic traditions and the measurable phenomena the Magos have been pretending aren't measurable. Corvath's proposed mechanism (residual divine consciousness saturating matter, diminishing as matter is processed) is correct. He knows it's correct. He cannot publish it because it would validate the Logosians while also validating the Church's theology about the divine sacrifice, which would force two camps that currently can't agree on anything into an uncomfortable alliance.
Caelia's Fire — Technically a ballad but also a written text. The narrative of the woman who burned imperial records for eight years. Exists in at least three written versions (the oldest is in the Magos archive, noted as "Roslandic folk material, approximate date 440 AF"). The most recent written version (1289 AF) has a final section that the previous versions don't include: a first-person passage supposedly in Caelia's voice, describing what she saw in the mountains before she disappeared. No one knows if this section is historically real or added for political effect. The addition of a first-person voice to a woman the empire erased entirely is, regardless of its historicity, one of the most significant political acts in recent Roslandic literary history.

PART SIX: LEGAL CODES AND SUCCESSION

CONTINENTAL OVERVIEW
The Book of Chains — the imperial legal code compiled under Varran I "the Just" (440-478 AF) — remains the baseline legal reference for most of the continent. Every regional legal system is either derived from it, reacting against it, or (in the Frozen South and Xaria) indifferent to it. The Ayanite order trains its judges in the Book of Chains and in regional modifications; the most consistent legal authority on the continent is the traveling Ayanite Arbiter, who can technically impose the Church's legal framework anywhere the secular authorities have failed or collapsed.

NIONIA
Legal foundation: Imperial law (Book of Chains) overlaid with Pure Way religious law since 1306 AF. Two parallel court systems: the civil Triumvirate courts (handling property, trade, inheritance) and the Domus Lux Inquisitorial courts (handling doctrinal crimes, political crimes, anything Jous's regime finds inconvenient to try in civil court).
Succession: Primogeniture — eldest son inherits title and primary property. Daughters inherit if no sons survive. The Senate previously could legitimize bastards by vote; the Pure Way has abolished this, which has created several legal disputes that the Triumvirate courts are handling very carefully.
Marriage law: Requires a Pure Way ceremony. The Church (Lovist) ceremony is now insufficient. Pre-Pure Way marriages are grandfathered. Divorce is technically possible (the old Senate procedure survives on paper) but requires Triumvirate approval, which requires Domus Lux non-objection, which is rare.
Criminal law highlights:
Heresy: Domus Lux jurisdiction; penalties from public penance to execution
Murder: civil courts; compensation to the victim's family; imprisonment or exile; execution rare except for serial cases
Theft: restitution + equal penalty (steal 10 Scales, return 10 and pay 10)
Debt default: civil indentured service to the creditor until the debt is worked off; limited to seven years under the old law; the Pure Way has extended this to life in cases of "deliberate deception" which is defined broadly
Unique to Nionia: The lex marmorea (marble law) — the specific legal tradition governing quarry rights, marble grade disputes, and the capostrada authority. Developed before the empire, never codified by the empire, surviving entirely on custom and Cassian family enforcement. The Pure Way doesn't know it exists. This is deliberate.

THE HEARTLANDS
Legal foundation: The Book of Chains as modified by four centuries of ducal decree. The Argenlord has emergency modification power. The Vaultkeepers maintain a parallel commercial arbitration system that handles all significant trade disputes faster and more reliably than the ducal courts.
Succession: Agnatic primogeniture (eldest son) for major ducal titles. The Argenlord title is explicitly non-hereditary by the Treaty of Five Bridges — elective every three years. Multiple attempts to make it hereditary have been blocked by the minor houses who lose power if any single dynasty consolidates the title permanently.
The Argenhold succession crisis: With the Feast of Poison, the neutral house that has held the Heartlands together for four centuries has one surviving heir. The succession question is: does Kaeo Argenhold inherit the duchy, and if so, under what conditions? The Book of Chains supports his claim unambiguously. Silverblood's regency is a political act with no legal basis. The Ayanite court in Faithir has declined to rule on this, which is the most political non-decision anyone in the region has made in years.
Inheritance law specifics:
Primary title and land: eldest son
Secondary properties: divided equally among all children, male and female
Bastards: inherit nothing without explicit testamentary inclusion, which requires Ayanite notarization
Guild-property inheritance: the guild decides, not the family; this creates constant friction
Marriage law:
Lovist ceremony required for legal validity
Betrothal contracts are legally binding property agreements; breaking a betrothal requires compensating the other party for what they would have received through the marriage
Dowry/bride-price negotiations are the primary content of betrothal contracts; the Vaultkeepers notarize and hold these in escrow
Criminal law highlights:
The grain laws: stealing grain during famine is treated more severely than murder; property crimes against agricultural infrastructure carry the harshest penalties in the region
Bridge law: destroying or obstructing a recognized trade bridge is a capital offense; this was used to threaten Morvayn and not enforced, which has damaged its deterrent value
Debt: same as Nionian base, but the Vaultkeepers' commercial law takes precedence for debts owed to registered merchants

ROSLAND
Legal foundation: The Iron Codex (the Roslandic constitution, ratified 905 AF and significantly modified 990 AF by Tomas Greenhand's guild reforms). The most complete written legal code on the continent for a republic; modeled on the remembered principles of the Aethelian stratocracy but adapted for post-imperial reality.
The Iron Codex's key provisions (currently under threat):
The High Baron is elected every ten years by nobles and guild representatives in equal proportion
The High Baron can be recalled by two-thirds supermajority
Guild voting rights are inheritable from parent to eldest child; they cannot be bought or sold
The judiciary is appointed by a joint committee of the High Baron and senior guild representatives; neither can control it alone
The emergency powers (invoked by Vlado's "Long Vigil") require renewal every six months; they have been renewed three consecutive times without reaching the constitutional threshold for a recall vote
Succession: Noble houses use eldest-child inheritance (not just eldest son — this is a specific Roslandic divergence from most of the continent). The High Barony is explicitly non-hereditary. Vlado Ironside's adoption of Valo and his plan to have Valo win the next election is technically legal but violates the spirit of the constitution in ways the Iron Codex cannot quite explicitly prohibit.
Marriage law:
The republic recognizes two forms of marriage: the civic bond (registered at the muster-field Speaking Stone, legally equivalent, no religious requirement) and the Lovist bond (Church ceremony, provides additional legal advantages in inheritance disputes). Both are legal; the civic bond was a Greenhand reform that the nobility fought and lost.
Divorce by mutual declaration at the Speaking Stone; requires division of shared property by the magistrate; contentious but exists
Children born outside of any bond are spoken-children — acknowledged if the parent names them at the Speaking Stone; this requires no ceremony, only the declaration. An unacknowledged child inherits nothing; a spoken-child inherits on equal footing with bonded-children
Criminal law highlights:
The Iron Codex's most Roslandic provision: the Forge-Witness rule — any citizen who witnesses a crime may give testimony in any court regardless of their social status. This is explicitly not the case in most Heartlander and Nionian courts, where a commoner's testimony requires corroboration by a propertied person
Corporal punishment for minor crimes replaced by fine or work-service in 990 AF reform; Ironside's Long Vigil has reintroduced flogging for certain political offenses under emergency powers

SANGREA
Legal foundation: No unified law. Each lord-patron's territory is legally autonomous. The Church (Ayanite courts) provides a backstop that technically applies everywhere; in practice, it applies where the secular lord hasn't already decided. The ley de sangre (blood law) — the customary law governing noble house obligations, feudal duties, and inter-house conflict — is as binding as written law in practice.
Succession: Strict agnatic primogeniture (eldest legitimate son). No exceptions without explicit testamentary provision. The catastrophic case: if Terrarossa ran out of male heirs, the house would legally dissolve and its property revert to the Doravanto crown — which is currently what House Solé is quietly engineering. Terrarossa's current line is Titus (58), Roric (30), and Roric has no children. The next fifteen years are existential for the old house.
The mayorazgo legal position: Legally a servant with specific contractual rights. In practice, as powerful as any minor noble. The mayorazgo contract is a Sangrean legal innovation that has no equivalent elsewhere — a detailed specifications-and-performance agreement between the lord and the estate manager that includes specific grounds for dismissal, specific duties, and specific protections. The best mayorazgos have contracts that are functionally irrevocable short of criminal conviction.
Marriage law:
Noble marriages require both families' consent, a Church ceremony, and — uniquely in Sangrea — a notarized carta de dote (dowry letter) that specifies exactly what passes between families. The carta de dote is the actual marriage contract; the ceremony is the public acknowledgment
Sangrean divorce is rare and effectively impossible for nobility: it requires Church tribunal ruling, which requires grounds (abuse, abandonment, or the specific ground of "incapacidad de sangre" — inability to produce heirs, which must be proven by a physician's testimony); most incompatible noble marriages simply maintain separate households
Criminal law highlights:
Honra law: the ley de honor allows noble-to-noble violence in specific circumstances (direct insult to honor, adultery, betrayal of hospitality) without criminal penalty if conducted according to the formal duel tradition; this is regularly abused
The Campaneros' legal immunity: by ancient custom (pre-empire), the Campaneros are legally neutral — they cannot be prosecuted for the messages they carry, even if those messages contain treasonous content. This protection has been tested three times and has held each time.

THE RED COAST
Legal foundation: The Copper Courts (traveling Ayanite judges empowered by the Red Crown) apply the Book of Chains modified by the specific Red Crown water law that supersedes it in hydraulic matters. The Sand-Law (Saffaren customary code) applies in the deep desert and is legally recognized by the Red Crown as a parallel jurisdiction.
Succession: Bilateral descent for the Red Crown title (eldest child, gender-neutral). The Alsiroth house uses strict agnatic succession, which creates a succession crisis every other generation. The Sadiq family uses bilateral succession internally, which has kept their commercial empire functioning across three generations while the Alsiroth title has passed to men of decreasing competence.
Water law (unique to the Red Coast):
The Qanat Right: whoever built a qanat owns it; whoever maintains it has usage rights; whoever lets it fall into disrepair loses usage rights. This creates a strong incentive structure for maintenance.
The Sharing Decree: when a qanat serves multiple communities, all communities have equal water access regardless of the building-house's preferences. Violation of the Sharing Decree is tried by Copper Court and can result in the qanat being placed under Crown management.
The Dry Season Protocol: when water supplies fall below threshold levels, the Crown can requisition any private water reserves for communal distribution. This has been invoked four times. Each time, the noble houses that lost private reserves have funded candidates against the sitting Red King at the next opportunity.
Marriage law:
The 'aqd al-zawaj (marriage contract) is primarily a property agreement; the emotional content is considered private. Both parties negotiate through family representatives; the couple may not be present at the negotiation. The contract specifies: what each party brings, what each party receives on dissolution, what the children's arrangement will be, and what grounds constitute legitimate dissolution.
Polygyny is legal (up to four, per the traditional framework); in practice it's confined to the very wealthy because the separate-household requirement makes it prohibitively expensive below a certain income level

THE FROZEN SOUTH
Legal foundation: The Whaletooth Compact — an oral agreement. The fire-songs serve as legal record. The fire-singer is the legal authority when disputes require historical reference. The Holmgang resolves disputes when negotiation fails. The Winter-Moot is the supreme legal authority of the south, binding on all signatories.
The fire-song as legal record:
A fire-song that references a specific agreement, border, or promise is legally binding
Altering a fire-song to change the recorded facts of an agreement is a serious offense — treated the same as destroying a written contract on the mainland
The extinction of a clan's fire-songs (as happened to Clan Hroth after their absorption into Aurax) is the legal equivalent of non-existence: you cannot sue, claim, testify, or inherit if your clan has no fire-songs
Succession: Primogeniture broadly, but with strong collective override: if the clan believes the heir is unfit, the Winter-Moot can name an alternative. This has happened six documented times in living memory, always under circumstances that were less about fitness than about which way the leverage ran. The Beinsverd have been quietly noting that Eirikr Aurax's current attempt to make the Pack Leader title permanent would effectively remove this override mechanism for the south's most powerful clan.
Marriage law:
No ceremony required; a couple who maintains a shared household for one full winter cycle is legally married
Dissolution by mutual declaration before a fire-singer
Children belong to the mother's clan by default; this is the single most important legal distinction between the Frozen South and everywhere else on the continent
Capital offenses (the short list):
Destroying a fire-song record
Violating Holmgang terms after the combat
Killing outside the Holmgang without the Moot's recognition
Betraying the location of a secret well to outsiders

VALLAN
Legal foundation: The most detailed minor legal tradition on the continent. The Waystone Law — the body of road-use and infrastructure obligations that grew up around the road-tax system — has the force of constitutional principle: obligations created by passing a waystone are legally binding.
Unique legal innovations:
The Bridge Guarantee: any bridge maintained by Vallan must be open to any peaceful traveler regardless of origin, faith, or relationship with Vallan's nobles. Violation of the Bridge Guarantee results in Bridge Revocation — the bridge is declared legally public property of the canton and the owning family loses maintenance control. This has never been invoked. The threat is sufficient.
The Canton Sovereignty principle: no Valley-King can impose any policy within a canton without a canton-elder vote. The Valley-King's authority is strictly cross-canton and external.
The Road-Tax Receipt as legal tender: a Road-Key bearing the Valley-King's seal functions as proof of lawful transit, which protects the holder from questioning about their presence in Vallan. This is used by people who need to cross Vallan without explaining why and who can afford the standard transit fee.
Succession: The Valley-Kingship is elective (canton elders vote); by tradition, the Valenne family is always nominated and always wins, but the fiction of election is maintained because the alternative (making it explicitly hereditary) would require constitutional amendment that the canton elders would never approve. Noble house inheritance follows eldest-child principle.

Document ends — Divine Veins Living World Codex, Part Two. Economics · Minor Courts · Art & Song · Law 1308 AF
DIVINE VEINS — THE DARK WORLD SUPPLEMENT
Folk Horror · Grimdark Texture · Lovecraftian Echo · Named Dark Places · Living Superstitions
Supplementary to the Living World Codex — 1308 AF

This document exists alongside the encyclopedic codex. Where the codex names what things are, this document names what things feel like — the darkness underneath the daily life, the horror indigenous to each culture, the superstitions that are quietly correct, the folk legends that encode truths the scholars haven't reached yet, and the named places where the world is thinnest.

PART ONE: THE DARK GRAIN OF EACH REGION

NIONIA — THE ISLAND THAT REMEMBERS BEING FREE
What the darkness feels like here: bureaucratic dread. The horror is not the monster under the bed — it is the man with a ledger deciding whether your name appears on a list. Under the Pure Way, Nionia has developed the specific terror of a society in which your neighbor may have reported you, your employer may have reported you, and the man who delivered your bread this morning may be compiling his weekly observations into a form that will reach the Domus Lux within the week. Everyone performs normalcy. Everyone performs compliance. The horror is that you can't tell the performers from the believers anymore.
The Pale House: Not just a detention facility — the thing that detention facilities become when they operate for two years without oversight. The building was originally the Admiralty Archives. It still smells of old ink and salt-canvas. The detained are held in the map-rooms; the interrogations happen in what was formerly the Harbor-Master's private study, which has a window facing the sea that the Harbor-Master used to watch the ships from and that now watches nothing. People released from the Pale House return slightly off — not broken, not changed in any way they can name, just slightly wrong about small things. They misjudge distances. They flinch at ink stains. Three of the forty-two released so far have walked into the sea within a month of release and not come back. This is not reported anywhere.
The Cantus at Dawn: The Pure Way's mandatory pre-dawn prayer broadcast from the Great Dome reaches every part of the island. It is a human voice — a specific Lux Cantor whose identity is never disclosed — and it sings the same fifteen notes in the same order every morning. There is a specific quality to the fifteenth note, the final one, that sailors have begun calling la nota che manca (the missing note) — the silence after it is slightly too long. Three beats where one beat belongs. Dockhands have started leaving before the cantus ends, not wanting to hear the silence. Nobody talks about this.
The Luminous Marble Vein: In the deepest section of the Marchia Ferrus quarry, sealed under a false floor put in by capostrada patriarch Benedar Sola forty years ago, there is a marble seam that glows. Not reflects light — generates it. The glow is warm-white, slightly gold, and completely steady — no flicker, no variation with temperature, nothing. Benedar sealed it because the workers who spent more than a few hours near it started having the same dream. In the dream, someone is counting. The counting never stops and never reaches a final number. Benedar's son Tomas has never opened the floor again. He checks the seal every morning.
Named Lovecraftian/dark locations:
La Bocca Nera (The Black Mouth) — a coastal sea-cave that produces, at specific low tides, a sound that sounds like a voice speaking a language no one recognizes; fishermen have been writing down what they hear for three generations; the words are consistent across different transcriptions
Il Campo dei Senza-Nome (The Field of the Unnamed) — the mass grave from the first Pure Way purge, now a public garden planted with white flowers; the flowers are healthier than any garden soil should support; the gardeners never notice that weeding is unnecessary
Thalvex's Anchor Point — a specific spot on the sea floor, marked on pre-imperial charts, where ships' compasses behave strangely; pre-Pure Way sailors considered it the location where Thalvex sank his anchor to hold the island in place; in 1308 AF, the echo-field reading there (if anyone knew how to read it) would be the highest concentration on the island

THE HORNS — WHERE THE TIDE HAS OPINIONS
What the darkness feels like here: maritime dread. The sea is not a metaphor here. The sea is the actual problem. It has behaviors that experienced pilots recognize and cannot explain: courses where the water is the wrong temperature, passages where sound travels differently, specific coordinates where ships arrive to find their clocks have disagreed with the sun by anywhere from six minutes to four hours. The Pilots' Guild logs these anomalies. They call the logs "Thalvex's Margin Notes" and they are the most carefully maintained records in the Horns — not because anyone understands them but because the pattern of non-understanding is itself information.
Bone Walk: The annual ritual where the Horns' dead of the past year are carried to the sea. Not burial — release. The bodies are placed on flat-bottomed craft and pushed into the outgoing tide at Brinehold, and the Pilot who reads the tide decides in which direction the dead are sent based on the specific conditions of that night. This is not metaphorical. There is a specific relationship between the direction the dead are sent and what the following fishing season looks like that the Pilots have been tracking since the guild was founded. The correlation is not perfect. It is also not explicable by any mechanism anyone has been able to identify. The Halversen Codex — the guild's private record — has a section on this that has never been shared with any mainlander and never will be.
The Galewater Void: A specific section of the Galewater passage — approximately forty square miles of open water — where, since approximately 1240 AF, fish have not been caught. Not fewer fish. No fish. The water is otherwise normal. The Horns' fishers have stopped trying to explain it and simply sail around it. The Pilots call it Thal's Silence and record the expansion of its boundary in the same logs as the clock anomalies. The boundary expands approximately one mile per decade. At current rate, it will reach the main harbor approaches of Nightspike in approximately thirty years.
Named dark locations:
Knotgrip Shallows — a bay where three separate ships have beached themselves in perfectly calm conditions with no mechanical failure; the ships are intact; the crews were never found; the shallows are six feet deep and perfectly navigable
The Skinned Coast — a stretch of cliff face north of Westhorn where the stone has no lichen, no moss, nothing; the rock is visually scoured; the Horns say a storm did it centuries ago; the area of bare rock has been slowly expanding toward the south at approximately one yard per year since anyone began measuring
Revka's First Chart — the Guildmaster's private original navigation chart, inherited from her grandmother's grandmother, shows a landmass in the Galewater where no landmass exists; she has checked the coordinates personally; there is nothing there; the chart cannot be explained away because it predates any reason to fabricate a phantom island

SANGREA — THE BEAUTY WITH THE DARK CENTER
What the darkness feels like here: the horror of abundance turned toward sacrifice. Sangrea is beautiful and violent and the violence is aesthetic. The corrida is the most honest expression of this: a tradition about ritual death, practiced in public, celebrated as art. The thing underneath it is the Xarian cosmological influence that came through three hundred years of trade contact — the understanding that beauty requires a price, that the sacred requires blood, and that this is not tragedy but structure. Most Sangreans feel this without being able to articulate it. The Ix'Vorath cult on the Red Coast has the articulation; some Sangreans in the border regions have noticed.
The Cascabella Night Market: In Altavista, in a specific plaza that changes location every week (the current location transmitted through the Carvallo relay system to those who need to know), a market operates from the third hour after midnight until one hour before dawn. The goods sold range from the mundane (goods that can't be moved during daylight for tax reasons) to the concerning (services that require darkness for reasons of discretion) to the genuinely alarming (the specific stall, present perhaps once in five markets, that sells objects the vendor calls "memorias del río" — river memories — small river-worn stones that, when held, produce in the holder a specific memory that is not their own; the vendor claims the memories come from people who drowned in the Fuente; the memories are consistent with accounts of the dead; no one has proved the vendor is not simply a skilled manipulator of the grieving and credulous; no one has proved the opposite either).
The Parrots After a Death: In Sangrean households with trained Carvallo parrots, the birds fall silent when a member of the household dies. Not quieter — completely silent, for an interval that varies from six hours to three days. When they resume speech, the first word they say is not from their trained vocabulary. No trainer has ever been able to explain this. Several trainers have documented it. The words vary; the phenomenon is consistent. The most documented first-word list (maintained by the Altavista Carvallo Guild chapter, never distributed) shows that seven of the forty-three recorded first words match names of living people who were subsequently involved in violent events within a year of the silence.
The Red Tapestry: In the Terrarossa great hall at Fuenterroja, a tapestry depicting the founding of House Terrarossa. Eight panels. In the sixth panel, a woman is depicted in a doorway holding a child. The woman's face is turned away. The woman's face has been turned away in every inspection, every drawing, every record of the tapestry's description, going back to the tapestry's creation. No one has ever seen it facing forward. This is not possible for a tapestry. The explanation that the tapestry was made with her face turned is unsatisfying because there are clear technical indicators that the facing-away is not the original weaving. The Terrarossa family does not discuss the tapestry.
Named dark locations:
El Pozo de las Voces (The Well of Voices) — a dry well outside Castesol where, if you lean in on moonless nights, you hear what sounds like people arguing in a dialect that no living Sangrean linguist can fully parse; the dialect is clearly Sangrean-rooted but archaic in ways that suggest it predates the Sunstone Wars
La Casa Sin Sombra (The House Without Shadow) — a specific abandoned hacienda on the Velazco road that casts no shadow at noon; geometrically impossible; documented in four separate surveys over eighty years; the current explanation is "unusual local topography," which satisfies no one who has stood there
Los Campos Rojos (The Red Fields) — the eastern battlefield of the Third Sunstone War, where the Fuente ran red for three days; the soil still produces, every spring, a specific red-tinted wildflower that grows nowhere else on the continent; botanists from the Isle who have analyzed it find no pigment mechanism to explain the coloration

THE HEARTLANDS — SILVER AND ROT
What the darkness feels like here: the darkness of institutions. The horror is not supernatural — it is the horror of a functional system allowed to function long enough that it has developed purposes its creators never intended. The Vaultkeepers are not evil; they are optimized for their function, and their function is now partially independent of the human beings they were created to serve. The ducal houses are not evil; they are old enough to have outlasted every value that originally justified their authority. The Book of Chains is not evil; it is simply incomplete in ways that the people who benefit from those gaps have successfully prevented from being addressed for four centuries.
The Silver Blight: A recurring agricultural phenomenon in the Argen basin that occurs approximately once every generation — a season where the grain harvest produces perfectly shaped grain with no nutritional value. The grain grinds into flour; the flour bakes into bread; the bread feeds no one. People fed exclusively on silver-blight grain for more than a week begin to lose weight regardless of quantity consumed, and begin to see, at the corners of their vision, figures standing at distance. The figures do not approach. They appear to be watching. They disappear when looked at directly. The current agricultural understanding: the blight is a fungal infection. The figures are early-stage nutritional collapse hallucinations. Both of these explanations are correct. Neither explanation addresses why the figures appear to be in roughly the same places every generation, or why three of those locations correspond to the sites of significant pre-imperial events that the people experiencing the hallucinations have no knowledge of.
Marvoss's Grave: The graves of the three children drowned at Stonebridge are marked. The graves are in the village church of Rivergate. The graves have been in the village church since the drowning, approximately 340 years ago. The graves are the correct size for children. Every priest who has tended the Rivergate church for the past century has noted in the parish records, using different language but consistent observation: the graves are warm. Warmer than the stone around them. Not body-temperature warm — just several degrees above ambient. The current priest has recorded this observation and then explicitly noted "I do not know what to make of this and choose not to speculate."
Named dark locations:
The Silvermere Depression — a perfectly circular lake twelve miles from Vornhold that has no inlet or outlet and maintains a constant water level regardless of rainfall or drought; the water is slightly silver-tinted from mineral content; local children are forbidden from swimming there; the prohibition predates any recorded reason for it; the fish in the lake are edible but have no eyes
The Broken Ledger — a specific room in the old Argenhold archives where no candle will stay lit; the room contains the financial records of the first Argenlord administration; three scholars who have attempted to read those records using portable lanterns have reported the same experience: the ledger appears to be written in a different hand on every page, and the hand on any page you're currently reading looks fresh, as if the ink is still wet
Marvoss's Reach — the section of the Argen river directly beneath Stonebridge where the three children drowned; the water there is measurably colder than fifty yards upstream or downstream; this has been measured six times; it is always colder; the cold extends to exactly the length of the bridge's shadow at noon

ROSLAND — IRON FOREST REPUBLIC
What the darkness feels like here: the darkness of deep time. Rosland is old. The forest is older. The empire came and built roads and left and the forest absorbed the roads and in another two hundred years the forest will have absorbed everything the empire built and then it will absorb everything the republic built and then it will still be there. The specific Lovecraftian quality of Rosland is this: the forest is not indifferent. Something in the forest has been there longer than humanity has been on this continent, and it has developed what might be called opinions, and its opinions manifest slowly, across the scale of centuries, in ways that look like weather or disease or simply bad luck until you lay the incidents end to end across generations and realize they form a pattern pointing in a direction.
The Daudrwood Petrified Trees: Already established. The trees are not dead. They are warm to the touch. Verra Daurn knows this and has not reported it because she has been measuring the warmth for eleven years and has noted that it increases approximately three degrees per decade and that the increase began in approximately 1280 AF, which is also when the first reports of unexplained miners disappearing in the eastern shafts began, which is also when the Blood Cartographers' maps first showed an anomalous echo-concentration in this region, though the Blood Cartographers and Verra Daurn have never communicated with each other.
What the Thorvach Feed Their Trees: The Hungry Grove sect believes the petrified trees in the Daudrwood hold something imprisoned. They believe feeding them — specifically feeding them bodies, which is what bodies mean in this context — loosens the prison incrementally. What they have not considered, because their theology provides no framework for it: what if the prison exists because whatever is inside needs to stay inside? What if the warmth increasing is not proof that the feeding is working but proof that the imprisoned thing is becoming aware of the feeding and reacting to it? Verra Daurn, who has been measuring the temperature, has also been noting the spatial distribution of the warmest trees. They are not random. They form a shape that she has been reluctant to write down and hasn't.
The Fire-Song Memory Problem: Several Roslandic fire-singers of advanced age have noted, in their own private records (never shared; this is the kind of thing you don't discuss), that the fire-songs know things that the fire-singers don't. Specifically: fire-songs sung in full, in the correct traditional setting, occasionally produce additional verses that no one in the room recognizes and that no one in the room sang. Not misheard existing verses — new material, consistently worded across different occasions, appearing to be continuations of songs that were interrupted by historical events (the imperial period, when fire-songs were banned). The "returning verses" — the fire-singers' private term — have been written down by three independent singers. The written records are stored in three different locations and have never been compared. If they were compared, they would be identical.
Named dark locations:
The Vitred Shaft — Mine shaft #7 in the Karthold eastern complex, collapsed and sealed in 1291 AF; the official cause was structural failure; the actual cause is in the Stelev family's private records; the shaft goes deeper than the survey records indicate and whatever is at the bottom has not been established because the three survey teams sent down before the collapse each returned two members fewer than they went in, each time
Koschei's Well — A specific spring in the eastern forest that has been producing water for documented centuries; the water is the best-tasting water in Rosland and has a specific quality that makes people who drink it sleep more deeply than usual; the sleep is dreamless; fire-singers have noted that people who drink Koschei's Well water regularly cannot participate in fire-song evenings — they open their mouth and nothing comes out
The Unnamed Mound — A burial mound in the forest east of Fairhaven that predates the empire, predates the Roslandic nation, predates any culture currently in the region; the Frostguard rangers use it as a landmark but do not camp within a hundred yards of it; the rule about not camping near it is in the Frostguard training material but the reason for the rule has been removed from every edition since approximately 1180 AF

THE HORNS — ADDITIONAL NAMED THINGS (ISLANDS)
Verwhisper: The moss island. Already the most echo-dense inhabited location in the known world. Prior Oaken, who has been meditating there for eleven years, has begun to hear the trees' root-systems processing water as something closer to language than fluid dynamics. He has been writing down what the roots say. The notebooks fill at approximately one per month. He is on his forty-third notebook. The notebooks are stored in the Silence Wing. He has not told anyone what they say because he is not sure anyone would understand the question well enough to be asked.
Shadowtide: The southern tooth. The midnight sun at midsummer. The specific dark of Shadowtide is thermal: the island sits in a warm current from the south that has no business being there given the island's latitude, and the warmth means the island is inhabitable by species that shouldn't survive this far north. The Ix'Vorath cultists who have established a quiet community on Shadowtide's western shore chose it specifically because the warmth extends belowground, and the specific ritual of the Vessel-Cutters requires a certain ambient temperature for the echo-release to propagate correctly. The community is small, organized, and has been there for twelve years. The Pilots' Guild knows the community exists. The Pilots' Guild does not discuss it with anyone from the mainland.

THE RED COAST — COPPER TEETH AND DESERT SILENCE
What the darkness feels like here: the darkness of thirst elevated to cosmology. The desert is not a metaphor. The desert kills and the desert takes and the desert is indifferent in a way that human beings in desert cultures have historically personified as the divine, because indifference at that scale requires a psychology to be manageable. The specific Red Coast dark is the dark of T'zal — the unnamed eastern deep, the direction from which no ship returns, the direction in which dying people sometimes turn their faces in their last hours without any explanation for why east suddenly matters.
The Night Market at Wahaat al-Sirr: The oasis of secret water (already the Tariqat al-Nur's retreat). The night market here is not the Cascabella's chaotic underground trade — it is formal, ancient, and organized. Twice yearly, at specific Velosi calendar dates that the Tariqat tracks with the miqyas instruments, merchants arrive at Wahaat al-Sirr from both inland and coast. What they trade is information. Not trade intelligence — cosmological intelligence. Observations of astronomical events. Records of echo-field fluctuations. The accounts of travelers who have gone east of the Saffaren's range and returned (these accounts are extremely rare; most travelers who go east do not return; the accounts of those who do are treated as primary source material for something no one is willing to name). The market keeps records. The records are encrypted in the Red Calligrapher's geometric script. The records go back approximately four hundred years.
The Eastern Horizon Prohibition: The Saffaren deep-desert clans have a prohibition that is not in the Sand-Law but is observed as if it were: you do not look east at the third hour after midnight. Not because anything visibly happens. Because three generations of Saffaren wise-people have noted, in consistent terms across that time, that looking east at the third hour produces the specific sensation of being looked at in return. From something very far away. That has been aware of you for a long time.
The Copper Taste of the Deep Qanat: In the oldest sections of the Al-Wadi qanat system — sections that predate the Red Crown by at least three hundred years and that no living engineer has personally inspected end-to-end — the water that emerges has a copper taste slightly different from the ordinary mineral content. The Qanat-Khanan master-engineers call this al-dam al-ard (the earth's blood). It is not harmful. It is not explicable. The oldest sections of the qanat occasionally produce, along with the water, objects that were not placed there: small carved stones in a geometric style no living craftsperson can reproduce, sometimes small flakes of an unidentified dark metal that does not rust.
Named dark locations:
Qasr al-Dhaba'ib (Castle of the Vanished) — a pre-Dominion fortress in the deep Saffaren that appears on no official maps; the Saffaren clans know its location; no one stays there; the outer walls contain, carved into the stone, a text in the pre-Dominion script that scholars have partially translated as a list; the list appears to be a census; the population number it records is larger than the entire current Red Coast population
The Mirror Flat — a section of the deep desert where the sand has been fused into dark glass over an area of approximately twenty square miles; no explosion, no volcanic activity, no heat source in the historical record explains it; the glass is very old, pre-empire; standing on it you can see your reflection directly beneath your feet; the reflection, in low light, has a slight delay

THE FROZEN SOUTH — GOLD AND COLD AND WHAT LIVES UNDER THE ICE
What the darkness feels like here: the darkness of scale and isolation. The horror of the Frozen South is the horror of being very small in a very large cold place where the thing that kills you is not malevolent — it simply cannot perceive you. Glacier Bear, blizzard, frostbite, starvation — none of these want to kill you. They simply are what they are and you are in the way. The specific existential dread of the Frozen South is that the universe operates at a scale where human beings don't register. The gold they dig from the mountains feels like compensation. The fire-songs feel like defiance. Both are.
The Glacier's Memory: The southern glaciers contain, visible through the ice in specific locations, objects. Not geological inclusions — objects. Tools. Structures. At one documented location near the Heitdalr's eastern face, a section of the glacier that calved in 1287 AF exposed what appeared to be a stone floor — flat, worked, with carved borders — that extended back into the ice for an unknown distance before the ice refroze over it. The Burned Priests of the Heitdalr sealed the site immediately. The Frostguard ranger who first found it (Sigrun of Clan Daelvik) reported what she saw. Her report is in the Guildmaster's locked records. The Heitdalr priests came to see her within two weeks of the report. She retracted her account publicly six months later and has declined to speak about it since.
The Winter-Moot's Sealed Record: Every Winter-Moot produces public records of the sessions. The sealed session — held on the second night of every Moot, attended only by the Pack Leader and the senior fire-singer of each clan — produces a record that is stored in the Kjölfoss Deeps Vault and never circulated. The sealed session's subject is consistent across every Moot: what has been seen in the south that year that cannot be publicly acknowledged. The contents of the sealed records from the past thirty years, if read in sequence, form a consistent picture of something that has been moving northward, in the ice, at approximately one mile per decade. The same senior fire-singer rarely attends consecutive Moots. This is not officially because of the sealed session content. It is also not not because of it.
Named dark locations:
Hvelving Djúp (The Hollow Deep) — a specific location on the southern coast where, at low tide, a cave system is accessible for approximately two hours; the cave system extends down and south at a steep angle; the sounds from inside the cave during the two-hour window are not wind-based; the Bearclaw clan, who consider it their territory, have a prohibition against entering that goes back further than their fire-songs can reach
Bjálki's Head — the mountain where Bjálki of the Bearclaw was shaved and exiled; the mountain is named after this event, which happened approximately 200 years ago; the mountain has no summit camp because the specific peak, which should be entirely granite, is warm to the touch in the section where the exile reportedly sat for the three days before he walked south and was never seen again
Gullfjara (Gold-Sand Beach) — the only beach in the Frozen South where gold flakes wash up in the surf regularly; Aurax controls it exclusively; the gold is real; it is also the only beach in the Frozen South where the sea doesn't freeze in winter; this is not geologically consistent with any available explanation

XARIA — THE BEAUTIFUL TERRIBLE
What the darkness feels like here: the darkness of a cosmology that is correct. Everywhere else in the world, the folk horror is uncertain — maybe the petrified trees are just trees, maybe the silver blight is just fungus, maybe the cave sounds are just wind. In Xaria, the cosmology says the gods ate each other, the remainder of the gods is present in all matter, feeding that remainder is the correct response to existence, and the mechanism for feeding it includes human blood. The specific horror of Xaria is that this is not a mistake, not a deception, not a primitive misunderstanding of a deeper truth. The echo-field is real. The Great Exchange is real. The blood really does matter. The exact details of the mechanism are wrong in ways that the K'tharr priesthood doesn't know and the Blood Cartographers are beginning to suspect — but the underlying premise is the closest any civilization on Mundus has come to the actual truth.
The Ix'Orath Children: Already established. The full horror: they are not just green-eyed. In full darkness — deep darkness, the kind found only underground or in rooms with no light source — they produce a faint luminescence. Not enough to read by. Enough to see that a child is in the corner. The K'tharr priesthood has been looking for these children with increasing systematic effort for the past forty years. The increasing effort correlates with the Ix'Orath children becoming more common. The priesthood's theory: the children are an aberration. The Reformation's theory: the children are what Ashborn have always been — the echo-field is responding to the concentrated suffering of the bound community by producing individuals capable of perceiving it directly. Both theories predict the children will become more common as the field strengthens. Neither theory has a good answer for what happens if the priesthood finds all of them.
The Codex Beneath the Codex: The K'ay tradition of folded bark-book production preserves Xaria's cosmological history. The public codices tell K'tharr's story in sequential panels, starting with the creation and ending with the establishment of the Great Exchange. There is a second tradition, known only to the most senior K'ay keepers, of a second set of panels — not depicted in any surviving complete form — that continue the story after the Exchange's establishment. The surviving fragments of these continuation panels are held in three separate locations and show, in the fragment that appears to come earliest in the sequence, something that the K'ay keeper who last catalogued them described as "K'tharr noticing something that was already there before he arrived." The keeper died six months after writing that description. The death was natural. The description is the last thing in her notebook.
Named dark locations:
Ix'Kan Zeroth — an unacknowledged location in the Xarian interior that the Great Exchange cartographers' maps circle but never label; the K'tharr priesthood calls it the Navel; what the Blood Cartographers' maps (which are being built from echo-density readings and have no cultural pre-knowledge) call it is: the highest echo-concentration on the continent, by a factor of seven, sitting under a dense jungle hill with no architectural features visible from outside
The Canal That Runs Backward — a specific canal in Canopolis's northern district that flows, during certain festivals, in the wrong direction; not symbolic; measurably wrong; the Qanat-Khanan equivalent (the Yaxché-Khanan, the tree-water engineers) have measured it with their instruments; the hydraulic explanation requires a pressure source below the city that cannot be accounted for by any known aquifer
The Featherwork That Won't Stay Still — in the Ix'Pal treasury, among the great featherwork pieces including K'tharr's Mantle, one piece (unlabeled; no provenance; appeared in the inventory in approximately 1190 AF with no record of acquisition) depicts not a divine scene but a landscape; the landscape is unrecognizable; the feathers in the landscape section of the piece are, when examined closely, slightly displaced from their original positions each time the inventory is taken; the total displacement is small; it has been, over 118 years, moving the depicted landscape incrementally toward something

PART TWO: FOLK SUPERSTITIONS AND WHAT THEY'RE ACTUALLY RESPONDING TO
These are things ordinary people believe. Most are wrong about the mechanism. Very few are wrong about the phenomenon.

"The second candle lights itself" (Nionian) If you have two candles burning and one goes out, the second will briefly flare before returning to normal height. Interpreted as Velos acknowledging Keth, or vice versa. Actually: the echo-field around a burning source is briefly disrupted when the source ends; the second candle's flame behavior reflects this disruption. The people who notice this are, statistically, slightly more echo-sensitive than average.
"Bread baked on the day of a death feeds only grief" (Heartlands) Don't bake bread in a house where someone died that day. The bread will be technically fine and emotionally wrong — people who eat it report a specific melancholy that lasts the rest of the day. The Magos explanation: a dying person's echo-presence saturates the immediate environment briefly; food prepared in this saturation absorbs trace impressions; the melancholy is a somatic response to echo-contact, not a supernatural phenomenon. This doesn't make the bread any less sad.
"The domovoi takes the first bite" (Rosland) The first portion of every meal left at the hearth. The domovoi is not present in most households. But in approximately one in forty Roslandic homes, something takes the portion. Not rats — the food disappears too cleanly, too consistently, without physical evidence. What takes it is not determined. What taking it does is: homes where the portion is regularly left have measurably warmer hearthstones year-round.
"Don't name a child at a crossing" (Horns) Children should not be named on a bridge, at a ford, at a tide-point. The explanation is folklore — it gives the water-spirits a hold on the name. The actual observed phenomenon: children named at crossing points are statistically more likely to die near water before age ten. This has been recorded by the Pilots' Guild in their demographic logs, where it appears as an anomaly they have classified as "cultural data point — mechanism unclear."
"The parrot knows who'll die next" (Sangrea) Trained Carvallo parrots have, documented across many trainers over generations, a consistent behavioral change in the 48-72 hours before a household member dies: they refuse to speak to that person specifically while continuing to speak normally to everyone else. The trainer community knows this. They do not discuss it with the households because there is no actionable information in it — you cannot stop a death by knowing it's coming, but you can cause tremendous distress by telling someone their parrot won't look at them.
"Three bears, three years" (Frozen South) If a Glacier Bear is seen three times in one winter near a specific settlement, that settlement will be abandoned within three years. The Frozen South clans treat this as literal predictive fact. The actual mechanism: Glacier Bears avoid areas of dense human activity; if one is appearing repeatedly near a settlement, the settlement's environmental footprint is shrinking — either because the population is declining or because the resource base is collapsing. The bear is the symptom, not the cause.
"Salt at the threshold keeps the Vessel-Cutters out" (Red Coast) Leave a thin line of salt across the main threshold of your home. The Ix'Vorath/Vessel-Cutter cult, which practices directed killing to release echo-density, specifically avoids targeting homes with salt thresholds because the salt-line is a recognizable folk protection marker and targeting a home with visible protections creates unnecessary attention risk. The superstition works because the cult makes it work by respecting it. This is not the reason the salt-line believers think it works.
"A fire-song unfinished will finish itself" (Rosland) If a fire-song is stopped mid-verse in a formal context, it will, on the same night, complete itself — someone in the group will begin singing the remaining verse without consciously choosing to. This is documented sufficiently that the Roslandic fire-singer tradition has formal protocols for deliberate interruptions. What is less documented, and what three fire-singers have noted in their private records: when an unfinished song completes itself, the completing singer occasionally sings verses that weren't in the original song. The additional verses are consistent across different singers completing the same song.

